window.IELTS_DATA={"build":"2026.07.02-curated-phrases-bands-v28","items":[{"section":"writing-general","title":"Application for an internship","prompt":"You have recently learned about an opening for an internship at a local company that you are interested in.\n\nWrite a letter to the director of the company. In your letter,\n- introduce yourself\n- explain how you learned about the internship\n- explain why you would be suitable for the internship","answer":"Dear Ms Carter,\n\nI am writing to apply for the marketing internship recently advertised on your company's careers page. I am currently completing the final year of a business degree at Hanoi University, with a particular focus on digital communication and consumer behaviour.\n\nI learned about the position through a presentation given by one of your former interns at a university careers event. Her description of the company's practical training and collaborative culture strongly encouraged me to apply.\n\nI believe I would be a suitable candidate for three reasons. First, I have managed social-media content for a student organisation and increased event registrations through a targeted campaign. Second, my coursework has given me <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a solid foundation</strong> in market research and data analysis. Finally, I am comfortable working in English and have experience presenting ideas to both small groups and large audiences.\n\nI have attached my CV and would <strong class=\"key-phrase\">welcome the opportunity</strong> to discuss how I could contribute to your team. Thank you for considering my application.\n\nYours sincerely,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"a solid foundation","vi":"nền tảng vững chắc"},{"en":"welcome the opportunity","vi":"trân trọng cơ hội"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – Writing Task 1 Sample Letters","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Application for an internship","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-001","_displayNo":"#001","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Applying for a part-time restaurant job","prompt":"A local restaurant is recruiting a part-time employee.\n\nWrite to the restaurant manager. In your letter:\n- apply for the position\n- describe relevant experience\n- state the days and hours you can work","answer":"Dear Sir or Madam,\n\nI am writing to apply for the part-time front-of-house position advertised in the window of Green Table Restaurant.\n\nI have eighteen months of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">relevant customer-service experience</strong> from working at a busy café near my university. My duties included taking orders, handling card payments, resolving minor complaints and preparing the dining area between sittings. The role taught me to remain polite and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">work efficiently under pressure</strong>, even during crowded weekend shifts. I also hold a current food-safety certificate and speak both English and Vietnamese fluently.\n\nI am available from 5 p. m. until closing on Monday, Wednesday and Friday, and at any time on Saturday or Sunday. During university holidays, I could take additional daytime shifts if required.\n\nI would <strong class=\"key-phrase\">welcome the opportunity</strong> to discuss the position and am <strong class=\"key-phrase\">available for interview</strong> this week. My CV and the contact details of my previous supervisor are attached.\n\nThank you for considering my application.\n\nYours faithfully,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"relevant customer-service experience","vi":"kinh nghiệm chăm sóc khách hàng phù hợp"},{"en":"work efficiently under pressure","vi":"làm việc hiệu quả dưới áp lực"},{"en":"welcome the opportunity","vi":"mong có cơ hội"},{"en":"available for interview","vi":"sẵn sàng tham gia phỏng vấn"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – General Training Letter Samples","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Applying for a part-time restaurant job","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-002","_displayNo":"#002","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Complaint about a faulty camera","prompt":"You bought a camera that was faulty, returned it to the shop and were promised a repair, but a week later it is still not ready.\n\nWrite to the company. In your letter:\n- introduce yourself and the purchase\n- explain what has happened\n- state what action you expect","answer":"Dear Sir or Madam,\n\nMy name is Alex Morgan, and I am writing regarding a Lumix G90 camera purchased from your King Street branch on 2 June, receipt number KS-7714.\n\nThe camera appeared normal in the shop, but at home the shutter repeatedly froze and several photographs were saved with a black band across the image. I returned it the following day, and your representative assured me that the repair would take no more than three working days.\n\nIt has now been eight days, and staff cannot tell me when the camera will be ready. This delay is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">not reasonably acceptable</strong> because I bought the equipment for a paid photography assignment next weekend. I have already given the shop <strong class=\"key-phrase\">ample opportunity</strong> to resolve the fault.\n\nI would therefore like either a new replacement of the same specification or <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a full refund</strong>. If neither can be arranged by Friday, I will have to hire another camera and may seek reimbursement for that cost. I hope the matter can be brought to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a prompt resolution</strong> without further delay.\n\nYours faithfully,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"not reasonably acceptable","vi":"không thể chấp nhận một cách hợp lý"},{"en":"ample opportunity","vi":"đủ thời gian và cơ hội"},{"en":"a full refund","vi":"khoản hoàn tiền toàn bộ"},{"en":"a prompt resolution","vi":"một giải pháp nhanh chóng"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – General Training Letter Samples","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Complaint about a faulty camera","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-003","_displayNo":"#003","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Complaint about a theatre visit","prompt":"You attended a good play at a theatre but could not enjoy it because of problems at the venue.\n\nWrite to the theatre manager. In your letter:\n- identify the performance and date\n- describe the problems\n- suggest what should be done","answer":"Dear Sir or Madam,\n\nI am writing about the evening performance of The Last Station at the Grand Theatre on Friday, 5 June.\n\nThe play itself was excellent, but the experience was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">seriously undermined by several problems</strong>. When my partner and I arrived, another couple had been allocated the same seats. An usher moved us to the front row, where a stage light shone directly into our eyes throughout the first act. In addition, the air-conditioning was not working, and the auditorium became uncomfortably hot.\n\nI appreciate that isolated technical problems occur, but a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">double-booking error</strong> should have been resolved before the performance began. The replacement seats were clearly unsuitable, yet staff did not offer us another option or explain how to make a complaint.\n\nI suggest reviewing the booking system, checking lighting positions before each show and training ushers to handle seating errors consistently. Given the disruption, I would also consider a partial refund or replacement tickets to be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a reasonable remedy</strong>.\n\nI look forward to your response.\n\nYours faithfully,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"seriously undermined by several problems","vi":"bị ảnh hưởng nghiêm trọng bởi một số vấn đề"},{"en":"double-booking error","vi":"lỗi đặt trùng chỗ"},{"en":"a reasonable remedy","vi":"một biện pháp khắc phục hợp lý"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – General Training Letter Samples","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Complaint about a theatre visit","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-004","_displayNo":"#004","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Complaint about noise at a recreation ground","prompt":"A school regularly brings pupils to a recreation ground near your home, and recent visits have caused problems.\n\nWrite to the head teacher. In your letter:\n- explain why you enjoy living near the ground\n- describe the recent problems\n- suggest what the school should do","answer":"Dear Sir or Madam,\n\nI live opposite Maple Recreation Ground and am writing about the sports sessions held there by pupils from your school.\n\nResidents generally <strong class=\"key-phrase\">value the open space</strong> because it provides trees, walking paths and a safe place for local children to play. We also understand that school sport is valuable and have never objected to normal daytime activity.\n\nHowever, during the past three weeks, several groups have left plastic bottles and food packaging behind. Footballs have repeatedly struck parked cars, and pupils have gathered outside nearby houses shouting for up to thirty minutes after the sessions ended. These incidents <strong class=\"key-phrase\">disrupt local residents</strong>, particularly older people and parents with young babies.\n\nCould teachers please <strong class=\"key-phrase\">supervise pupils more closely</strong>, ensure all rubbish is collected and keep pupils within the marked playing area? It would also help if groups left promptly once the lesson had finished. These simple measures would allow the school to continue using the ground without creating unnecessary conflict.\n\nYours faithfully,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"value the open space","vi":"trân trọng không gian mở"},{"en":"disrupt local residents","vi":"gây ảnh hưởng đến cư dân địa phương"},{"en":"supervise pupils more closely","vi":"giám sát học sinh chặt chẽ hơn"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – General Training Letter Samples","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Complaint about noise at a recreation ground","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-005","_displayNo":"#005","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Complaint about noisy neighbours","prompt":"You live in an apartment building but are having trouble with the behaviour of your neighbours.\n\nWrite a letter to inform the building manager of the situation. In your letter,\n- explain who you are\n- describe the situation concerning your neighbours' behaviour\n- suggest how the situation could be dealt with","answer":"Dear Building Manager,\n\nI am a resident of apartment 8B and am writing to report repeated late-night noise from apartment 8C. The problem has continued for nearly three weeks and is now seriously affecting my sleep and ability to work.\n\nThe occupants frequently play loud music and move furniture between midnight and 2 a. m. Last Saturday, a large gathering continued until almost 3 a. m., despite two polite requests from nearby residents to reduce the noise. I fully understand that people should be able to enjoy their homes, but the current situation is unreasonable in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a shared building</strong>.\n\nI would be grateful if you could remind the residents of the building's quiet-hours policy and speak to them directly. If the disturbance continues, a written warning may be necessary. It may also be useful to circulate the policy to all residents so that expectations are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">clear and consistent</strong>.\n\nPlease let me know what action will be taken. I am available to provide a dated record of the incidents if required.\n\nYours faithfully,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"a shared building","vi":"một tòa nhà dùng chung"},{"en":"clear and consistent","vi":"rõ ràng và nhất quán"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – Writing Task 1 Sample Letters","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Complaint about noisy neighbours","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-006","_displayNo":"#006","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Complaint about sports-centre changing rooms","prompt":"The changing rooms at a sports centre are in poor condition. You have complained before but nothing has changed.\n\nWrite to the manager. In your letter:\n- describe the problems\n- explain what happened after earlier complaints\n- state what action you expect","answer":"Dear Sir or Madam,\n\nI am writing to make a formal complaint about the changing rooms at Greenfield Sports Centre.\n\nSeveral lockers no longer close properly, two showers have been leaking for weeks, and the floor is frequently covered in water. The broken ventilation system has also created a strong smell and visible mould near the ceiling. These conditions are unpleasant and, more importantly, pose a safety risk.\n\nI have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">raised this issue repeatedly</strong> at reception on three occasions during the past month. Each time, I was told that maintenance had been informed, yet no repairs have been completed and no warning signs have been placed near the wet floor.\n\nI would like the centre to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take immediate corrective action</strong> by repairing the showers and lockers, cleaning the affected areas thoroughly and publishing a clear timetable for the ventilation work. Until the floor is safe, staff should inspect it regularly and place appropriate signs where necessary.\n\nPlease respond within seven days with details of the action you intend to take.\n\nYours faithfully,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"raised this issue repeatedly","vi":"đã nhiều lần phản ánh vấn đề này"},{"en":"take immediate corrective action","vi":"thực hiện biện pháp khắc phục ngay lập tức"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – Recent General Training Writing Task 1 Topics","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Complaint about sports-centre changing rooms","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-007","_displayNo":"#007","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Disputing an increase in car insurance","prompt":"Your insurer has informed you that your monthly car-insurance payment will increase, and you disagree with the decision.\n\nWrite to the insurer. In your letter:\n- explain why you are writing\n- state why the increase seems unjustified\n- say what you want the company to do","answer":"Dear Sir or Madam,\n\nI am writing regarding your notice dated 10 June, which states that my monthly car-insurance premium will rise by 28 per cent from August.\n\nI would ask you to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">review this decision</strong> because my circumstances do not appear to justify such a substantial increase. I have held policy number MC-44821 for six years and maintained a completely <strong class=\"key-phrase\">claim-free record</strong>. My vehicle, annual mileage and home address have not changed, and the car is parked overnight in a locked garage. I have also completed an approved defensive-driving course since my last renewal.\n\nPlease provide a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">clear breakdown</strong> of the factors used to calculate the new premium. If the increase resulted from incorrect information, I would like the policy amended immediately. If it reflects a general pricing change, please reconsider the quotation in light of my history and confirm whether a higher excess or revised level of cover would reduce the cost.\n\nI look forward to receiving a written response before the current policy expires.\n\nYours faithfully,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"review this decision","vi":"xem xét lại quyết định này"},{"en":"claim-free record","vi":"lịch sử không yêu cầu bồi thường bảo hiểm"},{"en":"clear breakdown","vi":"bản phân tích chi tiết, rõ ràng"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – General Training Letter Samples","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Disputing an increase in car insurance","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-008","_displayNo":"#008","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Documents left in a taxi","prompt":"You accidentally left important papers in a taxi.\n\nWrite to the taxi company. In your letter:\n- give details of the journey\n- explain why the papers matter\n- request specific help from the company","answer":"Dear Sir or Madam,\n\nI am writing to report a blue document case that I left in one of your taxis yesterday evening.\n\nI was collected outside City Hospital at approximately 6.20 p. m. and travelled to 18 King Street. I paid by card at 6.45 p. m., and the receipt shows journey reference TX-80417. I was seated in the rear left-hand seat and believe the case slipped onto the floor when I got out.\n\nIt contains signed employment forms, certified copies of my qualifications and other <strong class=\"key-phrase\">time-sensitive documents</strong> required for a visa appointment on Thursday. Some of these documents would take several weeks to replace.\n\nCould you please use the payment reference to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">trace the vehicle</strong> and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">contact the driver directly</strong>? I would be happy to collect the case from your office or meet the driver at a convenient location. A member of your staff can reach me on 07700 123456 at any time today.\n\nThank you for treating this matter as urgent.\n\nYours faithfully,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"time-sensitive documents","vi":"tài liệu cần xử lý gấp, có hạn thời gian"},{"en":"trace the vehicle","vi":"truy tìm/xác định chiếc xe"},{"en":"contact the driver directly","vi":"liên hệ trực tiếp với tài xế"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – Recent General Training Writing Task 1 Topics","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Documents left in a taxi","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-009","_displayNo":"#009","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Enquiring about a conference centre","prompt":"Your employer is planning a training course and has asked you to check whether a local conference centre is suitable.\n\nWrite to the centre manager. In your letter:\n- describe the course\n- list the equipment and facilities required\n- ask further questions about the venue","answer":"Dear Sir or Madam,\n\nI am writing to enquire about hiring the Lakeside Conference Centre for a two-day staff training course in October.\n\nThe programme will focus on customer-service skills and is expected to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">accommodate approximately</strong> forty-five participants. We would require one main room arranged in cabaret style and two smaller rooms for group exercises. The course would run from 9 a. m. to 4.30 p. m. on both days.\n\nPlease confirm whether the venue provides reliable Wi-Fi, a projector, wireless microphones and other <strong class=\"key-phrase\">audio-visual equipment</strong>. We would also need flip charts, movable tables and access to printing facilities. Tea, coffee and a light lunch should be available for all participants, including several people with dietary restrictions.\n\nCould you let me know whether parking is included, whether the building is fully accessible and what cancellation terms apply? I would also appreciate an <strong class=\"key-phrase\">itemised quotation</strong> covering room hire, equipment and catering.\n\nIf the centre is available on 15–16 October, I would be pleased to arrange a site visit next week.\n\nYours faithfully,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"accommodate approximately","vi":"có khả năng phục vụ khoảng"},{"en":"audio-visual equipment","vi":"thiết bị nghe nhìn"},{"en":"itemised quotation","vi":"báo giá chi tiết theo từng hạng mục"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – Recent General Training Writing Task 1 Topics","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Enquiring about a conference centre","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-010","_displayNo":"#010","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Important papers left at a hotel","prompt":"After attending a meeting at a hotel, you realised that you had left important documents behind.\n\nWrite to the hotel manager. In your letter:\n- state where you may have left the documents\n- explain why they are important\n- say what you would like the manager to do","answer":"Dear Sir or Madam,\n\nI attended a business meeting at the Riverside Hotel yesterday and believe I left a folder containing important documents in the building.\n\nThe meeting took place in the Oak Conference Room from 2 p. m. to 5 p. m. I was seated near the window and may have left the folder either under my chair or on the table beside the projector. It is dark grey and marked “Northgate Project”.\n\nThe folder contains signed contracts and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">confidential documents</strong> relating to a client tender that closes on Friday. Replacing the originals would be difficult and could delay the submission, so I would be grateful if a member of staff could <strong class=\"key-phrase\">check the meeting room</strong> as soon as possible. Please also ask the reception desk and housekeeping team whether it has been handed in.\n\nIf the folder is found, could you keep it securely at reception? I can collect it this afternoon. Alternatively, I will cover the cost if you need to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">send them by registered post</strong> to my office.\n\nYours faithfully,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"confidential documents","vi":"tài liệu mật"},{"en":"check the meeting room","vi":"kiểm tra phòng họp"},{"en":"send them by registered post","vi":"gửi bằng thư bảo đảm"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – Recent General Training Writing Task 1 Topics","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Important papers left at a hotel","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-011","_displayNo":"#011","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Improving parking at an office building","prompt":"Your office building has no adequate parking for employees.\n\nWrite to the building manager. In your letter:\n- explain the current problem\n- suggest a solution\n- describe how better parking would help staff","answer":"Dear Mr Lewis,\n\nI am writing on behalf of several employees regarding the lack of parking at Westgate Business Centre.\n\nAt present, only twelve spaces are available for more than eighty staff members. The surrounding streets have strict time limits, and the nearest public car park is almost twenty minutes away on foot. This has become <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a daily source of frustration</strong>, particularly for employees who begin early shifts or need to transport equipment.\n\nOne practical solution would be to lease part of the unused land behind the building and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">introduce a permit system</strong> for staff. If this is not immediately possible, the centre could negotiate discounted monthly passes with the Riverside car park and reserve a few existing spaces for employees with mobility needs.\n\nImproved parking would reduce late arrivals, make the building more accessible and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">improve punctuality</strong>. It would also prevent staff from moving their cars during working hours to avoid penalties.\n\nI would <strong class=\"key-phrase\">welcome the opportunity</strong> to discuss these options with you and provide a list of employees who would use the scheme.\n\nYours sincerely,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"a daily source of frustration","vi":"một nguyên nhân gây bực bội hằng ngày"},{"en":"introduce a permit system","vi":"áp dụng hệ thống cấp thẻ/giấy phép"},{"en":"improve punctuality","vi":"cải thiện sự đúng giờ"},{"en":"welcome the opportunity","vi":"mong có cơ hội"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – Recent General Training Writing Task 1 Topics","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Improving parking at an office building","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-012","_displayNo":"#012","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Lost watch on a train","prompt":"You left a valuable item on a train.\n\nWrite to the railway company. In your letter:\n- describe the item\n- state where and when you lost it\n- explain what you would like the company to do","answer":"Dear Sir or Madam,\n\nI am writing to report a watch that I believe I left on one of your trains on Monday, 8 June.\n\nThe item is a silver Seiko wristwatch with a dark-blue face and a narrow metal strap. There is a small scratch beside the number six, and the initials “A. m.” are engraved on the back. Although the watch is not especially expensive, it is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">of considerable sentimental value</strong> because it was a graduation gift from my grandfather.\n\nI travelled on the 18:10 service from Manchester Piccadilly to Leeds and was seated in Coach C, seat 24A. I removed the watch while working on my laptop and probably left it on the fold-down table when I got off at Leeds at approximately 19:05.\n\nCould you please <strong class=\"key-phrase\">check the lost-property records</strong> for that service and ask the cleaning team whether the watch was found? If it has been handed in, I can collect it from Leeds station or pay any reasonable postage costs to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">arrange for its return</strong>.\n\nI have attached a photograph of the watch and a copy of my ticket.\n\nYours faithfully,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"of considerable sentimental value","vi":"có giá trị tinh thần đáng kể"},{"en":"check the lost-property records","vi":"kiểm tra hồ sơ đồ thất lạc"},{"en":"arrange for its return","vi":"sắp xếp việc hoàn trả món đồ"}],"source":"British Council – General Training Writing Practice Test 2","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Lost watch on a train","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-013","_displayNo":"#013","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Offering a talk for an international day","prompt":"A local college is holding an international day, and you would like to give a presentation about your country.\n\nWrite to the college principal. In your letter:\n- describe what you would talk about\n- explain why the students would find it useful\n- ask about the arrangements for speakers","answer":"Dear Principal Harris,\n\nI am writing to offer a short presentation about Vietnam for the college’s international day in September.\n\nMy talk would cover three areas: regional food traditions, the importance of family celebrations, and the rapid changes taking place in major cities such as Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh City. I would use photographs, a short video and a few everyday objects to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">bring the subject to life</strong> rather than presenting a list of facts.\n\nI believe the session would be useful because it would <strong class=\"key-phrase\">give students a balanced picture</strong> of a country that is often discussed mainly as a tourist destination. It could also encourage students from different backgrounds to compare customs and ask questions about cultural similarities.\n\nCould you please tell me how long each presentation should be and how many students are expected? I would also like to know the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">technical requirements</strong>, particularly whether a projector, speakers and internet access will be available.\n\nI would be pleased to send a brief outline in advance.\n\nYours faithfully,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"bring the subject to life","vi":"làm cho chủ đề trở nên sinh động"},{"en":"give students a balanced picture","vi":"giúp học sinh có cái nhìn cân bằng"},{"en":"technical requirements","vi":"các yêu cầu kỹ thuật"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – Recent General Training Writing Task 1 Topics","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Offering a talk for an international day","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-014","_displayNo":"#014","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Problems with shared college accommodation","prompt":"You share a college room with another student, but the arrangement is making it difficult for you to study.\n\nWrite to the college accommodation officer. In your letter:\n- describe the current situation\n- explain why it is affecting your work\n- state what type of accommodation you would prefer","answer":"Dear Sir or Madam,\n\nI am writing to request a change to my current accommodation in West Hall, where I share Room 214 with another student.\n\nAlthough my roommate is friendly, our routines are completely incompatible. He regularly invites several friends into the room late in the evening and often plays online games without headphones. In addition, he works night shifts and returns at around 2 a. m., which wakes me almost every day.\n\nThis situation is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">seriously affecting my ability to study</strong> because I am preparing for final examinations and need several uninterrupted hours of study each evening. I have tried discussing the matter with him, but the improvements have only been temporary. As a result, I am sleeping poorly and have already missed two morning lectures.\n\nI would therefore be grateful if I could move to a single room, ideally in a quieter part of the residence. If no single room is available, I would be willing to share with a student who follows a more regular daytime schedule. I hope the college can help me find <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a quieter environment</strong> <strong class=\"key-phrase\">at your earliest convenience</strong>.\n\nYours faithfully,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"seriously affecting my ability to study","vi":"ảnh hưởng nghiêm trọng đến khả năng học tập của tôi"},{"en":"a quieter environment","vi":"một môi trường yên tĩnh hơn"},{"en":"at your earliest convenience","vi":"sớm nhất khi thuận tiện"}],"source":"IELTS.org – General Training Writing Sample Task 1A","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Problems with shared college accommodation","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-015","_displayNo":"#015","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Requesting help from a language tutor","prompt":"Your children are learning a foreign language at school but require extra support. A friend has recommended a private tutor.\n\nWrite to the tutor. In your letter:\n- explain why you are contacting them\n- describe the areas your children need help with\n- ask about their experience and teaching suggestions","answer":"Dear Ms Patel,\n\nI am writing on the recommendation of my colleague, Sarah Nguyen, to ask whether you could provide additional French tuition for my two children, aged eleven and thirteen.\n\nBoth children understand basic classroom vocabulary, but they are falling behind in speaking and listening. My younger son is hesitant to answer questions aloud, while my daughter finds it difficult to follow normal-speed recordings and often confuses verb endings. Their school teacher believes that regular one-to-one practice would give them the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">targeted support</strong> they need.\n\nCould you please <strong class=\"key-phrase\">outline your experience</strong> of teaching learners in this age group and explain how you normally assess a new student? I would also appreciate your view on whether they should study together or have separate lessons. Ideally, we are looking for one or two sessions each week after 5 p. m.\n\nPlease let me know your fees, availability and any materials the children would need. I would be happy to arrange an introductory meeting at your convenience.\n\nYours sincerely,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"targeted support","vi":"sự hỗ trợ có mục tiêu, đúng trọng tâm"},{"en":"outline your experience","vi":"trình bày khái quát kinh nghiệm của bạn"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – Recent General Training Writing Task 1 Topics","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Requesting help from a language tutor","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-016","_displayNo":"#016","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Suggestions for improving a public library","prompt":"Your local public library has asked users to suggest improvements to its services and facilities.\n\nWrite to the librarian. In your letter:\n- describe what you value about the library\n- explain what could be improved\n- suggest practical changes","answer":"Dear Sir or Madam,\n\nI am writing in response to your request for suggestions about the future development of Central Library.\n\nThe library is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a valuable community resource</strong>. I particularly value the knowledgeable staff, the quiet study area on the first floor and the wide selection of newspapers and reference books. The online reservation system is also straightforward and saves users a great deal of time.\n\nHowever, some facilities currently <strong class=\"key-phrase\">fall short of users’ needs</strong>. There are too few power sockets for laptop users, several chairs are worn and uncomfortable, and the building closes at 6 p. m. on weekdays, which is inconvenient for people who work full time. The children’s section also becomes extremely crowded at weekends.\n\nI would recommend installing additional charging points and replacing the oldest furniture. It would also be helpful to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">extend the opening hours</strong> until at least 8 p. m. on two or three weekdays. Finally, a small booking system for children’s activities could prevent overcrowding and allow staff to plan sessions more effectively.\n\nThank you for inviting public feedback. I hope these suggestions are useful.\n\nYours faithfully,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"a valuable community resource","vi":"một nguồn lực cộng đồng có giá trị"},{"en":"fall short of users’ needs","vi":"chưa đáp ứng đầy đủ nhu cầu của người dùng"},{"en":"extend the opening hours","vi":"kéo dài giờ mở cửa"}],"source":"IELTS.org – General Training Writing Sample Task 1B","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Suggestions for improving a public library","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-017","_displayNo":"#017","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Trying to reconnect with a childhood friend","prompt":"You saw a newspaper article about a childhood friend whom you have not contacted for many years.\n\nWrite to the editor. In your letter:\n- identify the article and edition\n- explain how you lost contact\n- ask for help reconnecting with your friend","answer":"Dear Editor,\n\nI am writing about the profile of Dr Linh Tran published in the Sunday edition of the City Herald on 14 June.\n\nLinh and I were close friends at Nguyen Du Secondary School, but we lost touch after her family moved overseas in 2008. At the time, neither of us used social media regularly, and the email address I had for her later stopped working. I have tried searching professional networks, but I have not been able to confirm whether the person I found is the same Linh.\n\nThe details in your article, particularly the name of her school and her interest in environmental science, strongly suggest that she is my former classmate. I understand that you cannot disclose private contact information. However, I would be grateful if you could <strong class=\"key-phrase\">forward my details</strong> by forwarding this letter and my email address to her. She could then decide whether she wishes to respond.\n\nYour assistance could <strong class=\"key-phrase\">put us back in contact</strong> after nearly two decades, and I would greatly appreciate it.\n\nYours faithfully,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Formal","phrases":[{"en":"forward my details","vi":"chuyển tiếp thông tin của tôi"},{"en":"put us back in contact","vi":"giúp chúng tôi liên lạc lại"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – Recent General Training Writing Task 1 Topics","subtype":"Formal","summary":"Trying to reconnect with a childhood friend","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-018","_displayNo":"#018","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Advice about choosing work instead of college","prompt":"A friend has asked whether they should attend college or start working. You think employment would suit them better.\n\nWrite to your friend. In your letter:\n- explain why college may not suit them\n- describe the advantages of getting a job\n- suggest suitable kinds of work","answer":"Hi Jenny,\n\nIt was great to hear from you. I have thought carefully about your choice, and I honestly think starting work would suit you better than going straight to college.\n\nYou have always been <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a practical, hands-on learner</strong>, whereas most college courses involve long lectures, extensive reading and several years of theoretical study. I am not saying you could not succeed, but I suspect you would find that environment frustrating and lose motivation quite quickly.\n\nA job would allow you to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">gain real-world experience</strong>, earn your own money and discover which type of work you genuinely enjoy. It would also give you more independence, and you could still take a professional course later once you have a clearer goal.\n\nBecause you are confident, organised and good with people, I would look at customer service, hotel reception or event support. An apprenticeship in sales or digital marketing might also be worth considering because it combines training with paid work.\n\nOf course, the final choice is yours, but there is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">no one-size-fits-all answer</strong>. Starting work now does not close the door to education in the future.\n\nTake care,\nAlex","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Informal","phrases":[{"en":"a practical, hands-on learner","vi":"người học thiên về thực hành"},{"en":"gain real-world experience","vi":"tích lũy kinh nghiệm thực tế"},{"en":"no one-size-fits-all answer","vi":"không có một đáp án phù hợp cho tất cả mọi người"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – General Training Letter Samples","subtype":"Informal","summary":"Advice about choosing work instead of college","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-019","_displayNo":"#019","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Changing plans for a cinema trip","prompt":"You arranged to see a film with a friend, but you can no longer go. Another friend can take your place.\n\nWrite to your friend. In your letter:\n- explain why you cannot attend\n- say who can go instead\n- explain why they would be good company","answer":"Hi Ben,\n\nI am really sorry, but <strong class=\"key-phrase\">something urgent has come up</strong> and I will not be able to see the film with you on Saturday evening. My manager has asked me to cover an urgent client presentation, and the meeting cannot be moved because the client is flying home on Sunday.\n\nThe good news is that Minh can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">step in at short notice</strong>. I checked with him before writing, and he is free at 7 p. m. He has already seen the first film in the series, so you will not have to explain the story, and he has offered to collect the tickets from the machine before you arrive.\n\nI think you two will <strong class=\"key-phrase\">get on really well</strong>. You both love science-fiction films, follow the same football team and have a very similar sense of humour. I have given Minh your number, and he will message you tomorrow to confirm where to meet.\n\nI am disappointed to miss it, but let’s arrange another evening next week. Dinner is on me to make up for changing the plan.\n\nAll the best,\nAlex","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Informal","phrases":[{"en":"something urgent has come up","vi":"có việc khẩn cấp đột xuất xảy ra"},{"en":"step in at short notice","vi":"thay thế, hỗ trợ trong thời gian báo trước rất ngắn"},{"en":"get on really well","vi":"rất hợp nhau"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – Recent General Training Writing Task 1 Topics","subtype":"Informal","summary":"Changing plans for a cinema trip","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-020","_displayNo":"#020","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Dog care while on holiday","prompt":"You are going on holiday next week and you need to ask your friend to watch your dog while you are away.\n\nWrite a letter to your friend. In your letter,\n- state how long you will be away\n- tell them what needs to be done\n- state how you will compensate them","answer":"Hi Daniel,\n\nI hope you are well. I am writing to ask whether you could look after my dog, Milo, while I am away in Da Nang from 12 to 19 July. You know him well, so I think staying with you would be far less stressful for him than going to a kennel.\n\nHis routine is simple. He needs a thirty-minute walk every morning and evening, fresh water throughout the day, and one cup of dry food at 7 a. m. and another at 6 p. m. I have left his food, lead and vet's number in a labelled box by the front door. Please also give him his allergy tablet every second evening.\n\nI know this is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a significant favour</strong>, and I do not want you to be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">out of pocket</strong>. I will cover all expenses and take you out for dinner when I return. I would also be happy to help with your house move next month.\n\nThanks for considering it. Please let me know whether this arrangement would work for you.\n\nBest,\nAlex","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Informal","phrases":[{"en":"a significant favour","vi":"một sự giúp đỡ đáng kể"},{"en":"out of pocket","vi":"phải tự bỏ tiền túi"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – Writing Task 1 Sample Letters","subtype":"Informal","summary":"Dog care while on holiday","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-021","_displayNo":"#021","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Friend visiting from overseas","prompt":"Your friend from overseas is coming to visit you next month.\n\nWrite a letter to your friend. In your letter,\n- tell them what they need to bring\n- tell them what they will be doing during the time they are visiting\n- warn them about some things that might be challenging","answer":"Hi Maya,\n\nIt is great news that you will be visiting Hanoi next month. The weather will probably be hot and humid, so bring light clothes, comfortable walking shoes and a compact rain jacket. You should also install a local transport app before you arrive because it makes getting around much easier.\n\nI have planned <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a balanced programme</strong> for your stay. We can spend the first day exploring the Old Quarter, visit the Museum of Ethnology on Saturday, and take a day trip to Ninh Binh if the weather is clear. I have also booked a small street-food tour, which should give you a good introduction to Vietnamese cuisine.\n\nThere are two things to be prepared for. Traffic can seem chaotic at first, and crossing busy roads requires patience. In addition, some smaller shops accept cash only, so it is sensible to carry a modest amount of Vietnamese currency.\n\nI am really <strong class=\"key-phrase\">looking forward to</strong> seeing you and showing you around. Send me your flight details when they are confirmed.\n\nTake care,\nAlex","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Informal","phrases":[{"en":"a balanced programme","vi":"một lịch trình cân bằng"},{"en":"looking forward to","vi":"mong chờ"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – Writing Task 1 Sample Letters","subtype":"Informal","summary":"Friend visiting from overseas","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-022","_displayNo":"#022","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"House and pet care during a holiday","prompt":"A friend has agreed to look after your home and pet while you are away.\n\nWrite to your friend. In your letter:\n- give contact details for your trip\n- explain how to care for your pet\n- describe any other household tasks","answer":"Hi Daniel,\n\nThanks again for agreeing to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">keep an eye on</strong> the flat and Milo while I am in Da Nang from 12 to 19 July. I will be staying at the Seaview Hotel, and you can reach me on my usual mobile number. If I am unavailable, please contact my sister Lan on 0903 555 812.\n\nMilo needs two small meals a day, at about 7 a. m. and 6 p. m. His food is in the lower kitchen cupboard. Please take him for a short walk each evening and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">stick to his usual routine</strong>, as sudden changes tend to upset him. He is not allowed on the balcony unless someone is with him.\n\nCould you also water the plants in the living room twice during the week and collect any post from the box downstairs? The rubbish is collected on Tuesday evening, so it would be great if you could leave the bin outside then.\n\nPlease <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make yourself at home</strong>; there is plenty of food in the fridge, and you are welcome to use the television and coffee machine.\n\nAll the best,\nAlex","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Informal","phrases":[{"en":"keep an eye on","vi":"trông nom, để mắt tới"},{"en":"stick to his usual routine","vi":"duy trì đúng nếp sinh hoạt thường ngày của nó"},{"en":"make yourself at home","vi":"cứ tự nhiên như ở nhà"}],"source":"British Council – General Training Writing Practice Test 1","subtype":"Informal","summary":"House and pet care during a holiday","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-023","_displayNo":"#023","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Instructions for looking after a flat","prompt":"A friend will stay in your apartment and look after it while you are away.\n\nWrite to your friend. In your letter:\n- give useful information about the apartment\n- provide important instructions\n- explain what to do if a problem occurs","answer":"Hi Sophie,\n\nThanks for staying in my flat while I am away. I thought I would <strong class=\"key-phrase\">run through the essentials</strong> before I leave on Friday.\n\nThe spare key is in the lockbox beside the front door; the code is 4821. The hot-water switch is inside the kitchen cupboard, and the Wi-Fi password is written underneath the router. Please use anything in the kitchen and feel free to invite Mark over for dinner.\n\nThe main things are to water the balcony plants every three days, collect the post and keep the place secure whenever you go out. The windows in the bedroom can look closed even when they are not locked, so please check them carefully. The rubbish bins are taken downstairs on Wednesday evening.\n\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">In the unlikely event</strong> of a leak or electrical fault, turn off the main switch beside the fridge and call the building caretaker, Mr Hoang, on 0908 222 410. For anything less urgent, just message me.\n\nHave a comfortable stay, and thanks again for helping.\n\nBest,\nAlex","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Informal","phrases":[{"en":"run through the essentials","vi":"đi nhanh qua các thông tin thiết yếu"},{"en":"In the unlikely event","vi":"trong trường hợp hiếm khi xảy ra"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – Recent General Training Writing Task 1 Topics","subtype":"Informal","summary":"Instructions for looking after a flat","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-024","_displayNo":"#024","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Selling a television to a friend","prompt":"You want to sell your television and think a friend may be interested.\n\nWrite to your friend. In your letter:\n- explain why you are selling it\n- describe the television\n- suggest when your friend could see it","answer":"Hi Chris,\n\nI remember you mentioned that you were looking for a television for your new flat, so I thought I would offer you mine before advertising it online.\n\nI am only selling it because I am moving into a furnished apartment next month and there is already a television there. The one I have is a 43-inch Samsung smart TV, about two years old, and it is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">in excellent working order</strong>. The screen has no scratches, the remote is included, and it supports Netflix, YouTube and wireless screen sharing. I still have the original box and receipt.\n\nI paid £420 for it, but I think £230 would be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a fair price</strong>, especially as you would not need to arrange delivery. There is no pressure at all if it is not what you want.\n\nYou could <strong class=\"key-phrase\">come round and have a look</strong> on Saturday afternoon or Sunday morning. I can connect it to the internet so that you can test the picture, sound and apps properly.\n\nLet me know what suits you.\n\nAll the best,\nAlex","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Informal","phrases":[{"en":"in excellent working order","vi":"hoạt động trong tình trạng rất tốt"},{"en":"a fair price","vi":"một mức giá hợp lý"},{"en":"come round and have a look","vi":"ghé qua xem thử"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – General Training Letter Samples","subtype":"Informal","summary":"Selling a television to a friend","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-025","_displayNo":"#025","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Planning the annual staff party","prompt":"Your workplace holds an annual party, and you have been asked to help organise the next one.\n\nWrite to your colleagues. In your letter:\n- explain what should be changed from last year\n- mention what did not work well last time\n- suggest a meeting place and time to plan the event","answer":"Hello everyone,\n\nI am writing so that we can start planning this year’s staff party before venues become fully booked.\n\nI think we should <strong class=\"key-phrase\">learn from last year’s experience</strong> and make the event less formal. Last year’s long speeches delayed dinner, while the fixed seating plan made it difficult for colleagues from different departments to mix. The music was also far too loud during the first hour, so conversation was almost impossible.\n\nThis time, I suggest a shorter welcome, a buffet rather than a set meal, and two simple team activities. We should also appoint one person to coordinate the venue and another to manage the programme, which would help us <strong class=\"key-phrase\">keep the programme running smoothly</strong>.\n\nCould we <strong class=\"key-phrase\">set aside half an hour</strong> next Wednesday at 4.30 p. m. in Meeting Room 3? I will bring a shortlist of venues and an initial budget. Please send me any dietary requirements or activity ideas before then so that we can discuss them efficiently.\n\nBest regards,\nAlex","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Semi-formal","phrases":[{"en":"learn from last year’s experience","vi":"rút kinh nghiệm từ sự kiện năm ngoái"},{"en":"keep the programme running smoothly","vi":"giúp chương trình diễn ra trôi chảy"},{"en":"set aside half an hour","vi":"dành ra nửa giờ"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – Recent General Training Writing Task 1 Topics","subtype":"Semi-formal","summary":"Planning the annual staff party","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-026","_displayNo":"#026","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Request to pay rent late","prompt":"You are having financial difficulties and need to ask your landlord for permission to pay this month’s rent late.\n\nWrite to your landlord. In your letter:\n- explain the reason\n- state when you will pay\n- explain how you will avoid the problem in future","answer":"Dear Mr Lewis,\n\nI am writing to ask whether I may pay this month’s rent on 15 July rather than on the usual first day of the month.\n\nThe delay is due to a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">temporary cash-flow problem</strong>. My employer changed its payroll provider last week, and several salaries, including mine, will not be processed until 12 July. I have sufficient income to cover the rent, but the funds will not reach my account before the normal payment date.\n\nI will <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make the full payment</strong> of £950 immediately after my salary is deposited and will send you the transfer confirmation that day. I apologise for the inconvenience and appreciate that regular payment is important.\n\nTo prevent a similar delay, I will keep one month’s rent in a separate savings account and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">set up a standing order</strong> for future payments. This means the rent will be transferred automatically even if my salary date changes again.\n\nI hope this temporary arrangement is acceptable. Please let me know if you need written confirmation from my employer.\n\nYours sincerely,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Semi-formal","phrases":[{"en":"temporary cash-flow problem","vi":"vấn đề dòng tiền tạm thời"},{"en":"make the full payment","vi":"thanh toán đầy đủ"},{"en":"set up a standing order","vi":"thiết lập lệnh chuyển tiền định kỳ"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – General Training Letter Samples","subtype":"Semi-formal","summary":"Request to pay rent late","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-027","_displayNo":"#027","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Requesting extended leave from work","prompt":"You need more than one month of leave from work for personal reasons.\n\nWrite to your manager. In your letter:\n- explain why and how long you need leave\n- describe how you will remain informed\n- suggest how your work can be covered","answer":"Dear Ms Reynolds,\n\nI am writing to request six weeks of unpaid leave from 3 August to 13 September so that I can support my father during his recovery from major surgery.\n\nHe lives alone in another city and will need help with transport, meals and medical appointments for the first month after leaving hospital. My siblings can assist later, but they are unable to cover the initial period.\n\nI am committed to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">ensuring a smooth handover</strong> during my absence. Before leaving, I will complete the July performance report, prepare detailed handover notes and brief Minh on the two client accounts I currently manage. He has already agreed to act as the main contact, while Hoa can approve routine expenses.\n\nTo <strong class=\"key-phrase\">keep up to date</strong>, I will check email each weekday and join the Monday team meeting remotely whenever possible. I will also be available by phone for genuinely urgent questions, although I will avoid interfering with day-to-day decisions.\n\nI hope this plan provides <strong class=\"key-phrase\">adequate cover</strong> for the department. I would be grateful for an opportunity to discuss the request this week.\n\nYours sincerely,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Semi-formal","phrases":[{"en":"ensuring a smooth handover","vi":"bảo đảm việc bàn giao diễn ra thuận lợi"},{"en":"keep up to date","vi":"duy trì việc cập nhật thông tin"},{"en":"adequate cover","vi":"sự bố trí nhân sự thay thế đầy đủ"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – General Training Letter Samples","subtype":"Semi-formal","summary":"Requesting extended leave from work","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-028","_displayNo":"#028","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-general","title":"Volunteering on a school trip","prompt":"Your child’s school is arranging a three-day trip abroad and has asked parents to volunteer.\n\nWrite to the head teacher. In your letter:\n- explain why you would like to join the trip\n- describe how you could help\n- ask for further practical details","answer":"Dear Mrs Brown,\n\nI am writing to volunteer for the three-day school trip to Singapore next month.\n\nI would be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">happy to assist</strong> because my daughter is travelling abroad without family for the first time, and I also believe parent volunteers can make the trip safer and less demanding for staff. I have previously accompanied two local day trips and am comfortable supervising groups of teenagers.\n\nDuring the visit, I could <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take responsibility for</strong> a small group during airport transfers, museum visits and meal breaks. I am trained in first aid and speak conversational Mandarin, which may also be useful if the group needs assistance in public places. In addition, I can help keep attendance records and communicate updates to parents.\n\nBefore confirming, could you please <strong class=\"key-phrase\">clarify the practical arrangements</strong>? I would like to know the travel dates, estimated cost, sleeping arrangements and whether volunteers need a background check or additional insurance.\n\nThank you for considering my offer. I am available to discuss the trip after school any day this week.\n\nYours sincerely,\nAlex Morgan","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Semi-formal","phrases":[{"en":"happy to assist","vi":"sẵn lòng hỗ trợ"},{"en":"take responsibility for","vi":"chịu trách nhiệm về"},{"en":"clarify the practical arrangements","vi":"làm rõ các công việc sắp xếp thực tế"}],"source":"IELTS Buddy – Recent General Training Writing Task 1 Topics","subtype":"Semi-formal","summary":"Volunteering on a school trip","visual":null,"id":"writing-general-029","_displayNo":"#029","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-001","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Cities","title":"Chorleywood village development","prompt":"Chorleywood is a village near London whose population has increased steadily since the middle of the nineteenth century. The map below shows the development of the village.","answer":"The map shows the growth of a village called Chorleywood between 1868 and 1994.\n\nIt is clear that the village grew as the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">transport infrastructure</strong> was improved. Four periods of development are shown on the map, and each of the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">populated areas</strong> is near to the main roads, the railway or the motorway.\n\nFrom 1868 to 1883, Chorleywood <strong class=\"key-phrase\">covered a small area</strong> next to one of the main roads. Chorleywood Park and Golf Course is now located next to this original village area. The village grew along the main road to the south between 1883 and 1922, and in 1909 a railway line was built crossing this area from west to east. Chorleywood station is in this part of the village.\n\nThe expansion of Chorleywood continued to the east and west alongside the railway line until 1970. At that time, a motorway was built to the east of the village, and from 1970 to 1994, further development of the village took place around motorway intersections with the railway and one of the main roads.","phrases":[{"en":"transport infrastructure","vi":"cơ sở hạ tầng giao thông"},{"en":"populated areas","vi":"khu vực đông dân cư"},{"en":"covered a small area","vi":"chỉ chiếm một khu vực nhỏ"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-001-1"]},"_displayNo":"#001","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Chorleywood is a village near London whose population has increased…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-002","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Cities","title":"Kolkata climate","prompt":"The climograph below shows average monthly temperatures and rainfall in the city of Kolkata.","answer":"The chart compares average figures for temperature and precipitation over the course of a calendar year in Kolkata.\n\nIt is noticeable that monthly figures for precipitation in Kolkata vary considerably, whereas monthly temperatures remain relatively stable. Rainfall is highest from July to August, while temperatures are highest in April and May.\n\nBetween the months of January and May, average temperatures in Kolkata rise from their lowest point at around 20°C to a peak of just over 30°C. Average rainfall in the city also rises over the same period, from approximately 20mm of rain in January to 100mm in May.\n\nWhile temperatures <strong class=\"key-phrase\">stay roughly the same</strong> for the next four months, the amount of rainfall more than doubles between May and June. Figures for precipitation remain above 250mm from June to September, peaking at around 330mm in July. The final three months of the year <strong class=\"key-phrase\">see a dramatic fall in</strong> precipitation, to a low of about 10mm in December, and a steady drop in temperatures back to the January average.","phrases":[{"en":"stay roughly the same","vi":"gần như giống nhau"},{"en":"see a dramatic fall in","vi":"ghi nhận mức giảm mạnh về"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-002-1"]},"_displayNo":"#002","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Climograph below shows average monthly temperatures and rainfall in the…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-003","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Cities","title":"Ageing populations","prompt":"The graph below shows the proportion of the population aged 65 and over between 1940 and 2040 in three different countries.","answer":"The line graph compares the percentage of people aged 65 or more in three countries over a period of 100 years.\n\nIt is clear that the proportion of elderly people increases in each country between 1940 and 2040. Japan <strong class=\"key-phrase\">is expected to</strong> <strong class=\"key-phrase\">see the most dramatic changes in</strong> its elderly population.\n\nIn 1940, around 9% of Americans were aged 65 or over, compared to about 7% of Swedish people and 5% of Japanese people. The proportions of elderly people in the USA and Sweden rose gradually over the next 50 years, reaching just under 15% in 1990. By contrast, the figures for Japan remained below 5% until the early 2000s.\n\nLooking into the future, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sudden increase in</strong> the percentage of elderly people is predicted for Japan, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">with a jump of</strong> over 15% in just 10 years from 2030 to 2040. By 2040, it is thought that around 27% of the Japanese population will be 65 years old or more, while the figures for Sweden and the USA will be slightly lower, at about 25% and 23% respectively.","phrases":[{"en":"is expected to","vi":"được dự đoán"},{"en":"see the most dramatic changes in","vi":"thấy những thay đổi lớn nhất trong"},{"en":"a sudden increase in","vi":"một sự gia tăng đột ngộttrong"},{"en":"with a jump of","vi":"với mức tăng là bao nhiêu"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-003-1"]},"_displayNo":"#003","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Graph below shows the proportion of the population aged 65 and over between…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-004","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Cities","title":"House prices in five cities","prompt":"The diagrams provide some information about the housing prices of five cities around the world from 1990 to 2000. Summarise the information by selecting and reporting the main features and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"San Francisco and Beijing are two cities which saw housing prices climb <strong class=\"key-phrase\">throughout the ten-year period</strong>. In the first five years, a 2% rise was recorded in San Francisco, and a 4% in Beijing. The increase accelerated in subsequent years, with a 3% gain seen in San Francisco and a neatly 6% in Beijing.\n\nBy comparison, the property market of Rome was continuously at recession, reflected in an average 3.5 per cent drop. Hong Kong and Sydney <strong class=\"key-phrase\">experienced a similar slump</strong> between 1995 and 2000. The housing price slipped 6 % in Hong Kong, as against its 5% gain in the previous five years. The decrease in the housing price in Sydney was narrower, 2 per cent only, but still disappointing, compared to its 3% increase in the first half of 1990s.\n\nTo recap, there were significant differences in the housing market in those five cities in the last decade of the last century. While some experienced a long period of growth, the rest were subject to price fluctuations.","phrases":[{"en":"throughout the ten-year period","vi":"trong suốt giai đoạn mười năm"},{"en":"experienced a similar slump","vi":"trải qua mức sụt giảm tương tự"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-004-1"]},"_displayNo":"#004","author":"Mat Clark","source":"Mat Clark","summary":"Diagrams provide some information about the housing prices of five cities…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-005","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"Living alone in England","prompt":"The bar chart below shows the proportions of English men and women of different ages who were living alone in 2011. The pie chart compares the numbers of bedrooms in these one- person households.","answer":"The two charts give information about <strong class=\"key-phrase\">single-occupant households</strong> in England in the year 2011. The bar chart compares figures for occupants' age and gender, and the pie chart shows data about the number of bedrooms in these homes.\n\nOverall, females made up a higher proportion of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">people living alone</strong> than males, and this difference is particularly noticeable in the older age categories. We can also see that the most common number of bedrooms in a single-occupant home was two.\n\nA significant majority of the people aged 65 or over who were living alone in England in 2011 were female. Women made up around 72% of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">single occupants</strong> aged 75 to 84, and 76% of those aged 85 or over. By contrast, among younger adults the figures for males were higher. For example, in the 35-49 age category, men accounted for nearly 65% of people living alone.\n\nIn the same year, 35.4% of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">one-person households</strong> in England had two bedrooms, while one-bedroom and three-bedroom homes accounted for 28% and 29.8% of the total. Under 7% of single-occupant homes had four or more bedrooms.","phrases":[{"en":"single-occupant households","vi":"hộ chỉ có một người sinh sống"},{"en":"people living alone","vi":"người sống một mình"},{"en":"single occupants","vi":"người sống một mình"},{"en":"one-person households","vi":"hộ gia đình một người"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-005-1"]},"_displayNo":"#005","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Bar chart below shows the proportions of English men and women of different…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-006","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"Changes in house prices","prompt":"The chart below shows information about changes in average house prices in five different cities between 1990 and 2002 compared with the average house prices in 1989. 1990 – 2002 compared with 1989","answer":"The bar chart compares the cost of an average house in five major cities over a period of 13 years from 1989.\n\nWe can see that house prices fell overall between 1990 and 1995, but most of the cities saw rising prices between 1996 and 2002. London <strong class=\"key-phrase\">experienced by far the greatest changes in</strong> house prices over the 13-year period.\n\nOver the 5 years after 1989, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the cost of average homes</strong> in Tokyo and London dropped by around 7%, while New York house prices went down by 5%. By contrast, prices rose by approximately 2% in both Madrid and Frankfurt.\n\nBetween 1996 and 2002, London house prices jumped to around 12% above the 1989 average. Homebuyers in New York also had to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">pay significantly more</strong>, with prices rising to 5% above the 1989 average, but homes in Tokyo remained cheaper than they were in 1989. The cost of an average home in Madrid rose by a further 2%, while prices in Frankfurt remained stable.\n\nOverall, the later period was far more positive for sellers, especially in London and New York.","phrases":[{"en":"experienced by far the greatest changes in","vi":"trải qua những thay đổi lớn nhất trong"},{"en":"the cost of average homes","vi":"chi phí của những ngôi nhà trung bình"},{"en":"pay significantly more","vi":"trả nhiều hơn đáng kể"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-006-1"]},"_displayNo":"#006","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Chart below shows information about changes in average house prices in five…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-007","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"Transport incidents and injuries","prompt":"The chart below shows numbers of incidents and injuries per 100 million passenger miles travelled (PMT) by transportation type in 2002.","answer":"The bar chart compares the number of incidents and injuries for every 100 million passenger miles travelled on five different types of public transport in 2002.\n\nIt is clear that the most incidents and injuries took place on demand-response vehicles. By contrast, commuter rail services recorded by far the lowest figures.\n\nA total of 225 incidents and 173 injuries, per 100 million passenger miles travelled, took place on demand-response transport services. These figures were <strong class=\"key-phrase\">nearly three times as high as</strong> those for the second highest category, bus services. There were 76 incidents and 66 people were injured on buses.\n\nRail services experienced fewer problems. The number of incidents on light rail trains equalled the figure recorded for buses, but there were <strong class=\"key-phrase\">significantly fewer injuries</strong>, at only 39. Heavy rail services saw lower numbers of such events than light rail services, but commuter rail passengers were <strong class=\"key-phrase\">even less likely to experience problems</strong>. In fact, only 20 incidents and 17 injuries occurred on commuter trains.","phrases":[{"en":"nearly three times as high as","vi":"cao gần gấp ba lần"},{"en":"significantly fewer injuries","vi":"số ca chấn thương ít hơn đáng kể"},{"en":"even less likely to experience problems","vi":"thậm chí ít có khả năng gặp sự cố hơn"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-007-1"]},"_displayNo":"#007","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Chart below shows numbers of incidents and injuries per 100 million…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-008","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"Teen internet and gaming time","prompt":"The chart shows the amount of time that 10- to 15-year-olds in the UK spend chatting on the Internet and playing games on consoles on an average school day.","answer":"The bar chart compares the time spent by 10 to 15-year-olds in the UK on two activities, namely chatting online and playing computer games.\n\nOverall, we can see that playing computer games is marginally more popular than chatting on the Internet. However, completely different trends can be seen if we look at the specific figures for boys and girls.\n\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">Boys aged between 10 and 15</strong> clearly favour playing on games consoles over chatting online. According to the chart, while 85% of boys play computer games every day, only 55% chat online daily. Furthermore, the majority of boys play on their consoles for more than one hour each day, and 10% do this activity for four hours or more.\n\nBy contrast, girls prefer chatting online. Close to 70% of 10 to 15-year-old girls engage in online conversation each day, compared to about 50% of this cohort who play computer games. Of the girls who do play on consoles, most of them play for less than an hour, whereas most girls who chat online do so for more than one hour, and nearly 10% chat for four hours or more.","phrases":[{"en":"Boys aged between 10 and 15","vi":"Bé trai từ 10 đến 15 tuổi"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-008-1"]},"_displayNo":"#008","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Chart below shows the amount of","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-009","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"British tourist attractions","prompt":"The chart below shows the results of a survey of people who visited four types of tourist attraction in Britain in the year 1999.","answer":"The pie chart compares figures for visitors to four categories of tourist attraction and to five different theme parks in Britain in 1999.\n\nIt is clear that theme parks and museums/ galleries were the two most popular types of tourist attraction in that year. Blackpool Pleasure Beach received by far the highest proportion of visitors in the theme park sector.\n\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">Looking at the information in more detail</strong>, we can see that 38% of the surveyed visitors went to a theme park, and 37% of them went to a museum or gallery. By contrast, historic houses and monuments were visited by only 16% of the sample, while wildlife parks and zoos were <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the least popular</strong> of the four types of tourist attraction, with only 9% of visitors.\n\nIn the theme park sector, almost half of the people surveyed (47%) had been to Blackpool Pleasure Beach. Alton Towers was the second most popular amusement park, with 17% of the sample, followed by Pleasureland in Southport, with 16%. Finally, Chessington World of Adventures and Legoland Windsor had each welcomed 10% of the surveyed visitors.","phrases":[{"en":"Looking at the information in more detail","vi":"Nhìn vào thông tin chi tiết hơn"},{"en":"the least popular","vi":"ít phổ biến nhất"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-009-1"]},"_displayNo":"#009","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Chart below shows the results of a survey of people who visited four types…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-010","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"UK telephone calls","prompt":"The chart shows the total number of minutes, in billions, spent on three types of telephone calls in the UK between 1995 and 2002.","answer":"The bar chart compares the amount of time spent by people in the UK on three different types of phone call between 1995 and 2002.\n\nIt is clear that calls made via local, fixed lines were the most popular type, in terms of overall usage, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">throughout the period shown</strong>. The lowest figures on the chart are for mobile calls, but this category also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">saw the most dramatic increase in</strong> user minutes.\n\nIn 1995, people in the UK used fixed lines for a total of just over 70 billion minutes for local calls, and about half of that amount of time for national or international calls. By contrast, mobile phones were only used for around 4 billion minutes. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">Over the following four years</strong>, the figures for all three types of phone call increased steadily.\n\nBy 1999, the amount of time spent on local calls using landlines had <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reached a peak</strong> at 90 billion minutes. Subsequently, the figure for this category fell, but the rise in the other two types of phone call continued. In 2002, the number of minutes of national / international landline calls passed 60 billion, while the figure for mobiles rose to around 45 billion minutes.","phrases":[{"en":"throughout the period shown","vi":"trong suốt thời gian hiển thị"},{"en":"saw the most dramatic increase in","vi":"chứng kiến...tăng đáng kể nhất"},{"en":"Over the following four years","vi":"Trong bốn năm tiếp theo"},{"en":"reached a peak","vi":"đạt mức cao nhất"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-010-1"]},"_displayNo":"#010","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Chart below shows the total number of minutes (in billions) of telephone…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-011","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"Olympic medal totals","prompt":"The chart below shows the total number of Olympic medals won by twelve different countries.","answer":"The bar chart compares twelve countries in terms of the overall number of medals that they have won at the Olympic Games.\n\nIt is clear that the USA is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">by far the most successful</strong> Olympic medal winning nation. It is also noticeable that the figures for gold, silver and bronze medals won by any particular country <strong class=\"key-phrase\">tend to be fairly similar</strong>.\n\nThe USA has won a total of around 2,300 Olympic medals, including approximately 900 gold medals, 750 silver and 650 bronze. In second place on the all-time medals chart is the Soviet Union, with <strong class=\"key-phrase\">just over 1,000 medals</strong>. Again, the number of gold medals won by this country is slightly higher than the number of silver or bronze medals.\n\nOnly four other countries - the UK, France, Germany and Italy - have won more than 500 Olympic medals, all with similar proportions of each medal colour. Apart from the USA and the Soviet Union, China is the only other country with <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a noticeably higher proportion of gold medals</strong> (about 200) compared to silver and bronze (about 100 each).","phrases":[{"en":"by far the most successful","vi":"thành công vượt trội nhất"},{"en":"tend to be fairly similar","vi":"có xu hướng khá tương đồng"},{"en":"just over 1,000 medals","vi":"hơn 1.000 huy chương một chút"},{"en":"a noticeably higher proportion of gold medals","vi":"tỷ lệ huy chương vàng cao hơn rõ rệt"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-011-1"]},"_displayNo":"#011","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Chart below shows the total number of Olympic medals won by twelve…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-012","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"French and Indian age structures","prompt":"The charts below compare the age structure of the population of France and India in 1984.","answer":"The two charts compare the populations of France and India in terms of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">age distribution by gender</strong> in the year 1984.\n\nIt is clear that the population of India was younger than that of France in 1984, with a noticeably larger proportion of people aged under 20. France, on the other hand, had a significantly larger percentage of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">elderly inhabitants</strong>.\n\nIn India, close to 14% of people were aged 5 or under, and each five-year age bracket above this contained an increasingly smaller proportion of the population. France’s population, by contrast, was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more evenly distributed</strong> across the age ranges, with similar figures (around 7% to 8% of all people) for each five-year cohort between the ages of 0 and 40. Somewhere between 10% and 15% of all French people were aged 70 or older, but the equivalent figure for India was only 2%.\n\nLooking more closely at gender, there was a noticeably higher proportion of French women than men in every cohort from age 50 upwards. For example, almost 3% of French 70- to 75-year-olds were women, while just under 2% were men. No significant gender differences can be seen on the Indian population chart.","phrases":[{"en":"age distribution by gender","vi":"phân bố độ tuổi theo giới tính"},{"en":"elderly inhabitants","vi":"cư dân lớn tuổi"},{"en":"more evenly distributed","vi":"phân bổ đồng đều hơn"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-012-1"]},"_displayNo":"#012","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Charts below compare the age structure of the population of France and…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-013","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"Yemen and Italy populations","prompt":"The charts show the age structure of the populations of Yemen and Italy in 2000 and projections for 2050.","answer":"The pie charts compare the proportions of people falling into <strong class=\"key-phrase\">three distinct age groups</strong> in Yemen and Italy in two different years.\n\nIt is clear that Italy had the older population in the year 2000, and that the same is predicted for the year 2050. The populations of both countries are expected to age over the fifty-year period.\n\nIn the year 2000, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">just over half of</strong> the population of Yemen was aged 14 or under, while most Italians (61.6%) fell into the 15 to 59 age group, and only 14.3% were children under 15 years of age. People aged 60 or over accounted for almost a quarter of the Italian population, but only 3.6% of the inhabitants of Yemen.\n\nBy 2050, the proportion of children under 15 is predicted to drop in both countries, most noticeably in Yemen where the figure <strong class=\"key-phrase\">is expected to</strong> fall by 13.1%. On the other hand, the figures for elderly people are expected to rise, by 2.1% in Yemen and a massive 18.2% in Italy. Finally, it is anticipated that the 15 to 59 age group will grow by around 10% in Yemen, but shrink by around 15% in Italy.","phrases":[{"en":"three distinct age groups","vi":"ba nhóm tuổi riêng biệt"},{"en":"just over half of","vi":"chỉ hơn một nửa"},{"en":"is expected to","vi":"được dự đoán"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-013-1"]},"_displayNo":"#013","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Charts below give information on the ages of the populations of Yemen and…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-014","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"US travel patterns and problems","prompt":"The charts below show reasons for travel and the main issues for the travelling public in the US in 2009.","answer":"The bar chart and pie chart give information about why US residents travelled and what travel problems they experienced in the year 2009.\n\nIt is clear that the principal reason why Americans travelled in 2009 was to commute to and from work. In the same year, the primary concern of Americans, with regard to the trips they made, was the cost of travelling.\n\nLooking more closely at the bar chart, we can see that 49% of the trips made by Americans in 2009 were for the purpose of commuting. By contrast, only 6% of trips were visits to friends or relatives, and one in ten trips were for social or recreation reasons. Shopping was cited as the reason for 16% of all travel, while unspecified ’personal reasons’ <strong class=\"key-phrase\">accounted for the remaining</strong> 19%.\n\nAccording to the pie chart, price was the key consideration for 36% of American travellers. Almost one in five people cited safety as their foremost travel concern, while <strong class=\"key-phrase\">aggressive driving</strong> and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">highway congestion</strong> were the main issues for 17% and 14% of the travelling public. Finally, a total of 14% of those surveyed thought that access to public transport or space for pedestrians were the most important travel issues.","phrases":[{"en":"accounted for the remaining","vi":"chiếm phần còn lại"},{"en":"aggressive driving","vi":"lái xe quá khích, cẩu thả"},{"en":"highway congestion","vi":"tắc nghẽn đường cao tốc"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-014-1"]},"_displayNo":"#014","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Charts below show reasons for travel and the main issues for the travelling…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-015","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"Parkway Hotel customer service","prompt":"The charts show how visitors rated the Parkway Hotel's customer service in 2005 and 2010.","answer":"The pie charts compare visitors’ responses to a survey about customer service at the Parkway Hotel in 2005 and in 2010.\n\nIt is clear that overall <strong class=\"key-phrase\">customer satisfaction</strong> <strong class=\"key-phrase\">increased considerably</strong> from 2005 to 2010. While most hotel guests rated customer service as satisfactory or poor in 2005, a clear majority described the hotel’s service as good or excellent in 2010.\n\nLooking at the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">positive responses</strong> first, in 2005 only 5% of the hotel’s visitors rated its customer service as excellent, but this figure rose to 28% in 2010. Furthermore, while only 14% of guests described customer service in the hotel as good in 2005, almost three times as many people gave this rating five years later.\n\nWith regard to negative feedback, the proportion of guests who considered the hotel’s customer service to be poor fell from 21% in 2005 to only 12% in 2010. Similarly, the proportion of people who thought customer service was very poor dropped from 15% to only 4% over the 5-year period. Finally, a fall in the number of ’satisfactory’ ratings in 2010 reflects the fact that more people gave positive responses to the survey in that year.","phrases":[{"en":"customer satisfaction","vi":"mức độ hài lòng của khách hàng"},{"en":"increased considerably","vi":"tăng đáng kể"},{"en":"positive responses","vi":"phản hồi tích cực"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-015-1"]},"_displayNo":"#015","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Charts below show the results of a questionnaire that asked visitors to the…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-016","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"Children's sports spending","prompt":"The first chart shows British parents' spending on children's sports from 2008 to 2014, while the second shows the number of children participating in three sports.","answer":"The line graphs show the average monthly amount that parents in Britain spent on their children’s sporting activities and the number of British children who took part in three different sports from 2008 to 2014.\n\nIt is clear that parents spent more money each year on their children’s participation in sports over the six-year period. In terms of the number of children taking part, football was significantly more popular than athletics and swimming.\n\nIn 2008, British parents spent an average of around £20 per month on their children’s sporting activities. Parents’ spending on children’s sports <strong class=\"key-phrase\">increased gradually over the following six years</strong>, and by 2014 the average monthly amount had risen to just over £30.\n\nLooking at participation numbers, in 2008 approximately 8 million British children played football, while only 2 million children were enrolled in swimming clubs and less than 1 million practised athletics. The figures for football participation <strong class=\"key-phrase\">remained relatively stable</strong> over the following 6 years. By contrast, participation in swimming almost doubled, to nearly 4 million children, and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">there was a near fivefold increase in</strong> the number of children doing athletics.","phrases":[{"en":"increased gradually over the following six years","vi":"tăng dần trong sáu năm tiếp theo"},{"en":"remained relatively stable","vi":"giữ tương đối ổn định"},{"en":"there was a near fivefold increase in","vi":"có một sự tăng gần như gấp 5 lần trong"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-016-1"]},"_displayNo":"#016","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"First chart below gives information about the money spent by British…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-017","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"Oil use and employment","prompt":"Chart A below shows the rate of oil consumption (in millions of barrels) in a small country from 1950 to 2010. Chart B shows the number of people employed in the oil industry in that country, and also the rate of unemployment throughout the country over the same time. Write a report summarising the information. Select and describe the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The charts show the progress of oil consumption, oil sector employment and national unemployment in a nation between 1950 and 2010. Regarding oil consumption, this fluctuated around 20 million barrels per year until 1970, when it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">rose steadily</strong> to reach 40 million in 2000 and around 50 million by 2010. Looking at the data on oil industry jobs, we see that the growth in consumption was matched by a roughly similar threefold trend in employment in that sector. Numbers fluctuated around 1,000 people until 1970, before climbing consistently, passing 1,800 in 1980 and reaching 3,100 in 2010. However, turning to national unemployment, this figure declined progressively over the entire period, dropping from 4% in 1950 to 3.1% in 1980, and finally arriving at 1.6% by the last year in question. Overall, we can say that the rise in oil use in this country was reflected in an approximately corresponding rate of growth in people employed in the oil business. At the same time, total unemployment dropped by more than half.\n\nOverall, this provides a direct comparison and shows a clear overall pattern.","phrases":[{"en":"rose steadily","vi":"tăng đều"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-017-1"]},"_displayNo":"#017","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"Chart A below shows the rate of oil consumption (in millions of barrels) in…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-018","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"Train passengers and ticket prices","prompt":"The chart below shows the number of passengers arriving at a train station per hour across a day, and also the average price (in US Dollars) of their tickets. Write a report summarising the information. Select and describe the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The table gives data about <strong class=\"key-phrase\">passenger volumes</strong> reaching a station every 2 hours in a day, and also the average ticket cost at those times. Passenger numbers peak 3 times during the day. For example, the number at 6am is 480, rising to 690 by 8am before falling again. There is then a peak of 700 at midday, followed by an afternoon decline to a low of 230 at 4pm. A third spike is at 6pm, reaching 670 before tailing off. The ticket prices partially follow this pattern. The 8am passenger surge is matched by a high price of $29, followed by a peak of $31 at midday and a decrease to $17 by 4pm. However, the 6pm spike in passenger numbers is accompanied by a low of $11 in prices, with a subsequent rise to $22 at 8pm and a final levelling off. In summary, ticket prices increase broadly in line with passenger traffic, except during the evening rush hour when they actually fall.\n\nThe midday period combined the highest passenger total with the highest average fare.","phrases":[{"en":"passenger volumes","vi":"lượng hành khách"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-018-1"]},"_displayNo":"#018","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"Chart below shows the number of passengers arriving at a train station per…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-019","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"Youth spending and life milestones","prompt":"Charts 1 and 2 below show the proportion of income spent on different areas by young people in Canada and Poland. Chart 3 shows the average age of certain life events for these countries, and an estimated global average age. Write a report summarising the information. Select and describe the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The charts show the percentage of youth income spent on various areas in Poland and Canada, and also three key life events by age compared to an estimated global norm. Looking firstly at income, we see that in Canada the 2 highest areas of expense are leisure and clothing, at 20% and 19% respectively. The other areas (housing, food, transport and studies) are all <strong class=\"key-phrase\">roughly similar</strong>, at between 14% to 16%. In Poland, however, studies <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take almost half the expenditure</strong> at 43%, followed by transport at 26%. Leisure and clothing are similar at 10% and 11%, and housing/food are the same at 5%. Regarding life events, we see that, in Poland, leaving home and buying a car happen at an age close to the predicted global norm of around 26 years, whereas in Canada they happen much earlier at 20 years or just under. Getting married, by contrast, is similar in both countries at around 30 years, which is much later than the world average of just over 20. In summary, young people’s expenditure in Canada is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more evenly split</strong> than Poland, where transport and studies take the vast majority. Poland is closer to the global average than Canada in terms of life events.","phrases":[{"en":"roughly similar","vi":"xấp xỉ tương đương"},{"en":"take almost half the expenditure","vi":"chiếm gần một nửa tổng chi tiêu"},{"en":"more evenly split","vi":"được phân bổ đồng đều hơn"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-019-1","writing-academic-019-2"]},"_displayNo":"#019","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"Charts 1 and 2 below show the proportion of income spent on different areas…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-020","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"UK travel and destinations","prompt":"The charts below give information about travel to and from the UK, and about the most popular countries for UK residents to visit.\nSummarise the information by selecting and reporting the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The first diagram compares changes in the number of British tourists who travelled abroad with that of foreign visitors to the United Kingdom over the last 20 years of the previous century. According to the graph, the former initially stood at more than 12 million and grew six-fold at the end of the survey. In comparison, the latter number was slightly less than that of the British tourists at the beginning of this period and experienced similar yet less intensive trends, reaching approximately half as high by the end of the century.\n\nThe bar chart reveals the top 5 countries visited by the British in the last year of the above survey. It can be observed that while France and Spain absorbed the largest numbers of British tourists with about 11 and 9 million visits respectively, Turkey was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the least popular</strong> among the five, visited by only about 30% as many British as France.\n\nTo sum up, tourism from and to the United Kingdom boomed in the 1980s and 90s. Moreover, most of the trips made by the British abroad were to 5 countries only.","phrases":[{"en":"the least popular","vi":"ít phổ biến nhất"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-020-1"]},"_displayNo":"#020","author":"Ebrahim Tahasoni","source":"Ebrahim Tahasoni","summary":"Charts below give information about travel to and from the UK, and about…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-021","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"World spending and population","prompt":"The charts below give information about world spending and population.\nSummarise the information by selecting and reporting the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The first pie chart compares the shares of four major items in global expenditure. It is observed that the most significant amounts are paid for food (almost a quarter of global expenditure) and transport (almost 20%), while housing also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">accounts for a considerable proportion</strong>. The least among the four is spent on clothing (merely 6 percent) and the remaining 40% is spent on a variety of other items. The second diagram illustrates how <strong class=\"key-phrase\">global population is distributed</strong>. According to this chart, there is a significant difference between the population of Asia and that of other continents since 3 out of every 5 human beings live in Asia. Europe and the Americas share similar proportions and together are host to roughly one-third of the world’s population, while the inhabitants of Africa form a mere one-tenth. To sum up, four items are responsible for three-fifths of the overall spending around the world, the most prominent share being that of food. Moreover, the largest share of the world’s population lives in Asia, the population of which <strong class=\"key-phrase\">outnumbers that of the rest of the world</strong> by 3 to 2.","phrases":[{"en":"accounts for a considerable proportion","vi":"chiếm một tỷ trọng đáng kể"},{"en":"global population is distributed","vi":"dân số thế giới được phân bố"},{"en":"outnumbers that of the rest of the world","vi":"nhiều hơn dân số của phần còn lại thế giới"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-021-1"]},"_displayNo":"#021","author":"Ebrahim Tahasoni","source":"Ebrahim Tahasoni","summary":"Charts below give information about world spending and population.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-022","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"Rotterdam port exports","prompt":"The charts give information about the amount of exports (millions of tonnes) moving through Rotterdam port in Holland to various global destinations in 2002 and 2012; and also the % rates of tax imposed on these exports by the receiving countries. Write a report summarising the information. Select and describe the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The tables show us the quantity of exports being transported through Rotterdam over a ten year period, and the level of taxation imposed on the goods at destination. Regarding the volumes, total exports increased slightly, reaching 18,600 million tonnes by 2012. Within this total, however, most zones declined in volume. For example, Europe – the largest destination – declined from 6,900 million to 6,400 million, and the USA – the second highest – went down by roughly 10% to 3,900 million. China dipped slightly to 2,300 million, and Latin America dropped from 1,800 to 1,500 million. The ’other’ zones remained static at 350 million. By marked contrast, volumes to Asia Pacific and Australasia more than trebled, hitting 2,550 and 2,300 million tonnes respectively. Turning to taxation, we see that tax <strong class=\"key-phrase\">increased considerably</strong> in all the zones that showed a decline in volumes, reaching 2% in the USA, China and Latin America, and rising from 5% to 8% in\n\nEurope. The ’other’ zones kept tax stable at 2%, while the growth zones reduced tax massively, from 5% to 2% in Asia Pacific and a fourfold decrease to 1% in Australasia. In summary, the decade showed a clear connection between increased export volumes and reduced levels of tax.","phrases":[{"en":"increased considerably","vi":"tăng đáng kể"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-022-1"]},"_displayNo":"#022","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"Charts give information about the amount of exports (millions of tonnes)…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-023","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"Urban traffic speed and fatalities","prompt":"The charts show (Chart a) the average speed of urban zone traffic (in kilometres per hour or kph) in a number of countries over a fifty year period, including a future estimate; and also (Chart b) the total number of urban zones per country (in thousands.) Write a report summarising the information. Select and describe the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The charts show the average velocity of city traffic over a fifty year timescale, with a forecast for the future, and also the number of urban zones by country. We can see that the general trend is for the speed to increase and then decrease. For example, in France, it increased from 60 kph in 1970 to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a peak of</strong> 86 kph in 1990, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">tailing off to</strong> a forecast 52 kph in 2020. Similarly, we see the USA peak at 57 kph in 1990, declining to 43 kph at the end. The UK and Russia have a similar trend, rising to 56 and 72 kph respectively in 2010 before falling to below the starting level. The same happens in Canada with a decline from 69 kph to 64 kph despite a peak of 73 kph. Chile, however, fluctuates around 51 kph, but remains static over the period. Italy, Brazil and Spain, by contrast, show <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a clear rise</strong>, finishing at 58, 57 and 61 kph respectively. Regarding urban zones, all countries except one see predicted increases of roughly four times by 2020. The exception is Russia, which sees a fall of about half to 3,200. Overall, the data <strong class=\"key-phrase\">does not suggest any correlation</strong> between increasing urban zones and average traffic speeds.","phrases":[{"en":"a peak of","vi":"mức đỉnh là"},{"en":"tailing off to","vi":"giảm dần xuống"},{"en":"a clear rise","vi":"mức tăng rõ rệt"},{"en":"does not suggest any correlation","vi":"không cho thấy mối tương quan nào"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-023-1"]},"_displayNo":"#023","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"Charts show (Chart a) the average speed of urban zone traffic (in…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-024","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"Airline crews and passenger capacity","prompt":"The first chart below shows the number of airline crew (pilots, stewards etc) needed to fly a passenger plane between Australia and a number of other countries. The second chart shows the number of passenger complaints per plane journey made on these routes, and average kilogram (kg) weight of luggage (or baggage) carried per passenger. Write a report summarising the information. Select and describe the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The charts give data about four flight destinations from Australia in terms of crew numbers, passenger complaints made and luggage weight per passenger. The largest crew (15 people) is needed for the flight to Germany, followed by Indonesia (11) and Malaysia (8.) The destination requiring the least crew per plane is New Zealand (with a crew of 6). This trend is reflected in the weight of luggage per passenger, with Germany having <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the heaviest baggage</strong> at 38 kg, and Indonesia the second heaviest at 32 kg. Malaysia flights carry 30 kg per passenger, and New Zealand has the lightest figure at 15 kg. However, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the pattern for customer complaints is reversed</strong>, with New Zealand flights having the most complaints (6 per flight) followed by Indonesia and Malaysia with 3 each. Flights to Germany have the fewest complaints, with only 1 per flight. Overall, it is apparent that flights to Germany require the most crew and baggage, while those to New Zealand require the least. However, passengers to Germany make the least complaints, while flights to New Zealand cause the most complaints. The Malaysia and Indonesia flights <strong class=\"key-phrase\">lie roughly between these two extremes</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"the heaviest baggage","vi":"lượng hành lý nặng nhất"},{"en":"the pattern for customer complaints is reversed","vi":"xu hướng về khiếu nại của khách hàng đảo ngược"},{"en":"lie roughly between these two extremes","vi":"nằm xấp xỉ giữa hai mức cực trị này"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-024-1"]},"_displayNo":"#024","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"First chart below shows the number of airline crew (pilots, stewards etc)…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-025","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Culture","title":"US violent crime","prompt":"The line chart below shows serious violent crime levels from 1978 to 2000 in the US. Serious violent crimes include rape, robbery, aggravated assault and homicide. Summarise the information by selecting and reporting the main features and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"In the first ten years, there were fluctuations in the total crime level, but the overall trend was upbeat. By about 1989, it rose to a record high, around 4.5 offences per thousand Americans, half the figure in 1980 (slightly over 3 offences), the lowest level recorded during the period. Victimisations rose and fell at a lower level between 2 and 2.5 offences over the same period, while crimes recorded by police showed a steady increase, reaching its highest in the year 1994, over 1.5 offences in a thousand. The arrest rate was the lowest, levelling off below 0.5 offences per 1,000.\n\nFrom 1988 onwards, the total violent crime level <strong class=\"key-phrase\">declined gradually</strong>, so did victimisations reported to police. In 2000, 3 out of a thousand Americans committed violent crime, while half as many victims were reported to the police. As to crimes recorded by police and arrests for violent crime, both dropped slightly in the last five years and the figures were 1.5 and 0.5 offences respectively in 2000.\n\nOverall, the violent crime rate, as well as victimisations reported to police, crimes recorded and arrests for violent crime, was not subject to strong fluctuations in the final two decades of the last century, although by the end of the century, there was a trend toward lower violent crime levels.","phrases":[{"en":"declined gradually","vi":"giảm dần"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-025-1"]},"_displayNo":"#025","author":"Mat Clark","source":"Mat Clark","summary":"Line chart below shows serious violent crime levels from 1978 to 2000 in…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-026","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Economy","title":"Fairtrade coffee and banana sales","prompt":"The tables below give information about sales of Fairtrade-labelled coffee and bananas in 1999 and 2004 in five European countries.","answer":"The tables show the amount of money spent on Fairtrade coffee and bananas in two separate years in the UK, Switzerland, Denmark, Belgium and Sweden.\n\nIt is clear that sales of Fairtrade coffee rose in all five European countries from 1999 to 2004, but sales of Fairtrade bananas only went up in three <strong class=\"key-phrase\">out of the five countries</strong>. Overall, the UK saw by far <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the highest levels of spending</strong> on the two products.\n\nIn 1999, Switzerland had the highest sales of Fairtrade coffee, at €3 million, while revenue from Fairtrade bananas was highest in the UK, at €15 million. By 2004, however, sales of Fairtrade coffee in the UK had risen to €20 million, and this was over <strong class=\"key-phrase\">three times higher than</strong> Switzerland’s sales figure for Fairtrade coffee in that year. The year 2004 also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">saw dramatic increases in</strong> the money spent on Fairtrade bananas in the UK and Switzerland, with revenues rising by €32 million and €4.5 million respectively.\n\nSales of the two Fairtrade products were far lower in Denmark, Belgium and Sweden. Small increases in sales of Fairtrade coffee can be seen, but revenue remained at €2 million or below in all three countries in both years. Finally, it is noticeable that the money spent on Fairtrade bananas actually fell in Belgium and Sweden.","phrases":[{"en":"out of the five countries","vi":"Trong số năm quốc gia"},{"en":"the highest levels of spending","vi":"mức chi tiêu cao nhất cho"},{"en":"three times higher than","vi":"cao gấp ba lần so với"},{"en":"saw dramatic increases in","vi":"ghi nhận mức tăng đáng kể về"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-026-1"]},"_displayNo":"#026","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Tables below give information about sales of Fairtrade*-labelled coffee and…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-027","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Education","title":"Education and science participation","prompt":"The charts below show the levels of participation in education and science in developing and industrialised countries in 1980 and 1990.","answer":"The three bar charts show <strong class=\"key-phrase\">average years of schooling</strong>, numbers of scientists and technicians, and research and development spending in developing and developed countries. Figures are given for 1980 and 1990.\n\nIt is clear from the charts that the figures for developed countries are much higher than those for developing nations. Also, the charts <strong class=\"key-phrase\">show an overall increase in</strong> participation in education and science from 1980 to 1990.\n\nPeople in developing nations attended school for an average of around 3 years, with only a slight increase in years of schooling from 1980 to 1990. On the other hand, the figure for industrialised countries rose from nearly 9 years of schooling in 1980 to nearly 11 years in 1990.\n\nFrom 1980 to 1990, the number of scientists and technicians in industrialised countries almost doubled to about 70 per 1000 people. Spending on research and development also saw rapid growth in these countries, reaching $350 billion in 1990. By contrast, the number of science workers in developing countries remained below 20 per 1000 people, and research spending fell from about $50 billion to only $25 billion.","phrases":[{"en":"average years of schooling","vi":"số năm đi học trung bình"},{"en":"show an overall increase in","vi":"cho thấy sự gia tăng tổng thể"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-027-1"]},"_displayNo":"#027","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Charts below show the levels of participation in education and science in…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-028","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Education","title":"UK school spending","prompt":"The three pie charts below show how the changes in annual spending by a particular UK schools in 1981, 1991, and 2001.","answer":"The pie charts compare the expenditure of a school in the UK in three different years over a 20-year period.\n\nIt is clear that teachers’ salaries <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made up the largest proportion of</strong> the school’s spending in all three years (1981, 1991 and 2001). By contrast, insurance was the smallest cost in each year.\n\nIn 1981, 40% of the school’s budget went on teachers’ salaries. This figure rose to 50% in 1991, but fell again by 5% in 2001. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">The proportion of spending on</strong> other workers’ wages <strong class=\"key-phrase\">fell steadily</strong> over the 20-year period, from 28% of the budget in 1981 to only 15% in 2001.\n\nExpenditure on insurance stood at only 2% of the total in 1981, but reached 8% in 2001. Finally, the percentages for resources and furniture/equipment fluctuated. The figure for resources was highest in 1991, at 20%, and the proportion of spending on furniture and equipment <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reached its peak</strong> in 2001, at 23%.\n\nAcross the period, staffing remained the dominant expense despite the changes in the smaller categories.","phrases":[{"en":"made up the largest proportion of","vi":"chiếm tỷ trọng lớn nhất"},{"en":"The proportion of spending on","vi":"Tỷ trọng chi tiêu cho"},{"en":"fell steadily","vi":"giảm đều"},{"en":"reached its peak","vi":"đạt mức cao nhất"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-028-1"]},"_displayNo":"#028","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Three pie charts below show how the changes in annual spending by a…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-029","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Education","title":"School layout redevelopment","prompt":"The two pictures compare the layout of a school as it was in the year 2004 with a proposed site design for the year 2024.","answer":"In 2004, there were 600 pupils attending the school, and the two school buildings were separated by a path running from the main entrance to the sports field. By 2024, it is expected that there will be 1000 pupils, and a third building will have been constructed. Furthermore, the plan is to join the two original buildings together, creating a shorter path that links the buildings only.\n\nAs the third building and a second car park will be built on the site of the original sports field, a new, smaller sports field will need to be laid. A new road will also be built from the main entrance to the second car park. Finally, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">no changes will be made to</strong> the main entrance and original car park.\n\nOverall, this provides a direct comparison and shows a clear overall pattern.\n\nThe proposed design therefore increases capacity mainly by replacing open space with buildings and transport access.","phrases":[{"en":"no changes will be made to","vi":"sẽkhông có thay đổi nào được thực hiện đối với"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-029-1"]},"_displayNo":"#029","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Two pictures compare the layout of a school as it was in the year 2004 with…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-030","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Education","title":"Children's TV and academic results","prompt":"This tables show data about the amount of television watched by children in different countries (hours per day) and also the average academic achievement of people in these countries (% of people completing each level.) Write a report summarising the information. Select and describe the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The chart gives facts about the daily TV use by children in various countries, plus the proportion finishing 3 levels of education. Regarding hours per day watching TV, the USA, Canada and the UK have the highest hours at 4. China and Italy are the next highest with 3, Brazil and India stand at 2 each, and Malta and the UAE have only 1 hour per day, which is a quarter of the maximum recorded. Turning to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">academic achievement</strong>, we see that 100% of children completed school in Italy, Canada and Malta. The other countries are all in the 90’s, except India which is 80%. High school completion <strong class=\"key-phrase\">ranges from</strong> 100% in Malta to levels in the 90’s (Italy, Canada, UAE) and the 80’s (UK, USA and Brazil.) China and India have the lowest levels, with 68% and 60% respectively. For University completion, the UK has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the highest level</strong> at 39%, followed by Canada (32%) and the USA (29%.) Italy, China and Brazil are all in the mid 20% range. The lowest figures here are for Malta and the UAE (18% and 19% respectively) and finally India with only 12%. In summary, TV use and education levels vary widely. It is noticeable, though, that the countries with the highest hours of TV per day are also those with the highest % levels of University attainment.","phrases":[{"en":"academic achievement","vi":"thành tích học tập"},{"en":"ranges from","vi":"dao động từ"},{"en":"the highest level","vi":"mức cao nhất"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-030-1"]},"_displayNo":"#030","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"This tables show data about the amount of television watched by children in…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-031","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Environment","title":"European waste management","prompt":"The chart below compares levels of recycling, as well as some less environmentally friendly forms of waste management, in fifteen European countries.","answer":"The bar chart shows the percentage of waste that is recycled, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">put into landfill</strong> or incinerated in various EU countries.\n\nIf we look at the fifteen EU countries as a whole, it is clear that more waste <strong class=\"key-phrase\">goes to landfill sites</strong> than to any other <strong class=\"key-phrase\">refuse management facility</strong>. In fact, while around half of the countries put the majority of their waste into landfill sites, only two countries recycle at least 50% of the waste that they produce.\n\nAustria and Belgium are the most <strong class=\"key-phrase\">environmentally friendly</strong> of the fifteen countries, recycling around 60% and 50% of their waste respectively. Germany, Sweden and Belgium also appear to have effective recycling programmes, resulting in roughly 40% of waste being processed in this way in each country.\n\nOther EU countries recycle far less. Greece, Ireland and the UK, for example, only recycle around 10% of refuse, and put between 80 and 90 per cent of their waste into landfill. Finally, while most <strong class=\"key-phrase\">non-recycled waste</strong> in the EU area goes to landfill, four countries, namely Luxembourg, Sweden, the Netherlands and Denmark, incinerate more waste than they bury.","phrases":[{"en":"put into landfill","vi":"đưa vàobãi chôn lấp"},{"en":"goes to landfill sites","vi":"được chuyển đến các bãichôn lấp"},{"en":"refuse management facility","vi":"cơ sở quản lý rác thải"},{"en":"environmentally friendly","vi":"thân thiện với môi trường"},{"en":"non-recycled waste","vi":"chất thải không tái chế"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-031-1"]},"_displayNo":"#031","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Chart below compares levels of recycling, as well as some less…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-032","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Environment","title":"Waste paper recycling","prompt":"The chart below shows the process of waste paper recycling. The flow chart shows how waste paper is recycled.","answer":"It is clear that there are six distinct stages in this process, from the initial collection of waste paper to the eventual production of usable paper.\n\nAt the first stage in the paper recycling process, waste paper is collected either from paper banks, where members of the public leave their used paper, or directly from businesses. This paper is then sorted by hand and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">separated according to</strong> its grade, with any paper that is not suitable for recycling being removed. Next, the graded paper <strong class=\"key-phrase\">is transported to</strong> a paper mill.\n\nStages four and five of the process both involve cleaning. The paper is cleaned and pulped, and foreign objects such as staples <strong class=\"key-phrase\">are taken out</strong>. Following this, all remnants of ink and glue are removed from the paper at the de-inking stage. Finally, the pulp can be processed in a paper making machine, which makes the end product: usable paper.","phrases":[{"en":"separated according to","vi":"được phân loại theo"},{"en":"is transported to","vi":"được vận chuyển đến"},{"en":"are taken out","vi":"bị loại bỏ"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-032-1"]},"_displayNo":"#032","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Chart below shows the process of waste paper recycling.","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-033","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Environment","title":"The water cycle","prompt":"The diagram below shows the water cycle, which is the continuous movement of water on, above and below the surface of the Earth.","answer":"The picture illustrates the way in which water passes from ocean to air to land during the natural process known as the water cycle.\n\nThree main stages are shown on the diagram. Ocean water evaporates, falls as rain, and eventually runs back into the oceans again.\n\nBeginning at the evaporation stage, we can see that 80% of water vapour in the air comes from the oceans. Heat from the sun causes water to evaporate, and water vapour condenses to form clouds. At the second stage, labelled ’precipitation’ on the diagram, water falls as rain or snow.\n\nAt the third stage in the cycle, rainwater may take various paths. Some of it may fall into lakes or return to the oceans via ’surface runoff’. Otherwise, rainwater may <strong class=\"key-phrase\">filter through the ground</strong>, reaching <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the impervious layer of the earth</strong>. Salt water intrusion is shown to take place just before groundwater passes into the oceans to complete the cycle.","phrases":[{"en":"filter through the ground","vi":"lọc qua mặt đất"},{"en":"the impervious layer of the earth","vi":"lớp không thấm nước của trái đất"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-033-1"]},"_displayNo":"#033","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Diagram below shows the water cycle, which is the continuous movement of…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-034","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Environment","title":"Global water use","prompt":"The graph and table below give information about water use worldwide and water consumption in two different countries.","answer":"The charts compare the amount of water used for agriculture, industry and homes around the world, and water use in Brazil and the Democratic Republic of Congo.\n\nIt is clear that global water needs <strong class=\"key-phrase\">rose significantly</strong> between 1900 and 2000, and that agriculture <strong class=\"key-phrase\">accounted for the largest proportion of</strong> water used. We can also see that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">water consumption</strong> was considerably higher in Brazil than in the Congo.\n\nIn 1900, around 500km³ of water was used by the agriculture sector worldwide. The figures for industrial and domestic water consumption stood at around one fifth of that amount. By 2000, global water use for agriculture had increased to around 3000km³, industrial water use had risen to just under half that amount, and domestic consumption had reached approximately 500km³.\n\nIn the year 2000, the populations of Brazil and the Congo were 176 million and 5.2 million respectively. Water consumption per person in Brazil, at 359m³, was much higher than that in the Congo, at only 8m³, and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">this could be explained by the fact that</strong> Brazil had 265 times more irrigated land.","phrases":[{"en":"rose significantly","vi":"tăng đáng kể"},{"en":"accounted for the largest proportion of","vi":"chiếm tỷ trọng lớn nhất trong"},{"en":"water consumption","vi":"sự tiêu thụ nước"},{"en":"this could be explained by the fact that","vi":"điều này có thể được giải thích bởi thực tế là"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-034-1"]},"_displayNo":"#034","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Graph and table below give information about water use worldwide and water…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-035","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Environment","title":"Waste produced by three companies","prompt":"The graph shows the amounts of waste produced by three companies between 2000 and 2015.","answer":"The line graph compares three companies in terms of their waste output between the years 2000 and 2015.\n\nIt is clear that there were significant changes in the amounts of waste produced by all three companies shown on the graph. While companies A and B saw waste output fall over the 15-year period, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the amount of waste produced</strong> by company C <strong class=\"key-phrase\">increased considerably</strong>.\n\nIn 2000, company A produced 12 tonnes of waste, while companies B and C produced around 8 tonnes and 4 tonnes of waste material respectively. Over the following 5 years, the waste output of companies B and C rose by around 2 tonnes, but the figure for company A fell by approximately 1 tonne.\n\nFrom 2005 to 2015, company A cut waste production by roughly 3 tonnes, and company B reduced its waste by around 7 tonnes. By contrast, company C <strong class=\"key-phrase\">saw an increase in</strong> waste production of approximately 4 tonnes over the same 10-year period. By 2015, company C’s waste output had risen to 10 tonnes, while the respective amounts of waste from companies A and B had dropped to 8 tonnes and only 3 tonnes.","phrases":[{"en":"the amount of waste produced","vi":"lượng chất thải thải ra"},{"en":"increased considerably","vi":"tăng đáng kể"},{"en":"saw an increase in","vi":"thấy sự tăng lên trong"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-035-1"]},"_displayNo":"#035","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Graph below shows the amounts of waste produced by three companies over a…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-036","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Environment","title":"Water use by sector","prompt":"The pie charts compare water use in San Diego County, California and worldwide.","answer":"The pie charts give information about the water used for residential, industrial and agricultural purposes in San Diego County, California, and the world as a whole.\n\nIt is noticeable that more water is consumed by homes than by industry or agriculture in the two American regions. By contrast, agriculture accounts for the vast majority of water used worldwide.\n\nIn San Diego County and California State, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">residential water consumption</strong> accounts for 60% and 39% of total water usage. By contrast, a mere 8% of the water used globally goes to homes. The opposite trend can be seen when we look at <strong class=\"key-phrase\">water consumption for agriculture</strong>. This accounts for a massive 69% of global water use, but only 17% and 28% of water usage in San Diego and California respectively.\n\nSuch dramatic differences are not seen when we compare the figures for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">industrial water use</strong>. The same proportion of water (23%) is used by industry in San Diego and worldwide, while the figure for California is 10% higher, at 33%.","phrases":[{"en":"residential water consumption","vi":"lượng nước tiêu thụ của khu dân cư"},{"en":"water consumption for agriculture","vi":"lượng nước tiêu thụ cho nông nghiệp"},{"en":"industrial water use","vi":"lượng nước sử dụng trong công nghiệp"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-036-1"]},"_displayNo":"#036","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Pie charts below compare water usage in San Diego, California and","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-037","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Environment","title":"Waste production by country","prompt":"The table below shows the amount of waste production (in millions of tonnes) in six different countries over a twenty-year period.","answer":"The chart compares the amounts of waste that were produced in six countries in the years 1980, 1990 and 2000.\n\nIn each of these years, the US produced more waste than Ireland, Japan, Korea, Poland and Portugal combined. It is also noticeable that Korea was the only country that managed to reduce its waste output by the year 2000.\n\nBetween 1980 and 2000, waste production in the US rose from 131 to 192 million tonnes, and rising trends were also seen in Japan, Poland and Portugal. Japan’s waste output increased from 28 to 53 million tonnes, while Poland and Portugal <strong class=\"key-phrase\">saw waste totals increase</strong> from 4 to 6.6 and from 2 to 5 million tonnes respectively.\n\nThe trends for Ireland and Korea were noticeably different from those described above. In Ireland, waste production <strong class=\"key-phrase\">increased more than eightfold</strong>, from only 0.6 million tonnes in 1980 to 5 million tonnes in 2000. Korea, by contrast, cut its waste output by 12 million tonnes between 1990 and 2000.\n\nThe gap between the United States and the other five countries remained substantial throughout the period.","phrases":[{"en":"saw waste totals increase","vi":"thấy tổng lượng chất thải tăng lên"},{"en":"increased more than eightfold","vi":"tăng hơn támlần"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-037-1"]},"_displayNo":"#037","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Table below shows the amount of waste production (in millions of tonnes) in…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-038","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Environment","title":"Hydroelectricity production","prompt":"The diagram below shows the process of using water to produce electricity.\nSummarise the information by selecting and reporting the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The picture explains the process through which water is used to produce electrical power. All in all, it comprises over ten stages. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">The process begins when</strong> seawater is heated by the sun and evaporates to form small clouds in the sky. Next, they merge into a storm could, which then rains over the mountain. This rainwater is gathered in the reservoir behind a dam. To following steps involve a pipe which connects the reservoir to a turbine as well as a pump, and is controlled using a valve. Once this valve is opened, water flows into the turbine and rotates it to produce electrical current, following which it is pumped back into the reservoir. After this, the electricity produced by the turbine is transferred to the transformer station though high voltage cables. The last stage is when the electrical power being delivered to domestic and industrial consumers as well as educational and medical facilities. Overall, hydroelectric power is generated using water from the sea through a relatively sophisticated procedure.\n\nOverall, this provides a direct comparison and shows a clear overall pattern.","phrases":[{"en":"The process begins when","vi":"quy trình bắt đầu khi"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-038-1"]},"_displayNo":"#038","author":"Ebrahim Tahasoni","source":"Ebrahim Tahasoni","summary":"Diagram below shows the process of using water to produce electricity.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-039","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Environment","title":"Transport carbon emissions","prompt":"The table compares carbon dioxide emissions from transport in several European countries in 1994 and 2004.","answer":"Germany, although having higher emissions than either the United Kingdom or France did, saw the amount decrease slightly from 47.2 to 46.7 million tonnes. By comparison, France recorded an increase of four million tonnes from 34.7 million in 1994, while the United Kingdom had a smaller growth, 2.5 million tonnes over the same period.\n\nIn all the three countries, road transport was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">responsible for the majority of emissions</strong>. In the United Kingdom, road transport produced emissions up to 32.6 million tonnes in 2004, 2 million more than ten years earlier, while other three transport sources did not show any remarkable growth. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">A similar pattern was seen</strong> in France, where road transport added 3.6 million tonnes to the total emissions within ten years. Germany, by contrast, was the only country of the three to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">experience a drop in</strong> road transport emissions. Other three transport sources had a lower emission volume as well, except civil aviation, with the amount rising to 1.2 million.\n\nAs shown in the table, both UK and France <strong class=\"key-phrase\">failed to reduce carbon dioxide emissions</strong> from transport sources during the period 1994 to 2004, in contrast to the decrease in Germany. Road transport continued to account for the biggest source of emissions.","phrases":[{"en":"responsible for the majority of emissions","vi":"gây ra phần lớn lượng khí thải"},{"en":"a similar pattern was seen","vi":"một xu hướng tương tự được ghi nhận"},{"en":"experience a drop in","vi":"ghi nhận mức giảm về"},{"en":"failed to reduce carbon dioxide emissions","vi":"không giảm được lượng khí thải carbon dioxide"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-039-1"]},"_displayNo":"#039","author":"Mat Clark","source":"Mat Clark","summary":"Table below shows carbon dioxide emissions from transport in three","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-040","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Environment","title":"Urban waste sorting","prompt":"Write a description of how urban refuse is assorted for recycling. Use the information in the diagram and write a description of this process.","answer":"Collecting and processing recyclables plays an important role in the treatment of urban refuse. The first step is collecting recyclables from rubbish bins. Three main types of recyclables are bottles (plastic or glass), paper and durables. If recyclables have already been put in the right rubbish bins, it will save plenty of time that is otherwise required for the second stage.\n\nIn the second stage, material recovery facilities will sort the recyclables more carefully. Part of recyclables will be sent to some customers for their own use. For example, soft drink companies have their own recycling facilities to take advantage of the soft drink containers collected. Newspapers and paper towels can be sent to paper and pulp mills.\n\nThe rest of recyclables will be cleaned, separated and smashed as the third part of the recycling loop, known as further-processing stage. The recycled materials produced are sold to different businesses. For example, engineering companies are regular buyers of aluminium, while property developers will buy glass or plastic for various usages.\n\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">At the final stage</strong>, all the recycled materials will become part of the items used by households daily. Once those items are disposed, it is expected that households will put them in appropriate rubbish bins. It is how the recycling loop keeps operating.","phrases":[{"en":"At the final stage","vi":"ở giai đoạn cuối"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-040-1"]},"_displayNo":"#040","author":"Mat Clark","source":"Mat Clark","summary":"Write a description of how urban refuse is assorted for recycling.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-041","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Digital game sales","prompt":"The bar graph shows the global sales (in billions of dollars) of different types of digital games","answer":"The bar chart compares the turnover in dollars from sales of video games for four different platforms, namely mobile phones, online, consoles and handheld devices, from 2000 to 2006.\n\nIt is clear that sales of games for three out of the four platforms rose each year, leading to a significant rise in total global turnover over the 7-year period. Sales figures for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">handheld games</strong> were at least twice as high as those for any other platform in almost every year.\n\nIn 2000, worldwide sales of handheld games stood at around $11 billion, while console games earned just under $6 billion. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">No figures are given for</strong> mobile or online games in that year. Over the next 3 years, sales of handheld video games rose by about $4 billion, but the figure for consoles decreased by $2 billion. Mobile phone and online games started to become popular, with sales reaching around $3 billion in 2003.\n\nIn 2006, sales of handheld, online and mobile games reached peaks of 17, 9 and 7 billion dollars respectively. By contrast, turnover from console games <strong class=\"key-phrase\">dropped to its lowest point</strong>, at around $2.5 billion.","phrases":[{"en":"handheld games","vi":"trò chơi cầm tay"},{"en":"No figures are given for","vi":"Không có số liệu nào được đưa ra cho"},{"en":"dropped to its lowest point","vi":"giảm xuống điểm thấp nhất"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-041-1"]},"_displayNo":"#041","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Bar graph shows the global sales (in billions of dollars) of different…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-042","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Coffee production","prompt":"The diagram below shows how coffee is produced and prepared for sale in supermarkets and shops.","answer":"The picture illustrates the process of coffee manufacture and preparation for sale on the market.\n\nIt is clear that there are 11 stages in the production of coffee. The process begins with the picking of coffee beans, and ends at the packing stage.\n\nLooking at the coffee production process in detail, coffee beans must first be picked in the fields. These beans are then dried, roasted, and cooled before being put in a grinding machine, which turns the beans into <strong class=\"key-phrase\">coffee granules</strong>.\n\nAt the sixth stage in the process, the ground coffee <strong class=\"key-phrase\">is mixed with</strong> hot water, and the resulting mixture <strong class=\"key-phrase\">is strained</strong>. Next, the mixture is frozen and then passed once again through the grinder. After that, the ground, frozen liquid is dried in a vacuum so that the water evaporates, leaving the coffee granules. Finally, these granules are packed into coffee jars for delivery to shops.\n\nThus, the beans pass through heating, cooling, mixing, freezing and drying before the finished product is packaged.","phrases":[{"en":"coffee granules","vi":"hạt cà phê hòa tan"},{"en":"is mixed with","vi":"được trộn với"},{"en":"is strained","vi":"được lọc"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-042-1"]},"_displayNo":"#042","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Diagram below shows how coffee is produced and prepared for sale in…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-043","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Weather forecasting process","prompt":"The diagram below shows how the Australian Bureau of Meteorology collects up-to-the- minute information on the weather in order to produce reliable forecasts","answer":"The figure illustrates the process used by the Australian Bureau of Meteorology to forecast the weather.\n\nThere are four stages in the process, beginning with the collection of information about the weather. This information is then analysed, prepared for presentation, and finally <strong class=\"key-phrase\">broadcast to the public</strong>.\n\nLooking at the first and second stages of the process, there are three ways of collecting weather data and three ways of analysing it. Firstly, incoming information can be received by satellite and presented for analysis as a satellite photo. The same data can also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">be passed to</strong> a radar station and presented on a radar screen or synoptic chart. Secondly, incoming information may be collected directly by radar and analysed on a radar screen or synoptic chart. Finally, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">drifting buoys</strong> also receive data which can be shown on a synoptic chart.\n\nAt the third stage of the process, the weather broadcast is prepared on computers. Finally, it is delivered to the public on television, on the radio, or as a recorded telephone announcement.","phrases":[{"en":"broadcast to the public","vi":"phát sóng tới công chúng"},{"en":"be passed to","vi":"được chuyển đến"},{"en":"drifting buoys","vi":"phao trôi"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-043-1"]},"_displayNo":"#043","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Diagram below shows how the Australian Bureau of Meteorology collects…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-044","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Salmon life cycle","prompt":"The diagram below shows the life cycle of a salmon, from egg to adult fish.","answer":"The diagram illustrates the stages in the life of the salmon, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">from birth to maturity</strong>.\n\nIt is clear that there are six main stages as the salmon develops from egg to mature adult. We can also see that salmon spend time in three distinct locations during the cycle, moving from river to estuary to ocean and then back upstream.\n\nSalmon begin their lives in rivers where the adult fish lay and incubate their eggs. After emerging from eggs, the young salmon spend the next stage of their lives being reared in freshwater areas. Then, at some point in their development, the fish swim downstream to river estuaries where rearing continues.\n\nFollowing the estuary rearing period, the maturing salmon migrate to the ocean, where they eventually become fully grown adults. Finally, the adult fish travel back upstream to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">spawning areas</strong> of rivers; here they reproduce and lay their eggs, and the life cycle begins anew.","phrases":[{"en":"from birth to maturity","vi":"từ khi sinh ra đến khi trưởng thành"},{"en":"spawning areas","vi":"khu vực sinh sản"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-044-1"]},"_displayNo":"#044","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Diagram below shows the life cycle of a salmon, from egg to adult fish.","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-045","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Honey bee life cycle","prompt":"The diagram shows the life cycle of a honey bee. The diagram illustrates the various stages in the life of a honey bee.","answer":"We can see that the complete life cycle lasts between 34 and 36 days. It is also noticeable that there are five main stages in the development of the honey bee, from egg to mature adult insect.\n\nThe life cycle of the honey bee begins when the female adult lays an egg; the female typically lays one or two eggs every 3 days. Between 9 and 10 days later, each egg hatches and the immature insect, or nymph, appears.\n\nDuring the third stage of the life cycle, the nymph <strong class=\"key-phrase\">grows in size</strong> and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">sheds its skin</strong> three times. This moulting first takes place 5 days after the egg hatches, then 7 days later, and again another 9 days later. After a total of 30 to 31 days from the start of the cycle, the young adult honey bee emerges from its final moulting stage, and in the space of only 4 days it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reaches full maturity</strong>.\n\nThe longest stages occur before the final moult, whereas the young adult reaches maturity relatively quickly.","phrases":[{"en":"grows in size","vi":"phát triển về kích thước"},{"en":"sheds its skin","vi":"lột da"},{"en":"reaches full maturity","vi":"đạt đến độ trưởng thành hoàn toàn"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-045-1"]},"_displayNo":"#045","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Diagram shows the life cycle of a honey bee.","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-046","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Silkworm and silk production","prompt":"The diagrams below show the life cycle of the silkworm and the stages in the production of silk","answer":"The diagrams illustrate the stages in the life of a silkworm and the process of producing silk cloth.\n\nThere are four main stages in the life cycle of the silkworm, from eggs to adult moth. The process of silk cloth production involves six steps, from silkworm cocoon to silk material.\n\nAt the first stage in the life cycle of a silkworm, the moth lays its eggs. Around ten days later, silkworm larvae hatch from the eggs; these larvae feed on mulberry leaves. Then, after four to six weeks, the larvae <strong class=\"key-phrase\">become covered in</strong> silk thread, and it takes between three and eight days for a full cocoon to be produced.\n\nFor silk cloth production, a cocoon is first selected and then boiled in water. After boiling, the silk thread that makes up the cocoon is unwound, and then several strands of thread <strong class=\"key-phrase\">are twisted together</strong>. At the fifth and sixth stages in the process, the thread can either be dyed and then woven into silk fabric, or it can be woven first and then dyed subsequently.","phrases":[{"en":"become covered in","vi":"được bao phủ bởi"},{"en":"are twisted together","vi":"được đanlại với nhau"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-046-1"]},"_displayNo":"#046","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Diagrams below show the life cycle of the silkworm and the stages in the…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-047","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Global water consumption","prompt":"The graph shows changes in global water use by sector from 1900 to 2000, while the table compares population, irrigated land and water consumption in Brazil and the Democratic Republic of Congo in 2000.","answer":"The line graph compares the average price of a barrel of oil with the food price index over a period of 11 years.\n\nIt is clear that average global prices of both oil and food <strong class=\"key-phrase\">rose considerably</strong> between 2000 and 2011. Furthermore, the trends for both commodities were very similar, and so a strong correlation (93.6%) is suggested.\n\nIn the year 2000, the average global oil price was close to $25 per barrel, and the food price index stood at just under 90 points. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">Over the following four years</strong> both prices <strong class=\"key-phrase\">remained relatively stable</strong>, before rising steadily between 2004 and 2007. By 2007, the average oil price had more than doubled, to nearly $60 per barrel, and food prices had risen by around 50 points.\n\nA dramatic increase in both commodity prices was seen from 2007 to 2008, with oil prices reaching a peak of approximately $130 per barrel and the food price index rising to 220 points. However, by the beginning of 2009 the price of oil had dropped by roughly $90, and the food price index was down by about 80 points. Finally, in 2011, the average oil price rose once again, to nearly $100 per barrel, while the food price index <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reached its peak</strong>, at almost 240 points.","phrases":[{"en":"rose considerably","vi":"tăng đáng kể"},{"en":"Over the following four years","vi":"Trong bốn năm tiếp theo"},{"en":"remained relatively stable","vi":"giữ tương đối ổn định"},{"en":"reached its peak","vi":"đạt mức cao nhất"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-047-1"]},"_displayNo":"#047","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Graph below shows changes in global","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-048","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"US meat consumption","prompt":"The graph below shows trends in US meat and poultry consumption.","answer":"The line graph shows changes in the per capita consumption of beef, pork, broilers and turkey in the United States between 1955 and 2012.\n\nIt is noticeable that beef was by far the most popular of the four types of meat for the majority of the 57-year period. However, a considerable rise can be seen in the consumption of broilers, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">with figures eventually surpassing those for</strong> beef.\n\nBetween 1955 and 1976, US beef consumption rose from around 60 to a peak of 90 pounds per person per year. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">During the same period</strong>, consumption of broilers also rose, to nearly 30 pounds per person, while the figures for pork fluctuated between 50 and 40 pounds per person. Turkey was by far <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the least popular</strong> meat, with figures below 10 pounds per capita each year.\n\nBy 2012, the amount of beef consumed by the average American had plummeted to around 50 pounds, but the consumption of broilers had doubled since the 1970s, to approximately 55 pounds per capita. By contrast, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">there were no significant changes in the trends for</strong> pork and turkey consumption over the period as a whole.","phrases":[{"en":"with figures eventually surpassing those for","vi":"với con số cuối cùng vượt qua con số của"},{"en":"During the same period","vi":"trong cùng thời gian đó"},{"en":"the least popular","vi":"ít phổ biến nhất"},{"en":"there were no significant changes in the trends for","vi":"không có thay đổi đáng kể nào trong xu hướng cho"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-048-1"]},"_displayNo":"#048","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Graph below shows trends in US meat and poultry consumption.","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-049","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"US phone expenditure","prompt":"The graph compares US consumers' average annual expenditure on cell-phone and residential phone services between 2001 and 2010.","answer":"The line graph compares average yearly spending by Americans on mobile and landline phone services from 2001 to 2010.\n\nIt is clear that spending on landline phones <strong class=\"key-phrase\">fell steadily</strong> over the 10-year period, while mobile phone expenditure rose quickly. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">The year 2006 marks the point at which</strong> expenditure on mobile services overtook that for residential phone services.\n\nIn 2001, US consumers spent an average of nearly $700 on residential phone services, compared to only around $200 on cell phone services. Over the following five years, average yearly spending on landlines dropped by nearly $200. By contrast, expenditure on mobiles rose by approximately $300.\n\nIn the year 2006, the average American <strong class=\"key-phrase\">paid out the same amount of money on</strong> both types of phone service, spending just over $500 on each. By 2010, expenditure on mobile phones had reached around $750, while the figure for spending on residential services had <strong class=\"key-phrase\">fallen to just over half this amount</strong>.\n\nThe two series therefore moved in opposite directions and crossed at the midpoint of the period.","phrases":[{"en":"fell steadily","vi":"giảm đều"},{"en":"The year 2006 marks the point at which","vi":"Năm2006 đánh dấu cột mốc tại đó"},{"en":"paid out the same amount of money on","vi":"chi trả một lượng tiền tương tự"},{"en":"fallen to just over half this amount","vi":"giảm xuống chỉ hơn một nửa số tiền này"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-049-1"]},"_displayNo":"#049","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Graph below shows US consumers' average annual expenditures on cell phone…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-050","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Garlsdon supermarket sites","prompt":"The map below is of the town of Garlsdon and shows two possible sites for a new supermarket. Summarise the information by selecting and reporting the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The first potential location (S1) is outside the town itself, and is sited just off the main road to the town of Hindon, lying 12 kilometres to the north-west. This site is in the countryside and so would be able to accommodate a lot of car parking. This would make it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">accessible to shoppers</strong> from both Hindon and Garlsdon who could travel by car. Since it is also close to the railway line linking the two towns to Cransdon (25 km to the south-east), <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a potentially large number of shoppers</strong> would also be able to travel by train. In contrast, the suggested location, S2, is right in the town centre, which would be good for local residents. Theoretically the store could be accessed by road or rail from the surrounding towns, including Bransdon, but as the central area is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a no-traffic zone</strong>, cars would be unable to park and access would be difficult. Overall, neither site is appropriate for all the towns, but for customers in Cransdon, Hindon and Garlsdon, the out-of-town site (S1) would probably <strong class=\"key-phrase\">offer more advantages</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"accessible to shoppers","vi":"dễ tiếp cận đối với người mua sắm"},{"en":"a potentially large number of shoppers","vi":"một lượng khách hàng tiềm năng lớn"},{"en":"a no-traffic zone","vi":"khu vực cấm phương tiện giao thông"},{"en":"offer more advantages","vi":"mang lại nhiều lợi thế hơn"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-050-1"]},"_displayNo":"#050","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Map below is of the town of Garlsdon and shows two possible sites for a new…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-051","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Problems in primary schools","prompt":"The table compares the problems faced by children in two primary schools in 2005 and 2015.","answer":"The table compares two primary schools in terms of the proportions of their pupils who experienced seven different <strong class=\"key-phrase\">educational problems</strong> in the years 2005 and 2015.\n\nIt is noticeable that school A had higher proportions of children with all seven educational difficulties in both years. However, while school A managed to reduce the incidence of most of the problems between 2005 and 2015, school B <strong class=\"key-phrase\">saw an overall rise</strong> in the percentage of children who were struggling.\n\nIn 2005, 42% of school A’s pupils <strong class=\"key-phrase\">found it difficult to</strong> follow instructions, whereas only 6% of pupils in school B experienced this problem. Similarly, between 30 and 40 per cent of children attending school A had problems in the areas of spelling, listening, verbal expression and concentration in lessons, while <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the equivalent figures</strong> for school B stood at between 5 and 15 per cent.\n\nIn 2015, the difference between the two schools was less pronounced. Notably, the proportion of children who struggled to follow instructions fell by 24% in school A, and this school also saw falls of 22%, 15%, 14% and 5% in the figures for children who had problems with concentration, listening, verbal expression and spelling. In school B, however, the proportion of children who <strong class=\"key-phrase\">struggled with</strong> spelling and following instructions doubled, to 10% and 12% respectively, and there was almost no change in the incidence of listening, verbal or concentration problems.","phrases":[{"en":"educational problems","vi":"vấn đề giáo dục"},{"en":"saw an overall rise","vi":"nhìn thấy sự gia tăng tổng thể"},{"en":"found it difficult to","vi":"gặp khó khăn khi"},{"en":"the equivalent figures","vi":"những con số tương đương"},{"en":"struggled with","vi":"gặp khó khăn với"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-051-1"]},"_displayNo":"#051","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Table below gives information about the problems faced by children in two…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-052","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Underground railway systems","prompt":"The table below gives information about the underground railway systems in six cities.","answer":"The table shows data about the underground rail networks in six major cities.\n\nThe table compares the six networks in terms of their age, size and the number of people who use them each year. It is clear that the three oldest underground systems are larger and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">serve significantly more passengers than</strong> the newer systems.\n\nThe London underground is the oldest system, having opened in 1863. It is also the largest system, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">with 394 kilometres of route</strong>. The second largest system, in Paris, is only about <strong class=\"key-phrase\">half the size of</strong> the London underground, with 199 kilometres of route. However, it serves more people per year. While only third in terms of size, the Tokyo system <strong class=\"key-phrase\">is easily the most used</strong>, with 1,927 million passengers per year.\n\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">Of the three newer networks</strong>, the Washington DC underground is the most extensive, with 126 kilometres of route, compared to only 11 kilometres and 28 kilometres for the Kyoto and Los Angeles systems. The Los Angeles network is the newest, having opened in 2001, while the Kyoto network is the smallest and serves only 45 million passengers per year.","phrases":[{"en":"serve significantly more passengers than","vi":"phục vụ nhiều hành khách hơn đáng kể so với"},{"en":"with 394 kilometres of route","vi":"với 394 km lộ trình"},{"en":"half the size of","vi":"một nửa kích thước của"},{"en":"is easily the most used","vi":"được sử dụng nhiều nhất"},{"en":"Of the three newer networks","vi":"Trong số ba mạng mới hơn"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-052-1"]},"_displayNo":"#052","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Table below gives information about the underground railway systems in six…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-053","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Consumer spending by country","prompt":"The table compares consumer spending on food, clothing and leisure in five countries in 2002.","answer":"The table shows percentages of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">consumer expenditure</strong> for three categories of products and services in five countries in 2002.\n\nIt is clear that the largest proportion of consumer spending in each country went on food, drinks and tobacco. On the other hand, the leisure/education category has the lowest percentages in the table.\n\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">Out of the five countries</strong>, consumer spending on food, drinks and tobacco was noticeably higher in Turkey, at 32.14%, and Ireland, at nearly 29%. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">The proportion of spending on</strong> leisure and education was also highest in Turkey, at 4.35%, while expenditure on clothing and footwear was significantly higher in Italy, at 9%, than in any of the other countries.\n\nIt can be seen that Sweden had the lowest percentages of national consumer expenditure for food/drinks/tobacco and for clothing/footwear, at nearly 16% and just over 5% respectively. Spain had slightly higher figures for these categories, but the lowest figure for leisure/education, at only 1.98%.","phrases":[{"en":"consumer expenditure","vi":"chi tiêu của người tiêu dùng"},{"en":"Out of the five countries","vi":"Trong số năm quốc gia"},{"en":"The proportion of spending on","vi":"Tỷ trọng chi tiêu cho"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-053-1"]},"_displayNo":"#053","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Table below gives information on consumer spending on different items in…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-054","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Mobile phone feature use","prompt":"The table below shows the percentage of mobile phones owners using various mobile features.","answer":"The table compares the percentages of people using different functions of their mobile phones between 2006 and 2010.\n\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">Throughout the period shown</strong>, the main reason why people used their mobile phones was to make calls. However, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">there was a marked increase in</strong> the popularity of other mobile phone features, particularly the Internet search feature.\n\nIn 2006, 100% of mobile phone owners used their phones to make calls, while the next most popular functions were text messaging (73%) and taking photos (66%). By contrast, less than 20% of owners played games or music on their phones, and there were no figures for users doing Internet searches or recording video.\n\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">Over the following 4 years</strong>, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">there was relatively little change in</strong> the figures for the top three mobile phone features. However, the percentage of people using their phones to access the Internet jumped to 41% in 2008 and then to 73% in 2010. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">There was also a significant rise in</strong> the use of mobiles to play games and to record video, with figures reaching 41% and 35% respectively in 2010.","phrases":[{"en":"Throughout the period shown","vi":"trong suốt thời gian được nêu ra"},{"en":"there was a marked increase in","vi":"có sự gia tăng rõ rệt"},{"en":"Over the following 4 years","vi":"Trong 4 năm tiếp theo"},{"en":"there was relatively little change in","vi":"có tương đối ít thay đổi trong"},{"en":"There was also a significant rise in","vi":"Cũngcó sự gia tăng đáng kể về"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-054-1"]},"_displayNo":"#054","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Table below shows the percentage of mobile phones owners using various…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-055","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Australian family poverty","prompt":"The table shows the proportion of different family types living in poverty in Australia in 1999.","answer":"The table gives information about poverty rates among six types of household in Australia in the year 1999.\n\nIt is noticeable that levels of poverty were higher for single people than for couples, and people with children were more likely to be poor than those without. Poverty rates were considerably lower among elderly people.\n\nOverall, 11% of Australians, or 1,837,000 people, were <strong class=\"key-phrase\">living in poverty</strong> in 1999. Aged people were the least likely to be poor, with poverty levels of 6% and 4% for single aged people and aged couples respectively.\n\nJust over one fifth of single parents were living in poverty, whereas only 12% of parents living with a partner were classed as poor. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">The same pattern can be seen</strong> for people with no children: while 19% of single people in this group were living below the poverty line, the figure for couples was much lower, at only 7%.\n\nSingle-parent households had the highest poverty rate, while aged couples recorded the lowest figure.","phrases":[{"en":"living in poverty","vi":"sống trong nghèo đói"},{"en":"The same pattern can be seen","vi":"Điều tương tựcũng có thể thấy"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-055-1"]},"_displayNo":"#055","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Table below shows the proportion of different categories of families living…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-056","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Honey bee life cycle","prompt":"The diagram below shows the life cycle of the honey bee.\nSummarise the information by selecting and reporting the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The chart illustrates the stages in the life of honey bees. All in all, this life cycle is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">comprised of six stages</strong> from egg to full maturity, and takes approximately five weeks (34 to 36 days to be exact) to complete. The first stage is when the female bee lays up to a couple of oval eggs once every 72 hours. These eggs hatch between nine and ten days later, and immature bees, called nymphs, emerge which lack the typical bee stripes. Over the next 3 weeks nymphs experience three moulting stages, that is, they shed their skins to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">allow further growth to occur</strong>: The first moulting happening 5 days after the eggs hatch, a week after which the second one takes place. Nine days later nymphs moult for a third time and young adult honey bees emerge, identified by their horizontally striped backs. These take four more days to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">mature into larger adult bees</strong> whose backs are marked with bolder and darker stripes, and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the cycle starts over again</strong>.\n\nOverall, this provides a direct comparison and shows a clear overall pattern.","phrases":[{"en":"comprised of six stages","vi":"gồm sáu giai đoạn"},{"en":"allow further growth to occur","vi":"cho phép quá trình phát triển tiếp tục"},{"en":"mature into larger adult bees","vi":"phát triển thành ong trưởng thành lớn hơn"},{"en":"the cycle starts over again","vi":"chu kỳ bắt đầu lại"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-056-1"]},"_displayNo":"#056","author":"Ebrahim Tahasoni","source":"Ebrahim Tahasoni","summary":"Diagram below shows the life cycle of the honey bee.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-057","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Fruit production and fertiliser use","prompt":"The first graph below shows the weight (in tonnes) of fruit produced by a farm during each month in 2013, and also the amount (in tonnes) of fertiliser used. The second graph shows the volume of rainfall in each month (in millimetres.) Write a report summarising the information. Select and describe the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The charts give information regarding the tonnage of fruit produced in a farm per month in 2013, the fertiliser used and the monthly rainfall in that year. We can see that fruit production <strong class=\"key-phrase\">rose steadily</strong> from just over 2 tonnes in January to a peak of roughly 4.2 tonnes by August. Output then fell rapidly, declining to around the initial 2 tonne mark in December. However, looking at fertiliser use, we see that this seasonal pattern is largely reversed: the most fertiliser (just under 1 tonne) was utilised in April, followed by a marked decline to zero in June and July. Fertiliser consumption then increased slightly in the autumn, rising to a total of around 0.7 tonnes before dipping to just below 0.5 tonnes at year end. Regarding rainfall, this appears to reflect the use of fertiliser, with an early high of 16mm in February, falling consistently to 4mm in July, August and September. Rainfall then increased steadily to reach 14mm in December. In summary, this farm generally employed the most fertiliser at seasons of high rainfall, and by contrast it produced the most fruit when both rainfall and fertiliser use were around their lowest.","phrases":[{"en":"rose steadily","vi":"tăng đều"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-057-1","writing-academic-057-2"]},"_displayNo":"#057","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"First graph below shows the weight (in tonnes) of fruit produced by a farm…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-058","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Dubai gold sales","prompt":"The graph below gives information about Dubai gold sales in 2002.\nSummarise the information by selecting and reporting the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The diagram given illustrates how gold sales in Dubai fluctuated over a period of 12 months. Overall, gold sales in Dubai <strong class=\"key-phrase\">remained relatively unchanged</strong> in 2002.\n\nIt is observed that in the first month of 2002, gold sales stood at 200 million dirhams and rose slightly to reach about 225 million in February. This was followed by another increase, although much steeper, in March when sales were almost 125 million dirhams higher than February. However, this upward trend was suddenly broken and sales <strong class=\"key-phrase\">plummeted dramatically</strong> over the next 4 months to reach a little over 100 million dirhams in July. August sales showed a significant rise back to January levels as figures nearly doubled, but this was not to last as they dropped again in September to the same level as they were in July. October came with a small increase of about 100 million dirhams in sales, after which sales figures <strong class=\"key-phrase\">levelled off</strong> and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">remained relatively static</strong> over the last two months of 2002.\n\nTo Sum up, sales were at their highest in March while the weakest sales figures could be observed in July and September.","phrases":[{"en":"remained relatively unchanged","vi":"duy trì tương đối ổn định"},{"en":"plummeted dramatically","vi":"giảm mạnh"},{"en":"levelled off","vi":"chững lại"},{"en":"remained relatively static","vi":"duy trì tương đối ổn định"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-058-1"]},"_displayNo":"#058","author":"Ebrahim Tahasoni","source":"Ebrahim Tahasoni","summary":"Graph below gives information about Dubai gold sales in 2002.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-059","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Global greenhouse gas emissions","prompt":"The charts compare the sources of global greenhouse gas emissions in 2002 and emissions from electricity generation.","answer":"As can be seen in the two pie charts, developing countries are expected to account for a bigger share of emissions in 2030, 48%, compared to 38% in 2002. In contrast, OECD countries are projected to make up a lower proportion, 43%, 9% down over the same period, Countries with transition economies are estimated to take up the remaining 9% in 2030, 1% less than in 2002.\n\nThe bar chart reveals that carbon dioxide emissions will expand to varying degrees in different sectors by 2030. Industry will continue to be the major producer of carbon dioxide, rising to more than 10 billion tons in 2030. Next comes the consumer sector, which is projected to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more than double</strong> its emissions from less than 4 billion to 8 billion or more tons. Transportation, the third largest producer, will see a huge growth to 6 billion, triple the amount in 2002. By comparison, waste combustion and other sectors make up a much lower proportion, each producing an estimated 1 billion carbon dioxide.\n\nTo summarise, developing countries will overtake OECD countries to become the major carbon dioxide emission producer by 2030. While industry is responsible for the highest amount of carbon dioxide emissions, consumer and transportation experience the greatest increases. —","phrases":[{"en":"more than double","vi":"tăng hơn gấp đôi"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-059-1"]},"_displayNo":"#059","author":"Mat Clark","source":"Mat Clark","summary":"Pie graphs show greenhouse gas emissions worldwide in 2002 and the","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-060","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"Teen smoking in Britain","prompt":"The table below describes the proportion of smokers in males and females (between the age of 15 and 20) in Britain. Summarise the information by selecting and reporting the main features and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"In 1970, smoking was not very popular among youngsters aged 15 to 20, with only 10 per cent of males smoking, and 5% in females. The following decade saw a dramatic change: the smoking rate among males leapt nearly 13% every five years to 35% in 1980, compared to a slower growth in females, rising approximately 8% every five years to 22% in 1980.\n\nOver the period between 1980 and 1990, smoking remained popular among young males, accounting for over a third of the 15-to-20 male population while young females showed a growing interest in smoking, pushing the smoking rate first to 34% in 1985, and then to 37% in 1990, even outmatching their male counterparts.\n\nOver the final years of the last century, the smoking craze in the 15-20 age group abated, either for males or for females. In 2000, an estimated 27 % to 28% of people in this age group were reported as smokers, lower than previous years, albeit still more than <strong class=\"key-phrase\">three times higher than</strong> 30 years earlier.\n\nFrom the table, it is clear that the 15-to-20-year-old population in Britain had a much higher percentage of smokers by the end of the last century than in the early 1970s.","phrases":[{"en":"three times higher than","vi":"cao gấp ba lần so với"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-060-1"]},"_displayNo":"#060","author":"Mat Clark","source":"Mat Clark","summary":"Table below describes the proportion of smokers in males and females…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-061","section":"writing-academic","topic":"General","title":"UK vehicle offences","prompt":"The table below shows motor vehicle offences in England and Wales between 1994 and 2004. Summarise the information by selecting and reporting the main features and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"In 1994, licence, insurance and record keeping offences were the most common type of offences and rose to 957 thousand in 2004, after a ten-year period of fluctuations. Speed limit offences initially ranked second in 1994 but became the main type of offences by 2004, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">recording a ten-year high</strong> at 2,076 thousand, more than three times the figure ten years earlier. Neglect of traffic signs and directions came third, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">averaging at around</strong> 250 thousand per year.\n\nDangerous, careless or drunken driving was the fourth main type of offences, dropping in much of the period 1994 to 2004 but finally <strong class=\"key-phrase\">hitting an all-time high</strong> at 231 thousand. Another two types of offences, accident offences and unauthorised taking (or theft) of motor vehicle, were the least common, also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">declining gradually</strong>.\n\nTo summarise, speed limit offences and licence offences were two main types of motor vehicle offences in England and Wales during the period 1994 to 2004 and speed limit offences deserved particular attention because it surged exponentially.","phrases":[{"en":"recording a ten-year high","vi":"ghi nhận mức cao nhất trong mười năm"},{"en":"averaging at around","vi":"đạt trung bình khoảng"},{"en":"hitting an all-time high","vi":"đạt mức cao nhất từ trước đến nay"},{"en":"declining gradually","vi":"giảm dần"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-061-1","writing-academic-061-2"]},"_displayNo":"#061","author":"Mat Clark","source":"Mat Clark","summary":"Table below shows motor vehicle offences in England and Wales between 1994…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-062","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Health","title":"Emergency department attendance","prompt":"The chart below shows figures for attendances at hospital emergency care departments in Northern Ireland by age group in December 2016 and December 2017.","answer":"The bar chart compares the number of visits made by people in six age categories to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">hospital emergency wards</strong> in Northern Ireland in the December of 2016 and 2017.\n\nIt is clear that elderly people and the youngest children were the most <strong class=\"key-phrase\">frequent visitors</strong> to A&E (accident and emergency) departments. Also, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">there was a slight increase in</strong> the rate of emergency care attendances among all six age groups from December 2016 to December 2017.\n\nLooking first at the older age groups, roughly 65 out of every 1000 people aged 75 and over attended A&E wards in December 2016, and this rose to almost 70 attendances per 1000-population one year later. Interestingly, those aged 65 to 74 were less than half as likely to require emergency treatment, with around 30 attendances per 1000-population in both months.\n\nAt the other end of the age scale, the figures for A&E visits by under-5s <strong class=\"key-phrase\">rose marginally</strong> from around 50 to approximately 52 per 1000-population over the one-year period. Children aged 5 to 15 <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made the fewest visits</strong>, at just over 20 per 1000-population in both months. Finally, there was almost no difference in the figures for emergency care attendances among people aged 16 to 44, 45 to 64 and 65 to 74.","phrases":[{"en":"hospital emergency wards","vi":"các khu cấp cứu của bệnh viện"},{"en":"frequent visitors","vi":"những người thường xuyên đến bệnh viện"},{"en":"there was a slight increase in","vi":"có sự gia tăng nhẹ trong"},{"en":"rose marginally","vi":"tăng nhẹ"},{"en":"made the fewest visits","vi":"đến thăm khám ít nhất"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-062-1"]},"_displayNo":"#062","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Chart below shows figures for attendances at hospital emergency care…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-063","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Health","title":"Hospital electricity use","prompt":"The charts below compare five different countries, showing the electricity used (measured in megawatts or mw) in a typical hospital during one week, and also the number of emergency medical calls made by local residents during the same week. The last chart shows the average time (in minutes) spent on assessing emergency cases by hospital medical staff before the patients are treated. Write a report summarising the information. Select and describe the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The charts show electricity use, local emergency calls and time spent on patients for a group of typical hospitals. Regarding electricity, we see that consumption in the French and Japanese hospitals is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">roughly stable</strong> during the week, fluctuating around 32 and 18 mw respectively. In Canada and Russia, electricity use <strong class=\"key-phrase\">climbs dramatically</strong> towards the end of the week, going from 26 to 38 mw and from 12 to 24 mw. In Argentina, however, the use actually declines by almost half. There is a similar pattern in the number of emergency calls made, which fluctuate in France (around 90 calls) and Canada (around 110.) In Canada these calls rise by roughly half, from around 105 on Monday to over 160 on Sunday, with the figure in Russia showing a similar growth to 110 by the weekend. Argentina is again the exception, with a decline of about half. By contrast, time spent on patient assessment is generally stable during the week in all the countries except Russia, where there is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a marked rise</strong> from Monday’s 12 minutes (which is the typical daily rate of each country except Japan) to 28 minutes on Sunday. In summary, it seems that electricity use may <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reflect an increase in</strong> emergency calls made, but only in Russia does assessment time increase by the same pattern.","phrases":[{"en":"roughly stable","vi":"tương đối ổn định"},{"en":"climbs dramatically","vi":"tăng mạnh"},{"en":"a marked rise","vi":"mức tăng rõ rệt"},{"en":"reflect an increase in","vi":"phản ánh sự gia tăng về"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-063-1","writing-academic-063-2"]},"_displayNo":"#063","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"Charts below compare five different countries, showing the electricity used…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-064","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Health","title":"UK obesity trends","prompt":"The graphs below summarise the results of a survey carried out by the Department of Health about the overweight population in Britain with projections. Summarise the information by selecting and reporting the main features and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The first two graphs show <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a marked rise in obesity</strong> in Britain by 2010. The number of men who have a weight problem is estimated to be as high as 6.8 million in 2010, over 50% higher than in 2003. The increase in the women who have the same problem tends to be smaller, rising almost 30% from 4.7 million to 6 million.\n\nIn children, it is another picture. The survey suggests that girls who are overweight will see a greater increase during the period 2003-2010 to more than 900 thousand, 100 thousand more than boys who have the same problem, although in 2003, there were more boys than girls suffering obesity, over 700 thousand versus about 690 thousand.\n\nAs shown in the third graph, children in households where both parents are obese are twice as likely to be obese as those in households where one parent is obese (12. 5%) and five times as those with parents having a healthy weight (5%).\n\nOverall, UK’s obese population will grow in size, including both children and adults. While men are expected to outnumber women by 2010, girls will surpass boys. The children with at least one parent having a weight problem are more likely to be obese than those with parents having a healthy weight.","phrases":[{"en":"a marked rise in obesity","vi":"mức tăng rõ rệt về tình trạng béo phì"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-064-1","writing-academic-064-2"]},"_displayNo":"#064","author":"Mat Clark","source":"Mat Clark","summary":"Graphs below summarise the results of a survey carried out by the…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-065","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Health","title":"Doctor consultation times","prompt":"The table shows data about the average length of time (in minutes) that people of different ages spend in a consultation with family doctors in a number of countries. Write a report summarising the information. Select and describe the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The chart gives information about the typical time that patients spend with doctors in various countries, split by age group. We can see that the most common trend is for the time to increase consistently with age. For example, the figure in France <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more than doubles</strong> from 16 to 38 minutes between the youngest and oldest people. Likewise, the USA figure rises from 13 to 31, the UK from 9 to 21, and Italy from 17 to 29. These are all <strong class=\"key-phrase\">substantial increases</strong>. Chile has a consistent but much smaller increase, from 32 to 39 minutes. Brazil also shows a rise, although after age 60 there is a decline from 26 minutes to an eventual 20. India has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a more marked rise and fall</strong>, peaking at 21 minutes for people aged 40 to 60, declining to 11 minutes for 70 plus. Two countries are exceptions. Japan fluctuates across the age groups, between 12 and 16 minutes. Kenya <strong class=\"key-phrase\">declines steadily</strong> as age increases, from 15 minutes for the youngest to 10 minutes for the oldest people. Overall, time spent with doctors generally increases with age, except in Japan and Kenya.","phrases":[{"en":"more than doubles","vi":"tăng hơn gấp đôi"},{"en":"substantial increases","vi":"những mức tăng đáng kể"},{"en":"a more marked rise and fall","vi":"mức tăng rồi giảm rõ rệt hơn"},{"en":"declines steadily","vi":"giảm đều"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-065-1"]},"_displayNo":"#065","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"Table shows data about the average length of time (in minutes) that people…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-066","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Technology","title":"Tablet prices and discounts","prompt":"Chart 1 below shows the normal price of a tablet computer in different stores (in US dollars), and the % discount offered by these stores when the products are sold on promotion. Chart 2 shows the % increase in volume sales when the discount promotions are happening, and Chart 3 shows funds (in 000 US dollars) spent on TV advertising during these promotions. Write a report summarising the information. Select and describe the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The charts show average prices, promotional discounts, sales uplifts and advertising budgets for 7 stores selling tablet computers. 4 of these stores have a normal price of around $300 per item (Slaker, Jones, Scots and Fraser.) 2 stores (Lewis and Nova) have a much higher price at $460 and $565 respectively. The lowest price ($180) is seen in Smith. We see <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a similar grouping</strong> in the promotional discounts offered, with the 4 mid-priced stores offering 10% off, the two higher-priced stores giving 20% (Lewis) and 25% (Nova), and Smith offering only 5% discount. Lewis and Nova also see <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the highest rate of uplift</strong> in sales volumes on promotion (at 21% and 23% respectively), while Slaker, Jones, Scots and Fraser are again similarly grouped with around a 12% increase each. Smith has the lowest sales increase with below 5%. Turning to TV advertising, Slaker, Jones, Scots and Fraser have roughly similar funds of between $63,000 and $70,000. Lewis and Nova have much lower spends at $18,000 and $21,000, while Smith does not spend money at all. In summary, the 4 mid-price stores spend the most on advertising and achieve similar uplifts with their 10% discounts. Lewis and Nova spend about one third of these levels, but achieve <strong class=\"key-phrase\">roughly double the uplift</strong> by offering approximately double the level of discount. Smith, with its lower normal price, is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">barely active on promotions</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"a similar grouping","vi":"một cách phân nhóm tương tự"},{"en":"the highest rate of uplift","vi":"mức tăng doanh số cao nhất"},{"en":"roughly double the uplift","vi":"mức tăng gần gấp đôi"},{"en":"barely active on promotions","vi":"hầu như không triển khai khuyến mãi"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-066-1","writing-academic-066-2"]},"_displayNo":"#066","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"Chart 1 below shows the normal price of a tablet computer in different…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-067","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Transport","title":"UK commuting trends","prompt":"The graph below shows the average number of UK commuters travelling each day by car, bus or train between 1970 and 2030.","answer":"The line graph compares figures for daily travel by workers in the UK using three different forms of transport over a period of 60 years.\n\nIt is clear that the car is by far the most popular means of transport for UK commuters <strong class=\"key-phrase\">throughout the period shown</strong>. Also, while the numbers of people who use the car and train <strong class=\"key-phrase\">increase gradually</strong>, the number of bus users <strong class=\"key-phrase\">falls steadily</strong>.\n\nIn 1970, around 5 million UK commuters travelled by car on a daily basis, while the bus and train were used by about 4 million and 2 million people respectively. In the year 2000, the number of those driving to work rose to 7 million and the number of commuting rail passengers reached 3 million. However, there was a small drop of approximately 0.5 million in the number of bus users.\n\nBy 2030, the number of people who commute by car is expected to reach almost 9 million, and the number of train users is also predicted to rise, to nearly 5 million. By contrast, buses are predicted to become a less popular choice, with only 3 million daily users.","phrases":[{"en":"throughout the period shown","vi":"trong suốt thời gian được nêu ra"},{"en":"increase gradually","vi":"tăng dần"},{"en":"falls steadily","vi":"giảm dần"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-067-1"]},"_displayNo":"#067","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Graph below shows the average number of UK commuters travelling each day by…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-academic-068","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Transport","title":"US population demographics","prompt":"Graphs below provide the latest figures about the demographics of the United States, including ethnic groups and the population, based on a census that was carried out and administered by US Census Bureau in 2006. Summarise the information by selecting and reporting the main features and make comparisons where relevant.","answer":"The table and bar chart describe changes in the size and ethnic composition of the United States population. Overall, the population rose substantially, while Hispanic and Asian communities grew much faster than the population as a whole.\n\nThe total population increased from 200 million in 1966 to 300 million in 2006. White Americans <strong class=\"key-phrase\">remained the largest group</strong>, representing roughly two thirds of the population in 2006, although their share grew more slowly than the national average. The Hispanic population climbed from about 8 million to 44.7 million, while the Asian population rose tenfold to 14.3 million. African Americans, who had been the second-largest group in 1966, became the third-largest by 2006.\n\nThe bar chart also shows that population <strong class=\"key-phrase\">growth accelerated over time</strong>. In the early decades of the twentieth century, the increase varied from around 7.5 million to 20 million per decade. From the middle of the century onwards, the country added at least 20 million people in most ten-year periods, and the rise exceeded 30 million during the 1990s.\n\nIn summary, the United States experienced sustained population growth, with <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the most striking proportional increases</strong> occurring among Hispanic and Asian Americans.","phrases":[{"en":"remained the largest group","vi":"vẫn là nhóm lớn nhất"},{"en":"growth accelerated over time","vi":"tốc độ tăng trưởng tăng dần theo thời gian"},{"en":"the most striking proportional increases","vi":"những mức tăng theo tỷ lệ nổi bật nhất"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-068-1"]},"_displayNo":"#068","author":"Mat Clark","source":"Mat Clark","summary":"Graphs below provide the latest figures about the demographics of the…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-academic-069","section":"writing-academic","topic":"Work","title":"Cycling to work in Britain","prompt":"The table shows changes in the number of residents cycling to work in selected areas of the United Kingdom between 2001 and 2011.","answer":"The table compares the numbers of people who cycled to work in twelve areas of the UK in the years 2001 and 2011.\n\nOverall, the number of UK commuters who <strong class=\"key-phrase\">travelled to work by bicycle</strong> <strong class=\"key-phrase\">rose considerably</strong> over the 10-year period. Inner London had by far the highest number of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cycling commuters</strong> in both years.\n\nIn 2001, well over 43 thousand residents of inner London <strong class=\"key-phrase\">commuted by bicycle</strong>, and this figure rose to more than 106 thousand in 2011, an increase of 144%. By contrast, although outer London had the second highest number of cycling commuters in each year, the percentage change, at only 45%, was the lowest of the twelve areas shown in the table.\n\nBrighton and Hove recorded the second biggest increase (109%) in the number of residents cycling to work, but Bristol was the UK’s second city in terms of total numbers of cycling commuters, with 8,108 in 2001 and 15,768 in 2011. Figures for the other eight areas were below the 10 thousand mark in both years.","phrases":[{"en":"travelled to work by bicycle","vi":"đi làm bằng xe đạp"},{"en":"rose considerably","vi":"tăng đáng kể"},{"en":"cycling commuters","vi":"người đi xe đạp đi làm"},{"en":"commuted by bicycle","vi":"đi lại bằng xe đạp"}],"subtype":"Academic Task 1","visual":{"images":["writing-academic-069-1"]},"_displayNo":"#069","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Table below shows changes in the numbers of residents cycling to work in","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-001","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Advertising","title":"Advertising","prompt":"Some of the methods used in advertising are unethical and unacceptable in today’s society. To what extent do you agree with this view?","answer":"Advertising is indispensable to a market economy because it informs consumers and allows firms to compete. Nevertheless, I largely agree that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a significant proportion of</strong> modern advertising is ethically unacceptable, particularly when it conceals commercial intent or targets people who cannot make fully informed choices.\n\nThe first concern is that digital advertising can blur the boundary between persuasion and manipulation. Online platforms collect extensive behavioural data and use it to predict when an individual is most receptive to a message. Consumers may therefore see personalised claims repeatedly without understanding why they have been selected. This practice can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">exploit informational asymmetry</strong>: advertisers know far more about the audience than the audience knows about the campaign. The problem is not merely that people are persuaded to buy unnecessary goods, but that their attention and personal data are used without meaningful consent.\n\nA second ethical problem arises when advertising is directed at children, people in financial difficulty or those with health-related anxieties. Such groups may be less able to assess exaggerated promises or long-term consequences. Promotions for high-interest credit, gambling or unproven health products can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">disproportionately affect vulnerable consumers</strong>, even when the wording is technically legal. In these cases, commercial freedom should not outweigh the duty to prevent foreseeable harm.\n\nThis does not mean that all advertising is objectionable. Clear product information, verifiable comparisons and creative brand communication can help consumers make better decisions. However, these practices must be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">subject to meaningful oversight</strong>, including transparent data rules, strict protection for minors and penalties for misleading claims.\n\nIn conclusion, advertising remains legitimate, but methods based on covert tracking, manipulation or exploitation are ethically unacceptable. Strong regulation is therefore necessary to preserve both <strong class=\"key-phrase\">consumer autonomy</strong> and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">public trust</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"a significant proportion of","vi":"một tỷ lệ đáng kể"},{"en":"exploit informational asymmetry","vi":"khai thác sự bất cân xứng thông tin"},{"en":"disproportionately affect vulnerable consumers","vi":"ảnh hưởng không cân xứng đến người tiêu dùng dễ bị tổn thương"},{"en":"subject to meaningful oversight","vi":"chịu sự giám sát thực chất"},{"en":"consumer autonomy","vi":"quyền tự chủ của người tiêu dùng"},{"en":"public trust","vi":"niềm tin của công chúng"}],"subtype":"Agree / Disagree · Nguồn đề: IELTS Buddy","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#001","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Are unethical advertising methods acceptable?","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-002","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Ageing","title":"Ageing: Population change","prompt":"In the developed world, average life expectancy is increasing. What problems will this cause for individuals and society? Suggest some measures that could be taken to reduce the impact of ageing populations.","answer":"It is true that people in industrialised nations can expect to live longer than ever before. Although there will undoubtedly be some negative consequences of this trend, societies can take steps to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">mitigate these potential problems</strong>.\n\nAs people live longer and the populations of developed countries grow older, several related problems can be anticipated. The main issue is that there will obviously be more people of retirement age who will be eligible to receive a pension. The proportion of younger, working adults will be smaller, and governments will therefore receive less money in taxes in relation to the size of the population. In other words, an <strong class=\"key-phrase\">ageing population</strong> will mean a greater tax burden for working adults. Further pressures will include a rise in the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">demand for healthcare</strong>, and the fact young adults will increasingly have to look after their elderly relatives.\n\nThere are several actions that governments could take to solve the problems described above. Firstly, a simple solution would be to increase the retirement age for working adults, perhaps from 65 to 70. Nowadays, people of this age tend to be healthy enough to continue a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">productive working life</strong>. A second measure would be for governments to encourage immigration in order to increase the number of working adults who pay taxes. Finally, money from national budgets will need to be taken from other areas and spent on vital healthcare, accommodation and transport facilities for the rising numbers of older citizens.\n\nIn conclusion, various measures can be taken to tackle the problems that are certain to arise as the populations of countries grow older.","phrases":[{"en":"mitigate these potential problems","vi":"giảm thiếu những vấn đề tiềm tàng"},{"en":"ageing population","vi":"dân số già hóa"},{"en":"demand for healthcare","vi":"nhu cầu chăm sóc y tế"},{"en":"productive working life","vi":"cuộc đời lao động hiệu quả"}],"subtype":"Causes / Effects / Solutions · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#002","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Ageing populations: problems and responses","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-003","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Animals","title":"Animals: Wildlife protection","prompt":"Wild animals have no place in the 21st century, so protecting them is a waste of resources. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Some people argue that it is pointless to spend money on the protection of wild animals because we humans have no need for them. I completely disagree with this point of view.\n\nIn my opinion, it is absurd to argue that wild animals have no place in the 21st century. I do not believe that planet Earth exists only for the benefit of humans, and there is nothing special about this particular century that means that we suddenly have the right to allow or encourage <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the extinction of any species</strong>. Furthermore, there is no compelling reason why we should let animals die out. We do not need to exploit or destroy every last square metre of land in order to feed or accommodate the world’s population. There is plenty of room for us to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">exist side by side</strong> with wild animals, and this should be our aim.\n\nI also disagree with the idea that protecting animals is a waste of resources. It is usually the protection of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">natural habitats</strong> that ensures the survival of wild animals, and most scientists agree that these habitats are also crucial for human survival. For example, rainforests produce oxygen, absorb carbon dioxide and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">stabilise the Earth’s climate</strong>. If we destroyed these areas, the costs of managing the resulting changes to our planet would far outweigh the costs of conservation. By protecting wild animals and their habitats, we maintain <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the natural balance of all life on Earth</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, we have no right to decide whether or not wild animals should exist, and I believe that we should do everything we can to protect them.","phrases":[{"en":"the extinction of any species","vi":"sự tuyệt chủng của bất kì loài động vật nào"},{"en":"exist side by side","vi":"cùng tồn tại"},{"en":"natural habitats","vi":"môi trường sống tự nhiên"},{"en":"stabilise the Earth’s climate","vi":"ổn định khí hậu Trái Đất"},{"en":"the natural balance of all life on Earth","vi":"cân bằng tự nhiên của mọi sự sống trên trái đất"}],"subtype":"Agree / Disagree · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#003","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Protecting wild animals","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-004","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Animals","title":"Animals","prompt":"Nowadays animal experiments are widely used to develop new medicines and to test the safety of other products. Some people argue that these experiments should be banned because it is morally wrong to cause animals to suffer, while others are in favour of them because of their benefits to humanity. Discuss both views and give your own opinion.","answer":"It is true that medicines and other products are routinely tested on animals before they are cleared for human use. While I tend towards the viewpoint that animal testing is morally wrong, I would have to support a limited amount of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">animal experimentation</strong> for the development of medicines.\n\nOn the one hand, there are clear <strong class=\"key-phrase\">ethical arguments</strong> against animal experimentation. To use a common example of this practice, laboratory mice may be given an illness so that the effectiveness of a new drug can be measured. Opponents of such research argue that humans have no right to subject animals to this kind of trauma, and that the lives of all creatures should be respected. They believe that the benefits to humans do not justify the suffering caused, and that scientists should use <strong class=\"key-phrase\">alternative methods</strong> of research.\n\nOn the other hand, reliable alternatives to animal experimentation may not always be available. Supporters of the use of animals in medical research believe that a certain amount of suffering on the part of mice or rats can be justified if human lives are saved. They argue that opponents of such research might feel differently if a member of their own families needed a medical treatment that had been developed through the use of animal experimentation. Personally, I agree with the banning of animal testing for non-medical products, but I feel that it may be a necessary evil where new drugs and medical procedures are concerned.\n\nIn conclusion, it seems to me that it would be wrong to ban testing on animals for vital medical research until equally effective alternatives have been developed.","phrases":[{"en":"animal experimentation","vi":"thử nghiệm trên động vật"},{"en":"ethical arguments","vi":"những cuộc tranh luận về mặt đạo đức"},{"en":"alternative methods","vi":"các phương pháp thay thế"}],"subtype":"Discuss both views + opinion · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#004","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"The ethics of animal experimentation","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-005","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Animals","title":"Animals in captivity","prompt":"Some people feel that it is always wrong to keep animals in captivity, for instance in zoos. Other people say that there are benefits for the animals and for humans. Discuss both sides of this debate, and give your personal view.","answer":"Zoos continue to be controversial, even now that they have evolved into ’animal parks’ or similar facilities. Most people love animals, and there are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">strong views on both sides</strong>, which I will discuss now. People opposed to zoos highlight the unnatural way in which animals live in such places. For example, captive animals do not need to hunt or raise offspring, and this means that they are not living as nature intended. Furthermore, the anti-zoo lobby point out that animals probably suffer mentally when kept in captivity, even if their surroundings are spacious and similar to the natural habitat. Symptoms of mental issues range from repetitive behaviour to eating disorders, and these are often seen in captive animals. Lastly, it is often said that zoos add little to animal conservation, which is better served by preserving their habitat. Conversely, those who support zoos say that in most cases they offer a secure and peaceful setting for animals, for example in high quality wildlife parks or reserves. They add that in many cases, the animals would suffer from loss of habitat or poaching in the wild, and in captivity they are at least safe and able to breed successfully. Finally, zoo enthusiasts feel that zoos and animal parks are part of an integrated system of protecting animals, involving habitat protection, breeding programmes and disease control. This all helps to safeguard <strong class=\"key-phrase\">endangered species</strong> and thus preserve the global ecosystem for the future benefit of all life forms.\n\nOverall, I feel that zoos provide a valuable service to society and the animal world, as they help to protect many species. This outweighs their possible disadvantages, as long as they are properly staffed and maintained.","phrases":[{"en":"strong views on both sides","vi":"những quan điểm mạnh mẽ từ cả hai phía"},{"en":"endangered species","vi":"loài có nguy cơ tuyệt chủng"}],"subtype":"Discussion","_displayNo":"#005","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"People feel that it is always wrong to keep animals in captivity, for…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-006","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Animals","title":"Animals: Species extinction","prompt":"Far too little has been done to prevent animals and plants from dying out, although people have noticed this problem for a long time. Why have people failed to improve this situation? What are your suggestions?","answer":"Nowadays, the progressive extinction of living species on the planet—either animals or plants— has arisen as a big environmental challenge, according to many scientists and researchers. Despite the growing concern on this issue, little progress has been made in this field, There are some factors that account for why this has happened. In my opinion, this situation can be remedied, provided that some reasonable steps are taken\n\nThe sharp fall in living species is first attributed to people’s continued and heavy reliance on them for their own interests. An age-old tradition is that animals are raised, bred and fed for human use. For example, laboratory animals, working animals and sport animals have been used for economic reasons or to fulfil different tasks throughout much of human history. The meat of rare animals is regarded as a delicacy in some countries, for example, whale meat in Japan. When it comes to plants, over-logging, over-grazing and soil erosion are the root causes of the dwindling vegetation. Over-utilisation of living species has made many animals and plants face extinction risk.\n\nAnother reason cited to explain this is that few people take the mass extinction of species seriously. For example, fur is desired and pursued as a fashionable status symbol in many countries, even in those countries where people are known for their environmental concern, such as New Zealand, Canada and Australia. Barely have buyers realised that their purchase decisions will encourage the fur business to further animal slaughter. Rainforest destruction is another example. Despite strong opposition to lumber harvesting, this problem continues simply because people have an ever-growing appetite for land to live on (such as buying luxury properties in the country) and wood products to consume (such as furniture). Humans’ pursuit of comfort and enjoyment has long been justified and condoned, even though the pursuit is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">at the expense of</strong> other species on the planet.\n\nFrom what has been discussed, it is clear that lack of awareness and over-reliance on natural resources are the main reasons why species are being pushed closer to the brink of extinction. Humane education represents a long-term commitment and will help raise a generation that has a real knowledge of environment protection and stays alert to the risk of animal exploitation and ecological degradation. In addition, it is imperative to carefully measure and control any activity that is likely to pose a threat on the survival of species. Decision makers and individual citizens alike should take into consideration the impacts of their decisions and behaviours on living species. It is important to realise that preservation of living species is not sentimental, but essential to the well-being of humankind.","phrases":[{"en":"at the expense of","vi":"đánh đổi bằng / gây tổn hại đến"}],"subtype":"Causes / Effects","_displayNo":"#006","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Far too little has been done to prevent animals and plants from dying out,…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-007","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Animals","title":"Animals: Wildlife protection","prompt":"Some people hold that we should spend money and time on the protection of wild animals while others suggest that the money should be spent on populations living in the poorest areas of the world. What is your opinion?","answer":"In these years, animal protection has become a subject of ongoing scientific research and an issue of concern. People take different views toward the enormous spending required by wildlife conservation. It is suggested that the spending should be diverted to helping human populations, especially those living below poverty line, because human life is more valuable than animal life. In my opinion, the investment in animal conservation is worthwhile.\n\nAnimals, as a significant part of an ecosystem, have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">profound impacts on</strong> the sustainability of an ecosystem and on the well-being of humanity. All animals are connected in one way or another in food chains. For this reason, the demise of a species can lead to overpopulation or underpopulation of another species and then put this species <strong class=\"key-phrase\">at the verge of extinction</strong>. The natural balance will be disrupted and the ecosystem cannot be sustained. It would disable vegetation from purifying water, recycling nutrient and pollinating crops. We humans are eventually affected.\n\nAnother justification for animal protection is that animals play a significant role in the development of industries, as an important natural resource. People derive substances and materials from animals for different purposes. A typical example is that animals provide essential substances for drug-making. It is also very common that designers and engineers <strong class=\"key-phrase\">turn to wildlife for inspiration</strong>. For instance, the invention of water-proof clothing drew upon the research on sharks.\n\nOn account of those benefits, wildlife protection is a significant strategy that has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">far-reaching effects</strong> on the future of human. However, when implemented, this strategy should be adapted in different contexts. It should be noted that spending money simply on animals is not the approach that promises the best outcomes in all circumstances. For example, in those regions where inhabitants struggle with weak economies and have few job sources, direct spending on any animal program would not stop people from hunting and trading animals for a living. An alternative strategy is creating jobs or providing subsidies, lifting these regions out of poverty.\n\nFrom what has been discussed, animals are key components of the whole natural order and have relevance to the sustainability of an ecosystem and the interests of humanity. Animal protection is” strategy that applies to the whole world, and might vary in different circumstances.","phrases":[{"en":"profound impacts on","vi":"tác động sâu sắc đến"},{"en":"at the verge of extinction","vi":"trên bờ vực tuyệt chủng"},{"en":"turn to wildlife for inspiration","vi":"tìm cảm hứng từ thế giới hoang dã"},{"en":"far-reaching effects","vi":"những tác động sâu rộng"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#007","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People hold that we should spend money and time on the protection of wild…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-008","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Animals","title":"Animals: Animal testing","prompt":"Some people strongly oppose animal experimentation, believing that it causes pain to animals, while some other people consider it necessary. What is your opinion?","answer":"Perhaps no subject in the moral community is as controversial as animal testing. Animals, many people believe, merit more humane treatment. When animal-based experiments have long been the centre of criticism, I am of the opinion that such experiments are essential to both the well-being of human beings and that of animals.\n\nThere is little doubt, first of all, that most of the animal-based experiments are conducted for the development of technology and to date, there is little chance of finding satisfying substitutions for animals. Animals are used mainly because they bear a close resemblance to humans, either in behaviour or in cell structure. They respond to external disturbances (such as electric shock) nearly in the same manner as humans do. There is much evidence that most of what people know about themselves, including pain, stress, reproduction and nutrition, is based on findings of animal-based experiments. Animal testing proves one of the main approaches to predict the risk when drugs or other products are used on humans.\n\nAnother fact to support animal-based experiment is that animals are not the equivalent of humans, and can be used as resources for human purposes. Animals have no capacity to recognise the rights of other species. Nor will they take in consideration the interests of other species. It is possibly one of the main reasons why animals feed on each other. Humans, by comparison, use animal experiments not only for their own interests but also for the interests of animals. For example, some medical discoveries can be used by veterinary surgeons to give medical care and treatment to sick animals.\n\nDespite the justifications given for vivisection, researchers have the obligation to reduce animal testing and animal suffering. There is a growing recognition that animal tests are mostly done for commercial purposes and most of them are avoidable. For instance, the cosmetic industry has been exploiting <strong class=\"key-phrase\">animal experimentation</strong> simply for diversifying products and maximising profits. The fewer cosmetic products people use, the fewer animals they have to slaughter. When scientists are empowered to carry out cruel experiments like vivisection, such powers should not be abused.\n\nTo summarise, one can subscribe to the notion that animals can be taken as resources intended for the benefit of humans, although meanwhile it is certain that suffering should be controlled to the minimum during experimentation.","phrases":[{"en":"animal experimentation","vi":"thử nghiệm trên động vật"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#008","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People strongly oppose animal experimentation, believing that it causes…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-009","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Art","title":"Art: Music","prompt":"Some people think that governments should give financial support to creative artists such as painters and musicians. Others believe that creative artists should be funded by alternative sources. Discuss both views and give your own opinion.","answer":"People have different views about the funding of creative artists. While some people disagree with the idea of government support for artists, I believe that money for art projects should come from both governments and other sources.\n\nSome art projects definitely require help from the state. In the UK, there are many <strong class=\"key-phrase\">works of art</strong> in public spaces, such as streets or squares in city centres. In Liverpool, for example, there are several new statues and sculptures in the docks area of the city, which has been redeveloped recently. These artworks represent culture, heritage and history. They serve to educate people about the city, and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">act as landmarks</strong> or talking points for visitors and tourists. Governments and local councils should pay creative artists to produce this kind of art, because without their funding our cities would be much less interesting and attractive.\n\nOn the other hand, I can understand the arguments against government funding for art. The main reason for this view is that governments have more important concerns. For example, state budgets need to be spent on education, healthcare, infrastructure and security, among other areas. These public services are vital for a country to function properly, whereas the work of creative artists, even in public places, is a luxury. Another reason for this opinion is that artists do a job like any other professional, and they should therefore earn their own money by selling their work.\n\nIn conclusion, there are good reasons why artists should rely on alternative sources of financial support, but in my opinion government help is sometimes necessary.","phrases":[{"en":"works of art","vi":"các tác phẩm nghệ thuật"},{"en":"act as landmarks","vi":"đóng vai trò là các địa danh biểu tượng"}],"subtype":"Discuss both views + opinion · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#009","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Public funding for creative artists","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-010","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Business","title":"Business: Money","prompt":"As well as making money, businesses also have social responsibilities. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Businesses have always aimed to make a profit, but it is becoming increasingly common to hear people talk about the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">social obligations</strong> that companies have. I completely agree with the idea that businesses should do more for society than simply make money.\n\nOn the one hand, I accept that businesses must make money in order to survive in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a competitive world</strong>. It seems logical that the priority of any company should be to cover its running costs, such as employees’ wages and payments for buildings and utilities. On top of these costs, companies also need to invest in improvements and innovations if they wish to remain successful. If a company is unable to pay its bills or <strong class=\"key-phrase\">meet the changing needs of customers</strong>, any concerns about <strong class=\"key-phrase\">social responsibilities</strong> become irrelevant. In other words, a company can only make a positive contribution to society if it is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">in good financial health</strong>.\n\nOn the other hand, companies should not be run with the sole aim of maximising profit; they <strong class=\"key-phrase\">have a wider role to play in</strong> society. One social obligation that owners and managers have is to treat their employees well, rather than exploiting them. For example, they could pay a “living wage” to ensure that workers have a good quality of life. I also like the idea that businesses could use a proportion of their profits to support local charities, environmental projects or education initiatives. Finally, instead of trying to minimise their tax payments by using accounting loopholes, I believe that company bosses should be happy to contribute to society through the tax system.\n\nIn conclusion, I believe that companies should place as much importance on their social responsibilities as they do on their financial objectives.","phrases":[{"en":"social obligations","vi":"những ràng buộc xã hội"},{"en":"a competitive world","vi":"một thế giới đầy sự cạnh tranh"},{"en":"meet the changing needs of customers","vi":"đáp ứng nhu cầu luôn thay đổi từ khách hàng"},{"en":"social responsibilities","vi":"các trách nhiệm đối với xã hội"},{"en":"in good financial health","vi":"tình hình tài chính ổn định"},{"en":"have a wider role to play in","vi":"có vai trò rộng lớn hơn trong"}],"subtype":"Agree / Disagree · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#010","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Corporate social responsibility","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-011","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Cities","title":"Cities","prompt":"More and more people are migrating to cities in search of a better life, but city life can be extremely difficult. Explain some of the difficulties of living in a city. How can governments make urban life better for everyone?","answer":"Cities are often seen as <strong class=\"key-phrase\">places of opportunity</strong>, but there are also some major drawbacks of living in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a large metropolis</strong>. In my opinion, governments could do much more to improve city life for the average inhabitant.\n\nThe main problem for anyone who hopes to migrate to a large city is that the cost of living is likely to be much higher than it is in a small town or village. Inhabitants of cities have to pay higher prices for housing, transport, and even food. Another issue is that urban areas tend to suffer from social problems such as <strong class=\"key-phrase\">high crime and poverty rates</strong> in comparison with rural areas. Furthermore, the air quality in cities is often poor, due to pollution from traffic, and the streets and public transport systems are usually overcrowded. As a result, city life can be unhealthy and stressful.\n\nHowever, there are various steps that governments could take to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">tackle these problems</strong>. Firstly, they could invest money in the building of affordable or social housing to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reduce the cost of living</strong>. Secondly, politicians have the power to ban vehicles from city centres and promote the use of cleaner public transport, which would help to reduce both air pollution and traffic congestion. In London, for example, the introduction of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a congestion charge</strong> for drivers has helped to curb the traffic problem. A third option would be to develop provincial towns and rural areas, by moving industry and jobs to those regions, in order to reduce the pressure on major cities.\n\nIn conclusion, governments could certainly implement a range of measures to enhance the quality of life for all city residents.","phrases":[{"en":"places of opportunity","vi":"nơi có nhiều cơ hội"},{"en":"a large metropolis","vi":"một đô thị lớn"},{"en":"high crime and poverty rates","vi":"tỷ lệ tội phạm và đói nghèo cao"},{"en":"tackle these problems","vi":"giải quyết những vấn đề này"},{"en":"reduce the cost of living","vi":"giảm chi phí sống"},{"en":"a congestion charge","vi":"phí ùn tắc giao thông"}],"subtype":"Causes / Effects / Solutions · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#011","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Urban living challenges and solutions","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-012","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Cities","title":"Cities: Rural-to-urban migration","prompt":"Many countries today are experiencing high levels of migration from rural areas to cities. What are the causes of this trend, and what effects does it have on the existing city dwellers? Give reasons for your answer, and provide ideas and examples from your own experience. You should write at least 250 words.","answer":"Migration from the countryside to cities is certainly a topical issue, as so many nations are seeing this pattern today. There are three main causes, and two key impacts, which I will outline now. The main cause is probably the lack of employment available to rural people. Rural industries, ranging from agriculture to food production and animal breeding, have all been rationalized and made far more efficient in recent years, meaning that fewer people are needed to staff them. Furthermore, the growth of employment opportunities in the cities means that people, especially youngsters, are tempted to move there by higher wages and the prospect of reliable work. Finally, many countries still have a weaker infrastructure in rural areas, especially in terms of transport and economic activity. For example, if a country dweller is unable to find public transport to get to work locally, that person will inevitably consider moving to a city where the infrastructure is far better established. Regarding the effects felt by the urban residents, perhaps the main impact is on accommodation. An increased urban population drives up the cost of buying or renting a home, leading to possible hardship for people who had assumed that prices would <strong class=\"key-phrase\">remain stable</strong>. We can see this clearly in major conurbations such as London, Sao Paolo or Delhi, where property prices are extremely high and continue to rise. The other main effect on the existing city population is the vastly increased competition for job opportunities, especially at a less skilled level. For instance, drivers, shop workers and hospitality staff find themselves competing for work with new arrivals who are often prepared to work for less. This can lead to a reduction in wages and consequent decline in standard of living, especially when combined with the increased cost of housing. To sum up, the causes of this trend are primarily to do with employment, and the effects are felt in terms of wages and accommodation.","phrases":[{"en":"remain stable","vi":"giữ ổn định"}],"subtype":"Causes / Effects","_displayNo":"#012","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"Countries today are experiencing high levels of migration from rural areas…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-013","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Cities","title":"Cities: Population change","prompt":"Overpopulation of urban areas has led to numerous problems. Identify one or two serious ones and suggest ways that governments and individuals can tackle these problems.","answer":"Rapid urban population growth can generate economic opportunity, but when housing and infrastructure fail to expand at the same pace, cities become less liveable. The most serious consequences are insecure housing and overloaded transport, both of which require action from governments as well as residents.\n\nA shortage of affordable homes forces low-income households into overcrowded or informal accommodation. Such housing may lack ventilation, sanitation or legal protection, exposing residents to illness and sudden eviction. At the same time, excessive demand for road space and public transport produces long commutes, air pollution and lost productivity. These pressures are mutually reinforcing: families pushed to distant suburbs often spend more time and money travelling to work, thereby <strong class=\"key-phrase\">deepening existing social inequality</strong>.\n\nGovernments should first increase the supply of well-connected, affordable housing rather than simply moving poorer residents to the urban fringe. Planning rules can require new developments to include lower-cost units, while public investment should extend water, schools and clinics alongside housing construction. Cities also need high-capacity public transport integrated with land-use planning. Reliable rail and bus networks allow denser neighbourhoods to function without proportional growth in private car use.\n\nIndividuals cannot solve structural shortages, but they can contribute. Residents can use public transport, share vehicles and support local planning proposals that increase housing density near employment centres. Community organisations can also identify unsafe properties, assist tenants and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">hold local authorities accountable for implementation</strong>. These actions are most effective when citizens <strong class=\"key-phrase\">have access to</strong> transparent data and formal channels for participation.\n\nIn conclusion, urban overpopulation becomes damaging when housing and transport systems are neglected. Governments must lead through coordinated investment and planning, while individuals can reduce pressure on infrastructure and demand that public commitments are fulfilled.","phrases":[{"en":"deepening existing social inequality","vi":"làm trầm trọng thêm bất bình đẳng xã hội hiện có"},{"en":"hold local authorities accountable for implementation","vi":"yêu cầu chính quyền địa phương chịu trách nhiệm về việc triển khai"},{"en":"have access to","vi":"được tiếp cận với"}],"subtype":"Problems and solutions · Nguồn đề: IELTS Buddy","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#013","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Urban overpopulation: problems and solutions","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"City","prompt":"Some people prefer to live in a house, while others feel that there are more advantages to living in an apartment. Are there more advantages than disadvantages of living in a house compared with living in an apartment?","answer":"Both houses and apartments can provide a comfortable home, but they suit different priorities. In my view, a house offers more space and privacy, while an apartment is usually more convenient and affordable. For many urban residents, the advantages of apartment living are greater.\n\nA house is attractive because it gives residents more control over their property. Families may have extra bedrooms, a garden and space for children or pets. Noise from neighbours is also less likely to be a problem. These benefits make a house especially suitable for larger families who value <strong class=\"key-phrase\">privacy and long-term stability</strong>.\n\nHowever, houses often cost more to buy, heat and maintain. They may also be located far from city centres, which increases commuting time. Apartments generally require less maintenance and are often close to jobs, shops and public transport. Modern buildings may also provide security, parking and shared facilities. For a single person or a small family, this can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reduce both cost and daily inconvenience</strong>.\n\nA further consideration is flexibility over time. An apartment may suit someone at the start of a career, but a house can become more attractive when a family grows or begins working from home. Buying either type of property also involves service charges, repair bills and transport costs, so the cheapest purchase price is not always <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the most economical choice over the long term</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, houses provide space and independence, but apartments offer practical advantages that are particularly important in crowded cities. The better choice depends on family size and income, although apartment living is likely to be more suitable for a larger proportion of urban residents because it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">makes efficient use of limited space</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"City","phrases":[{"en":"privacy and long-term stability","vi":"sự riêng tư và ổn định lâu dài"},{"en":"reduce both cost and daily inconvenience","vi":"giảm cả chi phí lẫn bất tiện hằng ngày"},{"en":"the most economical choice over the long term","vi":"lựa chọn tiết kiệm nhất trong dài hạn"},{"en":"makes efficient use of limited space","vi":"sử dụng hiệu quả không gian hạn chế"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"two-part","summary":"House vs. Apartment: Space Wins Despite Higher Costs","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-014","_displayNo":"#014","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-015","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Community","title":"Community: Work","prompt":"Some people think that all teenagers should be required to do unpaid work in their free time to help the local community. They believe this would benefit both the individual teenager and society as a whole. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Many young people <strong class=\"key-phrase\">work on a volunteer basis</strong>, and this can only be beneficial for both the individual and society as a whole and encourage a sense of shared civic responsibility. However, I do not agree that we should therefore force all teenagers to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">do unpaid work</strong>.\n\nMost young people are already under enough pressure with their studies, without being given the added responsibility of working in their spare time. School is just as demanding as a full-time job, and teachers expect their students to do <strong class=\"key-phrase\">homework and exam revision</strong> on top of attending lessons every day. When young people do have some free time, we should encourage them to enjoy it with their friends or to spend it doing sports and other leisure activities. They have many years of work ahead of them when they finish their studies.\n\nAt the same time, I do not believe that society has anything to gain from obliging young people to do unpaid work. In fact, I would argue that it goes against the values of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a free and fair society</strong> to force a group of people to do something against their will. Doing this can only lead to resentment amongst young people, who would feel that they were being used, and parents, who would not want to be told how to raise their children. Currently, nobody is forced to volunteer, and this is surely the best system.\n\nIn conclusion, teenagers may choose to work for free and help others, but in my opinion we should not make this compulsory.","phrases":[{"en":"work on a volunteer basis","vi":"làm việc tình nguyện"},{"en":"do unpaid work","vi":"làm công việc không hưởng lương"},{"en":"homework and exam revision","vi":"bài tập về nhà và việc ôn thi"},{"en":"a free and fair society","vi":"một xã hội tự do và công bằng"}],"subtype":"Agree / Disagree · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#015","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Compulsory community work for teenagers","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-016","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Crime","title":"Crime: Prison as punishment","prompt":"Some people who have been in prison become good citizens later, and it is often argued that these are the best people to talk to teenagers about the dangers of committing a crime. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"It is true that ex-prisoners can become normal, productive members of society. I completely agree with the idea that allowing such people to speak to teenagers about their experiences is the best way to discourage them from breaking the law.\n\nIn my opinion, teenagers are more likely to accept advice from someone who can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">speak from experience</strong>. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">Reformed offenders</strong> can tell young people about how they became involved in crime, the dangers of a criminal lifestyle, and what life in prison is really like. They can also dispel any ideas that teenagers may have about criminals leading glamorous lives. While adolescents are often indifferent to the guidance given by older people, I imagine that most of them would be extremely keen to hear the stories of an ex-offender. The vivid and perhaps shocking nature of these stories is likely to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">have a powerful impact</strong>.\n\nThe alternatives to using reformed criminals to educate teenagers about crime would be much less effective. One option would be for police officers to visit schools and talk to young people. This could be useful in terms of informing teens about what happens to lawbreakers when they are caught, but young people are often reluctant to take advice from <strong class=\"key-phrase\">figures of authority</strong>. A second option would be for school teachers to speak to their students about crime, but I doubt that students would see teachers as credible sources of information about this topic. Finally, educational films might be informative, but there would be no opportunity for young people to interact and ask questions. In conclusion, I fully support the view that people who have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">turned their lives around</strong> after serving a prison sentence could help to deter teenagers from committing crimes.","phrases":[{"en":"speak from experience","vi":"nói từ trải nghiệm"},{"en":"Reformed offenders","vi":"người phạm tội đã được cải tạo"},{"en":"have a powerful impact","vi":"có một ảnh hưởng mạnh mẽ"},{"en":"figures of authority","vi":"những người có thẩm quyền"},{"en":"turned their lives around","vi":"thay đổi cuộc đời theo hướng tích cực"}],"subtype":"Agree / Disagree · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#016","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Ex-prisoners educating teenagers","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-017","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Crime","title":"Crime and punishment","prompt":"In many countries, financial crime involving identity theft is increasing. What are the causes of this trend, and what effect does identity theft have on the victims involved? Give reasons for your answer, and provide ideas and examples from your own experience. You should write at least 250 words.","answer":"<strong class=\"key-phrase\">There is no doubt that</strong> identity fraud is a great concern, especially in western countries where people are most at risk. I think there are two main causes, and a number of damaging effects. The major cause is probably the almost universal use of digital technology to store financial data and undertake financial transactions. It is surprisingly easy for criminals to obtain personal information about a possible victim, and then to use this information to impersonate the target. Because bank accounts and loans can be applied for digitally, without the need for face-to-face contact, the criminals are able to apply for financial products remotely, often before the victim is even aware of the attack. The second key cause is, I believe, the increasing probability of ’traditional’ crimes (such as armed robbery, mugging or burglary) being detected. When criminals see the widespread use of CCTV, DNA profiling and fingerprinting, they are less inclined to indulge in such old-fashioned crimes. Rather, they prefer the lower risk and more profitable use of data-based crimes. The effects on the unfortunate victims can be quite devastating. Firstly, there is the loss of money from bank accounts or by being connected to a fraudulent loan. In some cases, this can take years for the victim to pay back or resolve with the banks and the authorities. Secondly, there is the damage to their credit rating, which means they may find it impossible to obtain legitimate credit in future. In extreme cases, people’s employment prospects can even be damaged as well, as they find themselves profiled as a financial risk. Overall, the presence of technology and the decline of ’traditional’ crimes are the key causes behind this trend. The effects on the victims involve long-term financial hardship in many instances.","phrases":[{"en":"There is no doubt that","vi":"không còn nghi ngờ rằng"}],"subtype":"Causes / Effects","_displayNo":"#017","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"Financial crime involving identity theft is increasing.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-018","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Crime","title":"Crime: Police street patrols","prompt":"Having police officers patrolling the streets is often considered an essential way to reduce crime. How effective do you think police street patrols are? What other ways of reducing crime can you propose? Give reasons for your answer, and provide ideas and examples from your own experience. You should write at least 250 words.","answer":"We are all keen to reduce crime wherever possible, and the role of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">visible policing</strong> is a hotly debated part of this. Personally, I feel that street patrols are highly effective, although there are several <strong class=\"key-phrase\">supplementary methods</strong> too. Regarding the effectiveness of patrols, evidence suggests that an increase in police on the streets leads directly to a drop in crime, especially crimes of violence and robbery. A good example is the experience of New York when it adopted the ’zero tolerance’ policy in the 1990s, a high-profile policing tactic which has been extended successfully to many other cities worldwide. When compared to other tactics that have been tried, ranging from citizen patrols to CCTV, there is little doubt that assertive police patrolling is the most effective resource we have. Turning to other methods, we should supplement police patrols with coordinated action elsewhere in the state. For instance, the courts should be prepared to issue deterrent sentences and prisons should be run strictly. This would help to deter people from committing crimes in the first place. Secondly, we should increase the resources available to the police away from the streets as well, for instance in detective and forensic departments, hopefully ensuring that detection rates are high when crimes do occur. Moreover, individuals and businesses should step up their own security arrangements to complement the police presence. For example, improved locks and lighting are simple measures which can reduce theft and burglary. All in all, I feel that visible police patrols have been proved to be the most effective way to reduce common crimes. Their effectiveness can be maximized by supporting action from elsewhere in the police and justice system, and by private citizens doing their part as well.","phrases":[{"en":"visible policing","vi":"hoạt động cảnh sát hiện diện công khai"},{"en":"supplementary methods","vi":"các biện pháp bổ trợ"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#018","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"Having police officers patrolling the streets is often considered an…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-019","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Crime","title":"Crime: Prison as punishment","prompt":"“Prison is the only truly effective form of punishment, because it separates criminals from society.” To what extent do you support this view?","answer":"<strong class=\"key-phrase\">There is no doubt that</strong> we need to find effective forms of punishment for criminals, and also find ways to protect citizens from the threat of crime. I personally feel that prison is only one of a range of options we should use, and is not always the most effective. Firstly, I do not accept that all criminals need to be separated from society. Juvenile and minor offenders can be punished through fines, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">community service</strong> or other non-custodial means. This is cheaper than prison, and prevents the damage to the criminal’s family which in itself could generate further social problems. Furthermore, by keeping these small-scale criminals in society, we can try to rehabilitate them, for example through training or education programmes. This will help to reduce re-offending in future. Besides this, if offenders are believed to be a threat to their fellow citizens, there are ways of containing them such as electronic tagging, curfews or regular reporting to the police. Such methods have been shown to be effective in reducing criminal behaviour and are themselves quite a strong punishment, as they restrict an offender’s freedom greatly. Finally, we should remember that prisons are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">to some extent</strong> ’schools of crime’ and in many cases prisoners end their jail terms as more capable and determined criminals than when they entered. Of course, it is true that in certain cases we need to both punish criminals and isolate them from other people. I recognise that violent or dangerous people need to be imprisoned – yet I believe this applies to a small minority of instances. To conclude, I feel that prison is a last resort in cases where there is no alternative. This does not make it the only effective punishment, but rather the most severe among a variety of possibilities.","phrases":[{"en":"There is no doubt that","vi":"không còn nghi ngờ rằng"},{"en":"community service","vi":"hoạt động phục vụ cộng đồng"},{"en":"to some extent","vi":"ở một mức độ nào đó"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#019","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"“Prison is the only truly effective form of punishment, because it…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-020","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Crime","title":"Crime: Corporal punishment","prompt":"Although it is generally prohibited, corporal punishment persists in many families. Do you think corporal punishment is an acceptable way to regulate children’s behaviour?","answer":"Corporal punishment is still used in some families because it can stop bad behaviour immediately. However, I do not believe that hitting a child is an acceptable form of discipline. It may produce short-term obedience, but it creates serious physical, emotional and educational risks.\n\nThe first problem is that physical punishment can easily <strong class=\"key-phrase\">blur the line between discipline and abuse</strong>. A parent who is angry or tired may use more force than intended, and a child has little power to protect himself or herself. Even when no visible injury occurs, repeated punishment can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cause lasting psychological harm</strong>. Children may become anxious, secretive or resentful, rather than learning why their behaviour was wrong.\n\nA second concern is the lesson that physical punishment teaches. When adults solve conflict by hitting, they <strong class=\"key-phrase\">model aggression as a legitimate response</strong> to frustration. Children may then copy this behaviour with siblings or classmates. Fear can also damage trust between parents and children, making honest communication less likely precisely when young people need guidance.\n\nParents still need effective ways to control unacceptable behaviour. The better approach is to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">set clear and consistent boundaries</strong>, explain the consequences of breaking them, and use proportionate measures such as loss of privileges or additional responsibilities. Praise for good behaviour is equally important because it shows children what they should do, not merely what they should avoid.\n\nIn conclusion, corporal punishment is neither necessary nor defensible. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">Non-violent forms of discipline</strong> can correct behaviour while preserving a child’s dignity, safety and relationship with the family.","phrases":[{"en":"blur the line between discipline and abuse","vi":"làm mờ ranh giới giữa kỷ luật và bạo hành"},{"en":"cause lasting psychological harm","vi":"gây tổn thương tâm lý lâu dài"},{"en":"model aggression as a legitimate response","vi":"coi hành vi hung hăng là một phản ứng chính đáng"},{"en":"set clear and consistent boundaries","vi":"đặt ra những giới hạn rõ ràng và nhất quán"},{"en":"non-violent forms of discipline","vi":"các hình thức kỷ luật không bạo lực"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#020","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Although it is generally prohibited, corporal punishment persists in many…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-021","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Crime","title":"Crime and punishment","prompt":"Do you think that parents should be punished if their five-year-old child commits a crime? From what age should children be held responsible for their own behaviour?","answer":"Parents have a major influence on a young child, but punishing them automatically for every offence committed by a five-year-old would be unfair. At that age, children have only a limited understanding of law and consequences. In my view, parents should be held accountable only when clear neglect or encouragement of wrongdoing can be proved.\n\nA five-year-old normally copies behaviour rather than forming a deliberate criminal intention. Parents are responsible for supervision, basic discipline and the examples they set at home. If a child repeatedly harms others because adults have ignored serious warning signs, allowed access to dangerous objects or actively encouraged aggression, the parents may reasonably face penalties or compulsory support programmes. This approach recognises <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a duty of reasonable supervision</strong> without treating every childhood mistake as parental misconduct.\n\nHowever, responsibility should gradually move from the parent to the child as judgement develops. A single fixed age cannot reflect every case, but the law can use age bands. Children under about ten should usually receive protection, education and family intervention rather than punishment. Older children can be held increasingly responsible when they understand that an act is wrong and can foresee its consequences. For serious offences, courts should consider maturity, intention and personal circumstances instead of relying only on age.\n\nIn conclusion, parents should not be punished simply because their young child commits an offence. Penalties are justified only where there is evidence of serious neglect or deliberate encouragement. Children themselves should assume <strong class=\"key-phrase\">increasing responsibility as their judgement matures</strong>, with rehabilitation remaining the main aim of the youth justice system.","phrases":[{"en":"a duty of reasonable supervision","vi":"nghĩa vụ giám sát hợp lý"},{"en":"increasing responsibility as their judgement matures","vi":"trách nhiệm tăng dần khi khả năng phán đoán trưởng thành"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#021","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Do you think that parents should be punished if their five-year-old child…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-022","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Crime","title":"Crime and punishment","prompt":"In recent years, the proportion of crimes committed by young people has risen. What are the causes of this problem, and what solutions can you suggest?","answer":"Youth crime usually has several causes rather than one simple explanation. In my view, the most important factors are unstable family life, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">repeated exposure to violence</strong> and a lack of realistic opportunities. Effective solutions must therefore combine early support with education and employment.\n\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">The breakdown of stable family relationships</strong> can leave young people without consistent supervision or clear boundaries. Parents who work long hours may have little time to notice changes in behaviour, while conflict or abuse at home can normalise aggression. A second factor is repeated exposure to violence through neighbourhood crime, social media or certain forms of entertainment. This does not automatically turn a teenager into an offender, but it can reduce sensitivity to harm and make risky behaviour appear ordinary. Finally, some young people see few legal routes to status or income, especially when they struggle at school and cannot find work.\n\nThe most effective response is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">early intervention</strong>. Schools should identify persistent absence, aggression and learning difficulties before they develop into more serious problems. Counselling and family-support services can help parents establish routines and manage conflict. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">After-school programmes</strong> are also valuable because sport, music and supervised study give teenagers a structured alternative to spending time on the street.\n\nGovernments and employers should also provide <strong class=\"key-phrase\">realistic routes into education and employment</strong>. Paid apprenticeships, vocational courses and entry-level jobs can give young people both practical skills and a reason to plan for the future. Serious offences still require proportionate punishment, but detention alone is unlikely to prevent reoffending unless it includes education and rehabilitation.\n\nIn conclusion, youth crime is driven mainly by weak support, exposure to violence and limited opportunity. Prevention is most successful when families, schools and employers act before criminal behaviour becomes established.","phrases":[{"en":"repeated exposure to violence","vi":"việc thường xuyên tiếp xúc với bạo lực"},{"en":"the breakdown of stable family relationships","vi":"sự đổ vỡ của các mối quan hệ gia đình ổn định"},{"en":"early intervention","vi":"can thiệp sớm"},{"en":"after-school programmes","vi":"các chương trình sau giờ học"},{"en":"realistic routes into education and employment","vi":"những lộ trình thực tế để tiếp cận giáo dục và việc làm"}],"subtype":"Causes / Solutions","_displayNo":"#022","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"In recent years, the proportion of the crimes committed by youngsters is on…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-023","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Crime","title":"Crime","prompt":"The only way to improve road safety is to impose severe punishment for driving offences. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Road safety has long been an issue of concern to the public, and to the government. Nothing qualifies as a sufficient compensation when a road accident occurs. Despite the painstaking effort to reduce death, injury and trauma across the world, many countries are seeing traffic accidents increase exponentially. In improving road safety, some people advocate <strong class=\"key-phrase\">harsh punishment</strong>. In my opinion, it is merely one of the many countermeasures and cannot prevent all criminal offences on the road.\n\nIn many cases, many automobile accidents occur not because drivers belittle or defy road regulations but because those regulations are unfamiliar to them. It is an everyday occurrence that rule-breaking acts and traffic crashes are linked to poor driving skills. Many drivers have limited experience in coping with different situations and an inaccurate estimation of the complexity of road conditions, despite having passed licence tests. It alerts people to the loopholes in policies, such as the loose control over car use, low requirements on driving training and low licence standards. In tackling those problems, it is imperative to require licence applicants to attend more safe-driving courses and pass strict tests,\n\nBesides education, other endeavours, such as improving road infrastructure and transportation systems, are equally important. Road conditions should be improved to allow different users, including drivers, cyclists and pedestrians, to use roads safely. Other facilities, such as stoplights and stop signs, can be used wherever appropriate to curb speed driving. Furthermore, authorities can sponsor the research for road safety measures and effective precautions, such as identifying risk factors of different driving patterns. By translating these findings into policies and practices, the government is in a stronger position to protect vehicle occupants and vulnerable road users.\n\nWider intervention of local authorities is also recommended, such as increasing patrols in those areas where accident rate is high. Road regulations should be reassessed and revised regularly so as to combat road offences more effectively. When the existing policies fail to regulate road users’ behaviour, tightening the control is preferred. However, as suggested before, strict standards require full compliance. Without regulations closely observed, standards are in fact vain.\n\nIt can therefore be made clear that punishment is not the only way to cut the accident rate and improve people’s safety on road. Some other measures, such as increasing road users’ knowledge of rules and defence driving skills, improving road infrastructure and enforcing compliance with standards, are all important.","phrases":[{"en":"harsh punishment","vi":"hình phạt nghiêm khắc"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#023","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Only way to improve road safety is to impose severe punishment for driving…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-024","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Crime","title":"Crime and punishment","prompt":"Many people are afraid to leave their homes because of crime. Some believe that more can be done to prevent crime, while others think that little can be done. What is your opinion?","answer":"The rise in the crime rate in the past decades has fuelled public worries about the rapidly declining safety of their communities. Some people take the position that little can be done to prevent themselves from victimisation. As opposed to this general pessimism, many people, however, maintain that in combating crime, people should <strong class=\"key-phrase\">adopt a proactive approach</strong>. I side with both of them.\n\nThe first point to support this is that the government can increase intervention, including launching anti-crime public campaigns, enforcing new laws, and providing education. A civilised society is characterised by a high literacy rate and a low crime rate. The negative relationship between these two parameters implies that one will be away from a life of crime if given the access to education, Another method relies on the combination of imposing tougher laws and training a more effective police force Not only does it penalise those offenders but it also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">deters prospective criminals</strong>. Moreover, the government can capitalise on the mass media throughout the country to alert the public to the threat of crime and teach citizens self-defence techniques.\n\nFor individual citizens, many crimes can be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">nipped in the bud</strong>, if they keep vigilant at crimes and are brave enough to fight back. It is particularly true in cases where burglars break into houses without an alarm system, and shoplifters target those shops that are not under the surveillance of security camera. In simple terms, it is people’s negligence that causes them to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">fall prey to the criminals</strong>. On other occasions, criminals are pampered by people’s cowardice. If they possessed courage to chase criminals or at least report to the police on a crime, there would be fewer victims.\n\nTo tackle crime, as indicated above, requires the commitment of nearly all members of society, from the government to ordinary citizens. Although there might not be a great deal one can do to prevent crimes from occurring, it is not entirely helpless. Solutions exist somewhere always, but wait to be found and practiced.","phrases":[{"en":"adopt a proactive approach","vi":"áp dụng cách tiếp cận chủ động"},{"en":"deters prospective criminals","vi":"răn đe những người có ý định phạm tội"},{"en":"nipped in the bud","vi":"ngăn chặn từ sớm"},{"en":"fall prey to the criminals","vi":"trở thành nạn nhân của tội phạm"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#024","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People are afraid of leaving their houses because of the spread of crimes.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-025","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Crime","title":"Crime: News media","prompt":"Some people suggest that there should be restrictions on a detailed description of crimes in the newspapers and on television. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"The violent content broadcast by the mass media (the television and the printing press in particular) have been singled out in recent years as a matter of urgent public concern. It has been argued that a detailed description of crime, especially violent crime, should be restricted. I agree on this suggestion based on the following concerns.\n\nThere can be little doubt that a complete description of crimes has a direct impact on viewers’ perception of crime, including its nature and impacts. Ongoing exposure to reports on crime scenes has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">desensitised viewers to</strong> the horrors of serious crimes such as homicide. Many TV programmes tend to dramatise the process of tracing criminals. So immersed are viewers in the storyline that few are encouraged to link the crime to a brutal and devastating act. Meanwhile, hardly has any newspaper or TV editor carried out a follow-up study of convicting criminals. This form of representation fails to alert viewers to the fact that no criminal can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">stay at large</strong> and all offenders will be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">brought to justice</strong>.\n\nMeanwhile, the depiction of violence is potentially the primary cause of “copycat” suicides, fights, shootings and bombings. People are inclined to vent their discontent in various ways, and one of the most common is violence. The documentary on a criminal or violent act provides them with role models, those characters who initiate most of the acts of violence on television. The portrayal of those characters encourages viewers to emulate violent behaviour, believing that their acts are likely to be acknowledged,\n\nDespite its enormous effects on the audience, the description of crimes on television or newspapers should not be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made a scapegoat for</strong> all social violence. It would divert people’s attention from the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">root causes of violence</strong>. Some depictions of violence are likely to contribute to harmful effects on viewers, whereas other portrayals may be pro-social and beneficial for the audience. For example, many programmes encourage no-violent alternatives to solutions. Similarly, television and newspapers have played a significant role in educating the audience about the advantages of building a non-violence community and the dangers of excessive drinking, car racing, drug using and other unlawful acts.\n\nAs suggested above, media violence, including the detailed picturing of violent acts, contributes at least partly to social violence and to the audience’s aggressive thoughts and behaviour. However, there is no simple cause-and-effect relationship between media violence and societal violence and both have multiple causes.","phrases":[{"en":"desensitised viewers to","vi":"khiến người xem trở nên chai lì trước"},{"en":"stay at large","vi":"vẫn chưa bị bắt"},{"en":"brought to justice","vi":"bị đưa ra trước công lý"},{"en":"made a scapegoat for","vi":"bị biến thành vật tế thần cho"},{"en":"root causes of violence","vi":"nguyên nhân gốc rễ của bạo lực"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#025","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People suggest that there should be restrictions on a detailed description…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-026","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Crime","title":"Crime","prompt":"Police in Britain do not carry guns. Some people believe that unarmed police are unable to protect citizens, but some suggest that arming the police will lead to a surge in violence in society. Discuss those two views.","answer":"Whether police officers should routinely carry guns depends on the level of risk in a particular society. Supporters argue that firearms allow officers to confront dangerous criminals, while opponents fear that routine arming would increase violence. I believe that most officers should remain unarmed, although specially trained units should have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">strictly regulated access to firearms</strong>.\n\nThe main argument for arming the police is protection. Officers may face criminals who already possess guns, and an unarmed response can place both the police and the public at risk. The visible possibility of an armed response may also deter some offenders. In areas where gun crime is common, it would be unrealistic to expect officers to deal with every incident without suitable protection.\n\nHowever, routine arming can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">raise the risk of fatal mistakes</strong>. Police officers often make decisions in seconds, sometimes in poor light or under intense pressure. A weapon can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">escalate otherwise manageable encounters</strong> and turn a misunderstanding into a death. Widespread firearms may also change the relationship between the police and the public, making ordinary citizens feel that they are dealing with a military force rather than a civil service.\n\nA balanced policy is therefore preferable. Ordinary patrol officers can remain unarmed, while specialist teams receive advanced training and respond to incidents involving firearms or terrorism. Clear rules should govern when weapons may be used, and every shooting should be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">subject to independent investigation</strong>. Officers also need strong training in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">negotiation, restraint and de-escalation</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, armed police are necessary in exceptional high-risk situations, but routine arming would create avoidable dangers. Limited access, specialist training and strict accountability offer better protection than giving every officer a gun.","phrases":[{"en":"strictly regulated access to firearms","vi":"quyền tiếp cận súng được kiểm soát nghiêm ngặt"},{"en":"raise the risk of fatal mistakes","vi":"làm tăng nguy cơ xảy ra sai lầm chết người"},{"en":"escalate otherwise manageable encounters","vi":"khiến những tình huống vốn có thể kiểm soát trở nên nghiêm trọng"},{"en":"subject to independent investigation","vi":"được điều tra độc lập"},{"en":"negotiation, restraint and de-escalation","vi":"đàm phán, kiềm chế và hạ nhiệt căng thẳng"}],"subtype":"Problems / Solutions","_displayNo":"#026","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Police in Britain do not carry guns.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-027","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Crime","title":"Crime and punishment","prompt":"Some scientists believe that studying the behaviour of 3-year-old children can predict their criminality. To what extent do you think a crime is a product of human nature or is it possible to stop children from growing up to be criminals?","answer":"The age-old nature vs nurture debate is concerned mainly with reaching a conclusion over genetic and environmental influences on criminal behaviour, which has long been a subject of interest to psychologists and criminologists. Some scientists subscribe to a view that studying the behaviour of 3-year-old children can help foretell their criminality. To the best of my knowledge, both genes and environment have a bearing over the development of one’s behaviour patterns, including criminal or violent behaviour.\n\nThe notion that some individuals have a genetic predisposition for criminal behaviour can seek support from many facts. For example, aggression and impulsivity, two personality traits commonly found among adult criminals, are in fact evident from as early as those people’s preschool years. Criminals are also diagnosed to share a similar set of psychological problems, indicating their heritable nature. If given the right circumstances, individuals with those genes would eventually engage in criminal activity, For example, the children raised in an environment where violence and illegitimacy are norms are more likely to commit similar crimes in adulthood. It is therefore fair to say that the effect of heredity is worsened by the environment.\n\nWhile the impact of genetic predisposition is recognised, genetics is not solely responsible for unlawful acts. Criminal tendencies are admittedly clear among those children whose parents have a long criminal history. However, the chances for their engagement in criminal activities would not become bigger until they are exposed to an environment that breeds such activities. Environment can modify, weaken or reinforce one’s characteristics. It is the reason why a child can act in a different manner from his or her parents. It is neither practicable nor rational to make a moral judgement on a child simply by their genetic makeup and /abel him or her as a criminal while ignoring the influence of factors like education.\n\nA proper understanding of the impact of environment on individual behaviour also enables people to recognise the influence of some other elements, such as schooling and upbringing. Children, whose biological parents have criminal records, have the potential for personal success, if adopted and reared by <strong class=\"key-phrase\">well-educated</strong> and upper class families. Likewise, children who experience family problems like family breakdown and child abuse are more likely to commit violent crimes later in life. These elements, working either in isolation or in groups, lead to a child’s criminal behaviour.\n\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">In the light of</strong> the facts outlined above, one can conclude that the interaction between genes and the environment is a predictor of criminal behaviour. Certain genes, when combined with certain environmental factors, lead to criminal behaviour. To prevent individuals with criminal disposition from committing crimes, schooling, parenting and some other factors are of critical importance.","phrases":[{"en":"well-educated","vi":"được giáo dục tốt; có học thức"},{"en":"In the light of","vi":"xét theo / căn cứ vào"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#027","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Scientists believe that studying the behaviour of 3-year-old children can…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-028","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Crime","title":"Crime and punishment","prompt":"There are more and more effective security measures in large cities to reduce the crime. Does this endeavour bring more benefits than problems?","answer":"In these years, the society has seen rapid proliferation of different measures aiming to prevent victimisation. It is followed by a protracted debate over its positive and negative impacts. In my opinion, it is a reflection of the inflated fear of crime, but not of actual levels of crime.\n\nTo a larger or lesser extent, the increased presence of anti-crime devices fuels the fear of crime and has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a devastating effect on</strong> people’s quality of life. Crimes are concentrated in particular areas, but the fear of crime spreads across the whole community and affects nearly every resident. The most annoying aspect of this trend is that people’s freedom is curtailed (for example, using the stairway of a building less frequently due to the alarm installed there) and sometimes, people’s privacy is invaded (due to the concealed surveillance cameras in offices). There is little, if any, evidence that the threat people perceive has a real life counterpart.\n\nOn the other hand, although some measures are said to deter or stop crime, they too often produce opposite outcomes. For example, lighting in a dark area may reduce fear but also enable criminals to see their targets more easily, leading to a high probability of attacks. The benefits of self-protective measures such as gun ownership and martial arts training are doubtful because nobody can say with certainty that the net effect is to decrease harm. Most personal defensive devices are either too difficult to use or less effective than expected.\n\nCrime reduction and crime prevention also rely on other approaches rather than on security measures. Criminals choose their targets based on time and whereabouts. Citizens will be less vulnerable to victimisation if they bypass those places where crimes frequently occur. There is no need. for carrying chemical agents for self-defense. Many mansions are armed with expensive indoor surveillance systems, but issuing passes to occupants and tenants and preventing easy access to the building is more effective and economical. In the inner city, where crimes are epidemic, eliminating the dilapidated buildings used by criminals for hiding or selecting a target is more useful than requiring all shops and residents nearby to install expensive security system. The central part of crime prevention is altering the environment, by which the root causes or at least the facilitators of crime can be eliminated.\n\nAs suggested above, it is difficult to measure the effectiveness of anti-crime equipment and users should examine it regularly, The crime prevention framework should focus on making the environment safe from crime, reducing the potential for crime in high-risk situations and halting the possibility of future crime.","phrases":[{"en":"a devastating effect on","vi":"tác động tàn phá đối với"}],"subtype":"Problems / Solutions","_displayNo":"#028","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"There are more and more effective security measures in large cities to…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-029","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture: Technology","prompt":"It is inevitable that traditional cultures will be lost as technology develops. Technology and traditional cultures are incompatible. To what extent do you agree or disagree with this view?","answer":"Some people believe that technological developments lead to the loss of traditional cultures. I partly agree with this assertion; while it may be true in the case of some societies, others seem to be unaffected by technology and the modern world.\n\nOn the one hand, the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">advances in technology</strong> that have driven industrialisation in developed countries have certainly contributed to the disappearance of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">traditional ways of life</strong>. For example, in pre-industrial Britain, generations of families grew up in the same small village communities. These communities had a strong sense of identity, due to their shared customs and beliefs. However, developments in transport, communications and manufacturing led to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the dispersal of families</strong> and village communities as people moved to the cities in search of work. Nowadays most British villages are inhabited by commuters, many of whom do not know their closest neighbours.\n\nOn the other hand, in some parts of the world traditional cultures still thrive. There are tribes in the Amazon Rainforest, for example, that have been completely untouched by the technological developments of the developed world. These tribal communities continue to hunt and gather food from the forest, and traditional skills are passed on to children by parents and elders. Other traditional cultures, such as farming communities in parts of Africa, are embracing communications technologies. Mobile phones give farmers <strong class=\"key-phrase\">access to information</strong>, from weather predictions to market prices, which helps them to prosper and therefore supports their culture.\n\nIn conclusion, many traditional ways of life have been lost as a result of advances in technology, but other traditional communities have survived and even flourished.","phrases":[{"en":"advances in technology","vi":"những tiến bộ công nghệ"},{"en":"traditional ways of life","vi":"lối sống truyền thống"},{"en":"the dispersal of families","vi":"sự phân tán của các gia đình"},{"en":"access to information","vi":"khả năng tiếp cận thông tin"}],"subtype":"Agree / Disagree · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#029","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Technology and traditional cultures","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-030","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture: Work","prompt":"’We should introduce laws to make businesses and state services employ equal numbers of male and female workers in every department or area of the company.’ How far do you support this idea? Give reasons for your answer, and support your essay with ideas and examples from your own experience. You should write at least 250 words.","answer":"The issue of equality for men and women at work is still widely debated, despite the extensive legislation that now exists in many countries. Personally, I do not feel that imposing a numerical target for gender is a sensible idea, and I will explain why. Firstly, we have to consider whether equal numbers of men and women really wish to do every job which is available. For example, few women wish to be airline pilots, and only a minority of school teachers are male. If we impose a law on airlines or schools, where will they find the people to fill these posts willingly? Furthermore, there is the huge issue of the existing workforce. Would it be right to dismiss a worker because he or she is of a certain gender, in order to create a statistically perfect balance? The effects would be disastrous for many hard-working people. Finally, I believe we should find ways to encourage equality of opportunity through support and guidance, rather than top-down legislation. For instance, improved child care facilities and subsidies would probably encourage more women into parts of the workforce which may currently be difficult to enter. I do understand the opposing view, which is that legislation is the quickest and most effective way to achieve gender equality. Nevertheless, I feel that the disruptive effects of ’overnight’ legislation would destabilise society and hinder many people’s prospects. Overall, I believe that equality is an excellent goal for society to strive for. Above all, though, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">I think that</strong> this needs to be a gradual process, based on careful support rather than sudden legislation.","phrases":[{"en":"I think that","vi":"tôi cho rằng"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#030","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"‘We should introduce laws to make businesses and state services employ…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-031","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture","prompt":"The advantages of the spread of English as a global language will continue\nto outweigh its disadvantages. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"In these years, there is a growing recognition that English is well on its way to, becoming the dominant global language. The impact of this trend is a subject of intense debate. It is my opinion that advantages of a dominant global language will continue to outweigh its disadvantages. The rise of a global language is a facilitator of cross-cultural communication and the communication between people with different language backgrounds. In different areas of global communication, such as science and news, recognising a common language removes communication barriers and increases convenience. On many formal occasions, English, as a working language, boosts efficiency and avoids misunderstanding. Likewise, the exchange of essential information like know-how and technologies will be tremendously promoted. One might argue that the rise of a global language would endanger other languages, in a belief that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an increasing number of</strong> people have turned to English as their first language. This viewpoint is flawed. The spread of global English has little, if any, influence on non-English-speakers’ <strong class=\"key-phrase\">language proficiency</strong>. People might be motivated to learn English as a foreign language but do not necessarily drop their native language because learning beginner or intermediate level English is sufficient for day-to-day communication. The dominance of English as a global language is, therefore, not a cause of the loss of language diversity. Its negative effect is reflected mainly in cultural imperialism. As international media recognises English as its root language, most of the broadcast information is related to the lifestyle, norms and beliefs of English-speaking countries. It might over time put many minority cultures <strong class=\"key-phrase\">on the verge of extinction</strong>, when those ethnic groups gradually adopt the Western culture. The effects of shrinking <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cultural diversity</strong> are destructive, causing people to live in a simple and monotonous world and think and act in similar ways. The development of English is overall, a positive global trend. It connects people who previously spoke different languages and enables them to exchange ideas, although it might lead to the loss of cultural diversity.","phrases":[{"en":"an increasing number of","vi":"số lượng ngày càng tăng"},{"en":"language proficiency","vi":"năng lực ngôn ngữ"},{"en":"on the verge of extinction","vi":"bên bờ tuyệt chủng"},{"en":"cultural diversity","vi":"sự đa dạng văn hóa"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#031","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Advantages of the spread of English as a global language will continue to…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-032","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture: Job satisfaction","prompt":"As most people spend a major part of adult life at the place of work, job satisfaction is an important part of individual well-being. What are the factors that contribute to job satisfaction? Are all the expectations for job satisfaction realistic?","answer":"Job satisfaction matters because adults spend a large part of their lives at work. It depends on several practical and psychological factors, but it is unrealistic to expect any job to provide constant happiness.\n\nAt the most basic level, employees need <strong class=\"key-phrase\">fair pay and reasonable job security</strong>. A salary should cover normal living costs, and workers should not feel that their position could disappear without warning. Working conditions also matter: manageable hours, respectful treatment and competent leadership can have a direct effect on morale. Beyond these basic needs, many people want <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sense of purpose</strong>. They are more satisfied when they understand how their work contributes to a useful result and when their effort is recognised.\n\nAnother important factor is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">scope for professional growth</strong>. Employees are likely to remain motivated if they can learn new skills, take on greater responsibility and see a clear route to promotion. Relationships with colleagues are equally significant because a supportive team can make demanding work more enjoyable. In contrast, poor communication or persistent conflict can make even a well-paid job difficult to tolerate.\n\nNevertheless, some expectations are unrealistic. No occupation can be interesting every day, and every workplace includes routine tasks, pressure and occasional disagreement. It is also unreasonable to expect an employer to provide personal fulfilment in every area of life. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">A healthy work-life balance</strong> usually depends on choices outside work as well as conditions inside it.\n\nIn conclusion, job satisfaction is built on fair treatment, meaningful work, development and supportive relationships. These are reasonable expectations, but employees should also accept that work will never be free from boredom or stress.","phrases":[{"en":"fair pay and reasonable job security","vi":"mức lương công bằng và sự ổn định việc làm hợp lý"},{"en":"a sense of purpose","vi":"cảm giác công việc có ý nghĩa"},{"en":"scope for professional growth","vi":"cơ hội phát triển nghề nghiệp"},{"en":"a healthy work-life balance","vi":"sự cân bằng lành mạnh giữa công việc và cuộc sống"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#032","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"As most people spend a major part of adult life at the place of work, job…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-033","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture: Music","prompt":"Creative artists should be given freedom to express their ideas through words, pictures, music or films. Some people nevertheless think that the government should restrict artists’ freedom of expression. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Artists need freedom to explore difficult ideas, and governments should not control art simply because it is unpopular or uncomfortable. However, I do not believe that artistic freedom should be completely unlimited. Restrictions are justified when a work clearly encourages violence, hatred or serious harm.\n\nThe strongest argument for freedom is that art helps society examine ideas that ordinary public debate may avoid. A film, novel or painting can question accepted beliefs, expose injustice and give a voice to people who are rarely heard. If artists fear punishment whenever they challenge authority, creative work becomes safe but shallow. Society then loses an important source of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">critical reflection</strong> and cultural progress.\n\nNevertheless, freedom of expression does not remove responsibility. A work that directly incites violence against a group, deliberately exploits children or presents criminal behaviour as an instruction manual can cause real harm. In such cases, a narrow legal limit is reasonable. The key is that restrictions should be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">clearly defined and independently reviewed</strong>. Governments should not ban work merely because it criticises politicians, religion or social customs.\n\nIn practice, many disputes can be handled without banning a work. Age classifications, content warnings and restricted exhibition spaces allow adults to make informed choices while protecting children. This is usually preferable to censorship because it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">responds to risk in a proportionate way</strong> and leaves room for serious discussion of controversial ideas.\n\nIn conclusion, artists should enjoy broad freedom because challenging art is valuable to an open society. Yet this freedom should stop where there is a clear and serious risk of harm. A system based on precise laws and independent courts would <strong class=\"key-phrase\">protect creative freedom</strong> without ignoring public safety.","phrases":[{"en":"critical reflection","vi":"sự suy ngẫm có tính phản biện"},{"en":"clearly defined and independently reviewed","vi":"được quy định rõ ràng và xem xét độc lập"},{"en":"responds to risk in a proportionate way","vi":"ứng phó với rủi ro theo cách tương xứng"},{"en":"protect creative freedom","vi":"bảo vệ tự do sáng tạo"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#033","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Creative artists should be given freedom to express their ideas through…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-034","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture: Sport","prompt":"Discuss the advantages and disadvantages of playing sports and participating in physical exercises.","answer":"Sport and recreational physical activity is an integral part of the society. Especially in today’s society, where people have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a growing concern</strong> about health, participation in recreational physical activity has been strongly promoted as part of a healthy lifestyle. What will be discussed below are the benefits of physical exercise, and some issues participants should pay attention to when increasing the level of physical activity.\n\nOne of the main benefits associated with regular exercise is the development of a healthy lifestyle. There is evidence that people can enjoy a longer life expectancy by adapting their daily lives to incorporate physical activity. There are many reasons for this. For example, sports perform a wide range of life-enhancing functions, such as boosting the immune system, burning fat, reducing the risk of experiencing major illnesses (e. g., heart disease, diabetes). In a society where physical inactivity, unbalanced diet, stress and other problems are becoming increasingly serious, playing sports has significant implications for the well-being of the general population.\n\nAnother major benefit achieved from regular activity is the enhancement of social life. Combined with a balanced diet, sports, such as jogging, cycling or swimming, enable people to maintain a healthy weight, keep in shape, thereby boosting confidence on social occasions. In addition, sports and regular physical activities provide opportunities for social interactions. For example, team sports, such as soccer, rugby and basketball, allow participants to meet new teammates regularly and improve social life.\n\nWhen physical exercise is highly recommended, it should be planned and managed well. Excessive physical exercise, for example, puts participants at risk of injury. It is commonplace and hazardous that some people take up long duration and high intensity exercise despite lacking sufficient stamina. Although these potential risks are not to negate the benefits of physical activity, participants should take precautions and follow the instructions of sports professionals, trainers and coaches. In general, participants are advised to start gently and then increase the frequency of the activity until they can stick to it as an everyday routine.\n\nOverall, there are many benefits to be gained from regular exercise, such as promoting health, preventing illness and boosting self-esteem. Sports and recreational injuries are nevertheless a common problem, which deserves people’s attention. These injuries can be avoided by increasing activity gradually to a desired level, instead of starting from intense training.","phrases":[{"en":"a growing concern","vi":"mối lo ngại ngày càng tăng"}],"subtype":"Advantages / Disadvantages","_displayNo":"#034","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Discuss the advantages and disadvantages of playing sports and…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-035","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture","prompt":"Do you think a museum is to educate or entertain people?","answer":"Museums have long been known as centres of research and education. By acquiring, conserving, researching and exhibiting a great variety of tangible items (such as artefacts and specimens), museums are of great educational value. However, this notion has been refuted by some people in recent years, who tend to think that museums are intended for entertainment as well. In my opinion, a museum can serve dual purposes, although education tends to play a larger part.\n\nMuseums impart knowledge to visitors through different means. One is collecting and displaying objects of scientific, artistic or historical importance at a specific site. Staff members working for museums are trained to provide interpretations of the collected objects to the general public. Viewing these items enables visitors to acquire knowledge of a given subject, such as history, art, environment and technology. History museums are for example concerned with specialised aspects of history at the local or national level. Another approach taken by a museum is to invite specialists to lecture regularly in different fields, which is instructive as well. An entertainment business, by comparison hardly serves an educational purpose.\n\nIn addition to the way it operates, a museum is distinct from any operator in the entertainment industry in some other aspects. First of all, museums are entirely not-for-profit. Although sometimes charging an admission fee, a museum very often has free entrance, and does not engage in any profit-making activity, It does not target any specific audience like an entertainment business does. Instead, it is open to the general public. Museums, meanwhile, choose items on display not according to their commercial values but according to the line of items they mainly focus on. For instance, a history museum would focus only on those items that are of historical value, although those items might not have sufficient market value.\n\nHowever, a noteworthy development of museums in recent years is related to entertainment <strong class=\"key-phrase\">to some extent</strong>. Similar to other educational institutions, museums have to balance their budget. Many museums have therefore sought to operate more activities to attract more visitors, in order for an additional entry fee to cover costs. In addition to the traditional services, such as making collected objects available for public viewing, and organising lectures, a museum is interested in such entertainments as films, musical or dance performances, most of which are linked to the culture of its host region. Art museums, for example, bear a close resemblance to art galleries, in exhibiting a wide range of artworks. Museums falling in this category give visitors pleasure, and can be taken as a provider of both knowledge and entertainment.\n\nAs suggested above, there are many benchmarks against which a museum can be made distinct from an entertainment provider. Some museums are now providing services in overtly entertainment nature, although educational for the most part.","phrases":[{"en":"to some extent","vi":"ở một mức độ nào đó"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#035","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Do you think a museum is to educate or entertain people?","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-036","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture","prompt":"Increasing travels between countries enable people to learn different cultures or to increase tension between people from different countries?","answer":"Globalisation is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a catch-all term</strong> that refers to any activity that involves more than one country, for example, travel from one country to another. The dramatic increase in transnational travel in recent years has sparked controversy over the potential impacts of this trend on individual countries, especially those new member states of globalisation. Some people are concerned that the upsurge in new arrivals will prompt local hostility against visitors. instead of promoting their understanding on mutual cultural background. This notion should be rejected as one can see many facts in favour of this development between countries.\n\nThe first reason why international travels would never bring conflict is rooted in the fact that both visitors and locals are economically motivated. International travel opens up opportunities for business development throughout the world. Entrepreneurs are interested not only in the domestic market but also in the oversea market. Foreigners should learn the culture of a country before winning over the local people. In turn, locals should show their hospitality to visitors in exchange for their trust. They share a view that acceptance of each other’s cultural background is a necessary condition for cooperation.\n\nUnderstanding a culture has other implications, Differences in social background, cultural values and religious belief might make the discrepancy of foreigners and local inhabitants on some issues indelible; however, the higher interaction, the higher level of communication and understanding. Arabians, for example, used to consider westerners as their foes. Now they have concrete relations with their western allies in many fields. In the initial stage, their divergence seemed inherent but over time, with better <strong class=\"key-phrase\">mutual understanding</strong>, they take the same position on many issues.\n\nUndeniably, it is likely that in some resorts, foreign visitors repel the local community with their scant regard for the local environment and conventions when they first arrive. However, it should be noted that most offense is accidental, rather than intentional. Instead, visitors disobey rules and conventions simply because they have no knowledge of them. This situation <strong class=\"key-phrase\">is expected to</strong> be improved with the passing of time when visitors from different countries increase their knowledge of a local culture.\n\nAccording to the above analysis, we can observe that the increase in the international travel should not be taken as the cause of any conflict that arises between two countries. Alternatively, one should recognise its role in improving mutual understanding between two countries.","phrases":[{"en":"a catch-all term","vi":"một thuật ngữ bao quát"},{"en":"mutual understanding","vi":"sự thấu hiểu lẫn nhau"},{"en":"is expected to","vi":"được dự đoán"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#036","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Increasing travels between countries enable people to learn different…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-037","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture: Work","prompt":"It is more important for a building to serve its purposes than to look beautiful. Architects do not need to worry about whether it is a real work of art. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"A building must first be safe and useful, but this does not mean that appearance is unimportant. I disagree with the idea that architects should ignore beauty. Good architecture combines function, cost and visual quality rather than treating them as separate goals.\n\nPractical requirements are clearly essential. A hospital needs efficient routes for patients and staff, a school needs suitable classrooms, and housing must be safe, affordable and easy to maintain. A beautiful design that creates dark rooms, poor access or excessive construction costs has failed its users. Architects must therefore begin with the needs of the people who use the building.\n\nNevertheless, appearance also affects daily life. Well-designed streets and public buildings can make people feel proud of their neighbourhood and encourage them to care for shared spaces. Natural light, balanced proportions and appropriate materials may also improve comfort without adding unreasonable cost. In addition, distinctive buildings can strengthen a city’s identity and attract visitors or investment. Beauty is not merely decoration when it contributes to wellbeing and a sense of place.\n\nThe best results come from integrating both aims from the start. Simple, durable materials can be attractive, and an efficient layout can still have character. In conclusion, function should have priority where safety or affordability is at stake, but architects should also seek <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a practical balance between usefulness and beauty</strong>. A building serves society best when it works well and improves its surroundings.\n\nFor this reason, design competitions and planning rules should reward buildings that remain useful for decades, use resources efficiently and contribute positively to the public realm. Such standards show that visual quality can be achieved without sacrificing affordability or function.","phrases":[{"en":"a practical balance between usefulness and beauty","vi":"sự cân bằng thiết thực giữa công năng và vẻ đẹp"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#037","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"It is more important for a building to serve its purposes than to look…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-038","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture: Money","prompt":"Millions of dollars are spent on space research every year. Some people argue that the money should be spent on improving living standards on Earth. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Space research requires enormous public investment, while many people still lack adequate housing, healthcare and education. Although these social needs deserve priority, I do not agree that governments should abandon space programmes. A limited and carefully directed budget can produce <strong class=\"key-phrase\">direct practical benefits</strong> on Earth and support valuable long-term research.\n\nThe strongest argument against space spending is opportunity cost. Money used for a distant mission cannot be spent on hospitals, schools or clean water. In poorer countries, these services can save lives immediately, whereas the benefits of space exploration may seem uncertain or remote. Governments should therefore avoid prestige projects that consume large sums without a clear scientific or public purpose.\n\nHowever, space research is not simply an expensive adventure. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">Satellite technology</strong> supports weather forecasting, navigation, communications and disaster management. It helps farmers monitor crops, allows emergency services to track storms and gives scientists reliable evidence about climate change. Research carried out for space missions has also contributed to advances in materials, computing and medicine. These benefits are shared far beyond the space industry.\n\nSpace science is also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a long-term investment</strong>. Knowledge about the Earth, the solar system and possible environmental threats cannot be developed quickly when a crisis appears. Maintaining expertise and international cooperation now may be crucial in the future. Nevertheless, funding should be transparent, evaluated independently and balanced against <strong class=\"key-phrase\">pressing social needs</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, basic living standards should receive the largest share of public money, but this does not make space research wasteful. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">A balanced funding model</strong> can meet urgent needs while preserving a programme that delivers practical technology and scientific knowledge.","phrases":[{"en":"direct practical benefits","vi":"những lợi ích thực tiễn trực tiếp"},{"en":"satellite technology","vi":"công nghệ vệ tinh"},{"en":"a long-term investment","vi":"một khoản đầu tư dài hạn"},{"en":"pressing social needs","vi":"những nhu cầu xã hội cấp thiết"},{"en":"a balanced funding model","vi":"mô hình phân bổ ngân sách cân bằng"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#038","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Millions of dollars are spent on space research every year.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-039","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture","prompt":"Some people argue that immigrants should adopt the local culture when they move to a new country. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Moving to another country requires immigrants to understand local customs, but it should not require them to abandon their own culture. I partly agree that newcomers need to adapt. They should respect the law and learn the language, while remaining free to preserve harmless traditions and community ties.\n\nAdaptation is essential for practical reasons. A person who can communicate in the local language is more likely to find work, use public services and build relationships outside an immigrant community. Understanding everyday conventions also prevents avoidable conflict. For example, expectations about punctuality, personal space or workplace communication may differ greatly between countries. Learning these norms helps newcomers <strong class=\"key-phrase\">participate fully in public life</strong>.\n\nHowever, integration is not the same as cultural surrender. Family traditions, food, music and religious practice can give immigrants stability during a difficult transition. Minority organisations may also provide language support, childcare and advice for new arrivals. These communities become harmful only when they isolate members from the wider society or reject basic legal principles. In most cases, they can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">preserve identity while supporting integration</strong>.\n\nThe host country has responsibilities as well. Schools, employers and public institutions should make participation possible and respond firmly to discrimination. Integration works best when newcomers are expected to contribute but are not treated as inferior for having a different background.\n\nIn conclusion, immigrants should adopt the language, laws and civic expectations of their new country. They should not be required to erase their heritage. A successful multicultural society creates a shared public culture with room for private difference.","phrases":[{"en":"participate fully in public life","vi":"tham gia đầy đủ vào đời sống công cộng"},{"en":"preserve identity while supporting integration","vi":"giữ gìn bản sắc đồng thời hỗ trợ hội nhập"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#039","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People argue that immigrants should adopt the local culture when","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-040","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture","prompt":"Some people argue that learning a second language involves learning the culture of the country where this language is spoken (including lifestyles). What is your opinion?","answer":"To most people, second language acquisition is a lengthy and exhausting process. A general approach taken by most learners is to learn vocabulary and memorise grammar rules. They contend that language speaks for itself and the meaning of language lies in the language itself. In my opinion, a language <strong class=\"key-phrase\">goes beyond its literal meaning</strong> and delivers different messages as situations change. The cultural context and background of a language <strong class=\"key-phrase\">have a bearing on</strong> the forming of a language. There is no distinction between acquiring a language and acquiring a culture.\n\nThe first reason to support the above contention is that culture influences the evolution and formation of a language. Learning a culture can help learners understand many aspects of a language, wording, syntax, and so forth. For example, word order, the order in which words appear in sentences, differs from language to language. In some languages, the object normally comes ahead of the subject, as opposed to the word order in the English language. It mirrors the disparity in ways of seeing things and ways of thinking between people who speak different languages. Learning a culture can draw the attention of learners to these differences and therefore lead them to use a foreign language appropriately.\n\nFamiliarity with a culture is also known as <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the prerequisite of communication</strong> with native speakers. Effective communication relies not only on wording, pronunciation and sentence construction but also on physical gesture, body language and facial expressions. In fact, non-verbal messages sometimes tell people more than verbal messages do. For example, silence in the English-speaking country might indicate the agreement of the speaker on something, but in some Asian countries, silence might convey a message to the contrary, disagreement or even resentment. It is clear that by learning the cultural dimensions of a language, a language learner can make him-or-herself acquainted with the skills and habits involved in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cross-cultural communication</strong>,\n\nAlthough the importance of studying the cultural aspect of language is indisputable, it should not be over-emphasised. For most learners, especially for those at an elementary level, the cultural elements of a language are remote and incomprehensible. Intrusion of these messages will create confusion. Learners will flounder when the progress toward success is little and the situation appears to be unmanageable. Language acquisition requires a high commitment of time and effort, so new learners are advised to concentrate on the language itself at the first stage.\n\nFrom what has been discussed, one can make it clear that culture is an element that determines the difference between languages. Failing to recognise this would impede language learning, However, for new learners, acquiring a culture is less practical, for it requires great effort and produces little outcome.","phrases":[{"en":"goes beyond its literal meaning","vi":"vượt ra ngoài nghĩa đen"},{"en":"have a bearing on","vi":"có ảnh hưởng đến"},{"en":"the prerequisite of communication","vi":"điều kiện tiên quyết của giao tiếp"},{"en":"cross-cultural communication","vi":"giao tiếp liên văn hóa"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#040","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People argue that learning a second language involves learning the culture…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-041","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture: Money","prompt":"Some people argue that the government should spend money on public services and facilities, but not on the arts. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"The role of arts in modern life is unique, providing people with entertainment and yielding various psychological rewards, such as relief from stress. Despite these benefits, the arts have been taken as luxury goods in many cases. It is suggested that public money of a city should be concentrated in projects like public facilities, which are more likely to bring immediate benefits to the public, rather than the arts. There are a number of facts indicating that this position is right.\n\nPublic facilities, widely accepted as one of the main precursors to a city’s development, should be one of the highest priorities. Those underdeveloped cities in particular, should direct sufficient funding toward public facilities. While municipal office buildings, courthouses and post offices are essential components of public services, libraries, hospitals, parks, playing fields, gymnasiums and swimming pools are available to the public for social, educational, athletic and cultural activities. By boosting spending on public facilities, cities are more capable to satisfy the needs of citizens and improve their standard of living.\n\nIn addition to social benefits, there are economic merits that public facilities can offer to communities. An integrated transport network (maritime, land and inland waterways transport and civil aviation), for example, promises the smooth and speedy movement of goods and people in a city. Industrial products, as well as agricultural produce of a city, can be delivered to other cities in exchange for steady income. Of equal importance are public Internet facilities. Providing <strong class=\"key-phrase\">access to information</strong> by improving Internet and other telecommunications facilities has relevance to the ease with which businesses in a city receive, process, use and send information. It is no exaggeration to say that entrepreneurs, either from home or abroad, will first examine the infrastructure of a city before deciding whether to pursue business opportunities there.\n\nThe arts, by comparison, although enabling people to see the world and the human condition differently and to see a truth one might ignore before, do not merit government spending. The first reason is that the arts—referring to music, film and literature altogether—are more likely to attract the investment of the private sector than public facilities. Businesspeople continue to invest in the arts in the expectation of earning lump sum income and the arts in return, continue to flourish without the government spending. Meanwhile, the arts are a key component of a culture and naturally passed down a from one generation to another. Unlike public facilities, they require no money to survive.\n\nIt is therefore clear that construction of public facilities should be given the foremost consideration. The concern about the well-being of individual citizens and that of a city is more acute than the apprehension about the survival and prospects of the arts, something that businesses have a stake in.","phrases":[{"en":"access to information","vi":"khả năng tiếp cận thông tin"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#041","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People argue that the government should spend money on public services and…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-042","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture: Tourism","prompt":"Some people believe that culture will be ruined if it is used to earn tourism revenue, but others consider that tourism is the only way of protecting a culture. Discuss both sides and give your own opinion.","answer":"There is little room for doubt that tourism is one of the fastest-growing industries in the world. However, its impact on culture remains <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a source of constant debate</strong>. This essay will elaborate on both positive and negative effects of tourism from a cultural perspective.\n\nProviding economic incentives for cultural preservation is unarguably one of the main contributions of tourism. To many tourists, culture and history are what they first consider when choosing a destination. Their mindset has been recognised by many tourism sites and money has been subsequently directed toward cultural protection, including the maintenance of key historical sites. Tourism is therefore one of the primary forces contributing to the preservation of a culture.\n\nIn addition to raising financing, tourism can make an indigenous culture known to the world and rally support worldwide to protect it. When a historic site or a site that shows a country’s cultural heritage is made accessible to the public, visitors from all over the world will soon flock there. They will share their experience in the local culture with their friends and families once they return home, assisting this site to gain international fame. Both financial and technological support will flood in for the conservation of natural and cultural resources.\n\nOn the negative side, tourism develops sometimes <strong class=\"key-phrase\">at the expense of</strong> part of culture. Food, festivals, costumes and other stimulating elements of a culture are highlighted to entertain tourists, constituting an insult to the locals and causing damage to the unique nature of a culture. Moreover, cultural commercialisation has made the sacred elements of a culture commonplace and tourists are encouraged to attach little importance to a unique tradition, which cannot be found elsewhere.\n\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">In the light of</strong> these facts, one can conclude that tourism is neither a boon nor a bane to cultural preservation. While its endeavour to protect an indigenous culture should be recognised, it has put the integrity of a culture at risk.","phrases":[{"en":"a source of constant debate","vi":"nguồn tranh luận không ngừng"},{"en":"at the expense of","vi":"đánh đổi bằng / gây tổn hại đến"},{"en":"In the light of","vi":"xét theo / căn cứ vào"}],"subtype":"Discussion","_displayNo":"#042","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People believe that culture will be ruined if it is used to earn tourism…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-043","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture","prompt":"Some people believe that new buildings should be built in traditional styles. To what extent do you agree or disagree with this opinion?","answer":"Architecture is an integral part of every single culture. Accordingly some people suggest that new buildings should be constructed with a classical style, in an effort to protect a nation’s <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cultural identity</strong>. I agree with their recommendation that maintaining a nation’s cultural identity is a priority.\n\nNew constructions might not only cause direct damage to those existing aged buildings, which are central to a nation’s culture, but also destroy the integrity of the cityscape, which characterises a country. Over the past decades, there has been a growing recognition that architecture is an element that distinguishes one culture from another. That’s why people are not surprised to see that buildings differ in styles from country to country. New constructions, if not aligned with the existing buildings, will impair the uniqueness of an architecture style, which has been widely recognised, studied and treasured by the world\n\nAnother main justification for upholding a traditional building style is that it contributes to the diversity of building models in a country. By preserving classical architecture, some regions are marked by the mingling of buildings of different ages and types. Many cities in Europe can be cited as examples, where buildings in a traditional or ancient format coexist with modernised buildings, performing different functions and serving dissimilar purposes. It bridges the past and the present history, and reminds people of the heritage of a country. It creates a modern identity of a region or country as well.\n\nDespite the role of old architecture works in retaining cultural heritage, not all the buildings should be necessarily designed and constructed in a traditional pattern, On the one hand, it is af odds ’with diversity. It comes as no surprise that ceaseless pursuit of a classical style will result in the sameness of buildings in a country. On the other, traditional building models require specific craftsmanship and building materials, which are neither affordable nor accessible to every developer, so they cannot be applied on a large scale.\n\nFrom the points enlisted above, it seems obvious that architecture is an approach of preserving a nation’s cultural heritage, so new construction should be undertaken to adhere to a traditional style. Although it might not be reflected in all buildings, it does play a great part in maintaining and reinforcing cultural identity of a region or country.","phrases":[{"en":"cultural identity","vi":"bản sắc văn hóa"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#043","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People believe that new buildings should be built in traditional styles.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-044","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture","prompt":"People in many countries do not wear their traditional costume. Some argue that they would forget their history and tradition. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Traditional costume, both national and regional, is universally recognised as <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an integral element of</strong> every single culture. Despite its importance to a culture and ethnicity, it is now less frequently worn by people, at a time when Western formal and informal clothes are rife. Below are a number of facts that suggest the role of traditional costumes in protecting ethnicity and identity.\n\nWearing traditional costumes, first of all, reminds people of many distinct characteristics of their culture. How people perceive their traditional costume shows the extent to which they are willing to respect and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">retain their cultural heritage</strong>. In Vietnam, for instance, female office workers are generally required to wear Ao Dai, a traditional dress, as a custom being <strong class=\"key-phrase\">handed down from generation to generation</strong>. It is a national symbol, giving millions of Vietnamese <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sense of ethnic identity</strong>, wherever they are. Besides, it represents cultural values of Vietnam and shows the perceived position of females in a Vietnamese society. Despite the success of Ao Dai, it is a rare example in today’s world, where most of the traditional costumes have been marginalised by Western-style business suits. People see national costume only in theatre, film and TV.\n\nAnother point to support the importance of traditional costume is their presence in many social settings. Traditional costumes are required on many occasions, either formal or informal. Generally, they come in two forms: one for everyday occasions, the other for festivals and formal wear. Both have cultural meanings. For example, in many societies, a considerable number of traditional costumes evolved specifically for the wedding ceremony, and the wedding couple, as well as guests, are expected to wear traditional clothes, a symbol of eternity and solemnity. Traditional dresses in most cases differ in styles and vary according to circumstances. For example, in China, ceremonial clothing tends to be dark while lighter-coloured clothing is worn mainly by the common people for everyday life and around the house use. As the culture is very often reflected in the way of life of a society, the role of traditional costumes in a culture is undisputed.\n\nTraditional costumes are therefore, worthy of people’s concern and should be preserved; however, it does not necessarily mean that one should wear traditional costumes all the time. People wear clothing in general for functional reasons. Traditional costumes are of cultural and social importance but might not suit every circumstance. For example, exercise clothes are needed when people participate in physical exercise and play sports. Western-style suits are used more broadly on formal occasions where people of different cultural backgrounds gather for serious issues, such as business. Dressing in a standard manner is a demonstration of respect, the key to mutual trust.\n\nOverall, the costume, as a distinctive style of dress of a particular people in a particular country, should be distinguished from the wardrobes people are wearing every day in ordinary settings. Failing to maintain the unique characteristics of traditional costume of a country will surely cause destruction on the integrity of a culture.","phrases":[{"en":"an integral element of","vi":"một yếu tố không thể tách rời của"},{"en":"retain their cultural heritage","vi":"gìn giữ di sản văn hóa"},{"en":"handed down from generation to generation","vi":"được truyền từ thế hệ này sang thế hệ khác"},{"en":"a sense of ethnic identity","vi":"ý thức về bản sắc dân tộc"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#044","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People in many countries do not wear their traditional costume.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-045","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture","prompt":"People think that the news media has influenced people's lives nowadays and it is a negative development. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"For many people, news is a regular part of life. An issue in dispute is whether the massive influence of the news media on people’s daily lives denotes a negative development. I believe that news media does more good than harm to the society.\n\nThe news media provides people with much of the information they need on a timely basis, although there are claims that it reports on issues and events purposely (only selecting those events that interest the audience). Anecdotal evidence shows that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">people from all walks of life</strong> have the habit of collecting information regularly from the news media, including print, broadcast and Internet-based media. Information assists people in decision making. For example, the Free Trade Agreement reached by the Chinese government and its New Zealand counterpart might open up many opportunities to both countries. For any business person, either in New Zealand or in China, failing to recognise and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">capitalise on this impending change</strong> would cause a costly loss.\n\nMeanwhile it should be recognised that the news media can sometimes save lives and reduce casualties. There is a lot of uncertainty about the surroundings, and people are susceptible to the damage caused by accidents, crimes and natural calamity. The news media <strong class=\"key-phrase\">conveys the firsthand information</strong> to concerned audiences and enable them to take corresponding actions right away. The authority can declare a state of emergency when it is necessary, organise evacuation and distribute aid to the needy areas, All these efforts count on the news media as the messenger.\n\nDespite their significant and ongoing contribution to the society, the news media might sometimes be harmful to society. It is a convention that the news media exaggerates the magnitude of the real threat (for example, the potential of a terrorism attack), to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">draw the attention of the desired audiences</strong> and in pursuit of high audience ratings. It ends up with causing panic among the population. Meanwhile, the news media tends to emphasise some issues or events, which virtually have little relevance to people’s daily lives, such as an occasional multiple vehicle accident, an affair that a celebrity is involved with, and the like. It <strong class=\"key-phrase\">distracts the audience from</strong> something that is much more noteworthy, for instance, poverty, environmental problems, to name but a few.\n\nIn summary, the role of news media as an information provider should be acknowledged. In case of emergency, it acts as a lifesaver. However, it is not to say that the news media can give people an overall view of the problems in society all the time.","phrases":[{"en":"people from all walks of life","vi":"mọi tầng lớp trong xã hội"},{"en":"capitalise on this impending change","vi":"tận dụng sự thay đổi sắp tới"},{"en":"conveys the firsthand information","vi":"truyền đạt thông tin trực tiếp từ nguồn"},{"en":"draw the attention of the desired audiences","vi":"thu hút sự chú ý của nhóm khán giả mục tiêu"},{"en":"distracts the audience from","vi":"làm khán giả xao nhãng khỏi"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#045","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People think that the news media has influenced people's lives nowadays and…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-046","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture","prompt":"There is a disagreement on the impact of increased business and culture contact between countries on a country’s identity. What is your opinion?","answer":"Closer business and cultural contact between countries can weaken certain traditions, but it does not inevitably destroy national identity. In my view, international contact can strengthen rather than erase national identity when governments and communities protect what is distinctive and allow culture to develop naturally.\n\nThe main risk is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cultural homogenisation</strong>. Global companies sell similar products in many countries, international media promote the same celebrities and younger people often adopt foreign fashions or expressions. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">Under commercial pressure</strong>, small local businesses, minority languages and traditional crafts may struggle to survive. If these trends continue without support, visible differences between societies can gradually become less pronounced.\n\nHowever, contact with other countries can also increase interest in local culture. Tourism creates demand for regional food, music, architecture and festivals. International audiences may give artists and small producers new markets, while digital platforms allow communities to document and share traditions that were previously known only locally. Exposure to other cultures can even make people more conscious of their own identity because comparison shows them what is distinctive about it.\n\nThe outcome therefore depends on policy and public choice. Schools can teach local history and language, governments can support cultural institutions, and planning rules can protect important buildings and neighbourhoods. At the same time, identity should not be treated as something fixed. Cultures have always borrowed ideas from one another, and selective change can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">keep traditions relevant to younger generations</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, international business and cultural exchange create some pressure towards uniformity, but they also provide resources and audiences for local culture. Countries can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">preserve distinctive traditions</strong> while <strong class=\"key-phrase\">engaging with the world on their own terms</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"cultural homogenisation","vi":"sự đồng nhất hóa văn hóa"},{"en":"under commercial pressure","vi":"dưới áp lực thương mại"},{"en":"keep traditions relevant to younger generations","vi":"giúp truyền thống vẫn phù hợp với thế hệ trẻ"},{"en":"preserve distinctive traditions","vi":"gìn giữ những truyền thống đặc trưng"},{"en":"engaging with the world on their own terms","vi":"hội nhập với thế giới theo cách chủ động của mình"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#046","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"There is a disagreement on the impact of increased business and culture…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-047","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture: Young people","prompt":"What are the benefits of requiring young people to serve the army? Does participation in community work qualify as an alternative?","answer":"Despite the fact that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">military conscription</strong> is voluntary in much of the world, it remains compulsory in some countries like South Korea. In peacetime, serving the army is more than simply protecting motherland from any potential military attack. An alternative view is that it can be deemed as a test of manhood and a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">rite of passage</strong> from boyhood into manhood. While military training has its merits, some alternatives, such as <strong class=\"key-phrase\">community service</strong>, can be taken into account.\n\nMilitary service allows young people to reap personal benefits and enhance their <strong class=\"key-phrase\">personal growth</strong>. First of all, trainees can raise their physical fitness and enjoy better health. They meanwhile develop a sense of team spirit and improve abilities to get along well with others. They learn to cope with problems independently and gain self-confidence. It also helps expand their social circle, a valuable, although intangible, asset when they return to civilian life. Servicemen have no difficulties in winning others’ respect and their experience is comparable to education, work experience or recommendations. They are very often perceived as efficient, organised and excellent time managers.\n\nDespite those benefits brought by military service, its mandatory nature is the nub of the argument. Many young people cannot cope with the high level of stress in the army. That's why community service is suggested as an alternative in most countries. As distinct from military service, which demands full engagement of conscripts, community service requires young volunteers to contribute part of their time, energy and skills only. Moreover, community service tends to render more direct assistance to participants in preparing for the workforce. By volunteering, young adults develop skills, gain work experience and explore career options. They can also acquire practical knowledge through service.\n\nIn view of the advantages and disadvantages of military service outlined above, one can conclude that military service is helpful only when it is voluntary. Mandatory military service does not fit all young people, whereas community service benefits every young person who wants to make a smooth transition from school to work.","phrases":[{"en":"military conscription","vi":"nghĩa vụ quân sự bắt buộc"},{"en":"rite of passage","vi":"nghi thức đánh dấu sự trưởng thành"},{"en":"community service","vi":"hoạt động phục vụ cộng đồng"},{"en":"personal growth","vi":"sự phát triển cá nhân"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#047","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"What are the benefits of requiring young people to serve the army?","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-048","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture: Fast food","prompt":"What is the difference between traditional food and fast food?","answer":"Fast food has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">come under fire</strong> over the past decade, following people’s growing concern on health. When people’s eating habits have shown a tendency to favour fast food, larger numbers of studies have been concentrated on its <strong class=\"key-phrase\">adverse impact</strong>. Below is an outline of some differences between fast food and traditional meals.\n\nFast food is distinguished from traditional food mainly by the selection of ingredients and cuisines. As distinct from a traditional meal, which has its emphasis on diversity and richness of flavour, taste and choice, fast food is well-known for its high levels of salt, fat and sugar and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">heavy reliance on meat</strong>, such as chicken and beef. When fast foods are processed and prepared for those time+minded eaters: who are eager to relieve hunger, traditional foods are diverse and varying. Fast foods might not vary significantly throughout a country, but traditional foods are diversified due to ethnic diversity. That's why fast foods are very often thought to have direct threats on local cuisines.\n\nAnother problem found in the regular consumption of fast food is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the high risk of obesity</strong>. A typical fast-food meal has a very high energy content, much higher than a traditional meal. In many outlets, the choice is so limited that it’s virtually impossible to select a combination of items with even a moderate energy density. Many popular fast-food menu items are unhealthy, so excessive consumption can lead to obesity. It is one of the main reasons why many fast-food chains have now incorporated healthier alternatives on their menus, e. g., salads and fresh fruit. McDonald’s is a telling example.\n\nMoreover, it is important to realise that a traditional meal has many of its cultural and social meanings. Although fast food is recognised for its convenience and saving people from the routine of home cooking, meanwhile it discourages people from preparing deliberate meals for their families and friends. People are thus less likely to spend time talking to each other. Having a traditional meal is of importance in many social situations, and can be taken as a unifying element in family life, bringing people together in times of trouble and in times of joy.\n\nAs suggested above, the fast food, although cheap and convenient, has its shortcomings and a diet high in fast foods can increase a person’s risk of gaining weight and other health problems. In terms of health, its impact on cuisine, community spirits and family solidarity, the real costs of convenient foods are shockingly high.","phrases":[{"en":"come under fire","vi":"bị chỉ trích mạnh mẽ"},{"en":"adverse impact","vi":"tác động bất lợi"},{"en":"heavy reliance on meat","vi":"sự phụ thuộc lớn vào thịt"},{"en":"the high risk of obesity","vi":"nguy cơ béo phì cao"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#048","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"What is the difference between traditional food and fast food?","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-049","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Culture","title":"Culture","prompt":"When international media (including movies, fashion shows, advertisements and other TV programmes) convey the same messages to the global audience, people argue that the expansion of international media has negative impacts on cultural diversity. What is your opinion?","answer":"International media gives people access to films, music and ideas from around the world. Although this can make popular culture more similar across countries, I do not think it must destroy cultural diversity. The outcome depends mainly on how local communities respond.\n\nThere is a genuine risk of cultural uniformity. Large media companies have the money to promote the same films, celebrities and consumer trends in many markets. Local artists may struggle to compete, and young audiences may start to see foreign lifestyles as more modern or attractive than their own. Over time, this can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">weaken local traditions</strong> and reduce demand for regional languages, music and crafts.\n\nHowever, international media can also widen cultural understanding. Streaming platforms allow small producers to reach audiences far beyond their home countries, while viewers can discover stories that were previously unavailable to them. Governments and schools can support this positive effect by funding local content, teaching cultural history and ensuring that national broadcasters include regional voices. In this way, societies can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">engage with global culture</strong> without abandoning their identity.\n\nCultural influence is also rarely one-way. Local musicians, filmmakers and designers often combine international techniques with regional stories, languages and styles. The result can be new forms of culture rather than simple imitation. Policies should therefore improve access to distribution and training so that local creators can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">compete on more equal terms</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, global media can place pressure on cultural diversity, but cultural loss is not inevitable. If countries invest in local creative industries and people remain interested in their own heritage, international media can become a channel for exchange rather than a force for uniformity. The aim should be to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">preserve local identity while remaining open</strong> to outside influence.","phrases":[{"en":"weaken local traditions","vi":"làm suy yếu truyền thống địa phương"},{"en":"engage with global culture","vi":"tiếp cận văn hóa toàn cầu"},{"en":"compete on more equal terms","vi":"cạnh tranh trong điều kiện bình đẳng hơn"},{"en":"preserve local identity while remaining open","vi":"giữ bản sắc địa phương nhưng vẫn cởi mở"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#049","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"When international media (including movies, fashion shows, advertisements…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-050","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education: Technology","prompt":"Some people think that all university students should study whatever they like. Others believe that they should only be allowed to study subjects that will be useful in the future, such as those related to science and technology. Discuss both these views and give your own opinion.","answer":"People have different views about how much choice students should have with regard to what they can study at university. While some argue that it would be better for students to be forced into certain key subject areas, I believe that everyone should be able to study the course of their choice.\n\nThere are various reasons why people believe that universities should only offer subjects that will be useful in the future. They may assert that university courses like medicine, engineering and information technology are more likely to be beneficial than certain art degrees. From a personal perspective, it can be argued that these courses <strong class=\"key-phrase\">provide more job opportunities</strong>, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">career progression</strong>, better salaries, and therefore <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an improved quality of life</strong> for students who take them. On the societal level, by forcing people to choose particular university subjects, governments can ensure that any knowledge and skill gaps in the economy are covered. Finally, a focus on technology in higher education could lead to new inventions, economic growth, and greater future prosperity.\n\nIn spite of these arguments, I believe that university students should be free to choose their <strong class=\"key-phrase\">preferred areas of study</strong>. In my opinion, society will benefit more if our students are passionate about what they are learning. Besides, nobody can really predict which areas of knowledge will be most useful to society in the future, and it may be that employers begin to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">value creative thinking skills</strong> above practical or technical skills. If this were the case, perhaps we would need more students of art, history and philosophy than of science or technology.\n\nIn conclusion, although it might seem sensible for universities to focus only on the most useful subjects, I personally prefer the current system in which people have the right to study whatever they like.","phrases":[{"en":"provide more job opportunities","vi":"mang lại nhiều cơ hội việc làm hơn"},{"en":"career progression","vi":"sự phát triển nghề nghiệp"},{"en":"an improved quality of life","vi":"chất lượng cuộc sống được cải thiện"},{"en":"preferred areas of study","vi":"ngành học ưa thích"},{"en":"value creative thinking skills","vi":"coi trọng kỹ năng tư duy sáng tạo"}],"subtype":"Discuss both views + opinion · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#050","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Freedom to choose university subjects","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-051","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"Universities should accept equal numbers of male and female students in every subject. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"In my opinion, men and women should have the same educational opportunities. However, I do not agree with the idea of accepting equal proportions of each gender in every university subject.\n\nHaving the same number of men and women on all degree courses is simply unrealistic. Student numbers on any course depend on the applications that the institution receives. If a university decided to fill courses with equal numbers of males and females, it would need enough <strong class=\"key-phrase\">applicants of each gender</strong>. In reality, many courses are more popular with one gender than the other, and it would not be practical to aim for equal proportions. For example, nursing courses tend to attract more female applicants, and it would be difficult to fill these courses if fifty per cent of the places needed to go to males.\n\nApart from the practical concerns expressed above, I also believe that it would be unfair to base <strong class=\"key-phrase\">admission to university courses</strong> on gender. Universities should continue to select the best candidates for each course according to their qualifications. In this way, both men and women <strong class=\"key-phrase\">have the same opportunities</strong>, and applicants know that they will be successful if they work hard to achieve good grades at school. If a female student is the best candidate for a place on a course, it is surely wrong to reject her in favour of a male student with lower grades or fewer qualifications.\n\nIn conclusion, the selection of university students should be based on merit, and it would be both impractical and unfair to change to a selection procedure based on gender.","phrases":[{"en":"applicants of each gender","vi":"ứng viên của mỗi giới"},{"en":"admission to university courses","vi":"việc tuyển sinh vào các khóa đại học"},{"en":"have the same opportunities","vi":"có cơ hội như nhau"}],"subtype":"Agree / Disagree · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#051","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Gender quotas in university admissions","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-052","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education: School homework","prompt":"Some people believe that school children should not be given homework by their teachers, whereas others argue that homework plays an important role in the education of children. Discuss both of these views and give your own opinion.","answer":"People’s opinions differ as to whether or not school children should be given homework. While there are some strong arguments against the setting of homework, I still believe that it is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a necessary aspect of education</strong>.\n\nThere are several reasons why people might argue that homework is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an unnecessary burden</strong> on children. Firstly, there is evidence to support the idea that homework does nothing to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">improve educational outcomes</strong>. Countries such as Finland, where school children are not given homework, regularly top international educational league tables and outperform nations where setting homework is the norm. Secondly, many parents would agree that the school day is already long enough, and leaves their children too tired to do further study when they return home. Finally, it is recognised that play time is just as beneficial as study time from the perspective of brain development.\n\nIn spite of the above arguments, I support the view that homework has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an important role to play</strong> in the schooling of children. The main benefit of homework is that it encourages independent learning and problem solving, as children are challenged to work through tasks alone and at their own pace. In doing so, students must apply the knowledge that they have learned in the classroom. For example, by doing mathematics exercises at home, students consolidate their understanding of the concepts taught by their teacher at school. In my view, it is important for children to develop an independent study habit because this prepares them to work alone as adults.\n\nIn conclusion, homework certainly has its drawbacks, but I believe that the benefits outweigh them in the long term.","phrases":[{"en":"a necessary aspect of education","vi":"một khía cạnh cần thiết của giáo dục"},{"en":"an unnecessary burden","vi":"một gánh nặng không cần thiết"},{"en":"improve educational outcomes","vi":"cải thiện kết quả giáo dục"},{"en":"an important role to play","vi":"một vai trò quan trọng"}],"subtype":"Discuss both views + opinion · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#052","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Homework in children’s education","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-053","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"Some people believe that studying at university or college is the best route to a successful career, while others believe that it is better to get a job straight after school.","answer":"Discuss both views and give your opinion.\n\nWhen they finish school, teenagers <strong class=\"key-phrase\">face the dilemma</strong> of whether to get a job or continue their education. While there are some benefits to getting a job straight after school, I would argue that it is better to go to college or university.\n\nThe option to start work straight after school is attractive for several reasons. Many young people want to start earning money as soon as possible. In this way, they can become independent, and they will be able to afford their own house or start a family. In terms of their career, young people who decide to find work, rather than continue their studies, may progress more quickly. They will have the chance to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">gain real experience</strong> and learn practical skills related to their chosen profession. This may lead to promotions and a successful career.\n\nOn the other hand, I believe that it is more beneficial for students to continue their studies. Firstly, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">academic qualifications</strong> are required in many professions. For example, it is impossible to become a doctor, teacher or lawyer without having the relevant degree. As a result, university graduates <strong class=\"key-phrase\">have access to</strong> more and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">better job opportunities</strong>, and they tend to earn higher salaries than those with fewer qualifications. Secondly, the job market is becoming increasingly competitive, and sometimes there are hundreds of applicants for one position in a company. Young people who do not have qualifications from a university or college will not be able to compete.\n\nFor the reasons mentioned above, it seems to me that students are more likely to be successful in their careers if they continue their studies beyond school level.","phrases":[{"en":"face the dilemma","vi":"đối mặt với tình huống khó xử"},{"en":"gain real experience","vi":"tích lũy kinh nghiệm thực tế"},{"en":"academic qualifications","vi":"bằng cấp"},{"en":"have access to","vi":"được tiếp cận với"},{"en":"better job opportunities","vi":"cơ hội việc làm tốt hơn"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#053","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"People believe that studying at university or college is the best route to…","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-054","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education: Private schools","prompt":"Families who send their children to private schools should not be required to pay taxes that support the state education system. To what extent do you agree or disagree with this statement?","answer":"Some people believe that parents of children who attend private schools should not need to contribute to state schools through taxes. Personally, I completely disagree with this view.\n\nFor a variety of reasons, it would be wrong to reduce taxes for families who pay for private education. Firstly, it would be difficult to calculate the correct amount of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">tax reduction</strong> for these families, and staff would be required to manage this complex process. Secondly, we all pay a certain amount of tax for public services that we may not use. For example, most people are fortunate enough not to have to call the police or fire brigade at any time in their lives, but they would not expect a tax reduction for this. Finally, if <strong class=\"key-phrase\">wealthy families</strong> were given a tax discount for sending their children to private schools, we might have a situation where poorer people pay higher taxes than the rich.\n\nIn my opinion, we should all be happy to pay our share of the money that supports public schools. It is beneficial for all members of society to have a high quality education system with <strong class=\"key-phrase\">equal opportunities</strong> for all young people. This will result in a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">well-educated workforce</strong>, and in turn a more productive and prosperous nation. Parents of children in private schools may also see the advantages of this in their own lives. For example, a company owner will need well qualified and competent staff, and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a well-funded education system</strong> can provide such employees.\n\nIn conclusion, I do not believe that any <strong class=\"key-phrase\">financial concessions</strong> should be made for people who choose private education.","phrases":[{"en":"tax reduction","vi":"giảm thuế"},{"en":"wealthy families","vi":"các gia đình giàu có"},{"en":"equal opportunities","vi":"cơ hội bình đẳng"},{"en":"well-educated workforce","vi":"nguồn lao động được đào tạo kĩ lưỡng"},{"en":"a well-funded education system","vi":"kệ thống giáo dục được đầu tư kĩ lưỡng"},{"en":"financial concessions","vi":"các ưu đãi tài chính"}],"subtype":"Agree / Disagree · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#054","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Private schools and education taxes","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-055","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"Some people believe that a gap year between school and university is a good idea, while others disagree strongly. Consider both sides of this debate and present your own opinion.","answer":"While gap years are increasingly popular, they continue to be rather controversial because the benefits are hard to quantify exactly. There are arguments on both sides of this very topical debate, and I will discuss them now. On the one hand, opponents of gap years point to the cost involved in areas such as air fares, accommodation and living expenses. All this money has to come from the student’s family, or even from borrowing to be paid later. Secondly, it is often said that gap years <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take a young person’s focus away from studying</strong>, and allows them to get involved in distractions such as travelling. This can make it hard to adjust to university life, damaging the student’s performance. Finally, there is a concern over the safety of young people if they are travelling to remote places. Being kidnapped or mugged is a poor start to an academic career, after all. On the other hand, supporters of gap years say that the skills learned <strong class=\"key-phrase\">outweigh the disadvantages</strong>. They highlight the independence and assertiveness that a student will acquire, in areas such as time management and interpersonal skills. They also say that these skills lead to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">greater career success</strong> later in life, thus cancelling out the costs involved. There are many examples of young people using gap years to achieve something significant, whether in voluntary work or in a sector of business that interests them. In conclusion, my own feeling is that a year off can indeed be a useful activity, with the experience leading to improved skills that are invaluable in the future. Of course, this is provided that the year is planned carefully and used for something <strong class=\"key-phrase\">genuinely worthwhile</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"take a young person’s focus away from studying","vi":"khiến người trẻ mất tập trung vào việc học"},{"en":"outweigh the disadvantages","vi":"lớn hơn những bất lợi"},{"en":"greater career success","vi":"thành công nghề nghiệp lớn hơn"},{"en":"genuinely worthwhile","vi":"thực sự đáng giá"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#055","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"People believe that a gap year between school and university is a good…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-056","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education: Children","prompt":"Some people believe that sport is an essential part of school life for children, while others feel it should be purely optional. Discuss these opposing views and give your own opinion.","answer":"Sport continues to be a controversial topic in the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">school curriculum</strong>, just as sport itself has become a controversial industry in some respects. There are valid opinions on both sides, which I will consider now. On the one hand, some people feel that sport uses up time which could be better spent on academic subjects such as exam preparation. In addition, it might be said that it is unwise to force children to do activities which they have no interest in. After all, some youngsters are just not sporty, and should be allowed to study instead. Finally, there are question marks over the wholesomeness of sport itself, with drugging and corruption scandals increasingly common, as we see in cycling at present. Some people believe that this lack of morals sets a poor example to young people. On the other hand, though, one major benefit of sport is that it helps children’s <strong class=\"key-phrase\">physical development</strong> at an important stage. If all their time was spent studying, they would become unfit and their minds would eventually suffer. Furthermore, supporters of school sport emphasize the importance of team building in sports such as football or hockey, which is often felt to be an excellent preparation for adulthood. Finally, many people feel that a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">competitive spirit</strong>, so important today, is fostered by sports at an early age. It is notable, for example, that many successful business people excelled in sport at school. Overall, I feel that sport should be compulsory for school children, because the positive effect on their mental and physical development outweighs the negatives. This is as long as children are given a wide range to choose from, to ensure their interest is high, and that the sports industry itself maintains the highest standards of conduct.","phrases":[{"en":"school curriculum","vi":"chương trình học ở trường"},{"en":"physical development","vi":"sự phát triển thể chất"},{"en":"competitive spirit","vi":"tinh thần cạnh tranh"}],"subtype":"Discussion","_displayNo":"#056","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"People believe that sport is an essential part of school life for children,…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-057","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"The computer is widely used in education and some people think that teachers will not play important roles in the classroom. To what extent do you agree?","answer":"Computers have been favoured by more and more educators and teachers as a key component of a perfect educational environment. Its role in a traditional classroom is nevertheless a subject of debate, with myriad arguments being advanced both in support of and against its impact on the role of a teacher.\n\nOne of the major drawbacks of the computer is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">lack of flexibility</strong>. Due to its programmatic limitations, its teaching is uniform, repetitive, standardised and therefore unsuited to the specific needs of a student. For example, it can only answer questions which have been programmed into it but fails to answer any unusual, non-standard and unprecedented question. By contrast, a human teacher can respond flexibly with giving <strong class=\"key-phrase\">well-tailored, persuasive and inspiring answers</strong>. For this reason, a computer hardly functions as effectively as a human teacher does.\n\nAnother disadvantage of the computer, which makes it unaligned with the philosophy of the contemporary education, is its failure to interact with students. Out of technical constraints, the computer is interested in eliciting the desired response only. Students’ unexpected performance, potentially exceptional and distinguished, is not recognised by the computer. It is fair to say that computers achieve nothing but make all education into <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an uncritical type of vocational training</strong>. Students are conditioned to absorb information without questioning and given no chance to express their personal opinions.\n\nThere are some other problems inherent in the computer-based teaching, such as inability to discipline students and failing to attend to students’ emotional needs, making this model of teaching not as competent as the traditional style. However, the contribution of the computer as a teaching aid can never be underrated. It not only assists teachers to present educational materials in diversified ways but also provides repetitive drills to improve the students’ command of knowledge. With the computer, the teacher can spend less time on paper work and concentrate more on the development of a student in other aspects, such as creativity and teamwork skills. It is essential to advancing rounded education.\n\nTaking into consideration those above-mentioned characteristics of computer-based teaching, one can conclude that the computer can only <strong class=\"key-phrase\">serve as a teaching aid</strong>, facilitating students’ interest in a topic and assisting them to take in information faster, rather than taking the place of the teacher.","phrases":[{"en":"lack of flexibility","vi":"thiếu tính linh hoạt"},{"en":"well-tailored, persuasive and inspiring answers","vi":"những câu trả lời phù hợp, thuyết phục và truyền cảm hứng"},{"en":"an uncritical type of vocational training","vi":"một kiểu đào tạo nghề thiếu tư duy phản biện"},{"en":"serve as a teaching aid","vi":"đóng vai trò công cụ hỗ trợ giảng dạy"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#057","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Computer is widely used in education and some people think that teachers…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-058","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education: Young people","prompt":"Discuss the advantages and disadvantages of studying abroad.","answer":"Studying abroad allows one to gain a real knowledge of a new culture and a new language. By interacting and communicating with native speakers daily, students can enhance their foreign language skills. They will simultaneously explore the values and ways of life of the host country. For example, Asian students might be surprised to find that communication in Western countries is starkly open and straightforward, in sharp contrast to the intense use of non-verbal messages in communication in their home countries, Not surprisingly, even simple everyday experiences, such as buying food and mailing letter, can help improve <strong class=\"key-phrase\">language proficiency</strong> and promote culture learning. It gives students new perspectives on how things are done.\n\nDuring their overseas trips, many students will learn how to take care of themselves and live independently, They might have initial difficulties in fulfilling even the simplest tasks at the very beginning, such as grocery shopping, doing laundry, making living arrangements and setting accounts for electricity, but before long, they will adapt to the new environment and become self-sufficient. Moreover, by interacting with people from different backgrounds, overseas students can exercise and improve their social skills, an experience which is of great value to their careers later in life.\n\nWhile studying abroad has its advantages, it might have its drawbacks. Most students lack life experience when they first travel overseas. Failure to cope with the problems that arise from their everyday lives might cause frustration, They feel helpless, suffer homesick and in worse cases, have a breakdown.\n\nAs suggested above, studying abroad poses both opportunities and challenges. While young people can become polyglots and independent individuals, gain opportunities for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">personal growth</strong> and develop an appreciation of cultural differences, they have to cope with the stress of living overseas.","phrases":[{"en":"language proficiency","vi":"năng lực ngôn ngữ"},{"en":"personal growth","vi":"sự phát triển cá nhân"}],"subtype":"Advantages / Disadvantages","_displayNo":"#058","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Discuss the advantages and disadvantages of studying abroad.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-059","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"Do you think it is better to send criminals to jail or let them receive education or job training?","answer":"In the public mind, a prison is a place to keep those who have done wicked things in captivity, in order that they will not contaminate law-abiding citizens. However, there is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a growing concern</strong> in these years that imprisonment is a less effective form of punishment, and some alternatives seem to promise more satisfying outcomes. I agree on this proposed change, with evidence that imprisonment can be merely taken as the last resort.\n\nEducation is of critical importance to rehabilitating an offender. It first changes delinquents’ attitudes toward society and family, a prerequisite to their reintegration into the community, It meanwhile allows them to keep in contact with the community, an opportunity that prisoners are normally deprived of. With the passing of time, they lose confidence and the ability to function responsibly in society. The risk of re-offending is thus higher. The third benefit is preventing offenders’ peer group effect, because by receiving education in a proper learning environment, offenders have a lower chance of reinforcing each other’s antisocial and criminal behaviours in group situations.\n\nSimilar to education, work is one of the most important interventions in corrections, whether it takes the form of work release or vocational training. Money is the main inducement of many crimes, such as shoplifting, robbery, burglary, and so forth. Job training enables offenders to acquire earning capacity and improve job skills. By this they can become productive members of society and have the opportunity to behave normally towards family or occupation or society. Greater post-release employment success will, in general, lead to a lower rate of recidivism.\n\nHowever, to those habitual criminals, who have committed crimes repeatedly and show little respect for the legal system, education and job training might not make any significant difference. This category of offenders gives little thought to their past or future. Their behaviours and thoughts are deeply ingrained and unbending, in which circumstance imprisonment is the best way of keeping them from being perpetrators. Meanwhile, imprisonment has deterrent effects and can deter potential offenders from becoming actual offenders.\n\nTo sum up, it is clear that the results of imprisonment can be mixed and it is only effective in restricting those who are very likely to commit repeated acts of violence, By contrast, education and vocational training suit those who committed less serious crimes, preventing them from becoming re-offenders after release and assisting them to reorganise their lives.","phrases":[{"en":"a growing concern","vi":"mối lo ngại ngày càng tăng"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#059","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Do you think it is better to send criminals to jail or let them receive…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-060","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"Do you think it is good to push students to study hard in their youth?","answer":"High expectations for children are nothing new in today’s society. It leads to the tendency to push children to study harder and harder. In my opinion, the connection between effort and achievement is quite obvious and should not be denied.\n\nAs children grow older, they are more capable of learning more and the amount of time they spend in studying should increase correspondingly. Hard work can raise the odds of success by increasing their knowledge (both general and specialised), improving their abilities and expanding their skill set. All are essential to their success later in life. Without the full commitment to schoolwork, students might end up with struggling with failing school performance and even dropping out of the school.\n\nFull engagement in schooling also matches the trends of a modern society. To succeed in today’s challenging economy, young people need advanced skills in core subjects like English, math and science, as well as the ability to use computers, solve problems effectively, think critically and work in teams. It appears that most students lack motivation to study and their attention can be diverted easily by such distractions as video games. Without an unmistakable message delivered to them that academic achievement is what makes them survive in this competitive world, they will not learn as much as their ability and effort permits.\n\nDespite the great value of hardworking, one should <strong class=\"key-phrase\">bear in mind</strong> the fact that students of all ages need time to play and relax. They should be given freedom to develop their hobbies and encouraged to dabble in different activities, so they can learn in depth about the world, explore ideas and soothe themselves. Children’s tolerance for stress is another noteworthy issue. Failing to cope with stress might disable students from maintaining their interest in studying. A prolonged period of learning is disruptive to children’s learning outcomes, distancing students from <strong class=\"key-phrase\">critical thinking</strong> and turning them into rote learners.\n\nFrom what has been discussed, studying hard is critical to a student’s success, helping him or her acquire more knowledge in his or her youth and leading him or her to focus on schoolwork. However, the balance between work and relaxation should be considered in equal measure. Parents and teachers are advised to help children design their timetables scientifically in case that they are fed up with studying.","phrases":[{"en":"bear in mind","vi":"ghi nhớ; lưu ý"},{"en":"critical thinking","vi":"tư duy phản biện"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#060","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Do you think it is good to push students to study hard in their youth?","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-061","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"Do you think middle school students should study international news as a subject?","answer":"Today, watching news, a means of learning what is happening around the world, has become a way of life to many people. When the value of news is undisputed, an issue of debate is whether it is necessary to include international news as part of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">school curriculum</strong>. I believe that it will be an encouraging change.\n\nThe first point to support the importance of international news is that it reminds young people of the forces of globalisation and international developments. In today’s world, businesses operate beyond borders and countries are closely connected with each other. Any country that fails to recognise this would miss out on the benefits of globalisation. To young people, watching international news leads them to develop a global perspective and world vision. They learn to elicit information from news and use it in decision making, for example, studying abroad, career option, and so forth. It is of critical importance as they are very likely to face stiff international competition later in life.\n\nAnother benefit obtained from studying international news is enhancing young people's capabilities and skills, such as <strong class=\"key-phrase\">critical thinking</strong> skills. Living in a society that is bombarded with different messages, many people have become lost in search for useful information and unable to understand and absorb information. Studying international news drives them to explore perspectives and get a view of every aspect of an international event. Reading editorials allows them to practice independent thinking.\n\nDespite those benefits, integrating international news into curriculum requires educators to address several issues in advance. First, students might be distracted by a great variety of conflicting arguments produced by different experts. However, as mentioned above, it is immensely conducive to the development of their analytical skills. Meanwhile, it could be time-consuming for students to read-those: news stories that are identical with each other in essence, although they appear in different papers. It, therefore, requires teachers to select news in advance and play an active role.\n\nIn conclusion, one has reasons to believe that international news deserves a place in school curriculum. By reading, watching and analysing international news, future generations will acquire knowledge of the whole world and enrich a variety of skills.","phrases":[{"en":"school curriculum","vi":"chương trình học ở trường"},{"en":"critical thinking","vi":"tư duy phản biện"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#061","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Do you think middle school students should study international news as a…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-062","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"Education used to be a short period of training, but today, people treat it like a lifelong practice. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"The notion of learning throughout life is not new but only until recently has been discussed to a larger extent. More than learning for employment opportunities and competitive positions, learners pursue academic opportunities for many other purposes today. One has reasons to believe that education is more likely to be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a lifelong pursuit</strong>, rather than an isolated practice in the century to come.\n\nBecause of technological advances, people are now given learning opportunities in different contexts at work, at home or through leisure activities. People in a modern society are not confined to formal channels (e. g., schools) but provided with more options, such as studying either via the Internet or television, known as distance learning or e-learning. Learning can occur at all ages. The working people, parents with childcare responsibilities, the disabled and the elderly are all able to learn now, with <strong class=\"key-phrase\">time and location constraints being transcended</strong>. The era when education was available only in formal schools and mainly intended for young people has passed.\n\nAnother force that drives lifelong education is the constantly changing nature of the society. It is certain that at the present time, no career fields can stay static. Because of the acceleration of scientific and technological progress, reeducation seems to be an urgent need throughout one’s working life, especially to those who work in hi-tech industries, such as IT. People feel compelled to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">keep themselves well-informed</strong> of all the latest changes in the industry they are working in, in case that they fall behind their peers. It is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">in sharp contrast to the past</strong>, where university education was sufficient for a professional career spanning three or more decades.\n\nPursuit of one’s own targets is another reason why education tends to last a lifetime nowadays. The interests of people in today’s society are not limited to material wealth and better standards of living, but involve other desires, ranging from self-expression, individuality to fulfilment of their own dreams. When formal education in the past was generally vocational and intended for sustaining life, many forms of education in today’s society are non-vocational. For example, many people study philosophy, psychology, painting, music, history and other arts subjects with the purpose to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">put meaning into the whole of life</strong>, rather than living simply as an income earner.\n\nIn summary, a combination of various factors, including the educational opportunities provided outside standard educational systems, individuals’ craving for achievement, and the soaring competitive pressure, accounts for why education has no endings in one’s lifetime.","phrases":[{"en":"a lifelong pursuit","vi":"một hành trình học tập suốt đời"},{"en":"time and location constraints being transcended","vi":"vượt qua những hạn chế về thời gian và địa điểm"},{"en":"keep themselves well-informed","vi":"luôn cập nhật đầy đủ thông tin"},{"en":"in sharp contrast to the past","vi":"trái ngược rõ rệt với trước đây"},{"en":"put meaning into the whole of life","vi":"mang lại ý nghĩa cho toàn bộ cuộc sống"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#062","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Education used to be a short period of training, but today, people treat it…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-063","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"Women remain underrepresented in some university subjects. Some people argue that this imbalance cannot be eliminated. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Although gender equality is widely promoted at modern colleges, females are still <strong class=\"key-phrase\">underrepresented in some subjects</strong>. Some people tend to treat it as a persistent problem, believing that the root of this problem is not in the university, but should be seen in a wider context. This conclusion is cursory and should be reviewed in today’s society.\n\nThe first point to note is that females have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made a lot of inroads into fields</strong> that have been traditionally dominated by men. To serve in the army was, for instance, the exclusive right of males, but today, more women have been enlisted. Many would consider the army as the most ideally “men only” profession. If females can make a success of it, they can succeed in every other field. The ascendancy of woman has been seen in the surge in their prominent positions in society and in the traditional blue collar business world. Women should not be considered unqualified or incapable of any university subject.\n\nUniversities that provide <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a gender-fair environment</strong> see benefits for both students and faculty. Historically, the gender imbalance at colleges has isolated students from the real world, where there is a high chance of dealing with females rather than just males. The tension or conflict between the sex in the university environment only allows students to exercise their ability to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">work with peers of the opposite sex</strong>. Faculty gets the chance to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">address the problem of gender inequality</strong> and discrimination, which has characterised campuses for decades. This results in a better learning environment, and thus a better thought of university.\n\nDespite what has been discussed, it should be admitted that to put gender equality into practice is a complex task. There are a number of hurdles a female applicant has to overcome in the pursuit of academic objectives, and the first is from family. Traditional families often feel reluctant to support their daughters’ guest for higher education. The idea that university is mainly for men to learn a trade to support their wives and family remains prevalent. The women’s role is being defined as supporting their husband through performing menial tasks of life.\n\nIn conclusion, achieving a gender balance in the university is no longer an unachievable aim at the present time. While the competence of women has widely been recognised by their male colleagues in a wide range of occupations, the balance between men and women in an academic environment is deemed as a necessity, Although problems such as gender prejudice and favouritism continue to prevent women’s full participation in some subjects, these problems are losing their leverage.","phrases":[{"en":"underrepresented in some subjects","vi":"có tỷ lệ tham gia thấp trong một số môn học"},{"en":"made a lot of inroads into fields","vi":"đạt nhiều bước tiến trong các lĩnh vực"},{"en":"a gender-fair environment","vi":"môi trường bình đẳng giới"},{"en":"work with peers of the opposite sex","vi":"làm việc với bạn học khác giới"},{"en":"address the problem of gender inequality","vi":"giải quyết vấn đề bất bình đẳng giới"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#063","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Gender imbalance has long been a general phenomenon not only in the labour…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-064","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"Good facilities can be found in cities but not in the countryside. Therefore, new doctors and teachers should be sent to the countryside. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Poor facilities have been found as a common sight of rural areas. To improve this situation, some suggest that new doctors and teachers should be assigned with tasks in the countryside, but not in urban areas, There are some strong arguments for this suggested solution.\n\nThe first is that hospitals, clinics and schools are severely understaffed in rural areas, compared with their overstaffed counterparts in the city. The imbalance of resource and staff has chronic effects on the well-being of rural people. Lack of education or medication has made them among the most disadvantaged in a country. Allocating new doctors and teachers to those areas can at least provide a temporary solution. Besides, it helps address the issue of distributing the graduates from medical school and normal college, with filling those vacancies for physicians and teachers in rural communities.\n\nTo the doctors or teachers that graduate freshly with a degree only, working in rural areas enables them to enrich work experience within the shortest possible period of time. Opportunities are scarce in the city, where numerous candidates are in the race for a single position. The chance of raising standards through practice is so meagre that it will over time hamper rural practitioners’ <strong class=\"key-phrase\">career development</strong> and make them uncompetitive in a skill-based society. Facility shortage to many doctors in the country is an opportunity, instead of a challenge. They are in a position to rely more on clinical skills than on sophisticated equipment. For teachers, they teach with few teaching aids. All contribute to the increment of their skills.\n\nDespite those benefits, the place of work should be chosen by doctors or teachers themselves and compulsory assortment is not justifiable. It is not ethical to stop the desire of individuals for a more satisfying quality of life. Needless to say working in rural areas has many issues to address, working conditions, transport and housing. For this reason, those graduates who volunteer to take rural employment deserve a better pay as a recognition of their contribution and also as an incentive.\n\nFrom what has been discussed, working for a period of time in the country can benefit new teachers and doctors alike with increasing their work experience and meanwhile, address the service shortage facing those areas. However, the voluntary sign-up should be guaranteed, instead of compulsory assignment.","phrases":[{"en":"career development","vi":"sự phát triển nghề nghiệp"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#064","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Good facilities can be found in cities but not in the countryside.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-065","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education: Children","prompt":"In modern society, some people argue that schools become unnecessary as children can study at home via the Internet. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"The rapid progression of the Internet has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">paved the way for</strong> the growing popularity of distance learning. People are now speculating on the possibility of the Internet taking the place of a traditional school. In my opinion, given the continued advance in technology, Internet-based learning can serve as an alternative to traditional class-based learning.\n\nOnline education has many advantages. It allows students to set their own study time. Unlike traditional learning, online courses offer children <strong class=\"key-phrase\">greater flexibility</strong> and enable them to create a timetable in line with their needs and characteristics. Students can also save tuition fees, because a virtual school normally charges students much less than a conventional school does. It is particularly a great option for those students with physical handicaps, who have great difficulties in commuting to school campus. For those who live far away from the school, online education is remarkably favourable. It can be expected that the Internet is very likely to replace a physical school as an education provider in the near future if its drawbacks are removed.\n\nThe first drawback of a virtual school is lack of human contact, as opposed to a noted merit of traditional teacher-led education, providing students with ongoing daily interactions with teachers. This weakness can be solved by taking advantage of bandwidth network technologies. The interaction between students can be guaranteed when one can contact with another—whenever and wherever he or she likes—via email, post comments on message boards and chat rooms, or even videoconference for communication. Educators are also concerned that online learning cannot make all skills and knowledge transferable. For example, some courses require a high proportion of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">hands-on practice</strong>, which is beyond the capacity of online training. This problem can be nevertheless addressed by introducing multimedia as a teaching aid. By using audio and video, students can sample different Learning styles and acquire both general and specialised knowledge of a subject.\n\nAs suggested above, there are plenty of benefits of online learning, including flexibility, cost-saving and convenience. Although it has two problems, lack of interaction and failing to provide a wide range of courses, both can be overcome <strong class=\"key-phrase\">as technology advances</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"paved the way for","vi":"mở đường cho"},{"en":"greater flexibility","vi":"tính linh hoạt cao hơn"},{"en":"hands-on practice","vi":"thực hành trực tiếp"},{"en":"as technology advances","vi":"khi công nghệ phát triển"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#065","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"In modern society, some people argue that schools become unnecessary as…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-066","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"In order to improve the quality of education, high school students should be encouraged to evaluate and criticise their teachers, but others think it will result in loss of respect and discipline in classroom. What is your opinion?","answer":"Teacher appraisal is not a new instrument in improving teaching performance or developing teacher training. However, when it comes to inviting the input of students and seeking their comments on teachers’ performance, there is disagreement. Some people object to this practice, saying that it leads to the loss of respect and discipline. In my opinion, students’ participation in teacher appraisal is definitely helpful, but it should be administered properly.\n\nA strong argument for using student ratings to evaluate teachers is that students’ judgement is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reliable and impartial</strong>. Because of their ongoing interaction with teachers throughout the semester, students have the authority to measure the performance and competence of a teacher, with the knowledge they have obtained from learning and the stance they have adopted toward the subject taught. A critical analysis of students’ feedback enables teachers to enhance their competence and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">adjust teaching aims and methods</strong> for better attainment of students’ learning objectives.\n\nStudents are also concerned about whether the teacher is fully committed to his or her job. The value of a teacher is determined as much by competence as by commitment. The school can therefore assess the performance of a teacher by collecting students’ feedback on some observable facts, such as a teacher’s punctuality and the legibility of his or her writing on the board. Teachers who perform poorly are advised to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reflect deeply on their teaching practice</strong>, the drawbacks in particular, which is the key to the improvement of their performance.\n\nDespite those overt advantages of encouraging students’ input, analysis of their input is important and should be handled carefully. Misinterpretation of students’ opinions might leave teachers an inaccurate picture of their strengths and weaknesses and lead them into a poor judgement about what they can do to satisfy the needs of their students. It is also important to guide teachers to perceive the feedback sensibly; otherwise, they might have feelings of powerlessness.\n\nWhat has been discussed is to support a notion that students’ input provides <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an important source of data</strong> for evaluating teachers, helping teachers not only to discover their disadvantages but also to make an improvement.","phrases":[{"en":"reliable and impartial","vi":"đáng tin cậy và khách quan"},{"en":"adjust teaching aims and methods","vi":"điều chỉnh mục tiêu và phương pháp giảng dạy"},{"en":"reflect deeply on their teaching practice","vi":"suy ngẫm sâu về phương pháp giảng dạy"},{"en":"an important source of data","vi":"một nguồn dữ liệu quan trọng"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#066","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"In order to improve the quality of education, high school students should…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-067","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"It is argued that university students should study a full range of subjects, instead of some specific subjects. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Since the second half of the last century, there has been a switch from the traditional manufacturing economy to a knowledge economy. Much of the world has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">placed a premium on</strong> the knowledge and skills one can obtain from higher education. Some academics suggest that university students should widen their study from a limited range of subject orientation to a high complexity of subjects, This proposed change merits serious consideration.\n\nFrom a social aspect, current employers show a tendency to recruit youngsters who can do a various array of jobs within a single position rather than job specialists. A clerk working for a bank, for example, is required to possess a collection of skills, ranging from those learned in the field of finance, accounting and economy to those in other relevant subjects, such as management, communication and sociology. As the job market is becoming increasingly competitive, students who dabble in different specialised areas and have experience in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">interdisciplinary study</strong> are expected to be in a advantageous position.\n\nFrom students’ perspective, learning different subjects can be both <strong class=\"key-phrase\">personally fulfilling and skill-enhancing</strong>. Many students tend to perceive it as unwieldy when studying several subjects they have no experience in. This challenge, if overcome, leaves individuals more room for skill enhancement. For example, extra learning requires students to take in essential information within a time frame. In coping with this task, students have to develop outstanding time management skills and show expertise in Juggling different jobs at a time, With know-how, they are more adjustable in this fast-changing social setting.\n\nAccording to the above advantages, learning different subjects does good to university students. Not only does it make students time-conscious and versatile, but also helps students to match the needs of a fast-changing and competitive society.","phrases":[{"en":"placed a premium on","vi":"đặc biệt coi trọng"},{"en":"interdisciplinary study","vi":"học tập liên ngành"},{"en":"personally fulfilling and skill-enhancing","vi":"vừa mang lại sự thỏa mãn cá nhân vừa nâng cao kỹ năng"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#067","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"It is argued that university students should study a full range of…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-068","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"It is generally believed that education is of vital importance to individual development and the well-being of societies. What should education consist of to fulfil both these functions?","answer":"Education is one of the largest items of government spending. It is regarded as the pathway to economic prosperity, an instrument for combating unemployment and the driving force behind scientific and technological advance. Given the importance of education for individuals and society, its scope, constituents and configuration have long been the subject of research, studies and discussion.\n\nTheoretically, a student <strong class=\"key-phrase\">is expected to</strong> acquire knowledge of a specific subject or profession at school, but throughout the learning process, education should focus on the development of their skills. A successful school leaver should show exceptional abilities to acquire, organise, interpret, evaluate and communicate information when graduate. Similarly, a proficient learner should meanwhile be a resource coordinator and user, proficient in identifying useful resources (such as information and capital) with speed and using them to the full advantage. A qualified student should also possess some other skills, such as problem solving and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">critical thinking</strong>, which are essential not only for their <strong class=\"key-phrase\">further education</strong> but also for their careers later in life.\n\nWhen students become knowledgeable and resourceful, they should be equipped with competence that would enhance the transition from school to work. An excellent learner is admittedly important to society, but more important is his or her productivity. Education should absorb new substances and embrace new concepts in order for students to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">keep in touch with</strong> community and have full knowledge of the needs of community. Besides, a school should facilitate the progress of students in every practical field and give them opportunities to try new tasks and take on new roles. By enhancing their hands-on skills and job-related skills, schools can foster students’ and society's future development and prosperity.\n\nWhen enhancing learners’ academic excellence and professionalism, education cannot overlook learners’ physical and psychological well-being. In this fast-changing and competitive society, many people are not in good form in coping with stress and health problems. Encouraging students to reduce stress and develop good health habits is therefore important. Sports, for example, function effectively as a health facilitator and as a good stress reliever, These extracurricular activities can be combined with academic activities to boost students’ mental health and learning outcomes.\n\nTo conclude, today’s students are expected to be versatile, productive and healthy individuals when they finish schooling. With society becoming more specialised and economies demanding more skills, students should focus on both theoretical and practical aspects of education. They should lay a stress on physical activities as well.","phrases":[{"en":"is expected to","vi":"được dự đoán"},{"en":"critical thinking","vi":"tư duy phản biện"},{"en":"further education","vi":"giáo dục sau phổ thông; học tập nâng cao"},{"en":"keep in touch with","vi":"giữ liên lạc với"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#068","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"It is generally believed that education is of vital importance to…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-069","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education: Children","prompt":"It is not uncommon that children are required to obey the rule of their parents and teachers. Some people are worried that too much control over children will not prepare them well for their adult life. Discuss both sides and give your opinion.","answer":"Adults’ intervention <strong class=\"key-phrase\">plays a pivotal role in</strong> a child’s development. Despite this general knowledge, people are very often confronted with the arguments about the appropriateness of some traditional teaching styles and methods, such as enforcing rules and requiring children’s compliance. I agree that rules set by parents contribute greatly to the shaping of children’s behaviour, personalities and all other personal characteristics, although I question the view that it is definitely beneficial to children.\n\nThere is no point in denying that rule setting is possibly the most effective method in overcoming some upbringing difficulties, such as protecting children from dangers and guiding them to act rationally. Children are adventuresome and full of curiosity. They attempt various activities, either with deliberation or on the spur of the moment. Imposing rules is therefore imperative, as it prevents many problems from occurring. For example, forbidding accessing knives, medicine, microwaves or ovens can minimise the risk of accidents and injuries. Some other rules, such as forbidding spitting, nose-picking and foul language, lead children to develop proper demeanour in different social situations, and to adhere to strict rules of professional etiquette from their early childhood.\n\nHowever, rules should be lifted gradually as children grow older, especially when it becomes clear that rules tend to restrain children’s mental development. In a traditional classroom, for example, rules are set and applied to underpin the authority of a teacher. Students are not allowed to pose questions at will, nor are they allowed to challenge teachers’ answers. Many of their questions remain unanswered, presenting obstacles to their learning process and forming numerous misconceptions. Another problem is that it will discourage students from reflecting on what they have learned, and dampen their passion for learning. They are trained as mechanical or rote learners, while their aptitude for creativity is stifled.\n\nAs indicated above, whether to impose rules on children is determined as much by the age of children as by the appropriateness of rules themselves. For younger children, strict rules should be set to ensure children’s safety and health. For older children, rules should be concerned about children’s behaviour on social occasions. When children become responsible and knowledgeable with age, rules should be phased out.","phrases":[{"en":"plays a pivotal role in","vi":"đóng vai trò then chốt trong"}],"subtype":"Discussion","_displayNo":"#069","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"It is not uncommon that children are required to obey the rule of their…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-070","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"It is widely accepted that people who have post-school qualifications earn a higher salary than those less educated do. University students should, therefore, pay all the full cost incurred over the course of obtaining a college education. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"With the labour intensive economy gradually giving way to knowledge-focused economy, the access to higher education has become an issue of broad interest. The proposal to charge all university students with tuition fees and allow no exemption arises mainly from the concern that tertiary education has to compete with many other urgent demands for public funds and struggle with underfunding. I believe that this policy, if implemented, will have an accumulative effect on the well-being of either individual students or the society as a whole.\n\nWhen laying the hope of future development over students, the government cannot shirk from the responsibility to finance them. The sustained growth of a country rests on young talents. In this sense, the government is investing, not spending money, A standard example is America, a country investing multimillion dollars in higher education on an annual basis and sponsoring students’ study by different forms of aid, such as scholarships, subsidies, allowances and student loans. It can be expected that these <strong class=\"key-phrase\">well-educated</strong> aspiring people, after finishing their education, will constitute a main drive of a state’s growth. Moreover, the government should plough a reasonable proportion of tax revenue, most being sourced from parents, back to their children.\n\nMeanwhile, it is worth mentioning that some schools tend to force a complex of charges over students, with the aim to extend their profit margin. Ignorant of their not-for-profit nature, many universities might deviate from their most important tasks, such as improving teaching quality. The persistence of this problem will make their academic service much less credible and quality of teaching and faculty staff uneven. A university can cover its expense by various means, such as the receipt of donation, or the government’s funding, instead of levying a high fee over students.\n\nThe reasons cited above have justified why university students need not pay more than a lower payment. While depending on young generations, the society should be more considerate- of’ their situation. The effort to encourage tertiary education participation will pay back sooner, rather than later.","phrases":[{"en":"well-educated","vi":"được giáo dục tốt; có học thức"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#070","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"It is widely accepted that people who have post-school qualifications earn…","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"Education: Children","prompt":"Some people think that parents should teach their children how to be good members of society. Others, however, believe that school is the best place to learn this. Discuss both views and give your own opinion.","answer":"Children learn social behaviour from both their families and their schools. Parents have the strongest influence in the early years, while schools give children daily opportunities to practise cooperation and responsibility. I therefore believe that both share this duty.\n\nParents shape a child’s first ideas about honesty, respect and self-control. Children observe how adults speak to others, keep promises and deal with disagreement. Advice is useful, but example is more powerful. A home in which adults act responsibly gives children <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a clear moral foundation</strong> before they enter wider society.\n\nSchools then expand this learning. In class, children must wait their turn, follow common rules and work with people from different backgrounds. Teachers can discuss bullying, fairness and civic responsibility, while group projects allow students to put these ideas into practice. Schools are particularly important when children do not receive consistent guidance at home, but they cannot <strong class=\"key-phrase\">replace parental example</strong>.\n\nCooperation between parents and teachers is especially important when a child behaves badly. If the two sides send opposite messages, rules lose their force. Regular communication, clear consequences and shared expectations help adults identify whether a problem begins at home, at school or online. This creates <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a consistent framework for social development</strong>.\n\nThis shared approach is especially valuable during adolescence, when peer pressure becomes stronger and rules are more likely to be questioned.\n\nIn conclusion, parents should introduce the values that make someone a good member of society, and schools should reinforce them through teaching and shared experience. The most effective approach is close cooperation between home and school, so that children receive <strong class=\"key-phrase\">consistent expectations in different settings</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Education","phrases":[{"en":"a clear moral foundation","vi":"nền tảng đạo đức rõ ràng"},{"en":"replace parental example","vi":"thay thế tấm gương của cha mẹ"},{"en":"a consistent framework for social development","vi":"một khuôn khổ nhất quán cho sự phát triển xã hội"},{"en":"consistent expectations in different settings","vi":"những kỳ vọng nhất quán trong các môi trường khác nhau"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"discuss","summary":"Parents vs. Schools: Teaching Children to Be Good Members of Society","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-071","_displayNo":"#071","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-072","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education: Children","prompt":"Some people argue that it is good for children to stay away from their families and go to a boarding school. Others suggest that children live with their families and attend a day school. What is your opinion?","answer":"Many parents expect their children to live at home until college. However, there are occasions on which parents have to send their children to a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">boarding school</strong>, an educational institution not only giving educational instruction but also providing food and lodging. A boarding school, as an alternative to a day school, has its advantages and disadvantages, as outlined below\n\nThe boarding school option means early separation from parents. For this reason, a student's <strong class=\"key-phrase\">self-reliance and independence</strong> are both bolstered. Living away from home, students have to make most of daily decisions by themselves. They have to adjust to another set of new circumstances and surroundings, which is a good opportunity for them to exercise a variety of skills, such as social skills. Rather than depending on their parents, students have to do the laundry themselves, manage their diets, and keep their bedrooms clean and tidy. They are more self-disciplined than those who attend day schools.\n\nIn addition, It is clear that to many parents, a boarding school provides a choice that merits particular attention, and sometimes, the sole option. Geographic relocation, for example, presents a problem of educational continuity. Because of their career, parents might have to resettle in a neighbourhood where schooling facilities are inadequate. A boarding school is the best option to them, as it protects children from the influence of frequent relocations. It also suits those families where parents are so devoted to their work that they fail to bear care responsibilities.\n\nAlthough boarding schools succeed in satisfying the needs of some families, opponents are concerned about their mixed impacts on children’s development. For example, their intervention on children’s academic years appears to be excessive. Extracurricular programmes occupy children’s free time and children are required to obey many rules, most of which are stringent and redundant. Any minor mistake can engender punishment or even expulsion. Without permission, students cannot go outside defined school bounds. It is no exaggeration to say that children are virtually living in an isolated world.\n\nFrom what has been discussed, one can observe that a boarding school has its position in a fast-paced society, assisting children to enhance their independence and undertaking care responsibilities as a replacement of parents, although students might have to face limited contact with their families, communities and the loss of freedom.","phrases":[{"en":"boarding school","vi":"trường nội trú"},{"en":"self-reliance and independence","vi":"tính tự lập và độc lập"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#072","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People argue that it is good for children to stay away from their families…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-073","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education: Money","prompt":"Some people argue that the government should spend money only on medical care and education but not on theatres or sport stadiums. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Where public money goes is an issue of broad interest to the general public. Some people advocate that the government should fund the sectors that bring tangible and immediate benefits to the public, such as medical care and educational systems, while opponents suggest that those large urban developments, such as stadiums and theatres, are worth government funding. In my opinion, the possibility remains that the two opinions can be reconciled and the government can coordinate budgeting to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">meet the needs of</strong> both.\n\nMedical care is essential to the economic and social well-being of a country, particularly of an underdeveloped country. Both empirical knowledge and academic research suggest that making education available throughout a country and eliminating illiteracy can pave the way for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">economic development</strong>. By receiving education, children from impoverished families can shake off poverty, climb high in the social ladder and live better off. Education also allows citizens to secure employment and earn regular income, thereby maintaining or improving their standard of living. For a country as a whole, education is linked to skilled workforce and to high productivity, affecting both resource use and national output.\n\nGovernment interference in healthcare and medical services is also highly recommended. Availability of affordable medical service is a mark of the social and economic development of a country. By providing the needy people with medical service, a country can inspire the loyalty of citizens. People feel assured living and working in a country where they can be given medical service when unemployed, sick, injured or retired. By comparison, if they cannot afford the high cost of visiting the clinic, hospitalisation, or buying drugs, they are less likely to enjoy their living. Social solidarity will eventually suffer.\n\nAlthough education and medical services are fundamental to the stability and development of a country, it is not to say that theatres or sport stadiums have no redeeming feature. In the hierarchy of human needs, those needs for food, shelter and health are among the basic. After these targets are attained, people turn to higher aspirations, entertainment and recreation. Leisure facilities like stadiums and cinemas satisfy people’s needs in these fields. A game between one’s motherland and a visiting country can raise people’s sense of national pride and ethnic unity. The cinema brings artistic pleasure to everyone.\n\nTo draw a conclusion, the decision to finance theatres or sport stadiums depends on the financial situation of a country. When an economy comes to maturity, the launch of recreational and entertainment projects of this kind is reasonable.","phrases":[{"en":"meet the needs of","vi":"đáp ứng nhu cầu của"},{"en":"economic development","vi":"phát triển kinh tế"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#073","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People argue that the government should spend money only on medical care…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-074","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education: Work","prompt":"Some people believe that students who graduate from high school should have one year’s time to obtain work experience before going to university. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Schooling plays an integral part in individual's life. At the end of high school, students who wish to continue with their education face two probable choices—either suspend their study for a year to obtain work experience, or go straight into university, The second choice appears to be more sensible.\n\nComing fresh out of high school, students do not have a clear understanding of the harsh realities of the world. Either in academic background or in work experience, they are not in a strong position to undertake early employment. Exposure to an unpredictable and daunting world will easily cause a sense of frustration and shake their confidence, both having <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a devastating effect on</strong> their development later in life.\n\nAnother problem of early employment is that most young people are not able to make a correct career decision. Choosing a career requires sufficient knowledge of one’s own strengths, aptitudes and the trends in the job market. Most young adults, unfortunately, lack such knowledge. Their initial experience in a job might lead them to jump on a conclusion and devote themselves to a career without careful consideration. So fast is their fondness for this job that their affinity to the job is mostly ephemeral. It can ruin their entire working lives.\n\nAnother noteworthy problem of working is that it might divert a young adult’s attention from his or her previous academic objectives. If students give up the opportunity of being educated and pursue other ventures, they will lose their abilities and willpower to lear something carefully and patiently. The side effect of disengagement from schooling might not be significant in the first several years, but with age, it will surely disadvantage them a lot. Before long, disillusioned with carly employment, young people might resolve to resume study but soon discover that they are not suitable for a learning environment any more.\n\nIt is therefore clear that students should not attempt a career life once they finish high school’s study. Instead they should go to college directly, and ensure that their future is built on solid foundations, before exploring what else life has to offer.","phrases":[{"en":"a devastating effect on","vi":"tác động tàn phá đối với"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#074","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People believe that students who graduate from high school should have one…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-075","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"Many people join distance-learning programmes (study material, post, TV, Internet) and study at home, but some people think that it cannot bring the same benefit as attending colleges or universities does. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"To <strong class=\"key-phrase\">keep abreast of</strong> the 21st century, large numbers of people are seeking to receive tertiary education. Distance learning, a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">state-of-the-art</strong> educational model, has received wide currency among qualification seekers. Despite being an important alternative to formal education, whether distance learning can achieve the same effect as the traditional form of university education—i. e., going to university in person—is open to debate.\n\nDistance learning, first of all, requires a high degree of maturity or commitment from students because it proceeds in the absence of teachers or tutors. It suits those <strong class=\"key-phrase\">self-motivated and self-directed</strong> students, instead of those who have difficulty in self-scheduling and independent learning, For young learners who generally lack motivation and self-control, their learning effort tends to be disorganised, futile and fragmentary. They will over time develop bad study habits and Jag behind their peers.\n\nThe second weakness of distance learning is its over-dependence on media. Media have a myriad of contents that are likely to divert students’ attention from their study. Online games and browsing webpages, for example, consume much of young learners’ time. In addition, sitting in front of the computer for several hours in succession might cause boredom, fatigue, or other physical problems. The university campus, in contrast, leaves no chance for this kind of problems, because students are supervised and monitored by faculty members, Meanwhile, their interactions with classmates are constant. It is beneficial for learners to organise teamwork and develop interpersonal relationships.\n\nAs indicated above, under no circumstance can distance learning be taken as a qualified substitute for traditional methods of learning. Learners’ low motivation and commitment, inadequate interaction with teachers and some other inherent problems have made it nearly impossible to replace a traditional class with a virtual class.","phrases":[{"en":"keep abreast of","vi":"theo kịp"},{"en":"state-of-the-art","vi":"hiện đại nhất"},{"en":"self-motivated and self-directed","vi":"có động lực và khả năng tự định hướng"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#075","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People join distance-learning programmes (study material, post, TV,…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-076","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"Some people think that students benefit greatly from going to private secondary schools, but others assert that private secondary schools have a negative impact on the young generation and the society alike. Discuss both views.","answer":"Parents seem to have ongoing preference for a private secondary school, although they have to pay extremely high tuition fees for their children. Despite the fact that a private school is very often associated with quality service, professional teaching staff, competitive courses and excellent facilities, critics are concerned about the harmful effects of private schools on society. The merits and demerits of this argument will be explored below.\n\nUnarguably, private schools outperform public schools based on their more flexible and advanced academic and extracurricular programmes. With this distinguishing advantage, private schools are capable of adjusting their programmes for students of different levels and assisting them to attain their objectives individually. Another remarkable quality of a private school is its proficiency in formulating and promoting different non-academic programmes, such as group sports and outings to foster students’ physical, emotional and social well-being.\n\nPrivate schools are also acclaimed as experts in addressing students’ discipline problems, Keen to consolidate its image as an excellent quality provider, a private school focuses not only on a student's academic performance but also on their demeanour. For this reason, physical fights, drug use, bullying and other behaviour problems are less likely to be seen in private schools. On the other hand, private schools have high entrance requirements and tuition standards, resulting in relative homogeneity of students’ family background. Students are mainly from medium or high income families. Upbringing and strict school discipline jointly contribute to better behaviour of students. It is no wonder that most of private school students are good-mannered and have a positive self-image.\n\nAlthough the position of a private school as a well-qualified education provider is prominent, it benefits some sections of school-age populations only. Because of tuition fees, a private school is accessible only to those who can pay, rather than those who can learn. It has denied most students’ access to quality education, potentially causing the gap between rich and poor to widen.\n\nThe arguments presented above have created a dilemma when people evaluate the effects of a private school on society. On the one hand, the private school is better than the public school <strong class=\"key-phrase\">in many aspects</strong>, such as teaching staff, learning environment and facilities. On the other, it tends to discriminate against students from low income families by maintaining high tuition fees. While teenagers from high income families continue to benefit from their social status, those of a lower class suffer enormously from lack of educational opportunities.","phrases":[{"en":"in many aspects","vi":"ở nhiều khía cạnh"}],"subtype":"Discussion","_displayNo":"#076","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People think that students benefit greatly from going to private secondary…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-077","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"Some people think that teachers should be responsible for teaching students to judge right and wrong and to behave well. Some say that teachers should only teach students about academic subjects. Discuss both views and give your opinion.","answer":"Traditionally, the task of teachers was to use a variety of methods and materials to impart the knowledge of a given field to students. However, this notion has been refuted by many people, who consider it important to integrate other elements in education, such as morality. In my opinion, moral education will become a central part of modern education and teachers should be responsible for correcting students’ behaviour and improving their moral values.\n\nEthics in plain words means studying and analysing right from wrong, which is identical with the objective of education, telling the young generation what is the right thing to do. Without being aware of the distinction between acceptable and unacceptable behaviour, young people become delinquents and criminals, rather than qualified workers and successful individuals. It is particularly true as people are living in a society where violent juvenile crime, teen pregnancy and suicide are becoming worrying problems. There is thus a strong call for linking the modification of young people’s behaviour to the teaching of moral and social values in schools. Teachers are expected to take preventive measures to address misbehaviours, such as substance abuse, focus on the root causes of the problems, such as family violence, and help those who appear troubled. It stops a problem among young people from occurring or recurrence.\n\nEthical principles and moral values have relevance to the order of a society and individual citizens’ quality of life. The young people who are unaware of standards of morality will end up with breaching their duties as law-abiding citizens and ruining the moral values of the society. Nor can they become happy, successful and productive. A good example to support this is that many recent business. frauds, bribery, embezzlement and other illegitimate activities have been found related to some <strong class=\"key-phrase\">well-educated</strong> but unethical people. Despite their strong educational background and high intelligence, they cause damage to enterprises and communities.\n\nEthical education can also help shape the behaviour pattern of individual citizens. Morality is neither a vain promise nor a collection of ideals that appear in writing only. It is reflected in how people respond and act in different social situations, such as whether they habitually or instinctively reserve seats for the elderly and disabled at a bus. When children and young people construct most of their knowledge of the world through social interactions, teachers are in a very good position to impart such knowledge to them. Young people are hence well informed of moral principles, code of conduct and motivated to speak and act in a manner as intended,\n\nAs suggested above, teachers should play a more active role in the moral development of young people, instead of simply translating knowledge of a subject into course materials and imparting it to students. They should pass on good judgement, moral principles and wisdom to students, all contributing to students’ individual life fulfilment and well-being.","phrases":[{"en":"well-educated","vi":"được giáo dục tốt; có học thức"}],"subtype":"Discussion","_displayNo":"#077","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People think that teachers should be responsible for teaching students to…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-078","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"Some people think the government should pay for health care and education, but there is no agreement about whether it is the government’s responsibility. What is your opinion?","answer":"Not surprisingly, health care and education are two areas of government priority in most, if not all, of the countries around the world. However, many tend to see the both areas as citizens’ individual responsibilities. This belief is partly right. The government and the citizens should be jointly responsible for the cost of education and health care service.\n\nThe first point to note is that government funding for education is of great benefit to families with children and the society as a whole. There are occasions on which parents cannot afford the cost of their education and their savings are meagre, compared with the formidable tuition fees being charged by a tertiary institution. Poor academic experience can impair one’s employability and put him or her into <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a seriously disadvantaged position</strong>. Government spending addresses this issue by providing aspiring students with access to a comfortable learning experience. In this knowledge-based society, possibly nothing is more valuable than the access to education.\n\nSimilarly, an individual should receive health care treatments, especially <strong class=\"key-phrase\">lifesaving ones</strong>, whether he or she has the means to pay. Access to health care is a basic human right and a measure to ensure a decent standard of living. In the event of the need for urgent or emergency treatment, government spending enables sufferers to receive immediate health care services. This is the fulfilment of the government's responsibility to its members. Needless to say, health care treatment costs are, in general, unaffordable to low income families. Government’s financial support is therefore required.\n\nDespite these facts, it is immoral that individuals shirk responsibility and try to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">pass all medical costs on to the government</strong>. In view of the fact that the government raises financing primarily from taxpayers’ income, individual’s over-exploitation of a health care system will in fact <strong class=\"key-phrase\">add a heavy burden on</strong> those hardworking and good-hearted citizens. Particular attention should be paid on those people whose health problems are attributed to their poor personal living habits (smoking, drinking, substance use or inactive lifestyle). In such cases, they should not be entitled for public medical services.\n\nAs suggested above, education and healthcare services are of primary importance to citizens, and the government has the responsibility to ensure that those services are available and affordable. However, it is not to say that the government should bear the costs of all healthcare and educational services that the citizens currently enjoy.","phrases":[{"en":"a seriously disadvantaged position","vi":"một vị thế bất lợi nghiêm trọng"},{"en":"lifesaving ones","vi":"những phương pháp điều trị cứu sống"},{"en":"pass all medical costs on to the government","vi":"đẩy toàn bộ chi phí y tế cho chính phủ"},{"en":"add a heavy burden on","vi":"tạo thêm gánh nặng lớn cho"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#078","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People think the government should pay for health care and education, but…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-079","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"Some people who have been successful in the society do not attribute their success to the theoretical knowledge they learned at university. What is your opinion on the factors contributing to one’s achievement?","answer":"People harbour different perceptions of tertiary education. Although higher education is recognised by many as the most important predictor of one’s success, its efficacy has been subject. to long discussion. It is always interesting to note that some people do not owe their success to the knowledge they acquired at university, despite the great effort they ever made in obtaining a qualification. In my opinion, tertiary education itself cannot guarantee one’s success, and there are many other elements combined to mould a successful role model.\n\nKnowledge, an essential element of one’s success, is normally acquired through formal education, but it is not the only approach. A university is home to those teaching professionals who have a firm grasp of a given knowledge area and can impart it to students by various techniques. However, not all the knowledge, experience and skills can be passed on to students by teaching. Experiences and rules of thumb are non-transferable at a traditional classroom, The only way to gain a mastery of them is the full participation in a job.\n\nIn addition to hands-on skills and practical experience, characters can foretell one’s prospects. Society has been polarised as economic and social changes make it more competitive. Those with outstanding <strong class=\"key-phrase\">academic qualifications</strong> are not sought-after as much as before. Employers show interest in other qualities of an applicant, for example, resilience, willpower and adaptability. It is increasingly believed that the most successful are normally those who are most likely to adapt to changes in their world. Some other qualities, such as the ability to work in a hard-working, stressful and ever-changing environment, are viewed as the shared traits of successful people. Running toward success is more of a marathon than of a sprint, Only those persistent, self-motivated and self-directed can eventually attain their objectives.\n\nThere are some other factors, such as opportunities, that play a contributing role in one’s success, but for simplicity’s sake, one does not need to cite all these factors to uphold the assertion that a college degree is not the precondition to personal success. Practical experience, a mastery of different skills and personality suffice to illustrate the complex nature of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">personal achievement</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"academic qualifications","vi":"bằng cấp học thuật"},{"en":"personal achievement","vi":"thành tích cá nhân"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#079","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People who have been successful in the society do not attribute their…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-080","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education: Sport","prompt":"Schools should teach children the academic subjects which have a close relationship with their future careers, so other subjects like music and sports are not important. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"There are many indications that schools have become increasingly vocation-oriented in recent years, with integrating many work-based courses in curriculum. Some academics advocate that sport and music classes should be cancelled in exchange for more academic classes, in an effort to help students beat other jobseekers. This argument has several strong elements that deserve attention.\n\nThe first is that few employers are interested in a job applicant’s performance as music lover or sports fan. Instead, they are keen to assess candidates’ <strong class=\"key-phrase\">academic records</strong> and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">professional skills</strong>. At a time when business grows complex and skill-based, the evidence that candidates have sufficient knowledge relating to their job profession is more capable to attract the eye of recruiters. A student excelling in a subject is far more marketable in the job market than one playing a music instrument adeptly, or displaying talents in a sport.\n\nAnother reason is that students, in most cases, engage themselves in sports or music spontaneously. There is no need to formalise their pastimes, when the amount of time they spend in academic activities is desperately inadequate. Teenagers and young adults have plenty of energy to expend daily. Even when heavily loaded with learning tasks, they exert themselves for outdoors and group activities. They gather for sport activities and concerts, but seldom review their textbooks after school. Given these elements, the top priority for educators is to maximise students’ contact with academic classes at school and to recommend sports and music as extracurricular activities only,\n\nThe above discussion favours a conclusion that sport and music classes should be cancelled so, students are more likely to commit themselves to academic courses, which are more important to, their future employability.","phrases":[{"en":"academic records","vi":"thành tích học tập"},{"en":"professional skills","vi":"kỹ năng nghề nghiệp"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#080","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Schools should teach children the academic subjects which have a close…","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"Education","prompt":"Some people think that it is better to educate boys and girls in separate schools. Others, however, believe that boys and girls benefit more from attending mixed schools. Discuss both these views and give your own opinion.","answer":"Some people believe that boys and girls learn better in separate schools, while others prefer mixed education. Although single-sex schools may reduce certain distractions, I believe mixed schools prepare students more effectively for adult life.\n\nSupporters of separate schools argue that teachers can adapt lessons to different learning patterns and that students may feel less pressure to perform for the opposite sex. In some subjects, girls or boys may also participate more confidently when they are not worried about stereotypes. These schools can therefore create <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a focused academic environment</strong> for some learners.\n\nHowever, the adult world is mixed, and schools should help young people communicate naturally with everyone. In a mixed classroom, students learn to cooperate, challenge stereotypes and judge classmates by ability rather than gender. Problems such as distraction or teasing should be managed through good discipline, not by separating students. Regular contact also helps young people develop <strong class=\"key-phrase\">mutual respect and social confidence</strong>.\n\nIt is also difficult to prove that gender separation itself produces better results. School quality, class size, teacher skill and family support often matter more. A well-run mixed school can address different learning needs through flexible teaching, while avoiding the assumption that all boys or all girls learn in the same way. This is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a more evidence-based approach</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, single-sex education can work well in particular cases, but its advantages are not strong enough to justify broad separation. Mixed schools offer both academic learning and realistic social experience, making them better suited to preparing students for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">study, work and public life</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Education","phrases":[{"en":"a focused academic environment","vi":"môi trường học tập tập trung"},{"en":"mutual respect and social confidence","vi":"sự tôn trọng lẫn nhau và tự tin xã hội"},{"en":"a more evidence-based approach","vi":"một cách tiếp cận dựa trên bằng chứng hơn"},{"en":"study, work and public life","vi":"học tập, công việc và đời sống xã hội"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"discuss","summary":"Single-Sex vs. Co-Educational Schools: Which Is Better?","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-081","_displayNo":"#081","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-082","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education","prompt":"Nowadays, some universities teach graduates practical skills that help them find employment, while others believe that the main function of university is to pursue knowledge for its own sake. What is your opinion?","answer":"Universities have two important roles: they develop knowledge and prepare students for adult working life. In my view, these aims are not in conflict. A strong university education should combine academic understanding with practical skills.\n\nKnowledge for its own sake remains valuable. Subjects such as history, mathematics and philosophy train students to analyse evidence, question assumptions and build logical arguments. These abilities are useful far beyond one job. They also allow universities to conduct research that may have no immediate commercial use but can later produce major social benefits. Reducing higher education to short-term job training would therefore <strong class=\"key-phrase\">narrow the purpose of university</strong>.\n\nAt the same time, graduates need to enter a competitive labour market. Universities should teach students how to communicate clearly, work in teams, solve unfamiliar problems and use relevant technology. Internships, project work and careers advice can help students <strong class=\"key-phrase\">connect theory with practice</strong>. This does not mean that employers should dictate the entire curriculum; rather, practical experience should support serious academic study.\n\nPractical preparation does not require universities to become training centres for a single employer. Research projects, placements, presentations and teamwork can connect theory with real problems while preserving academic depth. Graduates then leave with both specialist knowledge and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">skills that transfer between different careers</strong>, which is particularly valuable as industries change.\n\nIn conclusion, universities should not choose between knowledge and employability. Their best contribution is to give students a deep understanding of a subject while also developing skills that can be transferred to different careers. This balanced approach would produce graduates who are both <strong class=\"key-phrase\">intellectually independent and work-ready</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"narrow the purpose of university","vi":"thu hẹp mục đích của đại học"},{"en":"connect theory with practice","vi":"kết nối lý thuyết với thực tiễn"},{"en":"skills that transfer between different careers","vi":"các kỹ năng có thể chuyển đổi giữa những nghề nghiệp khác nhau"},{"en":"intellectually independent and work-ready","vi":"độc lập về tư duy và sẵn sàng làm việc"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#082","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Some universities offer graduate students skills that assist them to find…","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"Education: Television","prompt":"Some people say that television is useful for education, while others say it is useful only for entertainment. Discuss both views and give your own opinion.","answer":"Television can educate and entertain, and these functions often overlap. In my view, its educational value is significant, but most viewers use it mainly for relaxation. The quality of the programme matters more than the medium itself.\n\nEducational television can make complex subjects easy to understand. Documentaries show places, experiments and historical events that students cannot experience directly. News programmes can also improve public knowledge when they explain issues carefully rather than simply report headlines. For children and adults who have limited access to books or courses, television can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">bring useful knowledge into the home</strong>.\n\nAt the same time, entertainment is the main reason many people switch on the television. Drama, sport and comedy provide a simple way to rest after work. This is not necessarily negative, because good entertainment can reflect social problems, introduce new cultures and encourage discussion. The problem begins when viewers watch passively for many hours or when channels rely on sensational content to hold attention.\n\nThe quality of the programme is therefore more important than the label of education or entertainment. A documentary with accurate evidence can teach effectively, while a badly designed educational show may hold little attention. Broadcasters should combine reliable information with clear storytelling so that learning becomes <strong class=\"key-phrase\">engaging without becoming superficial</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, television is neither purely educational nor purely entertaining. It is a flexible medium whose value depends on programme quality and viewing habits. Broadcasters should produce accurate, engaging content, while viewers should <strong class=\"key-phrase\">choose programmes deliberately</strong> rather than watch without purpose.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Education","phrases":[{"en":"bring useful knowledge into the home","vi":"đưa kiến thức hữu ích vào gia đình"},{"en":"engaging without becoming superficial","vi":"hấp dẫn mà không trở nên hời hợt"},{"en":"choose programmes deliberately","vi":"chủ động lựa chọn chương trình"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"discuss","summary":"Television: Education or Entertainment?","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-083","_displayNo":"#083","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"Education: Music","prompt":"Some say that music, art and drama are as important as other school subjects, especially at the primary level. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Music, art and drama deserve an important place in primary education. They should not replace literacy, mathematics or science, but they support children’s development in ways that academic subjects alone cannot.\n\nCreative subjects help young children express ideas before they have the vocabulary to explain them fully. Drawing, singing and acting also develop concentration, coordination and confidence. A child who performs in a short play must listen to others, remember a sequence and manage nervousness. These are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">transferable skills</strong> that support learning across the curriculum.\n\nThe arts also make school more inclusive. Some pupils who struggle with written tests may show strong visual, musical or practical ability. Giving these children a chance to succeed can improve motivation and attendance. In addition, creative activities introduce students to their own culture and to unfamiliar traditions, helping them develop <strong class=\"key-phrase\">curiosity and cultural awareness</strong>.\n\nCreative subjects can also support achievement elsewhere. Music develops attention to pattern, drama improves speaking confidence, and art trains close observation. These benefits do not mean that every child must become a performer. They show that a balanced primary curriculum can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">develop abilities that standard tests often miss</strong>.\n\nIt can also improve attendance and motivation by giving children who struggle with written tests another way to participate successfully in school life.\n\nIn conclusion, primary schools should treat the arts as a core part of a balanced education, while still protecting enough time for basic academic skills. The aim is not to train every child as an artist, but to use creative work to build confident, observant and cooperative learners.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Education","phrases":[{"en":"transferable skills","vi":"kỹ năng có thể áp dụng trong nhiều lĩnh vực"},{"en":"curiosity and cultural awareness","vi":"sự tò mò và nhận thức văn hóa"},{"en":"develop abilities that standard tests often miss","vi":"phát triển những năng lực mà các bài kiểm tra tiêu chuẩn thường bỏ sót"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"opinion","summary":"The Importance of Music, Art, and Drama in Primary School","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-084","_displayNo":"#084","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-085","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"University education","prompt":"Some people believe the aim of university education is to help graduates get better jobs. Others believe there are much wider benefits of university education for both individuals and society. Discuss both views and give your opinion.","answer":"The purpose of university education is often debated. Some regard it primarily as professional preparation, whereas others emphasise its broader intellectual and social value. Although employability is an essential outcome, I believe universities serve society best when they combine vocational relevance with the development of independent judgement.\n\nThose who prioritise employment have a strong practical case. Higher education requires substantial investment from students, families and governments, so graduates reasonably expect <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a measurable return on that investment</strong>. Degree programmes can provide specialist knowledge, professional accreditation and access to occupations that would otherwise remain closed. In fields such as medicine, engineering and law, universities also protect the public by ensuring that entrants meet rigorous standards. From this perspective, a course that ignores labour-market realities may leave students heavily indebted but poorly equipped for work.\n\nHowever, reducing university to job training would overlook its wider contribution. Students learn to evaluate evidence, challenge assumptions and communicate across cultural or disciplinary boundaries. These capacities help individuals <strong class=\"key-phrase\">navigate complex public and private decisions</strong> long after specific technical knowledge becomes outdated. Universities also generate research, sustain cultural institutions and create spaces in which contested ideas can be examined rather than merely repeated. A society with citizens who can reason critically is better able to resist misinformation and hold powerful institutions accountable.\n\nIn my view, the two purposes are not mutually exclusive. Programmes should maintain academic depth while incorporating placements, collaborative projects and transferable skills. This approach would <strong class=\"key-phrase\">bridge the gap between scholarship and professional practice</strong> without turning every subject into narrow occupational training.\n\nIn conclusion, better employment is a legitimate aim of university education, but it is not the only one. The most valuable institutions prepare graduates both to earn a living and to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">participate intelligently in civic life</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"a measurable return on that investment","vi":"lợi ích có thể đo lường được từ khoản đầu tư đó"},{"en":"navigate complex public and private decisions","vi":"xử lý những quyết định công và tư phức tạp"},{"en":"bridge the gap between scholarship and professional practice","vi":"thu hẹp khoảng cách giữa học thuật và thực hành nghề nghiệp"},{"en":"participate intelligently in civic life","vi":"tham gia đời sống công dân một cách sáng suốt"}],"subtype":"Discuss both views + opinion · Nguồn đề: IELTS Buddy","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#085","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"The wider aims of university education","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-086","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Education","title":"Education: Unemployment","prompt":"Today, more school leavers are unable to find jobs. Discuss the causes of rising unemployment among young adults and suggest any solutions.","answer":"Rising unemployment among school leavers is caused mainly by <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a lack of practical experience</strong> and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a mismatch between education and labour-market needs</strong>. The problem can be reduced if schools, employers and governments share responsibility for the transition from study to work.\n\nMany young applicants leave school with theoretical knowledge but little evidence that they can use it in a workplace. Employers often prefer experienced candidates because training a beginner takes time and money. At the same time, some students specialise in areas with limited demand, while sectors such as construction, healthcare and technology struggle to recruit people with the right technical skills. Unrealistic expectations can add to the problem when graduates reject entry-level opportunities because the pay, status or location is not ideal.\n\nEducation should respond more closely to actual employment patterns. Schools and colleges can work with local employers to update courses, provide work placements and teach practical skills such as communication, problem-solving and digital literacy. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">Realistic career guidance</strong> is also essential so that students understand salary levels, recruitment requirements and possible training routes before they leave education.\n\nEmployers should create more <strong class=\"key-phrase\">paid apprenticeships</strong> and genuine junior positions. Governments can support this by offering temporary tax incentives for firms that train young workers, while requiring clear standards so that subsidies do not become a source of cheap labour. Short vocational programmes can also help unemployed graduates move into sectors with staff shortages.\n\nIn conclusion, youth unemployment is not simply the result of a weak economy. It also reflects limited experience, unsuitable training and poor information. Better coordination between education and employment would give school leavers <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a more realistic route into stable work</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"a lack of practical experience","vi":"sự thiếu kinh nghiệm thực tế"},{"en":"a mismatch between education and labour-market needs","vi":"sự lệch pha giữa giáo dục và nhu cầu thị trường lao động"},{"en":"realistic career guidance","vi":"định hướng nghề nghiệp thực tế"},{"en":"paid apprenticeships","vi":"các chương trình học nghề có trả lương"},{"en":"a more realistic route into stable work","vi":"một lộ trình thực tế hơn để có việc làm ổn định"}],"subtype":"Causes / Solutions","_displayNo":"#086","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Today, more school leavers are unable to find jobs.","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"Education","prompt":"Today people are travelling more than ever before. Why is this the case? What are the benefits of travelling for the traveller?","answer":"People travel more than in the past because journeys have become cheaper, faster and easier to arrange. Higher incomes and flexible working patterns have also made travel possible for a wider group of people. Overall, this trend brings substantial personal and economic benefits.\n\nLow-cost airlines, online booking and improved transport networks have reduced both the price and difficulty of travel. Social media also exposes people to destinations that they might never have considered. In addition, many people now study, work or have relatives abroad, so international travel has become <strong class=\"key-phrase\">part of ordinary life</strong> rather than a rare luxury.\n\nTravel can broaden people’s understanding by placing them in unfamiliar environments. Visitors learn how others live, communicate and solve everyday problems. Tourism also creates employment in transport, accommodation and local services. When managed well, it can provide income for rural areas and help fund the protection of historic sites and natural attractions.\n\nHowever, these benefits depend on responsible behaviour. Overcrowding, pollution and rising housing costs can harm local communities. Governments should therefore control development, improve public transport and ensure that tourism revenue reaches residents. With sensible planning, travel can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">support cultural exchange and local prosperity</strong> without overwhelming destinations.\n\nTravel has also become easier because information is widely available. People can compare prices, book accommodation and navigate unfamiliar places from a phone. At the same time, employers and universities increasingly value international experience. A well-planned trip can therefore <strong class=\"key-phrase\">combine personal enjoyment with practical learning</strong>, rather than serving only as a break from routine.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Education","phrases":[{"en":"part of ordinary life","vi":"một phần của đời sống thường ngày"},{"en":"support cultural exchange and local prosperity","vi":"hỗ trợ giao lưu văn hóa và sự thịnh vượng địa phương"},{"en":"combine personal enjoyment with practical learning","vi":"kết hợp niềm vui cá nhân với việc học hỏi thực tế"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"two-part","summary":"Why People Travel More: Education and Benefits","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-087","_displayNo":"#087","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-088","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Environment","title":"Environment","prompt":"Explain some of the ways in which humans are damaging the environment. What can governments do to address these problems? What can individual people do?","answer":"Humans are responsible for a variety of environmental problems, but we can also take steps to reduce the damage that we are causing to the planet. This essay will discuss environmental problems and the measures that governments and individuals can take to address these problems.\n\nTwo of the biggest threats to the environment are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">air pollution and waste</strong>. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">Gas emissions</strong> from factories and exhaust fumes from vehicles lead to global warming, which may have a devastating effect on the planet in the future. As the human population increases, we are also producing ever greater quantities of waste, which contaminates the earth and pollutes rivers and oceans.\n\nGovernments could certainly make more effort to reduce air pollution. They could introduce laws to limit emissions from factories or to force companies to use <strong class=\"key-phrase\">renewable energy</strong> from <strong class=\"key-phrase\">solar, wind or water power</strong>. They could also impose “green taxes’ on drivers and airline companies. In this way, people would be encouraged to use public transport and to take fewer flights abroad, therefore reducing emissions.\n\nIndividuals should also take responsibility for the impact they have on the environment. They can take public transport rather than driving, choose products with less packaging, and recycle as much as possible. Most supermarkets now provide reusable bags for shoppers as well as “banks’ for recycling glass, plastic and paper in their car parks. By reusing and recycling, we can help to reduce waste.\n\nIn conclusion, both national governments and individuals must play their part in looking after the environment.","phrases":[{"en":"air pollution and waste","vi":"ô nhiễm không khí và rác thải"},{"en":"Gas emissions","vi":"khí thải"},{"en":"renewable energy","vi":"năng lượng tái tạo"},{"en":"solar, wind or water power","vi":"năng lượng mặt trời, sức gió và sức nước"}],"subtype":"Causes / Effects / Solutions · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#088","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Environmental damage: shared responsibility","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-089","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Environment","title":"Environment","prompt":"Environmental problems are serious in many countries. It means that the only possible way to protect the environment is at an international level. To what extent do you agree or disagree on this hypothesis?","answer":"Globally, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">environmental degradation</strong> has been recognised as one of the main challenges that people have to overcome in the 21st century. The rapid deterioration of the environment is believed to impose a severe threat on people’s survival in the years ahead, if not solved effectively. In addressing this issue, countries worldwide should join forces and make a concerted effort, instead of working individually for inconsistent targets.\n\nThe first point to support international cooperation is that the impact of an environmental problem can be on the global scale. Common knowledge is that people live in a global environment and share natural resources and survive on the same biosphere. The interdependencies of ecosystems and the transport of pollutants are the main characteristics of the world. For instance, a stream or lake in a country can be affected by pesticides released from neighbouring croplands, lawns and gardens and by pollutants emitted thousands of miles away. Likewise, the depletion of a natural resource (such as deforestation) in one nation can have environmental and economic ramifications in many other countries.\n\nAnother benefit obtained from international cooperation is facilitating the exchange of goods, technology, know-how and capital. It is crucial for hammering out the best and quickest solution to the problem. Environmental problems are mainly found in underdeveloped countries, where industrial or agricultural developments are placed ahead of environmental protection. With a clear intent to restore the damaged environment, those countries have difficulties in making headway, in the absence of facilities or technologies. They need the support from the global community, especially those industrialised countries that have achieved remarkable progress in this field. By sharing experience in environmental management, countries can tackle problems with greater efficiency and at lower costs.\n\nTo summarise, cooperation between countries is inevitable in this global campaign, not only because the ecosystem is a unified mechanism but also because international engagement can make optimal use of financial and human resources. By collaborating with each other, countries can protect the global environment while using the fewest possible resources.","phrases":[{"en":"environmental degradation","vi":"suy thoái môi trường"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#089","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Environmental problems are serious in many countries.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-090","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Environment","title":"Environment","prompt":"Some industrialised countries have serious environmental problems. The damage to the environment is an inevitable result when a country tends to improve the standard of living. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Economic development can place heavy pressure on the environment, but serious damage is not an unavoidable price of a higher standard of living. I disagree with the view that pollution and resource loss must accompany progress. The outcome depends on the energy, transport and industrial policies a country chooses.\n\nRapid growth often increases electricity use, construction, traffic and consumption. If this expansion depends on coal, inefficient factories and weak regulation, air and water quality will deteriorate. Poorer governments may also prioritise immediate jobs and tax revenue over long-term environmental protection. These pressures explain why industrialisation has caused severe pollution in many countries.\n\nHowever, development also gives societies the money and technology needed to solve these problems. Cleaner power, efficient public transport and strict emissions standards can allow incomes to rise while pollution falls. Governments can price carbon, protect forests and require companies to pay for the damage they cause. Investment in insulation and renewable energy may even reduce household costs, so environmental policy can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">support rather than obstruct prosperity</strong>.\n\nPublic reporting is equally important: when emissions and health effects are measured openly, voters and investors can reward cleaner choices and challenge industries that transfer their costs to society. This also makes environmental performance easier to compare across sectors and over time.\n\nIn conclusion, environmental harm is a risk of badly managed growth, not an inevitable result of improving living standards. Countries should measure progress through health, resource security and quality of life as well as income. With firm regulation and clean investment, they can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">raise living standards without repeating past mistakes</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"support rather than obstruct prosperity","vi":"hỗ trợ thay vì cản trở sự thịnh vượng"},{"en":"raise living standards without repeating past mistakes","vi":"nâng cao mức sống mà không lặp lại sai lầm trong quá khứ"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#090","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Industrialised countries have serious environmental problems.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-091","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Environment","title":"Environment","prompt":"It is said that the best way to solve the world’s environmental problems is to increase the price of fuel. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"The burning of fossil fuels is universally recognised as the largest source of emissions of greenhouse gases in the world and one of the key factors responsible for global warming. When there is a growing concern about the destructive effects of global warming and other environmental problems, some people argue that the best approach to deal with such problems is to increase fuel prices, assuming that it will lead directly to the drop in car use. This approach is productive <strong class=\"key-phrase\">to some extent</strong>, but some other measures should be given equal consideration.\n\nFirst, car use alone does not make up the entire consumption of petrol, although people’s obsession with car use contributes greatly to greenhouse gas emission. Petrol is intended for other applications too, such as electricity generation, the daily running of equipment and machinery for industrial and agricultural purposes. People are not surprised to see that the appliances used by many families are powered by petrol as well. Therefore, when it comes to reducing greenhouse <strong class=\"key-phrase\">gas emissions</strong>, people should take different methods simultaneously, instead of relying on any single method only.\n\nPeople should meanwhile recognise the fact that the demand for petrol is generally inelastic, at least in the short run. The consumption of petrol would not vary significantly according to the fluctuation of petrol price. To such a high degree have people relied on petrol in their daily lives that they cannot cut petrol use immediately. Some people might argue that using public transport is an alternative, but notably, public transport itself is a large producer of carbon dioxide. Going on foot or by bike is clean, but not preferred by many people, who are extremely time conscious.\n\nTherefore, the effort to reduce greenhouse gases emission by curbing car use cannot achieve any immediate outcome unless sufficient time is given. Over a period of years, petrol consumption is very likely to drop, when households realise that fuels represent an increasing proportion of expenditure. People might turn to fuel-efficient cars or reduce non-essential trips, both resulting in the drop in petrol use, Car manufacturers are forced to enlarge research and development investment in producing hybrid cars or cars powered by renewable clean energy sources, a cure-all for car emission problems.\n\nIn conclusion, imposing petrol tax is neither the main nor the only solution to environmental problems that people are struggling to solve, although the utilisation of fossil fuels, particularly petrol, is the largest source of emissions. Some other methods should be taken into consideration as well.","phrases":[{"en":"to some extent","vi":"ở một mức độ nào đó"},{"en":"gas emissions","vi":"khí thải"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#091","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"It is said that the best way to solve the world’s environmental problems is…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-092","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Environment","title":"Environment","prompt":"One's character traits are strongly influenced by the place where he or she grew up. Discuss the impacts of an urban environment and those of a rural environment on a child’s character development.","answer":"It is well acknowledged that healthy growth conditions in early life are the prerequisite of a child’s positive growth patterns. For this reason, some people are concerned about the impacts of living in rural or urban areas on a child’s character development. Below is an outline of the potential impacts of a rural or urban environment on a child’s personality and behaviour.\n\nPoverty is one of the main problems in the countryside, either entrenched or escalating, leading directly to poor <strong class=\"key-phrase\">living standards</strong>. Because of parents’ limited disposable income, children in rural areas are less likely to receive adequate child care or comfortable housing than their urban counterparts. These conditions are crucial to children’s physical health and emotional well-being. Likewise, the soaring abuse and neglect rates in rural families negatively influence children’s character -building: Children in rural areas are ready outlets for their parents, who feel frustrated and depressed in maintaining a standard of living. Raised in an environment where violence is normal and consequences of violence are ignored, children might grow up to be individuals who are less conscious of the rights of others (including family members and friends) and more likely to use violence.\n\nAnother problem is literacy. Low standards of education, which seem to be a defining characteristic of rural areas, are attributed to a mixture of factors—lack of public schools, children’s early involvement in income-generating activities and inadequate awareness of education. It is quite clear that income disparity between urban and rural families leads to the difference in the access to education, which has a bearing on children’s characters. While a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">well-educated</strong> child is confident, broad-minded, creative and cultivated, a poorly-educated child is inhibited, narrow-minded or even boorish.\n\nIn spite of the fact that urban children can receive an excellent education, it does not automatically mean that they will grow up without character flaws. In fact, it seems that they are more susceptible to bad habits and social evils. Illegal substances are more common among urban juveniles than among rural adolescents. Uniformity and lifelessness of outdoor environments is another problem. Garden settings, which are believed to have a healing power for people living under great pressure, are rare in a metropolitan area. By comparison, children living in the country are more likely to access outdoor play, a recreation activity that can improve moods and prevent feelings of isolation.\n\nBased on the points outlined above, I believe that environment has a direct bearing on children’s character development. Poverty and illiteracy are two common features of rural areas and can contribute to children’s negative characters. By contrast, children from urban areas are more likely to fee! pressured and isolated, which can trigger erratic behaviour.","phrases":[{"en":"living standards","vi":"mức sống"},{"en":"well-educated","vi":"được giáo dục tốt; có học thức"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#092","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"One's character traits are strongly influenced by the place where he or she…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-093","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Environment","title":"Environment","prompt":"Some people believe that air travel should be restricted because it causes serious pollution and will use up the world’s resources. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"The environmental impact of air travel has attracted growing attention as more people use planes for work and leisure. Some therefore argue that restrictions should be imposed on flying. There are valid concerns behind this view, although a complete restriction would be neither practical nor necessary.\n\nThe first concern is that aircraft are responsible for a significant share of air pollution. Planes consume large quantities of fuel while taking off, landing and taxiing, and they produce emissions at high altitude. Some might suggest that air travel is the only suitable <strong class=\"key-phrase\">mode of transport</strong> for long-distance journeys. However, trains can often provide an effective alternative on shorter routes while using less energy and causing less pollution.\n\nAircraft also create noise pollution. Although the precise impact of noise on daily life is difficult to measure, persistent exposure can increase anxiety and annoyance. For people living near airports or beneath flight paths, this noise can become a serious and continuing disturbance.\n\nNevertheless, these problems do not mean that air travel should be heavily restricted. A more balanced response is to make aviation cleaner and more efficient. For example, airlines can replace older engines with cleaner models, improve flight planning and use fuller aircraft so that more passengers are carried with the same amount of fuel. Governments can also support high-speed rail where it is a realistic substitute.\n\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">In light of</strong> these considerations, the environmental damage caused by aviation deserves serious attention. However, targeted technological improvements and sensible transport policies are preferable to broad restrictions on air travel.","phrases":[{"en":"mode of transport","vi":"phương thức vận tải"},{"en":"In light of","vi":"xét theo; dựa trên"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#093","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People believe that air travel should be restricted because it causes…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-094","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Environment","title":"Environment: Books and reading","prompt":"Some people believe that public libraries should spend money on digital media, such as software, DVDs and videos, rather than books. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"A library, generally, refers to a place storing and managing books that can be booked or borrowed. In these years, there is a trend toward <strong class=\"key-phrase\">integrating new technologies</strong>, such as DVDs and videos, in libraries. Opponents argue that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the emphasis should be placed on</strong> providing books, rather than on increasing modern equipment. Modernisation is, in my opinion, an inevitable tendency, although the enlargement of a library's reserve <strong class=\"key-phrase\">should not be treated lightly</strong>.\n\nOne of the main advantages of using computers or other hi-tech products is improving efficiency. By recording information of books such as titles, authors, dates of publishing, or even summaries in a computer system, e-library allows readers to find a book promptly. Likewise, librarians are more able to store, seek out and manage books. Moreover, with the central network connecting libraries throughout a country or worldwide, a library user can easily locate a book in a library wherever it is.\n\nMeanwhile, one should note that e-books have become increasingly popular, increasing the likelihood that e-library will sooner or later take the place of a conventional library. Compared with paper books, e-books not only use much less space but also give readers more enjoyment in reading. For example, readers can customise their viewing experience easily by adjusting font, size and style of, characters, accessing the books that have the same subject, and modifying screen contract, and so forth. E-books appeal to young users or children specifically because of its remarkable ability to demonstrate or explain a subject vividly via pictures, videos or even movies.\n\nThe importance of updating the facilities is therefore evident, but it should be stressed that the primary responsibility of libraries is to provide as many books as possible to the public. A good library is judged not by the extent to which its facilities are modernised, but by how much information it can supply. The more books the library can make available, the more visitors it can attract. At the international level, nearly every distinguished library gains its fame by providing a vast collection and a delicate selection of books.\n\nAs suggested above, the library should focus not only on the instalment of modern equipment, but also on purchasing more books. The top priority for a library is to maximise the reserve of books and make the resource available.","phrases":[{"en":"integrating new technologies","vi":"tích hợp các công nghệ mới"},{"en":"the emphasis should be placed on","vi":"nên đặt trọng tâm vào"},{"en":"should not be treated lightly","vi":"không nên bị xem nhẹ"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#094","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People think that public libraries should only provide books and should not…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-095","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Environment","title":"Environment: Water resources","prompt":"Water resources around the world are falling deficient. Analyse the possible reasons and provide your suggestions.","answer":"Access to water is vital to every living creature on the planet. Despite the fact that approximately two thirds of the earth surface is covered with all forms of water bodies, countries worldwide are faced with different levels of water shortages, Some reasons can be cited to explain the emergence of this problem.\n\nA trigger for a water crisis is people’s lack of knowledge of the value of water. Given the ready availability of water in many countries, people tend to believe that the reserve of water in the world is infinite. Notwithstanding the increased expenditure on water supply, water is perceived as a cheap commodity by many families. Many people see water as a perpetual resource. For this reason, the unbridled use of water is commonplace, accelerating the exhaustion of this valuable resource.\n\nRapid population growth is another force contributing to the water crisis. Not only does it reduce the amount of water available for manufacture, farming and households, but also has a profound effect on the sustainability of aquatic ecosystems. Massive urban and industrial growth fuels unprecedented demands, often <strong class=\"key-phrase\">at the expense of</strong> aquatic ecosystems. Many water resources are not replenished before being reused and depleted.\n\nHuman-induced pollution is worthy of concern as well, a factor regarded by many as <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the root cause of</strong> the rapid loss of drinkable water. The untreated discharge of various pollutants such as heavy metals, organic toxins, oils and solids in water bodies is believed to have severe impacts. Industrialisation, meanwhile, results in abnormal climate and biological destruction. While some areas have become barren, other areas are hit by floods. Floods ravage everything, including reservoirs, dams and canals. The water supply problem will intensify.\n\nAs noted above, the steady loss of water is attributable to inappropriate usage, population growth and pollution. to tackle the above-mentioned problems, one can adopt various approaches, besides the existing strategies, such as restoration of ecosystems, rainwater harvest. New technologies can help ease water shortages, by tackling pollution and making used water recyclable. In agriculture, water use can be made far more efficient by introducing new farming techniques (e. g., drip irrigation). Drought-resistant plants can help cut the amount of water needed.","phrases":[{"en":"at the expense of","vi":"đánh đổi bằng / gây tổn hại đến"},{"en":"the root cause of","vi":"nguyên nhân gốc rễ của"}],"subtype":"Problems / Solutions","_displayNo":"#095","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Water resources around the world are falling deficient.","band":"8.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-096","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Equality","title":"Equality","prompt":"In many countries, a small number of people earn extremely high salaries. Some people believe that this is good for the country, but others think that governments should not allow salaries above a certain level. Discuss both these views and give your own opinion.","answer":"People have different views about whether governments should <strong class=\"key-phrase\">introduce a maximum wage</strong>. While in some ways it may seem reasonable to allow people to earn as much as companies are willing to pay, I personally believe that employee remuneration should be capped at a certain level.\n\nThere are various reasons why it might be considered beneficial to allow people to be paid extremely high salaries. If companies offer <strong class=\"key-phrase\">excellent pay packages</strong>, they can attract the most talented people in their fields to work for them. For example, technology companies like Google are able to employ the best programmers because of the huge sums that they are willing to pay. Furthermore, these well-paid employees are likely to be highly motivated to work hard and therefore drive their businesses successfully. In theory, this should result in a thriving economy and increased tax revenues, which means that paying high salaries benefits everyone.\n\nHowever, I agree with those who argue that there should be a maximum wage. By introducing a limit on earnings, the pay-gap between bosses and employees can be reduced. Currently, the difference between normal and top salaries is huge, and this can demotivate workers who feel that the situation is unfair. With lower executive salaries, it might become feasible to introduce higher minimum wages, and everybody would be better off. One possible consequence of greater equality could be that poverty and crime rates fall because the general population will experience an improved standard of living.\n\nIn conclusion, it seems to me that it would be better, on balance, for governments to set a limit on the wages of the highest earners in society.","phrases":[{"en":"introduce a maximum wage","vi":"áp dụng mức lương tối đa"},{"en":"excellent pay packages","vi":"gói lương thưởng hấp dẫn"}],"subtype":"Discuss both views + opinion · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#096","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Capping extremely high salaries","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-097","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Equality","title":"Equality","prompt":"In recent years, there has been growing interest in the relationship between equality and personal achievement. Some people believe that individuals can achieve more in egalitarian societies. Others believe that high levels of personal achievement are possible only if individuals are free to succeed or fail according to their individual merits. What is your view of the relationship between equality and personal success?","answer":"In my opinion, an egalitarian society is one in which everyone has the same rights and the same opportunities. I completely agree that people can achieve more in this kind of society.\n\nEducation is an important factor with regard to personal success in life. I believe that all children should <strong class=\"key-phrase\">have access to</strong> free schooling, and higher education should be either free or affordable for all those who chose to pursue a university degree. In a society without free schooling or affordable higher education, only children and young adults from wealthier families would have access to the best learning opportunities, and they would therefore be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">better prepared for</strong> the job market. This kind of inequality would ensure the success of some but harm the prospects of others.\n\nI would argue that equal rights and opportunities are not in conflict with people’s freedom to succeed or fail. In other words, equality does not mean that people lose their motivation to succeed, or that they are not allowed to fail. On the contrary, I believe that most people would feel more motivated to work hard and reach their potential if they thought that they lived in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a fair society</strong>. Those who did not make the same effort would know that they had wasted their opportunity. Inequality, on the other hand, would be more likely to demotivate people because they would know that the odds of success were stacked in favour of those from privileged backgrounds.\n\nIn conclusion, it seems to me that there is a positive relationship between equality and personal success.","phrases":[{"en":"have access to","vi":"được tiếp cận với"},{"en":"better prepared for","vi":"được chuẩn bị tốt hơn cho"},{"en":"a fair society","vi":"một xã hội công bằng"}],"subtype":"Agree / Disagree · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#097","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Equality and personal achievement","band":"9.0"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"Family: Children","prompt":"There is an increasing trend around the world of married couples deciding not to have children. Discuss the advantages and disadvantages for couples who decide to do this.","answer":"More married couples are choosing not to have children. This decision can give adults greater freedom and financial security, but it may also create personal and social disadvantages. On balance, the effects depend on the couple’s circumstances and the scale of the trend.\n\nFor individuals, remaining child-free can reduce financial pressure and allow more time for careers, relationships and personal interests. Raising a child requires substantial money, energy and long-term responsibility. Some people also decide that they cannot provide the stable home they would want for a family. In such cases, choosing not to become parents is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a responsible personal decision</strong> rather than a selfish one.\n\nThe disadvantages are less predictable. Some couples may later regret the decision or feel isolated in old age, although having children does not guarantee support. At a national level, a very low birth rate can shrink the future workforce and increase the cost of pensions and healthcare. Governments may then need immigration, later retirement or stronger family support policies to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">maintain a balanced population</strong>.\n\nThe wider social effect should also be considered. In countries with ageing populations, fewer births can reduce the future workforce and increase pressure on pensions and care services. This does not justify forcing couples to have children, but it shows why governments need family-friendly housing, childcare and employment policies that make parenthood <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a genuine choice rather than a financial penalty</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, couples should be free to decide whether parenthood suits them. The personal advantages can be considerable, but widespread childlessness may create demographic challenges. Policy should make raising children more affordable without pressuring people into parenthood.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Family","phrases":[{"en":"a responsible personal decision","vi":"một quyết định cá nhân có trách nhiệm"},{"en":"maintain a balanced population","vi":"duy trì cơ cấu dân số cân bằng"},{"en":"a genuine choice rather than a financial penalty","vi":"một lựa chọn thực sự thay vì một gánh nặng tài chính"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"advdis","summary":"Childless by Choice: The Growing Trend","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-098","_displayNo":"#098","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"Family: Children","prompt":"In modern times, children are spending less time with their families and more time with their friends. Why has this change occurred? Do you think parents should force their children to spend more time at home?","answer":"Many children now spend less time with their families and more time with friends. This change is partly caused by longer school days, digital communication and parents’ working hours. It can support independence, but excessive distance from family may weaken guidance and emotional security.\n\nFriendships are important because children need to learn how to cooperate with people of their own age. Through games, study and disagreement, they develop communication skills and a sense of identity outside the home. Older children in particular benefit from having friends who understand the same pressures and interests. This can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">build confidence and social independence</strong>.\n\nHowever, family contact remains essential. Parents usually provide long-term support, set boundaries and notice changes in behaviour that friends may miss. If children spend most of their free time online or away from home, family members may stop discussing school, relationships and personal worries. This can leave young people more exposed to peer pressure and unreliable advice.\n\nParents should respond by protecting regular family time rather than imposing constant control. Shared meals, weekend activities and limits on late-night socialising can maintain connection while respecting a teenager’s growing independence. Forced isolation from friends is likely to create resentment, whereas <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reliable routines and open conversation</strong> are more likely to bring children home willingly.\n\nIn conclusion, spending time with friends is a normal and valuable part of growing up, but it should not replace regular family interaction. Shared meals, planned activities and open conversation can help families <strong class=\"key-phrase\">maintain close relationships as children become more independent</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Family","phrases":[{"en":"build confidence and social independence","vi":"xây dựng sự tự tin và tính độc lập xã hội"},{"en":"reliable routines and open conversation","vi":"những thói quen ổn định và sự trò chuyện cởi mở"},{"en":"maintain close relationships as children become more independent","vi":"duy trì quan hệ gần gũi khi trẻ ngày càng độc lập"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"two-part","summary":"Children Spending More Time with Friends: Why and What Should Parents Do?","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-099","_displayNo":"#099","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-100","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Festivals","title":"Festivals","prompt":"Most people have forgotten the meaning behind traditional or religious festivals; during festival periods, people nowadays only want to enjoy themselves. To what extent do you agree or disagree with this opinion?","answer":"Some people argue that we no longer remember <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the original meaning of</strong> festivals, and that most of us treat them as opportunities to have fun. While I agree that enjoyment seems to be the priority during festival times, I do not agree that people have forgotten what these festivals mean.\n\nOn the one hand, religious and traditional festivals have certainly become times for celebration. In the UK, Christmas is a good example of a festival period when people are most concerned with shopping, giving and receiving presents, decorating their homes and enjoying traditional meals with their families. Most people look forward to Christmas as a holiday period, rather than a time to practise religion. Similar behaviour can be seen during non-religious festivals, such as Bonfire Night. People associate this occasion with making fires, watching firework displays, and perhaps going to large events in local parks; in other words, enjoyment is people’s primary goal.\n\nHowever, I disagree with the idea that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the underlying meaning of</strong> such festivals has been forgotten. In UK primary schools, children learn in detail about the religious reasons for celebrating Christmas, Easter and a variety of festivals in other religions. For example, in late December, children sing Christmas songs which have a religious content, and they may even perform nativity plays telling the story of Jesus’ birth. Families also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">play a role in</strong> passing knowledge of religious festivals’ deeper significance on to the next generation. The same is true for festivals that have a historical background, such as Bonfire Night or Halloween, in the sense that people generally learn the stories behind these occasions at an early age. In conclusion, although people mainly want to enjoy themselves during festivals, I believe that they are still aware of the reasons for these celebrations.","phrases":[{"en":"the original meaning of","vi":"ý nghĩa nguyên bản của"},{"en":"the underlying meaning of","vi":"ý nghĩa sâu xa của"},{"en":"play a role in","vi":"đóng vai trò trong"}],"subtype":"Agree / Disagree · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#100","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"The meaning of traditional festivals","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-101","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"General","title":"General: Advertising","prompt":"Advertising encourages customers to buy in quantity not in quality. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Living in the information age, people are bombarded with substantial daily doses of advertising in multiple media. The argument that advertising, with its overwhelming power, leads to consumers’ impulsive purchase has been accepted by more and more people. Consumers are encouraged by advertisements to purchase products in quantity without paying heed to quality. This allegation is flawed, as far as Tam concerned.\n\nThe first fact to note is that despite the strength of advertising, viewers remain as decision makers. They gather information from advertisements based on their own interest, While some people focus on quality, others are concerned with price. Likewise, advertisements stress different aspects of a product, either quality or price, which is determined by contexts. Consumers are now desensitised to the information delivered by commercials and become increasingly cautious. Quality is, in most cases, a primary concern to them. Even those most loyal users of advertising are now concentrated on product quality, believing that neither pricing nor advertising is an effective facilitator of sales and consumers’ satisfaction with quality is the key to repeat purchases.\n\nPrice is perhaps an inducement used by marketers to trigger sales, but other elements, such as product package, functions, after-sales service and warranty, appear to gain in importance. Advertising informs people of more choices, allowing them to make a buying decision according to their needs and favour a product for different reasons, either quality or price cuts. Needless to say, people have become more circumspect than ever before and more prone to the interaction of other factors, such as the advice of their friends, past experience, current knowledge and physiological state.\n\nIt is also necessary to draw a line between the concept of marketing and that of advertising. Advertising alone is not able to contribute high sales and the link between advertising and “product, usage is in fact not clear. In its broadest sense, advertising is merely a means of generating demand in society by offering specific information on a product or service in a persuasive format. It is similar to sales promotion, package sales, low-pricing strategy and other marketing techniques. Advertising simply conveys the message relating to price, rather than creating this message.\n\nThe facts outlined above, when taken together, are in favour of a view that consumers take in the information delivered by an advertisement differently, and they are influenced by a variety of factors and driven by forces in a decision making process. Quality is of concern to them in most cases, instead of price.\n\nOverall, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a balanced approach</strong> is more likely to create <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a long-term benefit</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"a balanced approach","vi":"một cách tiếp cận cân bằng"},{"en":"a long-term benefit","vi":"một lợi ích lâu dài"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#101","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Advertising encourages customers to buy in quantity not in quality.","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"General","prompt":"In recent years, there has been a rise in the popularity of second-hand clothing amongst the younger generation. Why is this happening? Do you think it's a positive or negative development?","answer":"Second-hand clothing has become increasingly popular among young people. The main reasons are lower prices, environmental concern and the desire to find distinctive items. I see this as a largely positive development.\n\nUsed clothes are often much cheaper than new products, which matters to students and young workers with limited budgets. Online platforms have also made buying and selling simple. At the same time, vintage shops offer styles that are not available in ordinary chain stores, allowing buyers to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">develop a more individual appearance</strong>.\n\nThe environmental benefit is equally important. Producing new clothes uses water, energy and raw materials, while fast fashion encourages people to discard items quickly. Reusing garments keeps them in circulation for longer and reduces waste. Although second-hand shopping cannot solve every environmental problem in the fashion industry, it can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reduce demand for disposable clothing</strong>.\n\nThere are minor concerns about quality, hygiene and misleading online descriptions, but these can be managed through clear information and return policies. In conclusion, the growth of second-hand fashion is positive because it makes clothing affordable, supports personal choice and encourages more responsible consumption.\n\nThere is also a cultural attraction. Second-hand shops offer unusual designs that are not available in mainstream chains, allowing young people to build a personal style at a lower cost. Concerns about hygiene can be addressed through cleaning and honest product descriptions. Overall, the trend <strong class=\"key-phrase\">extends the useful life of existing products</strong> and reduces demand for disposable fashion.\n\nIt also gives charities and small local businesses a useful source of income, so the benefits extend beyond the individual buyer.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"General","phrases":[{"en":"develop a more individual appearance","vi":"tạo phong cách cá nhân hơn"},{"en":"reduce demand for disposable clothing","vi":"giảm nhu cầu đối với quần áo dùng ngắn hạn"},{"en":"extends the useful life of existing products","vi":"kéo dài vòng đời hữu ích của các sản phẩm hiện có"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"positive","summary":"Consumer Behavior and Sustainable Fashion","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-102","_displayNo":"#102","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-103","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"General","title":"General","prompt":"Discuss the arguments for and against raising pets.","answer":"In these years, animal welfare has become a subject of controversy and it has been argued that animals should not be regarded as property by human beings or used against their own best interests. When pet raising has become a way of life in many societies around the world, it has, on the other hand, raised the question of whether it is a breach of animal rights. Below are some arguments concerning pet ownership.\n\nPet animals are known for their loyalty and playful characteristics and believed to have a positive effect on the health of their owners. The pressures of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">modern lifestyles</strong> are tremendous. Compared to previous generations, people are more likely to live independently and away from their families at the present time. Adopting a pet animal as a companion can give quality to the owner's life, and help reduce stress and blood pressure. It is also regarded as a solution to the feeling of isolation and loneliness. These two facts are combined to justify why there are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an increasing number of</strong> people now depending on pet animals as companions or even a therapy.\n\nRaising pets benefits pets as well. Providing companionship and giving pleasure to their owners, pets receive loving care and attention in return. Some might argue that holding a pet is unnatural, because pet animals would lose their original way of life. However, people should meanwhile recognise that some animals are unsuited to life in the wild. It is morally wrong that people force animals to struggle with food, clean water and other necessities in the wild environment.\n\nKeeping an animal is therefore beneficial, but, notably, there is no guarantee that every pet lives a happy life. Ignorance of an animal’s needs for space, exercise or contact with members of the same species, for instance, has been found as a common problem with raising pets. It should also be noted that many people adopt pets for wrong reasons, such as a statement of affluence or a status symbol. They are very likely to abandon or even kill pets when their initial interest subsides, When holding pet animals has become popular, other problems will result, e. g., pollution caused by excess manure.\n\nBased on the facts outlined above, people can conclude that pet-keeping is a tradition that can be either good or bad, from an ethical point of view. On the one hand, it gives people companionship and great pleasure and animals obtain a loving home and a happy life. On the other, inappropriate treatment can rob animals of the basic right to well-being.","phrases":[{"en":"modern lifestyles","vi":"lối sống hiện đại"},{"en":"an increasing number of","vi":"số lượng ngày càng tăng"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#103","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Discuss the arguments for and against raising pets.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-104","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"General","title":"General: Advertising","prompt":"Do the positive effects outweigh negative effects, when advertising gains in popularity?","answer":"It has always been difficult to assess the contribution of advertising. This issue is fraught with controversy, with concern being expressed over the harmful effects of advertising. Below are some arguments against this concern.\n\nIt is important to recognise that one of the key functions of advertising is to supply consumers with adequate and accurate information about all of the alternatives available to them. Every <strong class=\"key-phrase\">now and then</strong>, advertising is criticised on the ground that it can manipulate consumers to follow the will of the advertiser; however, evidence supports an opposing view that advertising merely promotes products that are most likely to satisfy consumers’ wants. In simple terms, it is consumers rather than advertisers who decide what are advertised.\n\nAdvertising also plays a significant role in fostering full employment and facilitating economic well-being. By conveying marketing information constantly to the target audience, advertising speeds the consumers’ acceptance of new goods and technologies. It guarantees the high turnover rate of the manufactured goods and therefore, sustainability of a business. It is also agreed that advertising is one of the main sponsors of many other industries, for example, the entertainment industry— particularly sports, music, and theatrical events.\n\nUnarguably, advertising is criticised every now and then for misleading the public. However, the rapid development of advertising, itself has provided a solution to this problem, as the information delivered to the audiences has made them knowledgeable consumers. Under this circumstance, they can easily distinguish inferior products from quality products with their knowledge. The misleading effect of advertising will be counteracted over time.\n\nTo summarise, advertising suggests what consumers need and contributes partly to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">economic development</strong>. In this sense, advertising is of great value to people and the society. The general perception of advertising as a source of misleading information is in fact a bias.","phrases":[{"en":"now and then","vi":"thỉnh thoảng"},{"en":"economic development","vi":"phát triển kinh tế"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#104","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Do the positive effects outweigh negative effects, when advertising gains…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-105","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"General","title":"General: Sport","prompt":"Do you think that international sports events like the Olympic Games would continue or gradually lose their momentum?","answer":"The Olympics, known as the world’s largest event, appeal to global audiences with displaying athletic skills and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">competitive spirit</strong>. Pageantry, keen rivalry, and high level of competition are the striking attractions of the Olympic Games. When many people are concerned about the forces that drive this event forward, there are fears about their sustainability. In my opinion, the Olympic torch will be carried by relay runners on and on and would never be extinguished.\n\nReasons why the Olympics would continue are many. First, people, especially young males, are in need of some form of outlet for their energy and emotion related with sports. The Olympics, as well as other international sports events, are ideal for them. Meanwhile, leisure activities are valued today, as economic conditions continue to improve. As part of the growing leisure industries, sport and sporting contests will become increasingly important. Moreover, the Olympics are of commercial values and of broad interest to mass media organisations, advertisers, sponsors and business managers. Because of those business opportunities, cities will not cease to compete to host sporting events. Needless to say, they can thus achieve or maintain world class status.\n\nApart from those tangible benefits, the Olympics possess other values. For example, the Olympics allow nearly all nations in the world to compete in the event rather than require any of them to meet the strict political requirements set by other worldwide organisations, such as the United Nations on sovereignty. The political, social and economic conflicts between countries and regions are disregarded in the face of Olympic spirit. Audiences are so engrossed by the grace, endurance and fortitude shown by athletes that they pay little attention to their nations of origin, cultural and language differences.\n\nDespite those elements in favour of sustaining this international event, the Olympics are facing many challenges today. The expenditures are one of the biggest. So many services and facilities are required for serving athletes, media and spectators that up to present, only those cities from industrialised countries are capable of and interested in hosting such events. The Olympics are meanwhile the hotbed of various scandals. Tempted by the prospect of large financial rewards, many athletes take proscribed performance-enhancing drugs, a stain on the sportsmanship pursued by the Olympics. Critics also view international sporting events as a substitute for war, turning international rivalry into a highly ritualised contest, What's more, the Games draw criticism for embracing commercialism. ’The Olympic torch, for example, an important symbol of the Olympics, has been used popularly in the commodity market.\n\nOverall, humankind’s passion for competing in and watching games, the special appeals of the Olympic Games, and economic and non-economic benefits brought to the host city all make the immediate demise of the games unlikely. However, in the pursuit of those high ideals, the Olympics are meanwhile at the risk of being the instruments of commercialism and nationalism.","phrases":[{"en":"competitive spirit","vi":"tinh thần cạnh tranh"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#105","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Do you think that international sports events like the Olympic Games would…","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"General","prompt":"In many countries, the government prioritises economic growth above all other concerns. Discuss the advantages and disadvantages of this.","answer":"Economic growth is necessary for jobs, public revenue and better living standards, but it should not be the government’s only priority. A country can become richer while its environment, health system and social trust deteriorate. Governments should therefore pursue growth alongside broader measures of progress.\n\nThe benefits of a growing economy are clear. Successful businesses create employment, wages rise and the state collects more tax. This money can fund schools, hospitals and infrastructure. In poorer countries, sustained growth can also reduce extreme poverty and give families access to basic services. For these reasons, governments cannot simply <strong class=\"key-phrase\">ignore economic performance</strong>.\n\nHowever, growth can produce serious costs if it depends on pollution, unsafe work or extreme inequality. Higher national income means little to people who cannot afford housing or healthcare. Governments should evaluate whether growth improves ordinary lives, not only whether production increases. Measures such as life expectancy, educational outcomes, air quality and income distribution provide <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a fuller picture of national progress</strong>.\n\nThe central question is how the gains are distributed. Growth that raises tax revenue can finance schools, hospitals and infrastructure, but growth concentrated in a few companies may leave wages and public services unchanged. Governments therefore need environmental limits and social investment so that higher output <strong class=\"key-phrase\">translates into a broader improvement in living standards</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, economic growth should remain an important objective, but not the objective that overrides every other concern. The best policy is growth that is environmentally sustainable and widely shared, so that higher output translates into better lives.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"General","phrases":[{"en":"ignore economic performance","vi":"bỏ qua hiệu quả kinh tế"},{"en":"a fuller picture of national progress","vi":"bức tranh đầy đủ hơn về tiến bộ quốc gia"},{"en":"translates into a broader improvement in living standards","vi":"chuyển thành sự cải thiện mức sống trên diện rộng"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"advdis","summary":"Economic Growth: Pros and Cons of Government Priority","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-106","_displayNo":"#106","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"General: Crime and punishment","prompt":"In some countries, even though the rates of serious crimes are decreasing, people feel less safe than ever before. What do you think are the causes of this problem and what measures could be taken to solve it?","answer":"People can feel less safe even when serious crime is falling. This apparent contradiction is often caused by intensive news coverage, online rumours and visible signs of disorder. Governments should respond with accurate information as well as effective policing.\n\nModern media reports violent incidents repeatedly because they attract attention. A crime that once appeared in a local newspaper may now circulate nationally through video and social media. As a result, people judge risk by the examples they remember rather than by long-term statistics. This can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">create a distorted sense of danger</strong>.\n\nFear also grows when residents see poor lighting, vandalism, drug use or aggressive behaviour in public places. These problems may not appear in serious-crime figures, but they affect daily experience. Authorities should improve street lighting, maintain public spaces and provide visible community policing. They should also publish clear local data and explain trends in plain language, helping citizens <strong class=\"key-phrase\">separate perception from actual risk</strong>.\n\nFear is also shaped by visibility rather than statistics alone. Continuous news alerts, graphic videos and neighbourhood rumours can make rare crimes feel common. Authorities should publish clear local data and explain trends honestly, while community policing can rebuild contact between residents and officers. These steps can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reduce the gap between perceived and actual risk</strong>.\n\nSchools and local organisations can support this effort by teaching practical safety without exaggerating danger or encouraging suspicion of strangers.\n\nIn conclusion, falling crime rates do not automatically produce a feeling of safety. Public confidence depends on trustworthy information and the condition of neighbourhoods. Combining prevention, visible local action and honest communication is the most effective response.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"General","phrases":[{"en":"create a distorted sense of danger","vi":"tạo cảm nhận sai lệch về mức độ nguy hiểm"},{"en":"separate perception from actual risk","vi":"phân biệt cảm nhận với rủi ro thực tế"},{"en":"reduce the gap between perceived and actual risk","vi":"thu hẹp khoảng cách giữa rủi ro được cảm nhận và rủi ro thực tế"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"problem","summary":"Feeling Unsafe Despite Falling Crime Rates","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-107","_displayNo":"#107","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-108","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"General","title":"General","prompt":"Some findings have revealed that cities around the world are growing large. Could you outline the possible causes and predict consequences?","answer":"Of those issues that have concerned the government, academics and the public throughout the world, urban sprawl is one of the most prominent. There are conflicting views toward this growing trend. While it has been taken as a positive development in many newly emerging cities, it is increasingly perceived as a threat to rural environment and considered a trigger for numerous urban problems, The objective of this essay is to evaluate the forces behind this trend and its consequences.\n\nPopulation growth is widely recognised as the primary reason. The room in the city centre is so limited that it fails to provide enough housing to accommodate an ever-growing population. Another problem that has intensified in the inner city is infrastructure shortage and poor conditions of buildings. Lack of amenities, such as water and electricity supply, waste disposal, sewage treatment, to name but a few, has left no choice to urban dwellers but to resettle in the suburbs, where they have easier access to new facilities,\n\nCity dwellers are not always moving outward unwillingly. The continued increase in household incomes gives renewed impetus to urban development. People nowadays have higher expectations fr quality of life and a growing appetite for lower-density housing with # larger open space. It is possibly the main reason why the read estate market has its focus now on the outskirts of the city, but not on the centre, In the meantime, the affordability and ubiquity of car ownership has made transport a less serious concern for those living in suburbs. They can commute daily between the place of work and the place of residence with ease.\n\nThe sustained expansion of cities will make a marked impact on the society in several dimensions. The high traffic volume between suburbs and urban areas would cause severe air pollution and reduce the lands suitable for farming. Urban sprawl requires large developments, causing areas to lose some of their unique qualities and characteristics. From the economic perspective, the relocation of a high population in suburbs will pose adverse fiscal impacts on the local government in infrastructure construction. To those who used to live in suburbs, the inflow of new inhabitants would damage the community spirit and make relations between neighbours fragile.\n\nUrban sprawl is therefore a trend that has a strong effect on the environment, communities and government budgeting. When urban decay and citizens’ desire for higher standard of living make this trend irreversible, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the emphasis should be placed on</strong> planned and sustainable development.","phrases":[{"en":"the emphasis should be placed on","vi":"nên đặt trọng tâm vào"}],"subtype":"Causes / Effects","_displayNo":"#108","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Findings have revealed that cities around the world are growing large.","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"General","prompt":"Multinational companies are becoming increasingly common in developing countries. What are the advantages and disadvantages of this?","answer":"Multinational companies can bring investment, technology and employment to developing countries, but they may also exploit weak regulation. Their overall impact is positive only when governments negotiate fair conditions and enforce labour and environmental standards.\n\nThe main advantage is economic opportunity. A large international firm can create thousands of direct and indirect jobs, train local workers and connect domestic suppliers to global markets. Competition may also improve product quality and introduce new management methods. These effects can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">raise productivity across the wider economy</strong>.\n\nThe risks are equally real. Some companies move production to countries where wages are low and regulation is weak. Profits may leave the country, while local communities carry the cost of pollution or unsafe work. Governments may also offer excessive tax concessions in the hope of attracting investment. To avoid this, contracts should require local training, transparent taxation and compliance with national law.\n\nHost countries can limit the disadvantages through enforceable rules. Foreign firms should meet the same labour, tax and environmental standards as domestic companies, and major contracts should include training for local staff. When regulation is credible, multinational investment can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">build local capability instead of creating dependence</strong>.\n\nLocal suppliers should also be given a fair chance to join international production networks, rather than being limited to low-paid and insecure work.\n\nIn conclusion, multinational companies are neither automatically beneficial nor harmful. Developing countries gain most when foreign investment supports local skills and suppliers rather than operating as an isolated low-cost industry. Strong institutions are needed to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">turn private investment into public benefit</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"General","phrases":[{"en":"raise productivity across the wider economy","vi":"nâng năng suất trong toàn bộ nền kinh tế"},{"en":"build local capability instead of creating dependence","vi":"xây dựng năng lực địa phương thay vì tạo ra sự phụ thuộc"},{"en":"turn private investment into public benefit","vi":"biến đầu tư tư nhân thành lợi ích công cộng"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"advdis","summary":"Multinational Companies in Developing Countries","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-109","_displayNo":"#109","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"General","prompt":"Some people think that the teenage years are the happiest time of most people's lives. Others think that adult life brings more happiness, in spite of greater responsibility. Discuss both views and give your own opinion.","answer":"Some people remember adolescence as the happiest period of life, while others prefer adulthood. I believe happiness depends more on personal circumstances than age, although adulthood often offers greater freedom and control.\n\nTeenagers may enjoy fewer financial responsibilities and more time with friends. School holidays, new experiences and strong social bonds can make this stage exciting. However, adolescence also involves academic pressure, insecurity and limited independence. Young people are often expected to make important choices before they fully understand themselves.\n\nAdults face work, bills and family duties, but they usually have more control over where they live, whom they meet and how they spend their time. They can build a career, form stable relationships and make decisions based on experience. For many people, this <strong class=\"key-phrase\">greater sense of agency</strong> outweighs the heavier responsibilities.\n\nHappiness also depends more on circumstances than age. A supported teenager may enjoy freedom from financial pressure, while another may experience anxiety or conflict. Similarly, adulthood can bring meaningful work and stable relationships, or it can bring isolation and debt. It is therefore more accurate to focus on <strong class=\"key-phrase\">autonomy, health and close relationships</strong> than to identify one universally happiest stage.\n\nGood public policy should therefore support wellbeing at every age instead of presenting youth or adulthood as a single ideal period.\n\nIn conclusion, there is no universal happiest age. A supportive family, good health, meaningful relationships and a sense of purpose matter more than whether someone is a teenager or an adult. Nevertheless, I would choose adulthood because independence makes it easier to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">shape life according to personal priorities</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"General","phrases":[{"en":"greater sense of agency","vi":"cảm giác làm chủ cuộc sống lớn hơn"},{"en":"autonomy, health and close relationships","vi":"quyền tự chủ, sức khỏe và các mối quan hệ thân thiết"},{"en":"shape life according to personal priorities","vi":"định hình cuộc sống theo ưu tiên cá nhân"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"discuss","summary":"The Happiest Years: Teenage vs. Adulthood","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-110","_displayNo":"#110","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-111","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"General","title":"General: Advertising","prompt":"There are many advertisements directed at children. Parents argue that children are misled, while advertisers consider advertising a source of useful information. What is your opinion?","answer":"The impacts of advertising on children have become an area of focus in these years. When the initial purpose of advertising is to disseminate information related to goods and services, many parents have associated it with their children’s unjustified desires to buy something unnecessary. Although the extent to which advertising influences young viewers is a matter of debate, its impact, in my opinion, is undisputed.\n\nOne of the main features of advertisements is giving products an exaggerated account. In addition to this tactic, advertisers tend to stress those attributes of a product that are likely to be valued by <strong class=\"key-phrase\">young consumers</strong>, while playing down others. Some advertisements might disclose detailed information about products (such as health hazards of overeating some types of food), but in most cases, such information appears normally in small print and children cannot read them clearly. Nor can children comprehend the messages with their literacy skills. As a result, young viewers are susceptible to the effects of a commercial, leading directly to their subsequent buying decisions or their thrust for buying.\n\nAnother main strategy adopted by advertisers is to associate products with lifestyles that are attractive to young people and deliver a strong message that the advertised products are what their peers want and will choose. Children are more concerned with a particular label and branded products than adults, for the simple reason that they are much less price sensitive. They have the desire to possess products they consider popular, fashionable and likely to be admired by their peers, but seldom take into consideration the functions and practical values of those products.\n\nWhen the negative impacts of advertising on children are acknowledged, it should be noted that as children grow up, they will make more sophisticated judgements about those tactics advertisers use to grab their attention, They are less receptive to advertising messages and meanwhile more likely to perceive advertising as a mere source of information, assisting them to learn products and services better. Meanwhile, some advertisements are non-commercial and provide information on such issues as anti-smoking, anti-drug, AIDS, healthy eating practices, and so forth. In this sense, it is premature to judge that advertising has no redeeming feature.\n\nTo summarise, by enhancing the image of advertised products, making exaggerated claims on products and services and portraying a fantastic way of life, advertising is liable for children’s impulsive purchases. Children are misguided to make a purchase. Although adolescents are less susceptible to the misleading information, the advertisements that are marketed to children should be restricted.","phrases":[{"en":"young consumers","vi":"người tiêu dùng trẻ"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#111","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"There are many advertisements directed at children.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-112","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"General","title":"General","prompt":"What are the factors that cause stress and how to cope with stress?","answer":"Life today is filled with sources of stress, much of which cannot be avoided, When stress appears to be a Lifelong problem to many people, how it actually forms remains a subject of controversy to many scientists. The objective of this essay is to outline both the sources of stress and appropriate ways of dealing with it,\n\nMany stressors arise from people’s circumstances. For example, the high-pressured and fast-paced lifestyle has made it unlikely for people to gain adequate leisure time. Failure to balance work and leisure causes them either to struggle with deteriorating health or to cope with psychological distress, e. g., anxiety and depression. Together with some other problems, such as disharmony with others, unpleasant work or living environment, it would increase stress to an unmanageable level.\n\nAnother group of stressors is intertwined with personality. People interpret events or situations differently. A problem taken as a threat by many people might be accepted as a positive challenge to others. Evidence is inconclusive about the reasons behind this distinction, but it is widely believed that a person of a cheerful disposition is less likely to be heavily affected by adversity. Of equal importance is the ability to handle with some issues, such as time and money. Considering the role of personality in deciding the attitudes toward an issue and responses to an event, the effect of stress management skills actually varies from person to person.\n\nMethods to cope with stress are many, but the most effective ones are in fact not remote or complicated but accessible and practicable. People under stress are advised to participate more in recreational activities, adopt a sound dieting habit, and exercise regularly. They should learn to black out worries and try to keep the effect of a challenge in life to a minimum. Finally, it is important to nurture a good <strong class=\"key-phrase\">state of mind</strong> and to perceive things positively.\n\nAs suggested above, environment factors can be taken as the sources of stress, and people’s personality determines the extent to which they are influenced by those factors. Adopting a healthy lifestyle and proper attitudes toward life can promote people’s physical and psychological well-being and help them relieve stress.","phrases":[{"en":"state of mind","vi":"trạng thái tinh thần"}],"subtype":"Causes / Effects","_displayNo":"#112","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"What are the factors that cause stress and how to cope with stress?","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"General","prompt":"In some countries, younger people are neglecting their right to vote. What problems does this cause and what are some of the possible solutions?","answer":"When young people do not vote, governments receive a less accurate picture of the population’s priorities. This can produce policies that favour older voters and weaken confidence in democracy. The best solutions are practical civic education and easier access to voting.\n\nLow youth turnout creates a representation problem. Politicians naturally pay more attention to groups that vote regularly, so issues such as housing costs, entry-level jobs and education may receive less priority. Young adults may then feel ignored, which further reduces participation and creates <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a cycle of political disengagement</strong>.\n\nSeveral measures could improve the situation. Schools should teach how elections and public budgets affect everyday life, rather than presenting politics as a list of institutions. Registration should be simple, polling information should be clear and early or postal voting should be widely available. Parties also need to select younger candidates and discuss policies in language that is direct and relevant.\n\nLow youth turnout can distort public priorities. Politicians naturally focus on groups that vote consistently, so housing, education and entry-level employment may receive less attention. Schools should teach practical civic skills, while registration and polling should be simple and accessible. These measures can make participation easier without telling young people how to vote.\n\nYouth councils and public debates can also show that political participation produces visible results in local communities.\n\nIn conclusion, neglecting the vote reduces the influence of young citizens and makes public policy less balanced. Governments cannot force genuine interest, but they can remove unnecessary barriers and help young people see that voting is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a practical way to protect their interests</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"General","phrases":[{"en":"a cycle of political disengagement","vi":"vòng lặp xa rời chính trị"},{"en":"a practical way to protect their interests","vi":"một cách thiết thực để bảo vệ lợi ích của họ"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"problem","summary":"Youth Voter Apathy: Problems and Solutions","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-113","_displayNo":"#113","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-114","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Global issues","title":"Global Issues","prompt":"We cannot help everyone in the world that needs help, so we should only be concerned with our own communities and countries. To what extent do you agree or disagree with this statement?","answer":"Some people believe that we should not help people in other countries as long as there are problems in our own society. I disagree with this view because I believe that we should try to help as many people as possible.\n\nOn the one hand, I accept that it is important to help our neighbours and fellow citizens. In most communities there are people who are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">impoverished or disadvantaged</strong> in some way. It is possible to find homeless people, for example, in even the wealthiest of cities, and for those who are concerned about this problem, there are usually opportunities to volunteer time or give money to support these people. In the UK, people can help in a variety of ways, from donating clothing to serving free food in a soup kitchen. As the problems are on our doorstep, and there are obvious ways to help, I can understand why some people feel that we should <strong class=\"key-phrase\">prioritise local charity</strong>.\n\nAt the same time, I believe that we have an obligation to help those who <strong class=\"key-phrase\">live beyond our national borders</strong>. In some countries the problems that people face are much more serious than those in our own communities, and it is often even easier to help. For example, when children are dying from <strong class=\"key-phrase\">curable diseases</strong> in African countries, governments and individuals in richer countries can save lives simply by paying for vaccines that already exist. A small donation to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an international charity</strong> might have a much greater impact than helping in our local area.\n\nIn conclusion, it is true that we cannot help everyone, but in my opinion <strong class=\"key-phrase\">national boundaries</strong> should not stop us from helping those who are in need.","phrases":[{"en":"impoverished or disadvantaged","vi":"nghèo đói và khó khăn"},{"en":"prioritise local charity","vi":"ưu tiên từ thiện trong nước"},{"en":"live beyond our national borders","vi":"sống bên ngoài biên giới quốc gia của chúng ta"},{"en":"curable diseases","vi":"những bệnh có thể chữa được"},{"en":"an international charity","vi":"tổ chức từ thiện quốc tế"},{"en":"national boundaries","vi":"biên giới quốc gia"}],"subtype":"Agree / Disagree · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#114","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Helping locally or helping people abroad","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-115","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Government","title":"Government","prompt":"Many governments think that economic progress is their most important goal. Some people, however, think that other types of progress are equally important for a country. Discuss both these views and give your own opinion.","answer":"People have different views about how governments should measure their countries’ progress. While economic progress is of course essential, I agree with those who believe that other measures of progress are just as important.\n\nThere are three key reasons why <strong class=\"key-phrase\">economic growth</strong> is seen as <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a fundamental goal</strong> for countries. Firstly, a healthy economy results in job creation, a high level of employment, and better salaries for all citizens. Secondly, economic progress ensures that more money is available for governments to spend on infrastructure and public services. For example, a government with higher revenues can invest in the country's transport network, its education system and its hospitals. Finally, a strong economy can help a country’s standing on the global stage, in terms of its <strong class=\"key-phrase\">political influence</strong> and trading power.\n\nHowever, I would argue that various other forms of progress are just as significant as the economic factors mentioned above. In particular, we should consider the area of social justice, human rights, equality and democracy itself. For example, the treatment of minority groups is often seen as a reflection of the moral standards and level of development of a society. Perhaps another key consideration when judging the progress of a modern country should be how well that country protects the natural environment, and whether it is moving towards <strong class=\"key-phrase\">environmental sustainability</strong>. Alternatively, the success of a nation could be measured by looking at the health, well-being and happiness of its residents.\n\nIn conclusion, the economy is obviously a key marker of a country’s success, but social, environmental and health criteria are equally significant.","phrases":[{"en":"economic growth","vi":"tăng trưởng kinh tế"},{"en":"a fundamental goal","vi":"một mục tiêu nền tảng"},{"en":"political influence","vi":"ảnh hưởng chính trị"},{"en":"environmental sustainability","vi":"tính bền vững môi trường"}],"subtype":"Discuss both views + opinion · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#115","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Economic growth versus broader progress","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-116","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Government","title":"Government: Money","prompt":"It is better to save money than to spend it. How far do you agree with this statement? Is saving more important than spending in today’s world? Give reasons for your answer, and provide ideas and examples from your own experience. You should write at least 250 words.","answer":"With the world in such economic turmoil, many of us face difficult choices in managing our money. Personally, I feel that saving is preferable to high spending, and I will explain why. Firstly, saving money is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sensible precaution</strong> in a world where the future is uncertain. It is possible, for example, that a person might meet unemployment, ill health or other crises at some point in life. It is essential to have some <strong class=\"key-phrase\">funds in reserve</strong> for these situations, and saving is for most people the only way to achieve this. Furthermore, I believe that saving is itself a good discipline for people to develop, as it builds skills of planning and reaching targets. We can see this in the way that disciplined people build up quite large sums through small monthly contributions to savings plans. In many cases this meets important objectives in their lives, including large purchases such as cars or property. Finally, we have to remember the reasons for the current economic problems besetting the world. The crisis was caused by excessive spending and insufficient saving – not just by individuals, but by corporations and even governments themselves. I feel that an emphasis on sensible saving should be a universal strategy now. I do appreciate that some people think differently, saying that it is better to live for the moment and spend accordingly. While some daily spending is essential, of course, I feel this is a potentially unwise viewpoint, especially considering recent global events. To conclude, I believe that saving is the wiser course, not just for financial but also for personal and political reasons. Sensible saving is an invaluable skill and a buffer against uncertainty.","phrases":[{"en":"a sensible precaution","vi":"một biện pháp phòng ngừa hợp lý"},{"en":"funds in reserve","vi":"khoản tiền dự phòng"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#116","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"It is better to save money than to spend it.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-117","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Government","title":"Government: Money","prompt":"The advocates of international aid believe that countries have a moral obligation to help each other, while the opponents consider it unnecessary, because money is misspent by the governments that receive it. Discuss these two points of view and give your opinion.","answer":"Supporters of international aid argue that wealthy countries have a moral duty to assist poorer ones, while critics point to corruption and waste. Both concerns are valid. In my view, aid remains necessary, but it should be targeted, transparent and designed to build local capacity rather than permanent dependence.\n\nThe strongest case for aid arises during emergencies. After war, drought or an earthquake, outside funding can provide food, medicine, clean water and temporary shelter far more quickly than a damaged government can. Longer-term support can also fund vaccination, teacher training and basic infrastructure. These investments save lives and may prevent instability from spreading across borders.\n\nCritics are right that money can be diverted by officials, spent on unsuitable projects or tied to the donor’s commercial interests. Large transfers made without local oversight may weaken accountability and encourage governments to rely on external finance. The answer, however, is not to abandon assistance. Donors should publish contracts, audit outcomes, work with reliable local organisations and release funds in stages. Wherever possible, aid should transfer skills and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">strengthen institutions that can continue the work</strong>.\n\nAid is most credible when local communities help choose the priorities, monitor delivery and report failures. This reduces the risk that donors fund impressive buildings or short projects that do not match daily needs.\n\nIn conclusion, international aid is justified both morally and practically, but its quality matters more than the headline amount. Carefully monitored programmes that respond to local priorities can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">deliver lasting benefits instead of short-term publicity</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"strengthen institutions that can continue the work","vi":"củng cố các tổ chức có thể tiếp tục công việc"},{"en":"deliver lasting benefits instead of short-term publicity","vi":"mang lại lợi ích lâu dài thay vì sự phô trương ngắn hạn"}],"subtype":"Discussion","_displayNo":"#117","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Advocates of international aid believe that countries have a moral…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-118","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Government","title":"Government: Housing","prompt":"Only government action can solve housing shortages in big cities. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Housing shortage has become a serious urban social issue in many parts of the world. It has been argued that only when the government has taken actions, can demand for homes be fulfilled. Yet to the best of my knowledge, the government alone cannot cope well with housing shortages.\n\nOne of the main objections to government intervention is that it would hamper the private sector and simultaneously pose a huge burden upon the state. In countries where the government is on a tight budget and the homeless population is large, the involvement of private property developers is required and recommended. Not only does it release the government from the burden of funding large-sized construction programmes but it also fosters the housing industry. Given its role in attracting public consumption and accelerating <strong class=\"key-phrase\">economic development</strong>, the housing industry should be at the mercy of the market, rather than the government.\n\nAnother drawback of state control over the housing market is that it could result in the stagnation of construction quality, functionality, facilities and other aspects of housing. Apartment blocks or other residential constructions would be built in a similar pattern and the cityscape would be monotonous. Excessive uniformity, especially in the size and number of rooms, will fail to meet comprehensive requirements raised by citizens on properties.\n\nDespite these objections, government intervention is essential in some segments of the market and can render more resistance to citizens. Single parents, the people with disabilities and other disadvantaged people are among those who are not ready to afford commercial housing. The government can provide them either with housing allowance to purchase their private properties or directly with economical houses.\n\nAs indicated above, in addressing homelessness and inadequate housing, the joint effort of both government and private sector is required. While government intervention would impede the property market and negatively influence the supply and demand relationship, government assistance is essential for low-income families and vulnerable individuals in need of housing.","phrases":[{"en":"economic development","vi":"phát triển kinh tế"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#118","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Only government action can solve housing shortages in big cities.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-119","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Government","title":"Government: Money","prompt":"People should keep all the money they earn and should not pay taxes to the state. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"The role of taxation is providing funds necessary for carrying out a variety of functions in a country. However, to many taxpayers, especially employers, paying tax remains the biggest headache. In my opinion, tax revenue is essential to a country. Below are somé of its main functions.\n\nAlthough many taxpayers see income tax as an appropriation of their earnings, tax is in fact a relief to taxpayers and their families, for example, by providing <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a safeguard against unemployment</strong> and a solution to other problems that they may confront in life. For example, those who lose their earning capabilities because of injuries, diseases and disabilities are entitled to the government's financial support, derived mainly from tax revenue. There is no point in denying that tax is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the principal source of finance</strong> that sustains many of the benefits offered by the welfare system of a country. Although most workers are not the beneficiaries currently, they will count on these benefits in their later years (as pensioners), as will their dependants (children and parents).\n\nTaxation is meanwhile an effective tool by which a society can achieve <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the redistribution of income</strong> and close the gap between the rich and the poor. In most countries, as a general rule, the higher the personal income, the higher the income tax. By imposing different tax rates, the government can distribute the tax burden across social classes, reducing income disparity between the rich and the poor.\n\nCorporate tax is deemed by business as a regular cost, which must be kept to a minimum, but it is not necessarily a bane. By levying different types of tax, the government can exert an influence on macroeconomic performance, which in turn influences the income of the business world. When the economy is on the verge of a recession, the government can reduce the tax and present tax incentives, which proves to be an effective policy in reviving the economy. By contrast, during the periods of growth, the government can raise the tax rate so as to prevent an overheated economy and combat inflation. It is fair to say that tax is one of the main tools in establishing a healthy environment <strong class=\"key-phrase\">conducive to business’s sustained growth</strong>.\n\nWhat have been discussed above are the benefits brought by taxation, all being essential to a country, its businesses and individual taxpayers. Although many taxpayers feel pressured by taxes, they will eventually benefit from the taxes they have paid and should therefore bear tax liabilities.","phrases":[{"en":"a safeguard against unemployment","vi":"mạng lưới bảo vệ trước thất nghiệp"},{"en":"the principal source of finance","vi":"nguồn tài chính chủ yếu"},{"en":"the redistribution of income","vi":"sự tái phân phối thu nhập"},{"en":"conducive to business’s sustained growth","vi":"thuận lợi cho tăng trưởng bền vững của doanh nghiệp"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#119","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People should keep all the money they earn and should not pay taxes to the…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-120","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Happiness","title":"Happiness","prompt":"Happiness is considered very important in life. Why is it difficult to define? What factors are important in achieving happiness?","answer":"It is no doubt true that the majority of people would like to be happy in their lives. While <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the personal nature of happiness</strong> makes it difficult to describe, there do seem to be some common needs that we all share with regard to experiencing or achieving happiness.\n\nHappiness is difficult to define because it means something different to each individual person. Nobody can fully understand or experience another person’s feelings, and we all have our own particular passions from which we take pleasure. Some people, for example, derive a sense of satisfaction from earning money or achieving success, whereas for others, health and family are much more important. At the same time, a range of other feelings, from excitement to peacefulness, may be associated with the idea of happiness, and the same person may therefore feel happy in a variety of different ways.\n\nAlthough it seems almost impossible to give <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a precise definition of happiness</strong>, most people would agree that there are some basic preconditions to achieving it. Firstly, it is hard for a person to be happy if he or she does not have a safe place to live and enough food to eat. Our <strong class=\"key-phrase\">basic survival needs</strong> must surely be met before we can lead a pleasant life. Secondly, the greatest joy in life is usually found in shared experiences with family and friends, and it is rare to find a person who is content to live in complete isolation. Other key factors could be individual freedom and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sense of purpose in life</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, happiness is difficult to define because it is particular to each individual, but I believe that our basic needs for shelter, food and company need to be fulfilled before we can experience it.","phrases":[{"en":"the personal nature of happiness","vi":"tính chất cá nhân của hạnh phúc"},{"en":"a precise definition of happiness","vi":"định nghĩa chính xác của hạnh phúc"},{"en":"basic survival needs","vi":"những nhu cầu sinh tồn cơ bản"},{"en":"a sense of purpose in life","vi":"cảm giác có mục đích trong cuộc sống"}],"subtype":"Two-part question · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#120","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Defining and achieving happiness","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-121","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Health","title":"Health","prompt":"In many countries today, there are concerns about the unhealthy lifestyles that people lead. What health issues are linked to modern lifestyles? What answers to these problems can you suggest? Give reasons for your answer, and support your essay with ideas and examples from your own experience. You should write at least 250 words.","answer":"Most people agree that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">modern lifestyles</strong> can be unhealthy, both physically and mentally. I believe there are three main problems, but also some <strong class=\"key-phrase\">practical steps</strong> we can take. Perhaps the largest problem is the issue of obesity, which is growing drastically in most Western countries. With people working at desks and using transport rather than walking, weight gain seems inevitable, and being overweight causes various medical issues including heart trouble and strokes. Another major problem linked to lifestyle is poor diet, with people who are short of time eating junk food rather than proper nutrients. Resultant health problems range from obesity to high cholesterol and even organ failure. Finally, we must consider the issue of mental health. Modern lifestyles are highly pressurised, with people expected to work at a fast pace for extended periods, and little scope for family life or relaxation, leading to enormous stress and anxiety. Turning to possible solutions, the biggest step would be to improve the level of education regarding health issues connected to lifestyle, especially obesity. The government, media and schools should work together to raise awareness of the dangers and to promote sports and other positive practices. A further step would be to use legislation to curb the consumption of unhealthy foods, for example by imposing higher sales taxes or by restricting availability in retail outlets. Furthermore, to deal with the psychological impacts, we should encourage employers to adopt more flexible working practices, allowing workers to lead a fuller private life with less stress. Overall, the key problems of obesity and stress can be addressed through a combination of awareness, targeted legislation and better employment practices.","phrases":[{"en":"modern lifestyles","vi":"lối sống hiện đại"},{"en":"practical steps","vi":"các bước thiết thực"}],"subtype":"Problems / Solutions","_displayNo":"#121","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"Today, there are concerns about the unhealthy lifestyles that people lead.","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"Health: Sport","prompt":"In many professional sports, there is an increase in the number of athletes using banned substances to improve their performance. What are the causes of the phenomenon and what are some of the possible solutions?","answer":"The use of banned performance-enhancing drugs is increasing in some professional sports. The main causes are intense financial pressure, weak detection and a culture in which winning is valued above long-term health. Solutions must address both athletes and the organisations around them.\n\nElite competitors may believe that a small physical advantage can determine contracts, sponsorship and selection. If they suspect that rivals are already using drugs, they may feel forced to do the same. Coaches, doctors or managers can also encourage abuse when their own careers depend on results. This creates <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a powerful incentive to take hidden risks</strong>.\n\nSports bodies should use independent testing, share information internationally and impose penalties on support staff as well as athletes. Testing should be frequent and unpredictable, with samples stored for later analysis as technology improves. At the same time, athletes need confidential medical advice and clear education about long-term harm. Whistle-blowers should receive protection so that organised doping systems are easier to expose.\n\nAthletes may also dope because detection appears uncertain and the rewards are immediate. Effective control therefore requires independent testing, long-term storage of samples and penalties for coaches or doctors who organise abuse. Confidential reporting systems can protect whistle-blowers. Together, these measures <strong class=\"key-phrase\">change the incentives surrounding performance-enhancing drugs</strong> rather than blaming athletes alone.\n\nIn conclusion, punishment alone will not solve the problem. Sport must reduce the pressure that rewards cheating and increase the chance that abuse is detected. A combination of independent oversight, education and protection for honest athletes can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">restore trust in competition</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Health","phrases":[{"en":"a powerful incentive to take hidden risks","vi":"động lực mạnh khiến người ta chấp nhận rủi ro ngầm"},{"en":"change the incentives surrounding performance-enhancing drugs","vi":"thay đổi các động lực xoay quanh thuốc tăng cường thành tích"},{"en":"restore trust in competition","vi":"khôi phục niềm tin vào thi đấu"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"problem","summary":"Banned Substances in Professional Sports","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-122","_displayNo":"#122","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"Health: Sport","prompt":"Being a celebrity, such as a famous film star or sports personality, brings problems as well as benefits. Do you think that being a celebrity brings more benefits or more problems?","answer":"Celebrity brings wealth, influence and unusual opportunities, but it also removes much of a person’s privacy. In my view, the benefits can be substantial, yet fame is only positive when the individual has strong support and realistic boundaries.\n\nA successful actor or athlete may earn a high income, travel widely and work on projects that would otherwise be impossible. Public recognition can also give celebrities a platform to support charities or raise awareness of important issues. In career terms, fame can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">open doors that talent alone may not</strong>.\n\nThe disadvantages are more personal. Famous people are photographed, judged and discussed by strangers, and ordinary mistakes can become public scandals. Their families may also face unwanted attention. Constant pressure to maintain an image can damage mental health, while it becomes difficult to know whether new relationships are genuine. High earnings do not automatically compensate for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the loss of a private life</strong>.\n\nThe balance often depends on the type of fame. A respected actor or athlete with professional support may use public attention to fund projects and influence useful causes. A person who becomes famous suddenly through social media may have less control over privacy and income. Fame is therefore <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an opportunity that requires strong boundaries and support</strong>, not an automatic benefit.\n\nIn conclusion, being a celebrity offers exceptional rewards but also serious costs. I would not describe it as clearly beneficial or harmful. The experience depends on whether the person can control access to their life, manage public pressure and maintain relationships outside the entertainment or sports industry.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Health","phrases":[{"en":"open doors that talent alone may not","vi":"mở ra cơ hội mà chỉ tài năng thôi chưa chắc có được"},{"en":"the loss of a private life","vi":"sự mất đi đời sống riêng tư"},{"en":"an opportunity that requires strong boundaries and support","vi":"một cơ hội đòi hỏi ranh giới rõ ràng và sự hỗ trợ vững chắc"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"two-part","summary":"Celebrity Life: More Benefits or More Problems?","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-123","_displayNo":"#123","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-124","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Health","title":"Health: Food","prompt":"Food can be produced much more cheaply today because of improved fertilisers and better machinery. However, some of the methods used to do this may be dangerous to human health and may have negative effects on local communities. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Fertilisers and machinery used to be welcomed by countries worldwide as essential elements of industrialised farming, a landmark in the history of global agriculture. However, because of being used on a large scale worldwide, they have caused heated controversy. There is ongoing debate on the possible damages of industrial farming caused to the environment and humanity, In my opinion, both are still irreplaceable, although efficient and scientific utilisation is highly recommended.\n\nFertilisers and machinery are both essential in increasing crop yields, a solution to starvation throughout the world. In history, manual work accounted for the majority of farming, from sowing, irrigating to harvesting. The slow pace of human labour made it impossible to produce enough crops to feed populations, Farming is, on the other hand, exposed to the influence of many elements—weather conditions, soil compositions, pests or some unpredictable events like natural disasters. Fertilisers enhance crops or other foods’ resistance to external disturbances, while machinery saves manpower by finishing the major part of the work. The yield is raised to the highest, and lands are used to the full. Enough food can be produced to meet the market need now, despite the continued growth of the population.\n\nSome people defy fertilisers and machinery because of their concern on environment. However, this notion has been challenged by advances in this area of knowledge. Technological innovation has made machinery more <strong class=\"key-phrase\">environmentally friendly</strong>, and many machines used for farming purposes are now able to operate without generating much waste. Fertilisers, by comparison, are much less environment-damaging. Most fertilisers are organic and free of ingredients incompatible with the environment. Nor do they have deleterious effects on people's health.\n\nDespite what has been discussed, farmers should beware of over-application of fertilisers. Front an environmental perspective, fertilisers and machinery should be classified and used with caution. The over-application of fertilisers not only has perpetually disastrous effects on farms but also injures the neighbouring ecosystem. Many scientific studies suggest that a long history of fertiliser use can significantly reduce land fertility. Other consequences include poisoning all wildlife feeding on farm crops (e. g., birds), and polluting the neighbouring water bodies. On health and safety grounds, fertilisers might bring irreparable damage to eaters’ health, for some chemicals, although not fatal themselves, might become life-threatening when accumulating inside eaters’ bodies.\n\nOn the basis of the above-mentioned arguments, people are convinced that the sustainable supply of foods still rests on fertilisers and machinery, and the key is to use them properly and in moderation.","phrases":[{"en":"environmentally friendly","vi":"thân thiện với môi trường"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#124","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Food can be produced much more cheaply today because of improved…","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"Health: Sport","prompt":"Some people say that the best way to improve public health is by increasing the number of sports facilities. Others, however, say that this would have little effect on public health and that other measures are required. Discuss both these views and give your own opinion.","answer":"Building more sports facilities may encourage some people to exercise, but it is not the best single way to improve public health. I agree with those who argue that broader measures are required because health is shaped by diet, education, income and the local environment.\n\nAdditional gyms, parks and swimming pools can make exercise more convenient. This is particularly useful in neighbourhoods where safe outdoor space is limited. However, facilities have little effect if they are expensive, badly located or used mainly by people who are already active. Access alone does not <strong class=\"key-phrase\">change deeply established habits</strong>.\n\nA more effective strategy would combine affordable exercise with prevention. Schools should teach practical nutrition, cities should provide safe walking and cycling routes, and governments should limit misleading marketing of unhealthy products to children. Basic healthcare should also identify problems such as high blood pressure before they become severe. These policies reach people who may never choose to join a sports centre.\n\nAccess to facilities matters most when it is part of a wider policy. Safe streets, affordable classes and school programmes can help people use those facilities regularly. Health education, food standards and preventive care are equally important because exercise alone cannot address smoking, poor diet or delayed diagnosis. Public health improves through <strong class=\"key-phrase\">several coordinated measures rather than one visible project</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, sports facilities are a useful part of public-health policy, but they cannot address the full range of causes behind poor health. The greatest improvement will come from <strong class=\"key-phrase\">making healthy choices easy and affordable</strong> in everyday life.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Health","phrases":[{"en":"change deeply established habits","vi":"thay đổi những thói quen đã hình thành lâu dài"},{"en":"several coordinated measures rather than one visible project","vi":"nhiều biện pháp phối hợp thay vì một dự án dễ thấy"},{"en":"making healthy choices easy and affordable","vi":"khiến lựa chọn lành mạnh trở nên dễ dàng và vừa túi tiền"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"discuss","summary":"Improving Public Health: Sports Facilities or Other Measures?","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-125","_displayNo":"#125","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"Health: Sport","prompt":"It is generally believed that some people are born with certain talents, for instance for sport or music, and others are not. However, it is sometimes claimed that any child can be taught to become a good sports person or musician. Discuss both these views and give your own opinion.","answer":"Natural ability can give people an early advantage in music or sport, but high performance is rarely the result of talent alone. I believe most people can reach a strong level through good teaching and sustained practice, although not everyone will become world-class.\n\nSome physical and mental characteristics are partly inherited. Height may help a basketball player, while a sensitive ear can make musical training easier. Children also differ in coordination, memory and speed of learning. These differences explain why two beginners may progress at different rates under the same conditions.\n\nNevertheless, talent has limited value without disciplined practice. Skilled performers repeat difficult tasks, receive detailed feedback and gradually correct weaknesses. Access to coaching, equipment and family support is often more important than people realise. A moderately talented child with excellent training may therefore outperform a gifted child who lacks opportunity or motivation. Practice can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">turn potential into reliable performance</strong>.\n\nResearch on expertise suggests that natural advantages affect the starting point, but sustained practice strongly influences the final level. A child with average coordination can still become a competent musician or athlete through good teaching and regular feedback. Schools should therefore provide broad opportunities before deciding who has talent. This prevents <strong class=\"key-phrase\">early labels from limiting later development</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, people are not born with identical abilities, but talent should not be treated as a fixed limit. Schools and coaches should give learners time, expert guidance and realistic goals. This approach recognises natural differences while preserving the belief that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">ability can be developed</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Health","phrases":[{"en":"turn potential into reliable performance","vi":"biến tiềm năng thành năng lực ổn định"},{"en":"early labels from limiting later development","vi":"những nhãn dán sớm hạn chế sự phát triển về sau"},{"en":"ability can be developed","vi":"năng lực có thể được phát triển"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"discuss","summary":"Natural Talent vs. Hard Work: What Makes a Great Athlete or Musician?","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-126","_displayNo":"#126","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-127","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Health","title":"Health: Food","prompt":"Some people think that killing animals for food is cruel, but others claim that animals are a necessary part of diet. What’s your opinion?","answer":"It is a widespread practice that livestock is raised and butchered for human consumption. Although it has been condemned as cruelty to animals, a counter-argument is that meat is the necessity for people's health and well-being. To the best of my knowledge, meat is a regular part of the diet and there is no alternative to animal food sources.\n\nThe first justification is that animal source foods <strong class=\"key-phrase\">provide a wide range of nutrients</strong> that are difficult to obtain in adequate quantities from plant source foods. Insufficient intake of those nutrients will produce negative health outcomes, such as poor growth. A diet with a good combination of meat and vegetable is thought to have considerable value. Some might argue that consumption of meat can pose health risks and increase the risk of foodborne illness. This statement is fallacious, considering the fact that people can kill bacteria and remove risk factors by cooking properly and using scientific methods in manufacture.\n\nAnother point to note is that most of the meat available in supermarkets for people’s consumption is produced by industrial agriculture. In view of the intense use of modern technology and mass production techniques, the produced livestock, poultry or fish cannot be taken as ordinary animals but only as manufactured goods. By making use of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">economies of scale</strong> to produce enough food at an affordable cost, industrial farming is essential to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">addressing food supply problems</strong>.\n\nThe significance of capitalising on animals as a food source is therefore undeniable, but it is important to realise that people cannot exploit animals and become addicted to meat consumption. Animal fats, for example, increase the risk of heart disease and meat is frequently associated with outbreaks of food poisoning. Meanwhile, people's insatiable desire for meat might lead to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">intensive livestock farming</strong> and animal slaughter, which has a direct impact on the well-being of animals worldwide.\n\nFrom the preceding discussion, one can see no reason why livestock or some other animals cannot be used as food. Switching to an animal free diet is a personal option, but the question remains whether one can ensure sufficient intake of nutrition necessary for one’s health. When there is little room for argument concerning the use of animals for meat, il is necessary to impose standards and prevent animal exploitation","phrases":[{"en":"provide a wide range of nutrients","vi":"cung cấp nhiều loại dưỡng chất"},{"en":"economies of scale","vi":"lợi thế kinh tế theo quy mô"},{"en":"addressing food supply problems","vi":"giải quyết vấn đề nguồn cung thực phẩm"},{"en":"intensive livestock farming","vi":"chăn nuôi thâm canh"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#127","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People think that killing animals for food is cruel, but others claim that…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-128","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Health","title":"Health: Mobile phones","prompt":"There are social, medical and technical problems associated with the use of mobile phones. What form do these problems take? Do problems of using mobile phones outweigh the benefits?","answer":"Across the world, especially the wealthier parts, the mobile phone has taken the place of telephone as an electronic telecommunication device, with the majority of the adult, teenager and even child owning one. As this technology has become rife, its drawbacks, which can be seen from social, medical and technical perspectives, deserve people's greatest attention.\n\nSimilar to many other hi-tech products, such as computers, mobile phones have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">detrimental effects on users’ health</strong>. For example, long-time heavy phone users seem to be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more prone to</strong> certain types of cancers, although evidence to date is inconclusive. Another serious health concern is the link between mobile phones and road accidents. It is argued that motorists have a much higher risk of collisions and losing control of the vehicle when driving and talking on the phone simultaneously, despite sometimes using hands-free systems.\n\nWhen the mobile phone has brought considerable convenience, people's obsession with convenience has meanwhile caused <strong class=\"key-phrase\">enormous disturbance</strong>. That’s why the use of mobile phones has been prohibited in many public places, such as libraries, theatres, hospitals and even transports, such as trains, buses and aircraft. Speaking at increased volume is considered impolite or even offensive. In schools, students are required to switch off cell phones before the class begins because mobile phones are responsible for a high amount of class disruptions.\n\nWhen its downside persists, the mobile phone has proven indispensable in modern life. It is handheld, lightweight, portable and multifunctional, allowing users to send text messages, exchange music files, make voice calls, browse the Internet, and so forth. Meanwhile, within twenty years, mobile phones are expected to be more pervasive as technical advances and mass manufacture will make them low-cost personal items. Given those factors, the mobile phone will continue to perform its role as a key social tool, by which one keeps in touch with others much more easily than did the generations before.\n\nAs suggested above, the contribution of the mobile phone to the society is prominent and people's dependence on it for communication is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an irreversible trend</strong>, although it has a number of problems that should be well handled.","phrases":[{"en":"detrimental effects on users’ health","vi":"tác động có hại đến sức khỏe người dùng"},{"en":"more prone to","vi":"dễ mắc phải hơn"},{"en":"enormous disturbance","vi":"sự gây phiền nhiễu nghiêm trọng"},{"en":"an irreversible trend","vi":"một xu hướng không thể đảo ngược"}],"subtype":"Problems / Solutions","_displayNo":"#128","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"There are social, medical and technical problems associated with the use of…","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"Health","prompt":"In some countries, it is becoming increasingly common for people to adopt a vegetarian diet. Do the advantages of this outweigh the disadvantages?","answer":"A vegetarian diet can improve health and reduce environmental pressure, but it requires careful planning. In my view, the advantages generally outweigh the disadvantages for people who have access to a varied diet and reliable nutritional advice.\n\nPlant-based meals are often rich in fibre, fruit and vegetables, and they can contain less saturated fat than diets based heavily on processed meat. Reducing meat consumption may therefore lower the risk of certain chronic diseases. It also decreases demand for land, water and animal feed, which can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reduce the environmental cost of food production</strong>.\n\nThe main disadvantage is the possibility of nutritional deficiency. People who remove all animal products need suitable sources of protein, iron, vitamin B12 and other nutrients. This can be difficult for children, pregnant women or low-income households if specialist foods are expensive. Cultural preferences and limited restaurant choices may also make the diet inconvenient.\n\nThe disadvantages are manageable but should not be ignored. Poorly planned diets may lack vitamin B12, iron or sufficient protein, especially for children and pregnant women. Clear nutritional advice and fortified foods can reduce these risks. The strongest case for vegetarianism is therefore based on <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a balanced diet rather than the simple removal of meat</strong>.\n\nRestaurants and schools can help by offering affordable, clearly labelled meals that make this choice practical rather than restrictive.\n\nIn conclusion, vegetarianism offers important health and environmental benefits, but it should not be adopted carelessly. Public advice should focus on balanced meals rather than simply telling people to avoid meat. With sensible planning, a vegetarian diet can be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">both healthy and sustainable</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Health","phrases":[{"en":"reduce the environmental cost of food production","vi":"giảm chi phí môi trường của việc sản xuất thực phẩm"},{"en":"a balanced diet rather than the simple removal of meat","vi":"một chế độ ăn cân bằng thay vì chỉ đơn giản loại bỏ thịt"},{"en":"both healthy and sustainable","vi":"vừa lành mạnh vừa bền vững"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"outweigh","summary":"Vegetarian Diet: Advantages Outweigh Disadvantages","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-129","_displayNo":"#129","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-130","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Health","title":"Health: Children","prompt":"The percentage of overweight children in western society has increased by almost 20% in the last ten years. Discuss the causes and effects of this disturbing trend.","answer":"The sharp rise in childhood obesity is not the result of a single poor choice. It reflects changes in the food environment, family routines and children’s daily activity, and its consequences extend well beyond appearance or short-term fitness.\n\nOne major cause is the widespread availability of inexpensive, energy-dense food. Highly processed meals and snacks are convenient for time-pressed households, while sophisticated marketing makes them especially attractive to children. Portion sizes have also increased, meaning that excessive calorie intake can become normal before a child understands nutrition. At the same time, many neighbourhoods and schools provide fewer opportunities for safe, unstructured physical activity. Screen-based entertainment has therefore <strong class=\"key-phrase\">displaced a substantial amount of active play</strong>, particularly where parents are reluctant to let children play outdoors unsupervised.\n\nThe immediate effects include reduced stamina, sleep problems and a higher likelihood of social stigma. More seriously, obesity during childhood can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">establish patterns that persist into adulthood</strong>. Children who become accustomed to sugary food and sedentary routines may find those habits difficult to reverse later. This increases the risk of type 2 diabetes, cardiovascular disease and joint problems at a younger age than previous generations experienced.\n\nThere are also psychological and social consequences. Overweight children may face bullying or exclusion, which can damage confidence and encourage further withdrawal from sport. Families and health systems then carry a growing financial burden as preventable conditions require long-term treatment. The trend therefore <strong class=\"key-phrase\">creates a cycle of physical and emotional disadvantage</strong> rather than an isolated medical issue.\n\nIn conclusion, childhood obesity is driven by unhealthy food environments and declining everyday activity. Its effects are cumulative, affecting health, self-esteem and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">public expenditure</strong>. Because the causes are structural as well as personal, the problem should be addressed through coordinated action by families, schools, food producers and governments.","phrases":[{"en":"displaced a substantial amount of active play","vi":"thay thế một phần đáng kể thời gian vận động"},{"en":"establish patterns that persist into adulthood","vi":"hình thành các thói quen kéo dài đến tuổi trưởng thành"},{"en":"creates a cycle of physical and emotional disadvantage","vi":"tạo ra vòng luẩn quẩn bất lợi về thể chất và cảm xúc"},{"en":"public expenditure","vi":"chi tiêu công"}],"subtype":"Causes and effects · Nguồn đề: IELTS Buddy","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#130","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Why childhood obesity is increasing","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-131","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Hobbies","title":"Hobbies","prompt":"Some people believe that hobbies need to be difficult to be enjoyable. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Some hobbies are relatively easy, while others present more of a challenge. Personally, I believe that both types of hobby can be fun, and I therefore disagree with the statement that hobbies need to be difficult in order to be enjoyable.\n\nOn the one hand, many people enjoy easy hobbies. One example of an activity that is easy for most people is swimming. This hobby requires very little equipment, it is simple to learn, and it is inexpensive. I remember learning to swim at my local swimming pool when I was a child, and it never felt like a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">demanding or challenging experience</strong>. Another hobby that I find easy and fun is photography. In my opinion, anyone can take interesting pictures without knowing too much about <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the technicalities of operating a camera</strong>. Despite being straightforward, taking photos is a satisfying activity.\n\nOn the other hand, difficult hobbies can sometimes be more exciting. If an activity is more challenging, we might feel <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a greater sense of satisfaction</strong> when we manage to do it successfully. For example, film editing is a hobby that requires <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a high level of knowledge and expertise</strong>. In my case, it took me around two years before I became competent at this activity, but now I enjoy it much more than I did when I started. I believe that many hobbies give us more pleasure when we reach a higher level of performance because the results are better and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the feeling of achievement</strong> is greater.\n\nIn conclusion, simple hobbies can be fun and relaxing, but difficult hobbies can be equally pleasurable for different reasons.","phrases":[{"en":"demanding or challenging experience","vi":"một trải nghiệm thử thách và đòi hỏi"},{"en":"the technicalities of operating a camera","vi":"kĩ thuật để sử dụng camera"},{"en":"a greater sense of satisfaction","vi":"cảm giác hài lòng"},{"en":"a high level of knowledge and expertise","vi":"một trình độ cao về kiến thức và chuyên môn"},{"en":"the feeling of achievement","vi":"cảm giác đạt được cái gì đó"}],"subtype":"Agree / Disagree · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#131","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Do difficult hobbies bring more enjoyment?","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-132","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Housing","title":"Housing","prompt":"In some countries, many more people are choosing to live alone nowadays than in the past. Do you think this is a positive or negative development?","answer":"In recent years it has become far more normal for people to live alone, particularly in large cities in the developed world. In my opinion, this trend could have both positive and negative consequences in equal measure.\n\nThe rise in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">one-person households</strong> can be seen as positive for both personal and broader economic reasons. On an individual level, people who choose to live alone may become more independent and self-reliant than those who live with family members. A young adult who lives alone, for example, will need to learn to cook, clean, pay bills and manage his or her budget, all of which are valuable life skills; an increase in the number of such individuals can certainly be seen as a positive development. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">From an economic perspective</strong>, the trend towards living alone will result in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">greater demand for housing</strong>. This is likely to benefit <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the construction industry</strong>, estate agents and a whole host of other companies that rely on homeowners to buy their products or services.\n\nHowever, the personal and economic arguments given above can be considered from the opposite angle. Firstly, rather than the positive feeling of increased independence, people who live alone may experience <strong class=\"key-phrase\">feelings of loneliness, isolation and worry</strong>. They miss out on the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">emotional support</strong> and daily conversation that family or flatmates can provide, and they must bear the weight of all household bills and responsibilities; in this sense, perhaps the trend towards living alone is a negative one. Secondly, from the financial point of view, a rise in demand for housing is likely to push up property prices and rents. While this may benefit some businesses, the general population, including those who live alone, will be faced with rising living costs. In conclusion, the increase in one-person households will have both beneficial and detrimental effects on individuals and on the economy.","phrases":[{"en":"one-person households","vi":"những hộ gia đình có một người"},{"en":"From an economic perspective","vi":"theo góc độ kinh tế"},{"en":"greater demand for housing","vi":"nhu cầu lớn hơn về nhà ở"},{"en":"the construction industry","vi":"ngành xây dựng"},{"en":"feelings of loneliness, isolation and worry","vi":"cảm giác cô đơn, xa lánh và lo lắng"},{"en":"emotional support","vi":"sự hỗ trợ tinh thần"}],"subtype":"Positive / Negative · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#132","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"The rise of one-person households","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-133","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Languages","title":"Languages: Money","prompt":"Several languages are in danger of extinction because they are spoken by very small numbers of people. Some people say that governments should spend public money on saving these languages, while others believe that would be a waste of money. Discuss both these views and give your opinion.","answer":"It is true that some minority languages may disappear in the near future. Although it can be argued that governments could save money by allowing this to happen, I believe that these languages should be protected and preserved.\n\nThere are several reasons why saving minority languages could be seen as a waste of money. Firstly, if a language is only spoken by a small number of people, expensive education programmes will be needed to make sure that more people learn it, and the state will have to pay for facilities, teachers and marketing. This money might be better spent on other public services. Secondly, it would be much cheaper and more efficient for countries to have just one language. Governments could cut all kinds of costs related to communicating with each <strong class=\"key-phrase\">minority group</strong>.\n\nDespite the above arguments, I believe that governments should try to preserve languages that are less widely spoken. A language is much more than simply <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a means of communication</strong>; it has a vital connection with <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the cultural identity</strong> of the people who speak it. If a language disappears, a whole way of life will disappear with it, and we will lose the rich cultural diversity that makes societies more interesting. By spending money to protect minority languages, governments can also preserve traditions, customs and behaviours that are part of a country’s history.\n\nIn conclusion, it may save money in the short term if we allow minority languages to disappear, but in the long term this would have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an extremely negative impact on</strong> our cultural heritage.","phrases":[{"en":"minority group","vi":"dân tộc thiểu số"},{"en":"a means of communication","vi":"phương tiện giao tiếp"},{"en":"the cultural identity","vi":"đặc tính văn hóa"},{"en":"an extremely negative impact on","vi":"tác động cực kỳ tiêu cực đến"}],"subtype":"Discuss both views + opinion · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#133","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Protecting endangered languages","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-134","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Media","title":"Media: Celebrities","prompt":"Nowadays celebrities are more famous for their glamour and wealth than for their achievements, and this sets a bad example to young people. To what extent do you agree or disagree with this statement?","answer":"It is true that some celebrities are known for their glamorous lifestyles rather than for the work they do. While I agree that these celebrities set a bad example for children, I believe that other famous people <strong class=\"key-phrase\">act as positive role models</strong>.\n\nOn the one hand, many people do achieve fame without really working for it. They may have inherited money from parents, married a famous or wealthy person, or they may have appeared in gossip magazines or on a reality TV programme. A good example would be Paris Hilton, who is rich and famous for the wrong reasons. She spends her time attending parties and nightclubs, and her behaviour promotes the idea that appearance, glamour and media profile are more important than hard work and good character. The message to young people is that success can be achieved easily, and that school work is not necessary.\n\nOn the other hand, there are at least as many celebrities whose accomplishments make them excellent role models for young people. Actors, musicians and sports stars become famous idols because they have worked hard and applied themselves to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">develop real skills and abilities</strong>. They demonstrate great effort, determination and ambition, which is required for someone who wants to be truly successful in their chosen field. An example is the actor and martial artist Jackie Chan, who has become world famous through <strong class=\"key-phrase\">years of practice and hard work</strong>. This kind of self-made celebrity can inspire children to develop their talents through application and perseverance.\n\nIn conclusion, it seems to me that the influence of celebrities on young people can be positive as well as negative.","phrases":[{"en":"act as positive role models","vi":"trở thành những hình mẫu tích cực"},{"en":"develop real skills and abilities","vi":"phát triển kỹ năng và năng lực thực chất"},{"en":"years of practice and hard work","vi":"nhiều năm rèn luyện và làm việc chăm chỉ"}],"subtype":"Agree / Disagree · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#134","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Celebrity influence on young people","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-135","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Media","title":"Media","prompt":"Many people prefer to watch foreign films rather than locally produced films. Why could this be? Should governments give more financial support to local film industries?","answer":"It is true that foreign films are more popular in many countries than <strong class=\"key-phrase\">domestically produced films</strong>. There could be several reasons why this is the case, and I believe that governments should promote <strong class=\"key-phrase\">local film-making</strong> by subsidising the industry.\n\nThere are various reasons why many people find foreign films more enjoyable than the films produced in their own countries. Firstly, the established film industries in certain countries have huge budgets for action, special effects and to shoot scenes in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">spectacular locations</strong>. Hollywood blockbusters like “Avatar’ or the James Bond films are examples of such productions, and their global appeal is undeniable. Another reason why these big-budget films are so successful is that they often star the most famous actors and actresses, and they are made by the most accomplished producers and directors. The poor quality, low-budget filmmaking in many countries suffers in comparison.\n\nIn my view, governments should support local film industries financially. In every country, there may be talented <strong class=\"key-phrase\">amateur film-makers</strong> who just need to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">be given the opportunity to</strong> prove themselves. To compete with big-budget productions from overseas, these people need money to pay for film crews, actors and a host of other costs related to producing high-quality films. If governments did help with these costs, they would see an increase in employment in the film industry, income from film sales, and perhaps even a rise in tourist numbers. New Zealand, for example, has seen an increase in tourism related to the 'Lord of the Rings' films, which were partly funded by government subsidies. In conclusion, I believe that increased financial support could help to raise the quality of locally made films and allow them to compete with the foreign productions that currently dominate the market.","phrases":[{"en":"domestically produced films","vi":"phim được sản xuất trong nước"},{"en":"local film-making","vi":"làm phim trong nước"},{"en":"spectacular locations","vi":"những địa điểm ngoạn mục"},{"en":"amateur film-makers","vi":"các nhà làm phim nghiệp dư"},{"en":"be given the opportunity to","vi":"được trao cơ hội để"}],"subtype":"Causes / Effects / Solutions · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#135","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Foreign films and local film funding","band":"9.0"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"News media","prompt":"Details of politicians' private lives should not be published in newspapers. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Politicians should not lose every right to privacy simply because they hold public office. Newspapers should publish private information only when it is clearly relevant to a politician’s duties, honesty or use of public resources.\n\nThere is a legitimate public interest in some personal matters. Undeclared financial relationships, conflicts of interest or behaviour that directly contradicts a public claim may affect trust and decision-making. Investigative reporting is therefore essential when private conduct reveals corruption, abuse of power or serious hypocrisy. In these cases, publication can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">hold powerful people accountable</strong>.\n\nHowever, details about family relationships, health or ordinary leisure activities are often published mainly to attract attention. Such stories can harm relatives who did not choose a public role and may discourage capable people from entering politics. Curiosity is not the same as public interest. Editors should be able to explain how a private fact affects the politician’s work before releasing it.\n\nA useful distinction is whether private information affects public duty. Evidence of corruption, hidden financial interests or serious abuse may be relevant because voters need it to judge integrity. Details about family relationships, health or ordinary leisure usually are not. Newspapers should apply <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a clear public-interest test</strong> instead of publishing material merely because it attracts attention.\n\nIn conclusion, the press needs freedom to investigate those in power, but that freedom should be guided by relevance and proportionality. Private information should be published when it exposes conduct that affects public duty, not merely because it is sensational. This standard would <strong class=\"key-phrase\">protect both accountability and personal dignity</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Media","phrases":[{"en":"hold powerful people accountable","vi":"buộc người có quyền lực phải chịu trách nhiệm"},{"en":"a clear public-interest test","vi":"một phép kiểm tra lợi ích công chúng rõ ràng"},{"en":"protect both accountability and personal dignity","vi":"bảo vệ cả trách nhiệm giải trình lẫn phẩm giá cá nhân"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"opinion","summary":"Politicians' Privacy: Should It Be Protected?","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-136","_displayNo":"#136","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-137","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Museums","title":"Museums","prompt":"Some people think that museums should be enjoyable places to entertain people, while others believe that the purpose of museums is to educate. Discuss both views and give your own opinion.","answer":"People have different views about the role and function of museums. In my opinion, museums can and should be both entertaining and educational.\n\nOn the one hand, it can be argued that the main role of a museum is to entertain. Museums are tourist attractions, and their aim is to exhibit a collection of interesting objects that many people will want to see. The average visitor may become bored if he or she has to read or listen to too much educational content, so museums often <strong class=\"key-phrase\">put more of an emphasis on</strong> enjoyment rather than learning. This type of museum is designed to be visually spectacular, and may have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">interactive activities</strong> or even games as part of its exhibitions.\n\nOn the other hand, some people argue that museums should focus on education. The aim of any exhibition should be to teach visitors something that they did not previously know. Usually this means that the history behind the museum’s exhibits needs to be explained, and this can be done in various ways. Some museums employ professional guides to talk to their visitors, while other museums offer headsets so that visitors can listen to detailed commentary about the exhibition. In this way, museums can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">play an important role in</strong> teaching people about history, culture, science and many other aspects of life.\n\nIn conclusion, it seems to me that a good museum should be able to offer an interesting, enjoyable and educational experience so that people can have fun and learn something at the same time.","phrases":[{"en":"put more of an emphasis on","vi":"chú trọng nhiều hơn vào"},{"en":"interactive activities","vi":"các hoạt động tương tác"},{"en":"play an important role in","vi":"đóng vai trò quan trọng trong"}],"subtype":"Discuss both views + opinion · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#137","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Museums: education or entertainment","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-138","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Music","title":"Music","prompt":"There are many different types of music in the world today. Why do we need music? Is the traditional music of a country more important than the international music that is heard everywhere nowadays?","answer":"It is true that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a rich variety of musical styles</strong> can be found around the world. Music is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a vital part of</strong> all human cultures for a range of reasons, and I would argue that traditional music is more important than modern, international music.\n\nMusic is something that accompanies all of us throughout our lives. As children, we are taught songs by our parents and teachers as a means of learning language, or simply as a form of enjoyment. Children delight in singing with others, and it would appear that the act of singing in a group creates a connection between participants, regardless of their age. Later in life, people’s musical preferences develop, and we come to see our favourite songs as part of our life stories. Music both expresses and arouses emotions in a way that words alone cannot. In short, it is difficult to imagine life without it.\n\nIn my opinion, traditional music should be valued over the international music that has become so popular. International pop music is often catchy and fun, but it is essentially a commercial product that is marketed and sold by business people. Traditional music, by contrast, expresses the culture, customs and history of a country. Traditional styles, such as folk songs and ceremonial music, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">connect us to the past</strong> and form part of our <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cultural identity</strong>. It would be a real pity if pop music became so predominant that these national styles disappeared.\n\nIn conclusion, music is a necessary part of human existence, and I believe that traditional music should be given more importance than international music.","phrases":[{"en":"a rich variety of musical styles","vi":"sự đa dạng phong phú của các phong cách âm nhạc"},{"en":"a vital part of","vi":"một phần thiết yếu của"},{"en":"connect us to the past","vi":"kết nối chúng ta với quá khứ"},{"en":"cultural identity","vi":"bản sắc văn hóa"}],"subtype":"Two-part question · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#138","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"The value of traditional music","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-139","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Online learning","title":"Online Learning","prompt":"Some universities now offer their courses on the Internet so that people can study online. Is this a positive or negative development?","answer":"It is true that online courses are becoming a common feature of university education. Although there are some drawbacks of Internet-based learning, I would argue that there are far more benefits.\n\nThe main drawback of the trend towards online university courses is that there is less direct interaction. Students may not have the opportunity to engage face-to-face with their teachers, and will instead have to rely on written <strong class=\"key-phrase\">forms of communication</strong>. Similarly, students who study online do not come into direct contact with each other, and this could have a negative impact on peer support, discussion and exchange of ideas. For example, whereas students on traditional courses can attend seminars and even discuss their subjects over coffee after lessons, online learners are restricted to chatting through website forum areas. These learners may also lack the motivation and element of competition that face-to-face group work brings.\n\nDespite the negatives mentioned above, I believe that online university courses are a positive development for various reasons. Firstly, they allow learners to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">study in a flexible way</strong>, meaning that they can work whenever and wherever is convenient, and they can cover the material at their own pace. Secondly, the cost of a university education can be greatly reduced, while revenues for institutions may increase as more students can be taught. Finally, online learning offers <strong class=\"key-phrase\">open access to</strong> anybody who is willing to study, regardless of age, location, ability and background. For example, my uncle, who is 65 years old, has recently enrolled on an online MBA course in a different country, which would have been impossible in the days before Internet-based education. In conclusion, while I recognise the possible disadvantages of online learning, I consider it to be a positive development overall.","phrases":[{"en":"forms of communication","vi":"các hình thức giao tiếp"},{"en":"study in a flexible way","vi":"học tập một cách linh hoạt"},{"en":"open access to","vi":"mở rộng quyền tiếp cận"}],"subtype":"Positive / Negative · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#139","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Online university courses","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-140","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society","prompt":"Some people think that in the modern world we are more dependent on each other, while others think that people have become more independent. Discuss both views and give your own opinion.","answer":"People have different views about whether we are more or less dependent on others nowadays. In my view, modern life forces us to be more independent than people were in the past.\n\nThere are two main reasons why it could be argued that we are more dependent on each other now. Firstly, life is more complex and difficult, especially because <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the cost of living</strong> has increased so dramatically. For example, young adults tend to rely on their parents for help when buying a house. Property prices are higher than ever, and without help it would be impossible for many people to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">pay a deposit and a mortgage</strong>. Secondly, people seem to be more ambitious nowadays, and they want a better quality of life for their families. This means that both parents usually need to work full-time, and they depend on support from grandparents and babysitters for child care.\n\nHowever, I would agree with those who believe that people are more independent these days. In most countries, families are becoming smaller and more dispersed, which means that people cannot count on relatives as much as they used to. We also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">have more freedom to</strong> travel and live far away from our home towns. For example, many students choose to study abroad instead of going to their local university, and this experience makes them more independent as they learn to live alone. Another factor in this growing independence is technology, which allows us to work alone and from any part of the world.\n\nIn conclusion, while there are some reasons to believe that people now depend on each other more, my own view is that we are more independent than ever.","phrases":[{"en":"the cost of living","vi":"chi phí sinh hoạt"},{"en":"pay a deposit and a mortgage","vi":"trả tiền đặt cọc và khoản vay thế chấp"},{"en":"have more freedom to","vi":"có nhiều tự do hơn để"}],"subtype":"Discuss both views + opinion · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#140","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Modern independence and interdependence","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-141","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society","prompt":"The older generations tend to have very traditional ideas about how people should live, think and behave. However, some people believe that these ideas are not helpful in preparing younger generations for modern life. To what extent do you agree or disagree with this view?","answer":"It is true that many older people believe in traditional values that often seem incompatible with the needs of younger people. While I agree that some traditional ideas are outdated, I believe that others are still useful and should not be forgotten.\n\nOn the one hand, many of the ideas that elderly people have about life are becoming less relevant for younger people. In the past, for example, people were advised to learn a profession and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">find a secure job</strong> for life, but today’s workers expect much more variety and diversity from their careers. At the same time, the “rules’ around relationships are being eroded as young adults <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make their own choices</strong> about who and when to marry. But perhaps the greatest disparity between the generations can be seen in their attitudes towards gender roles. The traditional roles of men and women, as <strong class=\"key-phrase\">breadwinners and housewives</strong>, are no longer accepted as necessary or appropriate by most younger people.\n\nOn the other hand, some traditional views and values are certainly applicable to the modern world. For example, older generations attach great importance to working hard, doing one’s best, and taking pride in one’s work, and these behaviours can surely benefit young people as they enter today’s competitive job market. Other characteristics that are perhaps seen as traditional are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">politeness and good manners</strong>. In our globalised world, young adults can expect to come into contact with people from <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a huge variety of backgrounds</strong>, and it is more important than ever to treat others with respect. Finally, I believe that young people would lead happier lives if they had a more “old-fashioned’ sense of community and neighbourliness. In conclusion, although the views of older people may sometimes seem unhelpful in today’s world, we should not dismiss all traditional ideas as irrelevant.","phrases":[{"en":"find a secure job","vi":"tìm một công việc đảm bảo"},{"en":"make their own choices","vi":"tự đưa ra lựa chọn"},{"en":"breadwinners and housewives","vi":"trụ cột và người phụ nữ trong gia đình"},{"en":"politeness and good manners","vi":"sự lịch sự và cách cư xử đúng mực"},{"en":"a huge variety of backgrounds","vi":"rất nhiều xuất thân khác nhau"}],"subtype":"Agree / Disagree · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#141","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Traditional values in modern life","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-142","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society: Money","prompt":"Some people think that it is best to save money, for example in a bank or savings scheme. Other people feel that money should be spent whenever it is available. Discuss these views and reach an opinion on this debate. Give reasons for your answer, and support your essay with ideas and examples from your own experience. You should write at least 250 words.","answer":"The question of whether to save or spend money is very topical today, as so many people are struggling with financial worries. There are valid arguments on both sides, which I will discuss now. On the one hand, it is often said that spending money is one way to relax and enjoy life, for instance by shopping or taking holidays, and there is certainly some truth in this. In addition, we usually have no choice but to spend quite a large proportion of our available salary on day to day expenses such as food, housing and transport, and so there is surprisingly little remaining to save anyway. Finally, spending money on products and services boosts the economy and creates employment, and in this sense is a worthwhile action. On the other hand, other people point out the dangers of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reckless spending</strong>, for example on frivolous or unnecessary items, which is often encouraged by advertising. Young people in particular are vulnerable to being influenced like this. Furthermore, advocates of saving often point out that, without <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a reserve of funds for emergencies</strong>, unemployment or illness, people are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">putting themselves at risk of hardship</strong> or even bankruptcy. This is especially true in the current economic situation. Lastly on this side of the debate, people emphasise the need to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">accumulate wealth</strong> during one’s lifetime, so that one’s children can inherit money or property which will increase their security and standard of living. Overall, I tend to agree that it is wiser to save money wherever possible, for reasons which benefit both individuals today and future generations.","phrases":[{"en":"reckless spending","vi":"chi tiêu thiếu kiểm soát"},{"en":"a reserve of funds for emergencies","vi":"khoản dự phòng cho tình huống khẩn cấp"},{"en":"putting themselves at risk of hardship","vi":"đẩy bản thân vào nguy cơ khó khăn"},{"en":"accumulate wealth","vi":"tích lũy tài sản"}],"subtype":"Discussion","_displayNo":"#142","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"People think that it is best to save money, for example in a bank or…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-143","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society: Children","prompt":"Many people today are worried about young children using video games. What problems might these games cause, for children and society as a whole? How could these problems be reduced?","answer":"The almost universal availability of video games among children has presented us with a number of challenges and decisions, none of which are straightforward. I believe there are three main problems associated with these products, and also three remedies we can adopt. Perhaps the major problem we need to deal with is the level of violence found in these games. Many of them feature aggressive or warlike characters, ranging from soldiers to criminals and killers. This inevitably leads children to believe that such behaviour is normal, or even desirable. A second issue is the obsessive way that some children use the games – for example, preferring their computers to real friendships, making these children isolated and socially naïve. Finally, there are physical effects from excessive gaming, including eye strain, insomnia and damage to posture. These can be difficult to reverse once they have taken hold. Turning to possible solutions, one key step would be to legislate more strictly to control the content of these games. They could, for instance, be reviewed by censors in the same way that films are. This would prevent unsuitable material influencing young minds. To <strong class=\"key-phrase\">tackle the problem</strong> of obsessive use, we could make more counselling and advice available through schools.\n\nTo reduce physical side effects, advice on safe use could be included as part of the packaging or even the game itself, so that youngsters are constantly aware of the risks. To sum up, this is a problem that has both social and physical effects, and the solution will require combined action by manufacturers, schools and authorities.","phrases":[{"en":"tackle the problem","vi":"xử lý vấn đề"}],"subtype":"Causes / Effects","_displayNo":"#143","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"People today are worried about young children using video games.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-144","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society: Children","prompt":"The children who grow up in a family short of money are more capable of dealing with problems in adult life than children who are brought up by wealthy parents. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Of those elements that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">bear a considerable influence on</strong> children’s personal development, one of the most influential is family background. There is a perception that the children who grow up in an impoverished family are more capable of solving problems than those from an affluent family. In my opinion, it might not always be the case.\n\nOne’s problem-solving abilities are mainly derived from the knowledge and experience obtained during his or her adolescence. Not surprisingly, children from poor families are less likely to maximise their education. First of all, their parents are unwilling to select a reputable school for them, as tuition fees can take up a large proportion of family income. Another reason is that education, in general, requires devoted time and energy, but many children have to work from an early age to supplement their parents’ income. Because of their poor educational background, they do not have specialised knowledge in solving problems as required in a specific area of work. They are thus <strong class=\"key-phrase\">at a severe disadvantage</strong> in problem-solving in a working environment.\n\nAnother problem that plagues the children from less advantaged backgrounds is their <strong class=\"key-phrase\">limited access to financial support</strong> and expert guidance. Children with highly-educated and rich parents are more likely to be better off economically, not only because they have sufficient financial backup but also because they can easily seek the support from others, for example, the friends of their parents, professionals in different occupations. It is true that compared with disadvantaged children, children from medium or high class families have many more opportunities to attend social functions like balls, banquets, and so forth, where they improve social skills, learn professional etiquette and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">consolidate their social network</strong>. With a larger social network, they are at an advantage in problem-solving.\n\nAs discussed above, while children from a poor background are normally socially inept and less knowledgeable, those from middle or upper class families have easy access to resources. These distinctions corroborate the assertion that family background has undisputed impacts on children’s problem solving abilities.","phrases":[{"en":"bear a considerable influence on","vi":"có ảnh hưởng đáng kể đến"},{"en":"at a severe disadvantage","vi":"ở thế bất lợi nghiêm trọng"},{"en":"limited access to financial support","vi":"khả năng tiếp cận hỗ trợ tài chính hạn chế"},{"en":"consolidate their social network","vi":"củng cố mạng lưới quan hệ xã hội"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#144","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Children who grow up in a family short of money are more capable of dealing…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-145","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society","prompt":"Discuss the reasons why people define happiness differently and how to\nobtain happiness?","answer":"People define happiness differently because they have different needs, values and life circumstances. For one person, happiness may mean professional success; for another, it may come from family life, health or personal freedom. In my view, people are most likely to become happy when their goals reflect their own values rather than social pressure.\n\nAge and circumstance strongly influence what matters to an individual. A student may value friendship and opportunity, while a parent may place greater importance on security and time with children. Income also changes priorities. Someone struggling to pay for food or housing will naturally connect happiness with financial stability, whereas a wealthy person may seek meaning, relationships or creative achievement. These differences explain why there is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">no single formula for happiness</strong>.\n\nPersonality is equally important. Some people enjoy competition and public recognition, while others prefer a quiet and predictable life. Culture also shapes expectations about marriage, work and personal independence. Problems arise when people pursue goals mainly because those goals appear impressive to others. A high salary or prestigious title may bring little satisfaction if the daily work conflicts with a person’s interests or health.\n\nA practical route to happiness is to identify a small number of realistic priorities and invest time in them consistently. Close relationships, useful work, adequate rest and physical health provide a stronger foundation than constant comparison with other people. It is also helpful to accept that happiness is not a permanent emotional state. A good life can include difficulty while still offering <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a stable sense of purpose and contentment</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, happiness varies because people differ in both circumstances and values. The best way to pursue it is to set realistic goals, protect important relationships and judge progress by <strong class=\"key-phrase\">personally meaningful standards</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"no single formula for happiness","vi":"không có một công thức duy nhất cho hạnh phúc"},{"en":"a stable sense of purpose and contentment","vi":"cảm giác ổn định về mục đích và sự mãn nguyện"},{"en":"personally meaningful standards","vi":"những tiêu chuẩn có ý nghĩa đối với chính bản thân"}],"subtype":"Causes / Effects","_displayNo":"#145","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Discuss the reasons why people define happiness differently and how…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-146","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society","prompt":"Earlier technological development brought more changes to the life of ordinary people than recent technological development do. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Earlier inventions such as electricity, sanitation, the railway and the motor car transformed ordinary life on a remarkable scale. Nevertheless, I do not agree that recent technology has produced fewer changes. Digital systems have altered communication, work, commerce and access to knowledge in ways that are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">equally far-reaching</strong>.\n\nThe case for earlier technology is strong because it solved basic physical problems. Electricity extended productive hours, clean water reduced disease, and modern transport allowed people and goods to move quickly. These developments <strong class=\"key-phrase\">created the foundations of urban life</strong> and raised life expectancy. Their effect was immediate and visible across entire populations.\n\nRecent technology, however, has changed how people organise almost every daily activity. A smartphone now serves as a bank, map, camera, library and communication device. Remote work and online education allow services to cross national borders, while digital medical records and data analysis improve diagnosis. These changes may appear less dramatic than the arrival of electricity, but they have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">restructured the way information and decisions move through society</strong>.\n\nThe two periods are also connected: modern digital tools depend on earlier infrastructure. It is therefore unhelpful to rank one era as universally more important. In conclusion, earlier inventions met fundamental physical needs, while recent innovations have transformed coordination and knowledge. Both have brought <strong class=\"key-phrase\">changes of comparable depth</strong> in different areas of life.\n\nThe impact of recent innovation is also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">still unfolding</strong>, particularly in artificial intelligence, biotechnology and clean energy. Their long-term consequences may eventually be as visible as those of the railway or the electric grid.","phrases":[{"en":"equally far-reaching","vi":"có tầm ảnh hưởng sâu rộng tương đương"},{"en":"created the foundations of urban life","vi":"tạo nền tảng cho đời sống đô thị"},{"en":"restructured the way information and decisions move through society","vi":"tái định hình cách thông tin và quyết định vận hành trong xã hội"},{"en":"changes of comparable depth","vi":"những thay đổi có chiều sâu tương đương"},{"en":"still unfolding","vi":"vẫn đang tiếp diễn"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#146","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Earlier technological development brought more changes to the life of…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-147","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society","prompt":"Fashion is difficult to follow, and some people argue that we should not follow it. They think that we should dress what we like and feel comfortable. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Fashion refers to a style of clothing worn by most people of a country. The growing concern about fashion in recent years comes as no surprise, considering the fact that fashion is very often at odds with, the traditional function of clothing, protecting wearers from the extremes of weather. In my opinion fashion is not a betrayal but an indicative of a principle that wearing clothing is for both functional and social reasons.\n\nFashions are linked to personal style. Fashions allow wearers to express emotion and solidarity with other people. People dress to their mood and according to circumstances. Buying fashionable clothes is a process in which the buyer translates his or her self-esteem into a personal style. A fashion indicates one’s taste, social class, likes and dislikes. It gives wearers a sense of identity and makes it possible for them to feel connected to society.\n\nFashions are designed and tailored to please buyers. Selecting, discussing and buying fashions can induce immense happiness. It has become a way of life and can be taken as a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">leisure activity</strong>, increasing interaction between people. With all types of images and colours, clothing is capable of giving buyers a desired look, boosting their moods and increasing their self-confidence. Fashion is about change which is necessary to keep life interesting.\n\nDespite the enjoyment brought by fashions, people should beware of their ever-changing nature and the expenditure of time and money on this commitment. A fashion usually remains popular for about one or two years at most and then is replaced by another. Many people have been obsessed with following the current fashions slavishly and pursuing the clothing with promised quality and limited availability ceaselessly, Many of them are motivated to buy outlandish clothing in a belief that they can thus keep up with fashion and their social positions are displayed\n\nOverall, there is no point in spurning fashion. Fashion is desired in a modern society as a means of expression and a source of enjoyment, although one should reduce unnecessary spending on fashions.","phrases":[{"en":"leisure activity","vi":"hoạt động giải trí"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#147","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Fashion is difficult to follow, and some people argue that we should not…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-148","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society: Advertising","prompt":"The high sales of popular consumer goods reflect the power of advertising but not the real need of the society where such products are sold. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Advertising is well-known as a method of promotion, a method used by corporations t0 introduce their products and services to the market, attract the eye of consumers and increase, sales. Critics of advertising argue that advertising is the main drive of soaring sales of some products and services, inducing consumers to purchase what they do not actually need in their daily lives. This contention is self-evident.\n\nAdvertisements conquer the audience mainly by sending them a message that they are lacking a specific brand or product that is likely to make them acceptable or even distinguished individuals in society. The advertisements as to medicine, dietary supplement and other life-enhancing products provide a typical example. Targeting the buyers that are doubtful or worried about health, advertisers have sought to encourage them to think that they are threatened by such problems as malnutrition, dysfunction of any part of their bodies. Lack of the knowledge in this field, the audience will rush to buy the advertised products. Such cases are ever-present, and the audience expects an immediate positive outcome —disregarding other solutions.\n\nAdvertising also works to create a best-seller image for a newly-marketed product. The audience is tempted to buy it in the hope that they can thus become one of the eyewitnesses and participants of a fad. It is not uncommon that cell phone users replace their phones every year, although the phone they have abandoned is still in usable conditions. They might not actually need to make purchases so frequently, but advertising spurs them to do so. The power of advertising has too often abused by advertisers, who tend to give an exaggerated account of the popularity of a product, soon after the product is marketed. So gullible are some buyers that they are driven to buy it. With the number of buyers growing, it will evolve into a buying craze.\n\nIn conclusion, people should stay alert to the influence advertising has on their decision making process. As indicated above, advertising has twisted the information about what product is needed, or what product is favoured, thereby driving people to make insensible buying decisions.\n\nHE DE\n\nOverall, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a balanced approach</strong> is more likely to create <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a long-term benefit</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"a balanced approach","vi":"một cách tiếp cận cân bằng"},{"en":"a long-term benefit","vi":"một lợi ích lâu dài"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#148","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"High sales of popular consumer goods reflect the power of advertising but…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-149","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society","prompt":"Opinions divide concerning what plays a more important role in people’s personality development, nature or nurture. What is your opinion?","answer":"The i idea of nature-versus-nurture has long been debated, with no conclusive resolution. People are faced with an apparent paradox: while some studies have ascertained that no nexus exists between genes and behavioural patterns, anecdotal evidence suggests that it is not <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a foregone conclusion</strong>. This essay is to evaluate these two schools of thoughts, with some facts being closely examined.\n\nIt is still a myth why some children, born in affluent families and raised in a positive enriching environment, still <strong class=\"key-phrase\">embark on a career of crime</strong> and self destruction. It points to factors outside of the parental and educational environment; or in plain words, it could <strong class=\"key-phrase\">be traced back to</strong> genetics and thus a natural progression. It must be remembered that life is not simple. Nor is any human being. Even though environment is so overwhelming that it either suppresses or fortifies personality traits of individuals, individuals differ from each other <strong class=\"key-phrase\">in many aspects</strong>, rather than show identical traits. Genetic difference shows its effect from as carly as one’s preschool years, throughout adolescence and into adulthood.\n\nThe impacts of nature seem sizeable in some other cases. For example, a couple can give birth to twins who resemble each other in both appearance and behaviour. Ruthlessly separated at birth, and brought up in completely different environment, the twins would most likely grow into identical adults, developing extremely similar characteristics and even showing the same likes and dislikes. So striking are the effects of their genetic make-up that those of the environment are obscured.\n\nDespite the strong proof that nature is responsible for one’s behaviour, it is not to deny the function of the environment people are raised in. Studies show that many young criminals come from problem families, who have a history of violence and crime. Without good job prospects, they end up with finding solace in gangs. The circle of poverty and crime will continue, as these young criminals start new families with the characteristics of their own.\n\nAs suggested above, people are made up by both learned and born traits. There is no need to reach a conclusion that either environment or nature plays a decisive part in one’s character and behaviour development. Although the effect of genetic heredity is overt, one cannot afford to ignore that of environment where a child is brought up.","phrases":[{"en":"a foregone conclusion","vi":"một kết luận đã được định trước / điều chắc chắn"},{"en":"embark on a career of crime","vi":"bắt đầu con đường phạm tội"},{"en":"be traced back to","vi":"có thể truy nguyên về / bắt nguồn từ"},{"en":"in many aspects","vi":"ở nhiều khía cạnh"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#149","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Opinions divide concerning what plays a more important role in people’s…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-150","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society","prompt":"Many people are optimistic about the 21st century and expect scientists to make positive changes to the world. To what extent do you agree or disagree with their optimism? What changes would you like to see in the new century?","answer":"I am cautiously optimistic about the twenty-first century. Science has the potential to improve health, energy and living standards, but progress will only be positive if governments use new knowledge responsibly. The changes I would most like to see concern clean energy and equal access to healthcare.\n\nThere are good reasons for optimism. Medical research has already made many diseases easier to diagnose and treat, while digital technology allows knowledge to spread quickly. Further advances in vaccines, early screening and personalised treatment could <strong class=\"key-phrase\">extend healthy life expectancy</strong>. Science can also make farming more efficient and help cities use water and energy more carefully.\n\nHowever, scientific progress can create new risks. Automation may remove jobs faster than workers can retrain, and poorly regulated data systems can threaten privacy. Environmental technology will also have limited value if countries continue to depend on fossil fuels. I would therefore like governments to invest heavily in renewable energy, public transport and energy-efficient housing. These measures would <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reduce emissions at source</strong> rather than simply deal with their consequences.\n\nA second priority should be affordable healthcare. Breakthroughs are of little value if only wealthy people can use them. Public funding, international cooperation and fair pricing are needed so that essential treatment is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">available regardless of income</strong>. Overall, science gives us strong reasons for hope, but its benefits must be guided by clear ethical rules and shared widely.\n\nScientific progress alone will not guarantee a better century. New medicines, clean energy and more efficient farming can improve millions of lives, but access and regulation determine who benefits. I would particularly like to see research focused on affordable disease prevention and low-carbon infrastructure. These priorities could <strong class=\"key-phrase\">turn technical progress into widely shared human progress</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"extend healthy life expectancy","vi":"kéo dài số năm sống khỏe mạnh"},{"en":"reduce emissions at source","vi":"giảm phát thải ngay từ nguồn"},{"en":"available regardless of income","vi":"được tiếp cận bất kể thu nhập"},{"en":"turn technical progress into widely shared human progress","vi":"biến tiến bộ kỹ thuật thành tiến bộ con người được chia sẻ rộng rãi"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#150","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People are optimistic about the 21st century and expect scientists to make…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-151","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society: Advertising","prompt":"Some people argue that advertising is discouraging people from being different individuals, and makes people to be or seem to be the same. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Advertising often encourages people to buy the same popular products, but it does not completely remove individuality. I partly agree that advertising promotes conformity, especially through global brands and social media. However, consumers still interpret messages differently and can use products to express personal preferences.\n\nThe pressure to conform is real. Companies repeat images of the ideal home, body or lifestyle until these standards appear normal. Influencers then display the same clothes, phones and beauty products to millions of followers. Young consumers may purchase these items mainly to avoid feeling excluded. In this way, advertising can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">turn social approval into a sales tool</strong> and narrow the range of choices that seem acceptable.\n\nNevertheless, people are not passive. Income, age, culture and personal values shape how they respond to a campaign. The same advertisement may attract one person and annoy another. Digital markets also make specialised products easier to find, so individuals can choose independent designers, niche music or goods linked to particular interests. Advertising may influence the options people notice, but it rarely determines every final decision.\n\nPlatforms and regulators can also require clear labels for paid promotion, helping audiences separate personal recommendation from commercial persuasion. It also discourages hidden commercial influence in everyday online content.\n\nIn conclusion, advertising contributes to similar tastes by promoting a limited set of highly visible lifestyles. Yet it cannot erase personal judgement or cultural difference. The best response is not to blame advertising for all conformity, but to improve media literacy and give consumers <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a wider and more transparent range of choices</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"turn social approval into a sales tool","vi":"biến sự công nhận của xã hội thành công cụ bán hàng"},{"en":"a wider and more transparent range of choices","vi":"một phạm vi lựa chọn rộng hơn và minh bạch hơn"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#151","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People argue that advertising is discouraging people from being different…","band":"8.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-152","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society","prompt":"Some people argue that history is of little or no use to us. Others believe that studying history gives many benefits. Discuss those views and give your own opinion.","answer":"History has long been <strong class=\"key-phrase\">recognised as a discipline</strong>, but it seems to be a fact that few students have a clear concept of why they should study it. Many people even argue that studying history is meaningless, considering the past differs in many important ways from the present. In my opinion, there are many facts to show the importance of history as a subject,\n\nDespite the scepticism over <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the relevance of historical events</strong> to today’s society, understanding the past contributes to people’s decision making in today’s social context. By studying history, people can draw on the experience of the generations before them, taking a similar path to success and avoiding a dead-end. Besides, they understand how and why people (e. g., Hitler, Napoleon) behaved as they did. They are aware that people are neither good nor bad but motivated in complex ways. Instead of being misguided by stereotypes or historians, one learns to analyse issues or subjects based on historical context and perspective, take a dispassionate view toward today’s political and social problems and trace origins and causes objectively\n\nTo students, studying history is not only to seek self-knowledge, but also to enhance their skills and make themselves all-round individuals. The study of history requires independent research as well as coherent explanations. Students are encouraged to do as much work independently as they can and to read widely and extensively. In addition to widening their experience, it helps students develop qualities of perception and judgements. Students are increasingly capable to analyse and compare conflicting views. All these improvements can foster a student’s intellectual independence, sharpness and maturity. These strengths are transferable across occupations and careers.\n\nAlthough studying history is beneficial, its importance should not be overstated. The world is changing so rapidly that the lesson from the past might be applicable in particular circumstances only, For instance, imperialism is now occurring in business or culture, rather than in colonies. Taking the same approaches to combat imperialism might be counterproductive. Studying history should not be taken as a demanding job but preferably as a pastime that satisfies people’s curiosity over the past. In addressing real-life issues, current events give people more hints and advice than historical events do.\n\nFrom what has been discussed, studying history is very important, particularly in increasing one’s knowledge and enhancing one’s intellectual abilities. However, it should not be attached with unjustified importance because its applications in today’s society are not known with certainty.","phrases":[{"en":"recognised as a discipline","vi":"được công nhận là một ngành học"},{"en":"the relevance of historical events","vi":"sự liên quan của các sự kiện lịch sử"}],"subtype":"Discussion","_displayNo":"#152","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People argue that history is of little or no use to us.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-153","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society","prompt":"Many people believe that the human society has developed into a throw-away society, which is filled with plastic bags and rubbish. What are the causes and solutions?","answer":"Although waste disposal does not grab a headline as frequently as many other environmental issues do, it does not mean that it is less serious. As a matter of fact, the treatment of garbage continues to be a problem worldwide. Despite its sizable influence, many citizens have not yet realised the seriousness of this issue, It is the goal of this article to outline the potential causes of this problem and suggest possible solutions, People should first recognise that the increment in garbage is a natural result of the social and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">economic development</strong>. Unethical businesses are the main creators of industrial waste, including heavy metal, chemicals, plastic, and other durable and non-recyclable materials. People’s quest for a better standard of living gives them incentives to manufacture a rich variety of consumer goods and disregard the potential impact on environment. This practice can date back to the earliest days of industrial revolution, producing enormous waste that are unable to be recycled and causing an environmental disaster. Another potential reason for the slow progress in waste treatment is people’s low awareness of the opportunities to reduce, reuse and recycle waste. Many people do not have a firm stand against over-consumption and excessive production of disposable items. Besides, many citizens are not environmentally conscious, disposing of wastes whenever and wherever they consider convenient. Meanwhile, many manufacturers tend to use virgin materials, rather than recyclable materials in the course of production. That’s why many communities are facing a particularly difficult position in waste treatment. The best approach to address waste issues is simply to minimise its generation, It is primarily because the more waste people produce, the more waste they have to cope with. Waste recycling offers another means, although it requires the spontaneous commitment of both businesses and citizens. Additionally, laws should be set out to regulate corporation behaviour and make their operation <strong class=\"key-phrase\">environmentally friendly</strong>. It is clear that the problem of waste disposal exists due to people’s ever-growing demand for manufactured goods and slow response to the impact of this problem on the environment. Tackling this problem depends not only on individuals' efforts to keep the waste to a minimum but also on businesses’ attempt to optimise their manufacture and reduce the inputs.","phrases":[{"en":"economic development","vi":"phát triển kinh tế"},{"en":"environmentally friendly","vi":"thân thiện với môi trường"}],"subtype":"Causes / Solutions","_displayNo":"#153","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People believe that the human society has developed into a throw-away…","band":"8.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-154","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society: Children","prompt":"Some people think that children should learn to compete, but others think that they should be taught to cooperate with others. What’s your opinion?","answer":"Competition can motivate children, while cooperation teaches them to work with others. In my view, schools should develop both qualities, but cooperation deserves greater emphasis because most adult achievements depend on shared effort rather than individual victory.\n\nHealthy competition can encourage pupils to practise, set goals and measure progress. A race, debate or academic challenge may show a child what focused effort can achieve. Problems arise when success is defined only as defeating classmates. Constant ranking can make weaker pupils withdraw, encourage cheating and create the belief that another person’s progress is a threat.\n\nCooperative tasks develop a broader set of skills. When pupils plan a presentation or solve a practical problem in a group, they must listen, explain ideas, divide responsibilities and manage disagreement. These abilities are essential in universities and workplaces. Cooperation also allows children with different strengths to contribute, which can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">turn individual ability into a stronger collective result</strong>.\n\nSchools do not need to remove competition entirely. They can compare teams, reward personal improvement and ensure that every child has a meaningful role. In conclusion, competition is useful when it remains fair and limited, but cooperation should form the foundation of classroom life. It prepares children to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">succeed without treating others as obstacles</strong>.\n\nTeachers should also assess both the final result and each pupil’s contribution. Otherwise, one confident child may control the task while quieter members receive little practice. Clear roles, peer feedback and rotating leadership make cooperation fairer and more educational. It also prevents group work from becoming a reward only for confident speakers.","phrases":[{"en":"turn individual ability into a stronger collective result","vi":"biến năng lực cá nhân thành kết quả tập thể mạnh hơn"},{"en":"succeed without treating others as obstacles","vi":"thành công mà không coi người khác là trở ngại"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#154","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People think that children should learn to compete, but others think that…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-155","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society","prompt":"People think that old buildings should be knocked down and give way to the new buildings. Do you agree or disagree? How important are old buildings to us?","answer":"Some old buildings should be protected, while others should be replaced when they are unsafe or no longer useful. I therefore disagree with the idea that age alone is a reason either to preserve or demolish a structure. Decisions should be based on historical value, condition and the needs of the surrounding community.\n\nImportant old buildings connect people with the history of a place. A traditional market, theatre or government building may show how earlier generations lived and what materials or techniques they used. Such structures can strengthen local identity, support tourism and provide architects with practical examples of earlier design. Once a unique building is destroyed, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">its cultural value cannot be recreated</strong> by a modern copy.\n\nNevertheless, preservation has limits. Some buildings are structurally dangerous, extremely expensive to maintain or poorly suited to modern needs. Keeping every ageing structure can prevent the construction of housing, schools or transport links in areas where land is scarce. In these cases, demolition may be justified after an independent assessment. Useful parts of the original building, such as a façade or significant interior features, can sometimes be incorporated into a new development.\n\nThe best policy is a clear classification system. Buildings of genuine architectural or historical importance should receive legal protection and realistic maintenance funding. Ordinary structures should be assessed more flexibly, with public consultation and a full comparison of renovation and replacement costs. This creates <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a balance between heritage and present-day needs</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, old buildings are important when they carry distinctive cultural, historical or design value. Others may reasonably give way to safer and more useful development, provided that the decision is based on evidence rather than short-term profit.","phrases":[{"en":"its cultural value cannot be recreated","vi":"giá trị văn hóa của nó không thể được tái tạo"},{"en":"a balance between heritage and present-day needs","vi":"sự cân bằng giữa di sản và nhu cầu hiện tại"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#155","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People think that old buildings should be knocked down and give way to the…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-156","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society","prompt":"Some people think that radio has become out-of-date, and there is no need to listen to the radio for entertainment and news. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"In the past, radio broadcasting was deemed as the most convenient and important source of information. However, with the emergence of other mass media, there is a perception that radio as a medium will be at stake in the future if it does not undergo any significant change. In my opinion, such pessimism is ungrounded.\n\nOne of the main reasons why radio would not become obsolete in the near future is that driving is rife across the world as a way of life. Radio is a regular piece of equipment installed in a car, and to car users, listening to the radio while driving is an effective means of taking full advantage of their time and gaining the latest information, such as news, weather forecast, share markets, and so forth. Increased car use gives radio high mobility and its exposure continues to lead other media. For those people who have no time in watching TV, radio provides immediate and easy <strong class=\"key-phrase\">access to information</strong>. Its continued popularity is also linked to its high affordability. Radio broadcasting is, in general, accessible to the audience with charging no fee. Another overt advantage is that a radio set is portable. On the occasions where people cannot watch TV, read newspapers or surf the net, they can listen to the radio\n\nThe advent of other technologies has also sustained the popularity of radio, For example, people can get radio via satellite, the Internet and cable nowadays. There are many other electronic devices, such as MP3 and MP4 players, which allow people to listen to the radio more easily and to use it for various entertainments, such as sharing their music collections. Although radio is unable to convey messages with sight and motion as television or Internet does, the improvement in those hi-tech devices will ensure that the radio can serve the needs of audiences as it always did.\n\nAs indicated above, radio broadcasting has many advantages that are scarcely found in other mass media, either electronic or print. With the developments in technology that enable radio to perform more functions and become more widely available, radio broadcasting will continue to form a very large segment of the mass media.","phrases":[{"en":"access to information","vi":"khả năng tiếp cận thông tin"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#156","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People think that radio has become out-of-date, and there is no need to…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-157","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society","prompt":"Some people think that telling the truth is not always essential. It is necessary to tell lies sometimes. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Honesty is essential for trust, but I do not believe that every fact must be stated in every situation. Small lies can sometimes be justified when they prevent unnecessary harm and do not deceive someone about an important decision.\n\nThe main reason to value truth is that relationships and institutions depend on reliable information. People need accurate facts when they make choices about health, money, work or family matters. A person who lies for personal gain may damage others and eventually lose credibility. For this reason, honesty should remain <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the normal rule rather than the exception</strong>.\n\nEven so, complete openness can occasionally be cruel or pointless. A gentle compliment may protect someone’s feelings, and a surprise party requires temporary secrecy. In more serious cases, a doctor might choose careful language when giving difficult news, although the patient should still receive the information needed to make decisions. The important test is whether the lie is intended to protect another person or merely to protect the liar. A harmless social lie should not be treated in the same way as <strong class=\"key-phrase\">deliberate deception for personal benefit</strong>.\n\nThe important distinction is between a harmless social lie and deception that removes another person’s ability to make an informed decision. Protecting a surprise party is very different from hiding debt, danger or professional misconduct. In serious matters, honesty should be the default because trust depends on <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reliable access to relevant facts</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, telling the truth is normally the best policy because it creates trust and accountability. Nevertheless, limited exceptions are reasonable when the issue is minor, the intention is kind and no important right is affected. This approach <strong class=\"key-phrase\">balances honesty with compassion</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"the normal rule rather than the exception","vi":"nguyên tắc thông thường chứ không phải ngoại lệ"},{"en":"deliberate deception for personal benefit","vi":"sự lừa dối có chủ đích vì lợi ích cá nhân"},{"en":"reliable access to relevant facts","vi":"khả năng tiếp cận đáng tin cậy với các sự thật liên quan"},{"en":"balances honesty with compassion","vi":"cân bằng sự trung thực với lòng cảm thông"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#157","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People think that telling the truth is not always essential.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-158","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society: Older people","prompt":"In many countries, the proportion of older people is increasing steadily. Do you think it is a positive or negative change to the society?","answer":"In many countries, the trends toward fewer children and more senior citizens are proceeding at an accelerated pace. A long and healthy old age was previously a cause for celebration, but now viewed as a “burden on society”. As far as I see, fears that problems will arise from an <strong class=\"key-phrase\">ageing population</strong> are unfounded.\n\nPeople tend to believe that the ageing of a society leads to slower growth of population size and to a shrinking workforce. The dominant way of looking at an older society has been to see this as a problem—an increasing burden on the working population. The fact is that as the number of young people falls, organisations will find it harder to recruit from their traditional pool of school-leavers and graduates. To tackle this problem, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an increasing number of</strong> sectors and companies are now desperate to keep their highly experienced older workers. Therefore, an ageing population will by no means constitute a problem because older people should work at or beyond retirement age. Nor will it lead to a crisis of labour.\n\nAnother widespread worry is the sufficiency of wealth available in society to sustain the retired population, Paradoxically, when people are concerned about the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">public expenditure</strong> on the retired population, they have ignored private transfers of time and money from the old generation to the young one. It is important to note that parents’ earning capacity grows nowadays because of having fewer children. The total time they spend caring for dependents drops, and they are thus released for productive work. When they reach retirement age, they are in a stronger position with better financial security. In later years their children should receive an adequate inheritance, assisting them in turn to achieve a comfortable retirement.\n\nIn addition to establishing a solid financial base for families, older people also have time to offer for other benefits of family and those of the community. Healthy and energetic, they are the backbone of voluntary services. Voluntary services are not worthless just because they are unpaid. Senior workers can provide families or voluntary organisations with legal, accounting, computer or other skills for free.\n\nAs suggested above, the fear that people will suffer from the “burden” of too many elderly people is unreasonable. Any issue that arises from having a larger, older and healthier elderly population should not be viewed as a challenge for the century to come, because improving health and increased life expectancy mean that today’s older population can lead a fuller life than any generation before them.","phrases":[{"en":"ageing population","vi":"dân số già hóa"},{"en":"an increasing number of","vi":"số lượng ngày càng tăng"},{"en":"public expenditure","vi":"chi tiêu công"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#158","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"The proportion of older people is increasing steadily.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-159","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society","prompt":"Throughout the history, male leaders often made the society more violent and conflicting. If women governed the world, the world would be more peaceful. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"The claim that female leaders would automatically make the world more peaceful is attractive but too simple. Gender may influence personal experience and priorities, yet <strong class=\"key-phrase\">gender alone is a poor predictor of political behaviour</strong>. Decisions about war and peace are shaped more strongly by institutions, national interests and the circumstances a leader faces.\n\nSupporters of the claim argue that women are generally more cooperative and less aggressive than men. They may also bring greater attention to welfare, family security and the human cost of conflict. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">Broader representation</strong> can improve debate because a government that includes people with different experiences is less likely to rely on a narrow set of assumptions. For this reason, increasing the number of women in leadership is valuable in its own right.\n\nHowever, a head of government does not act solely according to personality. Leaders operate under <strong class=\"key-phrase\">institutional constraints</strong>, military advice, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">electoral incentives</strong> and international pressure. A female leader may still authorise decisive action when national security is threatened, just as a male leader may choose negotiation and restraint. History contains examples of both patterns. It is therefore unsafe to treat peacefulness as a fixed female characteristic or violence as a fixed male one.\n\nThe better way to reduce conflict is to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">strengthen accountable institutions</strong>. Transparent decision-making, effective diplomacy, independent media and legislative oversight make it harder for any leader to start an unnecessary war. Diverse leadership can support these safeguards, but it cannot replace them.\n\nIn conclusion, the world would benefit from more women in positions of power because representation should be fair and decision-making should include wider perspectives. Nevertheless, peace depends primarily on political systems and incentives, not on the sex of the individual leader.","phrases":[{"en":"gender alone is a poor predictor of political behaviour","vi":"chỉ riêng giới tính không thể dự đoán tốt hành vi chính trị"},{"en":"broader representation","vi":"sự đại diện đa dạng hơn"},{"en":"institutional constraints","vi":"những ràng buộc thể chế"},{"en":"electoral incentives","vi":"những động lực từ bầu cử"},{"en":"strengthen accountable institutions","vi":"củng cố các thể chế có trách nhiệm giải trình"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#159","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Throughout the history, male leaders often made the society more violent…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-160","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society: Family life","prompt":"Today, people are getting greedy and selfish. Some people argue that we should go back to the old days, and show respect for the family and community, so that we can make the world a better place to live in. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Perhaps the tendency toward individualism has never been clearer than it is now. People seem to become increasingly self-centred and snobbish. I side with those people who believe that reviving the bygone concept of family and community is important.\n\nThe rise of egoism has profound consequences on the unity of a family, causing the breakdown of family solidarity. Every component of a family can be detrimentally affected, if one member is selfish. “Blood is thicker than water”, as an old saying indicates. People will turn to family first if they are confronted with problems. People used to live in a community in which they lived according to an ethos: of sharing and caring, but nowadays, members of a family tend to work separately for their individual benefits. They are ignorant of the fact that families not only give them tangible benefits (e. g. financial aid), but also offer <strong class=\"key-phrase\">emotional support</strong> from which they obtain strength, comfort and confidence.\n\nEgoism also causes people to ignore the good of the community, a problem that is disruptive to the community. So greedy are some people that they can go so far to engage in illegal activities. For example, some merchants earn handsome incomes from producing disqualified products and cajoling people to buy what they do not actually need, They, meanwhile, refuse to plough back any fraction of their income to the community. Individuals become indifferent to others’ interests and the relationship between individual members tends to become superficial, transient and ad hoc. People remain as onlookers when neighbours ask for help, and social solidarity has been dismantled in front of the overwhelming egoism.\n\nOverall, greed and egoism are set to bring both the society and the families in grave trouble. The best way to prevent people from further loss in social solidarity and community unity is to reconstruct the concept of family and community, show esteem to one’s family, friends, neighbours and even acquaintances, and recover <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sense of community</strong> and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">social cohesion</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"emotional support","vi":"sự hỗ trợ tinh thần"},{"en":"a sense of community","vi":"văn hóa cộng đồng"},{"en":"social cohesion","vi":"sự gắn kết xã hội"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#160","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Today, people are getting greedy and selfish.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-161","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society","prompt":"We can get knowledge from news, but some people think we cannot trust journalists. What do you think? What qualities do you think a successful journalist should have?","answer":"Today, it is important to note that the public has a growing appetite for different content areas of news, including national, local, entertainment, sports, politics, weather and traffic news. With news becoming increasingly important, public attention has been brought to the credibility of journalists. In my opinion, it would be over-simplistic to say that journalists can convey all messages to the audience without distorting them.\n\nNot surprisingly, whenever people talk of journalism, objectivity is the first word that springs to mind. Reporters are generally expected to disclose all facts and uncover all sides of an issue without <strong class=\"key-phrase\">introducing any bias</strong>, as opposed to commentators, who are allowed to provide personal opinions. However, in reality, objectivity is hard to achieve. Journalists have to succumb to either commercial or political pressure, distorting facts and misleading the public. In many countries, news organisations are controlled entirely by powerful political parties and enjoined to disregard the truth and disseminate information that guides public opinions.\n\nAnother factor contributing to the erosion of journalistic standards throughout the news business is that in these years, increasing weight has been given to following news values, entertainment, oddity and celebrity. To cater for the tastes of wider audiences, journalists can go so far as to twist the facts, fabricate news and spread rumours. Many news media have a clear preference on media personalities and use their public appeal to increase viewing rates, giving these public figures, who hardly remain neutral, numerous opportunities to express their opinions publicly on a subject in which they have a personal stake or bias. It is thus fair to say that news is now less trustworthy.\n\nIn general, a successful journalist should be first able to use careful judgement when organising and reporting information. Determination and persistence are required when journalists ought to defend the freedom of the press and ordinary citizens’ right to know the truth, despite being under different forms of pressure. In addition, they should be sensitive to and interested in current affairs at all levels. In acting as successful communicators and information senders, journalists should also have a good command of language skills and a real knowledge of different cultures, countries, races and social groups.\n\nOverall, people have reasons to suspect the credibility of a journalist. Either as a medium that deliberately affects the public interest or as a form of entertainment that does not attach much importance to seriousness, journalism has failed to maintain objectivity and live up to ideals of journalistic responsibility. Without showing respect to freedom of express and conveying messages accurately and promptly to the public, one cannot be acclaimed as a qualified journalist.\n\nOverall, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a balanced approach</strong> is more likely to create <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a long-term benefit</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"introducing any bias","vi":"đưa thiên kiến vào"},{"en":"a balanced approach","vi":"một cách tiếp cận cân bằng"},{"en":"a long-term benefit","vi":"một lợi ích lâu dài"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#161","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"We can get knowledge from news, but some people think we cannot trust…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-162","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society","prompt":"With the ageing of society, we are now beginning to see a growing interest in further abolition of mandatory retirement. Do you think that mandatory retirement is obsolete or should be sustained?","answer":"Mandatory retirement is a prominent issue raised by the continued expansion of the aged population. The notion that the older people should be forced out of employment because of age is set to become obsolete. However, the paradox is that a fixed retirement age is still being widely adopted by many employers as usual, either overtly or implicitly. My opinion is that the ways people look at older people as a section of the workforce should be subject to modification, in a world where the growth of the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">ageing population</strong> is a clear trend. Due to improved diet, higher incomes and medical advances, people nowadays live longer. The ongoing increase in the life expectancy leads to the subsequent extension of working lives. It comes as no surprise that productivity and intellectual ability of workers would remain the same as they approach age 65 and in the years beyond. Meanwhile, older employees have a wealth of experience and specialised knowledge they have obtained throughout their decades-long working lives. All stand them in good stead, despite their slightly reduced physical abilities, The age prejudice is therefore unjustified, causing businesses to lose a major source of expert personnel. Another disadvantage of mandatory retirement is the difficulty in finding qualified replacements for senior employees who have retired. Contrary to popular belief, senior employees are unlikely to impede promoting young employees. Instead, they ensure the consistency of staff training of an organisation. Many senior employees are willing to stay on the junior jobs and earn less when they reach retirement age. Besides, their leadership is essential to the improvement of younger employees’ skills. With senior employees, a corporation guarantees the diversity of perspectives and minimises the risk of relying on impetuous decisions made by young, inexperienced employees. Despite those justifications for longer working lives, working in later life might not be aligned with the interest of all older people. For blue-collar workers, their choice is very limited. They are either forced out because of ill health or tired of working days and nights. In many instances, despite being able to work, the majority of senior people prefer retirement, or at least working shorter hours. Income has failed to be an effective incentive, compared to being part of society and contributing to the society in later life. For this reason, retirement should be made a voluntary option to the senior. Based on the above-mentioned arguments, one can conclude that the changing demographics have lent support to raising the age of retirement or just abolishing mandatory retirement. It is in line with the extended life expectancy and in employers’ favour, although it is up to older people themselves in deciding whether to retire or not.","phrases":[{"en":"ageing population","vi":"dân số già hóa"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#162","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"With the ageing of society, we are now beginning to see a growing interest…","band":"8.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-163","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Society","title":"Society","prompt":"In many countries, women join the army as men do. However, some people argue that the army solely needs males. What is your opinion?","answer":"Stepping into the 21st century, women have set foot in nearly every walk of life. However, the army is still a male-dominated area in much of the world. A great many people hold bias against women’s enrolment in the army. In my view, females can contribute to the army just as males do, despite some of their shortcomings.\n\nThe first standpoint to conscript females is that they now have more chances to receive education. In comparison with the past, where the army recruitment policies focused on strength and fitness, the current focus is on academic ability. Physical fighting, either armed or unarmed, no longer features in modern warfare. It has been replaced by battles between tanks, armoured vehicles, missiles or warplanes, most of which are computerised. In other words, females can perform military tasks as their male counterparts do, provided that they are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">well-educated</strong> and well-trained.\n\nSecondly, women have inborn merits that stand them in good stead. Females are less likely to commit faults, for they are accustomed to dealing with matters with accuracy and caution. Patience and consideration of others account for the high presence of females\n\nNotwithstanding their strengths, females have some limitations they may need to overcome. The first obstacle is the social attitudes. Females have to cope with the pressure exerted by their families, acquaintances, or friends, as serving the army is widely seen as a deadly job, which is exclusively for males. The second obstacle is sexual discrimination and harassment, which seems common in most armies and can discourage females from serving their countries.\n\nIn conclusion, females’ presence in the army should be approved and encouraged. Their performance can he guaranteed by their innate strengths, despite the fact that they might have to cope with prejudices and other external disturbances.","phrases":[{"en":"well-educated","vi":"được giáo dục tốt; có học thức"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#163","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Women join the army as men do.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-164","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Sports","title":"Sports: Sport","prompt":"Extreme sports such as sky diving and skiing are very dangerous and should be banned. To what extent do you agree or disagree with this view?","answer":"In recent years, extreme sports have become increasingly popular, and some people argue that governments should prohibit them. I completely disagree with the idea that these sports are too dangerous, and I therefore believe that they should not be banned.\n\nIn my opinion, so-called extreme sports are not as dangerous as many people think. All sports <strong class=\"key-phrase\">involve some element of risk</strong>, and there should always be clear regulations and safety procedures to reduce the possibility of accidents. People who <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take part in</strong> extreme sports are usually required to undergo <strong class=\"key-phrase\">appropriate training</strong> so that the dangers are minimised. For example, anyone who wants to try skydiving will need to sign up for lessons with a registered club, and beginners are not allowed to dive solo; they must be accompanied by an experienced professional. Finally, the protective equipment and technology used in sports from motor racing to mountain climbing is constantly improving safety.\n\nWhile I support regulations and safety measures, I believe that it would be wrong, and almost impossible, to ban extreme sports. In the first place, we should all be free to decide how we spend our leisure time; as long as we understand the risks, I do not believe that politicians should stop us from enjoying ourselves. However, an even stronger argument against such a ban would be the difficulty of enforcing it. Many of the most risky sports, like base jumping or big wave surfing, are practised far away from the reach of any authorities. I cannot imagine the police being called to stop people from parachuting off a mountain face or surfing on an isolated beach.\n\nIn conclusion, I would argue that people should be free to enjoy extreme sports as long as they understand the risks and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take the appropriate precautions</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"involve some element of risk","vi":"có chứa một mức độ rủi ro nhất định"},{"en":"take part in","vi":"tham gia"},{"en":"appropriate training","vi":"quá trình đào tạo phù hợp"},{"en":"take the appropriate precautions","vi":"thực hiện các biện pháp phòng ngừa thích hợp"}],"subtype":"Agree / Disagree · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#164","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Should extreme sports be banned?","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-165","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Technology","title":"Technology","prompt":"Nowadays the way many people interact with each other has changed because of technology. In what ways has technology affected the types of relationships that people make? Has this been a positive or negative development?","answer":"It is true that new technologies have had an influence on communication between people. Technology has affected relationships in various ways, and in my opinion there are both positive and negative effects.\n\nTechnology has had an impact on relationships in business, education and social life. Firstly, telephones and the Internet allow business people in different countries to interact without ever meeting each other. Secondly, services like Skype <strong class=\"key-phrase\">create new possibilities for</strong> relationships between students and teachers. For example, a student can now take video lessons with a teacher in a different city or country. Finally, many people use social networks, like Facebook, to make new friends and find people who <strong class=\"key-phrase\">share common interests</strong>, and they interact through their computers rather than face to face.\n\nOn the one hand, these developments can be extremely positive. Cooperation between people in different countries was much more difficult when communication was limited to written letters or telegrams. Nowadays, interactions by email, phone or video are almost as good as <strong class=\"key-phrase\">face-to-face meetings</strong>, and many of us benefit from these interactions, either in work or social contexts. On the other hand, the availability of new communication technologies can also have the result of isolating people and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">discouraging real interaction</strong>. For example, many young people choose to make friends online rather than mixing with their peers in the real world, and these “virtual’ relationships are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a poor substitute for real friendships</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, technology has certainly revolutionised communication between people, but not all of the outcomes of this revolution have been positive.","phrases":[{"en":"create new possibilities for","vi":"tạo ra những khả năng mới cho"},{"en":"share common interests","vi":"có những sở thích chung"},{"en":"face-to-face meetings","vi":"buổi gặp mặt trực tiếp"},{"en":"discouraging real interaction","vi":"làm suy giảm tương tác thực tế"},{"en":"a poor substitute for real friendships","vi":"sự thay thế kém giá trị cho tình bạn thực sự"}],"subtype":"Two-part question · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#165","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Technology and human relationships","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-166","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Technology","title":"Technology: Education","prompt":"Some people regard video games as harmless fun, or even as a useful educational tool. Others, however, believe that videos games are having an adverse effect on the people who play them. In your opinion, do the drawbacks of video games outweigh the benefits?","answer":"Many people, and children in particular, enjoy playing computer games. While I accept that these games can sometimes have a positive effect on the user, I believe that they are more likely to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">have a harmful impact</strong>.\n\nOn the one hand, video games can be both entertaining and educational. Users, or gamers, are transported into virtual worlds which are often more exciting and engaging than real-life pastimes. From an educational perspective, these games encourage imagination and creativity, as well as concentration, logical thinking and problem solving, all of which are useful skills outside the gaming context. Furthermore, it has been shown that computer simulation games can improve users’ motor skills and help to prepare them for real-world tasks, such as flying a plane.\n\nHowever, I would argue that these benefits are outweighed by the drawbacks. Gaming can be highly addictive because users are constantly given scores, new targets and frequent rewards to keep them playing. Many children now spend hours each day trying to progress through the levels of a game or to get a higher score than their friends. This type of addiction can have effects ranging from <strong class=\"key-phrase\">lack of sleep</strong> to problems at school, when homework is sacrificed for a few more hours on the computer or console. The rise in obesity in recent years has also been linked in part to the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">sedentary lifestyle</strong> and lack of exercise that often accompany gaming addiction.\n\nIn conclusion, it seems to me that the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">potential dangers</strong> of video games are more significant than the possible benefits.","phrases":[{"en":"have a harmful impact","vi":"gây tác động có hại"},{"en":"lack of sleep","vi":"thiếu ngủ"},{"en":"sedentary lifestyle","vi":"lối sống ít vận động"},{"en":"potential dangers","vi":"những mối nguy hiểm tiềm tàng"}],"subtype":"Advantages outweigh disadvantages · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#166","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"The benefits and harms of video games","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-167","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Technology","title":"Technology: Crime and punishment","prompt":"Many people today are worried about ’cybercrime’ such as hacking and identity theft. What problems does ’cybercrime’ cause, and what solutions can you suggest for ordinary people and businesses to take? Give reasons for your answer, and provide ideas and examples from your own experience. You should write at least 250 words.","answer":"Cybercrime is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a cause of widespread concern</strong> today, as so many people use technology to store and transmit sensitive data. There are a number of problems that people suffer as a result of these crimes, but also some straightforward measures we can take to protect ourselves. Perhaps the worst problem stemming from this is the financial impact. If someone has his or her bank account emptied, or has false credit lines created under their name, they are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">potentially liable for large sums of money</strong>. Even if they can avoid the consequences, their bank or finance company has to cover the losses, which can damage their performance. A further problem is the way in which these stolen funds are used to subsidize other crimes, such as drug distribution or even terrorism. Once the money enters the criminal networks, we have no way of knowing how it will be used. Finally, there is the problem of anxiety and stress caused to the innocent victims of these crimes. The initial shock is often followed by months or years or legal wrangling, paperwork and a sense of insecurity. Turning to possible solutions, probably the most effective measure is to improve personal security, ranging from passwords to the shredding of documents. This denies the criminals the raw materials to work with. Secondly, we should <strong class=\"key-phrase\">raise awareness of the risks</strong> among the elderly or the very young – two groups who are often specifically targeted – via publicity and public education. Ultimately, however, it is the financial companies who can make the greatest contribution, by increasing their security and detection systems – ideally in partnership with the police. Overall, the problems caused are both financial and social, and the solutions should involve <strong class=\"key-phrase\">coordinated action</strong> by individuals, corporations and the state.","phrases":[{"en":"a cause of widespread concern","vi":"một nguyên nhân gây lo ngại rộng rãi"},{"en":"potentially liable for large sums of money","vi":"có thể phải chịu trách nhiệm cho khoản tiền lớn"},{"en":"raise awareness of the risks","vi":"nâng cao nhận thức về rủi ro"},{"en":"coordinated action","vi":"hành động phối hợp"}],"subtype":"Causes / Solutions","_displayNo":"#167","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"People today are worried about ‘cybercrime’ such as hacking and identity…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-168","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Technology","title":"Technology: Music","prompt":"The advance of science and technology has a significant impact on people, but the role of artists is also important, such as musicians, painters and writers. What can the arts tell us about life that science cannot?","answer":"Science explains how the natural world works, while the arts explore what human experience feels like. Both are important, but they answer different questions. Art can reveal emotion, identity and moral conflict in ways that scientific measurement alone cannot.\n\nA scientific study can describe the biological effects of grief, but a novel, painting or piece of music can help an audience understand the personal reality of loss. Art gives form to experiences that are difficult to measure, including love, fear, memory and belonging. Because people interpret a work differently, it can also encourage them to examine their own assumptions. In this sense, the arts provide <strong class=\"key-phrase\">insight into the inner life of other people</strong>.\n\nThe arts also preserve the character of a society. Stories, songs and images record how communities understand family, authority, religion and historical change. Science may explain the materials used in an ancient object, but art and literature help us consider what that object meant to the people who made it. This cultural record allows later generations to see the world through a different set of values.\n\nFinally, art can explore moral questions before society reaches a clear answer. Films about artificial intelligence, genetic engineering or war do not provide technical solutions, but they can show the human consequences of a decision. This imaginative function is valuable because facts do not automatically tell us what we ought to do.\n\nIn conclusion, science offers reliable explanations and practical discoveries, whereas the arts deepen our understanding of emotion, culture and moral choice. They do not compete with science; they provide <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a complementary way of understanding life</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"insight into the inner life of other people","vi":"sự thấu hiểu đời sống nội tâm của người khác"},{"en":"a complementary way of understanding life","vi":"một cách bổ trợ để hiểu về cuộc sống"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#168","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Advance of science and technology has a significant impact on people, but…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-169","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Technology","title":"Technology: News media","prompt":"Although more and more people read news on the Internet, newspapers will remain the most important source of news. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"The Internet is beginning to rival newspapers as the best place to find information about what is happening in the world. I believe that this trend will continue, and the Internet will soon be just as important as <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the traditional press</strong>.\n\nOn the one hand, I believe that newspapers will continue to be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a vital source of information</strong>, even in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the Internet age</strong>. Firstly, newspapers are the most traditional means of communicating the news, and not everyone wants to or can use the Internet instead. For example, old people or those in rural areas might not have the ability or opportunity to get online, while many of us simply prefer newspapers even if we do have Internet access. Secondly, newspapers can be trusted as reliable sources of news because they employ professional journalists and editors. Finally, many people like the experience of holding and reading a paper rather than looking at a computer screen.\n\nHowever, the Internet is likely to become just as popular as newspapers for a variety of reasons. The main reason is that it allows us much faster access to news in real time and wherever we are, on different gadgets and mobile devices. Another key benefit of online news compared to newspapers is the ability to share articles, discuss them with other people, give our views, and even contribute with our own updates on social media. For example, there has been an explosion in the use of platforms like Twitter and YouTube where anyone can share their news and views. A final point is that this source of news is less damaging to the environment.\n\nIn conclusion, I disagree with the view that newspapers will continue to be the main source of news, because I believe that the Internet will soon be equally important.","phrases":[{"en":"the traditional press","vi":"báo chí truyền thống"},{"en":"a vital source of information","vi":"một nguồn thông tin quan trọng"},{"en":"the Internet age","vi":"thời đại Internet"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#169","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Although more and more people read news on the Internet, newspapers will…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-170","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Technology","title":"Technology: Children","prompt":"Computers do not help children learn more effectively. On the contrary, the use of computers has a negative effect on children’s physical and mental development. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"In the new millennium, computer technology is set to become an essential feature of the society. People are very often confronted with the argument concerning the impact of widespread computer use on young people. In my opinion, using computers can be either beneficial or harmful, so moderation is the key.\n\nExcessive use of computers is unarguably detrimental, as it can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">place children at risk</strong> in terms of their physical, social and psychological development. Studies have pointed to the fact that children need physical activity and social interaction to be healthy, happy and productive individuals. Unmonitored use of computers isolates them from those activities and makes them indifferent to the real world. They are So immersed in the computer that they are rarely concerned about the people and matters around them. It leads to a drop in their interaction with others, organised sports and other social activities that are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">conducive to their development</strong>.\n\nAnother hazard of excessive computer use is children’s increased exposure to violent and sexual contents beyond their years, which have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">long-term negative effects</strong> on their lives. Repeated exposure to violence has been recognised and singled out as a decisive element responsible for children’s subsequent aggressive behaviour. Although computer games that have violent themes have been forbidden in many countries, tens of thousands of children are vulnerable to other forms of violence that spread on the Internet.\n\nDespite the negative effects of excessive computer use, adults can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take advantage of computer technology</strong> in different areas of education. Educational games, for example, are believed to have positive effects on children’s intellectual well-being. Some computer games are developed specifically to help children develop academic skills required for schoolwork. Computers meanwhile provide an escape for children who experience high levels of pressure in the daytime and offer them a balance between campus and off-campus life.\n\nAs suggested above, healthy and appropriate use of computers is accepted and encouraged. By giving children ongoing instructions, imposing a limit on computer time and classing the types of content a child can view, teachers and parents can use the computer technology to great advantage while avoiding possible harms.","phrases":[{"en":"place children at risk","vi":"đặt trẻ em vào nguy cơ"},{"en":"conducive to their development","vi":"có lợi cho sự phát triển của các em"},{"en":"long-term negative effects","vi":"tác động tiêu cực lâu dài"},{"en":"take advantage of computer technology","vi":"tận dụng công nghệ máy tính"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#170","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Computers do not help children learn more effectively.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-171","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Technology","title":"Technology","prompt":"Do you agree that modern technology has given us more leisure time than before?","answer":"In the history of mankind, possibly no century witnessed more progress in technology than the 20th century did. People have become increasingly interested in assessing the correlation between technological development and leisure time. As far as I am concerned, people’s leisure time has been’ shrinking as a result of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the tremendous advance in modern technology</strong>.\n\nAdmittedly, thanks to modern technology, people can thus spend less time on compulsory activities (e. g., working), but it should also be noted that other non-compulsory activities have come to consume a larger proportion of people's after-work life, such as education. If leisure refers to the time spent in non-compulsory activities, people's leisure time has in fact contracted. The growing concern on education has increased the likelihood that people are willing to give up their leisure lives for educational opportunities. This trend is attributed mainly to competition and fears of job loss, causing people to turn to on-the-job training and education for secured employment. Another incentive is the increasing flexibility of educational institutions. Worthwhile knowledge can be passed on from one generation of workers to another in different forms of education, such as televised teaching and online courses. It <strong class=\"key-phrase\">comes at the cost of their leisure time</strong>.\n\nPeople’s leisure lives are continuously eroded also because of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">ubiquity of modern technological tools</strong> (e. g., computers with Internet access and telecommunications equipment). It is noteworthy that people now take fewer and shorter vacations following the increase in the number of technology-based activities. For example, cell phones and laptops make people accessible to their superiors wherever they go and wherever they are. People are more stressed than any generation before. Meanwhile, people now have to engage in more everyday processes than ever before, such as shopping, food ordering, and so on. It seems that the time budget is burdened because more time should be invested in activities that were previously ignored or unnoticed.\n\nWhile posing a threat on people’s leisure lives, technologies might on other occasions, give workers more flexibility in controlling their work and more quality time after work. A traditional workweek has been cut, as the amount of manual work continues to decline because of automation. The availability of various means of transport has released working people from lengthy commutes. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">The line between work and private life is much more blurred</strong>, with many workers shopping, checking private emails and reading newspaper online even when working,\n\nFrom what has been discussed, one understands that the development of technology has tremendous impacts on people’s daily lives, although the exact impacts are not conclusive. When the proliferation of new technologies, such as computers, allows people to manage their own working time and accommodate family needs and lifestyle choices, it has locked them in a struggle to cope with more tasks in daily lives,","phrases":[{"en":"the tremendous advance in modern technology","vi":"sự tiến bộ vượt bậc của công nghệ hiện đại"},{"en":"comes at the cost of their leisure time","vi":"đánh đổi bằng thời gian nghỉ ngơi của họ"},{"en":"ubiquity of modern technological tools","vi":"sự hiện diện rộng khắp của các công cụ công nghệ hiện đại"},{"en":"the line between work and private life is much more blurred","vi":"ranh giới giữa công việc và đời sống riêng tư trở nên mờ nhạt hơn nhiều"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#171","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Do you agree that modern technology has given us more leisure time than…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-172","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Technology","title":"Technology: Work","prompt":"Many employees may work at home with modern technology. Some people claim that it benefits only workers, but not employers. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"The spread of telecommunication technology—using the Internet, telephone, fax, scanners or text messaging—has opened up a new range of possibilities for working at home. Discussion has centred on whether it represents a benefit to workers alone, but not employers. In my opinion, employers can take full advantage of home working as well.\n\nBy allowing employees to work at home, employers can widen the base from which they recruit and boost the chances of capitalising on rich human capital. For instance, parents with childcare responsibilities and those with disabilities prefer to work at home. Distance between their work place and their place of residence has never ceased to be a problem. Homeworking enables working people to perform their jobs at ease, and thus gives employers more options in human resource use.\n\nAnother benefit obtained from home-working is the boost for staff motivation. By working at home, employees can manage their time on their own and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">strike a balance between</strong> work and rest. Similarly important is that, without the presence of their immediate supervisors, they feel less stressful and more comfortable. Those two factors both play a part in boosting their productivity and job satisfaction.\n\nApart from those benefits, homeworking might have its drawbacks. A challenge that employers: have to face is the difficulty in managing and monitoring employees’ performance. Whether employees are as likely lo meet a deadline when working at home as they are in the workplace remains unclear. Similarly difficult is to maintain team spirit because employees have limited interaction between each other. Furthermore, staff training, an integral part of increasing human capital, is not practical in a business where homeworking predominates.\n\nTherefore, it is clear that although employers can benefit a lot from integrating homeworking into his or her business, e. g., introducing more flexibility and increasing employees’ job satisfaction, they should work out methods to prevent the problems that are likely to arise from this move.","phrases":[{"en":"strike a balance between","vi":"cân bằng giữa"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#172","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Employees may work at home with modern technology.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-173","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Technology","title":"Technology","prompt":"It is said that the fast pace of our everyday life, as a direct result of the rapid development of telecommunications technology and travel industry, has negative effects on individuals, nations and the globe. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Not surprisingly, many aspects of people’s daily lives have undergone considerable changes because of the recent development in technology. It is a particular concern that the pace of everyday life is becoming faster, resulting from the development in cars, air travel, telecommunications technology and the Internet. As well as benefits, this trend is to bring problems.\n\nOn the positive side, the fast rhythm of life requires people to enhance efficiency when working and then allows them to enjoy longer leisure time. With the advance in telecommunications, people can make inquires by phone, instead of travelling long distances. Internet access makes it possible for one to perform various tasks without leaving their offices. Even though people have to travel every <strong class=\"key-phrase\">now and then</strong> for meeting business partners, visiting clients in other cities or other purposes, modern transport networks reduce the amount of time they spend on commutes.\n\nThe acceleration of the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">pace of life</strong> also implies the expansion of people’s social circle. In the past, social relationships were limited by physical factors such as geographical distance and low mobility, but nowadays, one can travel further and get acquainted with more people with those technological advances, such as the railroad, the automobile and the telephone. For instance, the rapid penetration of telecommunications technology has made the mobile phone a key social tool and people rely on their mobile phone address book to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">keep in touch with</strong> their friends.\n\nOn the negative side, the fast-paced lifestyle is responsible for the upsurge in lifestyle-related problems. Jobs become demanding and require workers’ full commitment, resulting in their depression and pressure. Underneath the facade of continued contraction of official working hours, employees are actually working longer, primarily because fax, e-mail or other communication devices have made them accessible to their supervisors, colleagues and customers after work. They have to respond instantly to voice and email messages from others. Private life has to be sacrificed.\n\nAccording to the facts outlined above, the doubts about the negative effects of the acceleration of pace of life are not well-grounded. People now enjoy greater well-being, which is reflected in more quality family time, less travel-related stress and close contact with friends and family members. However, they might have to accept frequent intrusions as a by-product of convenient communication","phrases":[{"en":"now and then","vi":"thỉnh thoảng"},{"en":"pace of life","vi":"nhịp sống"},{"en":"keep in touch with","vi":"giữ liên lạc với"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#173","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"It is said that the fast pace of our everyday life, as a direct result of…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-174","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Technology","title":"Technology: Mobile phones","prompt":"It seems that with the increase in use of mobile phones and computers, fewer people prefer to write letters. Will the skill of writing disappear completely?","answer":"Text messages, emails and letters are everyday communication tools, although nowadays, text messages and emails appear to gain popularity while letters are used less frequently. The fears that writing skills will be attached with less importance are rooted mainly in the concern that the growing popularity of mobile phones and computers is about to make emails and text messaging much more popular. Such worries are unsupported,\n\nA majority of daily communications involve written correspondence, whether it takes the form of emails or letters. As different from communicating in speech, communicating in writing requires many techniques. The prevalence of emails and text messages will not change the purposes, contents and conventions of communication, but merely medium, font or sentence length. For example, successful written communications are normally measured by clarity and accuracy, two elements that remain unchanged despite <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the upsurge in the use of</strong> text messages and emails, An email or text message sender should pay the same attention to such elements as vocabulary, grammar, punctuation, wording and tone as a letter writer does to make sure that the reader understands and interprets the message as intended. Any misunderstanding or misinterpretation will cause dire consequences.\n\nAnother fact to note is that all communication is interpersonal and interactive, thereby requiring information senders to use language properly and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">convey messages clearly and precisely</strong>. to become a successful communicator, one should plan, tailor, and devise his or her writing according to the characteristics of the reader. Writing a message without considering <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the intended reader</strong> will increase the possibility of poor understanding or even misunderstanding. For example, choosing the right tone in communication is of great importance, Readers make assumptions about people’s mood and intentions and speculate on the implied meaning of the messages, according to the tone suggested by words. Getting the right tone is therefore an important writing skill that is likely to influence the success of communication. It is particularly true in cases where the messages people send contain emotional components. Failure to manipulate these components properly will cause discomfort or hard feelings of the reader.\n\nThe examples that are outlined above have apparently overturned the prevailing notion that writing skills will vanish sooner or later as a result of the increased use of text messaging and emails. Written communication requires a good understanding of the rules of language, such as grammar, vocabulary and tone. Without <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a good command of</strong> those writing skills, a communicator will encounter many awkward situations in daily communication.","phrases":[{"en":"the upsurge in the use of","vi":"sự gia tăng mạnh trong việc sử dụng"},{"en":"convey messages clearly and precisely","vi":"truyền đạt thông điệp rõ ràng và chính xác"},{"en":"the intended reader","vi":"đối tượng người đọc dự kiến"},{"en":"a good command of","vi":"khả năng sử dụng thành thạo"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#174","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"It seems that with the increase in use of mobile phones and computers,…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-175","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Technology","title":"Technology","prompt":"The leisure industry is growing rapidly. The active role of modern technology in people’s leisure lives nowadays has made them less creative. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Technology now occupies a large part of leisure time, leading some people to believe that it has reduced creativity. I disagree with this generalisation. Passive screen use can certainly become repetitive, but modern technology also gives ordinary people powerful tools to create, learn and share original work.\n\nThe negative argument is understandable. Recommendation systems often encourage users to watch similar videos for hours, and many games provide fixed goals rather than genuine freedom. When entertainment becomes automatic, people may spend less time reading, making things or inventing their own activities. This is mainly a problem of habit and design, not proof that all digital leisure is uncreative.\n\nIn contrast, affordable software allows people to edit films, compose music, draw, write and build games at home. Online courses teach techniques that were once available only through specialist schools, while creative communities provide feedback and collaboration. Even gaming can involve strategy, storytelling and the design of new worlds. Technology therefore <strong class=\"key-phrase\">lowers the barrier between consuming and creating</strong>.\n\nEducation can improve the balance by teaching people how digital platforms compete for attention. When users understand recommendation systems and set limits on passive viewing, they have more time for demanding activities such as writing, design or music production. Schools and families can reinforce this habit by valuing finished creative projects, not simply hours spent online.\n\nIn conclusion, modern leisure can become passive when people use technology without purpose. However, the same devices can greatly expand creative opportunity. The important issue is whether users merely scroll through content or choose to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">use digital tools actively and deliberately</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"lowers the barrier between consuming and creating","vi":"hạ thấp rào cản giữa việc tiêu thụ và sáng tạo"},{"en":"use digital tools actively and deliberately","vi":"sử dụng công cụ số một cách chủ động và có mục đích"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#175","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Leisure industry is growing rapidly.","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"Technology","prompt":"Nowadays the way many people interact with each other has changed because of technology. In what ways has technology affected the types of relationships people make? Is this a positive or negative development?","answer":"Technology has changed both the number and nature of people’s relationships. It allows individuals to maintain contact across distance and to meet others with similar interests, but it can also make communication more superficial. Overall, the effect is positive when digital contact supports rather than replaces real interaction.\n\nMessaging, video calls and social networks make long-distance relationships easier to maintain. Families separated by work or migration can speak regularly, and professional teams can cooperate across countries. Online communities also help people with rare interests or health conditions find support. Technology has therefore <strong class=\"key-phrase\">removed many barriers created by distance</strong>.\n\nThe weakness is that convenience can reduce depth. Short messages often replace longer conversations, and people may divide their attention between a screen and the person in front of them. Social media can also encourage comparison and create the impression of friendship without real trust. These problems are caused less by the technology itself than by habits of use.\n\nTechnology has expanded weak connections more than deep ones. People can maintain contact with former classmates or professional networks, yet close relationships still require attention, empathy and time together. Digital tools are most positive when they support those qualities rather than replace them. Users therefore need <strong class=\"key-phrase\">deliberate boundaries around online communication</strong>.\n\nFace-to-face time therefore remains essential for trust.\n\nIn conclusion, technology has expanded opportunities for connection, but strong relationships still require time, attention and honesty. People should use digital tools to arrange meetings, share meaningful experiences and stay in touch, while also protecting <strong class=\"key-phrase\">undistracted face-to-face time</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Technology","phrases":[{"en":"removed many barriers created by distance","vi":"xóa bỏ nhiều rào cản do khoảng cách tạo ra"},{"en":"deliberate boundaries around online communication","vi":"những ranh giới có chủ đích đối với giao tiếp trực tuyến"},{"en":"undistracted face-to-face time","vi":"thời gian gặp mặt trực tiếp không bị xao nhãng"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"positive","summary":"Technology Changing Relationships: A Negative Development","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-176","_displayNo":"#176","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"Technology","prompt":"Many people are now opting to provide technology companies with their personal data in exchange for access to software. Do the advantages of this outweigh the disadvantages?","answer":"Many people exchange personal data for access to useful software. This arrangement offers convenience and lower prices, but it also creates serious privacy risks. In my view, the advantages outweigh the disadvantages only when users receive clear information and genuine control.\n\nData can improve a service. Navigation apps use location information to suggest routes, while streaming platforms recommend content based on previous choices. Advertising revenue also allows many tools to remain free. For users with limited budgets, this can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">expand access to valuable digital services</strong>.\n\nThe problem is that consent is often weak. Privacy policies are long, data may be shared with third parties and a breach can expose sensitive information. Users may also be profiled in ways that affect prices, employment or political messaging without their knowledge. Companies should collect only what is necessary, explain the purpose in plain language and offer a paid or less personalised alternative.\n\nThe value of the exchange also depends on necessity and consent. A navigation app may need location data while it is guiding a journey, but it does not need to retain that history indefinitely. Companies should collect only what a service requires and explain the purpose clearly. This principle of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">data minimisation</strong> reduces risk without removing useful digital services.\n\nIn conclusion, sharing some data can be a reasonable exchange, but only under strict conditions. Strong regulation, limited collection and easy deletion are needed to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">give users meaningful control over their information</strong>. Without these safeguards, the convenience of free software does not justify the loss of privacy.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Technology","phrases":[{"en":"expand access to valuable digital services","vi":"mở rộng khả năng tiếp cận các dịch vụ số hữu ích"},{"en":"data minimisation","vi":"giảm thiểu dữ liệu được thu thập"},{"en":"give users meaningful control over their information","vi":"trao cho người dùng quyền kiểm soát thực chất đối với thông tin của họ"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"outweigh","summary":"Trading Privacy for Software: A Dangerous Exchange","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-177","_displayNo":"#177","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-178","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Tourism","title":"Tourism","prompt":"Foreign visitors should pay more than local visitors for cultural and historical attractions. To what extent do you agree or disagree with this opinion?","answer":"It is sometimes argued that tourists from overseas should be charged more than local residents to visit important sites and monuments. I completely disagree with this idea.\n\nThe argument in favour of higher prices for foreign tourists would be that cultural or historical attractions often depend on <strong class=\"key-phrase\">state subsidies</strong> to keep them going, which means that the resident population already pays money to these sites through the tax system. However, I believe this to be a very shortsighted view. Foreign tourists contribute to the economy of the host country with the money they spend on <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a wide range of goods and services</strong>, including food, souvenirs, accommodation and travel. The governments and inhabitants of every country should be happy to subsidise important tourist sites and encourage people from the rest of the world to visit them.\n\nIf travellers realised that they would have to pay more to visit <strong class=\"key-phrase\">historical and cultural attractions</strong> in a particular nation, they would perhaps decide not to go to that country on holiday. To take the UK as an example, the tourism industry and many related jobs rely on visitors coming to the country to see places like Windsor Castle or Saint Paul’s Cathedral. These two sites charge the same price regardless of nationality, and this helps to promote <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the nation’s cultural heritage</strong>. If overseas tourists stopped coming due to higher prices, there would be a risk of insufficient funding for the maintenance of these important buildings.\n\nIn conclusion, I believe that every effort should be made to attract tourists from overseas, and it would be counter productive to make them pay more than local residents.","phrases":[{"en":"state subsidies","vi":"trợ cấp của nhà nước"},{"en":"a wide range of goods and services","vi":"có nhiều sự lựa chọn về hàng hóa và dịch vụ"},{"en":"historical and cultural attractions","vi":"các điểm tham quan lịch sử và văn hóa"},{"en":"the nation’s cultural heritage","vi":"di sản văn hóa quốc gia"}],"subtype":"Agree / Disagree · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#178","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Higher entrance fees for foreign tourists","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-179","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Tourism","title":"Tourism","prompt":"’Tourism is always a force for good which enables people of different countries to understand each other.’ To what extent do you agree with this idea?","answer":"The role of tourism in the world today is widely debated, with some people claiming that it is indeed <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a force for international understanding</strong>. However, I personally do not entirely accept this, and I will explain why in this essay. Firstly, we must consider the potential negatives of contact between cultures. For example, when western tourists visit untouched parts of the world, their stay causes pollution for local societies. We see this in the litter left at Machu Picchu in Peru, and in the damage to ecology caused by safari tourism in Africa. Furthermore, there are numerous examples of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">tension between tourists and local cultures</strong>, ranging from drunken British tourists in Europe to American ’spring breakers’ in Canadian or Latin American resorts. In these cases, tourism actually leads to resentment and distrust between nationalities, not better understanding. A further reason to be wary of this idea is the economic aspect. It is sometimes said that tourism improves international relations because it encourages the flow of money from wealthy to less developed countries. In reality, however, the wealth generated usually stays in the hands of private companies or local officials, and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">rarely drips down into the population</strong>. Many of us have visited less developed nations as tourists, and have witnessed at first hand the poverty that exists <strong class=\"key-phrase\">outside the confines of the resort hotels</strong>. We leave with the impression that our stay has contributed nothing to the lives of those we have observed. This is not to say that tourism is entirely bad, of course. There are benefits in terms of improving local infrastructure such as roads and airports. But to say that it is ’always a force for good’ is to ignore the various problems it causes.","phrases":[{"en":"a force for international understanding","vi":"một động lực thúc đẩy sự hiểu biết quốc tế"},{"en":"tension between tourists and local cultures","vi":"căng thẳng giữa du khách và văn hóa địa phương"},{"en":"rarely drips down into the population","vi":"hiếm khi đến được với người dân"},{"en":"outside the confines of the resort hotels","vi":"bên ngoài phạm vi các khu nghỉ dưỡng"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#179","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"‘Tourism is always a force for good which enables people of different…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-180","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Transport","title":"Transport","prompt":"Some people think that strict punishments for driving offences are the key to reducing traffic accidents. Others, however, believe that other measures would be more effective in improving road safety. Discuss both these views and give your own opinion.","answer":"People have differing views with regard to the question of how to make our roads safer. In my view, both punishments and a range of other measures can be used together to promote better driving habits.\n\nOn the one hand, strict punishments can certainly help to encourage people to drive more safely. Penalties for dangerous drivers can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">act as a deterrent</strong>, meaning that people avoid <strong class=\"key-phrase\">repeating the same offence</strong>. There are various types of driving penalty, such as small fines, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">licence suspension</strong>, driver awareness courses, and even prison sentences. The aim of these punishments is to show dangerous drivers that their actions have negative consequences. As a result, we would hope that drivers become more disciplined and alert, and that they follow the rules more carefully.\n\nOn the other hand, I believe that safe driving can be promoted in several different ways that do not punish drivers. Firstly, it is vitally important to educate people properly before they start to drive, and this could be done in schools or even as part of an extended or more difficult driving test. Secondly, more attention could be paid to safe road design. For example, signs can be used to warn people, speed bumps and road bends can be added to calm traffic, and speed cameras can help to deter people from driving too quickly. Finally, governments or local councils could reduce road accidents by investing in better public transport, which would mean that fewer people would need to travel by car. In conclusion, while punishments can help to prevent bad driving, I believe that other road safety measures should also be introduced.","phrases":[{"en":"act as a deterrent","vi":"có tác dụng răn đe"},{"en":"repeating the same offence","vi":"tái phạm cùng một hành vi"},{"en":"licence suspension","vi":"thu bằng lái"}],"subtype":"Discuss both views + opinion · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#180","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Road safety: punishment or prevention","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-181","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Transport","title":"Transport","prompt":"Aircraft are increasingly used to transport fruit and vegetables to countries where these products are unavailable or out of season. Do the advantages of this development outweigh the disadvantages?","answer":"Flying fruit and vegetables across long distances gives consumers more choice and provides farmers with access to valuable export markets. However, routine air freight also creates high emissions and may encourage wasteful consumption. In my view, the advantages outweigh the disadvantages only for limited products and circumstances, not as a general food policy.\n\nThe main benefit is a more reliable food supply. Countries with short growing seasons can obtain fresh produce throughout the year, and unusual weather in one region does not have to cause an immediate shortage. Export income can also support farmers in countries whose climate allows them to grow high-value crops efficiently. For consumers, greater variety may improve diet, particularly where certain fruit or vegetables cannot be produced locally.\n\nThe environmental cost is substantial. Aircraft emit far more carbon per tonne of cargo than ships or trains, while refrigeration, packaging and rapid road delivery add further energy use. Air freight can also create the misleading impression that every product should be available in every season. This weakens demand for local crops and may increase food waste when delicate imports spoil before sale. These costs are difficult to justify for ordinary products that could be grown locally or transported more slowly.\n\nA sensible policy would reserve air transport for urgent shortages, highly perishable goods or small quantities with clear nutritional or economic value. Retailers should publish transport information and favour sea or rail freight whenever possible. In conclusion, imported produce can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">improve resilience and consumer choice</strong>, but unrestricted air freight has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an environmental cost that cannot be ignored</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"improve resilience and consumer choice","vi":"tăng khả năng thích ứng và lựa chọn của người tiêu dùng"},{"en":"an environmental cost that cannot be ignored","vi":"một cái giá môi trường không thể bỏ qua"}],"subtype":"Discussion","_displayNo":"#181","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Aircrafts have been increasingly used to transport fruit and vegetables to…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-182","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Transport","title":"Transport","prompt":"Space travel to the Moon is often cited as one giant leap for mankind. Yet some people argue that this achievement made little difference to our daily lives. What is your opinion?","answer":"The idea of travelling through space, even living and working on other planets, has fascinated people for centuries. Despite numerous setbacks and daunting expenditures, travelling in the outer space has never failed to attract people ’ s attention and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">provoke controversy</strong>. Sixty years after the first Moon landing, people question whether the feat, previously thought of as a giant leap for mankind, has substantially benefited people’ s lives. In my opinion, landing on the Moon has enormous relevance for the quality of life, albeit not always explicit.\n\nThe first implication of Moon landing is reflected in the likelihood of travelling on other planets. Moon, as the object in the outer space closet to the Earth, can serve as a launch site for the journeys to other planets. Having no atmosphere, the Moon is a permanent base for people to observe the universe easily and provide them with sufficient evidence they require for decision making on a great many significant issues, which are likely to have direct impact on them. For example, one can learn more about the treat of potentially hazardous objects that are likely to hit the Earth and destroy our civilisation.\n\nAnother remarkable breakthrough made by the Moon landing is that it reignites people’s enthusiasm in the natural sciences. When today’s youths become increasingly interested in such subjects as commerce, finance and business, space exploration successfully attracts and retains talents in space-related technologies. These young minds are convinced that unravelling the unknown of the universe is feasible, despite many challenges. They are inspired to think for the future, instead of being preoccupied with contemporary issues only.\n\nIt should also be noted that the Moon has water, the basic resource for people’s survival, and it abounds in solar energy, a clean and readily obtainable resource. It is also believed that minerals are plentiful there to be exploited. Some day, if people are forced to move off the Earth, the Moon might be the best shelter. Although people have not yet fully explored this possibility at this stage, preliminary investigation is imperative.\n\nBased on the above-mentioned facts, one can conclude that the Moon landing greatly impacts on distant future, although its effect is not apparent for the time being. The Moon is the eventual gateway to other planets and potentially the place of residence for the future generations, The scientific knowledge and economic benefits to be gained by building a sustainable Moon base are huge.","phrases":[{"en":"provoke controversy","vi":"gây tranh cãi"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#182","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"Space travel to the Moon is often cited as one giant leap for mankind.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-183","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Work","title":"Work","prompt":"Many people decide on a career path early in their lives and keep to it. This, they argue, leads to a more satisfying working life. To what extent do you agree with this view? What other things can people do in order to have a satisfying working life?","answer":"It is true that some people know from an early age what career they want to pursue, and they are happy to spend the rest of their lives in the same profession. While I accept that this may suit many people, I believe that others enjoy changing careers or seeking job satisfaction in different ways.\n\nOn the one hand, having <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a defined career path</strong> can certainly lead to a satisfying working life. Many people decide as young children what they want to do as adults, and it gives them a great sense of satisfaction to work towards their goals and gradually achieve them. For example, many children dream of becoming doctors, but to realise this ambition they need to gain the relevant qualifications and undertake years of training. In my experience, very few people who have qualified as doctors choose to change career because they find their work so rewarding, and because they have invested so much time and effort to reach their goal.\n\nOn the other hand, people find happiness in their working lives in different ways. Firstly, not everyone dreams of doing a particular job, and it can be equally rewarding to try a variety of professions; starting out on a completely new career path can be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a reinvigorating experience</strong>. Secondly, some people see their jobs as simply a means of earning money, and they are happy if their salary is high enough to allow them to enjoy life outside work. Finally, job satisfaction is often the result of working conditions, rather than the career itself. For example, a positive working atmosphere, enthusiastic colleagues, and an inspirational boss can make working life much more satisfying, regardless of the profession.\n\nIn conclusion, it can certainly be satisfying to pursue a particular career for the whole of one’s life, but this is by no means the only route to fulfilment.","phrases":[{"en":"a defined career path","vi":"con đường nghề nghiệp định sẵn"},{"en":"a reinvigorating experience","vi":"một trải nghiệm tràn đầy năng lượng"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#183","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"People decide on a career path early in their lives and keep to it.","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-184","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Work","title":"Work","prompt":"When choosing a job, the salary is the most important consideration. To what extent do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Many people choose their jobs based on the size of the salary offered. Personally, I disagree with the idea that money is the key consideration when deciding on a career, because I believe that other factors are equally important.\n\nOn the one hand, I agree that money is necessary in order for people to meet their basic needs. For example, we all need money to pay for housing, food, bills, health care, and education. Most people consider it a priority to at least earn a salary that allows them to cover these needs and have a reasonable quality of life. If people chose their jobs based on enjoyment or other <strong class=\"key-phrase\">non-financial factors</strong>, they might find it difficult to support themselves. Artists and musicians, for instance, are known for choosing a career path that they love, but that does not always provide them with enough money to live comfortably and raise a family.\n\nNevertheless, I believe that other considerations are just as important as what we earn in our jobs. Firstly, personal relationships and the atmosphere in a workplace are extremely important when choosing a job. Having a good manager or friendly colleagues, for example, can make a huge difference to workers’ levels of happiness and general quality of life. Secondly, many people’s feelings of job satisfaction come from their <strong class=\"key-phrase\">professional achievements</strong>, the skills they learn, and the position they reach, rather than the money they earn. Finally, some people choose a career because they want to help others and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">contribute something positive to</strong> society.\n\nIn conclusion, while salaries certainly affect <strong class=\"key-phrase\">people’s choice of profession</strong>, I do not believe that money outweighs all other motivators.","phrases":[{"en":"non-financial factors","vi":"những yếu tố không liên quan đến tài chính"},{"en":"professional achievements","vi":"thành quả về công việc"},{"en":"contribute something positive to","vi":"đóng góp điều tích cực cho"},{"en":"people’s choice of profession","vi":"lựa chọn nghề nghiệp"}],"subtype":"Agree / Disagree · Nguồn: PDF Simon/IELTS Nguyễn Huyền","visual":null,"_displayNo":"#184","author":"Simon","source":"Simon","summary":"Salary versus other job factors","band":"9.0"},{"id":"writing-task-2-185","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Work","title":"Work","prompt":"Many people today find it difficult to balance the demands of their work and personal life. What are the causes of this situation, and what can individuals and employers do to reduce the problem?","answer":"Finding a compromise between one’s job and one’s private life is probably harder than ever these days, especially if one has a family. There are several reasons for this, but also a number of measures we can take. Possibly the major factor is the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">increased workload</strong> that many people have to deal with. The predominance of the service sector means that most people work in office-related jobs, and they find that employers expect them to stay longer or be available outside <strong class=\"key-phrase\">traditional office hours</strong>. On top of this, the rise of communication tools – ranging from smart phones to laptops and teleconferencing equipment – has accelerated the trend, because people are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">always contactable</strong>. Furthermore, the economic recession has made the labour market increasingly competitive, and so workers are under pressure to cooperate in this process, fearing loss of promotion or even redundancy if they resist. However, there are various steps that can be taken to lessen the problem. Firstly, individuals should clarify with their employer the times when they expect to be free of work and out of contact, thus ensuring private time. Another positive development would be for employers to allow more flexible working hours, so that staff can take time off for important family events during the working day. Lastly, employers could offer advice and coaching to staff in areas such as time management, stress control and relaxation techniques. This would help to reduce the anxiety that stems from heavy workloads and long hours. In summary, we can say that technology and economics are creating this situation, but also that employees and companies together can reduce the impact.","phrases":[{"en":"increased workload","vi":"khối lượng công việc gia tăng"},{"en":"traditional office hours","vi":"giờ làm việc truyền thống"},{"en":"always contactable","vi":"luôn có thể bị liên lạc"}],"subtype":"Causes / Solutions","_displayNo":"#185","author":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","source":"Cambridge IELTS Consultants","summary":"People today find it difficult to balance the demands of their work and…","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"Work","prompt":"Some companies have uniforms for their staff which must be worn at all times. Discuss the advantages and disadvantages of this.","answer":"Staff uniforms can strengthen a company’s identity and make employees easy to recognise, but they may also reduce comfort and personal choice. Their value depends on the type of work and the quality of the uniform.\n\nThe main advantage is clarity. In hospitals, hotels or transport services, customers can quickly identify the person who can help them. A uniform can also create a professional appearance and reduce pressure on employees to buy different work clothes. In hazardous jobs, standard clothing may provide essential protection and support consistent safety standards.\n\nThe disadvantages arise when a uniform is uncomfortable, unsuitable for the weather or designed without consulting staff. Employees may feel that the company ignores individual needs, especially in relation to religion, disability or body shape. The cost of cleaning and replacement can also be unfair if workers must pay it themselves. Employers should therefore offer suitable options and review the design regularly.\n\nResponsibility for the uniform also matters. Employers should provide enough sets, pay for specialist cleaning when required and offer versions suitable for different climates, religions and physical needs. A policy is more acceptable when staff are consulted and the rules have a clear purpose. This can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">protect professional standards without creating unnecessary resentment</strong>.\n\nUniform rules should also be reviewed when duties change, rather than remaining fixed for reasons of tradition alone.\n\nIn conclusion, uniforms are useful where identification, hygiene or safety matters. They are less necessary in roles with little public contact. A sensible policy should balance company image with <strong class=\"key-phrase\">comfort, dignity and practical needs</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Work","phrases":[{"en":"protect professional standards without creating unnecessary resentment","vi":"bảo vệ tiêu chuẩn nghề nghiệp mà không tạo ra sự bất mãn không cần thiết"},{"en":"comfort, dignity and practical needs","vi":"sự thoải mái, phẩm giá và nhu cầu thực tế"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"advdis","summary":"Company Uniforms: Marketing Tool or Performance Barrier?","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-186","_displayNo":"#186","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"Work","prompt":"Most high-level positions in companies are filled by men even though the workforce in many developed countries is more than 50 per cent female. Companies should be required to allocate a certain percentage of these positions to women. To what extent do you agree?","answer":"Men still occupy most senior positions in many companies, even where women form a large part of the workforce. Some people propose fixed quotas for women in leadership. I support temporary targets and transparent selection, but not automatic promotion based only on gender.\n\nThe case for intervention is strong. Senior appointments often depend on informal networks, previous opportunities and assumptions about who looks like a leader. Women may also receive fewer high-profile assignments or face career penalties for caring responsibilities. If companies simply wait for the imbalance to correct itself, progress can remain extremely slow. Clear targets can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">force organisations to examine hidden barriers</strong>.\n\nHowever, rigid quotas can create doubts about whether an individual was selected on merit. A better approach is to require balanced shortlists, publish promotion data, offer flexible senior roles and judge candidates against clear criteria. Mentoring and fair access to major projects can expand the pool of qualified women before the final appointment.\n\nTargets should also be supported by a stronger promotion pipeline. Companies can audit pay and performance ratings, publish selection criteria and ensure that women receive access to leadership assignments. These measures address the causes of imbalance before the final appointment. They also make it easier to judge whether a target <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reflects genuine equality of opportunity</strong>.\n\nRegular review is necessary so that targets can be reduced once fair systems are established and representation improves naturally.\n\nIn conclusion, companies should take active steps to correct unequal opportunity, but leadership decisions must remain evidence-based. Time-limited targets combined with transparent recruitment can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">improve representation without lowering standards</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Work","phrases":[{"en":"force organisations to examine hidden barriers","vi":"buộc tổ chức phải xem xét những rào cản tiềm ẩn"},{"en":"reflects genuine equality of opportunity","vi":"phản ánh sự bình đẳng cơ hội thực sự"},{"en":"improve representation without lowering standards","vi":"cải thiện mức độ đại diện mà không hạ thấp tiêu chuẩn"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"opinion","summary":"Gender Quotas in Management: A Controversial Solution","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-187","_displayNo":"#187","band":"8.5"},{"section":"writing-task-2","title":"Work: Young people","prompt":"Nowadays more and more people have to compete with young people for the same jobs. What problems does this cause? What are some possible solutions?","answer":"Older workers increasingly compete with younger applicants for the same jobs. This can create longer unemployment, resentment and a loss of confidence for both groups. The best response is not to favour one age group, but to improve training and make recruitment more transparent.\n\nYoung applicants may struggle to gain their first experience because employers prefer candidates who can work immediately. Older applicants, meanwhile, may face assumptions that their skills are outdated or that they will be expensive to employ. When both groups are rejected repeatedly, the result can be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">long-term exclusion from the labour market</strong>.\n\nGovernments should fund practical retraining linked to real vacancies, while companies should describe the skills required rather than asking for a narrow age profile. Paid internships can help younger people enter a field, and short conversion courses can help experienced workers update digital or technical skills. Mixed-age teams should also be encouraged because they combine recent training with practical judgement.\n\nAge-diverse employment can actually benefit firms. Younger staff may bring recent technical training, while older staff contribute experience, judgement and established professional networks. Apprenticeships and mentoring can allow these strengths to complement each other. Employers should see age diversity as a source of combined capability rather than direct rivalry.\n\nPublic employment services can support this model by matching training funds to genuine shortages instead of offering generic courses with little labour-market value.\n\nIn conclusion, age competition becomes harmful when employers rely on stereotypes instead of evidence. Skills-based recruitment, accessible training and flexible career routes can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">give both generations a fair chance</strong> and reduce unnecessary conflict.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Work","phrases":[{"en":"long-term exclusion from the labour market","vi":"sự bị loại khỏi thị trường lao động trong thời gian dài"},{"en":"give both generations a fair chance","vi":"trao cơ hội công bằng cho cả hai thế hệ"}],"source":"IELTS Advantage – 100 Real Band 7, 8 + 9 IELTS Writing Task 2 Essay Samples","subtype":"problem","summary":"Job Competition Between Young and Old: Problems and Solutions","visual":null,"id":"writing-task-2-188","_displayNo":"#188","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-189","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Work","title":"Work: Sport","prompt":"Some people believe that national sports teams and individual athletes who represent their country should be financially supported by the government. Some people think that they should be funded by non-government groups (e. g. business, sponsorship). What is your opinion?","answer":"In recent years, one of the clearest trends in sports is that more and more corporations have come into play. It is a subject of discussion whether private financing should be accepted by the government to a larger extent and even the state can concede its control over national sports teams to private ownership. In my opinion, the involvement of entrepreneurs is essential and can be deemed as a complement to government administration.\n\nThere are many reasons why the private sector should play a more active role in sports. First, the government alone cannot afford the expenditure involved in the sports industry, such as salaries of athletes, administrative costs, and so forth. By organising competitions efficiently and economically, enhancing athletes’ market values, seeking out sponsors or patrons, the private sector not only raises necessary financing but also maximises the return of the sports industry. A business’s willingness to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take part in</strong> this industry is attributable to many incentives, For example, it would help create an image which is associated with enthusiasm, energy and passion and can be turned into enormous income. Meanwhile it contributes a lot to its solid position in society, as well as good reputation.\n\nMeanwhile, as sports have grown more competitive, the need for better equipment, facilities, nutrition and training methods has become urgent. Athletes should have well-developed physiques, which can be obtained only through extensive physical training and strict exercise. Private sponsors have expertise in different areas of technology, ranging from nutrition to the treatment of injuries. They can train athletes scientifically and effectively, reduce the risk of injuries and extend their career lives. Besides, as private sponsors are more financially capable of providing awards, bonus and other financial incentives to motivate athletes, their involvement is crucial to athletes’ performance on the playing field.\n\nThe role of the private sector is therefore indispensable, but it is not to say that the government should divest itself of intervening in the sports industry. Although the private sector is surely committed to seeking sponsorship and performing many fund-raising jobs, it is profit-oriented and therefore, very likely to make a decision ignorant of the interests of athletes. National teams are branded, marketed and sold as entertainment products, while the value of national pride and ethnic dignity is overlooked. It is also very likely that private investors are only interested in those sports with high media exposure, resulting in the unbalanced development of sports. For this reason, the government should retain the major ownership of the sports.\n\nIn conclusion, the sports world is in need of financial support and the assistance of the private sector. While providing financial resources, goods and services, business investors can obtain communicative and commercial benefits. By giving the green light to private financing, the government is more likely to advance the overall development of sports.","phrases":[{"en":"take part in","vi":"tham gia"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#189","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People believe that national sports teams and individual athletes who…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-190","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Work","title":"Work: Shopping","prompt":"Nowadays people can carry out tasks such as shopping and banking even business transactions without meeting each other face to face. What are the effects on individuals and the society?","answer":"With the wide use of the Internet, the way people conduct business and live their lives has vastly changed. Many businesses have websites that allow people to conduct business, execute deals and finish transactions online, as an alternative to a lengthy commute. Although people are thus free from the constraints of geography and time, there are some consequences of this trend that demand attention.\n\nSupposedly, with Internet access, people can perform transactions and to do shopping without leaving home, but meanwhile they have to pay a heavy price for it. One of the most negative aspects is, for instance, that it alters their social behaviours and habits. For many people, to spend part of the day on the Internet is quite normal. It can be expected that being addicted to Internet use, most of home telecommuters or Internet users will become socially isolated. Poor social life and feelings of loneliness are those problems that are very often found among heavy users.\n\nIt is also likely that people have become increasingly accustomed to living in a world that appreciates convenience and inactivity and they do not want to evade those maxims. It gives explanation of why the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">sedentary lifestyle</strong> is now prevailing and why people spend little time on leisure or recreational activities. Time has been spent in front of the computer or Internet. The net result is that they suffer serious loss of vision, back pain and obesity. It is true that many people finally end up with struggling with deteriorating health.\n\nDespite the negative effects, the Internet has its positive implications to the well-being of society. Online shoppers can seek out the lowest prices for items or services. Manufacturers, therefore, have to improve product quality and lower price levels in an effort to win the favour of consumers and secure a stable market share, Telecommuting-working at home using a computer is a solution to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">traffic congestion</strong>, the urban air pollution and petrol use.\n\nAs outlined above, people’s growing obsession with Internet use, such as online shopping or banking, has both immediate and long-term impacts on health, social involvement, lifestyles and emotional well-being. Although it is of great value from a net surfer’s perspective, people should step up efforts to minimise the negative effects.","phrases":[{"en":"sedentary lifestyle","vi":"lối sống ít vận động"},{"en":"traffic congestion","vi":"tình trạng ùn tắc giao thông"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#190","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People can carry out tasks such as shopping and banking even business…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-191","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Work","title":"Work","prompt":"People tend to believe that all young adults should undertake a period of unpaid work for the good of the community. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"Unpaid community work can give young adults useful experience and strengthen local services. However, I disagree with making it compulsory for everyone. Schools and governments should encourage participation and remove practical barriers, but the final choice should remain voluntary.\n\nVolunteering can be highly beneficial. Young people may learn to communicate with strangers, organise tasks and work as part of a team. A student who helps at a food bank or supports an environmental project also gains a clearer understanding of problems outside the classroom. These experiences can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">build practical skills and social awareness</strong> at the same time.\n\nThe difficulty with compulsory service is that unpaid work may affect young people unequally. Some students have caring duties, paid jobs or health problems, so a fixed requirement could place a heavier burden on them. Forced participation may also reduce motivation and lead organisations to receive unwilling workers. A better system would offer several forms of service, flexible hours and help with travel costs. This would make volunteering <strong class=\"key-phrase\">accessible rather than punitive</strong>.\n\nCommunity organisations also need quality rather than reluctant attendance. Volunteers should receive a clear role, basic training and feedback so that their time produces a real benefit. Schools can recognise service through certificates or course credit without making it a legal duty. This approach <strong class=\"key-phrase\">rewards meaningful participation rather than mere compliance</strong>.\n\nIn conclusion, community work should be strongly promoted but not imposed as a universal obligation. Young adults are more likely to contribute seriously when they understand the purpose of the work and can choose a suitable role. Voluntary programmes with good support would create <strong class=\"key-phrase\">lasting commitment to the community</strong>.","phrases":[{"en":"build practical skills and social awareness","vi":"xây dựng kỹ năng thực tế và nhận thức xã hội"},{"en":"accessible rather than punitive","vi":"dễ tiếp cận thay vì mang tính trừng phạt"},{"en":"rewards meaningful participation rather than mere compliance","vi":"ghi nhận sự tham gia có ý nghĩa thay vì chỉ tuân thủ hình thức"},{"en":"lasting commitment to the community","vi":"sự gắn bó lâu dài với cộng đồng"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#191","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People tend to believe that all young adults should undertake a period of…","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-192","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Work","title":"Work","prompt":"People tend to work longer hours nowadays. Working long hours has a negative effect on themselves, their families and the society, so working hours should be restricted. Do you agree or disagree?","answer":"In recent years, working hours have become a controversial issue, at a time when employees’ benefits have been given serious thought. Although the extension of working hours is believed to have an impact on general well-being and result in work-family conflict and job stress, this practice is remarkably popular in many countries. I am supportive of the argument that long working hours have a negative impact upon individuals, the organisations they work for, and ultimately upon the national economy and society as a whole.\n\nTo job holders, working long hours triggers at least two problems. It not only damages personal relationships, particularly within families, but also disrupts social life, weakens community participation and causes a feeling of stress, a psychological disturbance that is experienced by many working people. It also tends to exert pressure on the employment market and make fewer employment opportunities available. Those with caring responsibilities for example, would be disadvantaged, because they are either unable or unwilling to work long hours. A high unemployment rate is always regarded as a threat to a country’s economy.\n\nTo employers, long working hours, although promising maximum benefit from limited resources every <strong class=\"key-phrase\">now and then</strong>, have destructive effects in the long term. The primary reason is that employees tend to be less productive, and meanwhile, at greater risks of sickness. It would lead not only to the lower quality of work outputs but also to high turnover and absenteeism. As a result, employers have to spend much more on recruiting and training new workers. To a country as a whole, it has chronic effects, disabling the optimisation of resource use, human capital and natural resources.\n\nSome might argue that it is reasonable for an employer to expect some degree of flexibility during a particularly busy period, but to those employers, reliance on the jobs with extended hours has the tendency to become a regular event. Tolerance of this practice would allow employers to exploit labour and disregard the benefits that employees are entitled for, thereby posing a challenge to the legal system. It is time that employers assessed alternatives like re-scheduling, flexible working arrangements and job redesign to explore the full potential of each employee.\n\nAs shown from the above discussion one can see no reason why working long hours is acceptable. It would lead to low productivity and frequent sick leaves, thereby doing more harm than good to employers and the society alike.","phrases":[{"en":"now and then","vi":"thỉnh thoảng"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#192","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People tend to work longer hours nowadays.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-193","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Work","title":"Work","prompt":"Some people think that changing jobs periodically is good. What is your opinion?","answer":"In this fast-changing world, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">job-hopping</strong> (leaving the current employer for another employment opportunity) is not a rare scene. Much has been discussed about the gains and losses of such a career move. In my opinion, job-changing is an inevitable step in today’s labour market, reflecting the nature of a modern society.\n\nA new job implies opportunities for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">career development</strong>, an objective many working people intend to achieve. In general, there are two reasons behind a job holder’s motive for a new job. The first is that the current job cannot <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make the best use of</strong> his or her abilities. The second is that he or she cannot improve skills and gain new experience. Both can lessen the possibility of a brighter job prospect.\n\nJob-hopping, meanwhile, assists one to survive the keen competition. People are living in a fast-changing world and a once stable job is now vulnerable. Willingness to stay on the same job is no longer valued as much as before, Any employee, if complacent about the current employment, would be faced with threats posed by others. By comparison, taking the initiative to obtain a better job can at least drive people to increase skills and thereby improving the chance of continued employment.\n\nWhen job-hoppers are craving for new chances, some issues are particularly worthy of concern. The first is adjusting to a new environment, such as working with new colleagues and supervisors. Besides, while valuing a job hopper’s resume, employers too often tend to suspect his or her loyalty and resilience. It is therefore imperative for every potential jobseeker to learn the new employer better and evaluate the potential risk.\n\nThe above-mentioned facts give one a glimpse of the potential results of changing jobs. When the willingness to change a job and seize an opportunity represents a sound career move and provides the thrust for self-development, it might require a job applicant's extra efforts,","phrases":[{"en":"job-hopping","vi":"nhảy việc"},{"en":"career development","vi":"sự phát triển nghề nghiệp"},{"en":"make the best use of","vi":"tận dụng tốt nhất"}],"subtype":"Opinion","_displayNo":"#193","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"People think that changing jobs periodically is good.","band":"8.5"},{"id":"writing-task-2-194","section":"writing-task-2","topic":"Work","title":"Work: Children","prompt":"These days more fathers stay at home and take care of their children while mothers go out to work. What could be the reasons for this? Do you think it is a positive or a negative development?","answer":"It is true that men are increasingly likely to take on the role of househusband, while more women than ever are the breadwinners in their families. There could be several reasons for this, and I consider it to be a very positive trend.\n\nIn recent years, parents have had to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">adapt to various changes</strong> in our societies. Equal rights movements have made great progress, and it has become normal for women to gain qualifications and pursue a career. It has also become socially acceptable for men to stay at home and look after their children. At the same time, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the rising cost of living</strong> has meant that both marriage partners usually need to work and save money before starting a family. Therefore, when couples have children, they may decide who works and who stays at home depending on the personal preference of each partner, or based on which partner earns the most money.\n\nIn my view, the changes described above should be seen as progress. We should be happy to live in a society in which men and women have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">equal opportunities</strong>, and in which women are not put under pressure to sacrifice their careers. Equally, it seems only fair that men should be free to leave their jobs to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">assume childcare responsibilities</strong> if this is what they wish to do. Couples should be left to make their own decisions about which parental role each partner takes, according to their particular circumstances and needs.\n\nIn conclusion, the changing roles of men and women in the family are a result of wider changes in society, and I believe that these developments are desirable.","phrases":[{"en":"adapt to various changes","vi":"thích nghi với nhiều thay đổi"},{"en":"the rising cost of living","vi":"chi phí cho cuộc sống càng tăng"},{"en":"equal opportunities","vi":"cơ hội bình đẳng"},{"en":"assume childcare responsibilities","vi":"nhận trách nhiệm chăm sóc con cái"}],"subtype":"Essay","_displayNo":"#194","author":"ChatGPT","source":"Original synthesis","summary":"These days more fathers stay at home and take care of their children while…","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Animal","prompt":"What is your favourite animal and why?\nDo you like the same animal you liked when you were younger?\nWhat can you learn about people from the animals they like?\nWhich animals are popular as pets in your country?","answer":"Q: What is your favourite animal and why?\nA: Dogs are my favourite because they are responsive and emotionally expressive. A well-trained dog can become <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a genuine companion</strong>, rather than simply a pet.\n\nQ: Do you like the same animal you liked when you were younger?\nA: Yes. I liked dogs as a child because my grandparents had one, and that early experience shaped my preference. I still admire how easily dogs <strong class=\"key-phrase\">build trust with people</strong>.\n\nQ: What can you learn about people from the animals they like?\nA: You might get a small clue about someone’s lifestyle, but I would not read too much into it. An energetic person may prefer dogs, while someone who values quiet may choose cats, yet personality is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">far more complex</strong> than a pet preference.\n\nQ: Which animals are popular as pets in your country?\nA: Dogs and cats are the most common pets, while fish and small birds are popular in apartments. The choice often depends on space, cost and how much time the owner can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">devote to daily care</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Animal","phrases":[{"en":"a genuine companion","vi":"một người bạn đồng hành thực sự"},{"en":"build trust with people","vi":"xây dựng lòng tin với con người"},{"en":"far more complex","vi":"phức tạp hơn rất nhiều"},{"en":"devote to daily care","vi":"dành thời gian chăm sóc hằng ngày"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Animal","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-001","_displayNo":"#001","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Art","prompt":"Did you enjoy doing art lessons when you were a child?\nDo you ever draw or paint pictures now?\nWhen was the last time you went to an art gallery or exhibition?\nWhat kind of pictures do you like having in your home?","answer":"Q: Did you enjoy doing art lessons when you were a child?\nA: No I didn't. I was never very good at drawing or painting, and I found art lessons quite slow and boring. I preferred <strong class=\"key-phrase\">language and science lessons</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you ever draw or paint pictures now?\nA: No, I don't draw or paint these days, because there's never any need for me to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">create art at work</strong>, and I still don't enjoy art as a hobby.\n\nQ: When was the last time you went to an art gallery or exhibition?\nA: I honestly can't remember the last time I went to any kind of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">art exhibition</strong>; I'm <strong class=\"key-phrase\">not much of</strong> an art fan, and I tend to go to music concerts, the cinema or the theatre instead of art shows.\n\nQ: What kind of pictures do you like having in your home?\nA: I don't have any paintings or artistic images in my home, but I do have photos of family members and some nice photos of landscapes on the walls to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">brighten the place up</strong>.","author":"Simon","topic":"Art","phrases":[{"en":"language and science lessons","vi":"các tiết học ngôn ngữ và khoa học"},{"en":"create art at work","vi":"sáng tạo nghệ thuật trong công việc"},{"en":"art exhibition","vi":"triển lãm nghệ thuật"},{"en":"not much of","vi":"không thực sự là người yêu thích"},{"en":"brighten the place up","vi":"làm không gian trở nên tươi sáng hơn"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Art","id":"speaking-part-1-002","_displayNo":"#002","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Bicycle","prompt":"How are bicycles used in your country?\nHow popular are bicycles in your country?\nAre they used more now than in the past and why?\nWhat do bicycles mean to you?","answer":"Q: How are bicycles used in your country?\nA: Bicycles are mainly used for short journeys, exercise and leisure. In large cities they are less common for commuting because motorbikes dominate the roads, although public bicycle schemes are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">gradually gaining ground</strong>.\n\nQ: How popular are bicycles in your country?\nA: They are moderately popular, particularly among students and people who cycle for fitness. However, the lack of protected lanes prevents cycling from becoming <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a mainstream form of transport</strong>.\n\nQ: Are they used more now than in the past and why?\nA: Recreational cycling is more visible than it was a decade ago, partly because people are more health-conscious. Everyday commuting has not grown as quickly, since traffic safety remains <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a major concern</strong>.\n\nQ: What do bicycles mean to you?\nA: To me, a bicycle represents independence and uncomplicated exercise. It lets me travel at my own pace, avoid short car journeys and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">clear my head</strong> at the same time.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Bicycle","phrases":[{"en":"gradually gaining ground","vi":"dần trở nên phổ biến hơn"},{"en":"a mainstream form of transport","vi":"một phương tiện giao thông phổ biến"},{"en":"a major concern","vi":"một mối lo ngại lớn"},{"en":"clear my head","vi":"giúp đầu óc thư thái"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Bicycle","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-003","_displayNo":"#003","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Book","prompt":"What kinds of things do you enjoy reading in English?\nAre you someone who can read anywhere, or do you have a favourite place?\nDo you need peace and quiet to read, or can you concentrate in noisy places?\nHow did you first learn to read?","answer":"Q: What kinds of things do you enjoy reading in English?\nA: I enjoy reading non-fiction in English, especially books about psychology, technology and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">personal development</strong>. They improve my vocabulary while giving me ideas that I can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">apply in real life</strong>.\n\nQ: Are you someone who can read anywhere, or do you have a favourite place?\nA: I can read almost anywhere, but I concentrate best at a quiet desk by a window. That setting helps me <strong class=\"key-phrase\">stay fully absorbed</strong> without checking my phone every few minutes.\n\nQ: Do you need peace and quiet to read, or can you concentrate in noisy places?\nA: For difficult material, I need a fairly quiet environment. I can skim an article in a café, but serious reading requires enough silence for me to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">process the ideas properly</strong>.\n\nQ: How did you first learn to read?\nA: I first learned by sounding out short words with my parents and then reading illustrated stories at school. Once I discovered books I genuinely enjoyed, reading stopped feeling like homework and became <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a habit of my own</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Book","phrases":[{"en":"personal development","vi":"sự phát triển cá nhân"},{"en":"apply in real life","vi":"áp dụng vào đời sống thực tế"},{"en":"stay fully absorbed","vi":"duy trì sự tập trung hoàn toàn"},{"en":"process the ideas properly","vi":"xử lý ý tưởng một cách đầy đủ"},{"en":"a habit of my own","vi":"một thói quen do chính tôi lựa chọn"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Book","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-004","_displayNo":"#004","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Building","prompt":"Can you tell me about an interesting building in your hometown?\nWhy should we preserve historical buildings?\nHow have architecture and building materials changed in your country?\nWhat type of building do you prefer to live in and why?","answer":"Q: Can you tell me about an interesting building in your hometown?\nA: The Hanoi Opera House is one of the most striking buildings in my city. Its French-inspired façade and central location give it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a distinctive character</strong> that modern glass towers often lack.\n\nQ: Why should we preserve historical buildings?\nA: Historical buildings preserve evidence of how a city developed and give residents <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sense of continuity</strong>. Once they are demolished, the knowledge and atmosphere they carry cannot be recreated convincingly.\n\nQ: How have architecture and building materials changed in your country?\nA: New buildings use more steel, glass and prefabricated materials, while older homes relied heavily on brick and timber. Designs have also become more compact and energy-efficient to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">meet urban needs</strong>.\n\nQ: What type of building do you prefer to live in and why?\nA: I would prefer a medium-sized apartment with natural light, good soundproofing and access to public transport. I do not need luxury, but I value a home that is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">easy to maintain</strong> and comfortable throughout the year.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Building","phrases":[{"en":"a distinctive character","vi":"một nét đặc trưng riêng"},{"en":"a sense of continuity","vi":"cảm giác về sự tiếp nối lịch sử"},{"en":"meet urban needs","vi":"đáp ứng nhu cầu đô thị"},{"en":"easy to maintain","vi":"dễ bảo trì"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Building","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-005","_displayNo":"#005","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Chocolate","prompt":"Do you like chocolate?\nWhat type of chocolate do you prefer?\nWhen do you usually eat chocolate?\nDo people give chocolate as a present in your country?","answer":"Q: Do you like chocolate?\nA: Yes, I love chocolate. I like the taste, the texture and the feeling that you get when you eat it. And it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">goes really well with</strong> my favourite drink, coffee.\n\nQ: What type of chocolate do you prefer?\nA: I prefer <strong class=\"key-phrase\">dark chocolate</strong> to milk chocolate, because it has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a stronger taste</strong>. I also like chocolate when it's in a cake, and I love drinking hot chocolate too.\n\nQ: When do you usually eat chocolate?\nA: I try not to eat too much, but I probably eat or drink something that contains chocolate <strong class=\"key-phrase\">every couple of days</strong>.\n\nQ: Do people give chocolate as a present in your country?\nA: Yes, it's very common to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">give boxes of individual chocolates</strong> as a gift. You can give chocolates on any special occasion really: birthdays, Valentine's day, Easter, Christmas, and so on.","author":"Simon","topic":"Chocolate","phrases":[{"en":"goes really well with","vi":"rất hợp với"},{"en":"dark chocolate","vi":"sô-cô-la đen"},{"en":"a stronger taste","vi":"hương vị đậm hơn"},{"en":"every couple of days","vi":"cứ vài ngày một lần"},{"en":"give boxes of individual chocolates","vi":"tặng những hộp sô-cô-la riêng lẻ"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Chocolate","id":"speaking-part-1-006","_displayNo":"#006","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"City","prompt":"Which town or city do you come from?\nWhat's the best thing about living there?\nIs there anything you don't like?\nWhich places would you recommend to a tourist?","answer":"Q: Which town or city do you come from?\nA: I come from Hanoi, a large city in northern Vietnam. It combines historic neighbourhoods with rapidly developing business districts, so it feels both traditional and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">constantly in motion</strong>.\n\nQ: What's the best thing about living there?\nA: The best feature is the variety: there are parks, cafés, cultural sites and excellent food within a relatively small area. I also like the fact that daily services are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">within easy reach</strong>.\n\nQ: Is there anything you don't like?\nA: <strong class=\"key-phrase\">Traffic congestion</strong> and air pollution are the main drawbacks. At peak times, even a short journey can be exhausting, so the city needs a more reliable <strong class=\"key-phrase\">public transport network</strong>.\n\nQ: Which places would you recommend to a tourist?\nA: I would recommend the Old Quarter, Hoan Kiem Lake and the Temple of Literature. Together they give visitors <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a balanced picture</strong> of the city’s history and everyday life.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"City","phrases":[{"en":"constantly in motion","vi":"luôn vận động"},{"en":"within easy reach","vi":"dễ dàng tiếp cận"},{"en":"Traffic congestion","vi":"tình trạng ùn tắc giao thông"},{"en":"public transport network","vi":"mạng lưới giao thông công cộng"},{"en":"a balanced picture","vi":"một bức tranh toàn diện, cân bằng"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"City","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-007","_displayNo":"#007","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Clothes","prompt":"Are clothes and clothing fashions important to you?\nWhat different clothes do you wear for different situations?\nDo you wear different styles of clothes now compared to 10 years ago?\nDo you think the clothes we wear say something about who we are?","answer":"Q: Are clothes and clothing fashions important to you?\nA: No, clothes and fashions are not really important to me. I tend to wear clothes that are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">comfortable and practical</strong> rather than fashionable.\n\nQ: What different clothes do you wear for different situations?\nA: Well, I have to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">dress quite formally</strong> for work, so I wear a shirt and trousers. At home I prefer to wear jeans and a T-shirt, and on special occasions I might wear a suit.\n\nQ: Do you wear different styles of clothes now compared to 10 years ago?\nA: No, not really, because I don't follow fashion. I think I have dressed <strong class=\"key-phrase\">in a similar way</strong> for the last 10 years.\n\nQ: Do you think the clothes we wear say something about who we are?\nA: Yes, they probably do. Some people are really careful about what they wear because they want to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">be seen as</strong> stylish. Other people wear clothes that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">show wealth or status</strong>, such as clothes by famous designers.","author":"Simon","topic":"Clothes","phrases":[{"en":"comfortable and practical","vi":"thoải mái và thiết thực"},{"en":"dress quite formally","vi":"ăn mặc khá trang trọng"},{"en":"in a similar way","vi":"theo cách tương tự"},{"en":"be seen as","vi":"được xem là"},{"en":"show wealth or status","vi":"thể hiện sự giàu có hoặc địa vị"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Clothes","id":"speaking-part-1-008","_displayNo":"#008","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Clothes","prompt":"How important are clothes and fashion to you?\nWhat kind of clothes do you dislike and why?\nHow different are the clothes you wear now from those you wore 10 years ago?\nWhat do you think the clothes we wear say about us?","answer":"Q: How important are clothes and fashion to you?\nA: Clothes matter to me mainly in terms of comfort and appropriateness. I like to look presentable, but I do not follow every trend because style is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a matter of personal choice</strong>.\n\nQ: What kind of clothes do you dislike and why?\nA: I dislike clothes that are overly tight, heavily branded or difficult to care for. Even if something looks fashionable, I will not buy it unless it is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">comfortable enough for daily wear</strong>.\n\nQ: How different are the clothes you wear now from those you wore 10 years ago?\nA: My clothes are simpler and more practical now. Ten years ago I experimented with brighter colours, whereas today I prefer neutral items that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">work in several settings</strong>.\n\nQ: What do you think the clothes we wear say about us?\nA: Clothing can suggest someone’s profession, taste or attitude to formality, but it is not a complete picture of their character. People sometimes dress to meet expectations rather than to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">express their real personality</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Clothes","phrases":[{"en":"a matter of personal choice","vi":"vấn đề thuộc lựa chọn cá nhân"},{"en":"comfortable enough for daily wear","vi":"đủ thoải mái để mặc hằng ngày"},{"en":"work in several settings","vi":"phù hợp trong nhiều hoàn cảnh"},{"en":"express their real personality","vi":"thể hiện tính cách thật"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Clothes","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-009","_displayNo":"#009","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Clothes","prompt":"What types of clothes do you like to wear?\nWhat kind of clothes do people in your country usually wear?\nHow important is fashion to you?\nWhat kind of clothes do you dislike?","answer":"Q: What types of clothes do you like to wear?\nA: I usually wear simple shirts, trousers and comfortable shoes. I prefer well-made basics because they are easy to combine and do not <strong class=\"key-phrase\">go out of style quickly</strong>.\n\nQ: What kind of clothes do people in your country usually wear?\nA: Most people wear casual Western-style clothes in daily life, while traditional dress is reserved for weddings, festivals and formal occasions. Office workers tend to choose smart clothes that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">strike a balance between</strong> comfort and professionalism.\n\nQ: How important is fashion to you?\nA: Fashion has a limited role in my life. I want to look neat and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">appropriate for the occasion</strong>, but comfort, durability and fit matter more to me than following every seasonal trend.\n\nQ: What kind of clothes do you dislike?\nA: I avoid clothes that are uncomfortable, covered in large logos or impractical for the weather. I prefer an <strong class=\"key-phrase\">understated appearance</strong> and items that can be worn repeatedly.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Clothes","phrases":[{"en":"go out of style quickly","vi":"nhanh chóng lỗi mốt"},{"en":"strike a balance between","vi":"cân bằng giữa"},{"en":"appropriate for the occasion","vi":"phù hợp với hoàn cảnh"},{"en":"understated appearance","vi":"vẻ ngoài trang nhã, không phô trương"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Clothes","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-010","_displayNo":"#010","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Collecting","prompt":"Have you ever collected anything as a hobby?\nWhat kinds of thing do people often like collecting?\nWhy do you think people collect certain objects?\nIs there anything that you would like to collect in the future?","answer":"Q: Have you ever collected anything as a hobby?\nA: Yes. When I was younger I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">used to collect</strong> keyrings. I remember that my favourite was a Lego man keyring that someone bought me as a present.\n\nQ: What kinds of thing do people often like collecting?\nA: Some people collect cheap items like stamps, keyrings or toys. Others collect <strong class=\"key-phrase\">expensive antiques</strong>, watches, jewellery or even cars.\n\nQ: Why do you think people collect certain objects?\nA: Maybe they like the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">constant search</strong> for a new item, or they want to remember past experiences. Others might like the feeling of organising and presenting what they own.\n\nQ: Is there anything that you would like to collect in the future?\nA: Yes. If I could afford it, I'd love to have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a collection of guitars</strong> in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">different colours, shapes and sizes</strong>!","author":"Simon","topic":"Collecting","phrases":[{"en":"used to collect","vi":"từng sưu tầm"},{"en":"expensive antiques","vi":"đồ cổ đắt tiền"},{"en":"constant search","vi":"quá trình tìm kiếm liên tục"},{"en":"a collection of guitars","vi":"một bộ sưu tập đàn ghi-ta"},{"en":"different colours, shapes and sizes","vi":"nhiều màu sắc, hình dáng và kích thước khác nhau"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Collecting","id":"speaking-part-1-011","_displayNo":"#011","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Colours","prompt":"What colours do you like?\nDo colours affect your mood?\nDo you wear bright clothes?","answer":"Q: What colours do you like?\nA: I am particularly fond of blue because it feels calm and clean. It also works well in clothing and interior design without <strong class=\"key-phrase\">drawing too much attention</strong>.\n\nQ: Do colours affect your mood?\nA: Yes, to some extent. Soft, natural colours help me relax, whereas extremely bright colours can feel tiring when they cover a large space. The effect is subtle but <strong class=\"key-phrase\">noticeable over time</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you wear bright clothes?\nA: Only occasionally. I may wear one bright item, but I usually combine it with neutral colours so that the overall look remains <strong class=\"key-phrase\">simple and balanced</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Colours","phrases":[{"en":"drawing too much attention","vi":"thu hút quá nhiều sự chú ý"},{"en":"noticeable over time","vi":"dễ nhận thấy theo thời gian"},{"en":"simple and balanced","vi":"đơn giản và cân đối"}],"source":"Topic reference: IELTS Advantage (2026); questions adapted; answers rewritten and quality-audited by ChatGPT","subtype":"","summary":"Colours","id":"speaking-part-1-012","_displayNo":"#012","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Colours","prompt":"What is your favourite colour and why?\nDo you like the same colours now as you did when you were younger and why?\nWhat can you learn about people from the colours they like?\nDo colours have special meaning in your culture?","answer":"Q: What is your favourite colour and why?\nA: Navy blue is my favourite colour because it looks <strong class=\"key-phrase\">calm, professional and easy to combine</strong> with other colours. I also associate it with the sea and open space.\n\nQ: Do you like the same colours now as you did when you were younger and why?\nA: Not entirely. As a child I preferred bright red and orange, whereas I now choose blue, grey and dark green. My taste has become <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more understated</strong> as I have grown older.\n\nQ: What can you learn about people from the colours they like?\nA: Colour preferences may reveal whether someone enjoys bold or restrained styles, but any conclusion should be tentative. Culture, fashion and practical needs can influence choices as much as personality, so it is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">not a reliable test</strong>.\n\nQ: Do colours have special meaning in your culture?\nA: Colours do carry cultural meanings. Red is often associated with luck and celebration, while white can be connected with mourning, which shows that colour symbolism is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">highly culture-specific</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Colours","phrases":[{"en":"calm, professional and easy to combine","vi":"điềm tĩnh, chuyên nghiệp và dễ phối hợp"},{"en":"more understated","vi":"kín đáo và tinh tế hơn"},{"en":"not a reliable test","vi":"không phải một phép đánh giá đáng tin cậy"},{"en":"highly culture-specific","vi":"phụ thuộc rất nhiều vào văn hóa"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Colours","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-013","_displayNo":"#013","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Communication","prompt":"How do you usually keep in touch with members of your family?\nDo you prefer to speak to people by phone or by writing emails?\nDo you ever write letters by hand?\nIs there anything you dislike about mobile phones?","answer":"Q: How do you usually keep in touch with members of your family?\nA: I mostly <strong class=\"key-phrase\">keep in touch with</strong> my family by phone, and I've started using the Internet to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make video calls</strong>. I also try to visit members of my family in person as often as I can.\n\nQ: Do you prefer to speak to people by phone or by writing emails?\nA: <strong class=\"key-phrase\">It depends on the situation</strong>. I use email and text messages to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">communicate with friends</strong>, but my parents prefer it if I phone them.\n\nQ: Do you ever write letters by hand?\nA: No, I don't <strong class=\"key-phrase\">write letters by hand</strong> because it's so much easier to send an email that will arrive immediately.\n\nQ: Is there anything you dislike about mobile phones?\nA: Well, I don't like listening to other people's conversations in public places, and I don't like it when someone's phone rings in the cinema or during a lesson.","author":"Simon","topic":"Communication","phrases":[{"en":"keep in touch with","vi":"giữ liên lạc với"},{"en":"make video calls","vi":"gọi điện video"},{"en":"It depends on the situation","vi":"điều đó phụ thuộc vào tình huống"},{"en":"communicate with friends","vi":"giao tiếp với bạn bè"},{"en":"write letters by hand","vi":"viết thư bằng tay"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Communication","id":"speaking-part-1-014","_displayNo":"#014","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Computer","prompt":"When did you first use a computer?\nDo you think computers are bad for your health?\nWhich computer software do you use most?\nWhat did you mainly use your first computer for?","answer":"Q: When did you first use a computer?\nA: I first used a desktop computer at primary school. We learned basic typing and simple drawing programs, and I remember being fascinated by how quickly the machine <strong class=\"key-phrase\">responded to instructions</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think computers are bad for your health?\nA: They can be harmful if people sit for hours with poor posture or stare at the screen without breaks. The problem is usually not the computer itself but <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the way it is used</strong>.\n\nQ: Which computer software do you use most?\nA: I use web browsers, word-processing software and spreadsheets most often. They support almost every part of my work, from lesson preparation to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">organising information efficiently</strong>.\n\nQ: What did you mainly use your first computer for?\nA: My first computer was mainly for school assignments, basic research and educational games. Over time it became an essential tool for communication and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">independent learning</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Computer","phrases":[{"en":"responded to instructions","vi":"phản hồi theo lệnh"},{"en":"the way it is used","vi":"cách con người sử dụng nó"},{"en":"organising information efficiently","vi":"tổ chức thông tin hiệu quả"},{"en":"independent learning","vi":"việc tự học"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Computer","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-015","_displayNo":"#015","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Cooking","prompt":"Do you like cooking?\nWho did the cooking in your family when you were a child?\nDo you think that it's important to know how to cook well?\nDo you think that children should be taught cookery at school?","answer":"Q: Do you like cooking?\nA: Sometimes. I like <strong class=\"key-phrase\">preparing a special meal</strong> for family or friends who visit, but everyday cooking is a bit boring; it's something that has to be done, but it's not really fun.\n\nQ: Who did the cooking in your family when you were a child?\nA: My mother almost always did the cooking when I was young. I don't think she trusted my father to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make a nice meal</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think that it's important to know how to cook well?\nA: I'm not sure whether it's important to cook well, but I do think that everyone should <strong class=\"key-phrase\">know the basics</strong>. It definitely isn't healthy to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">rely on pre-prepared meals</strong> or fast food.\n\nQ: Do you think that children should be taught cookery at school?\nA: Yes, that's probably a good idea. If all children knew how to cook a few <strong class=\"key-phrase\">basic, healthy meals</strong>, that would surely be a good thing.","author":"Simon","topic":"Cooking","phrases":[{"en":"preparing a special meal","vi":"chuẩn bị một bữa ăn đặc biệt"},{"en":"make a nice meal","vi":"chuẩn bị một bữa ăn ngon"},{"en":"know the basics","vi":"nắm được những kiến thức cơ bản"},{"en":"rely on pre-prepared meals","vi":"phụ thuộc vào các bữa ăn chế biến sẵn"},{"en":"basic, healthy meals","vi":"những bữa ăn cơ bản và lành mạnh"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Cooking","id":"speaking-part-1-016","_displayNo":"#016","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Daily Routine","prompt":"What would you like to change in your daily routine?\nAre all your days the same?\nTell me about a typical weekday and a typical weekend.\nWhat is the balance of work/ study and free time in your normal days?","answer":"Q: What would you like to change in your daily routine?\nA: I would like to reduce the amount of time I spend looking at screens in the evening. Replacing that habit with reading or a short walk would help me <strong class=\"key-phrase\">wind down properly</strong> before bed.\n\nQ: Are all your days the same?\nA: Weekdays follow a fairly stable pattern, but weekends are much more flexible. I still keep a few fixed habits, such as exercise and meal times, because they <strong class=\"key-phrase\">give my day structure</strong>.\n\nQ: Tell me about a typical weekday and a typical weekend.\nA: On weekdays I work, exercise and prepare for the following day. At weekends I sleep a little later, meet friends or handle personal errands, so the pace is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">far less demanding</strong>.\n\nQ: What is the balance of work/ study and free time in your normal days?\nA: Work takes up most of my weekdays, but I protect time for exercise, meals and family. The balance is not perfect, yet I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make a conscious effort</strong> to maintain <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sustainable routine</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Daily Routine","phrases":[{"en":"wind down properly","vi":"thư giãn đúng cách"},{"en":"give my day structure","vi":"tạo cấu trúc cho ngày của tôi"},{"en":"far less demanding","vi":"ít áp lực hơn nhiều"},{"en":"make a conscious effort","vi":"chủ động nỗ lực"},{"en":"a sustainable routine","vi":"một lịch sinh hoạt bền vững"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Daily Routine","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-017","_displayNo":"#017","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Dancing","prompt":"Do you like dancing?\nHas anyone ever taught you to dance?\nDo you think that traditional dancing will be popular in the future?","answer":"Q: Do you like dancing?\nA: No, I don't like dancing. I'm not a big music fan, and dancing just makes me <strong class=\"key-phrase\">feel uncomfortable and self-conscious</strong>.\n\nQ: Has anyone ever taught you to dance?\nA: No, I've never been interested in learning to dance, so I've never <strong class=\"key-phrase\">taken any lessons</strong> or asked anyone to show me how to do it.\n\nQ: Do you think that traditional dancing will be popular in the future?\nA: I'm afraid I have no idea because I don't follow what's happening in the dancing world! I suppose it will always <strong class=\"key-phrase\">be popular with</strong> some people.","author":"Simon","topic":"Dancing","phrases":[{"en":"feel uncomfortable and self-conscious","vi":"cảm thấy không thoải mái và thiếu tự tin"},{"en":"taken any lessons","vi":"tham gia bất kỳ lớp học nào"},{"en":"be popular with","vi":"được ưa chuộng trong nhóm"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Dancing","id":"speaking-part-1-018","_displayNo":"#018","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Dancing","prompt":"Do you enjoy dancing and why?\nHas anyone ever taught you to dance?\nTell me about a traditional dance in your country.\nDo you think that traditional dancing will be popular in the future?","answer":"Q: Do you enjoy dancing and why?\nA: I enjoy dancing at social events, although I would not call myself skilled. It is enjoyable because the atmosphere is relaxed and people are more concerned with having fun than <strong class=\"key-phrase\">performing perfectly</strong>.\n\nQ: Has anyone ever taught you to dance?\nA: No one has taught me formally. I have picked up a few basic steps by watching friends and copying them, so my dancing is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">entirely informal</strong>.\n\nQ: Tell me about a traditional dance in your country.\nA: Vietnam has several traditional dances linked to festivals and regional cultures. They often use coordinated movements, colourful costumes and music to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">tell a cultural story</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think that traditional dancing will be popular in the future?\nA: I think it will survive, especially if schools and cultural groups present it in an engaging way. It may not become an everyday hobby, but it remains <strong class=\"key-phrase\">worth preserving</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Dancing","phrases":[{"en":"performing perfectly","vi":"thể hiện hoàn hảo"},{"en":"entirely informal","vi":"hoàn toàn tự học và không chính thức"},{"en":"tell a cultural story","vi":"kể một câu chuyện văn hóa"},{"en":"worth preserving","vi":"đáng được bảo tồn"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Dancing","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-019","_displayNo":"#019","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Dreams","prompt":"Do you often remember your dreams?\nCan dreams teach us anything?\nDo you think dreams can come true?","answer":"Q: Do you often remember your dreams?\nA: I remember dreams only occasionally, usually when I wake up during the night. Most details disappear within minutes unless the dream is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">unusually vivid</strong> or <strong class=\"key-phrase\">emotionally intense</strong>.\n\nQ: Can dreams teach us anything?\nA: They may reveal what has been occupying our attention, but I would be cautious about treating them as predictions. At most, they can provide <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a useful prompt for reflection</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think dreams can come true?\nA: Not in a supernatural sense. Occasionally a dream resembles a later event, but that is probably coincidence combined with selective memory rather than <strong class=\"key-phrase\">evidence of prediction</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Dreams","phrases":[{"en":"unusually vivid","vi":"sống động khác thường"},{"en":"emotionally intense","vi":"có cảm xúc mạnh"},{"en":"a useful prompt for reflection","vi":"một gợi ý hữu ích để suy ngẫm"},{"en":"evidence of prediction","vi":"bằng chứng về khả năng tiên đoán"}],"source":"Topic reference: IELTS Advantage (2026); questions adapted; answers rewritten and quality-audited by ChatGPT","subtype":"","summary":"Dreams","id":"speaking-part-1-020","_displayNo":"#020","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Dreams","prompt":"How often do you have dreams?\nWhat do you dream about?\nWhy do some people have nightmares?\nIs dreaming important to our well-being and health? Why?","answer":"Q: How often do you have dreams?\nA: I probably dream every night, but I remember only one or two dreams a week. I usually recall them when they are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">unusually vivid</strong> or when I wake up before the dream has faded.\n\nQ: What do you dream about?\nA: My dreams often combine ordinary places with unrealistic events, such as being late for an exam in a building I have never seen. They seem to reflect fragments of recent experiences rather than <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a hidden message</strong>.\n\nQ: Why do some people have nightmares?\nA: Nightmares can be triggered by stress, disturbed sleep or frightening experiences. When the brain is processing strong emotions, it may create threatening situations that feel <strong class=\"key-phrase\">surprisingly real</strong>.\n\nQ: Is dreaming important to our well-being and health? Why?\nA: Good-quality sleep is essential, but dreaming itself is still difficult to interpret. It may help the brain <strong class=\"key-phrase\">process memories and emotions</strong>, although its precise role remains <strong class=\"key-phrase\">open to interpretation</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Dreams","phrases":[{"en":"unusually vivid","vi":"sống động khác thường"},{"en":"a hidden message","vi":"một thông điệp ẩn giấu"},{"en":"surprisingly real","vi":"thật đến mức đáng ngạc nhiên"},{"en":"process memories and emotions","vi":"xử lý ký ức và cảm xúc"},{"en":"open to interpretation","vi":"có thể được diễn giải theo nhiều cách"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Dreams","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-021","_displayNo":"#021","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Emails And Handwriting","prompt":"At work or in your studies, do you often write things?\nHow often do you send emails?\nDo you prefer to write by hand or on a computer?\nDo you think computers might one day replace handwriting?","answer":"Q: At work or in your studies, do you often write things?\nA: Yes, I write a lot of emails <strong class=\"key-phrase\">as part of my job</strong>. I work for a company that has offices in several countries, so we use email to communicate.\n\nQ: How often do you send emails?\nA: I probably write between 5 and 10 work emails every day, and I send emails to friends or family <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a few times a week</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you prefer to write by hand or on a computer?\nA: It depends on what I am doing. I prefer the computer for most things because it’s faster and you can save or copy things, but I still like making notes or <strong class=\"key-phrase\">writing ideas down</strong> by hand.\n\nQ: Do you think computers might one day replace handwriting?\nA: No, I think we will always write by hand as well. I think it’s <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an important skill</strong>, and schools will continue to teach children to write by hand before they learn to type.","author":"Simon","topic":"Emails And Handwriting","phrases":[{"en":"as part of my job","vi":"như một phần công việc của tôi"},{"en":"a few times a week","vi":"vài lần mỗi tuần"},{"en":"writing ideas down","vi":"ghi lại các ý tưởng"},{"en":"an important skill","vi":"một kỹ năng quan trọng"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Emails And Handwriting","id":"speaking-part-1-022","_displayNo":"#022","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Family","prompt":"Can you describe your family?\nDo you have a large or a small family?\nHow much time do you spend with your family?\nWhat do you like to do together as a family?","answer":"Q: Can you describe your family?\nA: I come from a small, close family consisting of my parents, one sibling and me. We have different personalities, but we support one another and maintain <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a close-knit family</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you have a large or a small family?\nA: My immediate family is fairly small. That makes it easier for us to stay informed about one another’s lives and resolve disagreements before they <strong class=\"key-phrase\">become serious problems</strong>.\n\nQ: How much time do you spend with your family?\nA: I see my family regularly, especially in the evenings and at weekends. Even when everyone is busy, we try to share at least one meal and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">catch up with</strong> each other.\n\nQ: What do you like to do together as a family?\nA: We usually share a meal, take short trips or simply talk about what has happened during the week. None of those activities is unusual, but they give us <strong class=\"key-phrase\">uninterrupted time together</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Family","phrases":[{"en":"a close-knit family","vi":"một gia đình gắn bó"},{"en":"become serious problems","vi":"trở thành vấn đề nghiêm trọng"},{"en":"catch up with","vi":"trò chuyện và cập nhật tình hình với"},{"en":"uninterrupted time together","vi":"khoảng thời gian trọn vẹn bên nhau"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Family","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-023","_displayNo":"#023","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Family","prompt":"Who do you live with?\nDo you spend much time with your family?\nIs your family small or quite large?\nWhat do you do when you are all together?","answer":"Q: Who do you live with?\nA: I live with close family members in Hanoi. Sharing a home requires compromise, but it also provides <strong class=\"key-phrase\">practical support</strong> and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sense of belonging</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you spend much time with your family?\nA: I spend a reasonable amount of time with my family, mainly over dinner and at weekends. We are all busy, so those regular conversations help us <strong class=\"key-phrase\">stay closely connected</strong>.\n\nQ: Is your family small or quite large?\nA: My family is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">relatively small</strong>, which means decisions are easier to coordinate and everyone knows what is happening in one another’s lives.\n\nQ: What do you do when you are all together?\nA: We usually eat together, talk about work and occasionally take a short trip. The activity itself is not important; what matters is having uninterrupted time to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">strengthen our relationship</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Family","phrases":[{"en":"practical support","vi":"sự hỗ trợ thiết thực"},{"en":"a sense of belonging","vi":"cảm giác thuộc về"},{"en":"stay closely connected","vi":"duy trì sự gắn kết chặt chẽ"},{"en":"relatively small","vi":"tương đối nhỏ"},{"en":"strengthen our relationship","vi":"củng cố mối quan hệ"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Family","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-024","_displayNo":"#024","qaBands":["8.0","8.5","8.0","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Festival","prompt":"Can you describe one of the main festivals celebrated in your country?\nWhat can you tell me about the most important festival in your country?\nWhat special food and activities are connected with this festival?\nWhat do you most enjoy about it?","answer":"Q: Can you describe one of the main festivals celebrated in your country?\nA: Tet, the Lunar New Year, is the most important festival in Vietnam. Families reunite, clean and decorate their homes, and prepare for a fresh start, so the celebration <strong class=\"key-phrase\">brings people together</strong>.\n\nQ: What can you tell me about the most important festival in your country?\nA: Tet matters because it marks a new beginning and brings relatives back together after a busy year. Beyond the celebrations, it is a time to honour ancestors and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">renew family connections</strong>.\n\nQ: What special food and activities are connected with this festival?\nA: Traditional foods include bánh chưng, candied fruit and various family dishes. People also visit relatives, give lucky money to children and pay respect to ancestors, which helps <strong class=\"key-phrase\">preserve local identity</strong>.\n\nQ: What do you most enjoy about it?\nA: I enjoy the slower pace and the chance to spend uninterrupted time with family. The atmosphere is festive, but the most valuable part is the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">sense of renewal</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Festival","phrases":[{"en":"brings people together","vi":"gắn kết mọi người"},{"en":"renew family connections","vi":"thắt chặt lại các mối quan hệ gia đình"},{"en":"preserve local identity","vi":"gìn giữ bản sắc địa phương"},{"en":"sense of renewal","vi":"cảm giác khởi đầu mới"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Festival","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-025","_displayNo":"#025","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Films","prompt":"Are film stars paid too much money, in your opinion?\nDo you think there is too much violence in modern movies?\nWhat do you think about film censorship, and is it necessary?\nWhat was the last film you saw? Did you enjoy it?","answer":"Q: Are film stars paid too much money, in your opinion?\nA: A few global stars are paid extraordinary sums, but their names can determine whether a film attracts investment and audiences. The salaries seem excessive, although they reflect <strong class=\"key-phrase\">commercial value rather than social value</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think there is too much violence in modern movies?\nA: Some films rely too heavily on violence because it creates immediate excitement. Violence can serve a story, but repeated graphic scenes may become <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a substitute for good writing</strong>.\n\nQ: What do you think about film censorship, and is it necessary?\nA: Limited classification is necessary to protect children and warn viewers, but blanket censorship is risky. Adults should generally be free to choose what they watch, provided there is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">clear age guidance</strong>.\n\nQ: What was the last film you saw? Did you enjoy it?\nA: The last film I watched was a thoughtful drama about a family dealing with change. I enjoyed it because the characters felt believable and the story avoided <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an overly predictable ending</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Films","phrases":[{"en":"commercial value rather than social value","vi":"giá trị thương mại hơn là giá trị xã hội"},{"en":"a substitute for good writing","vi":"thứ thay thế cho kịch bản tốt"},{"en":"clear age guidance","vi":"hướng dẫn độ tuổi rõ ràng"},{"en":"an overly predictable ending","vi":"một cái kết quá dễ đoán"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Films","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-026","_displayNo":"#026","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Films","prompt":"Do you enjoy watching movies?\nDo you prefer to see a movie alone or with your friends?\nDo you prefer watching films at the cinema or at home?\nWhat is your most/least favourite type of movie?","answer":"Q: Do you enjoy watching movies?\nA: Yes, especially well-written dramas and documentaries. A good film allows me to relax while seeing a situation from <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a different point of view</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you prefer to see a movie alone or with your friends?\nA: I usually watch films with friends because discussing them afterwards adds to the experience. For serious or complex films, however, I sometimes prefer watching alone so I can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">pay close attention to</strong> the details.\n\nQ: Do you prefer watching films at the cinema or at home?\nA: I prefer the cinema for visually impressive films, but home is more convenient for ordinary viewing. The cinema offers immersion, while home allows me to pause and watch <strong class=\"key-phrase\">at my own pace</strong>.\n\nQ: What is your most/least favourite type of movie?\nA: My favourite genre is realistic drama, and I am least interested in formulaic horror films. I prefer stories with convincing characters and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">emotional depth</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Films","phrases":[{"en":"a different point of view","vi":"một góc nhìn khác"},{"en":"pay close attention to","vi":"chú ý kỹ đến"},{"en":"at my own pace","vi":"theo nhịp độ của riêng tôi"},{"en":"emotional depth","vi":"chiều sâu cảm xúc"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Films","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-027","_displayNo":"#027","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Food","prompt":"Do you like cooking?\nWho does the cooking in your home?\nDo you think family meals are important?\nWhat kind of food do you like?","answer":"Q: Do you like cooking?\nA: Yes, although I cook simple meals rather than elaborate dishes. I enjoy being able to control the ingredients and adjust flavours <strong class=\"key-phrase\">to my own taste</strong>.\n\nQ: Who does the cooking in your home?\nA: Cooking is shared in my home, depending on who has time. That arrangement is practical and prevents one person from carrying <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the entire responsibility</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think family meals are important?\nA: Yes, because they create a regular opportunity for people to talk without distractions. Even a short meal can help family members <strong class=\"key-phrase\">stay connected</strong>.\n\nQ: What kind of food do you like?\nA: I like fresh Vietnamese food, particularly dishes with vegetables, herbs and light broths. I am less keen on food that is excessively oily because it leaves me feeling <strong class=\"key-phrase\">heavy and tired</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Food","phrases":[{"en":"to my own taste","vi":"theo khẩu vị của riêng tôi"},{"en":"the entire responsibility","vi":"toàn bộ trách nhiệm"},{"en":"stay connected","vi":"duy trì sự gắn kết"},{"en":"heavy and tired","vi":"nặng nề và mệt mỏi"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Food","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-028","_displayNo":"#028","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Food","prompt":"What are your most/ least favourite foods?\nIf you invited a friend over for a meal, what would you serve?\nDo you prefer eating at home or in a restaurant and why?\nWhat special dish from your country would you recommend to a visitor?","answer":"Q: What are your most/ least favourite foods?\nA: I particularly enjoy fresh Vietnamese dishes with herbs, vegetables and light broths. I am least fond of food that is extremely greasy or sweet because it leaves me feeling <strong class=\"key-phrase\">heavy and tired</strong>.\n\nQ: If you invited a friend over for a meal, what would you serve?\nA: I would probably serve grilled chicken, rice, vegetables and a light soup. It is easy to prepare for several people and can be adapted to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">different dietary preferences</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you prefer eating at home or in a restaurant and why?\nA: I prefer eating at home on ordinary days because it is healthier and less expensive. Restaurants are enjoyable for special occasions, but home cooking gives me <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more control over ingredients</strong>.\n\nQ: What special dish from your country would you recommend to a visitor?\nA: I would recommend phở because it is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">widely available</strong> yet closely associated with Vietnamese cuisine. Its clear broth, herbs and rice noodles create <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a balanced combination of flavours</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Food","phrases":[{"en":"heavy and tired","vi":"nặng nề và mệt mỏi"},{"en":"different dietary preferences","vi":"các sở thích ăn uống khác nhau"},{"en":"more control over ingredients","vi":"nhiều quyền kiểm soát nguyên liệu hơn"},{"en":"widely available","vi":"phổ biến rộng rãi"},{"en":"a balanced combination of flavours","vi":"sự kết hợp hương vị cân bằng"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Food","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-029","_displayNo":"#029","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Free Time","prompt":"How much time do you spend at home?\nDo you prefer to spend your free time at home or outside the house?\nWhat do you do when you have some free time and you're at home?\nWould you like to have more spare time to spend at home in the future?","answer":"Q: How much time do you spend at home?\nA: Obviously I sleep at home, but I don't <strong class=\"key-phrase\">spend very much time at home</strong> during the day, because I'm usually busy with work.\n\nQ: Do you prefer to spend your free time at home or outside the house?\nA: During the day I prefer to be out of the house, so I like visiting family or <strong class=\"key-phrase\">meeting up with friends</strong>. But I do like relaxing at home in the evenings.\n\nQ: What do you do when you have some free time and you're at home?\nA: I usually sit and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">watch some TV</strong> or a film, or I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">listen to some music</strong>. I also like sitting outside if the weather is nice.\n\nQ: Would you like to have more spare time to spend at home in the future?\nA: No, not really. I get bored if I'm at home for too long. In the future, I imagine I'll still <strong class=\"key-phrase\">prefer to go out</strong> and do things rather than stay indoors.","author":"Simon","topic":"Free Time","phrases":[{"en":"spend very much time at home","vi":"dành nhiều thời gian ở nhà"},{"en":"meeting up with friends","vi":"gặp gỡ bạn bè"},{"en":"watch some TV","vi":"xem một chút truyền hình"},{"en":"listen to some music","vi":"nghe một chút nhạc"},{"en":"prefer to go out","vi":"thích ra ngoài hơn"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Free Time","id":"speaking-part-1-030","_displayNo":"#030","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Friends","prompt":"Are your friends mostly your age or different ages?\nDo you usually see your friends during the week or at weekends?\nThe last time you saw your friends, what did you do together?\nIn what ways are your friends important to you?","answer":"Q: Are your friends mostly your age or different ages?\nA: Most of my friends are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">about the same age</strong> as me because we met at school or university. I've got one or two friends who are older or younger that I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">met through work</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you usually see your friends during the week or at weekends?\nA: I tend to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">meet up with my friends</strong> at weekends because everyone's too busy during the week.\n\nQ: The last time you saw your friends, what did you do together?\nA: It was one of my friends' birthday last weekend. Six of us went <strong class=\"key-phrase\">out for a meal</strong> to celebrate.\n\nQ: In what ways are your friends important to you?\nA: I think it's important to have friends that you can talk to and share experiences with. My friends <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make me laugh</strong>, but I know I can also rely on them whenever I need help or support.","author":"Simon","topic":"Friends","phrases":[{"en":"about the same age","vi":"gần bằng tuổi nhau"},{"en":"met through work","vi":"quen nhau thông qua công việc"},{"en":"meet up with my friends","vi":"gặp gỡ bạn bè"},{"en":"out for a meal","vi":"ra ngoài ăn một bữa"},{"en":"make me laugh","vi":"khiến tôi bật cười"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Friends","id":"speaking-part-1-031","_displayNo":"#031","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Friends","prompt":"Do you prefer to have one particular friend or a group of friends?\nWhat do you like doing most with your friends?\nDo you think it's important to keep in touch with childhood friends?\nWhat makes a good friend?","answer":"Q: Do you prefer to have one particular friend or a group of friends?\nA: I prefer a small group of close friends rather than one exclusive friendship. Different friends bring different perspectives, while the group still gives me <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a reliable support network</strong>.\n\nQ: What do you like doing most with your friends?\nA: We usually have coffee, exercise or take short trips. The activity is secondary; I mainly enjoy having time to talk openly and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">share everyday experiences</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think it's important to keep in touch with childhood friends?\nA: It is valuable when the friendship remains healthy, because childhood friends understand your background. However, people change, so staying in touch should feel natural rather than <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a social obligation</strong>.\n\nQ: What makes a good friend?\nA: A good friend is trustworthy, honest and able to listen without immediately judging. Mutual respect matters more than constant agreement because it creates <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a genuine connection</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Friends","phrases":[{"en":"a reliable support network","vi":"một mạng lưới hỗ trợ đáng tin cậy"},{"en":"share everyday experiences","vi":"chia sẻ những trải nghiệm thường ngày"},{"en":"a social obligation","vi":"một nghĩa vụ xã hội"},{"en":"a genuine connection","vi":"một sự kết nối chân thành"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Friends","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-032","_displayNo":"#032","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Games","prompt":"What games are popular in your country?\nDo you play any games?\nHow do people learn to play games in your country?\nDo you think it's important for people to play games?","answer":"Q: What games are popular in your country?\nA: Well, if we can consider sports as games, then football is definitely the most popular game in my country, but we also love board games like chess.\n\nQ: Do you play any games?\nA: Not regularly these days. I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">play the occasional game of</strong> tennis with my brother-in-law, and I recently played a bowling game on the Nintendo Wii with my nephew. I wasn't very good at it.\n\nQ: How do people learn to play games in your country?\nA: I think children teach each other to play games. I remember a friend at primary school teaching me to play chess, for example.\n\nQ: Do you think it's important for people to play games?\nA: Yes, it's really important, especially for children. I think research has shown that play can improve <strong class=\"key-phrase\">brain development</strong>, intelligence, creativity, and the ability to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cooperate with others</strong>.","author":"Simon","topic":"Games","phrases":[{"en":"play the occasional game of","vi":"thỉnh thoảng chơi một trận"},{"en":"brain development","vi":"sự phát triển của não bộ"},{"en":"cooperate with others","vi":"hợp tác với người khác"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Games","id":"speaking-part-1-033","_displayNo":"#033","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Games","prompt":"Do you enjoy playing games?\nWhat kind of games do children play in your country?\nDo you think adults should play games?\nWhat kinds of games were popular when you were younger?","answer":"Q: Do you enjoy playing games?\nA: Yes, particularly strategy and word games. They are entertaining but also require concentration, so they provide <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a healthy mental challenge</strong>.\n\nQ: What kind of games do children play in your country?\nA: Children play mobile games, football, hide-and-seek and a variety of classroom games. Digital games are more visible now, but physical games remain important for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">social and motor skills</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think adults should play games?\nA: Certainly, provided gaming does not replace work, exercise or relationships. Games can reduce stress and keep the mind active, so they are not <strong class=\"key-phrase\">only for children</strong>.\n\nQ: What kinds of games were popular when you were younger?\nA: When I was younger, outdoor games and simple board games were common. Children had fewer devices, so entertainment depended more on imagination and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">face-to-face interaction</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Games","phrases":[{"en":"a healthy mental challenge","vi":"một thử thách trí tuệ lành mạnh"},{"en":"social and motor skills","vi":"kỹ năng xã hội và vận động"},{"en":"only for children","vi":"chỉ dành cho trẻ em"},{"en":"face-to-face interaction","vi":"sự tương tác trực tiếp"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Games","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-034","_displayNo":"#034","qaBands":["8.0","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Health & Fitness","prompt":"Is your health important to you?\nWhat do you do to improve your health?\nWhat is a major health concern in your country?\nWhat can be done about it?","answer":"Q: Is your health important to you?\nA: Yes, because health affects energy, concentration and independence. It is easy to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take it for granted</strong> until a problem appears, so prevention is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a worthwhile investment</strong>.\n\nQ: What do you do to improve your health?\nA: I exercise several times a week, sleep consistently and try to eat mostly unprocessed food. None of these habits is dramatic, but together they <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make a noticeable difference</strong>.\n\nQ: What is a major health concern in your country?\nA: Lifestyle-related conditions such as obesity, diabetes and stress are growing concerns. They develop gradually, which means public education and early screening should <strong class=\"key-phrase\">play a central role</strong>.\n\nQ: What can be done about it?\nA: Governments can improve preventive care, safe public spaces and nutrition education, while individuals need realistic habits they can maintain. The most effective response is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a shared responsibility</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Health & Fitness","phrases":[{"en":"take it for granted","vi":"xem đó là điều hiển nhiên"},{"en":"a worthwhile investment","vi":"một khoản đầu tư xứng đáng"},{"en":"make a noticeable difference","vi":"tạo ra sự khác biệt rõ rệt"},{"en":"play a central role","vi":"đóng vai trò trung tâm"},{"en":"a shared responsibility","vi":"trách nhiệm chung"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Health & Fitness","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-035","_displayNo":"#035","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Health & Fitness","prompt":"What kind of exercise do you do regularly?\nWhat kind of exercise do you enjoy least?\nWhy is exercise good for health?\nWhat kind of exercise would you suggest to someone who is very unfit?","answer":"Q: What kind of exercise do you do regularly?\nA: I do strength training and brisk walking several times a week. The combination improves fitness without requiring specialised facilities and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">fits naturally into my routine</strong>.\n\nQ: What kind of exercise do you enjoy least?\nA: I enjoy long-distance running least because repetitive impact can be uncomfortable. I prefer exercise that combines strength, mobility and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">steady progress</strong>.\n\nQ: Why is exercise good for health?\nA: Exercise strengthens the heart and muscles, improves sleep and helps regulate stress. It also supports long-term independence, which is often <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more important than appearance</strong>.\n\nQ: What kind of exercise would you suggest to someone who is very unfit?\nA: I would suggest daily walking and simple body-weight exercises. They are low-cost, easy to adjust and allow an unfit person to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">build confidence gradually</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Health & Fitness","phrases":[{"en":"fits naturally into my routine","vi":"phù hợp tự nhiên với nếp sinh hoạt của tôi"},{"en":"steady progress","vi":"sự tiến bộ đều đặn"},{"en":"more important than appearance","vi":"quan trọng hơn ngoại hình"},{"en":"build confidence gradually","vi":"xây dựng sự tự tin từng bước"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Health & Fitness","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-036","_displayNo":"#036","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Hobbies","prompt":"Do you have any hobbies?\nWhat are some of your hobbies?\nWhat do you usually do in your spare time?\nDo you prefer to stay alone or with your friends?","answer":"Q: Do you have any hobbies?\nA: Yes. I make time for reading, strength training and language learning. Having several interests gives me <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a healthy outlet</strong> outside work.\n\nQ: What are some of your hobbies?\nA: Reading helps me explore ideas, strength training gives me measurable physical goals, and language learning keeps me intellectually curious. Each hobby serves <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a different purpose</strong>.\n\nQ: What do you usually do in your spare time?\nA: I usually read, exercise or meet a friend for coffee. I try to choose activities that help me recover rather than spending all my free time <strong class=\"key-phrase\">scrolling without purpose</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you prefer to stay alone or with your friends?\nA: I enjoy both. Reading and training alone help me focus, while social activities prevent my routine from becoming too isolated, so I try to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">strike a balance</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Hobbies","phrases":[{"en":"a healthy outlet","vi":"một cách giải tỏa lành mạnh"},{"en":"a different purpose","vi":"một mục đích khác nhau"},{"en":"scrolling without purpose","vi":"lướt nội dung không mục đích"},{"en":"strike a balance","vi":"tạo sự cân bằng"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Hobbies","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-037","_displayNo":"#037","qaBands":["8.0","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Hobbies","prompt":"What do you do in your spare time?\nHow long have you been interested in this activity?\nDo you do this alone or with other people?\nHow much time do you spend doing this activity?","answer":"Q: What do you do in your spare time?\nA: <strong class=\"key-phrase\">In my spare time</strong> I usually train at the gym, read or take a quiet walk. I prefer activities that leave me mentally refreshed rather than simply filling time.\n\nQ: How long have you been interested in this activity?\nA: I have been strength training for several years. I started for general fitness, but the process of tracking small improvements made it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">personally rewarding</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you do this alone or with other people?\nA: I do some hobbies alone because solitude helps me concentrate, but I also exercise or go out with friends. That combination allows me to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">strike a healthy balance</strong> between independence and social contact.\n\nQ: How much time do you spend doing this activity?\nA: I spend roughly four or five hours a week on it. That is enough to make progress without allowing the hobby to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take over my schedule</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Hobbies","phrases":[{"en":"In my spare time","vi":"trong thời gian rảnh"},{"en":"personally rewarding","vi":"mang lại sự thỏa mãn cá nhân"},{"en":"strike a healthy balance","vi":"đạt được sự cân bằng lành mạnh"},{"en":"take over my schedule","vi":"chiếm hết lịch trình của tôi"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Hobbies","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-038","_displayNo":"#038","qaBands":["8.5","8.0","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Home & Accommodation","prompt":"How long have you lived there?\nWhat do you like about living there?\nWhat sort of accommodation would you most like to live in?","answer":"Q: How long have you lived there?\nA: I've lived there for about five years. It's the first house that I've owned; before that I was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">renting an apartment</strong>.\n\nQ: What do you like about living there?\nA: I like living there because I think the house <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reflects my personality</strong>: I decorated it myself, I chose all the furniture, and everything is where I want it to be.\n\nQ: What sort of accommodation would you most like to live in?\nA: If I could, I'd buy a bigger house near a beach or in the mountains, preferably somewhere <strong class=\"key-phrase\">with a warm climate</strong>.","author":"Simon","topic":"Home & Accommodation","phrases":[{"en":"renting an apartment","vi":"thuê một căn hộ"},{"en":"reflects my personality","vi":"phản ánh tính cách của tôi"},{"en":"with a warm climate","vi":"có khí hậu ấm áp"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Home & Accommodation","id":"speaking-part-1-039","_displayNo":"#039","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Home & Accommodation","prompt":"Do you live in a house or an apartment?\nWhich is your favourite room in your home?\nWould you change anything about your home?\nWould you like to move to a different home in the future?","answer":"Q: Do you live in a house or an apartment?\nA: I live in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a semi-detached house</strong> with three bedrooms in a suburb of Manchester. I've lived there for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">just over a year</strong>.\n\nQ: Which is your favourite room in your home?\nA: I don't really have a favourite room. But <strong class=\"key-phrase\">if I had to choose</strong>, I'd say the living room because that's where I go to sit and relax.\n\nQ: Would you change anything about your home?\nA: Yes, I've <strong class=\"key-phrase\">been meaning to</strong> redecorate it since I moved in last year. It needs a new kitchen, so that's what I'd change first.\n\nQ: Would you like to move to a different home in the future?\nA: Yes, I'd definitely move again at some point if I could afford to. I'd like to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">live in the countryside</strong>, or maybe in a different city or country.","author":"Simon","topic":"Home & Accommodation","phrases":[{"en":"a semi-detached house","vi":"một căn nhà liền kề một bên"},{"en":"just over a year","vi":"hơn một năm một chút"},{"en":"if I had to choose","vi":"nếu buộc phải lựa chọn"},{"en":"been meaning to","vi":"đã định làm từ lâu"},{"en":"live in the countryside","vi":"sống ở vùng nông thôn"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Home & Accommodation","id":"speaking-part-1-040","_displayNo":"#040","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Home & Accommodation","prompt":"Do you live in a house or an apartment?\nWhich room do you like most in your house?\nIs there anything about your house that you would like to change?","answer":"Q: Do you live in a house or an apartment?\nA: I live in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a semi-detached house</strong> with three bedrooms and a small garden.\n\nQ: Which room do you like most in your house?\nA: My favourite room is the kitchen because it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">looks out onto</strong> the back garden, and it's on the side of the house that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">catches the afternoon sun</strong>.\n\nQ: Is there anything about your house that you would like to change?\nA: Well, it would be nice if it were <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a detached house</strong> so that we could have windows on the wall that we currently share with our neighbours.","author":"Simon","topic":"Home & Accommodation","phrases":[{"en":"a semi-detached house","vi":"một căn nhà liền kề một bên"},{"en":"looks out onto","vi":"nhìn ra phía"},{"en":"catches the afternoon sun","vi":"đón ánh nắng buổi chiều"},{"en":"a detached house","vi":"một căn nhà biệt lập"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Home & Accommodation","id":"speaking-part-1-041","_displayNo":"#041","qaBands":["8.5","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Hometown","prompt":"Where are you from?\nDo you like your hometown?\nWould you prefer to live somewhere else?\nDo you think your hometown is a good place for young people?","answer":"Q: Where are you from?\nA: I'm from Manchester, which is a city in the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">north west of England</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you like your hometown?\nA: Yes, I like living in Manchester because it's where most of my friends live, and because there are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">plenty of things to do</strong> there. The only thing I don't like is the weather.\n\nQ: Would you prefer to live somewhere else?\nA: For the moment I'm happy living here, but <strong class=\"key-phrase\">at some point</strong> I'd like to live in a country with a warmer climate, and I'd like to live near a beach!\n\nQ: Do you think your hometown is a good place for young people?\nA: Yes, Manchester has lots of things for young people, such as <strong class=\"key-phrase\">sports facilities</strong>, music and cinemas.","author":"Simon","topic":"Hometown","phrases":[{"en":"north west of England","vi":"phía tây bắc nước Anh"},{"en":"plenty of things to do","vi":"nhiều hoạt động để làm"},{"en":"at some point","vi":"vào một thời điểm nào đó"},{"en":"sports facilities","vi":"cơ sở vật chất thể thao"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Hometown","id":"speaking-part-1-042","_displayNo":"#042","qaBands":["8.5","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Hometown","prompt":"Describe a place where you were born?\nTell me about the main types of buildings there?\nHow have buildings in your hometown changed since you were a child?\nCan you describe your hometown?","answer":"Q: Describe a place where you were born?\nA: I was born in Hanoi, a historic city in northern Vietnam. It is densely populated, but its lakes, old streets and mature trees give many areas <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a distinctive atmosphere</strong>.\n\nQ: Tell me about the main types of buildings there?\nA: The city contains traditional houses, French colonial buildings, apartment blocks and modern offices. This mixture reflects several stages of development rather than <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a single architectural style</strong>.\n\nQ: How have buildings in your hometown changed since you were a child?\nA: There are many more high-rise apartments and commercial buildings now. The city has gained modern facilities, although some neighbourhoods have lost part of their <strong class=\"key-phrase\">original character</strong>.\n\nQ: Can you describe your hometown?\nA: Hanoi is lively, culturally rich and sometimes chaotic. It offers excellent food and services, but traffic and pollution <strong class=\"key-phrase\">place considerable pressure on</strong> daily life.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Hometown","phrases":[{"en":"a distinctive atmosphere","vi":"một bầu không khí đặc trưng"},{"en":"a single architectural style","vi":"một phong cách kiến trúc duy nhất"},{"en":"original character","vi":"nét đặc trưng ban đầu"},{"en":"place considerable pressure on","vi":"gây áp lực đáng kể lên"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Hometown","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-043","_displayNo":"#043","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Hometown","prompt":"Where do you come from?\nWhere do you live?\nCan you tell me something about your hometown?\nCan you name some well-known scenic places in your city?","answer":"Q: Where do you come from?\nA: I come from Hanoi, Vietnam’s capital. It is an energetic city with a long history, a strong food culture and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a pace of development</strong> that is visible almost everywhere.\n\nQ: Where do you live?\nA: I live in Hanoi, in an urban district with easy access to shops and public services. The area is busy, but it is convenient enough to make daily errands <strong class=\"key-phrase\">relatively straightforward</strong>.\n\nQ: Can you tell me something about your hometown?\nA: My hometown is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a city of contrasts</strong>: historic streets sit beside modern districts, and quiet lakes are surrounded by extremely busy roads. That mixture gives Hanoi its distinctive character.\n\nQ: Can you name some well-known scenic places in your city?\nA: Hoan Kiem Lake, the Old Quarter and West Lake are among the best-known places. They show different sides of the city and are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">easy for visitors to explore</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Hometown","phrases":[{"en":"a pace of development","vi":"nhịp độ phát triển"},{"en":"relatively straightforward","vi":"tương đối thuận tiện"},{"en":"a city of contrasts","vi":"một thành phố đầy tương phản"},{"en":"easy for visitors to explore","vi":"dễ dàng để du khách khám phá"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Hometown","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-044","_displayNo":"#044","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Internet","prompt":"Do you use the internet much during the day?\nWhich website have you visited recently?\nWhat are some advantages of the internet?\nDo people in your country use the internet a lot?","answer":"Q: Do you use the internet much during the day?\nA: Yes, I use it throughout the day for work, communication and research. I try to use it deliberately, because constant notifications can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">fragment my attention</strong>.\n\nQ: Which website have you visited recently?\nA: I recently visited an educational website to compare language-learning resources. I liked the clear structure and the fact that the information was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">supported by practical examples</strong>.\n\nQ: What are some advantages of the internet?\nA: The internet gives people rapid access to information, services and communication. Its greatest advantage is that it can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">lower the barrier to entry</strong> for education and business.\n\nQ: Do people in your country use the internet a lot?\nA: Yes, especially in cities, where people rely on it for banking, shopping, entertainment and work. Usage is widespread, although digital skills and high-quality access remain <strong class=\"key-phrase\">unevenly distributed</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Internet","phrases":[{"en":"fragment my attention","vi":"làm sự chú ý của tôi bị phân mảnh"},{"en":"supported by practical examples","vi":"được minh họa bằng ví dụ thực tế"},{"en":"lower the barrier to entry","vi":"giảm rào cản tiếp cận"},{"en":"unevenly distributed","vi":"phân bố không đồng đều"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Internet","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-045","_displayNo":"#045","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Job","prompt":"Can you tell me about the job you do?\nWhat do you like or dislike about it?\nWhat plans do you have for your career in the future?\nHow serious is unemployment in your country?","answer":"Q: Can you tell me about the job you do?\nA: I work as an English teacher. My role involves planning lessons, explaining difficult points and giving feedback that helps learners <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make steady progress</strong>.\n\nQ: What do you like or dislike about it?\nA: I like seeing students become more confident and independent. The difficult part is the amount of preparation and marking, especially when several deadlines <strong class=\"key-phrase\">fall in the same week</strong>.\n\nQ: What plans do you have for your career in the future?\nA: I want to deepen my teaching expertise and use technology more effectively in my courses. In the longer term, I hope to develop learning materials that are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">both practical and rigorous</strong>.\n\nQ: How serious is unemployment in your country?\nA: Unemployment varies by sector, but young graduates often struggle to find work that matches their training. The challenge is not only the number of jobs but also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the mismatch of skills</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Job","phrases":[{"en":"make steady progress","vi":"tiến bộ đều đặn"},{"en":"fall in the same week","vi":"rơi vào cùng một tuần"},{"en":"both practical and rigorous","vi":"vừa thực tế vừa chặt chẽ"},{"en":"the mismatch of skills","vi":"sự không phù hợp về kỹ năng"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Job","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-046","_displayNo":"#046","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Laughing","prompt":"What kinds of thing make you laugh?\nDo you like making other people laugh?\nDo you think it's important for people to laugh?\nIs laughing the same as feeling happy?","answer":"Q: What kinds of thing make you laugh?\nA: I laugh most when I'm with friends talking about funny things that have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">happened to</strong> us. I also like watching comedians and comedy films.\n\nQ: Do you like making other people laugh?\nA: Yes, it's a nice feeling when you can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make someone laugh</strong> because you can see that you've made them happy. It's great to share a funny moment with someone.\n\nQ: Do you think it's important for people to laugh?\nA: Yes, of course. It's important to see the funny side of things; humour helps us not to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take life too seriously</strong>. I think that laughter is good for our health.\n\nQ: Is laughing the same as feeling happy?\nA: It's not exactly the same because you can be happy without laughing, and sometimes we laugh when something bad has happened; <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sense of humour</strong> can help us to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cope with difficult situations</strong>.","author":"Simon","topic":"Laughing","phrases":[{"en":"happened to","vi":"tình cờ"},{"en":"make someone laugh","vi":"khiến ai đó bật cười"},{"en":"take life too seriously","vi":"quá nghiêm trọng hóa cuộc sống"},{"en":"a sense of humour","vi":"khiếu hài hước"},{"en":"cope with difficult situations","vi":"ứng phó với những tình huống khó khăn"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Laughing","id":"speaking-part-1-047","_displayNo":"#047","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Maps","prompt":"Do you ever use maps?\nWhen do people usually need to use a map?\nDo you prefer electronic or paper maps?\nDo you ever ask people for directions instead of using a map?","answer":"Q: Do you ever use maps?\nA: Yes. Whenever I go somewhere new, I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">plan my journey</strong> with the help of a map.\n\nQ: When do people usually need to use a map?\nA: I imagine that some people use a map every day if they travel to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">different places for work</strong>. Others might only use a map when they're on holiday.\n\nQ: Do you prefer electronic or paper maps?\nA: I still prefer paper maps for a long journey; I like being able to open the map out on a table and see the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">full journey ahead</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you ever ask people for directions instead of using a map?\nA: Only if I'm really lost. Whenever I ask for directions, I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">find it difficult to</strong> remember what the person said. So I prefer to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">find my own way</strong>.","author":"Simon","topic":"Maps","phrases":[{"en":"plan my journey","vi":"lên kế hoạch cho hành trình"},{"en":"different places for work","vi":"nhiều địa điểm khác nhau vì công việc"},{"en":"full journey ahead","vi":"toàn bộ hành trình phía trước"},{"en":"find it difficult to","vi":"cảm thấy khó để"},{"en":"find my own way","vi":"tự tìm đường"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Maps","id":"speaking-part-1-048","_displayNo":"#048","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Mathematics","prompt":"At what age did you start studying mathematics?\nDo you like mathematics?\nIs it necessary for everyone to learn mathematics?\nDo you prefer to use a calculator when doing mathematics?","answer":"Q: At what age did you start studying mathematics?\nA: I can't exactly remember, but it was probably in my first year at primary school when I was 5 years old. I probably learned <strong class=\"key-phrase\">simple addition</strong> at that age.\n\nQ: Do you like mathematics?\nA: I don't dislike maths, but I wouldn't say that I've ever really liked the subject either. I'm happy to do <strong class=\"key-phrase\">simple calculations</strong>, but my brain can't cope with the complex stuff!\n\nQ: Is it necessary for everyone to learn mathematics?\nA: Yes, I think it is. We all need <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a basic grounding in maths</strong> so that we can do daily tasks, like <strong class=\"key-phrase\">managing our money</strong>, working out bills, and so on.\n\nQ: Do you prefer to use a calculator when doing mathematics?\nA: It depends. I quite like <strong class=\"key-phrase\">exercising my brain</strong> with anything that's easy enough, but I use the calculator on my phone for anything tricky.","author":"Simon","topic":"Mathematics","phrases":[{"en":"simple addition","vi":"phép cộng đơn giản"},{"en":"simple calculations","vi":"các phép tính đơn giản"},{"en":"a basic grounding in maths","vi":"nền tảng toán học cơ bản"},{"en":"managing our money","vi":"quản lý tiền bạc của chúng ta"},{"en":"exercising my brain","vi":"rèn luyện trí não"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Mathematics","id":"speaking-part-1-049","_displayNo":"#049","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Museum","prompt":"Which museums have you visited recently?\nWhat did you enjoy seeing there?\nWhich famous museum would you like to visit?\nWhich collections would you particularly like to see there?","answer":"Q: Which museums have you visited recently?\nA: I recently visited the Vietnam Museum of Ethnology in Hanoi. It presents the cultures of different ethnic groups through objects, photographs and reconstructed houses, which makes the visit <strong class=\"key-phrase\">highly informative</strong>.\n\nQ: What did you enjoy seeing there?\nA: I particularly enjoyed the traditional houses and everyday objects. They showed how climate, materials and customs shape the way communities <strong class=\"key-phrase\">organise daily life</strong>.\n\nQ: Which famous museum would you like to visit?\nA: I would like to visit the British Museum because its collection covers an enormous span of history. Seeing original objects would give me <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a more tangible connection</strong> with the past.\n\nQ: Which collections would you particularly like to see there?\nA: I would be most interested in ancient civilisations and the history of writing. Those collections can show how ideas travelled and how societies <strong class=\"key-phrase\">influenced one another</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Museum","phrases":[{"en":"highly informative","vi":"cung cấp nhiều thông tin hữu ích"},{"en":"organise daily life","vi":"tổ chức đời sống hằng ngày"},{"en":"a more tangible connection","vi":"một sự kết nối cụ thể hơn"},{"en":"influenced one another","vi":"ảnh hưởng lẫn nhau"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Museum","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-050","_displayNo":"#050","qaBands":["8.5","8.0","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Music","prompt":"Do you like music?\nWhat kind of music did you listen to when you were young?\nWhen was the last time you went to a concert?\nWould you like to participate in a live music show?","answer":"Q: Do you like music?\nA: No, I don't really like music, and I don't listen to it. It's <strong class=\"key-phrase\">not something that I've ever been interested in</strong>.\n\nQ: What kind of music did you listen to when you were young?\nA: I can't remember listening to much music as a child either. I suppose I must have heard some traditional music at festivals or parties, but I didn't <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take much notice of</strong> it.\n\nQ: When was the last time you went to a concert?\nA: I've never been to a music concert. Maybe I should try going to one; perhaps it would be interesting to see an orchestra playing <strong class=\"key-phrase\">classical music</strong>.\n\nQ: Would you like to participate in a live music show?\nA: No, definitely not. I don't <strong class=\"key-phrase\">play a musical instrument</strong> and I don't sing, so I can't imagine that I'd ever find myself performing to an audience.","author":"Simon","topic":"Music","phrases":[{"en":"not something that I've ever been interested in","vi":"không phải điều tôi từng hứng thú"},{"en":"take much notice of","vi":"để ý nhiều đến"},{"en":"classical music","vi":"nhạc cổ điển"},{"en":"play a musical instrument","vi":"chơi một nhạc cụ"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Music","id":"speaking-part-1-051","_displayNo":"#051","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Music","prompt":"Which musical instrument do you like listening to most?\nHave you ever learned to play a musical instrument?\nDo you think children should learn to play an instrument at school?\nHow easy would it be to learn to play an instrument without a teacher?","answer":"Q: Which musical instrument do you like listening to most?\nA: My favourite musical instrument to listen to is the guitar. I like the fact that there are different types of guitar, like classical, acoustic and electric. I love the variety of sounds a guitar can make.\n\nQ: Have you ever learned to play a musical instrument?\nA: I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">took some guitar lessons</strong> when I was younger and still have a guitar at home. I don't play it much nowadays. I wish I had more time to practise.\n\nQ: Do you think children should learn to play an instrument at school?\nA: Yes, I think it's a great skill and it's really enjoyable to be able to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">play a musical instrument</strong>. All children should be given this opportunity.\n\nQ: How easy would it be to learn to play an instrument without a teacher?\nA: It would probably be more difficult without a teacher. You need someone to show you what to do and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">correct your mistakes</strong>. You need a lot of discipline to teach yourself.","author":"Simon","topic":"Music","phrases":[{"en":"took some guitar lessons","vi":"đã học một vài buổi đàn ghi-ta"},{"en":"play a musical instrument","vi":"chơi một nhạc cụ"},{"en":"correct your mistakes","vi":"sửa lỗi cho bạn"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Music","id":"speaking-part-1-052","_displayNo":"#052","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Music","prompt":"Which instruments do you like listening to most and why?\nHave you ever learned to play a musical instrument at school and why?\nDo you think children should learn to play a musical instrument at school?\nHow easy would it be to learn to play an instrument without a teacher?","answer":"Q: Which instruments do you like listening to most and why?\nA: I enjoy the piano and acoustic guitar most. Both can sound intimate or powerful, and they work across many musical styles without <strong class=\"key-phrase\">overwhelming the melody</strong>.\n\nQ: Have you ever learned to play a musical instrument at school and why?\nA: I had a few basic music lessons at school but never became proficient. Even so, they taught me rhythm and showed me how much <strong class=\"key-phrase\">consistent practice</strong> a musician needs.\n\nQ: Do you think children should learn to play a musical instrument at school?\nA: Yes, at least at an introductory level. Music develops listening, coordination and discipline, while also giving children <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a creative form of expression</strong>.\n\nQ: How easy would it be to learn to play an instrument without a teacher?\nA: It is possible with videos and apps, but a teacher can correct technique before bad habits become fixed. Self-study works best when learners already have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a clear practice plan</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Music","phrases":[{"en":"overwhelming the melody","vi":"lấn át giai điệu"},{"en":"consistent practice","vi":"sự luyện tập đều đặn"},{"en":"a creative form of expression","vi":"một hình thức biểu đạt sáng tạo"},{"en":"a clear practice plan","vi":"một kế hoạch luyện tập rõ ràng"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Music","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-053","_displayNo":"#053","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Names","prompt":"How did your parents choose your name?\nDoes your name have any special meaning?\nIs your name common or unusual in your country?\nIf you could change your name, would you?","answer":"Q: How did your parents choose your name?\nA: To be honest, I'm not sure how they chose it; I've never asked them. I suppose it was just a name that they both liked, and maybe they thought it suited me.\n\nQ: Does your name have any special meaning?\nA: It might do, but I don't know what that meaning is; I've never <strong class=\"key-phrase\">looked it up</strong>. Maybe I'll google it later today; you've made me curious to find out!\n\nQ: Is your name common or unusual in your country?\nA: Yes, it's quite a common name. I remember that there were two other people with the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">same name as me</strong> in my class at school.\n\nQ: If you could change your name, would you?\nA: No, I definitely wouldn't. My name is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">part of my identity</strong> now, and it would feel strange to suddenly change it. I don't think my friends and family would like that either.","author":"Simon","topic":"Names","phrases":[{"en":"looked it up","vi":"tra cứu điều đó"},{"en":"same name as me","vi":"cùng tên với tôi"},{"en":"part of my identity","vi":"một phần bản sắc của tôi"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Names","id":"speaking-part-1-054","_displayNo":"#054","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Neighbours","prompt":"How well do you know the people who live next door to you?\nHow often do you see them?\nWhat kinds of problem do people sometimes have with their neighbours?\nHow do you think neighbours can help each other?","answer":"Q: How well do you know the people who live next door to you?\nA: I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">know my neighbours quite well</strong>. They're really nice people, and I always stop to talk whenever I see them.\n\nQ: How often do you see them?\nA: I see my neighbours at least <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a few times a week</strong>. We usually see each other when we're leaving for work in the morning or coming home in the evening.\n\nQ: What kinds of problem do people sometimes have with their neighbours?\nA: I think the most common problem is probably noise. It's difficult to live next to people who have a dog that barks at night, or who <strong class=\"key-phrase\">play loud music</strong>.\n\nQ: How do you think neighbours can help each other?\nA: Neighbours can do little things like watching your house if you go on holiday or taking a delivery if something arrives by post when you're not at home. I think these little favours are a good way for neighbours to help each other.","author":"Simon","topic":"Neighbours","phrases":[{"en":"know my neighbours quite well","vi":"biết khá rõ những người hàng xóm của tôi"},{"en":"a few times a week","vi":"vài lần mỗi tuần"},{"en":"play loud music","vi":"mở nhạc lớn"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Neighbours","id":"speaking-part-1-055","_displayNo":"#055","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"News","prompt":"Where do you normally get news from?\nHow does news reporting in your country differ from reporting abroad?\nTell me about an interesting news item you have read or heard recently.\nAre you interested in the news, and what kind of news do you follow?","answer":"Q: Where do you normally get news from?\nA: I mainly use reputable news websites and a small number of specialist newsletters. I compare more than one source when an issue is important because headlines alone rarely provide <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the full context</strong>.\n\nQ: How does news reporting in your country differ from reporting abroad?\nA: Domestic outlets naturally devote more space to local policy and social issues, while foreign media may interpret the same event through another political or cultural lens. Comparing them helps me <strong class=\"key-phrase\">identify possible bias</strong>.\n\nQ: Tell me about an interesting news item you have read or heard recently.\nA: I recently read about a medical technology that allows doctors to detect disease earlier. The story interested me because it showed how research can have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a direct practical benefit</strong>.\n\nQ: Are you interested in the news, and what kind of news do you follow?\nA: Yes, particularly news about science, education and major international events. I avoid following every update because constant exposure can create noise rather than <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reliable understanding</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"News","phrases":[{"en":"the full context","vi":"toàn bộ bối cảnh"},{"en":"identify possible bias","vi":"nhận diện thiên kiến có thể có"},{"en":"a direct practical benefit","vi":"một lợi ích thực tế trực tiếp"},{"en":"reliable understanding","vi":"sự hiểu biết đáng tin cậy"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"News","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-056","_displayNo":"#056","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Numbers","prompt":"Do you have a favourite number or a number that is special to you?\nDo any numbers have special importance in your country?\nAre you good at remembering numbers?\nWhat numbers do people often have to memorise?","answer":"Q: Do you have a favourite number or a number that is special to you?\nA: My favourite number is seven because it is the date of my birthday and it appears in many familiar cultural patterns. I would not call it genuinely lucky, but I have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a long-standing attachment</strong> to it.\n\nQ: Do any numbers have special importance in your country?\nA: Yes. The number 7, for example, is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">supposed to be a special number</strong> in my country. It appears in so many places, like the seven days of the week, the seven main notes in music, and the seven ages of man that Shakespeare described.\n\nQ: Are you good at remembering numbers?\nA: No, I'm not very good at remembering numbers. I don't think it's necessary to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">learn them by heart</strong>; I just save them on my phone.\n\nQ: What numbers do people often have to memorise?\nA: The most important number to remember on a daily basis is the pin number for your bank card. Without this you can't pay for anything or get cash out.","author":"Simon / ChatGPT","topic":"Numbers","phrases":[{"en":"a long-standing attachment","vi":"một sự gắn bó lâu dài"},{"en":"supposed to be a special number","vi":"được cho là một con số đặc biệt"},{"en":"learn them by heart","vi":"học thuộc lòng"}],"source":"IELTS Simon sample adapted by ChatGPT to replace an unfinished placeholder","subtype":"","summary":"Numbers","id":"speaking-part-1-057","_displayNo":"#057","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Parks","prompt":"Do you like parks?\nHow often do you visit parks?\nWhy are parks an important part of many towns and cities?\nWhat do you think could be done to make parks better?","answer":"Q: Do you like parks?\nA: Yes, I like parks because they're great places to relax or go for a walk. I think every city needs some green space where people can escape from the crowds.\n\nQ: How often do you visit parks?\nA: There's a park very close to where I live, so I probably go there <strong class=\"key-phrase\">once or twice a week</strong> if the weather's nice.\n\nQ: Why are parks an important part of many towns and cities?\nA: Parks are like an oasis where people get away from <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the hustle and bustle</strong> of city life. They are where people go to have lunch, to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take some exercise</strong>, or to forget about work for a while.\n\nQ: What do you think could be done to make parks better?\nA: Even well-designed parks have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">room for improvement</strong>. Cities could add safer paths, accessible toilets, shaded seating and better maintenance, while protecting quiet areas from excessive commercial activity.","author":"Simon","topic":"Parks","phrases":[{"en":"once or twice a week","vi":"một hoặc hai lần mỗi tuần"},{"en":"the hustle and bustle","vi":"sự hối hả và nhộn nhịp"},{"en":"take some exercise","vi":"tập thể dục"},{"en":"room for improvement","vi":"vẫn còn khả năng cải thiện"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Parks","id":"speaking-part-1-058","_displayNo":"#058","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Patience & Politeness","prompt":"Are you a patient person?\nIs it important to be polite?\nWhat do you do when others are rude?","answer":"Q: Are you a patient person?\nA: I am fairly patient when a situation is outside someone’s control, but less so when the same avoidable mistake is repeated. I try to pause before reacting so that frustration does not <strong class=\"key-phrase\">control my response</strong>.\n\nQ: Is it important to be polite?\nA: Yes, because politeness reduces unnecessary conflict and signals respect. It does not mean agreeing with everyone; it means expressing disagreement without <strong class=\"key-phrase\">attacking the person</strong>.\n\nQ: What do you do when others are rude?\nA: I stay calm, set a clear boundary and avoid matching their tone. If the behaviour continues, I end the conversation rather than allowing it to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">escalate further</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Patience & Politeness","phrases":[{"en":"control my response","vi":"chi phối phản ứng của tôi"},{"en":"attacking the person","vi":"công kích cá nhân"},{"en":"escalate further","vi":"leo thang hơn nữa"}],"source":"Topic reference: IELTS Advantage (2026); questions adapted; answers rewritten and quality-audited by ChatGPT","subtype":"","summary":"Patience & Politeness","id":"speaking-part-1-059","_displayNo":"#059","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Photography","prompt":"What type of photos do you like taking?\nWhat do you do with photos you take?\nWhen you visit other places, do you take photos or buy postcards?\nDo you like people taking photos of you?","answer":"Q: What type of photos do you like taking?\nA: I rarely take photographs because I prefer to stay present in the moment. I make an exception for family occasions or unusual places that I genuinely want to remember.\n\nQ: What do you do with photos you take?\nA: Most photos remain on my phone or in cloud storage. I occasionally create an album after a trip, but I admit that I do not <strong class=\"key-phrase\">organise them systematically</strong>.\n\nQ: When you visit other places, do you take photos or buy postcards?\nA: I don't really do either. I leave it to my friends or other family members to take photographs; I'm usually with someone who likes taking photos and can share them with me later.\n\nQ: Do you like people taking photos of you?\nA: No, I prefer not to be in photos. I always feel awkward when someone asks me to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">smile for the camera</strong>, and I don't think I'm very photogenic.","author":"Simon","topic":"Photography","phrases":[{"en":"organise them systematically","vi":"sắp xếp chúng một cách có hệ thống"},{"en":"smile for the camera","vi":"cười trước ống kính"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Photography","id":"speaking-part-1-060","_displayNo":"#060","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Photography","prompt":"Is photography becoming more popular these days, in your experience?\nDo you agree with the saying “The camera never lies”?\nWould you say photography is an art?","answer":"Q: Is photography becoming more popular these days, in your experience?\nA: Yes, smartphones have made photography available to almost everyone. People now document ordinary moments as well as special events, although the huge volume of images can make individual photographs <strong class=\"key-phrase\">feel less significant</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you agree with the saying “The camera never lies”?\nA: No. A photograph records something real, but framing, timing, editing and captions can completely change the message. Images are powerful evidence, yet they are still <strong class=\"key-phrase\">open to interpretation</strong>.\n\nQ: Would you say photography is an art?\nA: Yes, when the photographer uses light, composition and timing to communicate an idea or emotion. Technical accuracy alone is not enough; artistic photography involves <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a deliberate point of view</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Photography","phrases":[{"en":"feel less significant","vi":"có vẻ kém ý nghĩa hơn"},{"en":"open to interpretation","vi":"có thể được diễn giải theo nhiều cách"},{"en":"a deliberate point of view","vi":"một góc nhìn có chủ đích"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Photography","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-061","_displayNo":"#061","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Rain","prompt":"Do you like rain?\nDo you think that rain affects people's mood?\nDoes it often rain where you live?\nHave you ever been caught in the rain without a coat or umbrella?","answer":"Q: Do you like rain?\nA: No, not at all. It rains far too often in Manchester, where I live, and I'm <strong class=\"key-phrase\">fed up of it</strong>; I wish we had more sun!\n\nQ: Do you think that rain affects people's mood?\nA: Yes, definitely. I think <strong class=\"key-phrase\">rainy days and grey skies</strong> can be a bit sad and depressing. Where I live, people are much more cheerful when the sun comes out.\n\nQ: Does it often rain where you live?\nA: Yes, unfortunately it does. As I said, Manchester is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">known for being a rainy place</strong>; you can't trust the weather here, because it can cloud over and start raining at any moment.\n\nQ: Have you ever been caught in the rain without a coat or umbrella?\nA: Yes, many times. Just last week I went out without an umbrella and got soaked; I did have a coat on, but it didn't really help.","author":"Simon","topic":"Rain","phrases":[{"en":"fed up of it","vi":"chán ngấy điều đó"},{"en":"rainy days and grey skies","vi":"những ngày mưa và bầu trời xám xịt"},{"en":"known for being a rainy place","vi":"nổi tiếng là một nơi nhiều mưa"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Rain","id":"speaking-part-1-062","_displayNo":"#062","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Reading","prompt":"Do you like reading?\nDo you usually read for leisure or for work purposes?\nWhat was your favourite book or story when you were a child?\nDo you think it's important that children read regularly?","answer":"Q: Do you like reading?\nA: Yes, I like reading a lot. I read <strong class=\"key-phrase\">all sorts of things</strong>, including novels, newspapers, magazines, and online articles.\n\nQ: Do you usually read for leisure or for work purposes?\nA: Well, I have to do a certain amount of reading as part of my job, but I probably read more for enjoyment. I pick up a newspaper most days, and I usually <strong class=\"key-phrase\">have a book on the go</strong>.\n\nQ: What was your favourite book or story when you were a child?\nA: The first book I remember loving was Harry Potter and the Philosopher’s Stone. The magical setting immediately <strong class=\"key-phrase\">captured my imagination</strong>, and I read it so quickly that I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">could hardly put it down</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think it's important that children read regularly?\nA: Definitely. I think reading is possibly the most important skill that children learn. The ability to read <strong class=\"key-phrase\">opens the door to</strong> all aspects of education.","author":"Simon / ChatGPT","topic":"Reading","phrases":[{"en":"all sorts of things","vi":"đủ loại nội dung"},{"en":"have a book on the go","vi":"đang đọc dở một cuốn sách"},{"en":"captured my imagination","vi":"khơi dậy mạnh mẽ trí tưởng tượng của tôi"},{"en":"could hardly put it down","vi":"gần như không thể ngừng đọc"},{"en":"opens the door to","vi":"mở ra cơ hội tiếp cận"}],"source":"IELTS Simon sample adapted by ChatGPT to replace an unfinished placeholder","subtype":"","summary":"Reading","id":"speaking-part-1-063","_displayNo":"#063","qaBands":["8.5","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Robots","prompt":"What do you think of robots?\nDid you watch any cartoons related to robots in your childhood?\nDo you like the idea of robots helping you at home or driving your car?","answer":"Q: What do you think of robots?\nA: I think robots are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a clever idea</strong>. I'd love to have a robot that could speak to me and do things for me!\n\nQ: Did you watch any cartoons related to robots in your childhood?\nA: I can't remember <strong class=\"key-phrase\">watching cartoons with robots</strong>, but I remember that I liked the robots in films like Star Wars.\n\nQ: Do you like the idea of robots helping you at home or driving your car?\nA: Yes, definitely. It would be great to have a robot helper at home, and I like the idea of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">driverless cars</strong> - I think driving would be safer if cars were controlled by robots.","author":"Simon","topic":"Robots","phrases":[{"en":"a clever idea","vi":"một ý tưởng thông minh"},{"en":"watching cartoons with robots","vi":"xem phim hoạt hình có rô-bốt"},{"en":"driverless cars","vi":"xe tự lái"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Robots","id":"speaking-part-1-064","_displayNo":"#064","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Sea","prompt":"Do you live near the sea?\nHow do you feel when you are near the sea?\nWhat do you like and dislike about the sea?\nWould you like to live on an island and why?","answer":"Q: Do you live near the sea?\nA: I do not live directly beside the sea, so visiting the coast still feels special. It requires some travel, but that distance makes each trip <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a refreshing change</strong>.\n\nQ: How do you feel when you are near the sea?\nA: I usually feel calmer near the sea because the open horizon and repetitive sound of waves reduce mental clutter. It is one of the few places where I can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">switch off completely</strong>.\n\nQ: What do you like and dislike about the sea?\nA: I like the fresh air and wide views, but I dislike crowded beaches and plastic waste. The coast is most enjoyable when tourism is managed without <strong class=\"key-phrase\">damaging the environment</strong>.\n\nQ: Would you like to live on an island and why?\nA: I would enjoy living on an island for a short period, but probably not permanently. Isolation can be peaceful, yet limited healthcare, transport and job options would make daily life <strong class=\"key-phrase\">less convenient</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Sea","phrases":[{"en":"a refreshing change","vi":"một sự thay đổi mới mẻ"},{"en":"switch off completely","vi":"hoàn toàn thư giãn đầu óc"},{"en":"damaging the environment","vi":"gây tổn hại môi trường"},{"en":"less convenient","vi":"kém thuận tiện hơn"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Sea","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-065","_displayNo":"#065","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Shoes","prompt":"Do you like to buy expensive shoes?\nWhen you buy shoes, do you prefer convenience or style?\nWhy do you think some people buy many pairs of shoes?\nHave you ever bought shoes online?","answer":"Q: Do you like to buy expensive shoes?\nA: No. I tend to buy <strong class=\"key-phrase\">average-priced shoes</strong> because I'm more interested in comfort than expensive brands.\n\nQ: When you buy shoes, do you prefer convenience or style?\nA: I mainly look for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">comfort and convenience</strong>. But obviously I consider the style too, because I do choose shoes that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">match the clothes I wear</strong>.\n\nQ: Why do you think some people buy many pairs of shoes?\nA: I suppose they either like <strong class=\"key-phrase\">following the latest fashions</strong>, or they want a pair of shoes to match all of the different clothes or outfits that they have.\n\nQ: Have you ever bought shoes online?\nA: No, I haven't. I always like to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">try shoes on</strong> before I buy them, to make sure that they fit properly and feel comfortable.","author":"Simon","topic":"Shoes","phrases":[{"en":"average-priced shoes","vi":"giày ở mức giá trung bình"},{"en":"comfort and convenience","vi":"sự thoải mái và tiện lợi"},{"en":"match the clothes I wear","vi":"phù hợp với quần áo tôi mặc"},{"en":"following the latest fashions","vi":"chạy theo các xu hướng thời trang mới nhất"},{"en":"try shoes on","vi":"thử giày"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Shoes","id":"speaking-part-1-066","_displayNo":"#066","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Shopping","prompt":"Who does most of the shopping in your household?\nWhat kind of shopping do you like doing?\nIs shopping a popular activity in your country?\nWhat types of shops do teenagers like best in your country?","answer":"Q: Who does most of the shopping in your household?\nA: There isn't one person who does most of the shopping. I'd say it's <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a shared responsibility</strong> because we tend to go shopping together as a family.\n\nQ: What kind of shopping do you like doing?\nA: I quite like <strong class=\"key-phrase\">shopping for presents</strong> for people's birthdays or for Christmas. My favourite type of shop would have to be a bookshop.\n\nQ: Is shopping a popular activity in your country?\nA: Yes, it's very popular. Saturday is the busiest shopping day, and lots of people treat shopping as a kind of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">leisure activity</strong>, rather than something practical.\n\nQ: What types of shops do teenagers like best in your country?\nA: I'm <strong class=\"key-phrase\">not an expert on</strong> teenage behaviour, but I guess they like buying clothes, music, gadgets... that kind of thing.","author":"Simon","topic":"Shopping","phrases":[{"en":"a shared responsibility","vi":"trách nhiệm chung"},{"en":"shopping for presents","vi":"mua quà tặng"},{"en":"leisure activity","vi":"hoạt động giải trí"},{"en":"not an expert on","vi":"không phải chuyên gia về"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Shopping","id":"speaking-part-1-067","_displayNo":"#067","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Shopping","prompt":"Are you loyal to any brands?\nDo you want other people to know you buy a particular brand?\nDo you buy any products without considering the brand name?\nHow do you feel about going shopping?","answer":"Q: Are you loyal to any brands?\nA: I am loyal to a brand only when it has proved <strong class=\"key-phrase\">consistently reliable</strong>. I normally compare quality, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">after-sales service</strong> and price first, because I value practical performance over brand prestige.\n\nQ: Do you want other people to know you buy a particular brand?\nA: Not really. I prefer products that work well, and I do not see brand names as a way to signal status. That kind of consumption can easily become <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more about image than value</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you buy any products without considering the brand name?\nA: Yes, especially basic food, stationery and household goods. For simple items I compare ingredients, durability or price rather than <strong class=\"key-phrase\">relying on brand recognition</strong>.\n\nQ: How do you feel about going shopping?\nA: I see shopping as a practical task rather than entertainment. I enjoy it when I know what I need, but crowded stores and too many choices can make it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">needlessly time-consuming</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Shopping","phrases":[{"en":"consistently reliable","vi":"luôn ổn định và đáng tin cậy"},{"en":"after-sales service","vi":"dịch vụ hậu mãi"},{"en":"more about image than value","vi":"thiên về hình ảnh hơn giá trị"},{"en":"relying on brand recognition","vi":"dựa vào độ nhận diện thương hiệu"},{"en":"needlessly time-consuming","vi":"tốn thời gian không cần thiết"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Shopping","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-068","_displayNo":"#068","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Shopping","prompt":"Do you like shopping and why?\nDo you like shopping on the internet?\nWhat don't you like about shopping?\nWhat time do you do the shopping and why?","answer":"Q: Do you like shopping and why?\nA: I do not regard shopping as a hobby, but I enjoy it when I have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a clear purpose</strong> and enough time to compare products. I find <strong class=\"key-phrase\">aimless shopping</strong> tiring rather than relaxing.\n\nQ: Do you like shopping on the internet?\nA: Yes, for standard products that are easy to compare. It saves time and broadens my choice, although I still use physical shops for clothing or anything that requires <strong class=\"key-phrase\">careful inspection</strong>.\n\nQ: What don't you like about shopping?\nA: I dislike misleading discounts, pressure from sales staff and long queues. A good shopping environment should let customers compare options and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make an informed decision</strong>.\n\nQ: What time do you do the shopping and why?\nA: I usually shop early in the morning or on weekday evenings, when stores are quieter. Avoiding peak hours makes the process <strong class=\"key-phrase\">far more efficient</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Shopping","phrases":[{"en":"a clear purpose","vi":"một mục đích rõ ràng"},{"en":"aimless shopping","vi":"việc mua sắm không có mục đích"},{"en":"careful inspection","vi":"kiểm tra kỹ lưỡng"},{"en":"make an informed decision","vi":"đưa ra quyết định có đủ thông tin"},{"en":"far more efficient","vi":"hiệu quả hơn nhiều"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Shopping","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-069","_displayNo":"#069","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Sports","prompt":"What sports or physical activities do you regularly do?\nWhich sport or game would you like to be good at?\nDo you prefer watching or playing sports?\nDo you think children should be encouraged to do more sport?","answer":"Q: What sports or physical activities do you regularly do?\nA: Unfortunately I don't have time to do any sports or physical activities because of my work commitments. I'd like to find more time for regular exercise.\n\nQ: Which sport or game would you like to be good at?\nA: I would like to be good at tennis because it combines stamina, timing and precise control. Being able to place the ball accurately <strong class=\"key-phrase\">under pressure</strong> would be extremely satisfying.\n\nQ: Do you prefer watching or playing sports?\nA: I don't watch much sport on TV and I'm <strong class=\"key-phrase\">not a big sports fan</strong>, so I think I would probably enjoy doing sports more than watching them.\n\nQ: Do you think children should be encouraged to do more sport?\nA: Yes. Sport helps children develop <strong class=\"key-phrase\">teamwork and resilience</strong>, and it gives them a constructive way to use their energy. The emphasis should be on participation and improvement rather than winning at all costs.","author":"Simon","topic":"Sports","phrases":[{"en":"under pressure","vi":"trong tình huống chịu áp lực"},{"en":"not a big sports fan","vi":"không phải người hâm mộ thể thao cuồng nhiệt"},{"en":"teamwork and resilience","vi":"khả năng làm việc nhóm và sự bền bỉ"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Sports","id":"speaking-part-1-070","_displayNo":"#070","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Sports","prompt":"Do you like sports?\nDo you enjoy watching sports?\nDo you enjoy participating in any sports?\nWhat is your favourite sports activity?","answer":"Q: Do you like sports?\nA: Yes. I enjoy strength training, swimming and occasionally badminton. I prefer activities where progress can be measured and technique improves through <strong class=\"key-phrase\">consistent practice</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you enjoy watching sports?\nA: I watch major events occasionally, but I would rather participate than sit through an entire season. Watching is most enjoyable when I understand the strategy and have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a reason to care about the result</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you enjoy participating in any sports?\nA: Yes, particularly in individual exercise and casual games with friends. Participation improves my mood and gives me <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a clear physical challenge</strong>.\n\nQ: What is your favourite sports activity?\nA: Strength training is my favourite because it supports health, posture and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">long-term mobility</strong>. I also like the fact that progress is gradual and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">easy to track</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Sports","phrases":[{"en":"consistent practice","vi":"sự luyện tập đều đặn"},{"en":"a reason to care about the result","vi":"lý do để quan tâm đến kết quả"},{"en":"a clear physical challenge","vi":"một thử thách thể chất rõ ràng"},{"en":"long-term mobility","vi":"khả năng vận động lâu dài"},{"en":"easy to track","vi":"dễ theo dõi"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Sports","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-071","_displayNo":"#071","qaBands":["8.0","8.5","8.0","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Sports","prompt":"What sports do you like?\nWhat sports are played in your country?\nWhat are the sporting facilities like in your hometown?\nWhat is your favourite sport?","answer":"Q: What sports do you like?\nA: I like badminton and swimming because both are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">accessible and technically demanding</strong>. I also do strength training, although I see that more as structured exercise than a competitive sport.\n\nQ: What sports are played in your country?\nA: Football, badminton, volleyball and running are all common. Football attracts the largest audiences, while badminton is easy to play in schools, parks and community spaces, making it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">accessible to many people</strong>.\n\nQ: What are the sporting facilities like in your hometown?\nA: Facilities have improved, with more private gyms and sports centres than before. Public spaces are still unevenly distributed, so affordable access remains <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a practical concern</strong>.\n\nQ: What is your favourite sport?\nA: Badminton is probably my favourite sport because it is fast, social and easy to play without expensive equipment. It also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">rewards timing and technique</strong> rather than physical size alone.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Sports","phrases":[{"en":"accessible and technically demanding","vi":"dễ tiếp cận nhưng đòi hỏi kỹ thuật"},{"en":"accessible to many people","vi":"dễ tiếp cận với nhiều người"},{"en":"a practical concern","vi":"một vấn đề thực tế"},{"en":"rewards timing and technique","vi":"đòi hỏi và tưởng thưởng cho khả năng căn thời điểm cùng kỹ thuật"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Sports","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-072","_displayNo":"#072","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Study & Education","prompt":"Do you like studying?\nDo you prefer to study alone or with others?\nWhere do you prefer to go when you need to study?\nHow do you feel if someone disturbs you when you are studying?","answer":"Q: Do you like studying?\nA: Yes, I like studying because it's the best way to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">gain a deeper insight into</strong> any subject. I like reading, learning from others, and trying to understand difficult concepts.\n\nQ: Do you prefer to study alone or with others?\nA: I prefer to study alone because I need to be able to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">concentrate fully</strong>. Other people are a distraction.\n\nQ: Where do you prefer to go when you need to study?\nA: I like to find a quiet corner in my local library; being in an old building and surrounded by books seems to help me to focus on my work.\n\nQ: How do you feel if someone disturbs you when you are studying?\nA: It frustrates me because it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">breaks my concentration</strong>. I prefer to avoid distractions by going somewhere where nobody will interrupt me.","author":"Simon","topic":"Study & Education","phrases":[{"en":"gain a deeper insight into","vi":"hiểu sâu hơn về"},{"en":"concentrate fully","vi":"tập trung hoàn toàn"},{"en":"breaks my concentration","vi":"làm gián đoạn sự tập trung của tôi"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Study & Education","id":"speaking-part-1-073","_displayNo":"#073","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Study & Education","prompt":"Do you enjoy your time at school?\nWould you recommend your school to others?\nWhat subject did you find most interesting when you were at school?\nApart from classes, what else did you enjoy at school?","answer":"Q: Do you enjoy your time at school?\nA: Overall, yes. School gave me close friendships and a strong academic foundation, although the exam pressure was sometimes intense. Looking back, it was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a valuable learning experience</strong>.\n\nQ: Would you recommend your school to others?\nA: I would, mainly because the teachers were committed and the environment was disciplined without being hostile. No school is perfect, but it offered <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a supportive environment</strong>.\n\nQ: What subject did you find most interesting when you were at school?\nA: English was the most interesting subject for me because it opened access to books, films and people from other countries. It felt like a practical skill with <strong class=\"key-phrase\">long-term value</strong>.\n\nQ: Apart from classes, what else did you enjoy at school?\nA: I enjoyed clubs, school trips and informal time with classmates. Those activities developed confidence and teamwork in ways that ordinary lessons could not <strong class=\"key-phrase\">fully replicate</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Study & Education","phrases":[{"en":"a valuable learning experience","vi":"một trải nghiệm học hỏi có giá trị"},{"en":"a supportive environment","vi":"một môi trường hỗ trợ"},{"en":"long-term value","vi":"giá trị lâu dài"},{"en":"fully replicate","vi":"tái hiện đầy đủ"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Study & Education","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-074","_displayNo":"#074","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Study & Education","prompt":"What have you studied?\nWhat was your major?\nWhat kind of school did you attend?\nWhat was your favourite subject?","answer":"Q: What have you studied?\nA: I studied English language and teaching. The course combined linguistics, classroom methods and practical training, so it gave me both theory and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">practical experience</strong>.\n\nQ: What was your major?\nA: My major was English education. I chose it because I was interested in language and wanted a career where communication would <strong class=\"key-phrase\">play a central role</strong>.\n\nQ: What kind of school did you attend?\nA: I attended a state school with a fairly traditional structure. Classes were teacher-led, but good teachers still encouraged questions and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">critical thinking</strong>.\n\nQ: What was your favourite subject?\nA: English was my favourite subject because progress was practical and visible. Each new skill gave me access to more books, conversations and professional opportunities <strong class=\"key-phrase\">well beyond the classroom</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Study & Education","phrases":[{"en":"practical experience","vi":"kinh nghiệm thực tế"},{"en":"play a central role","vi":"đóng vai trò trung tâm"},{"en":"critical thinking","vi":"tư duy phản biện"},{"en":"well beyond the classroom","vi":"vượt xa phạm vi lớp học"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Study & Education","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-075","_displayNo":"#075","qaBands":["8.0","8.5","8.0","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Telephoning","prompt":"How often do you make telephone calls?\nWho do you spend most time talking to on the telephone?\nWhen do you think you'll next make a telephone call?\nDo you sometimes prefer to send a text message instead of telephoning?","answer":"Q: How often do you make telephone calls?\nA: I probably make three or four phone calls every day, usually just to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make arrangements with</strong> work colleagues or to speak to family and friends.\n\nQ: Who do you spend most time talking to on the telephone?\nA: I think it would be one of my closest work colleagues. We often call each other rather than meeting <strong class=\"key-phrase\">face-to-face</strong>.\n\nQ: When do you think you'll next make a telephone call?\nA: My family are expecting me to phone them as soon as I finish this exam. They'll want to know <strong class=\"key-phrase\">how it went</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you sometimes prefer to send a text message instead of telephoning?\nA: Yes. For a simple arrangement, a text message is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more efficient than a phone call</strong> because both people can read and answer it when convenient. I still call when the issue is urgent or needs discussion.","author":"Simon","topic":"Telephoning","phrases":[{"en":"make arrangements with","vi":"thu xếp công việc với"},{"en":"face-to-face","vi":"trực tiếp, mặt đối mặt"},{"en":"how it went","vi":"mọi việc diễn ra thế nào"},{"en":"more efficient than a phone call","vi":"hiệu quả hơn một cuộc gọi điện thoại"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Telephoning","id":"speaking-part-1-076","_displayNo":"#076","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Television","prompt":"Do you watch a lot of TV?\nTell me about television in your country?\nWhat is your favourite TV program?\nIs TV more important to you now than in the past?","answer":"Q: Do you watch a lot of TV?\nA: No, not much. I usually watch selected programmes online rather than following a television schedule, because that lets me choose content and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">avoid passive viewing</strong>.\n\nQ: Tell me about television in your country?\nA: Television still reaches a broad audience for news, sport and major entertainment programmes. Younger viewers increasingly stream content, so broadcasters are adapting to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">changing viewing habits</strong>.\n\nQ: What is your favourite TV program?\nA: I enjoy well-produced documentaries about science and society. They combine strong visuals with reliable explanation and often <strong class=\"key-phrase\">put complex issues into perspective</strong>.\n\nQ: Is TV more important to you now than in the past?\nA: It is less important to me now because I can access information and entertainment on demand. Television has become one option among many rather than <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the centre of home entertainment</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Television","phrases":[{"en":"avoid passive viewing","vi":"tránh xem thụ động"},{"en":"changing viewing habits","vi":"thói quen xem đang thay đổi"},{"en":"put complex issues into perspective","vi":"giúp nhìn nhận vấn đề phức tạp đúng mức"},{"en":"the centre of home entertainment","vi":"trung tâm giải trí gia đình"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Television","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-077","_displayNo":"#077","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.0","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Toys","prompt":"Did you play with toys when you were a child?\nWhat kinds of toys did you like?\nIn your country, do boys and girls play with the same types of toys?\nDo you think that toys help children to learn?","answer":"Q: Did you play with toys when you were a child?\nA: Yes, of course. I loved <strong class=\"key-phrase\">playing with toys</strong> when I was a child; I think all children do.\n\nQ: What kinds of toys did you like?\nA: <strong class=\"key-phrase\">As far as I remember</strong>, I mostly played with toy cars, planes and action figures from films or cartoons. I also liked building things with Lego.\n\nQ: In your country, do boys and girls play with the same types of toys?\nA: Not really. I think boys like the kinds of toys that I mentioned before, whereas girls play with dolls. My niece, for example, doesn't like toy cars; she prefers dressing dolls in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">different outfits</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think that toys help children to learn?\nA: Yes, I do. All toys encourage children to use their <strong class=\"key-phrase\">imagination and creativity</strong>. Even with simple toys, children imagine situations and invent games and rules.","author":"Simon","topic":"Toys","phrases":[{"en":"playing with toys","vi":"chơi với đồ chơi"},{"en":"As far as I remember","vi":"theo như tôi nhớ"},{"en":"different outfits","vi":"nhiều bộ trang phục khác nhau"},{"en":"imagination and creativity","vi":"trí tưởng tượng và sự sáng tạo"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Toys","id":"speaking-part-1-078","_displayNo":"#078","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Transport","prompt":"Do you use public transport?\nWhich type of public transport do you prefer?\nHow good is the public transport where you live?\nDo you think people should use public transport more?","answer":"Q: Do you use public transport?\nA: These days I mostly drive, and the main reason is that my usual journeys are much faster by car. For example, the half-hour drive that I do twice a week would take me three times as long by train and bus.\n\nQ: Which type of public transport do you prefer?\nA: I definitely prefer the train. I like being able to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">stroll up and down</strong>, and on some trains I can book a seat with a table and a socket, so that I can do some work.\n\nQ: How good is the public transport where you live?\nA: It's quite good. There's a train station not far from my house, and it's <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a direct line</strong> straight into the city centre. There are lots of bus routes too, and there's even a tram network in the centre of Manchester.\n\nQ: Do you think people should use public transport more?\nA: Yes, as long as it's convenient for them. Public transport is obviously more <strong class=\"key-phrase\">environmentally friendly</strong> than private cars, so we could reduce air pollution by using it more.","author":"Simon","topic":"Transport","phrases":[{"en":"stroll up and down","vi":"đi lại thong thả"},{"en":"a direct line","vi":"một tuyến đi thẳng"},{"en":"environmentally friendly","vi":"thân thiện với môi trường"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Transport","id":"speaking-part-1-079","_displayNo":"#079","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Transport","prompt":"Can you describe the transport system in your hometown?\nWhat is the most common means of transport in your country?\nDo traffic jams often occur in your city?\nHow can we solve this problem?","answer":"Q: Can you describe the transport system in your hometown?\nA: Hanoi relies heavily on motorbikes, buses, cars and an expanding metro system. The network is improving, but transfers between different modes still need to become <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more seamless</strong>.\n\nQ: What is the most common means of transport in your country?\nA: Motorbikes are still the most common personal vehicle because they are flexible in dense streets. Buses and the metro are increasingly important for people who want to avoid <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the cost of driving</strong>.\n\nQ: Do traffic jams often occur in your city?\nA: Yes, especially during morning and evening peaks. Rapid urban growth and high private-vehicle use have placed <strong class=\"key-phrase\">considerable pressure</strong> on roads designed for fewer users.\n\nQ: How can we solve this problem?\nA: The city needs frequent public transport, safe walking routes and better traffic management. Restrictions on private vehicles will work only when people have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a reliable alternative</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Transport","phrases":[{"en":"more seamless","vi":"liền mạch hơn"},{"en":"the cost of driving","vi":"chi phí lái xe"},{"en":"considerable pressure","vi":"áp lực đáng kể"},{"en":"a reliable alternative","vi":"một phương án thay thế đáng tin cậy"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Transport","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-080","_displayNo":"#080","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Travel & Holidays","prompt":"Do you like holidays?\nDo you prefer to travel or stay at home during holiday periods?\nWhat do most people do during their holidays in your country?\nWhen do you prefer to take your holidays?","answer":"Q: Do you like holidays?\nA: Yes, I love holidays because I get the chance to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take a break</strong> from work, to relax and unwind, and to spend time with my family.\n\nQ: Do you prefer to travel or stay at home during holiday periods?\nA: If I can I prefer to travel. It's nice to get away from everything and to have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a change of scenery</strong>. Also, I like visiting new places and doing some sightseeing.\n\nQ: What do most people do during their holidays in your country?\nA: During the summer especially, I think most British people go somewhere hot and sunny, to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">escape from the British weather</strong>!\n\nQ: When do you prefer to take your holidays?\nA: I like taking my holidays just <strong class=\"key-phrase\">outside the main summer season</strong>, which is July and August. If you go on holiday in May, June or September, everything is cheaper and places aren't so crowded with tourists.","author":"Simon","topic":"Travel & Holidays","phrases":[{"en":"take a break","vi":"nghỉ ngơi"},{"en":"a change of scenery","vi":"sự thay đổi không gian và khung cảnh"},{"en":"escape from the British weather","vi":"tránh thời tiết thất thường của Anh"},{"en":"outside the main summer season","vi":"ngoài mùa du lịch hè cao điểm"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Travel & Holidays","id":"speaking-part-1-081","_displayNo":"#081","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Travel & Holidays","prompt":"What form of transport do you prefer to use?\nHow much time do you spend travelling on a normal day?\nWhat do you do while you are travelling?\nDo you ever have problems with transport?","answer":"Q: What form of transport do you prefer to use?\nA: I prefer to travel by car because it means that I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">have my own space</strong>. Also, the buses and trains in my city are usually overcrowded; my car is much more comfortable.\n\nQ: How much time do you spend travelling on a normal day?\nA: I probably spend about an hour and a half travelling to and from work. I travel during the rush hours, so there is quite a lot of traffic.\n\nQ: What do you do while you are travelling?\nA: I usually listen to the radio or a CD. In the morning I like to listen to the news to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">find out what is happening</strong> in the world.\n\nQ: Do you ever have problems with transport?\nA: Yes, as I said, I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">get stuck in traffic</strong> on my way to and from work. I used to get annoyed by traffic jams, but now I'm used to them.","author":"Simon","topic":"Travel & Holidays","phrases":[{"en":"have my own space","vi":"có không gian riêng của mình"},{"en":"find out what is happening","vi":"tìm hiểu điều gì đang diễn ra"},{"en":"get stuck in traffic","vi":"bị mắc kẹt trong dòng xe"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Travel & Holidays","id":"speaking-part-1-082","_displayNo":"#082","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Travel & Holidays","prompt":"Do you like travelling? Why?\nDo you like to travel alone or with your friends?\nWhich other places have you travelled to?\nWhat do you usually do when you first arrive in a new place?","answer":"Q: Do you like travelling? Why?\nA: Yes, because travel interrupts routine and exposes me to different ways of living. Even a short trip can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">broaden my horizons</strong> if I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">pay attention to</strong> the place rather than simply taking photographs.\n\nQ: Do you like to travel alone or with your friends?\nA: I prefer travelling with one or two compatible people. Company makes the trip safer and more enjoyable, while a small group still leaves room for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">personal flexibility</strong>.\n\nQ: Which other places have you travelled to?\nA: I have travelled to several places in Vietnam, including Hue, Da Nang and Ho Chi Minh City. Each trip was different, but Hue was especially memorable because of its historic sites and slower <strong class=\"key-phrase\">pace of life</strong>.\n\nQ: What do you usually do when you first arrive in a new place?\nA: I usually check the neighbourhood on foot, learn the basic transport routes and identify a few practical places nearby. Doing that early helps me <strong class=\"key-phrase\">feel at ease</strong> for the rest of the trip.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Travel & Holidays","phrases":[{"en":"broaden my horizons","vi":"mở rộng tầm nhìn của tôi"},{"en":"pay attention to","vi":"chú ý đến"},{"en":"personal flexibility","vi":"sự linh hoạt cá nhân"},{"en":"pace of life","vi":"nhịp sống"},{"en":"feel at ease","vi":"cảm thấy thoải mái"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Travel & Holidays","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-083","_displayNo":"#083","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Travel & Holidays","prompt":"What are the benefits of visiting different countries?\nWhat are the negative effects of tourism?\nWhat do you need to do before you go abroad on holiday?\nWhat type of problems can people have on holiday?","answer":"Q: What are the benefits of visiting different countries?\nA: Visiting other countries can challenge assumptions, improve communication and provide <strong class=\"key-phrase\">first-hand knowledge</strong>. It is especially valuable when travellers <strong class=\"key-phrase\">engage with local life</strong> rather than staying in a tourist bubble.\n\nQ: What are the negative effects of tourism?\nA: Uncontrolled tourism can raise housing costs, overcrowd public spaces and damage natural sites. The problem is not tourism itself but growth that ignores <strong class=\"key-phrase\">local carrying capacity</strong>.\n\nQ: What do you need to do before you go abroad on holiday?\nA: I check entry rules, insurance, transport, accommodation and basic local customs. Careful preparation reduces avoidable stress while leaving enough freedom for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">spontaneous experiences</strong>.\n\nQ: What type of problems can people have on holiday?\nA: Common holiday problems include delayed transport, illness, lost documents and unexpected costs. Travel insurance, digital copies of documents and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a realistic backup plan</strong> make these problems much easier to manage.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Travel & Holidays","phrases":[{"en":"first-hand knowledge","vi":"kiến thức có được từ trải nghiệm trực tiếp"},{"en":"engage with local life","vi":"tiếp xúc với đời sống địa phương"},{"en":"local carrying capacity","vi":"khả năng tiếp nhận của địa phương"},{"en":"spontaneous experiences","vi":"những trải nghiệm ngẫu hứng"},{"en":"a realistic backup plan","vi":"một phương án dự phòng thực tế"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Travel & Holidays","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-084","_displayNo":"#084","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Trees","prompt":"Are there many trees in your hometown?\nWhat are the benefits of planting more trees?\nDo cities have enough trees?","answer":"Q: Are there many trees in your hometown?\nA: Some older parts of my hometown have mature trees, but rapidly developed districts often have fewer. The distribution is uneven, so access to shade and greenery depends greatly on <strong class=\"key-phrase\">where people live</strong>.\n\nQ: What are the benefits of planting more trees?\nA: Trees reduce heat, absorb some pollution, manage rainwater and make streets more pleasant. They also support urban wildlife and improve quality of life.\n\nQ: Do cities have enough trees?\nA: Many cities do not have enough healthy, well-maintained trees. Planting campaigns help, but long-term care and protection during construction are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">equally important</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Trees","phrases":[{"en":"where people live","vi":"nơi mọi người sinh sống"},{"en":"equally important","vi":"quan trọng không kém"}],"source":"Topic reference: IELTS Advantage (2026); questions adapted; answers rewritten and quality-audited by ChatGPT","subtype":"","summary":"Trees","id":"speaking-part-1-085","_displayNo":"#085","qaBands":["8.5","8.0","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Volunteer Work","prompt":"Have you ever done volunteer work?\nWhy do people volunteer?\nShould schools encourage volunteering?","answer":"Q: Have you ever done volunteer work?\nA: Yes, I have helped with small educational and community activities. The work was modest, but it showed me that regular <strong class=\"key-phrase\">practical support</strong> can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make a meaningful contribution</strong>.\n\nQ: Why do people volunteer?\nA: People volunteer to support a cause, gain experience or feel connected to their community. The strongest motivation is usually a combination of empathy and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sense of purpose</strong>.\n\nQ: Should schools encourage volunteering?\nA: Yes, provided the work is age-appropriate and genuinely useful. Volunteering can develop responsibility and empathy, but it should not become <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a box-ticking exercise</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Volunteer Work","phrases":[{"en":"practical support","vi":"sự hỗ trợ thiết thực"},{"en":"make a meaningful contribution","vi":"đóng góp có ý nghĩa"},{"en":"a sense of purpose","vi":"cảm giác có mục đích"},{"en":"a box-ticking exercise","vi":"một hoạt động làm cho có"}],"source":"Topic reference: IELTS Advantage (2026); questions adapted; answers rewritten and quality-audited by ChatGPT","subtype":"","summary":"Volunteer Work","id":"speaking-part-1-086","_displayNo":"#086","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Walking","prompt":"Do you like walking?\nDo you think walking is important?\nDo you think walking in the countryside is better than walking in the city?\nWhat could be done to improve the experience of walking in cities?","answer":"Q: Do you like walking?\nA: I'm not one for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">going on really long walks</strong> in the countryside, but I don't mind walking when I'm in a town or city, for example when I'm sightseeing in a new place.\n\nQ: Do you think walking is important?\nA: Yes, I think it's important to be active, and walking is the most basic physical activity that we can do.\n\nQ: Do you think walking in the countryside is better than walking in the city?\nA: Personally, no. As I said before, I like walking in the city, especially if it's somewhere with <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a lot of history</strong> like London or Paris.\n\nQ: What could be done to improve the experience of walking in cities?\nA: I suppose the main issues are space and safety. Pavements need to be wide enough to accommodate lots of pedestrians, and we need safe places to cross the street.","author":"Simon","topic":"Walking","phrases":[{"en":"going on really long walks","vi":"đi bộ những quãng đường rất dài"},{"en":"a lot of history","vi":"bề dày lịch sử"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Walking","id":"speaking-part-1-087","_displayNo":"#087","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Warm-Up","prompt":"Could you tell me your full name please?\nWhat is your name?\nDoes your name have any special meaning?\nWhy do many people change their names?","answer":"Q: Could you tell me your full name please?\nA: My full name is Nguyen Nhat Dien, although people usually call me Dien. It is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a straightforward name</strong>, so I rarely need to explain or shorten it.\n\nQ: What is your name?\nA: My name is Nguyen Nhat Dien, and most people simply call me Dien. It is short, familiar and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">easy to remember</strong>.\n\nQ: Does your name have any special meaning?\nA: It has a positive meaning in Vietnamese and was chosen by my family. I value it mainly because it connects me with them and gives me <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sense of identity</strong>.\n\nQ: Why do many people change their names?\nA: People may change their names because of marriage, migration, personal identity or professional reasons. A new name can make communication easier, although changing it also involves <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a great deal of paperwork</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Warm-Up","phrases":[{"en":"a straightforward name","vi":"một cái tên đơn giản, dễ hiểu"},{"en":"easy to remember","vi":"dễ nhớ"},{"en":"a sense of identity","vi":"cảm giác về bản sắc"},{"en":"a great deal of paperwork","vi":"rất nhiều thủ tục giấy tờ"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Warm-Up","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-088","_displayNo":"#088","qaBands":["8.5","8.0","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Weather","prompt":"What's the weather like in your country?\nDoes the weather affect your mood?\nWhat's your favourite season of the year?\nWhat do you usually do in winter?","answer":"Q: What's the weather like in your country?\nA: Vietnam has a varied climate, but Hanoi has hot, humid summers and cooler, drier winters. The transition seasons can be pleasant, although the weather is becoming <strong class=\"key-phrase\">less predictable</strong>.\n\nQ: Does the weather affect your mood?\nA: Yes, slightly. Bright, mild weather gives me more energy, while long periods of humidity can make daily tasks feel tiring. I try not to let it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">determine my whole day</strong>.\n\nQ: What's your favourite season of the year?\nA: Autumn is my favourite because the temperature is comfortable and the air is usually clearer. It is the easiest season for walking, working and spending time <strong class=\"key-phrase\">outdoors comfortably</strong>.\n\nQ: What do you usually do in winter?\nA: In winter I exercise indoors, drink hot tea and spend more time reading. I also enjoy walking on dry, cool days because the city feels <strong class=\"key-phrase\">quieter and calmer</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Weather","phrases":[{"en":"less predictable","vi":"khó dự đoán hơn"},{"en":"determine my whole day","vi":"quyết định toàn bộ tâm trạng trong ngày"},{"en":"outdoors comfortably","vi":"ngoài trời một cách thoải mái"},{"en":"quieter and calmer","vi":"yên tĩnh và thư thái hơn"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 1","summary":"Weather","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-1-089","_displayNo":"#089","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-1","title":"Work","prompt":"Do you work or are you a student?\nDo you enjoy your job?\nWhat's the best thing about your job?\nDo you prefer working alone or with others?","answer":"Q: Do you work or are you a student?\nA: I am <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a qualified doctor</strong>, but at the moment I am studying English so that I can work in this country.\n\nQ: Do you enjoy your job?\nA: Yes. I have wanted to become a doctor since childhood, and I still find the work meaningful because it allows me to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">help people recover</strong> and make difficult periods more manageable.\n\nQ: What's the best thing about your job?\nA: The best thing about my job is that I can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make a difference</strong> in people’s lives. It’s a great feeling to see someone recover after an illness because my colleagues and I were able to help.\n\nQ: Do you prefer working alone or with others?\nA: In a hospital you have to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">work as part of a team</strong>. I have got used to working with others, and I think you can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">achieve a lot more as a team</strong> than you would alone.","author":"Simon","topic":"Work","phrases":[{"en":"a qualified doctor","vi":"một bác sĩ có chuyên môn"},{"en":"help people recover","vi":"giúp người bệnh hồi phục"},{"en":"make a difference","vi":"tạo ra sự khác biệt"},{"en":"work as part of a team","vi":"làm việc như một thành viên của đội nhóm"},{"en":"achieve a lot more as a team","vi":"đạt được nhiều hơn khi làm việc theo nhóm"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 1","subtype":"","summary":"Work","id":"speaking-part-1-090","_displayNo":"#090","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe a future aim.\nYou should say:\n- what the aim is\n- when you hope to achieve it\n- what you need to do to reach your goal\n- and why this goal is important to you.","answer":"I am going to describe a future aim of mine, which is to write a book. I would like to write a novel, so the story or plot would be fictional, but it would probably <strong class=\"key-phrase\">be influenced by</strong> some of my own experiences, ideas and views. Unfortunately I have no idea where to start or what my novel would be about, so I cannot imagine achieving this aim until later in my life. Maybe it will be something that I do as a hobby when I retire, or I might suddenly be inspired to start writing much sooner. It’s just a vague objective at the moment. I think it must be extremely difficult to find the motivation to write a novel, so more than anything I would need time, commitment and the passion to keep working until I finished. I would probably need to set a goal of writing for a certain amount of time each day, and of course I would need a good idea for a story in the first place. This goal interests me because I have always wondered how people manage to create a work of fiction from nothing; I have always wondered whether I could do the same, and whether I would be capable of bringing a story to life. I have always enjoyed reading, and I would like to follow in the footsteps of my favourite authors.","author":"Simon","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"be influenced by","vi":"bị ảnh hưởng bởi"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a future aim","id":"speaking-part-2-001","_displayNo":"#001","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe a team project that you worked on.\nYou should say:\n- what it was\n- what you did","answer":"I would like to talk about <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a team project</strong> that I was involved in during my final term at business school. There were four of us on the team, and our task was to work with a local company to research a new market, in a European country, for one of their products or services. Our objective was to produce a report and give a presentation. The first thing we did was split into two groups of two. We had been assigned a company that produced <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a range of</strong> bicycle accessories, so two of us spent some time getting to know the company while the other two researched the market and the competitors in the target country, which was Germany. In the end, I think it was a successful project because we managed to identify a possible gap in the market in Germany for one of the company’s products. Our group presentation also went really well. Until that point, the course had been all about business theory, so it was quite a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">learning experience</strong> to work with a real company. I felt <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a real sense of accomplishment</strong> when we handed in our report and delivered our presentation, and I think all of us were proud of what we had done.","author":"Simon","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"a team project","vi":"một dự án nhóm"},{"en":"a range of","vi":"nhiều loại"},{"en":"learning experience","vi":"trải nghiệm học tập"},{"en":"a real sense of accomplishment","vi":"cảm giác thành tựu thực sự"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a team project that you worked on","id":"speaking-part-2-002","_displayNo":"#002","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe a time you travelled by public transport.\nYou should say:\n- what type of public transport you used\n- where you travelled from and to\n- what you did during the journey\n- and explain how you felt about travelling in this way","answer":"I am going to describe <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a train journey</strong> that I took last year between Manchester and London. I have made the same journey many times, but I will never forget this particular time because something happened that I was not expecting. It was a Sunday morning and I was due in London that afternoon. There was no traffic at all as I drove in to Manchester, and I was expecting a nice, peaceful trip on <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a half-empty train</strong>. But my first surprise came when I tried to print my prepaid ticket at one of the ticket machines: there was not a reserved seat number on my ticket, which meant that I would have to find an available seat. I was still wondering about this when I heard loud voices and singing coming from the main station concourse. Suddenly I realised what was happening - I was going to be on a train full of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">football fans</strong> travelling to a big match! Luckily I managed to find a seat before the train filled up. However, the noisy fans made sure that I couldn’t concentrate on any work; I couldn’t even read the newspaper without being interrupted by laughter, singing and football stories. In the end, I just sat and relaxed with a cup of coffee, watching and listening to the excited fans. All in all, it was not a bad journey; I love travelling by train and at least I had a comfortable seat so that I could <strong class=\"key-phrase\">sit back and relax</strong> for a couple of hours. I would have preferred a quieter trip, but the football fans were all friendly and good-natured, so I cannot really complain. Even so, I made sure that I avoided them on the way home later that day!","author":"Simon","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"a train journey","vi":"một chuyến đi bằng tàu"},{"en":"a half-empty train","vi":"một chuyến tàu chỉ có một nửa số ghế có người"},{"en":"football fans","vi":"những người hâm mộ bóng đá"},{"en":"sit back and relax","vi":"ngồi thoải mái và thư giãn"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a time you travelled by public transport","id":"speaking-part-2-003","_displayNo":"#003","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe an interesting lesson that you attended.\nYou should say:\n- where you attended this lesson\n- what it was about\n- and why you found it interesting","answer":"I'm going to talk about an interesting science lesson that I attended at secondary school when I was 14 or 15 years old. It was quite a long time ago, so I can't remember every detail, but the lesson was about respiration. We learned about how the lungs work, how we breathe, and how oxygen <strong class=\"key-phrase\">passes into the blood</strong>. The science teacher also talked to us about the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">effects of smoking</strong> on the lungs. I found this lesson interesting because my science teacher, Dr. Smith, always introduced new topics by showing us a video. We watched a short film about how respiration works, and I found this much easier to understand than a science textbook. The film showed diagrams of the lungs to explain the breathing process. Later in the lesson we saw real photos of healthy lungs and lungs that had been damaged as a result of smoking; they had turned black. I think the image of a smoker's lungs is the reason why I remember this lesson.","author":"Simon","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"passes into the blood","vi":"đi vào máu"},{"en":"effects of smoking","vi":"tác hại của việc hút thuốc"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"an interesting lesson that you attended","id":"speaking-part-2-004","_displayNo":"#004","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe something important that you learned in a maths lesson at primary school\nYou should say:\n- what is it\n- when you learned it\n- how you learned it\n- and explain how it became important in your future life.","answer":"I am going to talk about learning the multiplication tables for the numbers 1 to 12, which I remember doing in the penultimate year of primary school, when I was maybe 9 years old. As children, we called these the ’times tables’. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">As far as I remember</strong>, we started with the number 2, and we learned to multiply this number by each of the numbers from 1 to 12. Our teacher taught us to go through the tables speaking aloud; for example: 1 times 2 is 2, 2 times 2 is 4, 3 times 2 is 6 etc. We gradually worked our way through the tables for all of the numbers, and we learned the answers by heart. I think the teacher also gave us regular tests to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make sure that</strong> we had learned the tables properly. I am not sure whether I really understood at the time why it was important to learn the ’times tables’ by rote. But I think I enjoyed the challenge, and I was keen to get good marks in our tests. I also liked my teacher and wanted to do well for her. Many years later I realise how important it is to have the basic multiplication tables ingrained in my mind. It’s useful to be able to do quick calculations without having to think. Recently, for example, I needed to multiply 6 by 7 for some reason - I cannot even remember why - and the answer 42 just popped into my head. Another instance that I can think of is when I am calculating bill payments, earnings and savings over a 12-month period, and I find myself using the ’12 times table’. In these situations, I am glad that my primary school teachers were so insistent about learning to multiply by heart.","author":"Simon","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"As far as I remember","vi":"theo như tôi nhớ"},{"en":"make sure that","vi":"đảm bảo rằng"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"something important that you learned in a maths lesson at","id":"speaking-part-2-005","_displayNo":"#005","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe a car journey you went on.\nYou should say:\n- Where did you go;\n- What did you do there;\n- Who you went there with;\n- Why you wanted to go there for a car journey;\n- How you feel about it.","answer":"Today I would like to share with you a story about a car journey that I took part in.\nIt was about three years ago, when I had just graduated from university. In fact, it was in the middle\nof summer vacation, so my best friend and I decided to go on a trip to Nha Trang; <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a coastal city</strong> on\nthe South-Central Coast of Vietnam. We decided to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">set out</strong> for this city very early in the morning,\nas it is far from my hometown. I knew that we faced <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a long drive</strong> ahead, so it would be safer to\ntravel by car, rather than by motorbike.\nAfter 5 hours driving, we arrived at our destination. We were amazed to see beautiful beaches\nwith fine and clean sand, as well as clear ocean water with mild temperatures. We had a lot of\nactivities to do at the time, including eating out at night and swimming near the beaches. Also, we\nstayed for three nights with my uncle’s family and helped them with their regular tasks before\nsetting off home on the last day.\nAt first, I was under the impression that this trip would be kind of boring as didn't have many\nfriends to go with me in this trip. However, it turned out to be an amazing one, and it helped us\nlearn more about the countryside and the way of life of those who live there. If I have opportunities\nin the future, I would love to make more trips like that.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"a coastal city","vi":"một thành phố ven biển"},{"en":"set out","vi":"bắt đầu thực hiện; lên đường"},{"en":"a long drive","vi":"một chuyến lái xe đường dài"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a car journey you went on","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-006","_displayNo":"#006","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe a holiday or vacation you have been on\nYou should say:\nwhen you had it\nwhere you went\nwhat you did\nand explain how you felt about it","answer":"A few months ago, I went to the South of Vietnam for a vacation with my family. It was to the\nlovely coastal city of Nha Trang, which is also a very famous tourist destination. We decided to go\nthere by plane since it is nearly 1200 kilometres from Hanoi, and would take a long time by car or\ntrain.\nI was so eager for the trip that I prepared everything such as my clothes, camera and other\naccessories <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a week in advance</strong>. It took about an hour to fly there, and luckily, the flight took off\non time. The trip began with an incredible view from the airplane window and I can still remember\nbeing quite overwhelmed by the beauty of my city from above and the amazing sunset.\nThe time we spent in Nha Trang was a blast. We got to try out so many new things such as\nskydiving, surfing, and diving to see the coral reef. This place has one of the most beautiful beaches\nin Vietnam with deep blue water and pearly-white sand. Also, the food there was so unique and\ndelicious. I think the most memorable moment of that trip though was definitely when we bought\nfresh ingredients from a local market and grilled them by the beach. Sitting there by the fire on a\nbreezy night with the delicious smell freshly barbequed fish was an amazing experience.\nThe trip to Nha Trang really was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the holiday of a lifetime</strong>. We had a lot of fun and got to see a lot\nof spectacular scenery. We definitely enjoyed it and we will definitely go there again if we have a\nchance.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"a week in advance","vi":"trước một tuần"},{"en":"the holiday of a lifetime","vi":"kỳ nghỉ đáng nhớ nhất đời"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a holiday or vacation you have been on","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-007","_displayNo":"#007","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe a holiday you would like to take in the future\nYou should say:\n- When and where you would like to go\n- Who you would like to go with\n- What you would like to do on this holiday\n- Why you would like to take the holiday","answer":"I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">have itchy feet</strong>, so I always have a detailed plan for the next holiday trip in mind.\nThis time, I am going to wait for my children’s summer vacation so that I can take the whole family\non a trip together. I am a family person and I love to travel with my loved ones. And, you know,\nsummer will not be complete without sun tan and beach snapshots. Therefore, my destination must\nbe a seaside city and Vinh Hy bay is my ideal place. I have heard about this place a long time ago,\na friend of mine highly recommended this place after her trip there. It is known for natural scenic\nbeauty and delicious fresh seafood at an affordable price.\nI was curious, but couldn’t find time to travel there due to my <strong class=\"key-phrase\">tight working schedule</strong>. But this\nsummer we are going to make it. It’s only a 4-hour ride from our city to the bay, so I am going to\ngo by bike, as if I were going backpacking. One reason luring us to this place is that it's a pristine\nisland, which means it will not be crowded with tourists and the food here will not be overpriced.\nUnlike other beaches which offer a variety of water sports like canoeing, scuba-diving, water-\nskiing and skydiving, there will not be many activities to do in Vinh Hy bay apart from sun-bathing\nand eating seafood. But this is going be a family time, and to me, spending time together is already\nenough.\nIn case my children get bored, so I am going to bring some family games like UNO and castle-\nbuilding tools to enjoy time on the beach together. I am in dire need of this vacation as I want to\nescape from a stressful workload and pressure from city life for a while with my kids and my\nspouse. Also, I think it is a good idea to reward my children with a trip after studying hard\nthroughout the school year.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"have itchy feet","vi":"luôn muốn đi đây đó"},{"en":"tight working schedule","vi":"lịch làm việc dày đặc"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a holiday you would like to take in the future","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-008","_displayNo":"#008","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe a leisure activity near or on the sea\nYou should say:\nWhat it is\nWhat you should prepare\nWhy you have to prepare\nAnd explain how you feel about it.","answer":"I would like to talk about one of my favourite activities on the beach, swimming. You know, I live\nin Hai Phong, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a coastal city</strong> with golden beaches and the nearest seashore is just fifteen minutes\nfrom my house. So, in the summer, my friends and I often go there and swim in the cool water to\navoid the hot weather.\nActually, swimming is a relatively easy sport. I learned how to swim when I was about 8 years old\nand it took me only a week to get familiar with a number of swimming strokes, like breaststroke,\nbackstroke and butterfly. Before entering the water, I often warm up and stretch my muscles and\njoints to avoid any injuries, then put on my swimsuit and jump right in.\nI really enjoy swimming on the beach because of a few reasons. Firstly, unlike other water sports\nsuch as diving or windsurfing, which require costly equipment, swimming costs nothing. Secondly,\nswimming is extremely beneficial to our health. It provides an all-over body workout, as nearly all\nof our muscles are used during swimming. It also builds endurance, muscle strength and\ncardiovascular fitness. Lastly, going swimming is a good means of recreation as it allows me to\nunwind, alleviate stress and have a great time with my friends.\nSummer is coming so I will definitely make a plan to visit the beach soon. I intend to go to Nha Trang\nbeach as it’s considered one of the most magnificent beaches in the world.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"a coastal city","vi":"một thành phố ven biển"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a leisure activity near or on the sea","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-009","_displayNo":"#009","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe a lesson that you enjoyed\nYou should say:\nWhen it was\nWhat it was about\nWhat happened And\nexplain why you liked it","answer":"Well, I would like to share with you a really pleasant experience in an English class I had\nat my university.\nDuring one of our grammar lessons, the regular teacher was sick so the school had to send in a\nteacher to cover her place. And the substitute teacher, Thomas Hall, delivered an amazing lecture\nin English about how he thinks we should all learn languages through watching films.\nThroughout the two hours, he explained to us the process of learning a language and how films\ncan serve as an effective way to immerse yourself in a language. Basic elements like vocabulary\nand grammar can be easily absorbed if we focus on dialog in a TV show, and so <strong class=\"key-phrase\">in the long run</strong>,\nour overall language skills can be improved. This method helps us to learn any language\neffortlessly and in a short period of time.\nAt first, we were all sceptical about the ideas he introduced, however, after watching a short\nvideo to practice and doing a trial test, we were all convinced that learning by watching movies\nwas not hard at all and we could apply this to enhance our performance at school.\nI enjoyed this lesson so much because I find this method to be particularly effective for me. I\nalways felt unmotivated when learning by traditional methods and my results were never\ndesirable. But when I tried learning English using my favourite movies, you know what? My\nEnglish got better and better and very soon I was able to remember thousands of new words\nand write really complicated essays. Now, I can even proudly say that I have mastered the English\nlanguage.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"in the long run","vi":"về lâu dài"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a lesson that you enjoyed","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-010","_displayNo":"#010","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe a long journey you travelled by car\nYou should say:\nwhat it was\nwhen and where it happened\nwho was involved\nAnd explain if you enjoyed it or not.","answer":"I would like to describe quite a long but exciting journey that I went on last week by car from my\nhometown, Hue city, to the capital city, Hanoi.\nI had three travelling companions in the car with me, who were three of my close friends and we\nhad agreed on gathering at my house at 5am, which was our point of departure. Actually, I am quite\nan early riser, so I found it quite easy to get up that early and be ready on time. And luckily, the\nweather that day was really nice, so we were able to leave the windows down for most of the trip.\nThe fresh air and tranquillity of the countryside <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made me feel really</strong> relaxed but energetic at the\nsame time.\nAfter driving all day, we arrived in Hanoi quite late, by around 6:30pm and continued to drive\naround the lake a few times, until about 7pm, when the sun began to set and the streets became\na little quieter. After that, we stopped at our favourite cafe to sip on some coffee and reflect on\nour long day.\nI really enjoyed that car trip because of several reasons. To begin with, it was a great chance for\nme to see my country from a very different angle, a road trip with my mates. Usually I would take\nthe train or a plane to complete that journey. So this was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a great way to</strong> see things, stopping\nwhenever we liked, if we saw something that interested us, for example. This car trip also helped\nme to refresh my mind by just hitting the open road and leaving all my worries behind. It was also\na really great opportunity for me and my friends to enjoy each other’s company and exchange\nstories along the way from our daily lives. You know, we are often too busy to meet regularly, so\nchances like this are really valuable.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"made me feel really","vi":"khiến tôi thực sự cảm thấy"},{"en":"a great way to","vi":"một cách rất hiệu quả để"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a long journey you travelled by car","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-011","_displayNo":"#011","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe a long walk you had\nYou should say:\nwhere you went to\nwhen you went\nwho you went with\nAnd explain how you felt about this walk.","answer":"I would like to talk about a long walk that I have taken recently. So this was a walk around Hoan\nKiem Lake. I do this walk quite regularly actually, usually in the late evening, and usually whenever\nI am feeling <strong class=\"key-phrase\">under pressure</strong> at work or school.\nThat night, the fresh air and tranquil atmosphere around the lake <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made me feel relaxed</strong> but quite\nenergetic at the same time, and it helped me to refresh my mind to get ready for a new day to\ncome. There’s also a lot of police presence around the area which makes you feel quite safe, so\nyou do not have to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">be concerned about</strong> being pick-pocketed or something like that, you can really\njust concentrate your mind on other more important things.\nSurrounding the lake is a long spacious pavement, where people usually go jogging and walking,\nand after taking a long walk I just sat there on a bench, taking in the peaceful atmosphere. Most\nof the time I was just gazing at the stars, trying my best to let my mind unwind and meditate.\nThe reason I took this walk was because I had just had a huge fight with my best friend and he had\nstarted questioning some things about my life, and it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made me feel really</strong> awful. So following that,\nwe had an argument and all of a sudden I started questioning our relationship. Things just started\nfeeling very bizarre, so I went looking for something that would calm my mind.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"under pressure","vi":"trong tình huống chịu áp lực"},{"en":"made me feel relaxed","vi":"khiến tôi cảm thấy thư giãn"},{"en":"be concerned about","vi":"lo ngại về"},{"en":"made me feel really","vi":"khiến tôi thực sự cảm thấy"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a long walk you had","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-012","_displayNo":"#012","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe a new skill you would like to learn\nYou should say:\nWhat it is\nWho you want to learn it from\nHow you are going to learn it\nAnd explain why you want to learn it","answer":"Today I would like to share with you a skill I have always desired to learn, which is speaking\nGerman.\nA couple of years ago I had such a fantastic trip to Europe, and I was deeply impressed by the\nbeauty, uniqueness and modern style of the capital city, Berlin. I was wandering around all over\nthe city in many different shopping malls to find my father his favourite black Nike coat. I was\nfortunate enough to finally find it in the Kaufland shopping mall, however, when I flew back to\nVietnam, I realized that I had bought the female size. So it was after that incident that I decided\nto <strong class=\"key-phrase\">try my hand at</strong> learning German.\nThe first reason that makes German such an attractive language to learn is that it is pretty much\nthe second most common language spoken in Europe, for example, in Denmark, Hungary, Poland,\nAustria, and so on. And secondly, German <strong class=\"key-phrase\">bears a close resemblance to</strong> English, and shares pretty\nmuch the same alphabet, so I think that might make it a little easier to learn. Additionally, if I learn\nGerman, in the future I could certainly apply for a scholarship to study in Germany’s great\neducation system.\nI think learning a new language can also be really handy when travelling, can make you more\ndecisive and can bring you multitudes of cognitive advantages such as becoming smarter and\navoiding Alzheimer’s disease when you get older. And last but not least, I think life would be much\nmore exciting if you can speak multiple languages.\nSo, sometime in the near future, if I can handle my work and study load, I would love to give learning\nGerman a go.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"try my hand at","vi":"thử sức với"},{"en":"bears a close resemblance to","vi":"có nhiều điểm tương đồng với"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a new skill you would like to learn","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-013","_displayNo":"#013","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe a short trip that was special to you\nYou should say:\nwhen it was\nwhere you went\nwho you went with\nAnd explain why it was special.","answer":"I would like to describe a short but rather exciting tour that I went on last Saturday, which was a\nbicycle trip around Hoan Kiem Lake, which is also known as Sword Lake, and is one of the major\nscenic spots in Hanoi, the capital city of Vietnam.\nI went on this trip with three close friends of mine, and we agreed on riding our bicycles to the\nLy Thai To statue at 5am, which was to be our point of departure. I am actually quite the early\nriser so I found it pretty easy to get up that early and be there on time.\nAnd luckily the weather that day was really nice. The air was fresh and the tranquillity of the\nmorning <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made me feel relaxed</strong> but also energetic. We biked around the lake about five times until\naround 7am when the sun began to rise and the streets started to get crowded. After that, we\ngathered at our favourite cafe to sip on some coffee chat about our lives.\nI really enjoyed that short bike trip due to several reasons. Firstly, it was a great chance for me to\nsee our city from a very different perspective, a peaceful Hanoi without traffic jams and air\npollution. I was able to escape from <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the hustle and bustle</strong> of the city for a few hours and recharge\nmyself to get prepared for a new week.\nI think that cycling is also a really great exercise that helps me to strengthen my health, build up\nstamina and improve my immune system. And last but not least, I think this trip was a really great\nopportunity for me and my friends to get together and chat about our daily lives. You know, we\nare often too busy to meet regularly, so times like these are really valuable.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"made me feel relaxed","vi":"khiến tôi cảm thấy thư giãn"},{"en":"the hustle and bustle","vi":"sự hối hả và nhộn nhịp"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a short trip that was special to you","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-014","_displayNo":"#014","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe a special day out (A day out which does not cost too much)\nYou should say:\n- Where did you go on that day.\n- What did you do.\n- Who did you go out with.\n- Why was it special to you.","answer":"I went to the park with my friend the other day. She was my good friend in high school and we\nhave not seen each other for almost a year. As we were both having our semester break, we wanted\nto meet and catch up over dinner.\nWe actually planned to meet each other at the park and then decide on where to go later, but my\nfriend got there pretty late so we ended up staying there. We got two takeout milk tea glasses and\nkebabs from a small street vendor and found a comfortable corner to enjoy ourselves. We sat\nthere watching people passing by, talking about random things that came up. The weather that\nday was pretty nice actually. It was raining in the evening all week, so we were worried that we\nmight have to go home early. But it turned out to be a fine evening.\nI guess what makes the day special was the fact that, despite having to wait for my friend to show\nup and then not going anywhere like we originally planned to, we still had a lot more fun than I\nhad expected. We updated each other on what was going on in our lives and discussed our plans\nfor the future. It was a nice feeling to know even though we couldn’t meet and talk frequently, we\ncould still bond easily over milk tea and kebabs. It <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made me realize that</strong> sometimes we only need\ngood company and good conversations to make something memorable.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"made me realize that","vi":"khiến tôi nhận ra rằng"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a special day out (A day out which does not cost too much)","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-015","_displayNo":"#015","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe a special trip in the near future\nYou should say:\nWhen it will possibly be\nWhere you would go\nWhat preparation you need for the trip\nAnd explain why this would be a special trip","answer":"Travelling is what I enjoy the most in life and I have now visited most of the famous places in Vietnam.\nHowever, most of my trips were always with my friends, so now I really want to do something\ndifferent and take my parents on a very special trip to visit Thien Cam beach.\nWe will probably take this trip next June I think. At that time of year, there will not be any school\nfor me so things will be much easier to plan. My parents are also very excited about the trip and\nare <strong class=\"key-phrase\">really looking forward to it</strong>.\nThien Cam is the largest beach in Vietnam and is quite a popular tourist destination, famous for\nits big waves. It is located in the central part of the country, which is not really too far from where\nwe currently live. When we arrive, aside from enjoying the beach, we will probably visit some other\ntourist attractions around the area, and I guess that during the trip we will probably get some\nsouvenirs for our relatives as well.\nIn terms of the preparation, we are planning to go there by train so that we can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">enjoy the scenic\nbeauty</strong> of our country along the way. Of course we’ll probably have to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">book a hotel in advance</strong>,\nand bring our swimsuits, sunscreen and summer clothes. Another important thing to remember to\nbring is medicines, just in case someone gets sick.\nSo, the main reason this will be a special trip I guess is because my parents will be with me and this\nwill be the first time they visit this place. Having my parents there with me will really make it special\nbecause it's been more than 7 years since we <strong class=\"key-phrase\">took a holiday together</strong>.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"really looking forward to it","vi":"thực sự mong chờ chuyến đi"},{"en":"enjoy the scenic beauty","vi":"thưởng ngoạn cảnh đẹp"},{"en":"book a hotel in advance","vi":"đặt khách sạn trước"},{"en":"took a holiday together","vi":"cùng nhau đi nghỉ"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a special trip in the near future","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-016","_displayNo":"#016","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe a subject you would like to study that you never had the opportunity to study.\nYou should say:\nWhat is it\nWhat this subject deals with\nWhat benefits you would get\nAnd explain why you want to study this subject.","answer":"If I had a chance, I would like to study Japanese, which I always wanted to study when I was\nyounger.\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">Back in the day</strong>, I was crazy about manga – Japanese comic books. I could not <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take my eyes off</strong>\nthose stories, I read them every single day. And I told myself that I would study Japanese in the\nfuture. Unfortunately, when I grew up, I was up to my ears in study and then working to make a\nliving so I missed the chance to learn Japanese.\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">Now and then</strong> I think about that childhood dream and hope that one day, I can arrange my work\nand <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take part in</strong> a Japanese course. Being fluent in Japanese will make my dream come true. I\nwould possibly read manga in Japanese, not Vietnamese and get a chance to access more Japanese\nculture, which I am interested in after many years reading manga.\nThat’s all I want to share with you.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"Back in the day","vi":"hồi trước"},{"en":"take my eyes off","vi":"rời mắt khỏi"},{"en":"Now and then","vi":"thỉnh thoảng"},{"en":"take part in","vi":"tham gia"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a subject you would like to study that you never had the opportunity to study","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-017","_displayNo":"#017","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe a trip you took by bike\nYou should say:\nWhen and where the trip was\nWho you went with\nWhy you went by bike\nAnd explain how you felt about it.","answer":"I would like to describe a really exciting tour that I went on last Saturday, which was a bicycle trip\naround Hoan Kiem Lake, also known as Sword Lake, which is one of the major scenic spots in\nHanoi.\nI went on this trip with three travelling companions, who were all close friends of mine, and we\nagreed on riding our bicycles to the Ly Thai To statue at 5 am, which was our point of departure.\nI am actually quite an early riser so I found it quite easy to get up that early and be there on time.\nAnd luckily the weather that day was really nice. The air was fresh and the tranquillity of the\nmorning <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made me feel relaxed</strong> but energetic. We biked around the lake five times until about\n7am when the sun began to rise and the streets started to get crowded. After that, we gathered\nat our favourite cafe to sip on cups of strong coffee and to chitchat.\nI really enjoyed that bike trip due to several reasons. Firstly, it was a great chance for me to see\nour city from a very different perspective, a peaceful Hanoi without traffic jams and air pollution.\nI was able to escape from <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the hustle and bustle</strong> of the city for a few hours and refresh myself to\nget prepared for a new week.\nI think that cycling is also a really great exercise that helps me to strengthen my health, build up\nmy stamina and improve the immune system. And last but not least, I think this trip was a really\ngreat opportunity for me and my friends to get together and chat about our daily lives. You know,\nwe are often too busy to meet regularly, so times like these are really valuable.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"made me feel relaxed","vi":"khiến tôi cảm thấy thư giãn"},{"en":"the hustle and bustle","vi":"sự hối hả và nhộn nhịp"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a trip you took by bike","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-018","_displayNo":"#018","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe an activity you do to keep fit.\nYou should say:\n- What you do.\n- When and where you usually do it.\n- How you do it.\n- Why it can keep you fit.","answer":"Today I would like to talk about jogging; my favourite activity that I usually do to stay healthy. It’s\na kind of running at a slow or leisurely pace that helps to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">build up your physical fitness</strong>.\nI much prefer to go jogging in open spaces, like parks or lakesides, because you can enjoy fresh air\nand watch people doing various types of physical activity such as running, aerobic exercises or\nplaying badminton. I normally go jogging in the morning with my close friend on a daily basis for\nabout 30 minutes to 1 hour in order to keep fit.\nThere are many reasons why it can keep me fit. Firstly, this activity is a good way to gain an\nattractive appearance and keep in good shape, which is really beneficial to my health. Also, we\ncan improve our immune system and lower the risks of modern diseases, like diabetes or obesity,\nby jogging regularly. Unlike other forms of exercise, jogging is quite easy to do and it allows me to\nobserve people and things as I pass by. The second important reason is that doing this activity also\nallows me to ease my mind and get away from daily routine, the effects of which are limitless.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"build up your physical fitness","vi":"nâng cao thể lực"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an activity you do to keep fit","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-019","_displayNo":"#019","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe one activity stopped by the weather\nYou should say:\nWhen and where it happened\nWho was involved\nWhat the activity was\nAnd what you did after the activity was stopped","answer":"Anyone who is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a big fan of tennis</strong> definitely knows the name of tennis legend Novak Djokovic.\nAnd today I am going to tell you about the story of how I skipped school to watch the big game\nthat did not happen between Novak Djokovic and Dominic Thiem at the 2017 Roland Garros.\nYou know, I have been fascinated by the wonderful world of tennis since I first discovered the sport.\nMy father and I would always just sit around like a pair of couch potatoes whenever a big tennis\ncompetition was on. Novak has long been my hero on the court while my father has always been\na big fan of Roger Federer. I always love watching a tennis match with my favourite player,\nwhether he wins or loses, and I still love him either way because that’s just the way things go\nsometimes. I still admire his sportsmanship and talent and the way he elegantly yet powerfully\nmoves on the court.\nOn this particular day though of the quarterfinals Novak had to defeat Thiem to go through to\nthe semi-final and I was so excited to watch this game because Novak had previously lost the\nRoland Garros cup before two years in a row. Unfortunately, I had an unavoidable mid-term test\nthat day which meant it was impossible for me to watch the game live. But after wrestling with\nmy conscience, I decided to tell a lie to my father so that I could stay at home to watch the match.\nHowever, the weather in Paris that day turned out to be so terrible that the game was cancelled.\nI felt so guilty when I found out that the game was cancelled, and I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">got into big trouble</strong> by my father\nfor not showing up to take the mid-term test at school.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"a big fan of tennis","vi":"một người rất hâm mộ quần vợt"},{"en":"got into big trouble","vi":"gặp rắc rối lớn"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"one activity stopped by the weather","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-020","_displayNo":"#020","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe something special that you saved money to buy\nYou should say:\n- What was this thing.\n- Why was it special to you.\n- How much did it cost you.\n- How you felt after you bought it.","answer":"I am going to talk about a clock necklace that I gave my best friend, Julie.\nIt was at the end of grade 10 that she left me to continue her study abroad. For fear that I would\nbe forgotten someday, I tried to think of a farewell gift that could make her think of me every time\nshe saw it. It was not an easy task to find the right present; maybe it was because I was being too\npicky. She was more than a friend to me, she is more like my sister, or my soul mate. I did not want\nto give her something meaningful but useless, or something useful but emotionally empty. I\nwanted something that was special, something that would make her say “wow” when she received\nit. I wandered from shop to shop to look for something, but I didn't know what.\nOne day, I came across something reminding me of her right away - a vintage necklace with a clock\npendant. It perfectly suited her style, so she could wear it with any of her clothes. What I liked\nabout the clock was that it was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">custom-made</strong>, I could design the number and write a message on\nit too. The thing is, when giving her the necklace, I set the clock to the local time in Vietnam, so\nwhenever she needed to tell the time she would feel annoyed because of the difference in time\nzones, and I hoped that she would think of me right at the moment. The price was not expensive at\nall, about $20, but to a high school student like me at that time <strong class=\"key-phrase\">it was a fortune</strong>. I had to skip\nbreakfast for an entire month to purchase it, but it was totally worth it. She had no clue about how\nI bought it but she liked it anyway. I felt exhilarated when I could buy my bestie something\nbeautiful that she deserved, and I hoped that this chain would tie us forever.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"custom-made","vi":"được làm theo yêu cầu riêng"},{"en":"it was a fortune","vi":"rất đắt tiền"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"something special that you saved money to buy","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-021","_displayNo":"#021","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe something you do to keep healthy.\nYou should say:\n- What the activity is\n- When you do it\n- How often you do it\nAnd explain why it is a good way to look after your health.","answer":"I would like to share with you something that I am keen on doing in my leisure time to stay healthy,\nwhich is jogging.\nI <strong class=\"key-phrase\">took up this habit</strong> about 2 years ago. At that time, I was up to my ears with study to prepare for\nmy graduation examination so I was a little bit stressed out. Then I thought that I needed to do\nsomething energetic to release some stress, so I decided to have a crack at jogging.\nAt first, doing this was quite challenging for me because I led a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">sedentary lifestyle</strong>. I just sat in\nfront of my computer every day to complete my assignments. But after a few days of suffering\nfrom muscle aches, I got used to jogging and kept doing it in the evenings.\nWell, I have to say that this sport has helped me a lot in strengthening my physical health as well\nas my mental health. Thanks to jogging, I was able to lose my fat belly and get lean. Now, to be\nhonest, I am quite satisfied with my youthful appearance and trying to maintain it. Also, jogging\nallows me to unwind and enjoy fresh air, and whenever I go jogging I feel like my mind is being\nrefreshed.\nIn the future, I am going to keep doing this to stay healthy and maybe I will try some other sports\ntoo. That’s all!","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"took up this habit","vi":"bắt đầu hình thành thói quen này"},{"en":"sedentary lifestyle","vi":"lối sống ít vận động"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"something you do to keep healthy","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-022","_displayNo":"#022","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Activity","prompt":"Describe something you made yourself.\nYou should say:\nWhat you made.\nWhy you make it.\nHow you make it.\nAnd explain how you felt about it.","answer":"Now, I am going to talk about a cake that I made on my mother’s birthday, which, to be honest, was\nnot very successful. I first learned how to make a cake 2 years ago after buying a cook book from a\nlocal book store.\nThe cake that I made is called Tiramisu, which is a kind of traditional Italian cake. I first tried this\ncake quite a long time ago at a big restaurant in District 1 and I decided that it would be the perfect\ngift to surprise my mother with on her birthday. On the day that I made the cake, I got up quite early\nto buy the necessary ingredients from a supermarket. Everything seemed to be quite OK before I\nmade a mistake in the process. When condensing the whipping cream, I used a porcelain bowl\ninstead of the one made of stainless-steel shown in the instructions. As a result, the cream stayed\nin the liquid form and the whole cake <strong class=\"key-phrase\">turned into a big mess</strong>. Right after that, my mother got home\nand noticed what I was doing. You know, I expected that she would yell at me for the mess I\ncreated, but she smiled and said that she was very happy when seeing my attempt to make her a\nbirthday present by myself.\nI then cleaned up the kitchen and bought her a new dress to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">compensate for</strong> the cake that I ruined.\nWe actually enjoyed the birthday party a lot, and in the future I hope that I will be able to successfully\nmake that kind of cake for her on another birthday.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Activity","phrases":[{"en":"turned into a big mess","vi":"trở thành một mớ hỗn độn"},{"en":"compensate for","vi":"bù đắp cho"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"something you made yourself","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-023","_displayNo":"#023","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Event","prompt":"Describe a family celebration that you remember.\nYou should say:\n- what you were celebrating\n- who was present\n- what you and your family did to make the celebration special\n- and why you enjoyed the occasion.","answer":"I am going to describe my sister’s wedding day, which took place a few years ago in the town where I grew up. For my sister it was the biggest and most important day of her life. I think there were around 100 people at the marriage ceremony, which was held in a church. Even more people came to the party, or the wedding reception as we call it, after the ceremony. Of course, most members of my family were there, as well as the groom’s family and a collection of the bride and groom's friends and colleagues. To make the celebration special, we did what families normally do. My mother made sure that the church and the reception venue were nicely decorated - there were flowers everywhere! Obviously we all <strong class=\"key-phrase\">dressed for the occasion</strong>, and there were bridesmaids, gifts, a huge wedding cake, and so on. I enjoyed the occasion because it was great to see my sister so happy <strong class=\"key-phrase\">on her big day</strong>. The ceremony was perfect, and we all had a fantastic time at the reception. It’s rare for me to see all of my family and friends together in one place, so that’s probably what <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made the day so memorable</strong> for me.","author":"Simon","topic":"Event","phrases":[{"en":"dressed for the occasion","vi":"ăn mặc phù hợp với dịp đặc biệt"},{"en":"on her big day","vi":"trong ngày trọng đại của cô ấy"},{"en":"made the day so memorable","vi":"khiến ngày hôm đó trở nên đáng nhớ"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a family celebration that you remember","id":"speaking-part-2-024","_displayNo":"#024","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Event","prompt":"Describe a positive experience that you had as a teenager.\nYou should say:\n- what the positive experience was\n- where you were\n- who you were with\n- and explain why you found the experience positive.","answer":"I am going to describe the first time I visited England’s capital city, London, on a school trip when I was a teenager. I had never been to London before, and it was great to share that experience with my school friends. The positive experience was not confined to one particular place in London. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">As far as I remember</strong>, I enjoyed the whole trip, from the coach journey to the visits to various tourist attractions. We got off the coach near the Houses of Parliament, and so one of my first memories was seeing the famous ’Big Ben’ clock tower. We also visited the Tower of London, Buckingham Palace and Trafalgar Square. As I said earlier, it was a school trip, and I think there were around thirty of us, including two teachers. I was with a group of close friends, which <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made the experience more enjoyable</strong>. What really struck me about London was that it was historic but modern and thriving at the same time. It seemed to me to be a lively, fashionable and cosmopolitan place. Coming from a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">relatively small</strong> town, the experience made me keen to visit more capital cities in the future.","author":"Simon","topic":"Event","phrases":[{"en":"As far as I remember","vi":"theo như tôi nhớ"},{"en":"made the experience more enjoyable","vi":"khiến trải nghiệm thú vị hơn"},{"en":"relatively small","vi":"tương đối nhỏ"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a positive experience that you had as a teenager","id":"speaking-part-2-025","_displayNo":"#025","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Event","prompt":"Describe a happy family event that you remember well\nYou should say:\nwhat the event was\nwhen and where it happened\nWhat you saw or did\nand explain why you remember this event so well.","answer":"Well, this is a very nice topic for me and I would love to talk about one of my most memorable\nchildhood events that I had with my family. The celebration was to welcome a new member to our\nfamily, the birth of my nephew. My eldest sister gave birth to a beautiful and healthy baby boy\nand he was the first grandchild of my parents.\nAfter seeing the newborn baby for the first time, my father declared that this was a really special\noccasion and that we must celebrate to welcome the newest member into our family. So we all\ngot to work straight away organising and planning for the party, my parents <strong class=\"key-phrase\">set out</strong> to invite all\nthe guests and do the necessary shopping while my grandmother and sister cooked a lot of\ndelicious food.\nI was so happy and excited that when the gorgeous baby arrived, I did not leave his side. I wanted\nto be near him and play with him all the time but he was still so small that he couldn’t play with\nany of the toys I had given him. But it did not really matter because I could just stare at his cute face\nall day long anyway.\nIt really was a day full of happiness, amazement and celebration. The arrival of a beautiful baby\ninto the family had brought us all together. Many friends and relatives turned up for the occasion,\nand it was definitely a very happy event for our whole family, close friends and relatives.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Event","phrases":[{"en":"set out","vi":"bắt đầu thực hiện; lên đường"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a happy family event that you remember well","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-026","_displayNo":"#026","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Event","prompt":"Describe a recent happy event\nYou should say:\nwhat it was\nwhen and where it happened\nwho is involved\nAnd explain why it was happy.","answer":"I would like to talk about a special wedding that I recently attended, which was my brother’s\nwedding, which is possibly one of the happiest events in my entire life. It was only 2 months\nago and I still remember that day rather clearly.\nMy brother, who is my only sibling, decided to get married in the summer of 2017. And since\nmy brother’s fiancée is a Catholic, the wedding was a combination of both catholic and\ntraditional Vietnamese style. Because we were on the groom’s side, my family and I had to\nwake up early to follow my brother to his bride’s house. There my brother would ask for\npermission from his future parents-in-law to allow him to take their daughter to her new\nfamily. After getting the acceptance, both the bride and groom and all the guests headed to a\nfancy restaurant, where the wedding ceremony was celebrated. I remembered how well the\nentire room was decorated with sparkling light bulbs and purple ribbons, which was the bride’s\nfavourite colour. During the whole ceremony, myself and other guests witnessed the bride\nand groom <strong class=\"key-phrase\">exchanging vows</strong> with each other and this was indeed an unforgettable moment.\nAlso, this marriage was special for me in another sense, being that it was the first wedding I\nhad had the chance to be a part of, which really made the whole event a once-in-a-life-time\nexperience. It was really great to be able to see and feel the passionate love the couple had\nfor each other, through the way they looked at each other and the through the way they\nexpressed their vows. And finally, the wedding was carried out with a smooth and peaceful\natmosphere and I think that all the guests really had a great time attending this sacred\noccasion.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Event","phrases":[{"en":"exchanging vows","vi":"trao lời thề nguyện"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a recent happy event","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-027","_displayNo":"#027","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Event","prompt":"Describe an experience where you were late for an event\nYou should say:\n- When did this happen.\n- Why were you late.\n- What consequence have you caused.\n- How you felt afterwards.","answer":"I am an organised person and tardiness is not my problem. But I'd be lying if I told you that I am\nnever late.\nAs a matter of fact, there was a time that I was not on time for the job interview. It was just a couple\nof months ago when I was in search of a new part-time job to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">gain experience in</strong> my career. There\nwas a position in a company whose job description perfectly suited my needs and qualifications. I\ntruly wanted to get the job. I completed an application form online right after I was informed there\nwas a vacancy. To my surprise, just a day after that, they called me for an interview at 9 the next\nmorning. I was exhilarated to hear the news and prepared everything carefully the night before\nthe meeting. I chose what to wear, ironed the set of clothes to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">leave a good impression</strong> on the\ninterviewer, I also put a notebook and a pen in my purse in case I had to take notes during the\ninterview.\nWhen everything was done, I set the alarm at 7am so that I wouldn’t rush having breakfast and\nheaded to the firm. However, the problem was that I forgot to charge to phone and it ran out of\nbattery during my sleep. Therefore, it did not go off the next morning. I overslept and woke up at\n9am in frustration. I decided that I would rather stay at home than appear as an irresponsible latecomer\nin the eye of others. I did wonder if I should ask them to postpone the interview, but I couldn’t\nthink of a reasonable excuse, so I just let it go. The consequence was that I missed the chance to\ndo the job that I desperately wanted. I felt ashamed of myself for making such a silly mistake, but\nI did learn from it. I am now much more careful when it comes to similar situations.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Event","phrases":[{"en":"gain experience in","vi":"tích lũy kinh nghiệm trong"},{"en":"leave a good impression","vi":"để lại ấn tượng tốt"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an experience where you were late for an event","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-028","_displayNo":"#028","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Event","prompt":"Describe an important event that you celebrated\nYou should say:\n- What it was\n- Where it happened\n- Why it was important\n- How people felt about it","answer":"I would like to talk about the time I held a birthday party for my younger sister. It was back in 2015\nwhen she passed the university entrance examination with flying colors and immediately got\nadmitted to three top universities in Ho Chi Minh city, which came as a surprise to all of my family.\nTherefore, to mark her <strong class=\"key-phrase\">resounding success</strong> as well as her turning point in life, I celebrated her 18th\nbirthday, just a few days after she received the acceptance letters.\nMoving on to the details, I would say that it was more of a family dinner which only involved my\nown family and some of my sister’s close friends. However, I still tried my best to make it become\none of the most unforgettable events of her life by cooking many kinds of dishes that she adored,\nranging from Bun Cha to Pho, all of which were Vietnamese specialties. On top of that, I also\ninvited a music band to perform many of her favorite songs, which made the atmosphere at that\nparticular moment become cozier than ever before. In the end, we sang the birthday song when\nmy sister cut the cake. We congratulated her and wished her a successful college life ahead. Then\nwe ate cake and had a good feast together.\nAfter the party, my sister came to me and said that was the best birthday party she had ever had\nin her life. My parents at that time also felt moved because the bond between us was strengthened\na lot.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Event","phrases":[{"en":"resounding success","vi":"thành công vang dội"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an important event that you celebrated","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-029","_displayNo":"#029","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Event","prompt":"Describe an interesting event\nYou should say:\nWhat the event was\nHow you knew about this event\nWhy it was so interesting\nAnd explain your feelings towards this event.","answer":"Well, the event that I want to share with you today is my best friend’s wedding, which took place\n3 weeks ago and left a deep impression on me. I received a phone call from her last month and\nshe told me that she was going to be tying the knot soon, and to be honest, I had been waiting for\nthis to happen for quite a long time since both the bride and groom are close friends of mine, and\nI know them quite well. And since they are such close friends of mine, I knew that I would have to\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">take part in</strong> this special occasion at all costs.\nSo there were several things that made her wedding such a wonderful day. Firstly, I was quite\nimpressed by the way the room was decorated with lots of lights, candles and roses, which really\ncreated a cosy and romantic atmosphere. Secondly, the wedding was held in quite a modern way,\nwhich I found really great as I had only previously been to more traditional kind of weddings\nbefore.\nOne of the moments that really surprised me though was when the groom got up and sang a song\nfor the bride and all the guests sang along with him. Many people even got up to dance. He also\nplayed a video clip of himself that he had made where he expressed his love and appreciation for\nhis bride, which was very touching, and I think I even shed a tear.\nAnd the last thing I really enjoyed about being involved in the wedding was that it gave me the\nchance to meet many of my friends who I had not seen for a long time. We made use of this\nopportunity to take a lot of photos with one another and the newly-weds, of course.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Event","phrases":[{"en":"take part in","vi":"tham gia"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an interesting event","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-030","_displayNo":"#030","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Event","prompt":"Describe an occasion where somebody gave you positive suggestions.\nYou should say:\n- When you received\n- Who gave you the suggestions\n- What you did\n- Why the suggestions were positive/how you felt.","answer":"Today I would like to talk about an occasion that I received positive suggestions from my friend\nabout how to overcome procrastination.\nIt was about 3 years ago, when I was a senior student in my university. It was right before my\ndissertation. I used to have a serious procrastination problem as my <strong class=\"key-phrase\">word document</strong> was still blank\neven though it was only a month before the due date. In fact, I was not worried at all because I\nwas overconfident that I would eventually complete it no matter what happened. If this went on,\nI would probably have failed my dissertation.\nFortunately, my best friend that was in the same group as me (something I found really frustrating)\ndid not give up on me. He suggested that we could divide the dissertation into small projects and\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">set a deadline</strong> for each one. I did exactly what he advised and submitted my work successfully. As\na result, I graduated with flying colors. Now that I work, I also follow this procedure, which turned\nout to be quite useful. I feel grateful to his suggestion as, without it, my life would have followed\na different path and it would not be a better one.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Event","phrases":[{"en":"word document","vi":"tệp văn bản Word"},{"en":"set a deadline","vi":"đặt thời hạn"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an occasion where somebody gave you positive suggestions","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-031","_displayNo":"#031","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Event","prompt":"Describe an outdoor meal or picnic that you had\nYou should say:\n- Where it took place\n- What was the occasion\n- What you ate and drank there\nAnd explain whether you enjoyed it or not","answer":"I am going to talk about my 18th birthday party, which is one of the most memorable events in my\nlife.\nAt that time, one of my friends had decided to study abroad, and therefore, I wanted to throw a\nparty to celebrate my birthday and give her a farewell party as well, so I came up with the idea to\nhave a barbecue party in my backyard. After about 2 hours of preparing all the ingredients, the\nmeal was finally ready, and we all <strong class=\"key-phrase\">wolfed the food down</strong> quickly because we were so starving and\nbecause it was so scrumptious!\nAfter that, we enjoyed some cupcakes for dessert and talked. I was really impressed by the idea\nof one of my besties, who said that she really had a strong passion to run a café, and we talked\nabout it for 3 or 4 hours.\nIf you ask me about my feelings of that day, I would say that it was such a memorable time and I\ncherish all the memories they gave me from that party. I realised that we have all <strong class=\"key-phrase\">come of age</strong>\nsince then, and we all have our own paths to follow, so maybe we will never get another chance\nto hold a party like that again. Therefore, I have always <strong class=\"key-phrase\">attached a lot of importance to</strong> that day\nand consider it to be a symbol of our <strong class=\"key-phrase\">long lasting friendship</strong>.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Event","phrases":[{"en":"wolfed the food down","vi":"ăn ngấu nghiến"},{"en":"come of age","vi":"trưởng thành"},{"en":"attached a lot of importance to","vi":"coi trọng rất nhiều"},{"en":"long lasting friendship","vi":"tình bạn lâu bền"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an outdoor meal or picnic that you had","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-032","_displayNo":"#032","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Event","prompt":"Describe an unforgettable dinner\nYou should say:\n- When was the dinner.\n- Where was the dinner.\n- Who did you dine with.\n- Why is it unforgettable.","answer":"I would like to talk about an evening meal that I will never forget.\nIt was last summer when my boyfriend invited me to meet his parents. I was so excited yet nervous\nat the same time. He was my classmate back in high school, so I had met his mother several times\nbefore but not in a role of his girlfriend. I chose to have dinner on a weekday, the 10th of the month\nto be exact because it was the date that we started dating. His parents would be home at about\n6pm after their work, so it was perfect time to have dinner.\nAt first, we decided to go out for dinner but, on the second thought, a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">home-cooked meal</strong> would\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">leave a good impression</strong> on his parents so we decided to do that. It turned out to be a stupid\ndecision because I did not know how to cook at all. After hours searching for recipes on Google and\nwatch some cooking channels on Youtube, I managed to pick olive salad and roasted chicken,\nwhich I thought couldn’t be messed up. In the meanwhile, my boyfriend was setting up tables and\nlights on the veranda to create a warm atmosphere.\nFinally, as everything had just been finished, his parents came back home. We greeted and sat\ndown together in a small round table. It was awkward for the first few minutes because I did not\nknow what to say. However, in the middle of the meal, his parents paid me a compliment on the\ndishes I cooked and told me some secrets about my boyfriend’s childhood that eased my tension.\nHis mother and I were on the same page and could talk for hours about any of the conversation\ntopics. Admittedly, the food was not a great success. It was a bit salty and poorly decorated but\nwe had great time talking. This moment really helped <strong class=\"key-phrase\">strengthen our relationship</strong> by making me\nfeel like a member of his family.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Event","phrases":[{"en":"home-cooked meal","vi":"bữa ăn nấu tại nhà"},{"en":"leave a good impression","vi":"để lại ấn tượng tốt"},{"en":"strengthen our relationship","vi":"củng cố mối quan hệ"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an unforgettable dinner","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-033","_displayNo":"#033","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Event","prompt":"Describe an unusual dinner that you had\nYou should say:\n- When you had this dinner\n- Who you had it with\n- What dishes you had\n- And explain why you think this dinner was unusual","answer":"Well, my family usually enjoys our dinner at home with simple and traditional dishes, but there\nwas an occasion we had a very special meal together in a fancy restaurant.\nIt was around 3 years ago when I was tied up in revision for my final examination. After that high-\npressure time, I passed the exam with flying colors so my father decided <strong class=\"key-phrase\">to ease my mind</strong> by taking\nthe whole family to a Western restaurant for enjoying a cozy meal together.\nThat dinner was a little unusual to my family because we had never eaten in such a luxurious\nrestaurant, so my mother and I were very surprised at that time.\nThis French restaurant is located in downtown Ho Chi Minh City. Because it is situated in a well-\ntrodden area, this restaurant welcomes hundreds of guests every night. The food here, therefore,\nwas not very budget-friendly. Actually, it cost my family an arm and a leg, which made this dinner\neven more special to me. Even though my father is not the kind of person who makes a killing, he\nwas still willing to take my mother and me to such a restaurant as a reward for my hard work. So I\nreally appreciated him for that.\nI really enjoyed this dinner because it really helped me <strong class=\"key-phrase\">to relieve everyday stress</strong> and chill out after\nlong hard-working days. Besides, this unusual meal was also a very good chance for us to\nstrengthen our family bond because we all have been so busy for a long time.\nIn the future I will try to earn a lot of money to take my family to wonderful places like this to try\ndifferent cuisines and outstanding dishes, like lobster, abalone and salmon.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Event","phrases":[{"en":"to ease my mind","vi":"giúp tôi bớt lo lắng"},{"en":"to relieve everyday stress","vi":"giải tỏa căng thẳng hằng ngày"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an unusual dinner that you had","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-034","_displayNo":"#034","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Event","prompt":"Describe what you would do if you had a day off.\nYou should say:\n- What would you do?\n- Who would you do it with?\n- Why would you like to do it?","answer":"I would like to talk about what I would do if I had a day off. Actually, I have not been able to rest\nproperly lately, so I am desperately longing for a day off to completely recharge my energy.\nIf I had such a day, the first thing I would do is turn off my phone, so that I was uncontactable and\nno work could bother me. I wouldn’t even bother to call my bestie, since I want to totally shut\nmyself off from everything and just laze around at home. Let’s see, there are so many things I want\nto <strong class=\"key-phrase\">catch up on</strong>, like reading a book and my favourite TV series. I guess I would probably spend the\nmorning binge-watching the latest season of Master Chef. In the afternoon, I would <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take a walk</strong>\nin the park nearby. To be honest, I have moved into a new apartment a few months ago, but have\nnever had a chance to visit the park. That’s why I am thinking it would be nice to check it out when\nI am free.\nThere is no specific reason why I want to stay home on my day off. I simply feel that I am in serious\nneed of some time for myself. Too much socializing and working really tires me out, so I want to\nforget about all of that for a while. Of course, I believe this will help me regain my stamina and\nboost my productivity. That’s the end of my answer.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Event","phrases":[{"en":"catch up on","vi":"cập nhật phần đã bỏ lỡ"},{"en":"take a walk","vi":"đi dạo"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"what you would do if you had a day off","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-035","_displayNo":"#035","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Event","prompt":"Describe what you would do if you were given a day off\nYou should say:\nwhat you would like to do\nwho you would like to be with\nwhere you would like to do it\nAnd explain how you would feel at the end of the day.","answer":"So I am going to share with you an activity that I would love to do if I had a day off; and that is to\nspend my entire day participating in various outdoor activities, in order to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">relieve some stress</strong> and\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">recharge my batteries</strong>. I have been making some plans of a number of things that I would like to do\nwhen I get the chance, such as hiking or cycling in a mountainous area, and paying a visit to some\nhistorical places.\nSo, if I had a day off, I would like to spend it with my best friend, Lan. She loves travelling and\ndiscovering new places as well, and she knows basic first aid and how to survive if we were to\never get lost, so I think that she would be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the perfect partner to go with</strong>.\nNinh Binh province is my hometown so I would like to go there on my free day, and although I was\nborn and brought up there, I have not finished travelling through this massive mountainous\nprovince. Having numerous tourist attractions, Ninh Binh would enable me and my friend to enjoy\nthe fresh atmosphere, go hiking and visit various places, for example, the Stone Church and Hoa\nLu Palace.\nI have been suffering from quite <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a heavy workload</strong> in my job recently, so I am really in need of a day\noff that would allow me some time to do my favourite activities, making me feel more excited and\nhappier with my life.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Event","phrases":[{"en":"relieve some stress","vi":"giải tỏa căng thẳng"},{"en":"recharge my batteries","vi":"nạp lại năng lượng"},{"en":"the perfect partner to go with","vi":"người đồng hành lý tưởng"},{"en":"a heavy workload","vi":"khối lượng công việc lớn"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"what you would do if you were given a day off","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-036","_displayNo":"#036","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a book that you enjoyed reading because it made you think deeply\nYou should say:\n- what this book was\n- why you decided to read it\n- what reading this book made you think about\n- and explain why you enjoyed reading this book.","answer":"I am going to talk about a book that really <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made me think</strong>, and that has had <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a positive effect</strong> on my life. The name of the book is ’Atomic Habits’, and it’s about the compounding effect that small decisions and minuscule changes can have on people’s lives. I decided to read Atomic Habits after seeing an interview with the book’s author, James Clear, who is a world-renowned expert in the field of habit formation. In the interview, he told inspiring stories and revealed some simple life hacks that can make people more productive, motivated and happy. I found the whole idea of the ’science of tiny habits’ fascinating, and so I bought the book straight away. While reading the book, I was forced to confront my own habits and behaviours. I realised that I am nowhere near as productive as I could be, but that some small tweaks to my routine could make a significant and long-lasting difference. The book also gave me a framework to understand how good habits are formed and how bad habits can be broken. It has encouraged me to analyse my own habits accordingly. I thoroughly enjoyed reading Atomic Habits because I thought it was well researched, well reasoned and well written. The author’s ideas and advice are not simply his opinions; they are taken from cutting-edge research and real success stories. I enjoy reading books that change my way of thinking in some way or give me practical, life-altering ideas, and this was definitely one of those books.","author":"Simon","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"made me think","vi":"khiến tôi suy nghĩ"},{"en":"a positive effect","vi":"một tác động tích cực"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a book that you enjoyed reading because you had to think a","id":"speaking-part-2-037","_displayNo":"#037","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a film that you would like to see in the future.\nYou should say:\n- what the film is called\n- what it is about\n- how you heard about this film\n- and why you would like to see it.","answer":"I am going to talk about a film that I would like to see when it comes out later this year. It’s the new James Bond film, and I saw in the news that it’s going to be called ’Spectre’. I think ’Spectre’ refers to the name of the imaginary criminal organisation that James Bond has to defeat in the film. As ’Spectre’ has not been released yet, I do not know exactly what it will be about. But I can guess that the hero, Bond, is going to be on a mission to save the world from an arch-criminal as usual. I am sure it will be similar to most of the previous Bond films, with a plot line involving lots of twists and turns, and with Bond using his skills to defeat his nemesis in the end. I first heard about this film when I was watching the news a couple of months ago, and since then I have seen the official trailer on TV. There have also been various articles in newspapers discussing the actors who have been cast to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">play supporting roles in</strong> the film. The James Bond films are always big news here in the UK, probably because Bond himself is an English character. I would like to see ’Spectre’ at the cinema because I am sure it will be full of action scenes and special effects, and I like the fact that Bond’s missions always take place in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">spectacular locations</strong> in different parts of the world. Of course Bond films are totally unrealistic, you could even say ridiculous. But they're always fast, entertaining and fun, a bit like a roller-coaster ride!","author":"Simon","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"play supporting roles in","vi":"đóng vai trò hỗ trợ trong"},{"en":"spectacular locations","vi":"những địa điểm ngoạn mục"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a film that you would like to see in the future","id":"speaking-part-2-038","_displayNo":"#038","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a photograph of you that you like.\nYou should say:\n- where the photo was taken\n- what you were doing when it was taken\n- who took it\n- and explain why you like the photo.","answer":"The photograph that immediately <strong class=\"key-phrase\">comes to mind</strong> when I think of one that I like is my university graduation photo. It was taken just before the graduation ceremony that marked the end of my undergraduate degree. You cannot see anything in the background of the photo, but it was actually taken in the students’ cafe next to the hall where the ceremony was held. In the photo, I am wearing the traditional clothing for university graduates: a black gown and an academic cap, which is often called a mortar board. I am also holding my rolled-up degree certificate. Obviously this was a formal portrait photo, and so I was standing still, smiling and looking into the camera. The person who took the photo was a professional photographer. He had been hired by the university to set up in the cafe and take photos of graduates before the ceremony. He had a white screen, some lighting devices, and an assistant who took payments and collected our details. The reason why I like my graduation photo is that it reminds me of a pivotal moment in my life. Being presented with my degree certificate at the graduation ceremony was the culmination of four years of hard work, and it marked the end of the ’education’ stage of my life. I had achieved my objectives and made my family proud, and I knew that the next step was to look for my first proper job. Whenever I look at the photo it brings back happy memories, both of my university days and of the relief and contentment that I felt on my graduation day.","author":"Simon","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"comes to mind","vi":"nảy ra trong đầu; nghĩ đến đầu tiên"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a photograph of you that you like","id":"speaking-part-2-039","_displayNo":"#039","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a piece of clothing that you like wearing.\nYou should say:\n- what the item of clothing is\n- where and when you bought it\n- when you wear it\n- and explain why you like wearing it.","answer":"I am going to describe a coat that I often wear at the moment. The coat is dark blue in colour, and it’s <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made out of</strong> a lightweight, waterproof material, which makes it perfect for wearing at this time of year here in the UK. It also has a detachable hood, which I used yesterday when it was raining, and various pockets on the outside and on the inside. I bought the coat last year at the beginning of autumn when the weather started to get colder. It was easy to buy because I had had the exact same coat before; my old coat was starting to look a bit worn out, so I decided to buy a new version. As I knew which size I needed, I simply went online and found the best offer; I bought it through a shopping website, and it was delivered to my house a few days later. As I said, I am wearing this coat a lot at the moment. It’s my everyday coat for going to work or for when I go out shopping or for any other reason. The reason why I like this coat is that it’s so practical and functional. It’s waterproof and it keeps me warm, but it also comes in handy for carrying things like my phone, wallet, loose change, a pen, and even a notebook; I tend to fill my pockets with whatever I can. It even folds up small enough to fit in my bag when I do not need it.","author":"Simon","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"made out of","vi":"được làm từ"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a piece of clothing that you like wearing","id":"speaking-part-2-040","_displayNo":"#040","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a piece of furniture that you own.\nYou should say:\n- what it is\n- where you bought it\n- how you use it\n- and explain why you like it.","answer":"I'm going to talk about my favourite chair. It's a big, leather armchair that sits in my living room at home, just under my living room window. I didn't actually buy the armchair. One of my friends was moving house and was going to buy some new furniture. I had always liked his leather armchair, so he said I could have it if I managed to move it. The chair wouldn't fit in my car, and it was tricky to get it out of my friend's apartment. I had to hire a small van to take the armchair home. Obviously I use the armchair for sitting! It's my favourite place in the house to relax, read a book, watch TV or even do some work; the chair's arms are quite wide and flat, so my laptop fits nicely on either of them. Last night I fell asleep in my armchair while I was watching a film. The main reasons why I like this piece of furniture are that it's comfortable and it's <strong class=\"key-phrase\">in the perfect position</strong> in my living room. The only drawback might be that I enjoy sitting in the armchair too much, and sometimes I think it makes me lazy!","author":"Simon","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"in the perfect position","vi":"ở vị trí hoàn hảo"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a piece of furniture that you own","id":"speaking-part-2-041","_displayNo":"#041","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a plant, flower or tree that is famous or important\nYou should say:\n- what type of plant, flower or tree it is\n- where it grows or is usually seen\n- how it is used in your country\n- and why it is famous or important","answer":"I am going to talk about oak trees, and I will also describe a famous example called the Major Oak. This enormous tree stands in Sherwood Forest near Nottingham and is thought to be around a thousand years old. I would probably say that it is the most impressive tree I have ever seen.\n\nOak trees are common in England. They grow in woodland, fields, parks and gardens, and their strong timber has traditionally been used for furniture and the structural beams of buildings. I have several pieces of oak furniture at home, so the tree also has a practical connection with everyday life.\n\nThe Major Oak is different because it has been preserved as a landmark rather than cut for timber. Its trunk and branches are exceptionally broad, and visitors can immediately sense its age. I first saw it on a school trip and was struck by the idea that the same living tree had survived through so many periods of history.\n\nIt is also associated with the legend of Robin Hood, who is said to have used it as a meeting place. Whether or not that story is literally true, the Major Oak has become <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a powerful symbol of</strong> English history, strength and continuity.","author":"Simon / ChatGPT","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"a powerful symbol of","vi":"một biểu tượng mạnh mẽ của"}],"source":"IELTS Simon sample completed by ChatGPT after the source extraction was truncated","subtype":"","summary":"a plant, flower or tree that is famous or important","id":"speaking-part-2-042","_displayNo":"#042","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a vehicle you would like to buy in the future.\nYou should say:\n- what kind of vehicle it is\n- what you would use it for\n- and why you would like to buy it.","answer":"I would like to buy my own helicopter. I recently saw a TV programme about someone who flew around in his own helicopter, and I remember thinking that it would be great to have one. The helicopter on the programme was a small, blue, two-seater and it seemed quite easy to fly - that's the kind of thing I'd like to buy. Ideally, I would use my helicopter instead of a car. First, I would need to learn to fly it, but then I would use it to go on short trips or holidays. It would be fantastic to be able to avoid traffic jams, and get everywhere <strong class=\"key-phrase\">in a fraction of the time</strong> it normally takes. I would take friends and family sightseeing, over cities or mountain tops, and maybe I could even use it to do the shopping! The reason I would like to buy a helicopter is that you can park one almost anywhere. You do not need to find a runway or an airport like you would for a plane. So I would be able to park my helicopter in my garden - if I had a bigger garden. Also, I have always been <strong class=\"key-phrase\">intrigued by</strong> those helipads on the tops of tall buildings - I think it would be fun to land on top of a building. A helicopter probably is not a realistic choice of vehicle, but you never know - I might win the lottery!","author":"Simon","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"in a fraction of the time","vi":"chỉ trong một phần nhỏ thời gian thông thường"},{"en":"intrigued by","vi":"bị cuốn hút và tò mò bởi"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a vehicle you would like to buy in the future","id":"speaking-part-2-043","_displayNo":"#043","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"An electronic machine you want to buy\nYou should say:\nWhat it is\nWhen you know this machine\nWhat specific features you want\nAnd explain why you want this machine.","answer":"Today, I am going to talk about the Aqua air-conditioner that I really want to own in the next few\nweeks. This air-conditioner is produced in Vietnam but under the supervision of a big Japanese\ncompany, so I guess the quality should be ok. I first noticed this piece of equipment about 2 weeks\nago. At that time, I was watching a movie on the internet and an advert for this product came on\nthe TV, and I was immediately impressed by its design and functions. I immediately <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made a decision</strong>\nto buy one, since it is summer and the weather is boiling right now. However, there is one major\nproblem: I am running short on money as I have just overspent my monthly budget on a bunch of\nclothes and the price of this air-conditioner is quite high. Maybe I will have to borrow some money\nfrom my mother and then reduce my budget for food in the next few days in order to purchase it.\nTalking about this AC in a bit more detail, it’s designed with the latest technology that minimizes\nthe consumption of electricity that it uses. Besides that, it also has the auto-adjusting function,\nwhich means that it can automatically modify the temperature inside the room in order to reduce\nthe differences with the temperature outside. This is truly a valuable item for me to live with\nthrough the heat of the summer season.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"made a decision","vi":"đưa ra quyết định"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"An electronic machine you want to buy","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-044","_displayNo":"#044","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a book that you would like to read again\nYou should say:\n- What the book was about\n- Why you read it the first place\n- What you learned from this book\nAnd explain why you would like to read it again.","answer":"Okay so I would like to tell you about the book called Harry Potter, which is a fantasy novel,\nwritten by the British author J. K. Rowling. It’s one that I can reread <strong class=\"key-phrase\">time and time again</strong>.\nThe book describes the life of a young wizard named Harry Potter and his two best friends, Ron\nand Hermione. Harry has to struggle to kill the Dark wizard Lord Voldemort, whose aim is to\nbecome immortal and destroy all those who stand in his way of ruling the world.\nThe reason why this book <strong class=\"key-phrase\">comes to mind</strong> is that it is a reminder of my childhood. It was a gift for\nmy birthday from my parents to reward my high score in an exam at school. Up until now, I can\nstill remember clearly how fascinated I was when I received it.\nThanks to this book, I realized that determination and effort play essential roles in achieving my\ngoals. Since then, I have always worked hard to overcome all obstacles and challenges in my life.\nHarry Potter will always be on my to-read list for a number of reasons. Firstly, I have always been\na great admirer of science fiction books so I love the way that the author describes the whole\nmagical world with the magic school, Hogwarts, and the flying brooms. Secondly, reading this book\nnot only helps me to relax after a long day of work or study but also cheers me up whenever I am\nfeeling blue.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"time and time again","vi":"hết lần này đến lần khác"},{"en":"comes to mind","vi":"nảy ra trong đầu; nghĩ đến đầu tiên"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a book that you would like to read again","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-045","_displayNo":"#045","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a comedy TV series that you watch.\nYou should say:\nWhat TV series is it?\nWho are the main characters there?\nDescribe an interesting event from the series.","answer":"I am going to talk about “Who wants to be a millionaire”, one of my favorite TV shows ever.\nAs far as I can remember, it was originally a UK TV Game Show, and it made its first debut in\nVietnam around 10 years ago.\nThis was kind of a quiz show in which contestants have to go through a set of 15 questions with\nincreasing difficulty. The first 5 questions are pretty silly really, and they always give me and my\nfamily a good laugh. Contestants are given 4 lifelines to aid them with difficult questions, and most\nof them are usually used up when the contestant reaches around question 7 or 8. The entire show\nis <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sea of knowledge</strong>. Many questions from different fields are asked, ranging from trivial things\nlike ingredients needed to make cookies to academic stuff like quantum physics and archeology.\nYou know, I am quite a curious man, so back when I was a high school kid, I hardly missed an\nepisode. When the Internet became available in Vietnam, I started to watch the UK and US version\nas well, and knowledge acquired from those shows were really helpful to me in many of my high\nschool knowledge quizzes.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"a sea of knowledge","vi":"một kho kiến thức rộng lớn"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a comedy TV series that you watch","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-046","_displayNo":"#046","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a film that you did not enjoy.\nYou should say:\nWhat the film was\nWhen you watched it\nWho you watched it with\nAnd explain why you did not enjoy this film","answer":"I am going to be talking about the worst movie that I have watched in my entire life. Its name is\n“Deadpool”.\nIt was a sunny Friday morning a year ago when my bestie and I had nothing to do but to wander\naround the city with no specific direction. Suddenly I caught sight of the movie poster for\n“Deadpool” when we were waiting for the traffic light at the intersection. And as you may probably\nguess, we were in the cinema, just 15 minutes after that, with our box of popcorn, ready to enjoy\nthe movie. But in fact, it was one of the worst decisions that I have ever made.\nThe main character is a man whose superhuman ability was activated after being injected with a\nserum to cure his cancer, the movie was full of violence with a lot extreme fighting scenes, blood,\ngruesome torture scenes and an excessive use of bad language. While others, including my friend,\nwere applauding in excitement, I found myself suffering from a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">splitting headache</strong>. In fact, I was\nabout to leave when it was about one-third of the way through the movie, but as my friend kept\ninsisting me to stay, I remained seated, wishing the time would fly faster.\nI supposed Deadpool was not that bad as many youngsters were still fascinated by it, and more\nimportantly it became a success and won many awards. However, it is simply because the movie\nis not my taste and the inhumanity, even to bad people, is something I couldn’t stand. My friend\ntold me its sequel would be released soon, but to me once was enough for my suffering.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"splitting headache","vi":"cơn đau đầu dữ dội"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a film that you did not enjoy","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-047","_displayNo":"#047","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a kind of music or a song\nYou should say:\nWhat kind of music it is\nWhere you usually listen to it\nWhy you like it\nAnd say what kind of mood this music puts you in","answer":"I like to think of myself as a lover of music that is kind of sentimental and romantic. I love to listen\nto many different music genres, but the one that I particularly enjoy the most is ballads. It is the\ngenre that consists of slow tempo, sad vibes and heart-breaking lyrics.\nI usually listen to these kinds of song on my computer or on my MP3 player with my headphones\non, so you can basically see me listening to ballads pretty much all of the time, and just about\nanywhere. I am quite a sensitive guy, so whenever I feel sad, I just turn on my MP3 player and let\nthe melody express my feelings.\nBallads give me <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sense of nostalgia</strong>, and make me remember about wonderful memories from the\npast with special people. Every time a ballad is played, I remember my childhood, the sweet\nmemories and the reckless moments I had with my friends, my ex-lovers and my family. This genre\nis the key that opens up the door to my past. I love it with all of my heart.\nThis music puts me in a sad yet charming mood. I feel sad that the past days are gone and yet I\nwonder about the many future moments I will have with special people. Furthermore, if I fall asleep\nwhile listening to a ballad, I can dream of those memories and feel slightly happy when I wake up.\nIt really has everything that I seek for when it comes to a music genre.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"a sense of nostalgia","vi":"cảm giác hoài niệm"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a kind of music or a song","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-048","_displayNo":"#048","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a movie you would like to watch again.\nYou should say:\nWhat it was about\nWhen and where you watched it\nWho you watched it with\nAnd explain why you would like to watch it again.","answer":"The name of the movie I would like to check out again is Love Rosie, a romantic comedy starring\nSam Claflin and Lily Collins. Actually, it was an adaptation of a book called Where Rainbows End,\nwhich was an Irish best seller back in 2004.\nI remember watching it for the first time in 2014, shortly after it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">hit the big screen</strong>. My movie\nbuddy on that day was no other than my best friend, who was also a movie maniac like me. As we\nwere going through some movie trailers on the internet, Love Rosie caught our attention with its\nstunning cinematography and catchy soundtrack. We quickly booked our tickets and went to the\ncinema hoping the movie wouldn’t disappoint us. Lucky enough, this movie far exceeded our\nexpectations. The plot was about 2 childhood friends who had feelings for each other but kept\nmissing the chance to confess their love. In the end, they found the way back to each other and\ngot married. It was a happy ending, but there were so many heart-breaking scenes that I cried my\neyes out in the cinema.\nAbout why I like it and want to re-watch it, I guess the main reason is the witty dialogue in the\nmovie. The conversation between the main characters is simple, yet at the same time full of life\nlessons. I could relate to many of the words, and would love to watch it again to delve deeper into\nit. That is all I want to share about this movie, thanks for listening.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"hit the big screen","vi":"được công chiếu tại rạp"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a movie you would like to watch again","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-049","_displayNo":"#049","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a photo you have taken\nYou should say:\n- Where you took it.\n- When you took the photo.\n- What/who is in the photo.\n- How you felt about the photo.","answer":"I am going to talk about a photo that I took some years ago when my family went on holiday in\nPhan Thiet beach. The picture captured the memory of a very happy family. This is a priceless\npossession to me and I would like to keep it with me for the rest of my life.\nI have seen it thousands times and still I look at it with an indescribable delight. In the picture,\neveryone was smiling cheerfully. My father’s eyes were sparkling and the corners of his eyes\ncrinkled. To tell the truth, it was very rare to see my father’s smile as he always kept a serious\nfacial expression. Needless to say, my mother was standing next to him with warm happiness\nglowing in her face. My younger brothers and sisters were not really photogenic because they\nwere bursting out laughing for a reason I could not remember clearly.\nIn the back ground, the sun looked like it was gradually receding into the waters below. The sky\nconsisted of an assortment of shades, a blend of reds, oranges and yellows. The water below was\nmirroring this effect. The scene was beautiful.\nI have to admit that I know very little about the technical aspects of camera and to be honest I\ntake photos from my own preference rather than maintaining aspects a professional photographer\nwould do. Though the photo was not professionally shot, it is still the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">most treasured photo</strong> I could\nhave.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"most treasured photo","vi":"bức ảnh quý giá nhất"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a photo you have taken","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-050","_displayNo":"#050","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a piece of artwork that you have seen before.\nYou should say:\nWhere you saw it\nWhat it was about\nWhen you saw it\nAnd explain how you felt about it","answer":"Today I would like to tell you about one of the most well-known paintings in the world, which is\nalso my personal favourite, the portrait of Mona Lisa.\nYou know, the painting was created by Leonardo da Vinci, the famous Italian artist from the 15th\ncentury. When I first saw this painting in one of my high school textbooks, I just <strong class=\"key-phrase\">couldn’t take my\neyes off it</strong> due to some mysterious attractiveness.\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">At first sight</strong>, all I noticed in the painting was a long-haired woman with a friendly smile on her\nface, which was quite round, and she had no eyebrows either. The more I looked at it though, the\nmore I felt like she was actually smiling at me.\nSome people have claimed that Mona Lisa was simply an imaginary character while others have\nbelieved that she was actually Leonardo’s wife. Honestly, it does not really matter to me though\nbecause I think that the Mona Lisa is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a masterpiece that attracts people</strong> with that magical smile.\nThis is also one of the main reasons why I am a fan of the painting.\nIn terms of the actual truths behind this portrait though, I guess we may never know, but I think\nthat secrets make everything <strong class=\"key-phrase\">all the more intriguing</strong>.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"couldn’t take my eyes off it","vi":"không thể rời mắt khỏi bức tranh"},{"en":"at first sight","vi":"ngay từ cái nhìn đầu tiên"},{"en":"a masterpiece that attracts people","vi":"một kiệt tác cuốn hút người xem"},{"en":"all the more intriguing","vi":"càng trở nên hấp dẫn và bí ẩn"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a piece of artwork that you have seen before","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-051","_displayNo":"#051","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a piece of furniture you like. (in your home)\nYou should say:\n- What kind of furniture it is;\n- What it looks like;\n- Who bought it;\n- What the furniture are made of;\n- Why you like the furniture.","answer":"I am going to describe my night lamp, which my father gave me when I had to leave home for\nstudying.\nIt is a medium-sized plastic lamp, maybe twice or three times the size of a teddy bear. It is shaped\nlike a panda, with the socket hidden at the bottom of the lamp and the switch seated neatly on its\nhead. There’s a battery holder beside the socket, so you can always use the battery if you cannot\nfind an outside electrical socket to plug it in.\nIt was the very first time I would been given a night light. I would never used this type of lamp before, so I\nfelt really excited and grateful upon receiving it. My father told me that this lamp could help me\nsleep better. And you know what, it actually worked! The lamp gives out a nice cozy yellow light,\nand I am able to really sleep soundly with it on.\nI have been sleeping with this lamp beside my bed every night since the day I received it, and this\ncute little thing is one of my treasures. I plan to have it with me for a long time, so I am trying to\nkeep it in the best possible condition.\nI really like my night lamp for two reasons, firstly that is a gift which represents for my father’s\nlove for me and I owe him a lot of gratitude. Secondly, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">it also offers me a feeling of</strong> warmth and\ncomfort when having it in my room.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"it also offers me a feeling of","vi":"nó cũng mang lại cho tôi cảm giác"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a piece of furniture you like. (in your home)","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-052","_displayNo":"#052","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a piece of technology (not computer—related) you like to use\nYou should say:\nWhat the technology is\nWhen it was invented\nWhat it is used for\nHow you feel about it","answer":"I consider myself a technophile, so it’s hard for me to live a day without using technological\ndevices, especially my smartphone.\nIt was a present from my parents to congratulate me on my high school graduation four years ago,\nand it has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">come in handy</strong> ever since. It was the latest Android phone at that time with lots of cool\napps and functions, but no one has ever gave me proper instruction on how to use it. I had to\nresort to Google search to explore my phone and troubleshoot its problems when the screen\nsuddenly went black or the application failed to run. My phone is with me most of the time and\neven though I know it’s not good for my eyesight, I cannot help but use it on a daily basis and for\nmore than 6 hours a day. I cannot deny that this multifunctional device has a big influence on my\nlife, both positively and negatively. I no longer need dictionaries, notebooks, a camera, a music\nplayer or a TV because now I can look up new words, take notes, capture photos, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">listen to music</strong>\nand watch films on the screen of my phone.\nIn replacement of a heavy bulky laptop, my <strong class=\"key-phrase\">pocket-sized</strong> phone also allows me to create and edit\ndocuments on the move. On top of that, it saves me a lot of time and money going to stores thanks\nto online shopping and notifications of when there are special offers. However, the drawback is\nthat I am somewhat overdependent on it. If my phone suddenly runs out of battery or I forget it\nat home when I am outside, I may feel vulnerable and lonely. This phone has helped me a lot with\nmy work and study but I am thinking of reducing the time using it for my well-being.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"come in handy","vi":"trở nên hữu ích đúng lúc"},{"en":"listen to music","vi":"nghe nhạc"},{"en":"pocket-sized","vi":"nhỏ gọn vừa túi"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a piece of technology (not computer—related) you like to use","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-053","_displayNo":"#053","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a special cake you had\nYou should say:\nWhat kind of cake it is\nWhen you ate the cake\nWho you ate with\nAnd explain why you think the cake is special","answer":"I would like to talk about <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a special occasion</strong> when a simple cake literally changed my miserable life.\nThat was the time when I had just entered high school, which was 80km away from my hometown\nso I had to rent a flat and live alone near my school. Like many others, I was overwhelmed by the\nnew environment and unable to adapt quickly. As a result, I was living in solitude for the first few\nmonths and had no close friendship with anyone.\nBut then an incident happened. I got sick, like, horribly sick. I couldn’t even walk for 50 metres,\nmuch less go to school. During that time, I was stubborn and stupid enough to believe that my\ncondition would improve simply by waiting for my body to recover itself. As I was too weak to\nattend school, I asked my teacher to give me some days off. After 3 days lying in bed, my condition\nonly seemed to be worse, since most of the time I was sleeping and did not eat anything.\nBut then, at around 3pm that day I received a call from one of my friends. She asked me about my\ncondition and wanted to come over to check me out. When she came, I tried my best to walk\ndownstairs to meet her, and I was surprised when I saw her holding a cake in her hand. It turned\nout that she knew I was in trouble so she made the cake herself and brought it to me in the hope\nof cheering me up. That simple act almost made me cry, and I ate the whole cake with heartfelt\ngratitude for my friend.\nAfter that day my body healed up quickly, maybe it’s because I had finally put something into my\nstomach again. And of course, we became best friends after that moment. Now, even though we\nhave taken different paths, we still <strong class=\"key-phrase\">keep in touch</strong> with each other and regularly share our stories\nand experiences. All in all, I am deeply thankful for having such friendship in my life, all starting\nwith a cake.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"a special occasion","vi":"một dịp đặc biệt"},{"en":"keep in touch","vi":"giữ liên lạc"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a special cake you had","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-054","_displayNo":"#054","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a TV program you enjoy\nYou should say:\nWhat it is\nWhen you watch it\nWho you watch it with\nAnd explain why you like to watch it.","answer":"Well, I would like to talk about “The Walking Dead”, which is an American television drama series\nthat I have recently become crazy about.\nAs you might not know, The Walking Dead is the most popular TV show on air right now and\neverybody across the globe watches it. It portrays the world after a zombie apocalypse, where\nsociety has crumbled and there is no government to take care of the people’s welfare.\nThe show stars many talented and famous actors and actresses. Among them, I believe Andrew\nLincoln, who plays the leading role of a police officer, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">leaves the most significant impression</strong> on\naudiences and myself, mainly because of his outstanding acting skills and the devotion he put\ninto every scene.\nInterestingly enough, my favourite part about this show is the make-up of all the different\nzombies. You know, all the characters are well-designed and have to go through <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an elaborate\nmakeup process</strong> to achieve extremely realistic looks on screen.\nAnd the reason why I am a huge fan of The Walking Dead? Well, it is quite easy to explain. I have\nheld a great interest in Zombie apocalypse’s ever since I was a kid and I even dreamt about living in\none. Apart from that, I think that this series has a very stimulating plot along with many\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">unexpected twists</strong>, which raises great excitement for the viewers.\nI just simply <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cannot get enough of</strong> this show and I cannot wait for the beginning of the next season.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"leaves the most significant impression","vi":"để lại ấn tượng sâu sắc nhất"},{"en":"an elaborate makeup process","vi":"quy trình hóa trang công phu"},{"en":"unexpected twists","vi":"những tình tiết bất ngờ"},{"en":"cannot get enough of","vi":"xem mãi không chán"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a TV program you enjoy","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-055","_displayNo":"#055","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe a TV series you enjoy watching\nYou should say:\nWhat it is\nWhat it’s about\nWhen you first watched it\nAnd explain why you like watching it","answer":"Well, I would like to talk about The Walking Dead, which is an American television drama series I\nhave recently become crazy about.\nAs you might know, The Walking Dead is the most popular TV show on air at the moment and\neverybody across the globe is watching it. It portrays the world after a zombie apocalypse, where\nsociety has crumbled and there is no government anymore to take care of the people’s welfare. I\nfirst watched this series about 3 years ago and I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">immediately fell in love with it</strong>, and since then I have\nbecome really fond of horror movies as well.\nThe show stars many talented and famous actors, which is one of the main reasons why I love this\nseries. Andrew Lincoln is the actor who <strong class=\"key-phrase\">plays the leading role</strong> of a police officer and I think he\nleaves the most significant impression on the audience and me, mainly because of his <strong class=\"key-phrase\">outstanding\nacting skills</strong> and the devotion he puts into every scene.\nInterestingly enough, my favourite part about this show is the make-up of the various kinds of\nzombies, with each and every one of them having to go through <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an elaborate makeup process</strong> to\nachieve the extremely realistic looks they are able to get.\nSo as I was saying earlier, I really have had a great interest in the idea of a Zombie apocalypse ever\nsince I was a kid and I even dreamt of living in one once. But apart from that though, I think that\nthis series has a very stimulating plot and many unexpected twists which raise great suspense and\nexcitement for viewers.\nI just simply <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cannot get enough of this show</strong> and I cannot wait for the opening of the next season.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"immediately fell in love with it","vi":"ngay lập tức yêu thích bộ phim"},{"en":"plays the leading role","vi":"đóng vai chính"},{"en":"outstanding acting skills","vi":"kỹ năng diễn xuất xuất sắc"},{"en":"an elaborate makeup process","vi":"quy trình hóa trang công phu"},{"en":"cannot get enough of this show","vi":"xem bộ phim này mãi không chán"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a TV series you enjoy watching","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-056","_displayNo":"#056","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe an advertisement that you saw or heard or liked\nYou should say:\nWhere you saw or heard it\nWhat kind of advertisement it was\nWhat the content of the advertisement was (or, what product /service was\nadvertised)\nAnd explain how you felt about this advertisement/ why you liked it.","answer":"I would like to tell you about my all-time favorite advert for the paint product - Dulux Easy Clean.\nIt was many years ago when I watched this advert for the first time in the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">commercial break</strong> on\nTV and I have been in love with it ever since.\nThe advert starts with many children messing the walls of their house with color, mud and powder\nand enjoying their world of fun and creation. Then the drama begins when their mother comes back\nhome after a hard day at work. When just as she enters the front door, she comes to realize that\nher baby son is having fun with his crayons and doodling on the newly-painted wall. Unlike what\nviewers might guess what happens, the mother looks at her son, who is acting completely innocently,\nand gives him a big smile. Because the walls are painted with Dulux Easy Clean, all types of dirt\ncan be removed very easily. The advert then ends with a slogan that could be interpreted in two\nways; with Dulux Easy Clean, forgiveness is easy, or, with Dulux Easy Clean, erasing stains is no\nproblem.\nI am so fascinated by this ad for a number of reasons. First, it featured children acting typically –\nplayful, mischievous and innocent, which I find super cute. In fact, I cannot <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take my eyes off</strong> the TV\nscreen whenever this advert comes on, with the appearance of these little angels. Also, the song\nplayed in the advert was “I am sorry” that amazingly matched the content and the acting of the kids.\nOn top of that, it is the catchy slogan that left viewers with the deepest impression and I believe\nthe marketing team was successful in bringing <strong class=\"key-phrase\">brand awareness</strong> to their potential customers.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"commercial break","vi":"khoảng nghỉ quảng cáo"},{"en":"take my eyes off","vi":"rời mắt khỏi"},{"en":"brand awareness","vi":"mức độ nhận biết thương hiệu"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an advertisement that you saw or heard or liked","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-057","_displayNo":"#057","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe an advertisement you have seen recently.\nYou should say:\n- When and where you saw it;\n- What kind of advertisement it was;\n- What the contents of the advertisements were;\n- How you felt about it.","answer":"I'm going to talk about an advertisement for Blue Electronics, which is one of the biggest\nelectronics brands in Vietnam. I've seen its advertisements everywhere, on TV commercials and\neven on social media networks like Facebook and Instagram.\nThe advertisement shows a video of people dressed as blue household appliances, smiling, staring\ncreepily at the screen and dancing spontaneously to a really annoying yet catchy tune. I think the\naim of this ad is to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">create a big impression</strong> on the audience and to make the products seem more\nappealing to them. I also think they are trying to traumatise the audience so that whenever they\nhear that tune, they will think of Blue Electronics. I think the advert is interesting because the\ncompany is deliberately trying to influence and attract people’s attention, and they do this by\ntrying to present the household appliances as something special, and kind of like a useful friend\nfor everyone I guess. I think older people will probably not enjoy these kinds of advertisements\nbecause older people usually prefer more informative, serious kind of ads, whereas the younger\ngeneration seems to be crazier about this kind of advertisement, as I think they are more open and\nable to perceive more innovative and hilarious ideas.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"create a big impression","vi":"tạo ấn tượng mạnh"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an advertisement you have seen recently","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-058","_displayNo":"#058","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe an article you read about healthy life\nYou should say:\nwhere you read it from\nwhen you read it\nwhat the article was about\nAnd explain what you thought about this article","answer":"Today I want to share with you one of my most favourite articles of all time named “Ten ways to\nlive longer”, which was published in the Guardian - a very famous British magazine, and is, in my\nopinion, a must-read article about human health and well-being.\nI believe that the more people become wiser, the more they will care about their health. The first\nsurprising thing I noticed about this article was about the country with the longest life\nexpectancy, which was Japan, for both men and women. The question is, how do they do it? Well,\napparently Japanese people simply have regular health check-ups and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">pay close attention to</strong>\nhygiene in every aspect of their lives. Avoiding a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">sedentary lifestyle</strong> is one of the golden rules of\ngood health, yet this is still a major problem in many countries around the world. In other words,\nget your running shoes on and never just sit around all day. Another major point I learned was that\nyou should get your blood pressure checked regularly because high blood pressure is the number\none factor that leads to early death and years of poor health.\nAccording to the article, the ten things to do or avoid included some things like, not smoking,\neating seeds and not junk, drinking in moderation, staying out of hospital, and not getting\nstressed, which all seem quite obvious but can certainly change your life if you follow these rules.\nYou do not need to do strenuous or vigorous exercise in order to have better health. Simply drink\na little bit less each day, add a little bit more vegetables to your diet and do something as simple\nas carrying your heavy shopping bags instead of using the trolley to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">improve your muscle strength</strong>\nat least two days a week. Sounds easy, right?","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"pay close attention to","vi":"chú ý kỹ đến"},{"en":"sedentary lifestyle","vi":"lối sống ít vận động"},{"en":"improve your muscle strength","vi":"cải thiện sức mạnh cơ bắp"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an article you read about healthy life","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-059","_displayNo":"#059","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe an exciting book you have read.\nYou should say:\n- When you read it;\n- What type/kind of book it is;\n- What it is about;\n- Why you read it /Why it is exciting.","answer":"I would like to tell you about a book called Harry Potter, a fantasy novel, written by the British\nauthor J. K. Rowling. It’s one that I can re-read <strong class=\"key-phrase\">time and time again</strong>.\nThe book describes the adventure and life of a young wizard named Harry Potter and his two best\nfriends, Ron and Hermione. Harry has to struggle to kill the Dark wizard Lord Voldemort, whose\naim is to become immortal and destroy all those who stand in the way of his mission to rule the\nworld.\nThe reason why this book <strong class=\"key-phrase\">comes to mind</strong> is that it is a reminder of my childhood. It was a gift from\nmy mother to reward my achievement at school. Up until now, I can still remember clearly how\nfascinated I was when I received it.\nHarry Potter will always be on my to-read list for a number of reasons. Firstly, I have always been\na great admirer of science fiction books so I love the way that the author describes the whole\nmagical world with the magic school, Hogwarts, and the flying brooms. Secondly, reading this book\nnot only helps me to relax after a long day of work or study but also cheers me up whenever I am\nfeeling blue.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"time and time again","vi":"hết lần này đến lần khác"},{"en":"comes to mind","vi":"nảy ra trong đầu; nghĩ đến đầu tiên"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an exciting book you have read","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-060","_displayNo":"#060","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe an important letter you received.\nYou should say:\n- Who sent the letter;\n- What it is about;\n- Why it is important;\n- How you feel about it.","answer":"I am going to talk about the time when I received the official notification of my scholarship to join\nan exchange program in Japan. It was about three years ago. It feels like a long time ago but I can\nstill remember the day quite vividly.\nAt that time, I was a sophomore at university and one day I came across an advertisement for a\ntwo-month <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cultural exchange program</strong> in Japan for students from Southeast Asia. I was really\neager to apply for this program. Luckily my application was accepted and I was also nominated for\na scholarship.\nSo, about 2 months later, I received the letter from the Scholarship Committee informing me that\nI had been chosen to receive a full scholarship which would cover all kinds of fees and living\nexpenses for me during the program. I think <strong class=\"key-phrase\">my heart skipped a beat</strong> and I screamed out loud\nwhen I saw the word “Congratulations” in that email. I was really proud of myself to be chosen\nfrom hundreds of candidates to win this scholarship.\nIt was definitely the best news of the year. If I had not won the scholarship, my living expenses\nwould have been such a heavy <strong class=\"key-phrase\">financial burden</strong> for my parents, but thanks to the generous grants\nthat I received, I could really enjoy my time in Japan without worrying about the money. To this\nday I still keep this lucky email in my inbox to remind me of that special occasion.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"cultural exchange program","vi":"chương trình trao đổi văn hóa"},{"en":"my heart skipped a beat","vi":"tim tôi như hẫng một nhịp vì xúc động"},{"en":"financial burden","vi":"gánh nặng tài chính"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an important letter you received","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-061","_displayNo":"#061","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe an impressive story you heard from other people\nYou should say:\n- What was this story.\n- When did you hear about it.\n- Who told you this story.\n- Why you were impressed by it.","answer":"I would like to share a funny story that I heard from Julie, a friend of mine, a long time ago. It was\na random day that our group hung out at a coffee shop and sat at the circle table near the window,\nas we usually do. This was our favourite spot. But that day, instead of ordering a cappuccino as I\nusually do, I decided to try a completely new drink – mojito mixed with some fruit, though I cannot\nremember exactly what.\nThe mojito looked good on the outside but its taste was unbearable to me. Despite my warning,\nJulie insisted on trying it. It turned out that she liked the drink very much and in that moment, she\nconcluded that it tasted exactly like the toothpaste that she ate in her childhood. Learning of this\nincident, we were a bit shocked as to why she ate such a thing, so she continued to elaborate on\nher story. She recalled that she indeed thought that the taste of toothpaste was delicious, and\neven she was banned from eating it by her parents, she secretly saved money to buy one for\nherself a few years later. She added that she sneakily hid the tube in the room and she could finish\nthe whole thing in one go. We were frozen and all eyes were on her for a few seconds. Then we\nall <strong class=\"key-phrase\">burst into laughter</strong>. I still remember laughing so hard that my tears ran down.\nI was indeed impressed by her story. As the matter of fact, it was not the first time I had heard of\nsomeone enjoying eating toothpaste, but secretly saving money to do this was a surprise element\nand it was hilarious. And of course, it has become an inside joke between us since then.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"burst into laughter","vi":"bật cười"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an impressive story you heard from other people","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-062","_displayNo":"#062","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe an interesting advertisement\nYou should say:\nWhere you saw it\nWhat it’s about\nWhy you think it was an interesting advertisement","answer":"So I'm going to talk about an advertisement for Blue Electronics, which is one of the biggest\nelectronic brands in Vietnam. I've seen its advertisements everywhere, on TV commercials and\neven on social media networks like Facebook and Instagram.\nThe advertisement shows a video of people dressed as blue household appliances, smiling and\nstaring creepily at the screen and dancing spontaneously to a really annoying yet catchy tune.\nI think the aim of this ad is to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">create a big impression</strong> on the audience and to make the products\nseem more appealing to them. I also think they are trying to traumatize the audience so that\nwhenever they hear that tune, they will think of Blue Electronics.\nI think the advert is interesting because the company is deliberately trying to influence and\nattract people’s attention, and they do this by trying to present the household appliances as\nsomething special, and kind of like a useful friend for everyone I guess.\nI think older people will probably not enjoy these kinds of advertisements because older people\nusually prefer more informative, serious kind of ads, whereas the younger generation seems to be\nmore crazy about this kind of advertisement, as I think they seem to be more open and able to\nperceive more innovative and hilarious ideas.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"create a big impression","vi":"tạo ấn tượng mạnh"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an interesting advertisement","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-063","_displayNo":"#063","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe an interesting song you like\nYou should say:\nWhat it is\nWhich country the song comes from\nWhat story the song tells\nAnd explain why you think it is interesting.","answer":"One of my favorite songs is “Bonjour Vietnam”, a song composed and sung by Pham Quynh Anh\n- A French woman with Vietnamese origins. Though this song was released years ago, I still keep\nit in my “favorite” playlist on my phone.\nI first came across this song when it was discussed all over the media during my secondary school\nyears. You see, it’s really rare for such a beautiful song to be written about Vietnam, or the\nVietnamese identity for that matter. It’s about a Vietnamese expat desperately wanting to learn\nmore about her <strong class=\"key-phrase\">Vietnamese roots</strong>. She also wanted to go to Vietnam someday to know for herself\nwhether it was like what her parents and the media portrayed or not.\nTo be honest, the first time I heard this song, I did not understand a word but I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">was hooked by</strong> the\ngentle melody and the silky voice of the singer. I was later motivated to learn French to know the\nexact meaning of the lyrics. When I understood, it was all the more beautiful. I realized there was\nstill so much more to discover and love about my country. You could say my love for the beauty\nof Vietnam <strong class=\"key-phrase\">was rekindled</strong>.\nI really wish more quality songs like this can be produced in the future instead of the meaningless\nones that young generations are so obsessed with.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"Vietnamese roots","vi":"cội nguồn Việt Nam"},{"en":"was hooked by","vi":"bị cuốn hút ngay bởi"},{"en":"was rekindled","vi":"được khơi dậy trở lại"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an interesting song you like","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-064","_displayNo":"#064","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe an invention that changed people’s lives\nYou should say:\nWhat it was\nWho invented it\nWhen it was invented\nAnd explain how it changed people’s lives","answer":"I would like to talk about the telephone which, in my opinion, is one of the most revolutionary\ncreations that has changed our lives.\nAs far as I know, Alexander Graham Bell was the father of this terrific device and he invented it in\nthe last century <strong class=\"key-phrase\">through a lot of trial and error</strong>.\nIt is no exaggeration to say that human life has completely changed since the first telephone was\ndevised. A few centuries ago people could only communicate long distances through writing\nletters, which could <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take ages to be delivered</strong>. And in the case of emergencies or confidential\ninformation, writing letters really was not an effective way of communicating.\nSo, one of the main reasons that I believe that the telephone has changed people’s lives is simply\nby making communication between people so much faster, easier and more convenient than ever\nbefore. These days when you need to get in contact with somebody, all you need to do is pick up\nyour phone, dial a few numbers and wait for them to answer. And if they do not answer, then you\ncan usually just leave a voice message for them to let them know what it is you wanted to tell\nthem.\nFurthermore, I believe that communication is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">at the core of social development</strong>, and I think that\nthe advent of the telephone has made a great contribution to this area of life.\nSo, whether the information is urgent, confidential, or even down right unnecessary, I think that\nthe telephone has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made a massive difference to people’s lives</strong> and our societies as well.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"through a lot of trial and error","vi":"qua nhiều lần thử nghiệm và điều chỉnh"},{"en":"take ages to be delivered","vi":"mất rất lâu mới được chuyển tới"},{"en":"at the core of social development","vi":"đóng vai trò cốt lõi trong sự phát triển xã hội"},{"en":"made a massive difference to people’s lives","vi":"tạo ra thay đổi rất lớn trong cuộc sống con người"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an invention that changed people’s lives","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-065","_displayNo":"#065","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe something you bought according to an advertisement you saw.\nYou should say:\n- What it is;\n- When and where you see the advertisement;\n- Why you want to buy it;\n- How you feel about it.","answer":"About a couple of months ago I saw an advertisement on the internet for a special pair of running\nshoes. It was the picture that caught my attention first because the shoes looked very different\nfrom normal running shoes.\nThey were made from a special material and had a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">synthetic sole</strong> grafted onto the body so that\nthey fit like a glove on my foot. The bottom was quite similar to a normal running shoe so that it\ngripped well and provided protection for your feet.\nSpeaking of the advertisement, there was also a video that was maybe 3 or 4 minutes long and\nshowed a runner going up a rocky hill. The video explained how these running shoes allowed the\nrunner to feel more of the ground underneath his feet and grip better because of the flexing\nmotion of the bottom of the shoes.\nIt was more an informative ad than anything arty or creative, but it made me want to buy the shoes\nbecause I hadn't seen them before and I wanted to try them, so I ordered a pair in my size. I've\ntried them out a couple of times so far and they seem really good. They cost me just a little bit\nmore than some of the normal running shoes, but I think they're worth the extra money. The\nrunning experience is quite different from normal, personally, I prefer it.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"synthetic sole","vi":"đế giày tổng hợp"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"something you bought according to an advertisement you saw","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-066","_displayNo":"#066","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe your favorite flower.\nYou should say:\nWhat it is\nWhere it is grown\nIf it is common in your country\nAnd explain why it is your favorite flower.","answer":"Today I am going to talk about one of the most popular kinds of flower in the whole world and also\nmy favorite one, which is the rose. I first learned about this beautiful flower over 20 years ago\nwhen my mother told me about it.\nWith regards to its appearance, roses are a kind of small flower that can be found in almost all\nmarkets and supermarkets around the whole world. Usually, the roots of old rose bushes would\ndig very deep into the ground. The rose stem is small and thin but quite hard to break. From this\npart, a number of leaves grow as the plant starts to reach its maturity. In addition to this, touching\nthe stem of roses can be quite painful sometimes as many rose species have sharp thorns on their\nbody as a tool to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">protect them from predators</strong>. On top of this plant lies a part called the petal, from\nwhich the bud would rise and then turn into a very beautiful flower when the blooming season\narrives.\nIn the past, most roses around the world were only red, but now, thanks to the development of\nagricultural technology, people have been able to create roses in a wide range of colors, such as\npurple, yellow, white and so on. As I mentioned above, this flower is a common favorite on a global\nscale since it has always been considered the symbol of love. Besides that, roses have also been\nmentioned in several literary works, songs and movies.\nAs for myself, I usually give roses as a kind of gift for the people I love on some special days like\ntheir birthdays. Also, I have planted some roses in my garden and hope that in the future, I will be\nable to start my own business selling these flowers.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"protect them from predators","vi":"bảo vệ chúng khỏi động vật săn mồi"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"your favorite flower","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-067","_displayNo":"#067","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Object & Favourite","prompt":"Describe your favourite piece of clothing\nYou should say:\nWhere you got it\nWhen you got it\nHow often you wear it\nAnd explain why it is your favourite piece of clothing.","answer":"Well, I would like to tell you about a pair of ripped jeans that are my favorite item among all the\nthings I have in my wardrobe.\nYou know, I bought them for an unbelievably cheap price a long time ago in a second-hand\nclothing store. At that point, ripped jeans were really popular and everybody in my school was\nkeen on them. So, whenever I put these jeans on, I felt really stylish and thought I really stood out\nfrom the crowd. After a while though, trends started to change, but I refused to abandon my jeans.\nI wore them almost everywhere, from home to school and only changed them for formal events\nsuch as a ceremony or a wedding. Sometimes I even slept in my jeans because they were so\ncomfortable.\nActually, it is quite easy to understand why I fancy these jeans so much. Firstly, they instantly\ncreate a stylish and fashionable look for the wearer. Secondly, jeans are easy to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">mix and match</strong>\nand I can wear them with heaps of different shirts without worrying about looking ridiculous in\nother people’s eyes. And lastly, denim is so tough that it cannot be torn, so I can have them for a\nlong time and save a great deal of money.\nAll in all, I love my jeans and cannot get through a day without them. I think such an item should\nbe made trendy again so that the youngsters nowadays can really get to know their awesomeness.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Object & Favourite","phrases":[{"en":"mix and match","vi":"phối hợp linh hoạt"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"your favourite piece of clothing","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-068","_displayNo":"#068","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Describe a prize that you would like to win.\nYou should say:\n- what the prize is for\n- how you know about it\n- what you would have to do to win it\n- and why you would like to win this prize.","answer":"I am going to talk about a prize that I would like to win, which is the ’employee of the year’ award at the company where I work. At the end of December each year, the company directors give this award to a member of staff who has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made an outstanding contribution</strong> to the business over the previous twelve months. I first heard about this prize during my training and orientation period just after I got the job three years ago. It was early December and some of my colleagues were discussing who might be awarded ’employee of the year’ later that month. I was intrigued, and asked them to tell me more about the award. As I said, the prize is given for ’outstanding contribution to the business’. We do not have an exact definition of what this means, but we assume that you have to achieve certain standards, such as 100% attendance, good punctuality, meeting targets and deadlines, good teamwork, and so on. I think the winner also needs to have done something especially creative. For example, last year’s winner created a completely new service for our clients. I would like to win ’employee of the year’ because it would mean that my work had been recognised by the company directors, and this would definitely help me to progress in my career. It would also give me a great sense of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">personal achievement</strong>.","author":"Simon","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"made an outstanding contribution","vi":"có đóng góp xuất sắc"},{"en":"personal achievement","vi":"thành tích cá nhân"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a prize that you would like to win","id":"speaking-part-2-069","_displayNo":"#069","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Describe a TV programme or channel that you enjoy\nYou should say:\n- What it is called and what is it about?\n- When do you usually watch it\n- Why do you prefer it to other programmes or channels?","answer":"I rarely watch <strong class=\"key-phrase\">traditional television channels</strong> nowadays; I much prefer searching for interesting programmes or videos online. So, although it is not a conventional TV channel, I would like to talk about TED, a website that functions like a modern on-demand channel. TED stands for Technology, Entertainment and Design, and it features short talks on subjects ranging from science and education to health and social change.\n\nThe main advantage is that I can watch the talks whenever I want. I have the website saved on my phone, and I usually check it every few days. I often watch one presentation during my train journey to work because most talks are concise enough to fit into a short commute.\n\nI prefer TED to ordinary television because I learn something useful almost every time. Its slogan, “<strong class=\"key-phrase\">ideas worth spreading</strong>”, captures its appeal perfectly. Instead of spending an hour on a repetitive talk show, I can watch a specialist explain a breakthrough in medicine, a new teaching method or an unfamiliar social issue in ten or fifteen minutes.","author":"Simon","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"traditional television channels","vi":"các kênh truyền hình truyền thống"},{"en":"ideas worth spreading","vi":"những ý tưởng đáng được lan tỏa"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2 — cleaned and restored from the source text","subtype":"","summary":"a TV programme or channel that you enjoy","id":"speaking-part-2-070","_displayNo":"#070","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Describe an educational television programme that you liked.\nYou should say:\n- what the programme was about\n- when and where you saw it\n- how you found out about this programme\n- and why you liked it.","answer":"I am going to talk about one of my favourite educational TV programmes, which is a nature documentary called ’Planet Earth’. There were eleven episodes of this programme, and each one featured a different habitat on Earth, such as mountains, caves, deserts and jungles. The aim of the ’Planet Earth’ series was to take the viewer into those habitats, using <strong class=\"key-phrase\">spectacular footage</strong> of interesting animals, plants and landscapes. I first saw ’Planet Earth’ on television when it was broadcast by the BBC several years ago. I think it was shown every Sunday evening, which was the perfect time to watch a fascinating nature programme. Then, a few years ago, somebody bought me the DVD box set of the whole series as a Christmas present, and I watched the episodes again. I found out about this TV programme because it was advertised repeatedly in the weeks before it was first aired. The TV trailers were really <strong class=\"key-phrase\">eye-catching</strong> because they showed incredibly beautiful images of nature. I also recognised the voice of the narrator of the programme, the well-known naturalist David Attenborough. It was these trailers that persuaded me to watch the first episode. What I liked most about the ’Planet Earth’ series was its <strong class=\"key-phrase\">stunning photography</strong> and its global scope. For example, in the “Fresh Water” episode, they showed us the giant salamander in Japan, crocodiles in the river Nile, and river dolphins in the Amazon. I was amazed at how they had managed to film such interesting creatures in so many locations. I enjoyed learning about strange animal species, and the programme <strong class=\"key-phrase\">opened my eyes to</strong> the hidden wonders of our planet.","author":"Simon","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"spectacular footage","vi":"những thước phim ngoạn mục"},{"en":"eye-catching","vi":"bắt mắt"},{"en":"stunning photography","vi":"hình ảnh quay tuyệt đẹp"},{"en":"opened my eyes to","vi":"mở mang tầm mắt cho tôi về"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"an educational television programme that you liked","id":"speaking-part-2-071","_displayNo":"#071","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Describe a difficult choice that you made.\nYou should say:\nwhat the choice was\nwhen this happened\nwhat choice you made\nAnd explain why the choice was a difficult one.","answer":"So I am going to talk about a situation when I found it really difficult to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make up my mind</strong>. It was\nwhen I was a child, about ten years ago, and my parents were not getting on well with each other,\nwhich made the atmosphere at home really terrible. In the end, they got divorced, but I did not\nknow whom I should go to live with, my mother or my father.\nThat was a really difficult time in life for me because so many things changed, mostly in a negative\nway. I had a difficult time to choose who to live with because I loved both of my parents and we\nhad had many unforgettable memories together. So to solve this matter, our family spent a long\ntime discussing it and deciding on the best option for me.\nFinally, I chose to stay with my mother because she could take better care of me and she needed my\nsupport after the divorce. Though my father felt upset, he agreed with my choice, for my sake. You\nknow, I believe that was not only a tough choice for me but also for my parents as well.\nI always want to live under the same roof as both my parents, so choosing just one person to live\nwith was a hard thing for me. Not being able to see my father every day made me feel sad, so that\nwas one of the toughest choices I have ever had to make.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"make up my mind","vi":"quyết định dứt khoát"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a difficult choice that you made","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-072","_displayNo":"#072","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Describe a foreign food you would like to try.\nYou should say:\nWhat it is\nWhere you can eat it\nHow you know about this food\nAnd explain why you would like to try it","answer":"Today I would like to tell you about crepes, one of the most popular French street foods that I\nhave been <strong class=\"key-phrase\">longing to try</strong>.\nI first became interested in this food after learning about it through a TV program that I watched\nabout a year ago on different cultures around the world. The show gave a really detailed\ndescription of how to prepare this dish, what ingredients are required, the different fillings that\nare used to make different types of crepes, and why this food is so closely related to French\nculture. I was watching with utmost interest and attention and immediately jumped onto my\ncomputer to do some more research about it after the show ended.\nIt’s said that, walking around Paris you can locate street stands selling crepes everywhere and that\nthis dish is a really tasty afternoon snack to indulge in before dinner without ruining your appetite.\nAnd even though it is not that hard to find a crepe shop in Hanoi, I believe the taste cannot be\ncompared to the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">authentic recipe</strong> that only street stands or restaurants in France are capable of\ndelivering.\nSince watching this program, the idea of walking down the street in Paris while enjoying a delicious\ncrepe has been on the top of my wish-list ever since, and I have been saving up money recently\nhoping that I get to fulfil this dream sometime soon.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"longing to try","vi":"mong muốn được thử từ lâu"},{"en":"authentic recipe","vi":"công thức nguyên bản"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a foreign food you would like to try","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-073","_displayNo":"#073","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Describe a historical era you are interested in\nYou should say:\n- When this era was.\n- How you learned about it.\n- What it was famous for.\n- Why you are interested in this era.","answer":"If I could go in a time machine, I would choose to go back to the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">glorious time</strong> of Hong Bang period\nin about 2000 BC, the very first days of my country.\nAt that time, this place was not called Vietnam, it was under the rule of Hung Kings and was named\nVan Lang instead. What I find fascinating about this era is the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">legends and myths</strong> which I learned\nfrom History and Literature class back in school. Van Lang was a small country yet it was frequently\ninvaded by the mysterious people. Whenever this period of time is mentioned, people will\nimmediately relate to hundreds of wars, some even last for decades. We, the descendants, had no\nidea how they could win in those wars due to the sparse population and simple weapons, so we\nmade up stories and fables to honor the bravery of our ancestors. Some specific examples are the\nlegend of a three-year-old boy who went to war to save the country, or the myth of the Magic\nCrossbow which could deliver thousands of arrows and the story of the princess innocently\ntrusting her lover and betraying her father, and the list goes on.\nAlthough some of the stories are imaginary, it left a mark on me and nurtured my love for my home\ncountry since I was a little girl. Moreover, many of modern Vietnamese cultural practices also date\nback to this era, like cooking sticky rice cakes and displaying five-fruit trays on Tet holiday. This\nera can be considered the cradle of our culture. I am always curious about the origin of our\ncustoms, and I believe that going back to this time could provide me with first-hand experience as\nwell as a thorough understanding of my country’s tradition.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"glorious time","vi":"thời kỳ huy hoàng"},{"en":"legends and myths","vi":"truyền thuyết và thần thoại"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a historical era you are interested in","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-074","_displayNo":"#074","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Describe a piece of good news you heard\nYou should say:\nwhat this news was\nwhen and where you heard it\nhow you heard it\nAnd explain why you think it was good news","answer":"I am going to talk about the time when I received the official notification of my scholarship to join\nan exchange program in Japan about three years ago. It feels like a long time ago but I can still\nremember the day quite vividly.\nAt that time, I was a sophomore at university and one day I came across an advertisement for a\ntwo-month <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cultural exchange program</strong> in Japan for students from Southeast Asia. I was really\neager to apply for this program and luckily my application was accepted and I was also nominated\nfor a scholarship.\nSo about 2 months later, I received an email from the Scholarship Committee informing me that I\nhad been chosen to receive a full scholarship which would cover all kinds of fees and living\nexpenses for me during the program. I think <strong class=\"key-phrase\">my heart skipped a beat</strong> and I screamed out loud\nwhen I saw the word “Congratulations” in that email. I was really proud of myself to be chosen\nfrom hundreds of candidates to win this scholarship.\nIt was definitely the best news of the year. If I had not won the scholarship, my living expenses\nwould have been such a heavy <strong class=\"key-phrase\">financial burden</strong> for my parents, but thanks to the generous grants\nthat I received, I could really enjoy my time in Japan without worrying about the money. To this\nday I still keep this lucky email in my inbox to remind me of that special occasion.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"cultural exchange program","vi":"chương trình trao đổi văn hóa"},{"en":"my heart skipped a beat","vi":"tim tôi như hẫng một nhịp vì xúc động"},{"en":"financial burden","vi":"gánh nặng tài chính"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a piece of good news you heard","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-075","_displayNo":"#075","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Describe a success in your life\nYou should say:\nwhen it was\nwhat it was\nwhy you chose it\nhow you achieved.","answer":"Well, the success that I would like to share with you today is about my contribution to a social\nwelfare activity that occurred about 5 years back when I was just a freshman in college. I really\nfeel proud of this achievement as I believe I have done something really good for society.\nAt that time, the local authorities in my hometown had planned to destroy a public park and build\na shopping mall complex instead. I had taken notice of them cutting down the trees so I gathered\nmy friends to protest, though it was a very complicated situation.\nThe reason for me to do that was because that park was the only green space and recreational\narea for the local people. They came there every day to exercise, and enjoy the fresh air in order\nto maintain and improve their health. As well as this, it’s also home to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a large number of</strong> wild birds\nand other animals, which I feel is a very important thing to conserve.\nI know that going against the authorities is a really hard thing to do but I felt that I needed to do\nit for the sake of the community. We made some plans to contact the media and go to the local\nauthorities to express our view and opinion, and in the end, we succeeded and the construction\nof the shopping mall was cancelled, so I feel like this really was a success in my life.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"a large number of","vi":"một số lượng lớn"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a success in your life","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-076","_displayNo":"#076","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Describe a time you felt happy that you used your cellphone.\nYou should say:\n- What you do;\n- When, where you do it;\n- Who you do it with;\n- Why you felt happy using your cell phone.","answer":"I would like to share with you an unforgettable experience: when my mother gave me a smart phone.\nIt was when I took an entrance examination successfully which <strong class=\"key-phrase\">marked a significant milestone</strong> in\nmy life. Therefore, in order to reward my achievement in studying, my mother gave me an Iphone,\nthe most popular smart phone. Everyone across the globe wants to have it.\nAt that time, I can clearly remember how fascinated I was when I received it. I spent most of my\ntime discovering how to use it and it helped me communicate with my friends, family members\nand teachers. It gets me connected with the people I care about. I use the internet on my cell\nphone, check my emails, update my blog, track the statistics of my website, send and receive SMS,\nplay games, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">listen to music</strong> and take pictures, then share them on my Facebook and twitter profiles.\nBesides these I do lots of other things on my cell phone including using important apps, reading e-\nbooks, using it as a modem to use the internet on my PC. I could not imagine how my life would\nbe without my smart phone.\nI was thankful for the mobile phone that my mother gave me. Firstly, my productivity was\nsignificantly improved, I was surprised at how much I revised for my exams with my smart phone.\nMore importantly, I must say that my life was less boring with this amusement and recreational\ndevice that lets me play games and listen to music. Finally, I can update my social networking\nprofiles and get updates from my friends right from my cell phone.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"marked a significant milestone","vi":"đánh dấu một cột mốc quan trọng"},{"en":"listen to music","vi":"nghe nhạc"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a time you felt happy that you used your cellphone","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-077","_displayNo":"#077","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Describe a type of weather you like\nYou should say:\nwhat kind of weather it is\nwhen this weather usually occurs\nwhat you usually do during this weather\nAnd explain why you like this type of weather","answer":"I was born in Hanoi and have been living here for pretty much my whole life. Hanoi is known for\nall kinds of things, from street food to crazy rush hour traffic. And the city is also unique when it\ncomes to how fickle the weather is. In the summer, the mornings can be so <strong class=\"key-phrase\">scorching hot</strong> that you\nwill not want to leave your house or office, and then all of a sudden it’ll be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">raining cats and dogs</strong> in\nthe afternoon. Perhaps for someone who has spent more than 20 years living here, I somehow\nknow the best time of year to go out and enjoy a picnic or go on a bicycle tour with your friends:\nand that’s late autumn.\nThe weather during the last two weeks of October is just ideal for all kinds of activities. I mean,\nwho does not love looking at a pure blue sky? Or who does not love having a change of scenery after\na torturously hot Summer, instead, having a good time with your family in a gentle breeze? And\npeople always say that during this time of year, Hanoi is the most beautiful.\nThis is also when I like to spend some quality time with my mum and father and other people around\nme. We usually invite some neighbours around and have a barbecue out in the open. My father has\na very old cassette player, that he seems to be very proud of, maybe because no one in the\nneighbourhood has this kind of thing anymore, and he always brings it out during the barbecue\nand listens to some sport news with his friends while enjoying a few beers. Other people usually\nturn on some music and sing along. It’s just like a feast of a small Viking clan, and it is so fun to be\na part of.\nLiving in a city where the weather can be so harsh and pretty much unpredictable all year round, I\nthink having 2 weeks or so of perfect weather where I can have a truly joyous occasion with my\nfamily and neighbours is not so bad.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"scorching hot","vi":"nóng như thiêu đốt"},{"en":"raining cats and dogs","vi":"mưa như trút nước"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a type of weather you like","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-078","_displayNo":"#078","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Describe a useful website that you often visit.\nYou should say:\nWhat the contents of this website are\nHow you first found this website\nHow often you visit this website\nAnd explain how this website helps you.","answer":"So, if there is anything that I miss about America, it would definitely be Netflix. I am <strong class=\"key-phrase\">really into TV\nseries</strong>, you know, especially the DC comic series like the Flash, Green Arrow and Super-girl. Netflix\nis the world’s leading internet television network but it’s still unauthorized in Vietnam, so I found\nmy first few months at home really quite unbearable.\nFortunately though, Minh, my good friend and saviour, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">saved me from this dilemma</strong> by introducing\nme to an unbelievable website called newmovie. vn. So basically, the website’s owners, who\napparently are also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">real movie buffs</strong>, manage to get the hottest new shows from around the world\nand upload them on a daily basis for Vietnamese viewers for, if you can believe it, absolutely no\ncharge whatsoever. Newmovie. vn possesses unlimited access to not only my favourite tv series’\nbut also many other shows on my movies-to-watch list including things like Game of Thrones and\nSherlock Homes. Since this discovery, I have become addicted to the website and am a daily visitor.\nIn conclusion, newmovie. vn is a real lifesaver and honestly, I do not think I could <strong class=\"key-phrase\">put up with all the\nstress</strong> and assignments in my life without my daily dosage of films from newmovie. com.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"really into TV series","vi":"rất yêu thích phim truyền hình dài tập"},{"en":"saved me from this dilemma","vi":"giúp tôi thoát khỏi tình thế khó xử này"},{"en":"real movie buffs","vi":"những người thực sự mê phim"},{"en":"put up with all the stress","vi":"chịu đựng toàn bộ áp lực"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a useful website that you often visit","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-079","_displayNo":"#079","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Describe an environment law\nYou should say:\nwhat it is\nhow you first learned about it\nwho benefits from it\nAnd explain how you feel about this law","answer":"I would like to talk about a policy which the government put in place a long time ago, and I\nbelieve that has had a tremendously <strong class=\"key-phrase\">positive effect on</strong> the daily life of Vietnamese people.\nI do not remember the exact official title of the regulation, but generally, it states that people\nmust separate their household waste into three groups: organic, inorganic and recyclable\nmaterials, each of which has been assigned a different coloured bin. To effectively make this\nrule work, the government has had to install thousands of different coloured bins throughout\nthe city’s public areas.\nIn the past, waste disposal was such a daunting task for the local government to deal with\nbecause most people had very little environmental awareness, and they often just mixed their\ntrash into one giant mess, dumping it into rivers, on the streets or in any public place they felt\nlike. This became quite an alarming situation in Vietnam for a number of years and had an\nextremely detrimental impact on the environment, and not to mention the mess it was\ncreating in many urban areas.\nSo, by introducing this new law and by effectively campaigning it, a clear shift has occurred in\npeople’s daily lives, as now there is an effective and practical solution to get rid of everyday\nwaste, and people’s awareness around this issue has now significantly increased over the\nyears. I am really quite happy with how this law has helped to solve the waste problem in my\ncountry, rather than only the ineffective talk about the problem that was happening\nbeforehand.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"positive effect on","vi":"tác động tích cực đến"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an environment law","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-080","_displayNo":"#080","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Describe an important stage of your life\nYou should say:\nWhat part it is\nWhere you were then\nWhat memorable things you did\nAnd explain why this is the most enjoyable part / stage in your life.","answer":"I want to talk about the time I was preparing for the university entrance exam, which until now is\nstill the most important stage of my life. It actually happened 5 years ago, but the feeling was so\nintense that everything is still fresh in my memory.\nAs you know, in Vietnam, the university entrance exam has always been considered the most\nimportant examination in anybody’s life, and mine was no exception. In my time, all students were\nrequired to sit for an exam that covered the knowledge of 3 full years in high school. It was too\nmuch for anyone to handle; the amount of things to learn was so enormous that I remembered\nhaving to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">pull all-nighters</strong> almost every day. Of course, the competition was fierce, I mean you\nwouldn’t be admitted into the top schools unless your score were really high.\nBesides the stress of studying, I was also faced with the question of which major to choose. For\nmany, it was an easy pick, because they understood where their strengths and interest lied. For\nme, I had no idea whatsoever what I should do in the future, so I was feeling on edge during the\nentire period before the exam.\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">In hindsight</strong>, it was not an enjoyable time, but definitely a precious memory to me. It was the first\ntime I was ever involved in something that had such a huge impact on my life. Through this, I had\nan opportunity to have a closer look at my career orientation as well as my ability. It wouldn’t be\nan exaggeration to say that I became an adult after this. That’s all I want to share about this topic.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"pull all-nighters","vi":"thức trắng đêm để làm việc hoặc học"},{"en":"In hindsight","vi":"khi nhìn lại"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an important stage of your life","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-081","_displayNo":"#081","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Describe an interesting talk or speech you heard\nYou should say:\nWho gave the talk/speech\nWhere and when you heard it\nWhat it was about\nAnd explain why it was interesting?","answer":"Today I am going to talk to you about a speech that I came across two months ago on TV called\n“the power of vulnerability”.\nThe speech was delivered by Brene Brown who is an American scholar, an author and a public\nspeaker. She has been involved in research on <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a range of</strong> topics, including vulnerability, courage,\nshame, and empathy.\nI accidentally heard her speech when I was watching TV at home after a hard day at work. Her\nTED talk touched my spirit, evoked my sympathy and taught me many lessons. Firstly, I learned that\nI cannot ignore all the negative feelings I have. If I try to avoid them, I will not be able to feel happy,\ngrateful or joyful, and therefore, I need to have the courage to face and solve all the problems I\nhave in order to live happily.\nSecondly, thanks to this talk, I was able to understand how powerful it is to show other people my\nvulnerability, and that I should dare to take risks and do the things that I am not so sure about. For\nexample, I should be the one who says I love you first, even if I know I might be rejected.\nFinally, I learned how to love myself from the bottom of my heart and was able to give up\nirresponsible behaviour such as skipping meals or getting wasted whenever I was sad. And in\naddition to this, once I am able to love myself, I will not hurt other people who truly love me.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"a range of","vi":"nhiều loại"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an interesting talk or speech you heard","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-082","_displayNo":"#082","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Describe something you bought recently that made you happy.\nYou should say:\n- What it is.\n- When and where you bought it.\n- How it was used/what is was used for.\n- Why it made you happy.","answer":"Today I would like to talk to you about my new laptop. At the time, it made me really satisfied\nbecause of its <strong class=\"key-phrase\">high performance</strong>.\nIt was about 3 years ago, when I was a senior student in my university. At that time, I really needed\nto purchase a new laptop as soon as possible in order to do homework and assignments for my\nthesis, so I asked a lot of people about which brand I should buy. After considering everything, I\ndecided to buy a laptop from the DELL brand shop.\nWhen it comes to how I use this laptop, besides doing homework and assignments, I like watching\nmovies as well as playing games for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">recreational purposes</strong>, which have brought me a sense of fun\nuntil now.\nThere are so many reasons why I really love this laptop. Firstly, I bought it for a reasonable price.\nUnlike other famous laptop brands like ASUS and Lenovo, which usually <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cost an arm and a leg</strong>, this\nDELL laptop is suitable for people who are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">not well-off</strong> like me. Besides that, when using this\nlaptop, I can ease my mind by doing a range of recreational activities after a long day at school and\nget away from daily routine. In the future, I would like to keep this laptop as long as possible as I\nam\nextremely\nhappy\nto\nown\nit.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"high performance","vi":"hiệu suất cao"},{"en":"recreational purposes","vi":"mục đích giải trí"},{"en":"cost an arm and a leg","vi":"đắt cắt cổ"},{"en":"not well-off","vi":"không khá giả"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"something you bought recently that made you happy","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-083","_displayNo":"#083","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Describe two people from the same family\nYou should say:\nWho they are\nHow you know them\nIf they look a-like\nAnd if you like spending time with them.","answer":"I would like to describe twin sisters who live in the apartment next to mine. I met them about a year ago during a power cut, when I knocked on their door to borrow some candles. They invited me in until the electricity came back, and we became friends soon afterwards.\n\nAlthough they are twins, they <strong class=\"key-phrase\">look nothing alike</strong>. The older sister has short hair, a mischievous smile and a very outgoing personality. She is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a real social butterfly</strong> and can start a conversation with almost anyone. Her younger sister has long hair and is much <strong class=\"key-phrase\">quieter and more reserved</strong>. She usually listens carefully before speaking, but she has a dry sense of humour that makes me laugh.\n\nI enjoy spending time with them because their personalities <strong class=\"key-phrase\">balance each other out</strong>. The older one brings energy to any gathering, while the younger one notices details and gives thoughtful advice. We often have film nights at my apartment, order food and talk until late. Because they see situations differently, we <strong class=\"key-phrase\">never run out of things to talk about</strong>.\n\nWhat I value most is that they are both dependable. If I need practical help, one of them will usually be available, and they know they can rely on me as well. I hope we remain close even if one of us eventually moves away.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"look nothing alike","vi":"trông hoàn toàn không giống nhau"},{"en":"a real social butterfly","vi":"một người rất hòa đồng"},{"en":"quieter and more reserved","vi":"trầm tính và kín đáo hơn"},{"en":"balance each other out","vi":"bổ sung và cân bằng cho nhau"},{"en":"never run out of things to talk about","vi":"không bao giờ hết chuyện để nói"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"two people from the same family","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-084","_displayNo":"#084","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Describe your favorite season of the year.\nYou should say:\n- What the weather is like.\n- Why you like this season.\n- What activities you usually do during this season.\n- How different kinds of weather in this season affect people.","answer":"Today, I am going to tell you about my favourite season. Honestly, I love all the seasons but I think\nmy favourite is spring. Usually, it starts at the end of December in our country and lasts till the\nmiddle of March.\nThe weather in Vietnam is the best during spring because you will not suffer from the excessive\nheat of summer or the freezing wind of winter. The temperature is tolerable both day and night.\nOne of the best things about spring is that, during this poetic season, nature displays itself in\nbeautiful green and flowers are noticed everywhere. Fruit trees, such as cherry and apricot trees\nare <strong class=\"key-phrase\">in full blossom</strong>, and colourful flowers such as daffodils and marigolds bloom in parks and\ngardens. The sounds of spring are wonderful too. A typical spring day will begin when some birds\nstart their morning chorus as they look for a mate. We also celebrate Tet, one of the most\nanticipated holidays by the Vietnamese people. This is an occasion for pilgrimages, family reunions\nand many festivals. Parties full of delicious traditional dishes are the main theme for the whole\nholiday of Tet.\nI am of the opinion that different kinds of weather can affect people’s health. Even among those\nin the prime of health, an excessively hot or cold day can lead to illness or injury, let alone the\nelderly, who can be more susceptible to extreme weather conditions. Weather can also make a\nhuge impact on people's lives. Obviously, the weather dictates what you are going to wear for the\nday, often depending on the time of year. Also, winter snow storms in Western countries can\ncancel school or make your morning commute a hassle.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"in full blossom","vi":"đang nở rộ"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"your favorite season of the year","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-085","_displayNo":"#085","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Other","prompt":"Talk about something that makes you excited.\nYou should say:\n- What it is\n- How it is exciting\n- Why you feel excited about it","answer":"To be honest, there are not many exciting things going on in my life at the moment, but if I have to\ntalk about one, I would say the weekly coffee date with my best friend is what excites me the\nmost.\nThe reason why I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">look forward to</strong> this date so much is because my friend and I rarely have a chance\nto talk on weekdays. Back in school, the two of us were <strong class=\"key-phrase\">like the white on rice</strong>, I mean we were\ninseparable. I could spend days and nights gossiping with my best friend, and meeting each other\nwas never a problem for us. However, since graduation, both of us are always <strong class=\"key-phrase\">buried in work</strong>, so\nit gets harder to stay in contact regularly. So now, weekends are the only time we can meet up,\nand the thought of it never fails to excite me.\nThere are millions of things I and my bestie can do together. Most of the time, we choose a nice\ncafé to sit down and have a chat. On other occasions, we go shopping, or have brunch in a\nfancy restaurant. In fact, what we do does not really matter, as long as we can see each other. I feel\nrelieved every time I confide in my best friend, because I know she will always cheer me up and\ngive me some useful advice. All in all, this is one of the things that excites me the most, thank you\nfor listening.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Other","phrases":[{"en":"look forward to","vi":"mong chờ"},{"en":"like the white on rice","vi":"gắn bó vô cùng chặt chẽ"},{"en":"buried in work","vi":"ngập đầu trong công việc"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"something that makes you excited","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-086","_displayNo":"#086","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a school that you went to when you were a child.\nYou should say:\n- where the school was\n- when you went there\n- what the school and the teachers were like\n- and explain whether you enjoyed your time there.","answer":"I am going to describe the primary school I attended in the town where I grew up. It was a small state school within walking distance of my family home, so I walked there almost every day between the ages of five and eleven.\n\nThe school had only six main classrooms, one for each year group, as well as a library, a sports field and a large assembly hall. At the time it seemed enormous, but when I visited the area years later I realised how compact it actually was. The teachers were caring but firm, and they created an atmosphere in which children felt safe enough to ask questions and make mistakes.\n\nWhat I remember most clearly is taking part in the school play during my final year. I had to learn several lines and perform in front of pupils, teachers and parents. I was extremely nervous beforehand, but completing the performance gave me <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a genuine sense of achievement</strong>.\n\nI have fond memories of that school because it gave me close friendships and a strong academic foundation. More importantly, it taught me that confidence can be developed gradually through supportive challenges.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"a genuine sense of achievement","vi":"cảm giác thành tựu thực sự"}],"source":"Prompt adapted from IELTS Simon; unfinished place-name placeholders replaced by a complete original answer","subtype":"","summary":"a school that you went to when you were a child","id":"speaking-part-2-087","_displayNo":"#087","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a toy that was special to you when you were a child.\nYou should say:\n- when you got it\n- what it looked like\n- who gave it to you","answer":"One special toy that I remember getting was a Lego car. It was a birthday present from my parents. I can't remember exactly how old I was, but I was probably about 10 or 11. The special thing about this car was that I had to build it myself out of hundreds of pieces of Lego. The pieces came in a box with a picture of the finished car on the front, and I had to follow step-by-step instructions to put all the pieces together in the correct way. This wasn't an easy task because the car even had an engine, movable seats and gears. It took me a day or two to make, and required a lot of concentration. When the car was finished it looked great, and I felt <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sense of accomplishment</strong>. I seem to remember that I didn't play with the car very much; the fun part had been the process of building it.","author":"Simon","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"a sense of accomplishment","vi":"cảm giác hoàn thành và thành tựu"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a toy that was special to you when you were a child","id":"speaking-part-2-088","_displayNo":"#088","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe an artist or entertainer you admire\nYou should say:\n- who they are and what they do\n- how they became successful\n- how you found out about them\n- and why you admire them","answer":"I would like to talk about Ed Sheeran, a British singer-songwriter who performs mainly with his voice, an acoustic guitar and a loop pedal. I first became aware of him when a friend played “The A Team” for me, and I was struck by how a simple arrangement could carry such a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">strong emotional message</strong>.\n\nHe became successful gradually rather than through a single manufactured publicity campaign. Before he was internationally known, he performed in small venues, released music independently and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">built an audience</strong> through constant live work. His breakthrough came when his songs reached a much wider online audience and attracted support from established musicians.\n\nI admire him for two reasons. First, he writes much of his own material, so his music feels personal rather than interchangeable. Second, his live performances show technical control and creativity: he can build a complete arrangement alone by recording rhythms and harmonies in real time. Even though his music is commercially successful, the core of it still depends on songwriting and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">sustained practice</strong>, which makes his career feel earned.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"strong emotional message","vi":"thông điệp cảm xúc mạnh mẽ"},{"en":"built an audience","vi":"xây dựng được lượng khán giả"},{"en":"sustained practice","vi":"sự luyện tập bền bỉ"}],"source":"Prompt adapted from IELTS Simon; generic placeholder completed and quality-audited by ChatGPT","subtype":"","summary":"an artist or entertainer you admire","id":"speaking-part-2-089","_displayNo":"#089","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe an indoor game that you enjoyed as a child.\nYou should say:\n- what the game was\n- where you played it\n- who played this game with you\n- and why you liked it","answer":"As a child I enjoyed playing chess. I think chess is probably the best known board game in the world. It’s a game for two players, and the aim is to defeat the other player by taking his or her pieces and eventually trapping his King. This final move is called checkmate. I remember that it was a classmate of mine at primary school who first taught me to play chess. He had a small, portable chess set, and once I knew how each piece moved, we started playing at break and lunch times; we played in our classroom or outside on the school playground. Later my parents bought me my own chess set as a birthday present so that I could play at home. I taught my younger brother to play, and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">at some point</strong> I joined the school chess club. There I had the chance to hone my skills against some of the older pupils, and in my final year of primary school I made it onto the school team. There were five of us on the team, and we competed against children from other primary schools in the same town. I liked playing chess because I enjoyed the challenge of thinking ahead and trying to outwit my opponent. I was probably seven or eight years old when I started playing, and it seemed like a very mysterious and intellectual game at that time. Also, although I loved winning, chess taught me to learn from my losses and to congratulate the person who had beaten me.","author":"Simon","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"at some point","vi":"vào một thời điểm nào đó"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"an indoor game that you enjoyed as a child","id":"speaking-part-2-090","_displayNo":"#090","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe an interesting conversation you had with someone\nYou should say:\n- who the person was\n- where the conversation took place\n- what you talked about\n- and explain why you found the conversation interesting.","answer":"I am going to talk about an interesting conversation that I had a couple of weeks ago in a music shop. I was walking along one of the main shopping streets in the city centre, when a large window displaying all sorts of musical instruments caught my eye. Out of curiosity, I decided to go in and have a look around. The person I ended up speaking to was a shop assistant on the second floor, in the area of the shop <strong class=\"key-phrase\">dedicated to</strong> acoustic guitars. I had not intended to speak to anyone, but the assistant approached me in a friendly way and asked whether I had any questions. I explained to the assistant that I had not played the guitar for years, but that I wondered what the differences were between the various acoustic guitars on show. He talked to me about the different makes and models, whether they were factory or hand made, the woods and varnishes used, the variation in sound quality, and of course the price range. I found the conversation fascinating because the shop assistant was so knowledgeable. It was obvious that he had a passion for the guitar, and he did not mind talking to me even though I had made it clear that I did not intend to buy anything. He even picked up and played three or four of the instruments to demonstrate the differences in their sound.","author":"Simon","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"dedicated to","vi":"tận tâm với"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"an interesting conversation you had with someone you","id":"speaking-part-2-091","_displayNo":"#091","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a book you liked to read in your childhood\nYou should say:\nwho wrote this book\nwhat it is about\nwhen you read it\nand explain why you liked it.","answer":"Well, I am going to share with you the book that I was really fond of reading when I was a little girl,\nwhich is Harry Potter and the Philosopher’s Stone. It’s a fantasy novel written by the British author\nJ. K. Rowling, and she has become really popular all over the world now thanks to this fantastic\nseries of books.\nThe book illustrates the school life of a young wizard, Harry Potter, and his two best friends Ron\nand Hermione. Harry had a powerful enemy, the Dark Wizard, Lord Voldemort, who longed for\nimmortality and to rule the magic world.\nI started reading this book when I was about 8 years old I think. At that time, I was only beginning\nto <strong class=\"key-phrase\">improve my reading skills</strong>, and Harry Potter was quite a thick book so it took me ages to get\nthrough it.\nAs a little girl, I did not understand all the details in the book but I truly admired the story of Harry’s\nfriendship with Ron and Hermione. And I think it helped me to feel more confident to make friends\nwith my classmates, some of whom I still <strong class=\"key-phrase\">keep in touch</strong> with now. And I guess that is the main\nreason why I appreciate this book so much.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"improve my reading skills","vi":"cải thiện kỹ năng đọc"},{"en":"keep in touch","vi":"giữ liên lạc"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a book you liked to read in your childhood","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-092","_displayNo":"#092","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a businessman that you admire.\nYou should say:\n- Who his person is;\n- How you got to know this person;\n- What this person does;\n- How you think of this person.","answer":"Today I am going to tell you about a businessman that I really admire and respect. I live in a\nbeautiful and peaceful street and most of my neighbors are working for companies or running\ntheir own enterprises. Among them, I would pick Mr. Vincent as the most admirable\nbusinessman I have ever met.\nMr. Vincent is 30 years old and he established his first company when he was only 26. His\ncompany trades medical equipment, and it's name is Viet Sun. He has acquired a reputation\nas a profound and dedicated person to his work, I usually find him leaving for work early\nand getting home late. Even on weekends, instead of hanging out with friends, he is still\nglued to his computer screen.\nDespite being older than me by nearly 10 years but he looks really young and is always full\nof energy. Few people have the great passion and relevant skills to pursue to their goals. Mr.\nVincent is one of those who could achieve his dream by himself at the age of 26, and this is\nwhat I find most appealing about him.\nAnother of his lovely traits is definitely his wise advice. Therefore, whenever I feel\ndiscouraged, I will seek his advice. I have learned many useful things from him, not only in\neveryday things, but also in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">attitudes to life</strong>.\nTo me, he is not just a normal businessman, but a person whom I can share things with and learn\nmany things from. I really owe a lot of gratitude to him.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"attitudes to life","vi":"thái độ đối với cuộc sống"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a businessman that you admire","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-093","_displayNo":"#093","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a couple you know who have a happy marriage\nYou should say:\nWho they are\nHow you know them\nWhat they usually do together\nAnd how you feel about their marriage.","answer":"Well, I would like to talk about my own parents whose marriage is, without a doubt, a happy one.\nThey have been married for 30 years now and are the perfect couple in my eyes.\nWell, my mother and father are now in their 60’s and they are still really busy with their nine to\nfive jobs in a government office, but I think that both of them are going to retire later this year.\nDuring 30 years of marriage, my parents have been through thick and thin together but have never\nlost their love for each other. My parents usually just show their affection simply by always being\nhonest with each other and sharing their true feelings. Their <strong class=\"key-phrase\">mutual understanding</strong> for each other\nis so profound that sometimes it only takes one look to realise what the other is thinking.\nOf course they still have minor tiffs every <strong class=\"key-phrase\">now and then</strong>, you know, things like who will have to\npick up the kids or who gets the TV remote. However, my father is always the first one to give in and\nturn to comfort my mother. I think little action’s like these are actually the key to my parents’ long\nlasting relationship.\nTo me, mother and father are a perfect match and I admire their love for each other so much. Hopefully,\nin the future, I will have a partner that cares for me as much as my parents care for each other.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"mutual understanding","vi":"sự thấu hiểu lẫn nhau"},{"en":"now and then","vi":"thỉnh thoảng"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a couple you know who have a happy marriage","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-094","_displayNo":"#094","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a dinner you enjoyed with your friends.\nYou should say:\nwhen and where you had the dinner\nwhat you had\nwho you went with\nand explain why you enjoyed the dinner.","answer":"I have had many meals and taken part in many celebrations and parties <strong class=\"key-phrase\">over the years</strong> but among\nthese, there’s one particular time that I remember the most. A few months ago, I went to a\nbarbeque party on the rooftop of one of my friends’ homes. It was actually a farewell party for my\nbest friend since she was going to study abroad, and the meal and the party were both really\nfantastic.\nWe had been planning this party for a long time and so on the day, we gathered at my friend’s\nhouse and all went shopping and prepared everything together. We had a lot of amazing food that\nnight as my best friend has a real talent for cooking. Thanks to her secret recipe, all the meat was\nmarinated and seasoned perfectly and the taste was simply delicious. Besides the main dishes, a\nlot of drinks and snacks were served too. I myself enjoyed the dessert the most. It was a fluffy red\nvelvet cake with a classic cream cheese frosting. We bought that from a famous bakery in Hanoi\nand it was worth every penny.\nSo we ate the grilled meat, drank beer and chatted the whole evening. During the dinner, we talked\nabout our future, our funniest memories together and everybody had a real blast. There’s no doubt\nthat it could be quite a long time until we can all gather like that again, so that party is very\nmemorable to me.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"over the years","vi":"qua nhiều năm"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a dinner you enjoyed with your friends","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-095","_displayNo":"#095","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a family member that made you proud.\nYou should say:\nWho the person is\nHow close you are\nWhat he/she did that made you proud\nAnd explain why they made you proud.","answer":"There is no one else in this world I hold more respect for than my mother. She is my guardian, my\nfriend and my role model.\nMy mother is well into her forties now, but she still manages to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">maintain a youthful appearance</strong>.\nIn terms of her personality, she is an extremely compassionate, kind-hearted and attentive person\nwho always takes care of her children. She is both a mother and a friend to me as she always gives\nme valuable advice and is always willing to be there for me during all of the ups and downs in my\nlife. Although sometimes she drives me crazy, because she is such a perfectionist, I still hold a lot\nof pride and respect for her.\nThe reason that I am so proud of her is because she is such a strong-willed person. Ever since she\nwas young, she had to learn to be independent as my grandparents were constantly busy and\nalways on the go. She had to take care of almost everything, her younger brother, household\nchores and herself. Such challenges shaped her into the strong woman that she is now. Her\nindependence has also been strengthened through all the hardship she has dealt with in her life.\nWhen she reached her thirties, she decided that she wanted to run her own business, a clothing\nstore. All the members in our family tried to prevent her from doing this since we all thought it\nwas a bad idea because she would have to face a lot of competition from other nearby shops.\nBut through her determination and perseverance she has managed to make a success out of her\nbusiness and it really is something for us to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">look up to</strong>, and I keep reminding myself every day to\ntry to be as strong as my mother, a real-life “wonder woman.”","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"maintain a youthful appearance","vi":"duy trì vẻ ngoài trẻ trung"},{"en":"look up to","vi":"ngưỡng mộ và xem là hình mẫu"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a family member that made you proud","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-096","_displayNo":"#096","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a family member who has had an important influence on you\nYou should say:\nWho the person is;\nWhat kind of person he or she is;\nWhat this person has done to influence you;\nAnd explain why you think this person is important to you.","answer":"I am going to talk about my mother who has played an essential role in my life. She is my guardian,\nmy friend and my role model.\nMy mother is in her forties now, but she still maintains a youthful look. In terms of personality,\nshe is an extremely compassionate and kind-hearted person who always takes care of her\nchildren. She really is a mother and a friend to me as she always gives me valuable advice and is\nwilling to stand by me through all the ups and downs of my life. Although sometimes she drives\nme crazy due to her being a perfectionist, I still hold so much pride and respect for her.\nI am also influenced by her strong-will. Ever since she was young, she had to learn to be\nindependent as my grandparents were very busy and constantly on the go. She had to take care\nof almost everything: her younger brother, household chores and herself. Such challenges shaped\nher into the strong person that she is now.\nHer determination, as well as her perseverance, are really something for us to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">look up to</strong>. And I\nkeep reminding myself every day to be as strong as my mother, a real-life “wonder woman.”","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"look up to","vi":"ngưỡng mộ và xem là hình mẫu"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a family member who has had an important influence on you","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-097","_displayNo":"#097","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a famous athlete you know\nYou should say:\nWho he or she is\nHow you know him or her\nWhat he or she has achieved\nWhy he is famous","answer":"Being a big fan of basketball, I have long idolized the legend of this sport - Michael Jordan, also\nknown as MJ. I first got curious about his life when I saw a logo portraying him on a product of the\nbrand, Nike, and his life turned out to be intriguing to me.\nHe played in the position of shooting guard in one of the most renowned teams, the Chicago Bulls,\nand was famous for his exceptional leaping ability, illustrated by performing slam dunks from the\nfree throw line. Early in his NBA career, while playing for the University of North Carolina, he\nappeared on the cover of Sports Illustrated with the heading “A star is born” just over a month into\nhis professional career. It was not only his talent but also his dedication that made him a strong\nclutch performer. He spent hours studying films of his opponents to improve his defense. Even\nwhen his right knee was injured, Jordan did not miss any games in the season from 1986 to 2001.\nThroughout his career, he led the Chicago Bulls to six championships, was awarded the NBA Most\nValuable Player five times and was the first player to be honored with both the NBA’s Defensive\nPlayer of the year award and Most Valuable Player awards. All the compliments that journalists\ngave him were not an overstatement.\nAlthough Michael Jordan retired in 2003, his skills and his legacy are still <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a great inspiration</strong> for\nany basketball player or person considering pursuing a basketball career. He is also active in charity\nactivities. His clothing line, Jordan brand, has made donations to different organizations across\nAmerica. It’s difficult to describe how amazing Michael Jordan is in words, just watch a few of his\nvideos playing in NBA games or his interviews, you’ll figure it out yourself.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"a great inspiration","vi":"một nguồn cảm hứng lớn"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a famous athlete you know","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-098","_displayNo":"#098","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a famous person that you are interested in\nYou should say:\n- Who this person is.\n- How you know about this\nperson.\n- What this person is famous for.\n- Why you are interested in this person.","answer":"A famous person who I am really interested in is definitely My Tam. She is the best pop singer in\nViet Nam who <strong class=\"key-phrase\">embarked on her singing career</strong> in 1999. The Da Nang-born singer has recently\nbecome Vietnam’s first-ever artist to be listed on Billboard’s World Albums chart, after releasing\nher ninth studio album ’Tam 9’.\nMy Tam is my biggest idol because she is a great singer with beautiful voice. Some years ago, I\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">caught a glimpse of</strong> her on TV and was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">immediately hooked</strong> by her outstanding performance. I\nhave became her loyal fan since then. I really like the way she sings and the way she expresses the\nfeeling of the song. To my admiration, she has always worked seriously to give high quality music\nproducts.\nMy Tam is beloved for her good personality too. She is known to all her fans for her gregariousness\nand sense of humour. Besides, she has also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">devoted her time to</strong> organizing free concerts for\nuniversity students nationwide. Together with her fans and friends, she has been doing a lot of\ncharity activities silently to help the poor, the sick and the homeless people.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"embarked on her singing career","vi":"bắt đầu sự nghiệp ca hát"},{"en":"caught a glimpse of","vi":"thoáng nhìn thấy"},{"en":"immediately hooked","vi":"ngay lập tức bị cuốn hút"},{"en":"devoted her time to","vi":"dành thời gian cho"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a famous person that you are interested in","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-099","_displayNo":"#099","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a helpful person at work or school\nYou should say:\nWho it was\nWhat this person did\nHow this person helped\nAnd explain how you felt after this person helped you.","answer":"I would like to describe one of my teachers who taught me at high school, who <strong class=\"key-phrase\">had a great\ninfluence on me</strong> and was the person who helped me succeed in my university entrance\nexamination. Her name is Linh and she taught me English for 3 years of high school and was also\nmy form teacher. She was in her late 40’s then but looked young for her age.\nI was really influenced by the way she taught us in class. Her thoroughness in teaching inspired\nme to study English, even though I had not been interested in it before. We never felt bored in her\nclasses, she always told us interesting stories about British and American culture and people, and\nalso organized some games so that we could learn new vocabulary and grammar effortlessly.\nI remember that during the three months before the university entrance exam, which was the most\nimportant exam of my life, she had delivered some free classes for the students who were not quite\nup to standard, including myself. She patiently <strong class=\"key-phrase\">guided us through difficult questions</strong> and provided\nmany useful tips to help deal with the test. Thanks to her effective teaching method and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">great\ndedication</strong>, I was able to pass the university entrance exam with almost a perfect score in English.\nAlthough I have graduated from high school and now study in Hanoi, I often visit her on the\nholidays and tell her about my daily life in the big city and she is always available to give me some\nadvice about any problems I have. I am <strong class=\"key-phrase\">forever grateful</strong> to have Mrs. Linh in my life.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"had a great influence on me","vi":"có ảnh hưởng lớn đến tôi"},{"en":"guided us through difficult questions","vi":"hướng dẫn chúng tôi xử lý các câu hỏi khó"},{"en":"great dedication","vi":"sự tận tâm lớn"},{"en":"forever grateful","vi":"luôn biết ơn"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a helpful person at work or school","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-100","_displayNo":"#100","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a leader or politician who you admire.\nYou should say:\nWho is he/ she?\nWhat is so appealing about him?\nWhat type of leader is he/ she\nAnd explain why do you admire him /her.","answer":"I would like to talk about Mr David Cameron, the former Prime Minister of the UK and I do believe\nthat he is the most professional person that I have ever known in my life.\nFirst, I would like to get the ball rolling by touching on the matter of how I knew him. it was about\n5 years ago more or less, when I travelled to England and had a chance to meet him in front of\nNumber 10 Downing Street.\nOn the subject of his appearance, I must confess that I was struck by his powerful and presentable\nlook at the first time seeing him. He was so charismatic and confident that everyone wanted to\nlisten to him when he was talking as well as debating with others over political issues. As well as\nthat, he was always cool headed in every situation because he <strong class=\"key-phrase\">weighed up the pros and cons</strong>\nbefore making any decision instead of jumping to a conclusion.\nThere are several reasons why I really admire Mr Cameron. First, he led his party in a democratic\nway. You know, he always listened to everyone’s opinions and commented fairly on them. Second,\nwith his contributions to many areas, ranging from medicine to social welfare, the UK has become\nthe fifth strongest economy globally.\nFor all these reasons, I want to reaffirm that David Cameron is the most honorable leader that I\nhave ever met. And in the future, if I have a chance, I will go back to the UK to meet him once\nagain.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"weighed up the pros and cons","vi":"cân nhắc ưu và nhược điểm"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a leader or politician who you admire","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-101","_displayNo":"#101","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a memorable story told by someone\nYou should say:\nWho told you the story?\nWhen you heard the story\nWhat the story was about\nWhy you found it memorable.","answer":"I would like to share a funny story that I heard from Julie, a friend of mine, a long time ago. It was\na random day that our group hung out at a coffee shop and sat at the circle table near the window,\nas we usually do. This was our favourite spot. But that day, instead of ordering a cappuccino as I\nusually do, I decided to try a completely new drink – mojito mixed with some fruit, though I cannot\nremember exactly what.\nThe mojito looked good on the outside but its taste was unbearable to me. Despite my warning,\nJulie insisted on trying it. It turned out that she liked the drink very much and in that moment, she\nconcluded that it tasted exactly like the toothpaste that she ate in her childhood. Learning of this\nincident, we were a bit shocked as to why she ate such a thing, so she continued to elaborate on\nher story. She recalled that she indeed thought that the taste of toothpaste was delicious, and\neven she was banned from eating it by her parents, she secretly saved money to buy one for\nherself a few years later. She added that she sneakily hid the tube in the room and she could finish\nthe whole thing in one go. We were frozen and all eyes were on her for a few seconds. Then we\nall <strong class=\"key-phrase\">burst into laughter</strong>. I still remember laughing so hard that my tears ran down.\nI was indeed impressed by her story. As the matter of fact, it was not the first time I had heard of\nsomeone enjoying eating toothpaste, but secretly saving money to do this was a surprise element\nand it was hilarious. And of course, it has become an inside joke between us since then.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"burst into laughter","vi":"bật cười"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a memorable story told by someone","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-102","_displayNo":"#102","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a new friend you`ve made recently\nYou should say:\nWho the person is\nWhat kind of person he/she is\nHow you met this person\nAnd explain why you made friends with him/her","answer":"I am going to talk about Mrs. Kim who is a lovely lady that I recently befriended.\nI started college life 3 months ago and on my first day of school I was unable to navigate my way\nto my new university where I was studying. Google Maps was not really as helpful as I thought it\nwould be and I couldn’t figure out the way by asking the locals either. So, after many hours of\nwandering around, I finally <strong class=\"key-phrase\">resorted to asking</strong> a lady who was selling noodles from a food cart near\nwhere I was standing. I asked the lady if she knew the way to the HCMC University of Education,\nand she just smiled and pointed at the large, five-story building across the road. Turns out I was\nthere all along! So, after thanking the lady, we had a little chat and I found out she also came from\nNinh Thuan, which is my hometown! We immediately became good friends and now her food cart\nhas become my favourite lunch spot whenever I am at university.\nSo I guess the main reason that Mrs. Kim and I have become good friends is basically because I\nthink she is a really sweet lady. As I have gotten to know her better I have realized that she is had quite\na tough life, yet she has managed to maintain a sweet and gentle personality that many other\nwomen who have been through struggles like her would have lost by now. I guess the other reason\nwe get on so well is because we share the same hometown, and I tend to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">get on well</strong> with people\nfrom my hometown. Sometimes I think the best friendships are made so unexpectedly.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"resorted to asking","vi":"cuối cùng phải nhờ đến việc hỏi"},{"en":"get on well","vi":"hòa hợp với nhau"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a new friend you`ve made recently","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-103","_displayNo":"#103","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a person who does well in work\nYou should say:\nWho the person is\nHow do you know this person\nWhat kinds of work this person does\nAnd explain why this person can do well","answer":"Recently I took a job as a maths teacher at an International school. Describing a person who does\nwell at work makes me think of the head of the Maths department at my school, Mr Lawrence aka\nLaurie. I met Laurie in the school cafeteria over coffee and we began to talk about his role as the\nhead of Maths.\nLaurie told me he is been a maths teacher since 1985 so that’s… 33 years <strong class=\"key-phrase\">in the trade</strong>. He loves his\njob, and he said he’d be a Maths teacher for 500 hundred years if I he did not die of old age first. To\nbe honest, I was quite taken aback by this comment. I always get a feeling somewhere between\nadmiration and sympathy for teachers who commit almost every aspect of their life to their work.\nAdmiration because of the dedication to their students and their craft; sympathy because they\nhave given up so much to become the teacher they are today.\nIt is precisely this quality, though, that explains why Laurie a person who does well at work. His\nwork and his life are intimately linked, and if Laurie wants to lead a good life, this is almost\nsynonymous with him being a good teacher.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"in the trade","vi":"làm trong ngành"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a person who does well in work","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-104","_displayNo":"#104","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a person who gave a clever solution to a problem\nYou should say:\nWho the person is\nWhen and where it happened\nWhat the problem was\nAnd explain why it was a clever solution","answer":"To ’<strong class=\"key-phrase\">think outside of the box</strong>’ is always the term that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">comes to mind</strong> whenever a problem arises\nand not everyone succeeds in coming up with a solution, but there is one person on this planet\nthough who always surprises me with his cleverness and ability to come up with a solution to\neven some of the toughest problems. His name is Nam and he is my older brother.\nMy mother always told us that even though we’re brothers and we have a close–knit relationship,\nwe’re still as different as two people could possibly be. I am quite an active person and have a\ntendency to make very quick decisions, while my brother is extremely calm and usually solves\nproblems in a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">level-headed</strong> kind of way, and that’s the reason why he has been a kind of saviour\nto me on a number of occasions.\nThere was a time that I consider as an important landmark in my life which was when I took the\nentrance exam to university. And similar to my mother, I suffer from hypotension which is low\nblood pressure and sometimes causes dizziness when I am hungry or tired. In certain\ncircumstances, I just need the sugar from a couple of candy bars to recover, but actually I am quite\nan absent-minded person so I usually forget to carry any with me.\nOn that day, when the start of the examination was getting nearer, I was so nervous that I couldn’t\nthink clearly and my hands had begun to shake. All of a sudden I found some tiny chocolate bars\nin my pocket, and they absolutely saved my life! In the end, it turned out that my brother\nremembered to put some in my pocket for me in order to avoid this situation. So thoughtful and\nso smart he was to do such a thing!","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"think outside of the box","vi":"tư duy khác biệt và sáng tạo"},{"en":"comes to mind","vi":"nảy ra trong đầu; nghĩ đến đầu tiên"},{"en":"level-headed","vi":"bình tĩnh và sáng suốt"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a person who gave a clever solution to a problem","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-105","_displayNo":"#105","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a person who has apologized to you\nYou should say:\nwhen it was\nwho the person was\nwhy this person apologized\nand explain how you felt about it.","answer":"Well I think that we all tend to make some mistakes in life <strong class=\"key-phrase\">now and then</strong>, sometimes intentionally,\nand sometimes unintentionally, but we usually regret them afterwards. I always try to apologize\nfor what I do wrong, and of course, I expect the same from others.\nSo last month, my friend borrowed my car for the day and he knows very well that I am very\npossessive about my car. I asked him to take good care of it as I know he is not a very good driver,\nand in fact, this is the reason why his father does not buy him his own car.\nBut he promised me to drive it very cautiously and safely, however when he returned it in the\nevening he sounded very low and he told me that someone hit the car from the rear when he was\nstuck in a traffic-jam and that caused him to hit the car in front of him. He was feeling very guilty\nfor not taking care of the car and he apologized repeatedly for his negligence, and he assured me\nthat he would get it repaired the first thing the next morning.\nI did feel sorry for him though, but at the same time very sad as my car was damaged, but\nsomewhere in my mind I knew that this was not his fault. Normally, I easily lose my temper but it\nwas because of his sincere apology that I couldn’t stay mad at him for very long.\nSo the next day, he went with me to the mechanic and luckily the damage was not so bad or\nexpensive to fix. He apologized again and assured me that he’d be more vigilant in the future. We\nare still good friends and I feel that receiving an apology and forgiving someone is the best way to\nmaintain and make relationships stronger.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"now and then","vi":"thỉnh thoảng"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a person who has apologized to you","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-106","_displayNo":"#106","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a person who knows a lot/is knowledgeable.\nYou should say:\n- Who the person is;\n- What the person do;\n- What kinds of things he knows;\n- What you learn from him/her.","answer":"To ’<strong class=\"key-phrase\">think outside of the box</strong>’ is always the term that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">comes to mind</strong> whenever a problem arises\nand its difficult to find a solution. There is one person on this planet though who always surprises\nme with his cleverness and ability to come up with a solution to even some of the toughest\nproblems. His name is Nam and he is my older brother.\nMy mother always told us that even though we’re brothers and we have a close–knit relationship,\nwe’re still as different as two people could possibly be. I am quite an active person and have a\ntendency to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make very quick decisions</strong>, while my brother is extremely calm and usually solves\nproblems in a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">level-headed</strong> kind of way. It is for this reason that he has been a kind of savior to\nme on a number of occasions.\nThere is a time that I consider an important landmark in my life, which was when I took the\nentrance exam to university. And, similarly to my mother, I suffer from hypotension which is low\nblood pressure and sometimes causes dizziness when I am hungry or tired. In certain circumstances,\nI just need the sugar from a couple of candy bars to recover, but actually I am quite an absent-\nminded person so I usually forget to carry any with me. On that day, when the start of the\nexamination was getting nearer, I was so nervous that I couldn’t think clearly and my hands had\nbegun to shake. All of a sudden, I found some tiny chocolate bars in my pocket, and they saved\nmy life! In the end, it turned out that my brother remembered to put some in my pocket for me in\norder to avoid this situation. He was so thoughtful and smart to do such a thing!","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"think outside of the box","vi":"tư duy khác biệt và sáng tạo"},{"en":"comes to mind","vi":"nảy ra trong đầu; nghĩ đến đầu tiên"},{"en":"make very quick decisions","vi":"đưa ra quyết định rất nhanh"},{"en":"level-headed","vi":"bình tĩnh và sáng suốt"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a person who knows a lot/is knowledgeable","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-107","_displayNo":"#107","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a person you know\nYou should say:\n- Who this person is.\n- How long you have known each other.\n- How you got to know him/her.\n- How you feel about this person.","answer":"I am going to talk about a friend I met in college who goes by the name Moon.\nI met her during our freshman year orientation, and I personally think I was very lucky to have\nbeen introduced to her. She is a Chinese student whom everybody adores. I have known her for\n3 years, and in all those 3 years, I have never once been bored by her or her presence. She is\nalways <strong class=\"key-phrase\">energetic and fun to be with</strong>. We had a lot of classes together in our first year and she\nalways came to help me with my homework in the weekends. I got to know her better through\nour reviews for exams together and our hangouts after class. Cheerful as she might have appeared\nto be, she received a lot of pressure from her parents about good grades and getting into a good\ngraduate school. I admire the way she always tried to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">stay positive despite all the stress</strong> she was\nunder.\nNow that we’re in our final year of university, I do not see her as often anymore. But <strong class=\"key-phrase\">once in a while</strong>,\nshe sends me a message to check how I am doing with my schoolwork and I really appreciate her\nfor that. Either way, I know that I have cherished our time together, and that whether or not we\ncan keep being in each other’s lives, I will always look back on our college experiences with great\nfondness.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"energetic and fun to be with","vi":"tràn đầy năng lượng và vui vẻ khi ở cạnh"},{"en":"stay positive despite all the stress","vi":"giữ tinh thần tích cực bất chấp áp lực"},{"en":"once in a while","vi":"thỉnh thoảng"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a person you know","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-108","_displayNo":"#108","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a person you know who is beautiful or handsome.\nYou should say:\nWho the person is\nWhen you met the person at the first time\nWhat the person’s character\nAnd explain how you feel about the person.","answer":"I would like to tell you about a man who used to be a role model for me when I was growing up, and\nthat is my older brother. I have to say that I really looked up to him. He is 8 years older than me,\nand we took different paths. He is tall, strong, charming and extremely confident. His appearance\nand strength slightly resembles the Superman that often appeared on TV throughout my\nchildhood. In school he was not good in academic subjects like math or physics, but he was highly\ncapable in all kinds of sport, which was completely diametrical to me. I was born small and weak,\nbut fortunately I could pick up words and solve math problems a little bit faster than my peers.\nHowever, as you can easily guess, it was my brother that all girls in my school paid attention to.\nHe was also a leader of his own gang. I know a gang sounds a bit naughty but they did not cause\nany problems to the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">local community</strong> or anything. Rarely did I see him walk alone, there were\nalways some cool-looking dudes accompanying him, like following an alpha wolf. He often got\ninvolved in a fight to prove his power in school, and I never saw him lose. Of course, my father,\nwho is a high school teacher, did not like that. He often punished my brother in the hope of changing\nhis eldest son into something “better”, like me, without knowing that it was my brother that I\nadmired so much. However, my brother was stubborn, so despite all my father’s efforts, he did not\nchange a bit, at least not until he got seriously injured in a fight with 20 gangsters. After that, he\ntransformed into a different person. Now he has his own family, a wife and a son. If you look at\nhim now, you would never guess that mature man used to do a bunch of crazy stuff. I still look up\nto him, but no longer because of all those badass things from the past. Now I admire his calmness\nand confidence when facing a difficult situation, and I am happy that my brother has changed in a\npositive way.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"local community","vi":"cộng đồng địa phương"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a person you know who is beautiful or handsome","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-109","_displayNo":"#109","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a place where you often visit with your friends or family\nYou should say:\nWhere the place is\nHow you know the place\nHow you go there\nWhy you want to visit","answer":"I would like to share with you the Freedom Park which is situated in the heart of district 4.\nThis is a fantastic place for people who want to enjoy fresh air and a cool breeze in the early\nmorning without any noise from vehicles on the streets. As I told you just now, I am residing in\nDistrict 4 and since the first time I moved there, I have taken notice of Freedom Park due to its\ntranquility.\nEach and every morning, people in the locality go to the park <strong class=\"key-phrase\">to take a stroll</strong> and work out to kick\noff their new day full of energy. The interesting thing is that the place offers people a variety of\npublic sports facilities that people can use to boost their <strong class=\"key-phrase\">mental wellness</strong>. Apart from that, at the\ntop of the hill in the park, there is a lovely small cafe that sells some kinds of breakfast food such\nas hamburgers, sausage, Pho and fried rice. After a few hours of doing exercise people can enjoy\na good cheap breakfast.\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">If my memory serves me right</strong>, the first time I went there was two years ago with my girlfriend. It\nwas incredibly peaceful, especially when the night fell and all the lights were on. My girlfriend and\nI walked along the small paths flowing through the park, hand in hand together. Everything was\nabsolutely romantic.\nFor all these reasons, Freedom Park always comes out on top of my list when it comes to a place\nwhere I can get back to nature and put my feet up. In the future, I hope I have more spare time to\ngo there with my family and friends in order to enjoy such a peaceful and relaxing atmosphere.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"to take a stroll","vi":"đi dạo thư thả"},{"en":"mental wellness","vi":"sức khỏe tinh thần"},{"en":"If my memory serves me right","vi":"nếu tôi nhớ không nhầm"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a place where you often visit with your friends or family","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-110","_displayNo":"#110","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a polite person you met\nYou should say:\nWho the person is\nHow you know the person\nWhat the person looks like\nAnd explain why you think the person is polite.","answer":"Well, the person I would like to talk to you about is a very good friend of mine, Mai. She must be one\nof the nicest and most polite individuals I know.\nWe’ve basically known each other since forever because we were in the same class from high\nschool through to college. She is like my partner in crime and we can share everything together\nfrom schoolwork to our love lives.\nYou know, the first time I met her she <strong class=\"key-phrase\">left a deep impression on me</strong> because on the first day of\nschool I got lost while trying to find my classroom and she really <strong class=\"key-phrase\">helped me out</strong>. Surprisingly, we\nwere also arranged by the teacher to be desk-mates.\nAnd the reason why I think she is so polite is simply because she has really <strong class=\"key-phrase\">good manners</strong>. She\nabuses the word “thank you” even on the slightest occasion. For instance, I have noticed that\nwhenever we eat at a restaurant, she will thank the waiters whenever they bring a dish to the\ntable. And another example would be that every time she gets off a bus, she will always say thank\nyou to the driver, which a lot of people probably think is not necessary, but I am sure the waiters and\nbus drivers really appreciate it. Finally, whenever our classmates ask her to help them with difficult\nhomework, she never complains or shows any hesitation. And due to this, she always <strong class=\"key-phrase\">maintains a\ngood reputation</strong> thanks to her politeness.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"left a deep impression on me","vi":"để lại ấn tượng sâu sắc với tôi"},{"en":"helped me out","vi":"giúp tôi vượt qua khó khăn"},{"en":"good manners","vi":"cách cư xử tốt"},{"en":"maintains a good reputation","vi":"duy trì danh tiếng tốt"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a polite person you met","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-111","_displayNo":"#111","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a project or a piece of work you did together with someone\nYou should say:\n- What it was\n- What you have done\n- Why you have chosen this person(s) to work with\nAnd explain what you did to finish the project.","answer":"I am going to tell you about a project I did with my younger sister that I have always taken pride in. And\nthat’s my mother’s 50th birthday party, which took place last year.\nTo be frank, I am not usually a very good team mate, and most projects I have ever done always\nend up in disaster. That’s why I couldn’t care less when the little girl brought up the idea of\nthrowing a surprise birthday party for mother. I was pretty sure I would mess everything up.\nHowever, my sister was so determined and she literally forced me to prepare everything with her.\nI did hesitate, of course, but <strong class=\"key-phrase\">on second thoughts</strong>, I was also quite curious about mother’s reaction\nthe moment she would <strong class=\"key-phrase\">be taken by surprise</strong>.\nSo I was in. At first, I planned to just buy mother a gift for fear that I might ruin everything. Khanh,\nmy little sister, was not very pleased with my intention to quit. And rather, she just told me to make\nmother a video full of our memories together, and I couldn’t do anything but follow her orders.\nFinally, mother’s birthday came. She did not even remember it; let alone be aware of what we had\ndone, because we agreed to keep it a secret beforehand. Right at the moment she came home,\nshe was really taken aback by a note telling her to come to the kitchen. All the lights in the house\nhad been turned off, so she had to carefully make her way there. When she got there, we played\nthe video and her favourite song. She stood still for a moment, and then tears of joy streamed\ndown her face. We knew we had got her.\nAfter all, the plan turned out to be quite a success, and besides a sense of accomplishment, I also\nfelt really thankful to see my mother so happy for the first time in a while.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"on second thoughts","vi":"sau khi suy nghĩ lại"},{"en":"be taken by surprise","vi":"bị bất ngờ"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a project or a piece of work you did together with someone","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-112","_displayNo":"#112","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a situation when someone made noise\nYou should say:\nwhen it happened\nwho made the noise\nwhere it was\nAnd explain how you felt about it.","answer":"So I am going to talk about when my neighbour <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made a lot of noise</strong> when he renovated his house a\nfew months ago. The noise of the drills, hammers and other power tools during the daytime was\nreally annoying.\nI heard that a newcomer had bought the house next to mine and because of some problems with\nwater leakage; he had made up his mind to do some repairs and renovations to the house, and\nafter that, the noise of hammers, saws, and drills seemed to be endless around my house all day\nlong, even on the weekends. My neighbour wanted to live in his house as soon as possible so he\nwould start the work early every morning, and that made my family members and I wake up earlier\nthan usual.\nDuring this time I felt extremely exhausted and I really wanted to make a complaint so that my\nneighbour would take some actions but his house renovations were legal so there was nothing I\ncould do. Hearing the noise all the time drove me crazy, and had quite a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">negative impact</strong> on my\nwork.\nSometimes I was sleepless all night. But luckily, after about a month or so, my neighbour finished\nthe renovations and the terrible construction noises ceased. I finally felt relieved!","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"made a lot of noise","vi":"gây ra rất nhiều tiếng ồn"},{"en":"negative impact","vi":"tác động tiêu cực"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a situation when someone made noise","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-113","_displayNo":"#113","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a sports person you admire\nYou should say:\n- Who is he/she.\n- What did he/she do.\n- What do you know about his/her life story.\n- How much do you know about sports.","answer":"Being a big fan of basketball, I have long idolised the legend of this sport - Michael Jordan, also\nknown as MJ. I first got curious about his life when I saw a logo portraying him on a product of the\nbrand, Nike, and his life turned out to be intriguing to me.\nHe played in the position of shooting guard in one of the most renowned teams, the Chicago Bulls,\nand was famous for his exceptional leaping ability, illustrated by performing slam dunks from the\nfree throw line. Early in his NBA career, while playing for the University of North Carolina, he\nappeared on the cover of Sports Illustrated with the heading “A star is born” just over a month into\nhis professional career. It was not only his talent but also his dedication that made him a strong\nclutch performer. He spent hours studying films of his opponents to improve his defense. Even\nwhen his right knee was injured, Jordan did not miss any games in the season from 1986 to 2001.\nThroughout his career, he led the Chicago Bulls to six championships, was awarded the NBA Most\nValuable Player five times and was the first player to be honoured with both the NBA’s Defensive\nPlayer of the year award and Most Valuable Player awards. All the compliments that journalists\ngave him were not an overstatement.\nAlthough Michael Jordan retired in 2003, his skills and his legacy are still <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a great inspiration</strong> for\nany basketball player or person considering pursuing a basketball career. He is also active in charity\nactivities. His clothing line, Jordan brand, has made donations to different organisations across\nAmerica. It’s difficult to describe how amazing Michael Jordan is in words, just watch a few of his\nvideos playing in NBA games or his interviews, you’ll figure it out yourself.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"a great inspiration","vi":"một nguồn cảm hứng lớn"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a sports person you admire","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-114","_displayNo":"#114","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a time when someone helped you\nYou should say:\nWho helped you\nWhen it was\nWhy s/he helped you\nAnd describe how you felt about it.","answer":"I am going to tell you about a time when I received support from a stranger. You know, it was back\na month ago when I was on my way back home from work when it was very late. Everything was\nfine until a sudden torrential rain poured down and my raincoat was nowhere to be found. Even\nworse, I couldn’t find any shop or house on the roadsides with a cover where I could hide for a\nwhile. So, I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">kept moving on</strong>, accepting the worst-case scenario that I would be as wet as a drowned\nrat.\nBut then, from my <strong class=\"key-phrase\">rear-view mirror</strong>, I noticed a young woman who tried to chase me with her\nmotorbike. When she got loser, her voice was loud enough for me realize her suggestion to help\nme by giving me her extra raincoat. I was rather skeptical at first as my mother always warns me not\nto trust anyone in the street, but after looking at her, I knew that her sincerity should not be\nquestioned. I then received the raincoat with both hands and looked at her with my deepest\nappreciation. She gave me a warm smile and asked me to keep the raincoat for myself. I looked at\nher until she disappeared in the distance, and then headed home.\nI was still soaked when I got home. However, it was the kindness of the woman that warmed me\nfrom inside my heart. Obviously, she was no one I had ever met before but was willing to help me\nfor no reward, and her humanity in this society was something I would always cherish.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"kept moving on","vi":"tiếp tục tiến về phía trước"},{"en":"rear-view mirror","vi":"gương chiếu hậu"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a time when someone helped you","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-115","_displayNo":"#115","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a time when someone visited your home\nYou should say:\n- Who he or she was\n- When it happened\n- What you did\n- How you felt about the visit","answer":"So it was around 4 months ago since I invited one of my very close friends to come over to my\nhouse for dinner. It was Christmas Eve, and my friend is an expat living far away from home. As I\ndid not want him to spend his Christmas alone, I asked him to join my family for a special family\ndinner. My friend is an American, and since he couldn’t have turkey on Thanksgiving that year, my\nmother decided to make turkey for him that night.\nOne of the funny things I remember about that night was that pretty much all the cooking\nappliances in my house were electrical, even the stove and all of a sudden it was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a blackout</strong> an\nhour right before dinner time so by the time my friend got to my house, none of the food was\nready. I was quite embarrassed, but my friend was pretty cool about it. We lit up the candles and\nmy father went out to buy some bread and ham. We were talking and eating while waiting for the\npower to turn back on. We had an absolutely amazing time talking about <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the cultural differences</strong>,\nhow hospitable Vietnamese people are, and how <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the language barrier</strong> did not stop him from getting\nto know the locals.\nAnyway, we got to eat the turkey after a two-hour delay. Even though my mother made it quite\ndifferently from the way my friend’s family did, he really enjoyed it. And I must say that my parents\nabsolutely adored him after that night. Since then, he has been coming over more often and\nbecoming a very close friend to our family.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"a blackout","vi":"một đợt mất điện"},{"en":"the cultural differences","vi":"những khác biệt văn hóa"},{"en":"the language barrier","vi":"rào cản ngôn ngữ"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a time when someone visited your home","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-116","_displayNo":"#116","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a toy that you received when you were a child.\nYou should say:\n- What the toy was.\n- Who gave it to you.\n- How you used it.\n- An explanation of how you felt when you got this toy.","answer":"Well, the first <strong class=\"key-phrase\">sentimental item</strong> that came to mind when I saw this topic was the stuffed animal\nnamed Marsupilami. This special toy was a birthday present. I can't remember exactly how old I\nwas, but I was probably about 5 or 6. This toy was important to me because I longed for it and it\nwas a gift from my parents.\nThe toy was identical to the character in the cartoon I had watched. Therefore, I felt as if he had\ncome from the movie. Marsupilami was a black-spotted yellow monkey-like creature with dog-like\nears. The character was characterised by an incredibly long, strong and flexible tail, used for almost\nany task.\nAs a kid, this was a fascinating and exciting toy for me. In the beginning, I did not allow any of my\ncousins and friends to touch Marsupilami. Marsupilami used to sit proudly on my bed each and\nevery day, and every night he \"slept\" next to my pillow.\nThanks to the toy, I experienced a happy childhood. As the saying goes, \"Teddy bears don't need\nhearts as they are already stuffed with love.\" This is also true for my beloved Marsupilami.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"sentimental item","vi":"vật có giá trị tình cảm"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a toy that you received when you were a child","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-117","_displayNo":"#117","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe a visitor in your home\nYou should say:\n- Who this visitor was.\n- When he/she visited your home.\n- Why he/she came to visit.\n- Whether you liked him/her or not","answer":"Today I would like to talk about one of the guests who visited my family and left a great impression\non me. His name was Armane, a Frenchman and my brother’s business partner for more than 2\nyears. I heard from my mother that my brother <strong class=\"key-phrase\">happened to meet</strong> him at yoga and meditation\nclass. Last week, he came to our house to say goodbye before returning to Paris.\nArmane had a masculine look, with large blue eyes and a wide forehead. His sharp nose looked\nperfect, too. Although he was European, he seemed to have a profound understanding of\nVietnamese culture. The way he used the chopsticks and rolled the vegetables with rice paper told\nme that he was deeply aware of our customary table manners. Armane also shared with us that\nat first he found it really stressful to follow such <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a minefield of social no-nos</strong>.\nWithin a week of his visit, Armane surprised us with a thank-you card which he meticulously made\nhimself. We were really happy to hear from Armane. Although my parents were understanding of\nforeigners’ unfamiliarity with the norms of Vietnamese society, they were really impressed that\nArmane had mastered many traditional practices. He <strong class=\"key-phrase\">earned our utmost respect</strong>.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"happened to meet","vi":"tình cờ gặp"},{"en":"a minefield of social no-nos","vi":"một loạt điều cấm kỵ dễ mắc phải trong giao tiếp"},{"en":"earned our utmost respect","vi":"nhận được sự tôn trọng sâu sắc của chúng tôi"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a visitor in your home","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-118","_displayNo":"#118","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe an adventurous person who you know.\nYou should say:\nWho the person is\nHow you know this person\nWhat this person does that is adventurous\nAnd explain why you think this person likes to take risks.","answer":"Although I do not know this person personally, I am going to talk about Bear Grylls, a famous\nadventurer with his own survival show on the National Geographic channel.\nYou do not need much explanation when you hear this name. Bear Grylls is an embodiment of\nadventure and courage himself. In his show, he went to remote places with harsh conditions to\ntry to survive for several days. He would then try to find food and water in the most unlikely\nplaces, sometimes hunting wild animals or eating bugs just to survive. I feel like there’s nothing\nthis guy is afraid to do. I mean, he even drank his own urine and ate an animal eye once.\nI do not know why he is such a risk-taker but I think he is just really confident in his survival skills.\nWhatever comes his way, he can cope with it and make it till the end. Besides, he made this show\nto teach people what to do when they are stuck in the same situation so he had to set a good\nexample for them.\nI am really <strong class=\"key-phrase\">in awe of</strong> Bear. I do not even dare to eat bugs so I cannot imagine going through his ordeal.\nNow that he is a bit old, I do not know if he is going to continue with his show but probably he will.\nHe is a tough guy.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"in awe of","vi":"vô cùng ngưỡng mộ"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an adventurous person who you know","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-119","_displayNo":"#119","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe an experience that you taught a friend or a relative.\nYou should say:\n- When it happened and what it was;\n- Who was taught by you;\n- Why you taught someone something;\n- How difficult it was for you.","answer":"The experience I am going to tell you about is that I taught my mother how to use Facebook to\nsend messages and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">keep in touch with</strong> people. My mother is an middle-aged woman marching towards her\n50s. She did not attend college but went to work directly after high school, which was quite\ncommon in her era. Ever since marriage, the focus of her life has been the family. She made sure\nmy father and I eat well and dress well, and we have a nice clean house too.\nThus she did not have much time to pay attention to the development of technology and often\nfelt puzzled facing all those <strong class=\"key-phrase\">high-tech devices</strong> like smartphones, laptops and smart televisions.\nLast year, my mother asked me whether I knew how to post statuses and pictures through\nFacebook since her friends were getting used to up-to-date technology and messaging through apps\nlike Facebook or Viber became pretty popular. I said of course and patiently showed her how to\nopen the app, how to log in and use all the functions of the app. She was so careful that she even\nwrote down all the procedures. After several practice attempts, she could do this by herself. I saw\na big smile appear on her face.\nI didn't <strong class=\"key-phrase\">find it difficult to</strong> teach a woman like my mother to use modern devices, and using them\nallowed her to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">catch up with</strong> her friends and also what’s happening in the world.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"keep in touch with","vi":"giữ liên lạc với"},{"en":"high-tech devices","vi":"các thiết bị công nghệ cao"},{"en":"find it difficult to","vi":"cảm thấy khó để"},{"en":"catch up with","vi":"trò chuyện và cập nhật tình hình với"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an experience that you taught a friend or a relative","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-120","_displayNo":"#120","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe an experience when you spent time with a child.\nYou should say:\nWhen you spent time with this child\nWho this child was\nWhat you did together\nAnd how you felt about the experience.","answer":"So, I would like to tell you about an experience when I spent time with a kid. It was when I was about\n15 years old and I had to look after my brother’s 2 year old son, who is my nephew. It was on a\nweekend one time when I was visiting my brother and his wife and their son. My brother’s wife\nwas at work that day and he had to go out to the shops to pick-up some groceries to cook for\ndinner, but instead of all of us go together, he decided that it would be much more convenient if\nhe went alone and I stayed at home to look after my nephew while he was gone. At first I was a\nbit shocked that he came up with this idea because I had never looked after a small child on my\nown before and I was a bit nervous and did not know what to do or what to expect, especially if\nsomething went wrong. But my brother reassured me that he would only be gone for about 30\nminutes or so and that everything would be fine, and if I needed to contact him in an emergency\nthen I should just call him on his mobile phone. So I reluctantly agreed.\nAnyway, so my brother went off to the supermarket and I stayed at home with my nephew. At\nfirst I think I just put on one of his favourite cartoons on the TV to try and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">keep him occupied</strong> for\na while, but this only worked for so long. After around 15 minutes, he got bored of that and wanted\nto do something else, so I then went and got all of his toys from his bedroom and brought them\nout into the lounge room and tipped them on the floor. We then made a big mess playing with his\ntoys for about 10 minutes before he quickly became bored again. So then after that I went to the\nkitchen and found some of his favourite snacks and we sat back down to watch cartoons again on\nthe television and eat the snacks. After about 5 minutes though, thankfully he fell asleep until my\nbrother arrived home. So, all in all, it was a fine experience I guess. I was quite relieved that nothing\nbad happened and I realized that it was not that difficult to look after small kids.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"keep him occupied","vi":"giúp cậu ấy luôn có việc để làm"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an experience when you spent time with a child","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-121","_displayNo":"#121","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe an interesting neighbour you know.\nYou should say:\nWho this person is\nHow you know this person\nWhat this person likes to do\nAnd explain why you think this neighbour is interesting.","answer":"I must say, I am extremely fortunate to have such a wonderful neighbour, Duy, who is really\nfriendly and always <strong class=\"key-phrase\">willing to assist</strong> me whenever I am in trouble.\nDuy and I live in the same building, and our apartments are next to each other. We came to know\neach other when the electricity to the entire building was cut off one evening. Unfortunately, I\nhad run out of candles and the torch was nowhere to be found, so I had to go to the apartment\nnext door for help, and this was when I first met my neighbour. He was extremely helpful and\nenthusiastic and he asked me to hold his torch while he lit the candles in his apartment. I was really\ngrateful for his help and a few days later, I made some snacks for him as a thank-you gift. Since\nthen, we have become quite close friends.\nThe more I got to know Duy, the more I began to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">look up to</strong> him. Even though he is well into his\nfifties and lives on his own, as he lost his family in a car accident, he still manages to see life\nthrough rose coloured glasses. His motto in life is “to keep moving forward”. He works and studies\nat the same time, and on the weekends, he travels to an orphanage to teach maths to the kids\nthere.\nHe really is a wonderful neighbour and I know I could call on him if I ever needed to. We will\nalways help each other out when we can, and because we both live on our own, it’s really important\nto have a good friend close by.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"willing to assist","vi":"sẵn lòng giúp đỡ"},{"en":"look up to","vi":"ngưỡng mộ và xem là hình mẫu"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an interesting neighbour you know","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-122","_displayNo":"#122","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe an interesting person from another country.\nYou should say:\n- Who this person is;\n- How you know this person;\n- What this person does;\n- Why this person is interesting.","answer":"Today I am going to tell you about an interesting person from another country that I really admire\nand respect. I am currently studying English at ZIM English center and there are a lot of\nforeign teachers who are very kind, well-mannered and friendly. Among them, I would pick\nMr. Vincent as the loveliest one I have met.\nMr. Vincent comes from America, the most developed country in the world, and he has lived\nin Vietnam for 2 years. He has acquired a reputation as a profound and dedicated teacher at\nmy English school, I usually find him leaving for work early and getting home late. He first\napplied to Zim a year ago and since then he has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">endeared himself to</strong> everybody in the school.\nWhat I find most appealing about him is that he is so polite and he has really good manners.\nHe uses the word “thank you” even on the slightest occasion. For instance, I have noticed that\nwhenever we eat at a restaurant, he will thank the waiters whenever they bring a dish to the\ntable. And another example would be that every time he gets off a bus, he will always say thank\nyou to the driver, which a lot of people probably think is not necessary, but I am sure the waiters\nand bus drivers really appreciate it. Whenever his students ask him to help them with difficult\nhomework, he never complains or shows any hesitation. And due to this, he always maintains a\ngood reputation thanks to his politeness.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"endeared himself to","vi":"khiến mọi người yêu mến"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an interesting person from another country","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-123","_displayNo":"#123","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe an occasion that someone or something made noise\nYou should say:\n- When this happened\n- Who this person was/what this thing was\n- What kinds of noise was\nAnd explain what you did when you heard the noise.","answer":"I remember a period last year when the apartment above mine was being renovated. The work began at about seven every morning, and the loudest sound came from an electric drill being used on the concrete floor. Because I was preparing lessons from home, the noise <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made it almost impossible</strong> to concentrate.\n\nAt first, I tried to tolerate it because renovation work is temporary. After several days, however, the drilling continued outside the building's permitted hours, so I spoke to the neighbour calmly rather than confronting the workers. I explained that the sound was disrupting both my work and my sleep, and I asked whether the noisiest tasks could be limited to the middle of the day.\n\nThe neighbour was apologetic and arranged a clearer schedule with the contractor. From then on, I worked at a library during the two-hour drilling period, while the workers avoided early mornings. The experience taught me that a practical complaint is more effective when it includes <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a reasonable solution</strong> instead of anger. It also showed the value of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">addressing a problem directly</strong> before frustration builds up.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"made it almost impossible","vi":"khiến việc đó gần như không thể"},{"en":"a reasonable solution","vi":"một giải pháp hợp lý"},{"en":"addressing a problem directly","vi":"giải quyết vấn đề một cách trực tiếp"}],"source":"Prompt adapted from ZIM; answer rewritten and quality-audited by ChatGPT","subtype":"","summary":"an occasion that someone or something made noise","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-124","_displayNo":"#124","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe an occasion when you helped a person.\nYou should say:\n- What the situation was\n- Who you helped\n- How you helped\n- How you felt after giving help.","answer":"There are many times I ask myself what I have to do to be able to provide support for others.\nHowever, when I got a thank you from a stranger, a little boy, I realised helping was such a simple\nthing to do. I helped him without even knowing it.\nI cannot recall the exact time and date. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">To the best of my recollection</strong>, I had a day off work, and I\nsaw a boy selling balloons and other toys at a street fair. He looked at the crowd in despair, since\nno one showed any interest in his stuff. I went over to him and I saw his eyes light up. I bought a\nfew toys and asked him some questions. From his answers, I knew that he was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">having a hard time</strong>,\nwhich can drive anyone to tears. His mother was in shock after his father had walked out on the\nfamily <strong class=\"key-phrase\">out of the blue</strong>. She could not work anymore due to her state of mind. He had to earn\nmoney for him, his mother and his younger sister to live.\nWhen I got back from holiday, I took a picture of the toys and posted it on my Facebook page with\na caption about the boy’s story. I also named the street where he was selling and called on my\nfriends to buy his stuff if possible. It’s hard to imagine the effect of a social networking site like\nFacebook. However, tons of people came to buy his stuff and offer him help. After some months,\nI returned to visit him. He and his mother showed me great appreciation and said that my simple\naction had changed their life. They couldn’t have asked for more, and I couldn’t be happier.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"To the best of my recollection","vi":"theo những gì tôi nhớ rõ nhất"},{"en":"having a hard time","vi":"đang trải qua giai đoạn khó khăn"},{"en":"out of the blue","vi":"bất ngờ; không báo trước"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an occasion when you helped a person","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-125","_displayNo":"#125","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe an old friend you enjoy talking with\nYou should say:\nWho this person is\nHow you knew him/her\nWhat you usually talk about\nAnd explain why you want to talk to this person","answer":"I am going to tell you about Nguyen, one of my university friends. Among all of the people I have met,\nNguyen is perhaps the most approachable and funny guy. Back in college, we used to hang out a\nlot until he went abroad for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">further education</strong>.\nNguyen was not my classmate, and we are not in the same clubs at university either. I just met him\nby chance when we were both candidates in a citywide singing contest in our second year. At that\ntime, he was an average guy with a silly smile always on his face, but of course that was not what\nmade me notice him. I actually never did, until we bumped into each other at school a few months\nlater. We talked more after that and became great friends since then.\nIf there is something special about Nguyen, that has to be his way of speaking. He used to speak\nin such a charming voice and include a lot of playful jokes, which always cracked me up even when\nI was in a bad mood. Also, we shared a lot in common, from our passion towards music and all\nkinds of instruments to our love interests. I was really in awe the first time I found out about his\ncrush on a girl in his class, because if I were a boy, I would definitely be crazy about her.\nThese things would be enough to explain why we can talk with each other for hours. Sometimes,\nI even spent the whole day, from 7 in the morning to 10 in the evening, to just lie next to him on\nthe floor of a quiet café, and just talk. What really surprises me is that we did not start a romantic\nrelationship as people around us expected. After all, I finally found my lover, and so did he. We’re\nstill friends, great friends, but at the moment, we’ve got our own lives and our own relationships.\nHowever, he is still, to me, the best person I like to talk to.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"further education","vi":"giáo dục sau phổ thông; học tập nâng cao"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an old friend you enjoy talking with","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-126","_displayNo":"#126","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe one of your best friends\nYou should say:\n- What this person looks like\n- When and where you met this person\n- What you do when you are together\nAnd explain why he/she is one of your best friends","answer":"Well, the person I would like to talk to you about is a very good friend of mine, Mai. She must be one\nof the nicest and most down-to-earth individuals I know.\nIf I were to describe how she looks I would say Mai is a very gorgeous and charming girl who\nalways attracts a lot of attention from men. She is much taller than me so it’s kind of embarrassing\nstanding next to her to be honest. Mai also has straight brown hair and deep, dark brown eyes.\nLike most teenagers, she pays a lot of attention to her appearance and likes dressing in the latest\nand most snazzy fashion. I do not think I have ever seen her in a plain old T- shirt or jeans.\nAnyway, we’ve basically known each other since forever because we were in the same class from\nhigh school through to college. You know, the first time I met her, she left a deep impression on\nme because on the first day at school, I got lost while trying to find my classroom and she was my\nsaviour. Coincidentally, we were arranged by the teacher to become desk-mates.\nAnd with regards to why she became my bestie, well, I guess the main reason is that we really hit\nit off right from the start, and we also see eye to eye on a lot of things such as fashion, sport and\neven video games. She is my closest friend so I feel like we can share everything together, from\nschoolwork to our love lives. The thing I admire most about Mai is that she is really protective and\nlikes to look after people.\nAs a normal human being, however, Mai also has her shortcomings. She is never on time, and is\nsometimes quite <strong class=\"key-phrase\">absent-minded</strong> and inconsiderate and that makes people think she never takes\nthings seriously. But I do not think this is true. She has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a strong sense of responsibility</strong> and I know\nthat I can always rely on her. For me, friendship is the most important thing in the world and I am\nproud to say that I have such a loyal and helpful friend – she is really one in a million.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"absent-minded","vi":"đãng trí; thiếu tập trung"},{"en":"a strong sense of responsibility","vi":"ý thức trách nhiệm cao"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"one of your best friends","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-127","_displayNo":"#127","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe someone who is a good parent.\nYou should say:\n- Who the person is.\n- How you know him/her.\n- What the person do.\n- Why you think he/she is good.","answer":"Speaking of a role model in parenting, I would like to talk about my best friend’s father.\nHe is working as a doctor and due to his <strong class=\"key-phrase\">tight working schedule</strong>, I do not have many chances to talk\nto him, even though I come over his house <strong class=\"key-phrase\">on a frequent basis</strong>. However, I still know him very well\nthrough stories told by my best friend. Also, her <strong class=\"key-phrase\">well-educated</strong> manner proves to me that he has\ndone a good job raising her up. Vietnamese parents are known to be “tiger parents”, but he should\nbe considered an exception. He respects his daughter’s decisions and never forces her to do\nthings that are not at her will. Unlike other doctors, he always encourages her to pursue her dream\nto be a singer rather than follow the family line of work in the medical field. Even when she causes\ntrouble and receives bad grades at school, she is not afraid to tell her father because she knows that\nhe is more than a parent to her, he is truly a friend who can give her good advice and help her find\npossible ways of improving herself.\nYou know, being a doctor is not just <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a nine to five job</strong>, he has to work on a night shift several times\na week, but he still managed to take good care of his child. He is good at maintaining a work-life\nbalance. He allocates the whole weekend apart from work and social life to spend time with his\nfamily where he often teaches his daughter cooking and survival skills. Sometimes he takes her to\nthe cinema to watch the latest blockbusters so that they can have a discussion on movies and\nrelated life situations. All in all, he is the type of parent that I wish to become in the future.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"tight working schedule","vi":"lịch làm việc dày đặc"},{"en":"on a frequent basis","vi":"một cách thường xuyên"},{"en":"well-educated","vi":"được giáo dục tốt; có học thức"},{"en":"a nine to five job","vi":"công việc hành chính từ chín giờ đến năm giờ"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"someone who is a good parent","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-128","_displayNo":"#128","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe someone you admire who is much older than you\nYou should say:\nwho this person is\nhow long you have known him/ her\nwhat qualities he/ she has\nAnd say why you admire him/ her.","answer":"Well, the first person who came to my mind is my grandmother. She is almost in her 80’s and she\nhas always been a major influence on me.\nI guess I could say that I have known my grandmother my whole life because she was actually there\nthe day I was born, and after the death of my grandfather she started to live in our house, so I was\nlucky enough to grow up and pass my adolescent years with her love and affection.\nSince my childhood, she has always cared and loved me with all of her heart, and she is a really\nkind and wise woman which is why I always turn to her for advice. I think she is a compassionate\nperson with a big heart, and always tries to help others whenever she can, and I can recall many\noccasions when she <strong class=\"key-phrase\">took great risks</strong> to help other people out.\nShe is also a successful mother of four children, one of whom is my father. She has devoted her\nentire life for the betterment of her kids, educating and guiding them to become good people. She\npossesses a very charming personality and always pleases everyone around her. Even a stranger\ncan feel the warmth of her heart within only a short time.\nI could really talk about her all day long because I love and admire her for many reasons. But I must\nsay, the most important reason is her unconditional love for me. She is a great mentor who always\nshows me the positive side of things and guides me through my hardest times. Talking to her is a\nsoothing experience and the stories she tells are always informative and full of important lessons\nand morals. I think she has had a great influence on my attitude in life and on my personality, and\nfor all these reasons there’s a strong bond between us, and I admire her very much.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"took great risks","vi":"chấp nhận những rủi ro lớn"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"someone you admire who is much older than you","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-129","_displayNo":"#129","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe something you enjoy doing with an old person in your family\nYou should say:\n- What it is\n- How often you do it\n- Who you do it with\n- Why you enjoy doing it with this person","answer":"Well, now I am going to tell you something about an activity that I am particularly keen on doing\nwith my 80-year-old grandmother, which is watching an Indian soap opera series on TV. Honestly,\nthe series that we like best is “8-year-old bride” and it is broadcast every day on Today TV.\nThe first time my grandma and I knew about this TV series was about 4 months ago after seeing\nthe 1st episode of it. As I still remember, on that day, we were both highly impressed by a character\nin the film called Anandi and since then, we have never missed even a single episode. This series\nmainly tells the story of a girl named Anandi, who had to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">live a miserable life</strong> since she was in a\nforced marriage at the age of 8. After that, she also encountered several difficulties and pains\nthroughout her life.\nAs I mentioned, this series is shown every evening at 8 pm and I always try my best to arrange my\nwork so that I can enjoy it with my beloved grandma. During the time we watch, she also tells a\nlot of things about the meaningful details in each episode, which I could hardly realise if watching\nalone. In fact, I have learned quite a lot of wonderful lessons from both this series and my\ngrandmother and the most important lesson would be: “Getting married too early can be the most\nterrible mistake that one can make”.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"live a miserable life","vi":"sống một cuộc đời khổ sở"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"something you enjoy doing with an old person in your family","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-130","_displayNo":"#130","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe something you learned in a place or from someone\nYou should say:\nWhat it was\nWhere or who you got it\nWhat the situation was\nHow you felt","answer":"I am so lucky to have the chance to learn so many things from the people around me; the list of\nthings I have learned would be a very long one. I would like to emphasize one thing that I learned\nfrom a middle-aged woman in my neighborhood, and that is the pleasure of voluntary activities.\nWe call her Ms. Lan. She was born and grew up during <strong class=\"key-phrase\">one of the most turbulent periods</strong> in\nVietnamese modern history. Now, in her late 50s, she became interested in trying to make a\ndifference — working for her own volunteer organization.\nShe has been running a group of dedicated, compassionate young people who are all committed\nto making a positive difference to the lives of senior citizens in nursing homes around the town.\n“Spending time with the elderly is very important, they do not always have relatives to visit them\nso I try to fill that gap and spend a bit of time with them. I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">have a rapport with</strong> elderly people, I am\na patient person and I like to sit down and talk to them,” she once told us.\nDuring my working under her guidance, I have learned about the benefits of working as a volunteer.\nIf you have ever volunteered, you may have noticed that you felt fantastic afterward. Community\nservice can help you gain confidence by giving the chance to try something new and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">build a real\nsense of achievement</strong>. Besides, volunteering can help you meet different kinds of people and make\nnew friends.\nGenerally speaking, volunteering can have a real and valuable positive effect on people,\ncommunities and society. Besides, I believe that we can learn much about life from those who\nhave seen it almost to the end.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"one of the most turbulent periods","vi":"một trong những giai đoạn biến động nhất"},{"en":"have a rapport with","vi":"có sự đồng cảm và kết nối với"},{"en":"build a real sense of achievement","vi":"xây dựng cảm giác thành tựu thực sự"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"something you learned in a place or from someone","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-131","_displayNo":"#131","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Person","prompt":"Describe something you learned in a place/from a person.\nYou should say:\n- What you learned.\n- When this happened.\n- Where it was/ Who taught you.\n- How difficult it was to learn.","answer":"I am so lucky to have the chance to learn so many things from the people around me; the list of\nthings I have learned would be a very long one. I would like to emphasise one thing that I learned\nfrom a middle-aged woman in my neighborhood, and that is the pleasure of voluntary activities.\nWe call her Ms. Lan. She was born and grew up during <strong class=\"key-phrase\">one of the most turbulent periods</strong> in\nVietnamese modern history. Now, in her late 50s, she became interested in trying to make a\ndifference — working for her own volunteer organization.\nShe has been running a group of dedicated, compassionate young people who are all committed\nto making a positive difference to the lives of senior citizens in nursing homes around the town.\n“Spending time with the elderly is very important, they do not always have relatives to visit them\nso I try to fill that gap and spend a bit of time with them. I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">have a rapport with</strong> elderly people, I am\na patient person and I like to sit down and talk to them,” she once told us.\nDuring my working under her guidance, I have learned about the benefits of working as a volunteer.\nIf you have ever volunteered, you may have noticed that you felt fantastic afterward. Community\nservice can help you gain confidence by giving the chance to try something new and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">build a real\nsense of achievement</strong>. Besides, volunteering can help you meet different kinds of people and make\nnew friends.\nGenerally speaking, volunteering can have a real and valuable positive effect on people,\ncommunities and society. Besides, I believe that we can learn much about life from those who\nhave seen it almost to the end.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Person","phrases":[{"en":"one of the most turbulent periods","vi":"một trong những giai đoạn biến động nhất"},{"en":"have a rapport with","vi":"có sự đồng cảm và kết nối với"},{"en":"build a real sense of achievement","vi":"xây dựng cảm giác thành tựu thực sự"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"something you learned in a place/from a person","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-132","_displayNo":"#132","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a beautiful garden that you like.\nYou should say:\n- where it is\n- what you can see there\n- what people do there\n- and explain why you like it.","answer":"Today I'd like to describe my home garden, which I think is a beautiful one and which I like very much. The garden is part of my home's backyard, and my house is located in the suburbs, about a 1-hour drive from the city of San Francisco. There is a big tree right in the middle of my garden, which is surrounded by a hot tub, a small water fountain, several bushes, a section for vegetables, and different kinds of flowers. This garden was actually one of the reasons why my wife and I chose to buy our house because it had been <strong class=\"key-phrase\">beautifully maintained</strong> by the previous owner’s gardener and landscaper. It’s been only 1 year since we bought the house and now we are taking care of the garden ourselves. Even though we are not experts in gardening, we still try our best to plant things that we like, such as roses and tulips, and we even grow our own tomatoes. Whenever family and friends come to visit us, we invite them to have a relaxing time in our hot tub, and enjoy the view. So in other words, our garden has also become a kind of resort! It definitely requires lots of hard work to properly maintain the garden, but it gives us <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a great sense of accomplishment</strong> to “decorate” it the way we like. All in all, the garden is one of the best features of my home and it is a place where I can relax after a long day of work or during the weekends.","author":"Simon","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"beautifully maintained","vi":"được chăm sóc rất đẹp"},{"en":"a great sense of accomplishment","vi":"cảm giác thành tựu lớn"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a beautiful garden that you like","id":"speaking-part-2-133","_displayNo":"#133","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a café that you have been to.\nYou should say:\n- where it is\n- why you went there\n- what you ate or drank\n- and explain why you liked or disliked the café.","answer":"I am going to describe a café that I go to maybe once a week. It’s just down the road from where I live, near Manchester, so it’s really convenient for me to walk down there for a coffee or a bite to eat, and to use the wifi. The last time I went to this local café was on Friday afternoon. I was trying to do some work at home, but I found myself getting distracted by little jobs around the house. So I decided to have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a change of scenery</strong>; I put my laptop in my bag and made the short walk to the café, where I spent the next few hours getting all of my work done. With a nice cup of coffee and just the right level of background noise, I found it much easier to concentrate. Over the course of the afternoon, I drank two cups of coffee and a glass or two of water. The café owner takes a lot of pride in making the best ’flat white’ coffee in the area, so that’s what I tend to drink. If I remember correctly, the second coffee that I ordered was a decaf, because I try to avoid drinking too much caffeine in the afternoon. I did not have anything to eat on that occasion, but I do sometimes have one of the home-made cakes that they sell. There are a few reasons why I like going to my local café. I suppose the main reasons are the coffee, the free wifi and the friendly staff. However, on Friday I also managed to sit at my favourite table near one of the windows, and the café was not very busy. So the atmosphere and noise level were just right, and I was able to focus on my work without distractions for most of the afternoon.","author":"Simon","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"a change of scenery","vi":"sự thay đổi không gian và khung cảnh"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a café that you have been to","id":"speaking-part-2-134","_displayNo":"#134","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a festival that is important in your country\nYou should say:\n- when the festival occurs\n- what you did during it\n- what you like or dislike about it\n- and explain why this festival is important","answer":"I would like to describe Tet, the Lunar New Year, which is the most important traditional festival in Vietnam. It usually falls in late January or February and marks both the beginning of a new lunar year and a rare period when families can spend several uninterrupted days together.\n\nBefore Tet, my family cleans the house, prepares food and buys flowers. On New Year’s Eve, we have dinner together, and during the following days we visit relatives, give children lucky money and pay respect to our ancestors. What I enjoy most is the sense of renewal: unfinished disagreements are often put aside, and people begin the year with more generous intentions.\n\nThe only aspect I dislike is the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">commercial pressure</strong>. Travel becomes expensive, shops are crowded and some families feel obliged to spend more than they can afford. Even so, Tet remains deeply important because it preserves <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cultural identity</strong> and renews family bonds. For many people who live far from home, it is the one occasion when returning to their family takes priority over work.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"commercial pressure","vi":"áp lực thương mại"},{"en":"cultural identity","vi":"bản sắc văn hóa"}],"source":"Prompt adapted from IELTS Simon; answer rewritten and quality-audited by ChatGPT","subtype":"","summary":"a festival that is important in your country","id":"speaking-part-2-135","_displayNo":"#135","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a modern building.\nYou should say:\n- where it is\n- what it is used for\n- and why you like/dislike it.","answer":"I'm going to describe a modern building in Manchester. It's called the Beetham Tower, and it's the tallest building in the city, with about 50 floors. Although it's called the Beetham Tower, most people know this building as the Hilton Hotel. In fact, the bottom half of the tower is the hotel and the top half is apartments. The apartments are expensive because the location and views make them very desirable. I'm not sure if I like the design of the building, it's just a huge glass tower, but it definitely stands out. It has become <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a famous landmark</strong> in the city. You can see it as you approach Manchester, and it's an easy place to meet people because it's so distinctive and easy to find. The most interesting thing about the Beetham Tower is that there is a bar/restaurant on the 23rd floor which has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">spectacular views</strong> of the city; it's definitely the best vantage point in Manchester because there are no walls, only huge windows, so you can look out over the city in any direction. I'd recommend anyone who visits Manchester to go there and experience the view.","author":"Simon","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"a famous landmark","vi":"một địa danh nổi tiếng"},{"en":"spectacular views","vi":"tầm nhìn ngoạn mục"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a modern building","id":"speaking-part-2-136","_displayNo":"#136","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a place of entertainment (e. g. theatre, cinema,\nYou should say:\n- what this place would be\n- where it should be\n- and why you think this place of entertainment is needed","answer":"The place of entertainment that I wish we had close to where I live is a sports centre. My ideal sports centre would have a gym, swimming pool, indoor and outdoor football pitches, courts for tennis, badminton and squash, and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an all-purpose area</strong> for things like gymnastics and circuit training. I can think of the perfect place for this facility: There’s a disused piece of land just down the road from where I live, where an old warehouse was knocked down. It’s near to the main road and the train station, so it would be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">easy for people to get to</strong>. There are plans to build houses on this plot of land, but I think a sports centre would be much better for local residents. The good thing about a sports centre is that everyone can use it. There could be sports lessons and clubs for children and teenagers - things like swimming lessons and football team practice sessions. I am sure many adults in my local area would join the gym, use the pool, and book the courts for games of tennis or badminton. The centre could even hold sports events, such as competitions, that would <strong class=\"key-phrase\">attract spectators as well as participants</strong>. I think we need a good sports centre where I live because people currently have to travel to the next town if they want to find some of the facilities, activities, lessons and clubs that I have mentioned. I think a sports complex would give young people, in particular, something fun and productive to do in the evening and at weekends. Playing sport keeps people healthy and makes them feel happy, so I think a sports centre would <strong class=\"key-phrase\">brighten up my local area</strong> and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">improve our quality of life</strong>.","author":"Simon","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"an all-purpose area","vi":"một khu vực đa năng"},{"en":"easy for people to get to","vi":"thuận tiện để mọi người đi tới"},{"en":"attract spectators as well as participants","vi":"thu hút cả khán giả lẫn người tham gia"},{"en":"brighten up my local area","vi":"làm khu vực tôi sống trở nên sinh động hơn"},{"en":"improve our quality of life","vi":"cải thiện chất lượng cuộc sống của chúng tôi"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a place of entertainment (e.g. theatre, cinema,","id":"speaking-part-2-137","_displayNo":"#137","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a subject that you think should be removed from school\nYou should say:\n- what the subject is\n- why you think it is unnecessary for children to study it\n- and explain what you would replace it with.","answer":"I am going to suggest that art could be taken out of the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">school curriculum</strong>. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">In my experience</strong>, art lessons at school tend to include drawing, painting, and the making of collages using paper, fabric and other household materials. There are a few reasons why I think that school art lessons are unnecessary. Firstly, I do not believe that drawing and painting are essential skills that children will need when they leave school. Children might find these activities enjoyable, but it’s unlikely that they will need them in the working world. Secondly, children can draw, paint and make collages in their own time at home; parents can encourage this, and they can even join in. Finally, remembering my own art lessons at school, I do not think we learned any real art skills; the teachers left us to draw or create things, but they did not provide much technical instruction. Instead of art lessons, children could do more work on core subjects like maths, science or language. These subjects are more likely to help children in later life when they enter the job market, and I think both children and their teachers would benefit if more time were devoted to them.","author":"Simon","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"school curriculum","vi":"chương trình học ở trường"},{"en":"In my experience","vi":"theo kinh nghiệm của tôi"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a subject that you think should be removed from school","id":"speaking-part-2-138","_displayNo":"#138","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a time when you received good service in a restaurant or café\nYou should say:\n- when this was\n- what kind of restaurant or cafe you were in\n- why you were there\n- and why you thought the service was good","answer":"I am going to talk about the service we received in a restaurant where a friend of mine celebrated his birthday last Saturday evening. My friend had decided to book a table in a local Italian restaurant for the party. It was a small, family-run place, but this made it feel all the more welcoming and inviting. The atmosphere was great and the service was excellent. As I mentioned, I went to the restaurant because a friend had invited me to celebrate his birthday there. There were about ten of us there - mostly people I have known since university - and it was really nice to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">catch up with</strong> them and chat about what we had all been up to since we last got together. The service was good because the restaurant staff and owners really made us feel at home. From the moment we walked in, the waiters were polite, approachable and attentive; nothing was too much to ask. They brought out a cake with candles and sang ’Happy Birthday’ to my friend, although we had not asked them to do this, and the restaurant owners kept checking whether we were happy with everything, which was thoughtful of them. All in all, the delicious food, good company and friendly service made it an unforgettable evening.","author":"Simon","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"catch up with","vi":"trò chuyện và cập nhật tình hình với"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a time when you received good service in a restaurant or","id":"speaking-part-2-139","_displayNo":"#139","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe an enjoyable day out in the countryside that you had.\nYou should say:\n- where you went on this day out\n- who you were with\n- what you did\n- and explain why you enjoyed the day","answer":"I am going to describe a recent trip to a lovely place called the Tissington Trail. The Tissington Trail is a path or track that follows the route of a former railway line through beautiful countryside in the county of Derbyshire, here in the UK. The old railway line was taken up many years ago, and it was transformed into a recreational trail that is ideal for walkers, cyclists and horse riders. I went to the Tissington Trail because we had some family members, my brother and sister-in-law and their daughter, staying with us over the weekend. They had come up to Manchester from London, and they wanted my wife and I to take them somewhere where they could breathe in some fresh countryside air and get away from <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the hustle and bustle</strong> of the city. To reach the trail we had to park in Tissington itself, which is a charming, picturesque village. We hired some bicycles there and set off along the trail. It was an easy ride because the trail is mostly flat, with just a few gentle dips and inclines, and we were able to enjoy the stunning scenery as we passed through areas of woodland, a dramatic limestone ravine, and grassy meadows that were covered with colourful wild flowers. The part of the day that I enjoyed the most was when we cycled through a historic railway tunnel on our bicycles. The tunnel has been fitted with a sound installation that plays eerie steam train noises as you pass through it; we all loved the idea that the sounds transport you back in time, and that you feel like you’re on an old steam train with its whistles and clunking machinery. It was a really nice day out, and we all enjoyed relaxing in the village tearoom at the end of our bike ride.","author":"Simon","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"the hustle and bustle","vi":"sự hối hả và nhộn nhịp"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"an enjoyable day out in the countryside that you had","id":"speaking-part-2-140","_displayNo":"#140","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe an interesting house or apartment that you have visited.\nYou should say:\n- where the house or apartment was\n- who lived there\n- what it looked like on the outside and/or inside\n- and explain why you found this house or apartment interesting.","answer":"I am going to describe an apartment that I recently visited in the city centre of Manchester. The apartment was on the 10th floor of a brand new block that has just been built. This building is on the edge of the main commercial area of the city, and the apartment overlooks several of Manchester’s busiest shopping streets. Nobody was living in the apartment when I went there, because it had only just been put on the market. I went to see it with a friend who is thinking of moving to Manchester; he wanted to view some different properties, and I decided to go along and see what the newest apartments were like. From the outside, the apartment was in a tall, shiny glass building - nothing too remarkable. On the inside, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">as far as I remember</strong>, there were not many different colours: the walls were an off-white colour, the floors were done in whitish tiles, and the kitchen appliances were all silver metal coloured. I think the kitchen surfaces were made from dark grey granite. The main feature, in terms of the look of the apartment, was the huge floor-to-ceiling window in the living room, which allowed the sunlight to flood in. Although the white and silver decor was not really to my taste, I did like the fact that the apartment seemed so cool, clean and spacious. I particularly liked the open-plan kitchen and living room, which had all sorts of gadgets that could be operated by a mobile phone app. For example, I learned how to use the app to control the lighting, heating, blinds, security cameras and even the cooker. I found it fascinating that the apartment contained so much up-to-the-minute technology, and that everything seemed to be connected via wifi. It felt like I was taking a glimpse into the future.","author":"Simon","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"as far as I remember","vi":"theo như tôi nhớ"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"an interesting house or apartment that you have visited","id":"speaking-part-2-141","_displayNo":"#141","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe an old building that you like.\nYou should say:\n- where it is\n- what it is used for\n- and why you like it.","answer":"I'm going to describe a very famous building in New York: the Empire State Building. People might not think of it as an old building, but the Empire State Building was built in 1931, so I don't think it can be classed as new. It's located on Manhattan and it's probably the most distinctive and recognisable building when you look at New York's skyline. As far as I know, the Empire State Building is an office building, but visitors can go up to an observation deck on the top floor, which is the 102nd floor. There's also a 360-degree observation area on the 86th floor. Apparently, the building makes more money from the sale of tickets to the observation floors than it does from office rentals. I think the Empire State Building is still one of the most impressive skyscrapers in the world. It's such an iconic structure, and it's amazing to think that it was built around 80 years ago. The best thing about the building is the viewing deck on the top floor, which offers <strong class=\"key-phrase\">spectacular views</strong> of the city; it's definitely the best vantage point in New York. I'd recommend anyone who visits the city to go there and experience the view.","author":"Simon","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"spectacular views","vi":"tầm nhìn ngoạn mục"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"an old building that you like","id":"speaking-part-2-142","_displayNo":"#142","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe an open-air or street market which you enjoyed\nYou should say:\n- where the market is\n- what the market sells\n- how big the market is\n- and explain why you enjoyed visiting it.","answer":"I am going to describe a street market that I have enjoyed visiting many times in Manchester. It’s the Manchester Christmas Market, and it comes to the city for about a month from the end of November every year. The market stalls are spread across several sites in the city centre, but the centrepiece is the large European market in Albert Square next to the Town Hall. The Christmas Market stalls sell <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an array of Christmas gifts</strong> and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">mouth-watering food</strong> and drink from all over Europe. It’s a great place to find handmade crafts such as jewellery, ornaments, wooden toys and other souvenirs, but it’s the food and drink that seem to be most popular. Probably the biggest seller is the ’Gluhwein’, a hot, sweet wine which is sold in a souvenir mug. The market was originally quite small, occupying just one of the central squares in Manchester, but it’s grown quickly in recent years, spilling over into maybe five other pedestrian streets and a few other squares. Apparently there are over 200 stalls now, so it’s become a really big event attracting thousands of visitors. The main reason I have always enjoyed visiting the Christmas Market is the fantastic atmosphere. When I went there last December, it did not matter how cold or wet the weather was, Manchester seemed to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">come alive</strong> when the market opened; the streets were bustling with people and there was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a real festive feel</strong> to the city.","author":"Simon","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"an array of Christmas gifts","vi":"nhiều loại quà Giáng sinh"},{"en":"mouth-watering food","vi":"đồ ăn hấp dẫn"},{"en":"come alive","vi":"trở nên sống động"},{"en":"a real festive feel","vi":"bầu không khí lễ hội rõ nét"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"an open-air or street market which you enjoyed","id":"speaking-part-2-143","_displayNo":"#143","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe your favourite season in your country.\nYou should say:\n- when that season is\n- what the weather is like at that time of year\n- how that season is different from other seasons\n- and why it is your favourite season.","answer":"My favourite season in England is winter. A typical English winter would last around 4 or 5 months between November and March, but when I say that I like the winter, I am really thinking about the coldest month or two each year. During those really wintry months, the temperature drops below zero and it often snows. Over the last few years we’ve had periods of quite <strong class=\"key-phrase\">heavy snowfall</strong>, to the extent that roads have been blocked and schools have had to close. Last winter I remember looking out of the window one morning and seeing everything <strong class=\"key-phrase\">covered in a layer of white</strong>. Obviously the snow is what differentiates winter from the other seasons, but when it does not snow there is not much difference between winter, autumn and spring; winter is just a bit colder. The reason I have chosen winter as my favourite season is because I like the snow. I live near the countryside, and the landscape looks beautiful when everything is covered in white. We also celebrate Christmas and New Year in the winter, and these are my favourite festivals.","author":"Simon","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"heavy snowfall","vi":"tuyết rơi dày"},{"en":"covered in a layer of white","vi":"được phủ bởi một lớp trắng"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"your favourite season in your country","id":"speaking-part-2-144","_displayNo":"#144","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a café you like or dislike\nYou should say:\nWhere it was\nWhen you went there\nwhat you ate or drank\nAnd explain why you liked or disliked the café.","answer":"The fast pace of modern life in the city can be too much for an introvert like myself and I\nsometimes desire some time to retreat into my shell and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take a little retreat</strong>. Fortunately, I found\nthe perfect place called “Secret garden” which I am going to share with you right now.\n“Secret garden” is a garden-themed coffee shop located on the rooftop of a building in the centre\nof Hanoi. The café is well-known for its floral and botanical-inspired design, which gives you a\nsense of peace and tranquillity while enjoying some cake and coffee at the same time.\nI have become a frequent guest there and usually go at weekends. My favourite activities in\nthis coffee shop are reading books while listening to relaxing instrumental music, having a warm\ncup of tea with cookies or simply just sitting in the exterior garden and enjoying the view.\nDespite being popular, the coffee shop is still able to manage a quiet and soft atmosphere. The\nsetting is perfect with relaxing music, and the staff are really well-trained and cater to the guests’\nneeds quite well. Also, other guests there are usually really quite respectful and generally do not\ndisturb other people by talking or laughing too loudly.\nIt’s rare to find a place like this in Hanoi and I always recommend it to my friends who need a break\nfrom the busy city life.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"take a little retreat","vi":"tạm rời nhịp sống thường ngày"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a café you like or dislike","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-145","_displayNo":"#145","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a city or country you most want to live in the future\nYou should say:\nWhat is it\nWhere is it located\nWhy do you like it","answer":"I would like to tell you about Tokyo, the city I want to live in the most in the future. It is the capital\ncity of Japan and is the most populous metropolitan area in the world.\nThe most important reason I wish to settle down in Tokyo is the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">co-existence</strong> of modern and\ntraditional values. It’s the kind of city where the red gates of a centuries-old Shinto shrine may\nwell be found just next door to a glass skyscraper showcasing the finest 21st century technology.\nOr where a quiet green lane lined with wooden low-rise houses and an old school tofu shop might\nsit just <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a short stroll from</strong> a neon-lit square packed with flickering billboards and rainbow-bright\nstreet fashion.\nThe hectic life in Tokyo is also an irresistible attraction for young people. Tokyo's railway system\nseems like it was designed to win world records. It's rare to find a location in the metropolitan area\nthat can't be reached with a train ride and a short walk.\nI feel that the city is moving toward the future. I believe Tokyo will become a city that is full of\nsurprises.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"co-existence","vi":"sự cùng tồn tại"},{"en":"a short stroll from","vi":"chỉ cách một quãng đi bộ ngắn"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a city or country you most want to live in the future","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-146","_displayNo":"#146","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a city or country you want to live the most in the future.\nYou should say:\n- What city it is.\n- Where it is located.\n- Why you like it.","answer":"I would like to tell you about Tokyo, the city I want to live in the most in the future. It is the capital\ncity of Japan and is the most populous metropolitan area in the world.\nThe most important reason I wish to settle down in Tokyo is the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">co-existence</strong> of modern and\ntraditional values. It’s the kind of city where the red gates of a centuries-old Shinto shrine may\nwell be found just next door to a glass skyscraper showcasing the finest 21st century technology.\nOr where a quiet green lane lined with wooden low-rise houses and an old school tofu shop might\nsit just <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a short stroll from</strong> a neon-lit square packed with flickering billboards and rainbow-bright\nstreet fashion.\nThe hectic life in Tokyo is also an irresistible attraction for young people. Tokyo's railway system\nseems like it was designed to win world records. It's rare to find a location in the metropolitan area\nthat can't be reached with a train ride and a short walk. It is also common knowledge that you\ncould spend hours drooling over the elaborate pastries and picture-perfect sushi rolls in a\ndepartment store.\nI feel that the city is moving toward the future. I believe Tokyo will become a city that is full of\nsurprises.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"co-existence","vi":"sự cùng tồn tại"},{"en":"a short stroll from","vi":"chỉ cách một quãng đi bộ ngắn"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a city or country you want to live the most in the future","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-147","_displayNo":"#147","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a city or town you have been to\nYou should say:\nWhere it is\nWhen you visited it\nWhat you did there\nAnd explain why you like it","answer":"I would like to talk about Singapore, one of several cities I have visited and really enjoyed. I vacationed\nin this wonderful city last summer with my sister, Min, and we stayed there for 5 days.\nSingapore is a city-state located to the southeast of Vietnam and it took us only 2 hours to fly\nthere from Hanoi.\nWhen I arrived in Singapore, I was quite impressed by the way the city looked. The streets were\nincredibly clean, I could walk around the city all day and come back home without any dirt on my\nshoes. During my stay in Singapore, I did some shopping and visited some famous landmarks like\nthe Merlion statue, Singapore zoo and the botanical gardens.\nFor me, Singapore is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">well worth visiting</strong> for many reasons. Firstly, the public transport system in\nSingapore is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">extremely reliable</strong>. People do not have to spend hours waiting for buses or trains, and\nthe staff are very friendly and helpful. Another thing that I miss about Singapore is its <strong class=\"key-phrase\">multi-cultural\nnature</strong>. During the 5 days that I spent in Singapore, I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">bumped into people</strong> from many different\ncountries. English is the first language of this country so it was great to get the chance to practice\nmy English-speaking skills with the local people and also other tourists. Five days in Singapore\npassed by so fast that I wish I could have stayed a bit longer.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"well worth visiting","vi":"rất đáng để ghé thăm"},{"en":"extremely reliable","vi":"cực kỳ đáng tin cậy"},{"en":"multi-cultural nature","vi":"tính đa văn hóa"},{"en":"bumped into people","vi":"tình cờ gặp mọi người"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a city or town you have been to","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-148","_displayNo":"#148","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a crowded place\nYou should say:\nWhere it was\nWhen you went there\nWhat you did there\nAnd explain how you felt about the crowded place.","answer":"I would like to talk about my recent trip to Ba Den pagoda, which was an experience that I always\nremember due to the massive amount of visitors that I encountered while I was there.\nSo usually, during the Tet holiday, my family often drives to Tay Ninh province to visit my\ngrandfather and last year we decided to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take a short trip</strong> to Ba Den pagoda on Ba Den Mountain.\nBefore getting on the cable car to go up to the pagoda, I thought that maybe there might be a lot\nof Buddhist worshippers up there, as this sacred place tends to attract countless visitors all year\nround, let alone during Tet, which is the biggest holiday in Vietnam. And, I was right. There were\npeople with flowers and candles everywhere. On one corner, lines of people were trying to light\ntheir incense sticks, and inside the pagoda many people were kneeling and praying with their eyes\nclosed. It was pretty hard for us to even find any room to stand.\nBut, in the end, we successfully managed to find a way through the crowd and got close to the\nworshipping place, however my grandfather stayed outside as he cannot stand all the smoke and\nlack of oxygen.\nYou know, although I understand that most Vietnamese people enjoy going to pagodas and\ntemples during these special days of the year to wish for good luck, and well-being and happiness,\nI really do not think I will be doing that again anytime soon.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"take a short trip","vi":"thực hiện một chuyến đi ngắn"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a crowded place","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-149","_displayNo":"#149","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a dream house or apartment you want to live in.\nYou should say:\n- Where it is\n- What your dream home is like\n- Why you like this dream home\n- What you would do to get it.","answer":"Today I am going to talk about my vision of an ideal home that I want to live in the future.\nMy long-term goal is to be able to settle down in one of the villas in District 7, or any other upscale\nneighborhood in HCMC. This is because I do not want to settle for anything less when it comes to\nhousing, and District 7 has good access to all kinds of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">infrastructure facilities</strong>, such as good\ninternational schools for my children, good hospitals, good roads and many shopping centers.\nIn this area, there is a 3-storey villa with a big garden, and it also has a small pond next to a big\ntree, which I would really love to have. I will plant different types of trees and maybe have a small\npond for some fish as well. I love pets, so I will definitely keep some cats and dogs, and they can play\naround in the garden area. As for the interior, to give the space a modern style, I will have it painted\nin bright colors like yellow and white – which are my personal favorites and hang up paintings from\nlocal artists as well as some pot plants around the home.\nPart of the reason why I want to live in a villa is because I want to have a big family. I will definitely\nbring my parents to live here with me and my wife, and together we’ll bring up my future children.\nThis villa is going to be the symbol of my hard work and I firmly believe that if I focus on this goal,\nI can make it a reality.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"infrastructure facilities","vi":"cơ sở hạ tầng"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a dream house or apartment you want to live in","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-150","_displayNo":"#150","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a garden/park you have visited\nYou should say:\n- Where it was\n- What it looked like\n- What you did there\n- Why you liked it there.","answer":"Today I would like to talk about Tao Dan Park, which is one of the most well-known public parks\nin Ho Chi Minh City, and it is also the place that I usually visit.\nTao Dan Park is a public park located <strong class=\"key-phrase\">in the heart of the city</strong>, and it is most commonly known for\nmany beautiful flowers as well as big trees, which gives you a sense of peace and tranquility whilst\nbeing able to do some physical activities, like jogging or walking.\nI have become a frequent guest there and usually go at weekends. My favorite activities in this\npark are playing badminton and going jogging with some of my friends, if they have free time, or\nsimply sitting on the bench and enjoying the view. Despite being popular, this park is still able to\nmaintain a quiet and soft atmosphere. Also, other guests there are usually quite respectful and\ngenerally do not disturb other people by talking or laughing too loudly.\nIt’s rare to find a place like this in Ho Chi Minh and I always recommend it to my friends when they\nneed a break from the busy city life.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"in the heart of the city","vi":"ngay trung tâm thành phố"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a garden/park you have visited","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-151","_displayNo":"#151","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a good place where people go to swim.\nYou should say:\nWhat is this place?\nWhere is it situated?\nWhy is it so popular?","answer":"To be completely honest with you, I am incredibly obsessed with swimming as it is a good way for\nme to enhance my stamina. So, for that reason, I would like to tell you about the Central Pool in\nDistrict 4 which I often frequent at weekends.\nFirst, I would like to mention the dimension of this pool. As the name of it suggests, it is the biggest\nswimming pool in HCM city at 80m wide and 120m long. As well as that, it is divided into two\nareas, one for adults and the other for children.\nThe pool is open 24 hours a day / 7 days a week. Next to it, there is also a giant restaurant\nspecializing in Vietnamese and Japanese cuisine. It is a perfect place for people to unwind with a\nwide range of food after hours of training in the water. Not to mention, the staff and the lifeguards\nthere work professionally and more importantly they are always on time, which gives swimmers\nincluding me a sense of respect and satisfaction.\nFor all these reasons, this pool is always crowded at weekends, so people have to book tickets in\nadvance if they want to have a chance to swim there. As for me, I even bought tickets for the\nwhole year in order to freely <strong class=\"key-phrase\">gain access to</strong> the pool. If I had more spare time, I would definitely\ninvite more friends to come with me so that all of us can work out together.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"gain access to","vi":"tiếp cận được"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a good place where people go to swim","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-152","_displayNo":"#152","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a leisure facility (cinema, theater, sports center) you would like to have in your hometown.\nYou should say:\n- What it is;\n- Why you would like to have this facility in your hometown;\n- When will you go there;\n- How the facility changes your life;\n- How you felt about it.","answer":"So, today I am going to talk about an outstanding swimming pool called, the Four Seasons, which\nattracts around a thousand people a day and which many consider to be the most popular pool in\nthe city.\nFour Seasons is an indoor public pool located in my local sports complex. The reason why the pool\nis called Four Seasons is because it’s a heated pool and people can go there to enjoy the warm\nwater all year round.\nAs you may know, swimming is now becoming quite a popular exercise and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">recreational activity</strong>\nfor people of all ages in Ho Chi Minh city, and I also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">took swimming lessons</strong> through my time at\nschool. However, it was not until about a year ago that I started to pay regular visits to this pool. I\nam grateful to my best friend for introducing me to this wonderful place.\nI think that Four Seasons is such a popular place for several reasons. Firstly, safety is their highest\npriority, and there’s always a well-trained lifeguard there to enforce the pool safety rules and\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">perform any water rescues</strong> if necessary. Secondly, the quality of the facilities is excellent. The pool\nis nicely heated and regularly sanitised. There are also clean changing rooms with showers and big\nlockers for all your clothes and other belongings. I think that all of this creates the best experience\nfor the people that go there to swim. I believe that the Four Seasons swimming pool totally\ndeserves its great reputation.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"recreational activity","vi":"hoạt động giải trí"},{"en":"took swimming lessons","vi":"đã học bơi"},{"en":"perform any water rescues","vi":"thực hiện cứu hộ dưới nước"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a leisure facility (cinema, theater, sports center) you would like to have in your hometow","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-153","_displayNo":"#153","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a newly-opened shop\nYou should say:\nWhere the shop is\nWhen it opened\nWhat it sells\nAnd how you feel about the shop.","answer":"I am going to talk about a newly-opened convenience store in my neighbourhood called Circle K.\nActually, Circle K is an extremely popular chain-store from America and has multiple outlets\naround Hanoi now.\nBut the Circle K that I am speaking about was recently built only a couple of blocks away from\nwhere I live and I noticed it as soon as it was built. Also, because of its <strong class=\"key-phrase\">eye-catching logo</strong> with a\ngiant, red letter K in a white circle, it’s quite hard to miss.\nI think that the main reason that I became <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a regular customer</strong> of Circle K was because of one\nparticular item that they sell in their stores, and I was on cloud nine when I discovered it, my\nfavourite alcoholic drink, Vodka Cruiser. You know Cruiser’s only contain 4.5% alcohol which is\nperfect for a lightweight like me. And so, after my discovery, Circle K pretty much became a regular\nhangout spot of mine where my buddies and I would sometimes meet up and sit outside the store\nwith a couple of Cruiser’s chatting about our lives and stuff. It’s actually kind of embarrassing but\nCircle K is the place where I come to let off some steam after a break up or some other big drama\nI have in my life.\nSo yeah, as long as Circle K still keeps on selling Vodka Cruisers, it will always be my favourite\nshop.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"eye-catching logo","vi":"logo bắt mắt"},{"en":"a regular customer","vi":"một khách hàng thường xuyên"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a newly-opened shop","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-154","_displayNo":"#154","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a place in your city you want to go to\nYou should say:\n- What this place is.\n- Where this place is.\n- Why you like this place.\n- What do you want to do there.","answer":"Ho Chi Minh City is a popular tourist destination due to its fascinating culture, classic French\narchitecture, sleek skyscrapers as well as ornate temples and pagodas. As a result, it is pretty\ndifficult to pick out one particular place among millions of tourist attractions in Ho Chi Minh City.\nPersonally, I believe that Bitexco Financial Tower is the most impressive skyscraper. It is located\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">in the heart of Ho Chi Minh City</strong>’s business and entertainment district. At completion in 2010, it\nbecame the tallest building in Vietnam until January 2011.\nThe creative mastermind behind Bitexco <strong class=\"key-phrase\">drew inspiration for this skyscraper’s unique shape from</strong>\nVietnam’s national flower, the lotus. To the Vietnamese, the lotus is a symbol of purity,\ncommitment and optimism. This 68-storey building features many offices, shops, restaurants. The\nmain attraction at the tower is the Sky Deck where visitors can enjoy <strong class=\"key-phrase\">dramatic views across the\nbustling city</strong> below.\nThere are lots of places I like to go in Ho Chi Minh city, depending on my mood. If you want to\nenjoy the hectic and modern lifestyle, Bitexco is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an ideal attraction to consider</strong>.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"in the heart of Ho Chi Minh City","vi":"ngay trung tâm Thành phố Hồ Chí Minh"},{"en":"drew inspiration for this skyscraper’s unique shape from","vi":"lấy cảm hứng cho hình dáng độc đáo của tòa nhà từ"},{"en":"dramatic views across the bustling city","vi":"tầm nhìn ấn tượng bao quát thành phố nhộn nhịp"},{"en":"an ideal attraction to consider","vi":"một địa điểm rất đáng cân nhắc"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a place in your city you want to go to","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-155","_displayNo":"#155","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a place people can listen to music. (such as a theatre or a music hall)\nYou should say:\n- Where it is;\n- What kind of music is performed there;\n- What types of people go there;\n- Why people go there;\n- How you feel about it.","answer":"There are plenty of places that people living in my city could visit in order to be entertained by\nlistening to music. Amongst them, I prefer Hoa Binh <strong class=\"key-phrase\">performing arts center</strong>; the most popular one.\nHoa Binh performing arts center is located in Ho Chi Minh City, near the city centre and I happened\nto have a chance to visit there a year ago. As far as I recall, the performing arts center was shaped\nlike a circle in order to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">improve the acoustics</strong>.\nIn the theater, all sorts of performances take turns to be carried out. And many influential\norchestras and troupes from home and abroad have performed there. When coming to this\ntheater, you get a chance to listen to various genres of music, ranging from pop and rock music to\nfolk songs free of charge. A lot of professional musicians and singers have their music\nperformances there and I'm constantly having my mind blown by how talented and skillful the\nartists are.\nThe theater is also open to visitors for sightseeing. I strongly recommend you to visit there. Even\nif you are not to attend a play or a concert, it’s still worth going to the theater to appreciate its\nunique design or see the art exhibitions displayed there.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"performing arts center","vi":"trung tâm nghệ thuật biểu diễn"},{"en":"improve the acoustics","vi":"cải thiện âm học"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a place people can listen to music. (such as a theatre or a music hall)","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-156","_displayNo":"#156","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a place where people go to listen to music\nYou should say:\nWhat kind of music is performed there\nWhat type of people go there\nWhy people go there\nExplain your impressions of this place","answer":"I am going to tell you about a famous music pub I frequently visit. It is a place named Polygon,\nwhich is located in a hidden corner of Cat Linh street.\nI first knew of this place through my close friend, who was a big fan of live music. Instead of playing\njust one genre, this pub offers <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a wide variety of</strong> styles depending on the artists they invite each\nday. The bands there mostly play western pop, but on special occasions there were also jazz and\nballad nights.\nAs far as I know, this place is a hotspot for youngsters that have a taste for band music. Some are\nhere to have a drink with friends while bobbing their head to the music, some simply need a place\nto <strong class=\"key-phrase\">dance the night away</strong>. For me personally, I love seeing talented artists singing their heart out\non stage.\nRegarding what impressions I have of this pub, I would describe it as a place of freedom. It is where\nstrangers can easily connect with each other through music. The audience can take the stage if\nthey want to, and artists can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">improvise a tune</strong> when someone makes a request. I would highly\nrecommend this pub to anyone who is interested in band music.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"a wide variety of","vi":"nhiều loại đa dạng"},{"en":"dance the night away","vi":"nhảy múa suốt đêm"},{"en":"improvise a tune","vi":"ngẫu hứng một giai điệu"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a place where people go to listen to music","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-157","_displayNo":"#157","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a place where you can read and write.\nYou should say:\nWhere this place is\nHow do you know this place\nWhat do you do there\nAnd explain why you think it’s a good place for reading and writing.","answer":"Well, I am gonna talk about the City Library which is one of the largest libraries in Ho Chi Minh\ncity. I went there for the first time, like, 3 years ago when I was a senior in college. It was in the\nmiddle of the final examinations so I was terribly busy with homework and exams. That’s why I\ndecided to try <strong class=\"key-phrase\">to ease my mind</strong> after that exhausting time by reading some new books, so I visited\nthis library.\nThis library is, more or less, 5 kilometers away from my house and is located in downtown Ho Chi\nMinh city, which is a very bustling area with tons of people, noise and traffic. This library attracts\na lot of visitors every day because of its variety of fascinating books.\nYou know, this library is well-known for its tranquility and it is like a heaven for those who have a\nburning passion for books, especially novels and comics. It is equipped with very long tables and\nis well air-conditioned. Many of my essays were written there because this library provides me\nwith a great range of learning materials. At first, I thought that this library was kinda boring because\nI was not a big fan of books. However, after I visited once, this place turned out to be wonderful.\nActually, I have become a big reader since the time I went to this library and read books there.\nEvery time I read books in this library, I feel like I can relieve everyday stress and ease my mind\nafter hard days at work. Besides that, books and other materials in this library also enable me to\nexpand my horizons and learn lots of new things. That’s why I really like this building.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"to ease my mind","vi":"giúp tôi bớt lo lắng"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a place where you can read and write","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-158","_displayNo":"#158","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a place where you want to work\nYou should say:\n- where it is\n- what kind of work you would like to do\n- when you would like to work there\nAnd explain why you want to work in this place.","answer":"Well, the place that I have always wanted to work but have not yet had the chance to visit is Tokyo,\nthe capital city of Japan.\nI have dreamed of working in this city ever since I learned about it from a travel and lifestyle\nchannel. And even though it is considered <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a major cosmopolitan city</strong>, I am always amazed at its\nability to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">preserve the cultural aspect</strong> of Japan. The existence of such marvellous temples in the\ncentre of the city, or the sight of Japanese women wearing kimonos just seems quite amazing to\nme. Apart from this, the city where I live, Hanoi, is currently suffering from a serious air pollution\nproblem, so it would be a nice break to be able to find a job in one of the cleaner countries in the\nworld.\nRecently, there have been many agencies and organizations that help undergraduates or\nrecent graduates to find employment in Japan, and so if everything <strong class=\"key-phrase\">goes according to\nplan</strong>, in about 6 months I will start working as a marketing intern for an English centre located in\nGinza, which is one of the busiest streets in Tokyo. Fingers crossed that everything goes according\nto plan and I am able to enter <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a completely new phase in my life</strong>.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"a major cosmopolitan city","vi":"một thành phố quốc tế lớn"},{"en":"preserve the cultural aspect","vi":"gìn giữ bản sắc văn hóa"},{"en":"goes according to plan","vi":"diễn ra đúng kế hoạch"},{"en":"a completely new phase in my life","vi":"một giai đoạn hoàn toàn mới trong cuộc đời"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a place where you want to work","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-159","_displayNo":"#159","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a place you visited\nYou should say:\nwhere it was (or is)\nwhen you visited it\nwhat it looked like\nAnd explain why you visited it.","answer":"<strong class=\"key-phrase\">The fast pace of modern life</strong> in the city can be too much for an introvert like myself and I\nsometimes really need some time to retreat into my shell and have a little retreat. Fortunately, I\nfound the perfect little place called “Secret garden” which I am going to share with you now.\n“Secret garden” is a garden-themed coffee shop located on the rooftop of a building in the centre\nof Hanoi. The café is well-known for its floral and botanical-inspired design, which gives you <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a\nsense of peace and tranquillity</strong> while being able to enjoy some cake and coffee at the same time.\nI have become a frequent guest there and usually go at weekends. My favourite activities in\nthis coffee shop are reading books while listening to relaxing instrumental music, having a warm\ncup of tea with cookies or just simply sitting in the exterior garden and enjoying the view.\nDespite being popular, the coffee shop is still able to manage a quiet and soft atmosphere. The\nsetting is perfect with relaxing music, and the staff are really well-trained and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cater to the guests’\nneeds</strong> quite well. Also, other guests there are usually quite respectful and generally do not disturb\nother people by talking or laughing too loudly.\nIt’s rare to find a place like this in Hanoi and I always recommend it to my friends who need <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a break\nfrom the busy city life</strong>.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"the fast pace of modern life","vi":"nhịp sống hiện đại hối hả"},{"en":"a sense of peace and tranquillity","vi":"cảm giác bình yên và thư thái"},{"en":"cater to the guests’ needs","vi":"đáp ứng nhu cầu của khách"},{"en":"a break from the busy city life","vi":"khoảng nghỉ khỏi nhịp sống đô thị bận rộn"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a place you visited","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-160","_displayNo":"#160","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a popular place\nYou should say:\nWhere is this place?\nWhen did you first visit this place?\nHow often do you go to this place?\nAnd explain why it is so popular.","answer":"So, today I am going to talk about an outstanding swimming pool called, the Four Seasons, which\nattracts around a thousand people a day and many consider this to be the most popular pool in\nthe city.\nFour Seasons is an indoor public pool located in my local sports complex. The reason why the pool\nis called Four Seasons is because it’s a heated pool and people can go there to enjoy the warm\nwater all year round.\nAs you may know, swimming is now becoming quite a popular exercise and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">recreational activity</strong>\nfor people of all ages in Hanoi, and I also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">took swimming lessons</strong> through my time at school.\nHowever, it was not until about a year ago that I started to pay regular visits to this pool, and all\nthanks to my best friend for introducing me to this wonderful place.\nSo, I think that Four Seasons is such a popular place for several reasons. Firstly, safety is their\nhighest priority, and there’s always a well-trained lifeguard there to instruct the pool safety rules\nand <strong class=\"key-phrase\">perform any water rescues</strong> if necessary. Secondly, the quality of the facilities is excellent. The\npool is nicely heated and regularly sanitized. There are also clean changing rooms with showers\nand big lockers for all your clothes and other belongings, and I think that all of this creates the best\nexperience for the people that go there to swim. I believe that the Four Seasons swimming pool\ntotally deserves its great reputation.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"recreational activity","vi":"hoạt động giải trí"},{"en":"took swimming lessons","vi":"đã học bơi"},{"en":"perform any water rescues","vi":"thực hiện cứu hộ dưới nước"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a popular place","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-161","_displayNo":"#161","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a public place that you think needs improvements.\nYou should say:\n- What the place is.\n- When you visit the place.\n- What do you like and dislike about the public place","answer":"A public place that needs improvement is Dam Sen Park in Ho Chi Minh City. It is a large amusement park that many families visit at weekends, and parts of it still feel like <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a green oasis</strong> in a crowded city.\n\nI went there recently with my nieces and nephews. The children enjoyed the rides, but I noticed that several areas had <strong class=\"key-phrase\">fallen into disrepair</strong>. There were too few rubbish bins, some walls were covered in moss, and weeds had grown around unused facilities. The most worrying problem was finding discarded needles near a quiet corner of the park. That is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a serious safety hazard</strong>, especially for children wearing thin shoes.\n\nThe authorities do not need to redesign the whole park. They should first <strong class=\"key-phrase\">carry out basic maintenance</strong>: remove dangerous waste, repair damaged paths, improve lighting and place more bins in busy areas. Regular cleaning and visible security staff would also discourage littering and antisocial behaviour. In the longer term, old toilets and abandoned structures could be renovated.\n\nI still like the park because it offers affordable outdoor entertainment for families. However, people will only continue to use it if they feel safe. A relatively modest programme of cleaning and repairs could <strong class=\"key-phrase\">restore public confidence</strong> and make the park attractive again.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"a green oasis","vi":"một ốc đảo xanh"},{"en":"fallen into disrepair","vi":"xuống cấp do thiếu bảo dưỡng"},{"en":"a serious safety hazard","vi":"mối nguy hiểm nghiêm trọng về an toàn"},{"en":"carry out basic maintenance","vi":"thực hiện công tác bảo trì cơ bản"},{"en":"restore public confidence","vi":"khôi phục niềm tin của người dân"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a public place that you think needs improvements","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-162","_displayNo":"#162","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a recent development in your city\nYou should say:\n- What this development is.\n- How it could help people.\n- What benefits it could bring.\n- Whether it changes your life or not.","answer":"One of the newest additions to my city that I have noticed is that the public parks are now equipped\nwith <strong class=\"key-phrase\">communal exercise equipment</strong>.\nI have seen then being installed gradually over the last few months, and now they are common\nenough that even small local neighborhood parks also have them. I believe that they are going to\nbe very helpful to a lot of different people. No matter what, most people can use more exercise in\ntheir life. With these sets of equipment, now there is an extra way for them to get this much\nneeded exercise. People who want to exercise but would normally not go to the gym now have a\nnew way to access equipment. This will help them find more ways to work out without costing\nthem much time or money.\nIn addition, this would also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">serve as an encouragement</strong> for people who normally do not think about\nexercise to start paying more attention to this topic. They now can try out these machines at no\ncost to themselves, and this can help them gauge their interest in different exercising routines.\nMore importantly, this helps people <strong class=\"key-phrase\">get used to</strong> the idea of exercise as a necessary part of life.\nI believe that this will personally benefit me. I normally spend a lot of time in the park, and this will\nbe very helpful in allowing me to spend some of that time more productively and in a way that\nbenefits my health.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"communal exercise equipment","vi":"thiết bị tập luyện dùng chung"},{"en":"serve as an encouragement","vi":"đóng vai trò khích lệ"},{"en":"get used to","vi":"trở nên quen với"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a recent development in your city","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-163","_displayNo":"#163","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a rule at your school that you agree or disagree with.\nYou should say:\n- What the rule is;\n- What will happen when students break the rule;\n- Why school makes the rule;\n- Why you agree or not.","answer":"Vietnamese high school is known for imposing a lot of strict rules on students, and mine is not an\nexception.\nThere is one rule in my school I cannot stand. This is that male and female students are not allowed\nto be seen together, or sit next to each other, even in class or during break time. If we violate the\nrule, or if we are caught standing near a student of a different gender, we will receive a warning\nfrom the supervisor. If it continues, we can be temporarily expelled from school for three days to\na week. I know that there is a reason behind this. Rumor is that some couples skipped school to\nsecretly hang out, and thus failed to pass the university entrance exam. The principal is concerned\nthat the teenagers may fall in love and neglect their studies, so this rule is to limit the interaction\nbetween boys and girls in order not to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">develop an intimate relationship</strong>. However, I think that it\nhas gone too far. I do agree that the main duty of students is to study, but it is not wrong for us,\nboys and girls, to spend time together. We are old enough not to let our study be interfered. Not\nto mention that, sometimes, it’s just pure friendship. Each gender has different strengths and\nweaknesses, for example boys are often good at Maths and Physics while girls excel at Literature\nand languages. So, if we learn together, we can actually help each other to learn better.\nTo me, this separation is nonsense and meaningless. It not only prevents us from enjoying our high\nschool years to the fullest but also causes conflicts between students and the school. The only\nway I believe it to be helpful to students’ learning is to show them the consequences of poor\nlearning performance and educate them in taking advantage of having friends of mixed genders.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"develop an intimate relationship","vi":"phát triển một mối quan hệ thân thiết"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a rule at your school that you agree or disagree with","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-164","_displayNo":"#164","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a science subject you learned in your school.\nYou should say:\n- What do you learn about\n- How about the teacher\n- What do you think of the teacher\n- How you feel about it.","answer":"There were many science subjects that I used to learn a long time ago, but today I would like to\ntalk about Biology, which was one of the subjects that I had a chance to learn at school.\nIt was about 6 years ago, when I just entered high school. It was right at the beginning of the term,\nand I was terribly busy studying many subjects on a weekly basis. One of these subjects was\nBiology because it was one of many <strong class=\"key-phrase\">mandatory subjects</strong> that I had to study. At that time, my\nclassmates and I studied this subject with a teacher whose name was Linh. She was an experienced\nand <strong class=\"key-phrase\">highly respected teacher</strong> in my school.\nAt first, I was under the impression that Biology in high school was really complicated, as in the\nfirst lessons I couldn’t even understand what my teacher taught us in class, and I even suffered\nfrom stress and bad performance in mid-term tests. However, I never surrendered and kept trying\nday by day, so it gradually became easier. Finally, I passed with flying colors at the end of the term\nthanks to her sound advice about how to study this subject more effectively. Biology would not\nhave been easy to pass if we did not have this level of determination and perseverance when\nlearning it.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"mandatory subjects","vi":"các môn học bắt buộc"},{"en":"highly respected teacher","vi":"một giáo viên rất được kính trọng"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a science subject you learned in your school","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-165","_displayNo":"#165","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a service from a company or shop\nYou should say:\nWhat the service was\nWhen and where you received the service\nWhom you were with\nAnd explain how you feel about it","answer":"Well, this is indeed an interesting question. Well, regarding some excellent service that I received,\nI must say that I was really impressed by a company called Traveloka, which <strong class=\"key-phrase\">provided me with</strong> a\nbooking service for flight tickets and a hotel reservation.\nLast summer, my mother and I made up our mind to go on a trip to Taiwan. Previously, we would\njust simply book a package tour from a travel agent and they would take care of all the expenses\nand itinerary for us. However, this time both me and my mother wanted to do everything on our\nown, from booking the plane tickets to choosing the hotel and planning the trip.\nThanks to a friend’s recommendation, I tried booking flight tickets online, from a website called\nTraveloka. com. This website is a product of the Traveloka company, which aims to provide a user-\nfriendly platform for users to search and book flight tickets and hotel rooms.\nAt first I held a lot of doubt over this website since I had never bought plane tickets online before.\nHowever, after browsing through the site for a while, I was quite impressed by the sites’ smartly\ndesigned layout and easy-to-follow content, and furthermore, it only took a few minutes to find\nthe plane tickets that I wanted. Another good point to mention about the service was how quickly\nand convenient the payment was. They offered a variety of payment methods, such as credit\ncard, bank transfer or direct debit, which would suit many different customers’ needs.\nThanks to Traveloka, I managed to book the plane tickets at a reasonable price and at lightning\nspeed. Both my mother and I were completely satisfied with the service that we received, and\nwe gave the website a 5 star rating on the user review page. I would also recommend this site to\nother friends of mine.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"provided me with","vi":"cung cấp cho tôi"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a service from a company or shop","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-166","_displayNo":"#166","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a shop that has opened in your hometown\nYou should say:\nWhat shop it is\nWhat it sells (or, what you usually buy there)\nWhen you first started going to this shop (or, how you came to know about this\nshop)\nAnd explain why you like (to go to) this shop","answer":"Well, a shop that has just opened in my hometown I want to share with you is Tranquil café, which\nis one of the best book coffee shops in Hanoi.\nThis cafe is decorated in an old, traditional Hanoi style with loads of bookshelves and attracts many\nforeign tourists.\nI still <strong class=\"key-phrase\">vividly remember</strong> the first time I went there 3 months ago, which was also the opening day.\nThat was entirely coincidental. At that time, I came across an article about a new go–to place in\nHanoi. As I was so curious about that café, I decided to visit and it caught my eye immediately.\nThat space was so unique with gorgeous paintings and decoration. It really made me feel at home.\nAs for the reasons why I am fond of this place, I have to say that's because of its <strong class=\"key-phrase\">warm ambience</strong>,\nwhich I have not found in other cafes yet. You know, Hanoi is a busy and noisy city and I am so\nexhausted and irritated whenever I travel on the road. Therefore, I often go there as <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a hideaway</strong>\nto run away from the hustle and bustle. I find it extremely soothing with a cup of coffee and a\nsmall book. And an interesting thing is if I go there on Saturday nights, I can enjoy some soft music\nplayed by their staff. I am also pleased that the waiters tend to remember their customers and\noften give me a small discount. They really know how to retain their customers.\nFor all these reasons, I would say that I will still keep going back there in the long run.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"vividly remember","vi":"nhớ rất rõ"},{"en":"warm ambience","vi":"bầu không khí ấm cúng"},{"en":"a hideaway","vi":"một nơi ẩn mình yên tĩnh"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a shop that has opened in your hometown","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-167","_displayNo":"#167","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a shopping street you would like to go.\nYou should say:\nWhat is this place?\nWhere is it situated?\nWhy is it so popular?","answer":"Well I am gonna talk about Nguyen Trai street, which is one of the most crowded shopping streets\nof Ho Chi Minh city. I went there once, like, 3 years ago when I was a freshman at university. It\nwas at the end of the first semester so I was swamped with assignments and revision. That’s why\nI decided <strong class=\"key-phrase\">to chill out</strong> after that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">nerve-racking</strong> time by wandering around my neighborhood with\nmy besties and by chance, I found this shopping heaven.\nNguyen Trai shopping street is, more or less, 5 kilometers away from my house. It is located in\ndowntown Ho Chi Minh City, which is really bustling with tons of people, noise and traffic. This\nstreet attracts a lot of visitors every day because of its variety of delicious food.\nIt has been 2 years since the last time I went there so I really hope that I can manage my timetable\nto have a day off and go back. You know, this street is well-known for the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">high-end products</strong> sold\nthere, especially food and clothes. I plan to visit this street at the end of this month after I finish\nmy project. At first, I thought that Nguyen Trai street was kinda boring because I did not feel\ncomfortable in crowded places. However, after I went there once, this street turned out to be\nquite fabulous. Actually, I really want to go back to this place again and again in the future.\nThe reason is quite simple. I just want to go shopping around <strong class=\"key-phrase\">to relieve everyday stress</strong> and ease\nmy mind after hard days at work. Besides that, I plan to go there with my family because I believe\ngoing shopping together is a good way for us to understand each other better.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"to chill out","vi":"thư giãn"},{"en":"nerve-racking","vi":"căng thẳng đến thót tim"},{"en":"high-end products","vi":"sản phẩm cao cấp"},{"en":"to relieve everyday stress","vi":"giải tỏa căng thẳng hằng ngày"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a shopping street you would like to go","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-168","_displayNo":"#168","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a street you know well\nYou should say:\nWhere it is\nWhat the main buildings are\nHow often you go there\nAnd explain how you feel about this street","answer":"Well, there are quite a few streets that I could have chosen to talk about, but I would have to say the\none I most enjoy going to is Ly Thai To Street, which is one of the most popular tourist areas in\nHanoi.\nRegarding the location, the street is somewhere in the centre of the city, about fifteen to twenty\nminutes’ drive from where I live. So I normally go there by scooter.\nAnd as for how often I go there, well on average, I guess probably something like once or twice a\nmonth, which I know is not a lot, but unfortunately, I just do not have enough time to go there as\noften as I would like to.\nAnyway, most of the time I actually just go there for the street food, because there are loads of\nstalls which do really good food, like barbecued squid, bacon sandwiches, chicken wings and stuff\nlike that. So that's basically what I mainly go there for. There’s also quite a few little shops selling\nvarious souvenirs and handicrafts as well, but I do not spend much time in them because most of\nthe things are pretty overpriced. For example, a pack of postcards will probably <strong class=\"key-phrase\">set you back</strong> about\n30,000 dong or so, whereas if you went to any bookshop in the city, it would probably only cost\nabout 10,000 dong.\nBut anyway, in terms of why I like this street, firstly, as I just mentioned, the food there is fantastic,\nand as well as that, I also like that fact that it's pedestrianised, so there's a lot of space to walk\naround without having to worry about getting hit by a car! And another thing worth mentioning is\nthat most of the buildings are pretty old, so it gives the street a really nice, traditional feeling.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"set you back","vi":"khiến bạn phải trả một khoản tiền"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a street you know well","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-169","_displayNo":"#169","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a tall building in your hometown you like or dislike.\nYou should say:\nWhere it is\nWhat it is used for\nWhat it looks like\nAnd explain why you like or dislike it.","answer":"Well, I am gonna talk about Bitexco which is one of the most crowded buildings in Ho Chi Minh\ncity. The first time I went there was, like, 3 years ago when I was a student in high school. It was\nat the end of the term so I was struggling with projects and presentations. That’s why I decided to\nrelax after that stressful time by going around the city with my besties and by chance, we came to\nthis shopping heaven.\nBitexco building is, more or less, 5 kilometers away from my house, located in downtown Ho Chi\nMinh city, which is a very bustling area with tons of people, noise and traffic. This building attracts\na lot of visitors every day because of the variety of fancy clothes stores there.\nYou know, this building is well-known for the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">high-end products</strong> sold there, especially food and\nclothes. Its shape is based on the lotus, our traditional flower but to be honest, it looks more like\ncorn to me. At first, I thought that Bitexco building was kinda boring because I did not feel\ncomfortable in crowded places. However, after I went there once, this place turned out to be quite\nfabulous. Actually, it has become the landmark of HCM city for many years.\nEvery time I visit Bitexco, I feel like I can relieve everyday stress and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">ease my mind</strong> after hard days\nat work. Besides that, I always go there with my family for shopping because I believe going\nshopping together is a good way for us to understand each other better. That’s why I really like\nthis building.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"high-end products","vi":"sản phẩm cao cấp"},{"en":"ease my mind","vi":"giúp tôi yên tâm hơn"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a tall building in your hometown you like or dislike","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-170","_displayNo":"#170","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe a traditional product in your country.\nYou should say:\n- What it is;\n- When was the first time you tried it;\n- How to make it;\n- How you like it.","answer":"I would love to talk about rice, the most important agricultural plant in my country.\nEver since I was in my early elementary years, the rice plant has appeared in almost every subject,\nfrom literature to natural science to geography. And even in real life, the rice plant can be spotted\nall across the countryside around Vietnam.\nIt never ceases to amaze me how such a simple plant could support a whole nation’s economy. Up\nto this day, millions of Vietnamese families are still dependent on the cultivation of rice to make\nends meet. And the fact that Vietnam has become one of the world’s leading rice exporters is more\nsolid proof of the relevance of this plant in my country. Besides this, rice has been an indispensable\npart of the main meal of most families for centuries and children practice the habit of eating rice\nfrom a very young age, and as for the older generation, they cannot go a day without rice in some\nform or another.\nOver thousands of years, the rice plant has played a really important role in Vietnamese culture\nand many traditions and ceremonies originate from the farmers hopes for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an abundant crop</strong>, and\nmany of these traditions are considered important established customs to foreign visitors. I think\nthat the rice plant has become one of the greatest symbols for the Vietnamese spirit and deserves\nlarge appreciation from all generations.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"an abundant crop","vi":"một vụ mùa bội thu"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a traditional product in your country","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-171","_displayNo":"#171","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe an art and craft activity you did at school\nYou should say:\nWhat it was\nWhat you did for this activity\nWho you did it with\nAnd explain how you felt about this activity.","answer":"I would like to talk about a craft activity I did in elementary school - origami. I guess I do not need to\nsay much because origami is already so popular worldwide. It’s the art of paper folding in order\nto create a particular object or animal.\nIt was all the rage in my old school because to do this, you have to be very skillful and patient to\nmake a beautiful paper figure. It was like a challenge for young kids, you see. I was caught up in\nall this hype so I asked my desk mate to show me the ropes. Although he was a boy, he was one\nof the best in my class when it came to origami. Anyway, he showed me how to fold the easiest\nfigure - the crane. It looked so easy when he did it. He told me to just follow the exact steps and\nI could create a paper crane. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">Easier said than done</strong>, though, because in the end my crane was\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">misshapen beyond recognition</strong>. I did not know what I did wrong. Even when he patiently showed\nme one more time, the result was not much better. He finally gave up on me and I was sorely\ndisappointed in myself.\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">In retrospect</strong>, I think I was too clumsy and careless. I rushed things because I wanted to do it so\nbadly. But origami is not about speed, it requires patience and accuracy. That’s why I admire\norigami artists so much. Maybe in the future I might try origami again, but this time I will take my\ntime and relax more.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"Easier said than done","vi":"nói dễ hơn làm"},{"en":"misshapen beyond recognition","vi":"biến dạng đến mức không thể nhận ra"},{"en":"In retrospect","vi":"khi hồi tưởng lại"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an art and craft activity you did at school","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-172","_displayNo":"#172","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe an enjoyable experience you had in the countryside.\nYou should say:\nWhen and where you went\nWho you went with\nWhat you did there\nAnd explain why you think it was enjoyable.","answer":"I would like to talk about last summer when I had <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an unforgettable opportunity</strong> to visit my\nhometown, which is a small village located in the north of Vietnam.\nMy entire family, including my parents, myself and my younger sister, decided to spend the day\ndriving to the village. For my parents, this would be the chance for them to see their relatives who\nthey had not seen in a long time. And for me and my sister, we hoped to get a closer insight into\nthe life of the locals as well as strengthen our family bonds.\nSo, the four of us hit the road really early in the morning, at about 5 a. m. And after about 4 hours\nof driving, we arrived at a peaceful and tranquil village. To my astonishment the scenery was\ncompletely different from the neighbourhood where I currently live. We admired the breathtaking\nlandscapes of green paddy fields, winding paths and small houses standing next to each other.\nAfter that we went to visit our relatives who were all really friendly and warm-hearted people and\ngreeted us with great enthusiasm. The whole morning was spent talking and chatting about our\nlives and old memories. At noon, our family was treated to a gourmet meal, full of local and\norganically grown ingredients. In the afternoon, one of our relatives took us to see the paddy fields\nand the village’s famous lake. My sister and I got to learn how to fish and feed the chickens, which\nwas a novel experience since we had never done this before.\nAll of us were over the moon the whole day, which really was a once in a life time experience and\nwould be embedded in our memory for a long time.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"an unforgettable opportunity","vi":"một cơ hội không thể quên"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an enjoyable experience you had in the countryside","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-173","_displayNo":"#173","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe an ideal house\nYou should say:\nwhere it is\nwhat it looks like\nwhen you would like to live in\nAnd explain why you would like to live in it","answer":"So I am going to talk about the perfect house that I would like to live in. I would like it to be spacious,\ncomfy and tranquil and it should therefore be located in a rural area with a quiet and peaceful\natmosphere.\nPainted white and pink, the house would somehow look like a little palace for a royal family.\nNatural light is a must for this house, and it must contain an effective window system for good\nventilation. The house would be equipped with modern appliances and air-conditioning for\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">comfort and convenience</strong>. Trees and flowers would be planted around it for decoration and to\nmake it look beautiful.\nMy ideal house, which would be full of natural light and surrounded by a lot of beautiful gardens,\nwould be the perfect place for me when I am in need of relaxation, and an escape from my heavy\nworkload in the city. I would be able to enjoy the fresh air, and living there would be the perfect\nway to relieve stress.\nTo be honest, having the chance to live in such a house would be a dream come true for me, feeling\nlike a king in his own castle, and I hope that one day I can actually build a house like this to live in.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"comfort and convenience","vi":"sự thoải mái và tiện lợi"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an ideal house","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-174","_displayNo":"#174","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe an important plant in your country\nYou should say:\nWhat the plant is\nHow you know it\nWhy it is important\nAnd explain how much you like the plant.","answer":"Well I would love to talk about rice, the most important agricultural plant in my country.\nEver since I was in my early elementary years, the rice plant has appeared in almost every subject,\nfrom literature to natural science to geography. And even in real life, the rice plant can be spotted\nall across the countryside around Vietnam.\nIt never ceases to amaze me how such a simple plant could support a whole nation’s economy.\nUp to this day, millions of Vietnamese families are still dependent on the cultivation of rice to\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">make ends meet</strong>. And the fact that Vietnam has become one of the world’s leading rice exporters\nis more solid proof of the relevance of this plant in my country. Besides this, rice has been an\nindispensable part of the main meal of most families for centuries and children practice the habit\nof eating rice from a very young age, and as for the older generation, they cannot go a day without\nrice in some form or the other.\nOver thousands of years, the rice plant has played a really important role in Vietnamese culture\nand many traditions and ceremonies originate from the farmers hopes for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an abundant crop</strong>, and\nmany of these traditions are considered important established customs to foreign visitors.\nI think that the rice plant has become one of the greatest symbols for the Vietnamese spirit and\ndeserves large appreciation from all generations.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"make ends meet","vi":"trang trải cuộc sống"},{"en":"an abundant crop","vi":"một vụ mùa bội thu"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an important plant in your country","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-175","_displayNo":"#175","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe an important river/ area of water in your country\nYou should say:\nHow long the river is\nWhere it is\nWhat it looks like\nWhy it is important","answer":"I am going to talk about the Mekong river, one of the biggest and most important rivers located in\nsouthwestern part of Vietnam. With a length of about 2,700 miles, the river is the 7th longest is\nAsia. Locally, it's called \"River of the Nine Dragons\" because the small branches of the river are,\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">since time immemorial</strong>, associated with the image of nine majestic dragons. Needless to say, the\nriver is mentioned in a variety of poems and songs.\nIn terms of agriculture, the mighty river together with its surrounding delta has been known as\nthe agricultural heart of southern Vietnam and the ’rice bowl’ of the whole country. The Mekong\nis also Vietnam's most important fishing region.\nIf you are a discerning tourist who really has ’wearing a conical hat in a sampan boat in Vietnam’\non your bucket list, a trip to Mekong Delta is a must. It is carpeted in a dizzying variety of greens\nand is also a place where boats, houses and markets float upon the innumerable rivers, canals and\nstreams that criss-cross the landscape like arteries. Embarking on a Mekong River cruise provides\ntourists with fascinating insight into the local rural way of life, including the opportunity to visit\nsome of the region’s best-known sites, along with plenty of hidden gems.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"since time immemorial","vi":"từ thời xa xưa"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an important river/ area of water in your country","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-176","_displayNo":"#176","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe an important skill which cannot be learned at school\nYou should say:\n- What the skill is\n- Why it cannot be learned at school\n- Why it is important\n- How we can learn it","answer":"Today I would like to talk about making presentations, which is a skill that I learned from my mentor\nwho used to encourage and give me many pieces of sound advice.\nIt was about 3 years ago, when I was studying in an English language center in order to improve\nmy English skills to a higher level. During that time, my peers and I had many opportunities to make\npresentations in English under the guidance of Jimmy, who is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a born presenter</strong> and is head and\nshoulders above everyone else in teaching students how to speak in front of the crowd. At first, I\nwas faced with various obstacles when speaking in front of my classmates, especially the first time\nbecause I had butterflies in my stomach, so I really <strong class=\"key-phrase\">struggled with</strong> speaking in front of a lot of\npeople confidently, and I even suffered from failures. However, I gradually overcame the\ndifficulties and got the hang of it, and things became easier for me since then.\nAs for why this skill is essential, I believe that when studying at universities or working in\ncompanies, people have to speak publicly <strong class=\"key-phrase\">on a frequent basis</strong> in order to prove their ability in their\nstudy or their work. Therefore, by watching YouTube videos or going to learning centers, learners\ncan improve their presentation skills to a higher degree.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"a born presenter","vi":"người có năng khiếu thuyết trình bẩm sinh"},{"en":"struggled with","vi":"gặp khó khăn với"},{"en":"on a frequent basis","vi":"một cách thường xuyên"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an important skill which cannot be learned at school","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-177","_displayNo":"#177","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe an interesting event in your school\nYou should say:\n- What the event was.\n- When the event was.\n- Why it was interesting.\n- How you felt about it.","answer":"An interesting event at my school was the annual sports day when I was about thirteen. It took place on the school field and included running races, long jump, high jump, shot put and a tug-of-war competition.\n\nWhat made the day enjoyable was the atmosphere. Teachers and parents stood around the field and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cheered us on</strong>, while each class had its own banner. The music, announcements and friendly rivalry created <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a real sense of occasion</strong>. I entered the 100-metre race, the long jump and shot put. I was nervous before the first event, but once the competition began, I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">pushed myself harder than usual</strong>.\n\nI eventually won the long jump and came second in the other two events. My class finished as the overall runner-up, so we were slightly disappointed not to win, but we were still proud of our result. The head teacher presented the trophies at the end of the afternoon, and everyone stayed to applaud the winners.\n\nI remember the event because it was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a memorable shared experience</strong> rather than an ordinary school day. It showed me that sport can bring people together and give quieter students a chance to contribute. I also felt <strong class=\"key-phrase\">proud of contributing to my class</strong>, not just of winning an individual medal.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"cheered us on","vi":"cổ vũ chúng tôi"},{"en":"a real sense of occasion","vi":"bầu không khí đặc biệt và trang trọng"},{"en":"pushed myself harder than usual","vi":"nỗ lực nhiều hơn thường lệ"},{"en":"a memorable shared experience","vi":"một trải nghiệm chung đáng nhớ"},{"en":"proud of contributing to my class","vi":"tự hào vì đã đóng góp cho lớp"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an interesting event in your school","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-178","_displayNo":"#178","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe an interesting place that few tourists visit.\nYou should say:\n- Where it is;\n- When you went there;\n- What you can see there;\n- Why there is a few people to go.","answer":"To be honest, it’s really hard to think about a place which is interesting and that few people know\nabout. And today I will talk about one of my favorite restaurants. It is actually <strong class=\"key-phrase\">in the suburbs of my\nhometown</strong>. You know, this restaurant doesn't even have a name. We always call it “Năm Grandma”\nbecause the owner as well as the chef is an old grandma, whose name is Năm and she only offers\nlunch.\nThe restaurant is on a busy street and very near a school. It is quite a small and hectic place.\nFrom the outside, the restaurant does not look very impressive and even a little bit poor. Inside\nthere are lots of old square wooden tables, each with about four chairs around them.\nThis restaurant has several dishes, and you do not need to order from the menu, just <strong class=\"key-phrase\">pick up what\nyou want from the kitchen</strong>. Each of them is so delicious to me. If you go there too late, you won't\nget the most popular one. Whenever I was free, I'd go there with my friends or family to enjoy my\nfavorite dishes.\nYou know, even though it is a small restaurant, the delicious food made everyone who has been\nthere <strong class=\"key-phrase\">fall in love with it</strong>. In my mind, it should be the best restaurant in the world. However, few\npeople know it, maybe because it didn't have a name and you know, my hometown is a small city,\nso, it cannot be a famous place.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"in the suburbs of my hometown","vi":"ở vùng ngoại ô quê tôi"},{"en":"pick up what you want from the kitchen","vi":"tự chọn món mình muốn từ bếp"},{"en":"fall in love with it","vi":"dần yêu thích nơi đó"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an interesting place that few tourists visit","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-179","_displayNo":"#179","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Place","prompt":"Describe an occasion where you received a good service from a company or shop\nYou should say:\n- What the service was.\n- When and where it happened.\n- Whom you were with.\n- How you felt about it.\n- Explain why you think it was good service.","answer":"I am going to talk about how satisfied I was when receiving good service from a music shop a\ncouple of months ago.\nOne day, after watching a really motivational concert, I decided to start learning how to play the\nguitar. As I was walking along one of the main shopping streets in the city centre to look for a\nmusic shop, a large window displaying all sorts of musical instruments <strong class=\"key-phrase\">caught my eye</strong>. I decided to\ngo in and have a look around.\nA young good-looking shop assistant appeared and greeted me with a glowing smile. After\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">exchanging pleasantries</strong>, I explained to the assistant that I had never played the guitar before in\nmy life and that I wondered what the differences were between the various acoustic guitars on\nshow. He talked to me about the different makes and models, whether they were factory or hand\nmade, the woods and varnishes used, the variation in sound quality and, of course, the price range.\nThough I was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a bit overwhelmed</strong> by what he said as a non-musician, I highly appreciated his\nattitude.\nTo tell the truth, it is difficult to find very smart and efficient customer service nowadays. I was\nquite satisfied with the service the young man provided, he was obviously well-trained, and he\nwas patient enough to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">fully understand what my problem was</strong> and used his professional skills to\ndeal with it. Besides, he was very proficient in acoustic guitar playing, and seemed reliable to me.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Place","phrases":[{"en":"caught my eye","vi":"thu hút ánh nhìn của tôi"},{"en":"exchanging pleasantries","vi":"trao đổi vài câu xã giao"},{"en":"a bit overwhelmed","vi":"hơi choáng ngợp"},{"en":"fully understand what my problem was","vi":"hiểu đầy đủ vấn đề của tôi"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an occasion where you received a good service from a company or shop","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-180","_displayNo":"#180","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a change that you would like to see in your local area.\nYou should say:\n- what the change would be\n- who would be involved in making the change\n- how it would be done\n- and why you would like to see the change happen.","answer":"The change that I would like to see in my local neighbourhood is the pedestrianisation of the main shopping street in the town centre. I would like to see traffic diverted around this area in order to make it safer and more attractive for visitors and shoppers. Most of the traffic that clogs up the main street is just passing through the town, but it’s the local people who have to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">put up with the congestion</strong>, noise and pollution. It’s the job of the local council to make changes like the one I am suggesting. But before the council does anything, there usually needs to be some pressure from local people to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">bring a problem to light</strong>. So, perhaps we need a campaign by local residents who want to see this change. Then the council might contract a town planner or an architect to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">come up with some possible designs</strong> for a new road system. I am not sure how exactly the process of creating a pedestrian street would work, but I imagine that it would require detailed planning. Perhaps a bypass would need to be built around the town centre first. This would give drivers a faster alternative to driving through the town, and it would allow the main shopping street to be blocked off and pedestrianised. I would like to see this change because it would really improve the quality of life of residents in the town where I live. I can imagine the new pedestrian street having cafes and restaurants with outdoor seating. It would be a safer and more pleasant place for families to go shopping, and I am sure this would have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a positive knock-on effect</strong> on local shops and businesses.","author":"Simon","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"put up with the congestion","vi":"chịu đựng tình trạng tắc nghẽn"},{"en":"bring a problem to light","vi":"đưa một vấn đề ra ánh sáng"},{"en":"come up with some possible designs","vi":"đề xuất một số phương án thiết kế"},{"en":"a positive knock-on effect","vi":"hiệu ứng tích cực lan tỏa"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a change that you would like to see in your local area","id":"speaking-part-2-181","_displayNo":"#181","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a funny situation that made you laugh.\nYou should say:\n- when this situation took place\n- what happened\n- how you reacted and why you found the situation funny.","answer":"I'm going to talk about a funny thing that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">happened to</strong> me a couple of weeks ago. I think it was a Saturday morning, and I was sitting having a coffee in a café near where I live. I was on my own so I decided to read the newspaper while drinking my coffee. I must have been quite engrossed in what I was reading because the time passed quickly, and I suddenly realised that I needed to get going. What I didn't realise was that I had been sitting with my legs crossed, and one of my legs had completely gone to sleep. As I stood up to leave the café, I quickly became aware that my left leg was 'dead', but it was too late; I started to fall. I thought I could catch myself on the table, but the table tipped over and I fell to the floor in front of everyone in the café! I can remember being on my knees in the middle of the café, looking up at the staff and customers around me. I felt really embarrassed and I expected the other people to find it funny, but to my surprise nobody was laughing. They were all worried that something really bad had happened to me! As I got up from the floor, I had to explain to the whole café that I was fine. I was embarrassed at the time, but I laughed about it later!","author":"Simon","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"happened to","vi":"tình cờ"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a funny situation that made you laugh","id":"speaking-part-2-182","_displayNo":"#182","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a situation that made you angry.\nYou should say:\n- when it happened\n- what happened\n- how you felt","answer":"A recent situation that made me angry was getting stuck in a traffic jam on the way to meet some friends. It happened at lunchtime last Sunday, and I had not expected the roads to be busy because most people were not working.\n\nEverything was going smoothly until I suddenly saw a long queue of cars ahead. I had no choice but to join it and wait to get past whatever was causing the delay. Eventually, I discovered that roadworks had reduced the road to a single lane, and it took me an extra thirty minutes to pass them.\n\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">Traffic congestion</strong> does not usually make me angry, but this time I felt <strong class=\"key-phrase\">frustrated and powerless</strong>. I knew my friends were waiting for me, yet there was nothing I could do and no way of knowing how long the delay would last. When I finally reached the roadworks, I was relieved to be moving again, but I was still stressed because I was already half an hour late.","author":"Simon","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"Traffic congestion","vi":"tình trạng ùn tắc giao thông"},{"en":"frustrated and powerless","vi":"bực bội và bất lực"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2 — restored from the complete source text","subtype":"","summary":"a situation that made you angry","id":"speaking-part-2-183","_displayNo":"#183","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a time when you had to do something in a hurry.\nYou should say:\n- what you were doing\n- when this was\n- why you had to hurry\n- and explain how you felt at that time","answer":"I am going to talk about a time when I had to get ready in a great hurry for a work trip. It happened about five years ago, when several colleagues and I had to catch an early flight. A senior colleague had offered to collect me from home at 5.30 in the morning.\n\nThe problem was that I overslept. I had set an alarm, but I must have switched it off without fully waking up. At exactly 5.30, the doorbell rang, and I looked at the clock in shock. I jumped out of bed, dressed in record time, splashed water on my face, brushed my teeth and pulled on my shoes without properly tying the laces.\n\nFortunately, my suitcase had already been packed. I grabbed it, apologised repeatedly to my colleague and got into the car. We reached the airport <strong class=\"key-phrase\">with only minutes to spare</strong>, but the other passengers had been waiting and I felt deeply embarrassed.\n\nThe incident taught me a practical lesson. Before any early journey, I now <strong class=\"key-phrase\">set two independent alarms</strong> and place my phone far enough away that I have to get out of bed to turn it off.","author":"Simon / ChatGPT","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"with only minutes to spare","vi":"chỉ còn dư vài phút"},{"en":"set two independent alarms","vi":"đặt hai báo thức độc lập"}],"source":"IELTS Simon sample completed by ChatGPT after the source extraction was truncated","subtype":"","summary":"a time when you had to do something in a hurry","id":"speaking-part-2-184","_displayNo":"#184","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a time when you were not satisfied with a service.\nYou should say:\n- what the service was\n- who provided it\n- what happened\n- and explain why you were unhappy with the service.","answer":"I am going to describe a time when I experienced poor service from staff in a restaurant. This happened a couple of months ago, when some family members, who live abroad, came to stay. We decided to visit a nearby town, and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">at some point</strong> everyone was a little hungry, so we thought we would have a bite to eat. The first restaurant that we came across looked perfect. It had plenty of empty tables - we had not booked in advance - and we were all happy with the menu. But as soon as we walked through the door, things <strong class=\"key-phrase\">started to go wrong</strong>, and we were not at all impressed with the attitude of the staff. After standing around for a few minutes waiting for someone to greet us, I managed to attract the attention of a waitress who told me that we had come into the restaurant through the wrong door. So, I went over to the main door, only to be told by the manager that there were no tables free for a party of our size - there were eight of us. I could see several free tables with four seats, so I suggested simply moving two of these tables together. But the manager was adamant that this was impossible; our only option was to divide the family and sit at two separate tables. By this time, some of my family members were getting fed up. The restaurant was half empty, yet we were being treated as if they did not need customers. We decided we did not want to sit at separate tables or stay in a place where we <strong class=\"key-phrase\">felt unwelcome</strong>. We left, feeling disappointed by how dismissive the restaurant manager had been, and fortunately we found a much friendlier place to eat just around the corner.","author":"Simon","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"at some point","vi":"vào một thời điểm nào đó"},{"en":"started to go wrong","vi":"bắt đầu xảy ra vấn đề"},{"en":"felt unwelcome","vi":"cảm thấy không được chào đón"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a time when you were not satisfied with a service","id":"speaking-part-2-185","_displayNo":"#185","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a time when you were really busy.\nYou should say:\n- when this was\n- why you were so busy\n- how you managed the situation\n- and explain how you felt at the time.","answer":"I am going to talk about the time I left a university assignment until the last minute and had to work flat out to get it finished. This was about ten years ago when I was doing my Master’s degree. I had to do several 3000-word assignments for the modules on my Master’s course, but I remember that there was one in particular that I really <strong class=\"key-phrase\">struggled with</strong>. I had been procrastinating and putting it off for weeks, and in the end I left myself just two days to get the whole assignment done. This included finding and reading relevant books and articles, deciding on my thesis and assignment title, and producing a final draft which had to be handed in to the department office before the deadline. The pressure of such a close deadline actually forced me to manage the task in a really efficient way. My first step was to decide on the general area that I wanted to write about, and then I limited myself to just ten research sources. I printed the most relevant pages, highlighted the key paragraphs and made some notes to summarise and synthesise the ideas that I found interesting. Finally, I just started writing the main body of the assignment, and I wrote the title and the introduction last.","author":"Simon","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"struggled with","vi":"gặp khó khăn với"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 2","subtype":"","summary":"a time when you were really busy","id":"speaking-part-2-186","_displayNo":"#186","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe something you did that made you feel proud of yourself.\nYou should say:\n- what you did\n- when you did it\n- why you felt proud of what you had done\n- and explain how you felt when this happened.","answer":"One of my <strong class=\"key-phrase\">proudest achievements</strong> was completing my undergraduate degree. The moment I remember most clearly was receiving my final examination results and discovering that I had performed better than I expected.\n\nI graduated about ten years ago after several demanding years of study. The course included difficult assignments, presentations and group projects, so the final result represented far more than passing a set of exams. It showed that I had developed the discipline to manage long-term work and continue when progress felt slow.\n\nMy family supported me throughout the degree, but I also had to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take responsibility for</strong> my own schedule and motivation. During the final term, I spent many evenings in the library and learned to divide large tasks into smaller, manageable stages.\n\nI felt proud because the degree was the first major goal I had achieved through sustained effort. It also opened the door to further study and employment, so its value was both personal and practical. Looking back, it gave me confidence that I could handle other demanding projects in the future.","author":"Simon / ChatGPT","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"proudest achievements","vi":"những thành tựu đáng tự hào nhất"},{"en":"take responsibility for","vi":"chịu trách nhiệm về"}],"source":"IELTS Simon sample adapted by ChatGPT to replace unfinished name and year placeholders","subtype":"","summary":"something you did that made you feel proud of yourself","id":"speaking-part-2-187","_displayNo":"#187","band":"9.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a change in your life.\nYou should say:\nWhat the change was\nWhen it happened\nWhy it happened\nAnd explain how you have benefited from this change","answer":"I would like to talk about one of the greatest transformations in my life. I used to weigh around\n65 kilos and after about 6 months of continuous dieting and working out, I successfully lost 15\nkilos.\nWhen I was a teenager, I mainly subsisted on fast foods such as fried chicken, hamburgers or\ncrisps. And with a number of high school exams I was often forced to stay up late and eat even\nmore. As a result, I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">put on weight</strong> rapidly and one day, when I stepped on a scale, it read 65 kilos,\nand I knew that I had to start my weight- loss journey or I would become overweight.\nAfter consulting my aunt, who worked as a nutritionist, I understood that losing weight was all\nabout diet and exercise. Firstly, I cleaned out my fridge of all my favourite unhealthy foods, and\nbegan cooking homemade meals. I also drank at least 2 litres of water a day instead of soft drink.\nSecondly, I registered at my local gym and started to workout at least three times a week. And as\nwell as this, I started going to bed early at night and waking up at 5 am to go biking every morning.\nAfter 6 months of working out regularly and resisting junk food, my weight dropped to 50 kilos.\nHowever, it was not only about the weight loss, but also about the changes in my health. I felt\nstronger and happier than ever before. I rarely got sick and my skin also looked brighter. More\nimportantly though, I regained my self-confidence. I used to run and hide from cameras, but now\nI am much more comfortable being photographed. And the best thing is that I am now able to\nfinally wear my old dresses and skinny jeans.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"put on weight","vi":"tăng cân"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a change in your life","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-188","_displayNo":"#188","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a decision that you disagreed with\nYou should say:\nWho made this decision\nWhat it was\nHow you told him/her\nAnd explain why you disagreed with the decision","answer":"So today I am going to tell you about an important milestone in my life which was the first\nargument I had with my parents. Firstly let me explain why I took this experience so seriously. I am\nusually a real mama’s boy who always obeys my parents, especially my mother who is definitely the\nstricter of the two. She is so bossy and direct that it usually has to be her way or the highway. And\nalso, my mother is awfully protective of me and never allows me to have or join in any sleepover\nwhatsoever. And that leads to the main part of my story, which happened three weeks ago.\nIt was my best friend’s birthday party and he invited me to sleep over at his house. I was so thrilled.\nI mean this was going to be my first sleepover. My excitement did not last long though as my mum\nimmediately said no when I brought it up. Filled with anger, I found myself raising my voice at my\nmother for the first time in my life and said “Mom, I am a 21-year-old man. I can take care of\nmyself”. She was so surprised at my response and scolded me even harder. But I stood my ground.\nI believed it was about time I expressed my feelings and let her know how I felt. I felt that I was\nold enough to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">be responsible for</strong> myself and my mother needed to stop protecting me. Finally, she\nunderstood and let me go.\nBut I will never forget that day when I would go against my mother’s decision and also the fact\nthat I got super wasted that night and was grounded for the next two months.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"be responsible for","vi":"chịu trách nhiệm về"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a decision that you disagreed with","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-189","_displayNo":"#189","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a difficult decision that you once made\nYou should say:\n- What the decision was\n- How you made your decision\n- What the results of the decision were\n- Why it was difficult to make.","answer":"I have made many difficult decisions in my life, but today I would like to talk about the decision of\nchoosing which university to study at.\nIt was about 2 years ago, when I graduated from high school. At that time, I was terribly busy as I\nhad to prepare the application form for the university entrance exam. I had to make an important\nbut difficult decision.\nAt that time, I was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">at a crossroads</strong>, where I had to decide which university to apply for. My interest\nwas in English language, which was taught in many separate universities. Fortunately, my older\nbrother, who graduated from the University of Pedagogy, gave me some sound advice. Having\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">weighed up the pros and cons</strong> of each school, he encouraged me to choose the university\nspecialising in my subject. Finally, I applied for this school after thinking carefully about all the\noptions.\nAt present, I feel so satisfied with the learning environment of this university that I am always\nthankful for my decision as well as my brother’s advice. Without his guidance, I probably wouldn’t\nbe as content with my university life as I am.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"at a crossroads","vi":"đứng trước bước ngoặt cần quyết định"},{"en":"weighed up the pros and cons","vi":"cân nhắc ưu và nhược điểm"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a difficult decision that you once made","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-190","_displayNo":"#190","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a plan\nYou should say:\nWhat the plan is/was\nWhen you thought of the plan\nWho is involved in the plan\nAnd say how you did/think you will achieve the plan","answer":"Well I just turned 18 this year, so apparently it is time for me to plan something special for the\nfuture. There are many things that I could do, but one of the plans that I find the most intriguing\nis to go travelling to Singapore.\nI came up with this plan after I had finished my university entrance exam in June, and three of my\nbest friends have decided to come with me. So we kind of feel that after 12 years of hard work\nand constant studying that <strong class=\"key-phrase\">taking a break is really essential</strong>. I think we all decided on Singapore\nbecause it’s such a modern city with such a clean environment, and not to mention the fact that\nit’s so close to Vietnam, it’s just a short flight.\nTechnically we’re all just barely adults so it might take some time to persuade our parents to allow\nus to go on this trip together though.\nFirst of all, we decided that it is vital to choose a tour, because going on a tour will make our\nparents feel more secure. It might be quite boring though due to the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">lack of spontaneous activities</strong>,\nbut it seems like it’s the best option to persuade our parents.\nAnother thing to consider is the price of the tour. If it’s too expensive, I am afraid our parents will\nnot let us go either, so choosing an affordable tour is a must.\nApparently, we must <strong class=\"key-phrase\">book our plane tickets in advance</strong> too, not only to get the cheapest price but\nalso so that we are more well-prepared. When we reach Singapore, I think we will be polite\ntourists, listen carefully to the tour guide and avoid doing anything illegal. So that’s our great plan\nto achieve <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a much-needed vacation</strong>.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"taking a break is really essential","vi":"việc nghỉ ngơi thực sự cần thiết"},{"en":"lack of spontaneous activities","vi":"thiếu các hoạt động ngẫu hứng"},{"en":"book our plane tickets in advance","vi":"đặt vé máy bay trước"},{"en":"a much-needed vacation","vi":"một kỳ nghỉ rất cần thiết"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a plan","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-191","_displayNo":"#191","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a positive change that you made to your life.\nYou should say:\n- When it happened\n- Where it happened\n- What the change was\nAnd explain how you have benefited from this change\n( or, explain how you feel about this change)","answer":"I would like to tell you about a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">life-changing</strong> decision that I have made lately. It was when I decided to\nchange my entire career path. You know, 6 months ago I was still a <strong class=\"key-phrase\">real-estate agent</strong>. I would been\nworking as a salesman for around a year and a half and I was making some progress and seeing\nsome positive results. But somehow, as I kept digging deep into this career, I realized it did not really\nsuit me. I mean, when I pictured myself 5 years from then, I did not think I wanted to be a salesman\nanymore. That’s why I quit my job and went on to test my ability in an unrelated area. I wanted to\nbe a teacher. As I was searching, I realised that a job teaching IELTS in Hanoi offers quite a lucrative\nincome, so I started learning everything I could about IELTS.\nOf course, the journey was arduous at the beginning, I was overwhelmed with all the self-learning\nmaterials that I found on the internet. I knew at that time that I couldn’t do it alone so I sought out\nthe help of my friends. I found one who shared the same goals as me and we began studying\ntogether. Mainly what we did was keep each other motivated and disciplined, so we set out some\nground rules to follow, whoever broke the rules would receive harsh punishment. Just like that,\nafter 2 months, we were ready to take the test, and we took it on the same day. Now, we are both\nIELTS teachers and are enjoying our new responsibilities. Of course as a new teacher I have to\nfigure out a lot of things and do a lot of research to develop a deep understanding of teaching\nmethods. But, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">in retrospect</strong>, I have to say that I have made the right move. The new job gives me a\nlot of fun and opens doors to numerous opportunities for self-improvement. So all in all, this a\npositive change in my life.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"life-changing","vi":"thay đổi cuộc đời"},{"en":"real-estate agent","vi":"nhân viên môi giới bất động sản"},{"en":"in retrospect","vi":"khi hồi tưởng lại"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a positive change that you made to your life","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-192","_displayNo":"#192","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a recent change in your life\nYou should say:\nWhat the change was\nWhen it happened\nHow you felt about it\nAnd explain if it was a positive or negative change for you","answer":"I suppose one of the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">biggest turning points</strong> in my life was when I graduated from university just a\ncouple of months ago. I looked for a job and began working full-time right after that so I have not\nreally had time to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take a deep breath</strong> and reflect on this momentous change.\nPeople say that university is one of the best periods of time in your life, and that you will miss it\nonce you are employed. That’s not true for me, because I was very relieved when I finally got my\ndegree. I did not get to learn a lot in school and was always irritated by the poor attitude of the staff\nthere. Throughout 4 years, all I wanted was to get a job so that I could support myself first and\nthen my family. And that has finally come true. I am more in my element when I am working because\nI constantly learn new things and have to deal with new challenges.\nBut the biggest change for me is that now I can take care of myself financially and not have to rely\non my family anymore. I already worked part-time when I was in university, but what I made was not\nnearly enough to save for a rainy day, let alone support my family. So although my work is not all\nroses, I am still very glad I have made it this far. Personally I feel this change has had a very positive\nimpact on me.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"biggest turning points","vi":"những bước ngoặt lớn nhất"},{"en":"take a deep breath","vi":"hít một hơi thật sâu"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a recent change in your life","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-193","_displayNo":"#193","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a situation when you had to be polite\nYou should say:\n- What situation it was\n- Who were there\n- Why you had to be polite\n- How you showed politeness","answer":"I would like to talk about a time when I saved a bus seat for a pregnant lady.\nIt was a rainy day around 3 years ago when I was still a freshman at university. On a bus trip from\nmy dormitory to the city center to attend <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a music festival</strong> sponsored by Heineken, I met a pregnant\nlady who got on the bus at one of the stations. At that time, the bus was already <strong class=\"key-phrase\">swarming with</strong>\nstudents, and many of them even had to stand as there were not enough seats for all. In that\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">stuffy atmosphere</strong>, the lady’s face suddenly turned pale and she had to hold on to the hand rail\ntightly. Sweat was rolling off her forehead.\nWithout hesitation, I stood up and asked her to take my seat. Then I quickly opened the glass\nwindow, trying to release the heat from inside the bus. After taking a deep breath, the lady seemed\nto feel better and started to have conversation with me. She told me that she was on the way to\nvisit her aunt who was in the hospital. She knew that the bus was full but she couldn’t wait for the\nnext one in order not to be late for the visiting hours. She also thanked me a lot for saving her the\nseat. Without a place to sit on the bus, she thought she would have fainted because of dizziness.\nI think any person who witnessed that moment would also have the same reaction as me. For me,\nI did it simply because it was necessary, and my action just came from my instinct, without any\nhesitation. If the lady had stood for a long time, that would have affected not only her health but\nalso her baby inside. Also, I always thought of my mother’s advice to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">pay close attention to</strong> things\naround me and provide support to people at the right time as it could be very meaningful.\nTherefore, at the end of that day, I was still thrilled because I had helped not only one, but two\npeople. I mean the mother and her baby.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"a music festival","vi":"một lễ hội âm nhạc"},{"en":"swarming with","vi":"đông nghịt; đầy ắp"},{"en":"stuffy atmosphere","vi":"bầu không khí ngột ngạt"},{"en":"pay close attention to","vi":"chú ý kỹ đến"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a situation when you had to be polite","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-194","_displayNo":"#194","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a situation where you have to be polite\nYou should say:\n- What it is.\n- What you do to be polite.\n- Why you have to be polite.\n- How you feel about it.","answer":"I would like to start by saying that I always try to be polite in all situations, because that was how\nI was brought up. However, I have to admit that there are just some individuals out there who\nenjoying feeding on negative energy.\nIt happened when I had to work in a team with other university friends on an assignment in\nEconomic Studies. In our group then, there was one person who I disliked because he always had\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">half-baked</strong> knowledge on everything and a perception that he knew everything. His attitude made\neveryone in our group really annoyed and sometimes the teamwork became stressful.\nSo, regarding why I had to be polite, it was because we had to work together over a period of\nabout four months and ensure the best outcome. Although it was difficult at first because of his\npersonality and the fact that he always thought that he was right and had the best ideas, eventually\nwe all managed to work as a team and by the end of the project he wasn't really as bad as he had\nbeen at the beginning and was more willing to collaborate with the rest of us in the group. And\nthat was my experience of being nice to someone I disliked.\nThe incident helped me understand that it is impossible to shield yourself from negativity, so the\nonly things you can do are learn how to deal with hateful people and grow thicker skin.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"half-baked","vi":"chưa được suy tính kỹ"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a situation where you have to be polite","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-195","_displayNo":"#195","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a time that you arrived early\nYou should say:\nWhen it was;\nHow early you arrived;\nWhy you arrived early;\nAnd explain how you felt about it.","answer":"So last week I actually had to show up early for my friend’s wedding party. And as her bestie, I\nthink it’s my responsibility to help her have the best wedding ever, so on her wedding day, I\ndecided to show up early and help her with all the preparations. I think it was about 5am when I\narrived at the front door of her house. Actually, I am quite the night owl, so it was a little difficult\nfor me to get up that early but once I saw the big smile on her face I was completely awake and\ngot to work right away. So, the list of things-to-do was quite long, decorating the room with\nflowers, cleaning dishes, preparing the food, so I was really glad that I had decided to come early.\nBy about 9am, after everything was thoroughly done, the wedding ceremony began in a very\nsincere and happy atmosphere.\nWitnessing the bride and groom <strong class=\"key-phrase\">exchanging vows</strong> was quite emotional and I even shed a tear or\ntwo. I felt very happy for her that she’d finally found her Mr. Right. And after the wedding party,\ndespite being exhausted, I was also quite relieved and delighted because I think my help was one\nof the factors that really made her day so special.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"exchanging vows","vi":"trao lời thề nguyện"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a time that you arrived early","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-196","_displayNo":"#196","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a time when you had a problem with a piece of equipment\nYou should say:\n- What equipment it was\n- What problem you had\n- When you had this problem\nAnd explain what you did about this problem.","answer":"I am actually very quick when it comes to technology and devices, but I am going to tell you one time\nwhen I really couldn’t deal with a technical problem on my phone.\nThis story dates back to when I got my very first smartphone. You know, at that time, about 7 – 8 years\nago, most students only had a basic phone, or, a dumbphone, which could only serve 2 or 3 functions.\nHaving a brand new, updated iPhone seemed to be such a big deal, and I immediately became the\ntarget of jealousy when I brought my phone to school.\nAt first, it was really great to be the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">centre of attention</strong>, but after a while, I realised that my friends\ntried to download a ton of applications to my device. When I got my phone back, one of them secretly\ntold me that a boy had installed a harmful app which would cause serious battery drain, and right after\nthat, the phone shut down. It came as a real shock to me as that was just the first day I had that phone.\nI was speechless for hours, paralysed with fright. I did not know how to tell mother and father about the\nincident, because I was very sure they would kill me the second they found out about it. Also, I couldn’t\nget my phone fixed at the store because I was flat broke then. In that moment, I really thought that\nmy life was over.\nMy desk mate noticed my silence and turned to see my eyes full of tears. I thought she was going to\nsay something to cheer me up, but no, she just laughed so hard at me until my whole face turned red.\nI stopped crying and looked at her with curiosity, and she told me to turn my phone on. It worked. It\nturned out that I was actually fooled by my classmates.\nThat’s how I fixed the problem with my phone, in such a surprisingly easy way.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"centre of attention","vi":"trung tâm của sự chú ý"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a time when you had a problem with a piece of equipment","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-197","_displayNo":"#197","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a time when you had to work hard to achieve a goal\nYou should say:\nwhat the goal was\nwhen this happened\nwhat you did to achieve this goal\nand explain why the goal was important to you.","answer":"I am the type of person who never likes to rely on luck. I believe that everything can only be\nachieved through hard work and determination, and my final year in high school was one of the\ntimes that I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">spared no effort</strong> to achieve my goal.\nAt that point, I was still a senior student and like all the other students, passing the University\nentrance exam to get into my dream University was my main goal. But for me, I felt that the\npressure was even higher since I had chosen Hanoi Medical University – one of the top\nUniversities in Vietnam. There are thousands of students taking part in that exam every year so it\nis <strong class=\"key-phrase\">highly competitive</strong>.\nIn order to compete with the other candidates, every day I would spend hours in the library to\nread as many books as possible and to learn as much as I could. And even after school, I usually\nstayed up late to review everything I had learned that day. It was a long process with a lot of hard\nwork but I did not feel tired at all because becoming a doctor was one of my greatest desires. I was\nwilling to put in a lot of hard work and effort for that dream and to not let anything stop me from\nachieving it.\nSo in the end, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">all the hard work paid off</strong>, and I passed the entrance exam with outstanding results\nand became a medical student. When I received the results, I was so happy that I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">burst into tears</strong>.\nAll of my hard work for the year had helped me achieve one of my big goals in life so far.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"spared no effort","vi":"không tiếc công sức"},{"en":"highly competitive","vi":"có tính cạnh tranh rất cao"},{"en":"all the hard work paid off","vi":"mọi nỗ lực đã được đền đáp"},{"en":"burst into tears","vi":"bật khóc"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a time when you had to work hard to achieve a goal","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-198","_displayNo":"#198","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a time when you saw an interesting animal\nYou should say:\n- What animal it was\n- When and Where you saw it\nAnd explain how you feel about this animal","answer":"Well, I am going to talk about an occasion on which I got to see a group of small monkeys. As we\nall know, monkeys are one of the funniest animals in nature. They are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">full of curiosity</strong>, adventure\nand mischief, and have great intelligence. They often live in the jungle, mostly in tropical rain\nforests, and jump from tree to tree to seek out food and play. The diet of a monkey includes nuts,\nberries, fruits, anything that smells good, and not to mention, bananas, which is always at the top\nof their list.\nAnyway, back to the main point, the first time I saw a real monkey was a long time ago, when I\nwas in secondary school. My friends and I travelled to a mountain located somewhere on the\noutskirts of Hanoi, and when we were climbing the mountain, suddenly a group of small monkeys\nappeared in the middle of the road ahead in the distance. They were jumping up and down from\ntrees before they approached us. Then the monkeys stared at me and my friends as though they\nwanted to communicate and ask for food, so I decided to give them some of our snacks. They were\nreally cute creatures, you know, their hands are like a mini version of ours, which makes them look\nlike little kids.\nHowever, although I am quite into monkeys, I have to admit that they are unexpectedly sneaky. In\nsome tourist attractions around Vietnam, you can easily spot a troop of monkeys stealing food\nfrom street vendors, and other unsuspecting tourists. Unfortunately, there’s nothing we can do\nbut watch them run off into the jungle with our food as they are way faster and smarter than you\nmay think.\nAnyway, the trip was truly a once-in-a-life-time experience for me as I got to touch and feed wild\nmonkeys. Seeing them first hand also <strong class=\"key-phrase\">made me realize that</strong> they share more common features with\nhumans than I would previously thought, which really evoked my curiosity about the theory of how\npeople evolved from apes over millions of years.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"full of curiosity","vi":"đầy tính tò mò"},{"en":"made me realize that","vi":"khiến tôi nhận ra rằng"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a time when you saw an interesting animal","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-199","_displayNo":"#199","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a time when you were looking at the sky\nYou should say:\nWhen and where you looked at the sky\nWho you looked at sky with\nHow you felt when looking at it\nAnd explain why you looked at the sky","answer":"Looking at the sky seems like the sort of thing we might do every day without actually having any\nawareness of doing it. But today I want to share with you the time when I had an opportunity to\nlook up into the sky from a city on the other side of the planet.\nA couple of years ago I had a great opportunity to escape from the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">scorching hot</strong> summer in Hanoi\nto one of the most stunning cities in Europe, London. Usually the weather in London is pretty\nmuch day after day of overcast clouds and dreariness with high levels of rainfall throughout the\nyear. However when I arrived in London, I guess I must have caught a lucky break in the clouds as\nthe city was lit up in sunlight.\nBut while I was travelling from the airport to my hotel in the west part of London with my mother,\nI opened the car window to glance around and feel the wind on my skin and in my hair. By this\npoint, the sun had disappeared and the sky was overcast and grey with loads of thick clouds. There\nwere many people on the street walking in a hurry to avoid the rain, while others were too\nabsorbed with their phones to even notice the coming rain.\nI was so excited and curious about this huge city that I decided not to let the rain ruin my first day,\neven though I got soaking wet in the heavy downpour as I got out of the cab and moved my\nluggage. For the rest of the day, I spent my time looking at the sky from my hotel room’s window\nwhile the rain <strong class=\"key-phrase\">kept pouring down</strong>. I love London, without a doubt, but that kind of weather totally\nmade me feel depressed.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"scorching hot","vi":"nóng như thiêu đốt"},{"en":"kept pouring down","vi":"mưa như trút nước liên tục"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a time when you were looking at the sky","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-200","_displayNo":"#200","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a time when you were not allowed to use your cell phone\nYou should say:\nWhere you were\nWhen it happened\nWhat you were doing\nAnd why you were not allowed to use your cell phone","answer":"Well, I think that mobile phones have now become the must-have item for everybody in daily life,\nso much so that we somehow feel we cannot live without them. I always remember the one time\nthat I had to be apart from my phone when I was sitting my high school graduation exam 2 years\nago, and I have to say it was quite uncomfortable.\nSo, my high school graduation exam is a mandatory examination that students have to take at the\nend of grade 12 to get their diploma and their score is what determines their ability to enter into\nuniversity. It’s one of the most important events in a student’s life, I guess, because it not only\npretty much shapes their future but also helps to reassure them of their own ability.\nAnd of course, cell phones are not allowed in the test, to ensure that no one gets <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an unfair\nadvantage</strong> by cheating. If your phone makes a noise, or if you are seen using it at any time,\nincluding during breaks, you may be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">dismissed from the examination</strong> immediately, and your scores\nwill be cancelled without exception.\nI myself had a bad habit of always going on the internet on my phone to make sure I got the right\nanswers when doing the practice tests at home, so during the exam, I constantly had <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a burning\ndesire to</strong> reach for my phone but obviously it was just a thought and I did not dare to do it. However\nthe feelings of uncertainty about my results were haunting me and made me really nervous, and\nit was not until I handed in my papers and checked the answers when I got home, was I able to feel\ncalm again.\nFrom this experience, I realized that I do <strong class=\"key-phrase\">rely too much on my phone</strong>. And although it’s a great tool\nto assist studying I do think we should learn how to be more confident in ourselves and our\nknowledge without having to look at our phones all the time.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"an unfair advantage","vi":"lợi thế không công bằng"},{"en":"dismissed from the examination","vi":"bị đình chỉ khỏi kỳ thi"},{"en":"a burning desire to","vi":"mong muốn mãnh liệt được"},{"en":"rely too much on my phone","vi":"phụ thuộc quá nhiều vào điện thoại"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a time when you were not allowed to use your cell phone","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-201","_displayNo":"#201","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe a time when you worked in a team\nYou should say:\nwhat the activity was\nwho you worked with you\nhow easy or difficult it was\nAnd explain how you felt about being part of this team.","answer":"I would like to talk about <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a team project</strong> that I was involved in during my “British and American culture”\nclass at the Foreign Trade University in Hanoi. There were six of us on the team, and our task was\nto identify the differences in the travelling habits of British and American tourists. Our objective\nwas to produce a report and give a presentation.\nSo the first thing we did was split into two groups of three. We had to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">conduct a survey</strong>, so three\nof us spent some time designing a questionnaire while the other three prepared an outline for the\nreport. One of the difficulties we encountered was finding enough people for the survey because\nwe needed 50 British and 50 Americans. But thanks to Facebook, we were able to reach enough\npeople from those countries who were willing to help us out and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">fill in the online survey</strong>. In the\nend, I think it was a successful project because we were able to figure out the main travelling\npatterns of people from the US and the UK. Our group presentation also went really well.\nIt was really a memorable experience for all of us and I felt <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a real sense of accomplishment</strong> when\nwe handed in our report and delivered our presentation. But what I was most proud of was how\nwell our team worked together. There were still some minor tiffs between some of the team\nmembers, but overall I think each member showed a good level of responsibility and teamwork.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"a team project","vi":"một dự án nhóm"},{"en":"conduct a survey","vi":"tiến hành một cuộc khảo sát"},{"en":"fill in the online survey","vi":"điền khảo sát trực tuyến"},{"en":"a real sense of accomplishment","vi":"cảm giác thành tựu thực sự"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"a time when you worked in a team","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-202","_displayNo":"#202","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe an achievement that you are proud of.\nYou should say:\n- What you do;\n- When, where, and how you do it;\n- How difficult it is;\n- Why you are proud of it.","answer":"I would like to talk about one of my personal achievements that I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take pride in</strong>, and that is passing\nmy university entrance examination. This exam is known to be nerve-wracking and challenging,\nespecially when you wish to attend the prestigious schools in town.\nTo be honest, back in high school, I was not much of a diligent student. I had no appreciation of hard\nwork and self-improvement. Higher education was not something I aimed at, all I wished for was to\ngraduate from high school. But in my senior year, I had a chance to study with a dedicated\nLiterature teacher. The messages that she delivered in each lesson were <strong class=\"key-phrase\">mind-opening</strong> and\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">thought-provoking</strong>, activating my desire for self-betterment. At the same time, I harbored my\nhope of being a teacher. I know that it was not easy for a student with bad academic results like\nme to get into the University of Education, but when I set my heart on something, I will go to great\nlengths to attain it. The exam included three core subjects, namely Maths, Literature and English.\nLanguages were my forte, but Maths was not my thing. I started to study around the clock and\ntook an active role in learning by doing extra algebra exercises and seeking help from my teachers\nwith any questions that arose. There were times when I was exhausted and disheartened, but the\nencouragements from my teachers were helpful in keeping me motivated.\nFinally, the hard work paid off. I was over the moon when informed to be accepted to that\nuniversity. I was proud of myself for the determination and effort it took to step out of my comfort\nzone and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make my dream come true</strong>.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"take pride in","vi":"tự hào về"},{"en":"mind-opening","vi":"mở mang tư duy"},{"en":"thought-provoking","vi":"gợi nhiều suy ngẫm"},{"en":"make my dream come true","vi":"biến ước mơ của tôi thành hiện thực"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an achievement that you are proud of","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-203","_displayNo":"#203","band":"8.5"},{"section":"speaking-part-2","title":"Situation","prompt":"Describe an experience that you had when you left home\nYou should say:\n- What is it\n- When did it happen\n- And how do you feel about that experience","answer":"I am going to tell you about the time when I got lost in a forest 80 km away from my house. It was\n1 year ago, I was on a 2-day company trip to a famous resort not so far from the centre of Hanoi.\nThe first day was fun, as I had many incredible experiences with all my co-workers. We were\neating, drinking and singing until we were too drunk to move our heads. And as usual, being drunk\nis when we do all kinds of crazy stuff. The place where we camped was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">adjacent to</strong> a huge forest.\nI, who was literally <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cross-eyed drunk</strong>, came up with a brilliant idea. “Let’s go discovering that\nforest” – I said to those people who were still able to walk. And, crazy as it sounds, they were all\ninterested in what I said.\nSo, around 10 of us left our camp and advanced into the forest. The night was dark, so we turned\non the flash on our phones to see. At first, when we could still see our camping fire, we were\nexcited. I, as the leader, kept walking having no idea where I was heading. At first, the dark forest\nseemed to be rather amusing. But then, after around 20 minutes of roaming, we found ourselves\n<strong class=\"key-phrase\">in the middle of nowhere</strong>, and even worse, none of us remembered the way back to our camp. As\nwe walked a little bit further, we saw a giant Banyan tree and a temple right next to it. The pale\nred light from the temple made it look a bit creepy. Right at that moment, one of my colleagues\ntold a ghost story about a temple in his hometown. The story was so horrifying that one of us gave\nout a shrill scream.\nWe instantly regretted our decision, but as I said earlier none of us had any idea how to get back\nto our camp. We called some friends in the camp and asked them for help. Luckily some were still\nawake and they immediately went to those who owned the place and told them about our\nsituation. Of course the locals knew where the tree was so they told us to wait. As scared as we\nwere, we had to stay near the tree waiting for people to come to rescue us. After 15 minutes, the\nlocals came and showed us the way back to our camp. We all felt lucky and we were all tired, but\nsomehow we managed to stay awake all night long talking about the journey. I will never forget\nthat day, it was a truly memorable trip.","author":"ZIM","topic":"Situation","phrases":[{"en":"adjacent to","vi":"nằm liền kề với"},{"en":"cross-eyed drunk","vi":"say đến mức mất tỉnh táo"},{"en":"in the middle of nowhere","vi":"ở một nơi hẻo lánh"}],"source":"ZIM – 179 IELTS Speaking Part 2 Samples","subtype":"","summary":"an experience that you had when you left home","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-2-204","_displayNo":"#204","band":"8.0"},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Advertising","prompt":"Do you think there are too many game shows on TV nowadays and why?\nDo you think that people pay attention to adverts on TV and why?","answer":"Q: Do you think there are too many game shows on TV nowadays and why?\nA: Yes, there are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">far too many</strong> game shows on TV for my liking. I suppose the channels show these programs because they are popular, and they must be very profitable. A good example is 'Who wants to be a millionaire?', which has been sold to TV channels across the world. Personally, I'm not a fan of game shows, and I'd much rather watch a film or an original drama series.\n\nQ: Do you think that people pay attention to adverts on TV and why?\nA: Yes, I think we are all influenced <strong class=\"key-phrase\">to some extent</strong> by television advertising; otherwise companies would not spend so much money on it. Advertisers create memorable images and link products with desirable lifestyles. Even when viewers do not buy immediately, an advert can plant a seed in their minds and affect a later decision.","author":"Simon","topic":"Advertising","phrases":[{"en":"far too many","vi":"quá nhiều"},{"en":"to some extent","vi":"ở một mức độ nào đó"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Advertising","id":"speaking-part-3-001","_displayNo":"#001","qaBands":["9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Advertising","prompt":"Do you think advertisements influence what people buy?\nWhat criteria should be used to assess a good advertisement?","answer":"Q: Do you think advertisements influence what people buy?\nA: Yes, mainly by creating familiarity and attaching a product to a desirable image. Advertising rarely forces a purchase, but repeated exposure can make one brand feel safer or more familiar, which gives it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a subtle psychological advantage</strong>.\n\nQ: What criteria should be used to assess a good advertisement?\nA: A good advertisement should be clear, truthful and memorable, and it should speak to a specific audience without misleading them. Creativity matters, but credibility matters more because an advert that exaggerates will eventually <strong class=\"key-phrase\">damage consumer trust</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Advertising","phrases":[{"en":"a subtle psychological advantage","vi":"một lợi thế tâm lý tinh tế"},{"en":"damage consumer trust","vi":"làm tổn hại lòng tin của người tiêu dùng"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Advertising","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-002","_displayNo":"#002","qaBands":["8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Advertising","prompt":"What's the most popular form of advertising in your country?\nWould you like to work for an advertising company?\nDo you agree that advertisements for smoking should be banned?","answer":"Q: What's the most popular form of advertising in your country?\nA: Short-form video and social-media advertising are probably the most visible forms now. They are cheap to target, easy to share and highly personalised, although that same personalisation can feel <strong class=\"key-phrase\">uncomfortably intrusive</strong>.\n\nQ: Would you like to work for an advertising company?\nA: Possibly, if the company had strong ethical standards. The work can combine research, language and creativity, but I would not want to promote products through fear, deception or manufactured insecurity.\n\nQ: Do you agree that advertisements for smoking should be banned?\nA: Yes. Smoking creates serious public-health costs, and advertising can normalise an addictive product, especially for young people. A ban is justified because it helps <strong class=\"key-phrase\">protect vulnerable audiences</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Advertising","phrases":[{"en":"uncomfortably intrusive","vi":"xâm phạm một cách khó chịu"},{"en":"protect vulnerable audiences","vi":"bảo vệ nhóm khán giả dễ bị tổn thương"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Advertising","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-003","_displayNo":"#003","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Advice","prompt":"Is it better to get advice from a friend or from a family member?\nWhat would you say are the characteristics of a good adviser?\nShould people make their own work and career decisions, or is it a good idea to ask for advice about this?","answer":"Q: Is it better to get advice from a friend or from a family member?\nA: I think it depends on the kind of advice that you need. Parents and grandparents probably have more <strong class=\"key-phrase\">life experience</strong> than a friend, and so you might get a wiser or more sensible answer from them. On the other hand, friends are less likely to become too worried if you go to them with a problem. For example, I probably wouldn't want to burden my parents with a financial problem.\n\nQ: What would you say are the characteristics of a good adviser?\nA: Well, firstly, a good adviser should be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a good listener</strong>, someone who takes the time to understand the situation before offering advice. Secondly, an adviser should try to be objective, and avoid judging the person who is seeking help. Finally, I think the best advisers have the ability to ask the right questions and encourage others to find their own answers.\n\nQ: Should people make their own work and career decisions, or is it a good idea to ask for advice about this?\nA: I would say it is a combination of both. Most people benefit from discussing career choices with family, teachers or experienced colleagues because other people may notice risks or possibilities they have missed. However, the final decision should rest with the individual, who must take ultimate responsibility for the consequences.","author":"Simon","topic":"Advice","phrases":[{"en":"life experience","vi":"kinh nghiệm sống"},{"en":"a good listener","vi":"một người biết lắng nghe"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Advice","id":"speaking-part-3-004","_displayNo":"#004","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Advice","prompt":"Does that person still give you advice?\nIs it helpful to learn from other people's experiences?\nWhat kind of advice do parents give to their children?","answer":"Q: Does that person still give you advice?\nA: Yes, but I now ask for perspective rather than instructions. The most useful advice helps me see consequences I may have missed while leaving me to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take responsibility for</strong> the final decision.\n\nQ: Is it helpful to learn from other people's experiences?\nA: Definitely. Other people’s experience can shorten the learning curve and warn us about predictable mistakes. However, we still need to adapt their lessons because advice that worked in one situation may not <strong class=\"key-phrase\">transfer perfectly to another</strong>.\n\nQ: What kind of advice do parents give to their children?\nA: Parents commonly advise children about education, money, relationships and personal safety. The best advice becomes less controlling as children mature and gradually encourages them to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">think independently</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Advice","phrases":[{"en":"take responsibility for","vi":"chịu trách nhiệm về"},{"en":"transfer perfectly to another","vi":"áp dụng hoàn toàn sang hoàn cảnh khác"},{"en":"think independently","vi":"suy nghĩ độc lập"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Advice","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-005","_displayNo":"#005","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Animals","prompt":"In what ways are humans different from other animals?\nWhat are the main roles of animals in your country?","answer":"Q: In what ways are humans different from other animals?\nA: Humans differ mainly in our capacity for complex language, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">cumulative culture</strong> and long-term planning. Other animals can solve problems and form social bonds, but humans can pass highly detailed knowledge across generations and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reshape entire environments</strong>.\n\nQ: What are the main roles of animals in your country?\nA: Animals provide food, labour, companionship and ecological services such as pollination and pest control. Their role is changing as farming becomes more mechanised and urban families increasingly keep animals for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">emotional companionship</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Animals","phrases":[{"en":"cumulative culture","vi":"văn hóa được tích lũy qua nhiều thế hệ"},{"en":"reshape entire environments","vi":"thay đổi toàn bộ môi trường"},{"en":"emotional companionship","vi":"sự đồng hành về cảm xúc"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Animals","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-006","_displayNo":"#006","qaBands":["8.0","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Animals","prompt":"What is involved in taking care of a pet?\nHow do you think people's attitudes towards animals will change in the future?\nWhat do you think should be done about poaching endangered animals?","answer":"Q: What is involved in taking care of a pet?\nA: Proper care involves suitable food, exercise, hygiene, veterinary treatment and regular attention. People should also consider the animal’s expected lifespan before adopting it, because ownership is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a long-term commitment</strong>.\n\nQ: How do you think people's attitudes towards animals will change in the future?\nA: I expect welfare standards to become stricter and public concern about factory farming and wildlife protection to grow. At the same time, urban pet ownership will probably increase, making animals an even more visible part of family life.\n\nQ: What do you think should be done about poaching endangered animals?\nA: Poaching should be addressed through stronger enforcement, reduced demand for illegal products and better economic alternatives for local communities. Punishment alone is not enough if people living near wildlife have no reason to benefit from conservation.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Animals","phrases":[{"en":"a long-term commitment","vi":"một cam kết lâu dài"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Animals","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-007","_displayNo":"#007","qaBands":["8.5","8.0","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Books & Reading","prompt":"Are there any occasions when reading at speed is a useful skill?\nAre there any jobs in which people need to read a lot? Which ones?\nDo you think reading novels is more interesting than reading factual books, and why?","answer":"Q: Are there any occasions when reading at speed is a useful skill?\nA: If I am reading something interesting, I prefer not to rush because I want to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">absorb it properly</strong>. Reading quickly is useful when I need only one fact or a general impression, such as when I <strong class=\"key-phrase\">skim a bill</strong>, a timetable or a long work email.\n\nQ: Are there any jobs in which people need to read a lot? Which ones?\nA: Researchers, lawyers, journalists, academics and policy professionals often need to read large amounts of material. In reality, most office workers also process hundreds of emails and documents every week, so <strong class=\"key-phrase\">efficient reading</strong> is valuable in many occupations.\n\nQ: Do you think reading novels is more interesting than reading factual books, and why?\nA: Both types of book can be equally interesting in my opinion. A good novel can transport you to another world where the characters in the book become almost real. On the other hand, factual books can give you <strong class=\"key-phrase\">fascinating insights into</strong> anything from psychology to ancient history.","author":"Simon","topic":"Books & Reading","phrases":[{"en":"absorb it properly","vi":"tiếp thu nội dung một cách đầy đủ"},{"en":"skim a bill","vi":"đọc lướt một hóa đơn"},{"en":"efficient reading","vi":"khả năng đọc hiệu quả"},{"en":"fascinating insights into","vi":"những hiểu biết sâu sắc và hấp dẫn về"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Books & Reading","id":"speaking-part-3-008","_displayNo":"#008","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Books & Reading","prompt":"What kind of books do you read?\nWhat types of books do children like?\nShould we encourage children to read books and why?","answer":"Q: What kind of books do you read?\nA: I mainly read non-fiction on psychology, education and technology, along with an occasional novel. Non-fiction gives me practical ideas, while fiction develops empathy by allowing me to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">inhabit another person’s perspective</strong>.\n\nQ: What types of books do children like?\nA: Younger children often prefer illustrated stories, humour and adventure, while teenagers may be drawn to fantasy, mystery or books linked to films and games. The key is giving them enough choice to discover <strong class=\"key-phrase\">what genuinely holds their attention</strong>.\n\nQ: Should we encourage children to read books and why?\nA: Yes, but encouragement should not become constant testing. Parents can read with children, keep books within reach and let them choose topics, which helps reading become <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a source of pleasure</strong> rather than another school obligation.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Books & Reading","phrases":[{"en":"inhabit another person’s perspective","vi":"đặt mình vào góc nhìn của người khác"},{"en":"what genuinely holds their attention","vi":"điều thực sự thu hút sự chú ý của chúng"},{"en":"a source of pleasure","vi":"một nguồn vui"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Books & Reading","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-009","_displayNo":"#009","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Books & Reading","prompt":"Why do you think some people write books?\nWhat type of books do you read often?\nDo you prefer to read a book or watch a movie on the same subject and why?","answer":"Q: Why do you think some people write books?\nA: People write to tell stories, preserve knowledge, influence debate or make sense of their own experience. For many authors, writing is both a profession and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a way of organising thought</strong>.\n\nQ: What type of books do you read often?\nA: I often read <strong class=\"key-phrase\">research-based non-fiction</strong> about education, psychology and technology. I also read novels occasionally because fiction <strong class=\"key-phrase\">develops a different kind of understanding</strong>: it allows the reader to experience another person’s motives from the inside.\n\nQ: Do you prefer to read a book or watch a movie on the same subject and why?\nA: I usually prefer the book when I want depth, because it can explore inner thoughts and background in far greater detail. A film is more immediate and visually powerful, but it inevitably <strong class=\"key-phrase\">compresses the original material</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Books & Reading","phrases":[{"en":"a way of organising thought","vi":"một cách tổ chức suy nghĩ"},{"en":"research-based non-fiction","vi":"sách phi hư cấu dựa trên nghiên cứu"},{"en":"develops a different kind of understanding","vi":"phát triển một kiểu thấu hiểu khác"},{"en":"compresses the original material","vi":"rút gọn nguyên tác"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Books & Reading","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-010","_displayNo":"#010","qaBands":["8.0","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Celebrations","prompt":"What types of parties do people have, and why are parties important?\nWhy do you think some people like parties but others hate them?\nDo you think parties will become more popular in the future?","answer":"Q: What types of parties do people have, and why are parties important?\nA: People have parties to celebrate special occasions like birthdays, weddings, or the beginning of a new year. I think it's important to celebrate these things because they are landmarks in our lives. Parties are a good way to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">bring people together</strong>, and they're an opportunity to let off some steam.\n\nQ: Why do you think some people like parties but others hate them?\nA: Most people like parties because they have a good time - eating a nice meal, chatting to friends, or having a dance. People who don't like them might find social situations difficult because they are shy, or maybe they don't enjoy having to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make small talk with</strong> people they don't know.\n\nQ: Do you think parties will become more popular in the future?\nA: I do not think parties will necessarily become more popular; they have always been <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a basic form of social life</strong>. The format may change, with smaller gatherings or events organised online, but people will continue to celebrate and socialise together.","author":"Simon","topic":"Celebrations","phrases":[{"en":"bring people together","vi":"gắn kết mọi người"},{"en":"make small talk with","vi":"trò chuyện xã giao với"},{"en":"a basic form of social life","vi":"một hình thức cơ bản của đời sống xã hội"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Celebrations","id":"speaking-part-3-011","_displayNo":"#011","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Celebrations","prompt":"Do you think new festivals will be introduced in the future?\nWhy do you think festivals are important in the working year?\nWould you agree that the original significance of the festivals is often lost today?","answer":"Q: Do you think new festivals will be introduced in the future?\nA: Yes. New festivals may emerge around environmental causes, local identity or modern cultural interests. Some will be commercial, but others can become meaningful if communities <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make them their own</strong>.\n\nQ: Why do you think festivals are important in the working year?\nA: Festivals interrupt routine and give people a shared reason to rest, meet relatives and reflect on tradition. That break can improve morale and strengthen <strong class=\"key-phrase\">social cohesion</strong>.\n\nQ: Would you agree that the original significance of the festivals is often lost today?\nA: Partly. Commercial promotion can overshadow religious or historical meaning, especially when a festival becomes mainly about shopping. However, traditions naturally evolve, so change does not necessarily mean that the celebration has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">lost all cultural value</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Celebrations","phrases":[{"en":"make them their own","vi":"biến chúng thành nét riêng của cộng đồng"},{"en":"social cohesion","vi":"sự gắn kết xã hội"},{"en":"lost all cultural value","vi":"mất toàn bộ giá trị văn hóa"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Celebrations","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-012","_displayNo":"#012","qaBands":["8.5","8.0","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Celebrations","prompt":"What types of parties are popular in your country?\nWhat sort of activities do people do at parties?\nWhat do you think of attending parties?","answer":"Q: What types of parties are popular in your country?\nA: Birthday parties, weddings, family gatherings and company celebrations are the most common. Younger people may prefer informal events, while older generations often value occasions that bring <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the extended family</strong> together.\n\nQ: What sort of activities do people do at parties?\nA: People usually eat, talk, take photographs, play music and sometimes organise games or speeches. The best parties leave enough structure to avoid boredom without making guests feel that every minute is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">overly programmed</strong>.\n\nQ: What do you think of attending parties?\nA: I enjoy small or medium-sized gatherings where conversation is possible. Very large parties can be exciting, but they often feel superficial and make it difficult to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">connect with people properly</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Celebrations","phrases":[{"en":"the extended family","vi":"đại gia đình"},{"en":"overly programmed","vi":"bị lên lịch quá mức"},{"en":"connect with people properly","vi":"kết nối với mọi người một cách thực sự"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Celebrations","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-013","_displayNo":"#013","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Change","prompt":"Why do some older people resist change?\nIs technological change always positive?","answer":"Q: Why do some older people resist change?\nA: Some older people resist change because familiar routines provide competence and security. A new system can make them feel dependent or excluded, especially when it is introduced without training or <strong class=\"key-phrase\">respect for existing habits</strong>.\n\nQ: Is technological change always positive?\nA: No. Technology can increase efficiency and access, but it can also displace jobs, weaken privacy or create dependence. Its value should be judged by outcomes, not novelty, and by whether benefits are shared fairly.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Change","phrases":[{"en":"respect for existing habits","vi":"sự tôn trọng đối với thói quen hiện có"}],"source":"Topic reference: IELTS Advantage (2026); questions adapted; answers rewritten and quality-audited by ChatGPT","subtype":"","summary":"Change","id":"speaking-part-3-014","_displayNo":"#014","qaBands":["8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Children","prompt":"Do you think it is important for boys to play with boys' toys and for girls to only play with girls' toys?\nDo you think it is good if parents only buy educational toys for their children?","answer":"Q: Do you think it is important for boys to play with boys' toys and for girls to only play with girls' toys?\nA: I think boys <strong class=\"key-phrase\">naturally seem to prefer</strong> playing with \"boys' toys\" and girls with \"girls' toys\". When I was young I had toy cars, trucks, guns and things like that, whereas my sister always wanted to play with dolls. I don't suppose it really matters if a boy plays with a doll or a girl plays with a toy car, but children learn quickly what toys are supposed to be for boys and for girls.\n\nQ: Do you think it is good if parents only buy educational toys for their children?\nA: No. Educational toys can be useful, but children also learn through imaginative and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">unstructured play</strong>. If every toy is chosen for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an obvious academic purpose</strong>, play can become another lesson rather than a chance to experiment, create rules and enjoy themselves.","author":"Simon","topic":"Children","phrases":[{"en":"naturally seem to prefer","vi":"dường như tự nhiên có xu hướng thích hơn"},{"en":"unstructured play","vi":"hoạt động chơi tự do, không bị sắp đặt"},{"en":"an obvious academic purpose","vi":"một mục đích học thuật rõ ràng"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Children","id":"speaking-part-3-015","_displayNo":"#015","qaBands":["9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Children","prompt":"Did you like to do more things at that age?\nWhat can people do to make the best use of their life?\nWhat is the most important event for a teenager?","answer":"Q: Did you like to do more things at that age?\nA: Yes, I would probably have tried more creative and outdoor activities. Children often avoid unfamiliar things because they fear failure, so gentle encouragement can help them step outside their comfort zone.\n\nQ: What can people do to make the best use of their life?\nA: People need to protect their health, maintain close relationships and pursue work that gives them a sense of direction. Achievement matters, but so does learning to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">appreciate ordinary life</strong>.\n\nQ: What is the most important event for a teenager?\nA: There is no single event, but finishing school or making a first major educational choice is often significant. It is one of the first moments when a teenager sees that decisions can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">shape future opportunities</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Children","phrases":[{"en":"appreciate ordinary life","vi":"trân trọng cuộc sống bình thường"},{"en":"shape future opportunities","vi":"định hình cơ hội tương lai"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Children","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-016","_displayNo":"#016","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Children","prompt":"What kinds of children's activities are there available in your city?\nWhat do you need to do to interest a child in such activities?\nHow do you think adults should improve their relations with children?","answer":"Q: What kinds of children's activities are there available in your city?\nA: My city offers sports clubs, music classes, libraries, art workshops and public parks. The main problem is unequal access, because high fees and travel time can prevent some families from <strong class=\"key-phrase\">taking advantage of them</strong>.\n\nQ: What do you need to do to interest a child in such activities?\nA: Adults should connect the activity with the child’s interests, let them try it without pressure and praise effort rather than immediate success. Children are more engaged when they feel <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a degree of choice</strong>.\n\nQ: How do you think adults should improve their relations with children?\nA: Adults should listen seriously, keep promises and explain rules instead of relying only on authority. A relationship improves when children feel respected but still have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">clear and consistent boundaries</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Children","phrases":[{"en":"taking advantage of them","vi":"tận dụng những hoạt động đó"},{"en":"a degree of choice","vi":"một mức độ tự chủ lựa chọn"},{"en":"clear and consistent boundaries","vi":"ranh giới rõ ràng và nhất quán"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Children","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-017","_displayNo":"#017","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Cities","prompt":"How is life different in cities compared to rural areas?\nHow do you think life in big cities could be made easier?\nWhat do you think cities will be like in 50 years time?","answer":"Q: How is life different in cities compared to rural areas?\nA: Firstly, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the cost of living</strong> in cities is much higher. Housing is much more expensive in cities compared to rural areas; everything costs more. I think life in cities is more difficult. There are more people, so there's more competition for jobs. Life is a lot slower in rural areas, everyone knows each other and there's a sense of community. I don't think rural areas experience the social problems that you find in cities, like crime and homelessness.\n\nQ: How do you think life in big cities could be made easier?\nA: In my opinion cities need to be well-planned. Good public transport can definitely <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make life easier</strong> because there are so many people and it can be really stressful just to move around. Public areas like parks are also important because people need space to relax, and I think cities should be made into healthier places to live and work.\n\nQ: What do you think cities will be like in 50 years time?\nA: I imagine cities will be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">less polluted</strong> because we'll have electric cars and better public transport. More people might work from home so maybe cities won't be so busy. But I think there will probably still be problems because more and more people are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">migrating to cities</strong>. So I'm not so optimistic about issues like crime, homelessness and unemployment.","author":"Simon","topic":"Cities","phrases":[{"en":"the cost of living","vi":"chi phí sinh hoạt"},{"en":"make life easier","vi":"làm cuộc sống dễ dàng hơn"},{"en":"less polluted","vi":"ít ô nhiễm hơn"},{"en":"migrating to cities","vi":"di cư đến các thành phố"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Cities","id":"speaking-part-3-018","_displayNo":"#018","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Cities","prompt":"What makes a city a good place to live?\nHow can crowded cities improve residents' living standards?","answer":"Q: What makes a city a good place to live?\nA: A good city needs affordable housing, safe streets, reliable transport, green space and access to work and healthcare. The best cities make daily life convenient without sacrificing <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sense of community</strong>.\n\nQ: How can crowded cities improve residents' living standards?\nA: They can invest in mass transit, mixed-use neighbourhoods, public housing and local parks. The aim should be to shorten daily journeys and improve services in every district, rather than concentrating opportunity in <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a small central area</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Cities","phrases":[{"en":"a sense of community","vi":"cảm giác cộng đồng"},{"en":"a small central area","vi":"một khu trung tâm nhỏ"}],"source":"Topic reference: IELTS Advantage (2026); questions adapted; answers rewritten and quality-audited by ChatGPT","subtype":"","summary":"Cities","id":"speaking-part-3-019","_displayNo":"#019","qaBands":["8.0","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Cities","prompt":"Do you think large-scale migration from the countryside to cities is positive or negative?\nDo you think that the possibility of working from home via the internet will lead to many people going back to the countryside?\nIn what ways do the new megacities of Asia, Africa, and South America differ from older ones such as London or New York?","answer":"Q: Do you think large-scale migration from the countryside to cities is positive or negative?\nA: It is mixed. Migration can give people better jobs and education, but rapid growth can overwhelm housing, transport and public services. The outcome depends on whether urban planning <strong class=\"key-phrase\">keeps pace with population growth</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think that the possibility of working from home via the internet will lead to many people going back to the countryside?\nA: It may encourage some people to move, especially those seeking cheaper housing and a quieter environment. However, schools, healthcare, social life and internet quality still matter, so remote work alone will not cause <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a mass return to rural areas</strong>.\n\nQ: In what ways do the new megacities of Asia, Africa, and South America differ from older ones such as London or New York?\nA: Many newer megacities have grown much faster than their infrastructure and contain large informal settlements. Older global cities also have inequality, but they usually possess more mature transport systems and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">long-established institutions</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Cities","phrases":[{"en":"keeps pace with population growth","vi":"theo kịp tốc độ tăng dân số"},{"en":"a mass return to rural areas","vi":"một làn sóng trở về nông thôn quy mô lớn"},{"en":"long-established institutions","vi":"các thể chế lâu đời"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Cities","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-020","_displayNo":"#020","qaBands":["8.0","8.0","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Collecting","prompt":"Do you think you will ever have the biggest collection in the world?\nHow valuable might your collection become in the future?\nWhy do you think some people collect things?","answer":"Q: Do you think you will ever have the biggest collection in the world?\nA: Probably not, and that would not be my goal. A collection is more meaningful when each item has a story or fills a clear gap, rather than when size becomes <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an end in itself</strong>.\n\nQ: How valuable might your collection become in the future?\nA: Its future value would be uncertain because markets and tastes change. I would regard any financial gain as a bonus and focus on the collection’s <strong class=\"key-phrase\">personal and historical value</strong>.\n\nQ: Why do you think some people collect things?\nA: People collect for nostalgia, curiosity, status or the satisfaction of organising knowledge. The activity can create expertise and community, although it becomes unhealthy if it causes debt or <strong class=\"key-phrase\">takes over a person’s life</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Collecting","phrases":[{"en":"an end in itself","vi":"mục đích tự thân"},{"en":"personal and historical value","vi":"giá trị cá nhân và lịch sử"},{"en":"takes over a person’s life","vi":"chi phối toàn bộ cuộc sống của một người"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Collecting","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-021","_displayNo":"#021","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Communication","prompt":"What are the different ways people communicate?\nDo you prefer to write a letter to a friend or send an email and why?\nHow has technology affected the way people communicate?","answer":"Q: What are the different ways people communicate?\nA: People communicate face to face, by phone, messaging apps, email, video calls and formal written documents. The best method depends on urgency, complexity and whether the message requires <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a personal human touch</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you prefer to write a letter to a friend or send an email and why?\nA: For everyday communication I would choose email because it is fast and searchable. I would write a physical letter only for a very personal occasion, where handwriting can add <strong class=\"key-phrase\">emotional weight</strong>.\n\nQ: How has technology affected the way people communicate?\nA: Technology has made communication immediate and global, but it has also reduced patience and increased misunderstanding. Short messages are efficient, yet difficult conversations still benefit from <strong class=\"key-phrase\">face-to-face interaction</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Communication","phrases":[{"en":"a personal human touch","vi":"sự tương tác mang tính cá nhân"},{"en":"emotional weight","vi":"sức nặng cảm xúc"},{"en":"face-to-face interaction","vi":"sự tương tác trực tiếp"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Communication","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-022","_displayNo":"#022","qaBands":["8.0","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Competition","prompt":"Why do you think some school teachers use competitions as class activities?\nIs it a good thing to give prizes to children who do well at school and why?\nWould you say that schools for young children have become more or less competitive since you were that age and why?","answer":"Q: Why do you think some school teachers use competitions as class activities?\nA: I think teachers use competitions to motivate the children in their classes. I'm sure that teachers try all kinds of activities to engage their pupils, and competitions might be one of the best ways to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">keep children interested</strong> or get them excited. Children love winning things.\n\nQ: Is it a good thing to give prizes to children who do well at school and why?\nA: It might be a good idea to encourage children to do well in games or sports, but I don't think we should give children prizes for their <strong class=\"key-phrase\">academic work</strong>. Children need to learn that the reason for studying is to learn useful things that will help them in their lives. I don't like the idea of children thinking that they will only work hard if there is a prize.\n\nQ: Would you say that schools for young children have become more or less competitive since you were that age and why?\nA: Schools for young children seem more competitive than they were in the past. Testing begins earlier, parents compare results more closely, and some children attend extra classes before they have developed a healthy attitude to learning. That pressure may improve short-term performance, but it can also reduce curiosity.","author":"Simon","topic":"Competition","phrases":[{"en":"keep children interested","vi":"duy trì sự hứng thú của trẻ"},{"en":"academic work","vi":"việc học tập học thuật"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Competition","id":"speaking-part-3-023","_displayNo":"#023","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Competition","prompt":"Do you enjoy entering competitions?\nHave you entered any other competitions?","answer":"Q: Do you enjoy entering competitions?\nA: I enjoy competitions when they test a real skill and provide useful feedback. I am less interested in events dominated by luck, because the best outcome should be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">personal improvement</strong>, not only a ranking.\n\nQ: Have you entered any other competitions?\nA: Yes, mainly academic and language competitions when I was younger. Preparing for them taught me to organise my time, handle pressure and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">learn from mistakes</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Competition","phrases":[{"en":"personal improvement","vi":"sự tiến bộ cá nhân"},{"en":"learn from mistakes","vi":"học hỏi từ sai lầm"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Competition","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-024","_displayNo":"#024","qaBands":["8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Consumerism & Possessions","prompt":"Why do some people prefer domestically produced goods to imported products?","answer":"Q: Why do some people prefer domestically produced goods to imported products?\nA: Some people buy domestic products because they want to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">support local employment</strong> and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">keep money within the national economy</strong>. Others trust familiar standards or believe local food and goods are easier to trace. Price and quality still matter, but national loyalty can influence the final choice.","author":"Simon","topic":"Consumerism & Possessions","phrases":[{"en":"support local employment","vi":"hỗ trợ việc làm tại địa phương"},{"en":"keep money within the national economy","vi":"giữ dòng tiền trong nền kinh tế quốc gia"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Consumerism & Possessions","id":"speaking-part-3-025","_displayNo":"#025","qaBands":["9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Consumerism & Possessions","prompt":"In your country, what possessions show a higher status or position in society?\nDo you think we place too much importance on possessions?\nDo you think things were different 50 years ago?","answer":"Q: In your country, what possessions show a higher status or position in society?\nA: In my country, expensive property, premium cars, luxury watches and designer clothing often signal status. These objects are visible, so people use them to communicate wealth or professional success, even though they reveal very little about character.\n\nQ: Do you think we place too much importance on possessions?\nA: Probably. Advertising and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">social comparison</strong> encourage people to treat new possessions as evidence of success. This is particularly difficult for teenagers, who may feel <strong class=\"key-phrase\">strong peer pressure</strong> to own the same devices or brands as their friends.\n\nQ: Do you think things were different 50 years ago?\nA: Fifty years ago, people generally owned fewer products and repaired them for longer. Advertising was <strong class=\"key-phrase\">less pervasive</strong>, credit was harder to obtain, and status was not displayed through such a rapid cycle of upgrades. Materialism existed, but <strong class=\"key-phrase\">consumer culture</strong> was less intense.","author":"Simon","topic":"Consumerism & Possessions","phrases":[{"en":"social comparison","vi":"sự so sánh xã hội"},{"en":"strong peer pressure","vi":"áp lực đồng trang lứa mạnh mẽ"},{"en":"less pervasive","vi":"ít hiện diện và chi phối rộng khắp hơn"},{"en":"consumer culture","vi":"văn hóa tiêu dùng"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Consumerism & Possessions","id":"speaking-part-3-026","_displayNo":"#026","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Consumerism & Possessions","prompt":"What are the valuable personal possessions in your country?\nHow has your attitude towards keeping personal possessions changed?\nWhy do you think people keep valuable things?","answer":"Q: What are the valuable personal possessions in your country?\nA: Homes, land, jewellery, vehicles and increasingly electronic devices are seen as valuable. Their importance reflects both practical use and the desire for financial security.\n\nQ: How has your attitude towards keeping personal possessions changed?\nA: I have become more selective. I used to keep things because they might be useful one day, but now I retain items that serve a purpose or carry <strong class=\"key-phrase\">genuine personal meaning</strong>.\n\nQ: Why do you think people keep valuable things?\nA: They may keep them as investments, family heirlooms or symbols of achievement. Valuable objects can also provide reassurance because they feel like <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a form of security</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Consumerism & Possessions","phrases":[{"en":"genuine personal meaning","vi":"ý nghĩa cá nhân thực sự"},{"en":"a form of security","vi":"một hình thức bảo đảm"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Consumerism & Possessions","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-027","_displayNo":"#027","qaBands":["8.0","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Consumerism & Possessions","prompt":"What kinds of possessions show status in your country?\nDo you think it was different for your grandparents?\nModern society is often called 'materialistic'. Why do you think this is?","answer":"Q: What kinds of possessions show status in your country?\nA: Expensive cars, property, branded clothing and premium electronics often signal status. The signal works only because society collectively attaches prestige to them, even when their practical value is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">not proportionate to the price</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think it was different for your grandparents?\nA: Yes. Their generation tended to value durable household goods, land and savings, partly because products were scarcer. Status today is more visible and changes faster because social media constantly displays <strong class=\"key-phrase\">new symbols of success</strong>.\n\nQ: Modern society is often called 'materialistic'. Why do you think this is?\nA: Modern economies encourage frequent consumption, while advertising links products with identity and happiness. People also compare themselves with a much wider group online, which can create <strong class=\"key-phrase\">constant pressure to upgrade</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Consumerism & Possessions","phrases":[{"en":"not proportionate to the price","vi":"không tương xứng với giá tiền"},{"en":"new symbols of success","vi":"những biểu tượng thành công mới"},{"en":"constant pressure to upgrade","vi":"áp lực liên tục phải nâng cấp"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Consumerism & Possessions","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-028","_displayNo":"#028","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Countryside","prompt":"What advantages does living in the countryside have, compared to living in a city?\nHave areas of countryside in your country changed since you were a child?\nDo you think that visits to the countryside should be something that schools offer to their children?","answer":"Q: What advantages does living in the countryside have, compared to living in a city?\nA: I think there are some clear advantages to living in the countryside. First, with the clean air and lack of traffic or industry, countryside areas are much healthier places than the average city. Another benefit would be the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">sense of community</strong> that comes with living in a small village where everyone knows each other. Finally, it seems to me that the <strong class=\"key-phrase\">pace of life</strong> in the countryside is slower, and the people are more laid back and friendly, compared to the hustle and bustle and the stress of city life.\n\nQ: Have areas of countryside in your country changed since you were a child?\nA: The countryside near my home has changed only gradually because large areas are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">protected from development</strong>. Some villages have gained better roads and tourism facilities, but the main hills, paths and woodland remain recognisable.\n\nQ: Do you think that visits to the countryside should be something that schools offer to their children?\nA: Yes, I think it's a great idea for schools to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take children on trips</strong> to the countryside, especially if those children live in a large town or city. A visit to the countryside can be both relaxing and educational; children can go for walks in the fresh air, and at the same time see animals and plants that they may never have seen before. If schools don't offer this opportunity, some children will never see life outside the city.","author":"Simon","topic":"Countryside","phrases":[{"en":"sense of community","vi":"văn hóa cộng đồng"},{"en":"pace of life","vi":"nhịp sống"},{"en":"protected from development","vi":"được bảo vệ khỏi hoạt động xây dựng và phát triển"},{"en":"take children on trips","vi":"đưa trẻ đi tham quan"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Countryside","id":"speaking-part-3-029","_displayNo":"#029","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Customer Service","prompt":"How important is customer service for you?\nWhat can companies do to improve their customer service?\nWhy do you think employees sometimes fail to provide good customer service?","answer":"Q: How important is customer service for you?\nA: Customer service is really important for me because I like to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">feel welcome and valued</strong> as a customer. If companies want us to use their products or services, I believe they should treat us well and therefore encourage us to return. For example, I have a favourite cafe where I like to go, and the friendly staff are the main reason that I've become a loyal customer.\n\nQ: What can companies do to improve their customer service?\nA: I think managers need to train their employees to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">deliver great customer service</strong>. There are lots of things that staff members can do, such as ensuring that customers are greeted in the right way, their problems are handled quickly, and they are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">asked for feedback</strong>. For example, the staff in my favourite cafe greet customers as soon as they come through the door, and they always check that we are happy before we leave.\n\nQ: Why do you think employees sometimes fail to provide good customer service?\nA: When employees' treatment of customers isn't good, I think it's usually because they are unhappy doing their jobs. This might be because they are treated badly by their managers, or because they haven't been encouraged to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take pride in</strong> their work. I remember in my first ever job, for example, I didn't like the work that I was given, and so I probably wasn't as thoughtful or attentive as I should have been when I had to speak to customers.","author":"Simon","topic":"Customer Service","phrases":[{"en":"feel welcome and valued","vi":"cảm thấy được chào đón và đánh giá cao"},{"en":"deliver great customer service","vi":"cung cấp dịch vụ khách hàng xuất sắc"},{"en":"asked for feedback","vi":"được xin ý kiến phản hồi"},{"en":"take pride in","vi":"tự hào về"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Customer Service","id":"speaking-part-3-030","_displayNo":"#030","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Dance","prompt":"What dances are popular in your country?\nWhat is the general attitude towards dancing in your country?\nDo young people dance any differently from 10 years ago?","answer":"Q: What dances are popular in your country?\nA: Contemporary social dance, K-pop routines and traditional festival dances are all visible. Their popularity varies by age, but online videos have made new styles <strong class=\"key-phrase\">spread extremely quickly</strong>.\n\nQ: What is the general attitude towards dancing in your country?\nA: Most people see dancing as entertainment or exercise, although some remain shy about doing it publicly. Attitudes are becoming more relaxed as dance classes and performances become <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more socially accepted</strong>.\n\nQ: Do young people dance any differently from 10 years ago?\nA: Yes. Young people learn routines from global online platforms and combine styles more freely than before. The result is more experimental, though sometimes less connected to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">local traditions</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Dance","phrases":[{"en":"spread extremely quickly","vi":"lan truyền cực kỳ nhanh"},{"en":"more socially accepted","vi":"được xã hội chấp nhận hơn"},{"en":"local traditions","vi":"truyền thống địa phương"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Dance","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-031","_displayNo":"#031","qaBands":["8.0","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Decisions","prompt":"What are the typical choices people make at different stages of their lives?\nShould important choices be made by parents rather than by young adults?\nWhy do some people like to discuss choices with other people?","answer":"Q: What are the typical choices people make at different stages of their lives?\nA: Children make choices about friends and study habits; young adults choose education, work and relationships; later decisions often concern housing, family and retirement. The stakes change, but every stage requires people to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">weigh short-term and long-term consequences</strong>.\n\nQ: Should important choices be made by parents rather than by young adults?\nA: Parents should advise, but capable young adults need to make the final decision. Taking ownership allows them to learn from outcomes and develop <strong class=\"key-phrase\">independent judgement</strong>.\n\nQ: Why do some people like to discuss choices with other people?\nA: Discussion exposes assumptions and reveals options that one person may have missed. It is particularly useful for high-stakes choices, provided the adviser does not try to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take control of the decision</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Decisions","phrases":[{"en":"weigh short-term and long-term consequences","vi":"cân nhắc hệ quả ngắn hạn và dài hạn"},{"en":"independent judgement","vi":"khả năng phán đoán độc lập"},{"en":"take control of the decision","vi":"chi phối quyết định"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Decisions","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-032","_displayNo":"#032","qaBands":["8.0","8.0","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Decisions","prompt":"Why is decision-making important in our lives?\nHow can we make good decisions?\nDo you think parents should allow their children to make their own decisions?","answer":"Q: Why is decision-making important in our lives?\nA: Decision-making shapes education, work, relationships and health, so it is a core life skill. Good decisions do not guarantee success, but they improve the odds and reduce <strong class=\"key-phrase\">avoidable regret</strong>.\n\nQ: How can we make good decisions?\nA: We should define the goal, gather <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reliable information</strong>, compare options and consider what could go wrong. For major choices, it also helps to sleep on the decision and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">seek an independent perspective</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think parents should allow their children to make their own decisions?\nA: Yes, gradually. Children need age-appropriate choices so they can practise judgement while the consequences are still manageable. Parents should provide boundaries but avoid <strong class=\"key-phrase\">solving every problem for them</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Decisions","phrases":[{"en":"avoidable regret","vi":"sự hối tiếc có thể tránh được"},{"en":"reliable information","vi":"thông tin đáng tin cậy"},{"en":"seek an independent perspective","vi":"tìm kiếm một góc nhìn độc lập"},{"en":"solving every problem for them","vi":"giải quyết mọi vấn đề thay cho con"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Decisions","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-033","_displayNo":"#033","qaBands":["8.0","8.0","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Dreams","prompt":"What can dreams tell us about ourselves?\nWhy are dreams considered important in many cultures?\nDo you think it is helpful to interpret someone's dreams for them?","answer":"Q: What can dreams tell us about ourselves?\nA: Dreams may reflect recent concerns, memories and emotions, but they are not a transparent window into personality. They can prompt reflection, although any interpretation should remain <strong class=\"key-phrase\">tentative rather than certain</strong>.\n\nQ: Why are dreams considered important in many cultures?\nA: Dreams feel vivid and mysterious, so cultures have often treated them as messages, warnings or spiritual experiences. They also offer stories through which communities can express <strong class=\"key-phrase\">shared fears and hopes</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think it is helpful to interpret someone's dreams for them?\nA: It can be helpful if interpretation encourages someone to discuss emotions, but it should not be presented as scientific fact. A therapist may explore a dream carefully, whereas a fixed symbolic reading can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">create false certainty</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Dreams","phrases":[{"en":"tentative rather than certain","vi":"mang tính thăm dò chứ không tuyệt đối"},{"en":"shared fears and hopes","vi":"những nỗi sợ và hy vọng chung"},{"en":"create false certainty","vi":"tạo ra sự chắc chắn sai lầm"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Dreams","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-034","_displayNo":"#034","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Education","prompt":"What do you think makes a good lesson?\nDo you think it is better to have a teacher or to teach yourself?\nDo you think the traditional classroom will disappear in the future?","answer":"Q: What do you think makes a good lesson?\nA: I think a good lesson is one that is interesting and engaging. By 'engaging' I mean that the students should feel involved in the lesson; they should feel that they are learning something new that is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">relevant to them</strong>. In my opinion, a lot depends on how the teacher <strong class=\"key-phrase\">delivers the content</strong> of the lesson in a way that students like. My favourite teacher at university used to involve the students by making us teach some of the lessons ourselves.\n\nQ: Do you think it is better to have a teacher or to teach yourself?\nA: Well, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">there's no substitute for</strong> a good teacher. I think you can teach yourself, but you can learn a lot more quickly <strong class=\"key-phrase\">with the guidance of a teacher</strong>. For example, when learning a language, you really need someone to correct your mistakes; you can get the grammar and vocabulary from books, but books can't tell you where you're going wrong.\n\nQ: Do you think the traditional classroom will disappear in the future?\nA: The traditional classroom will not disappear, but it may become less dominant. Students can learn factual content online and use classroom time for discussion, feedback and practical work. The teacher’s role may shift from delivering information to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">guiding and evaluating learning</strong>.","author":"Simon","topic":"Education","phrases":[{"en":"relevant to them","vi":"có liên quan trực tiếp đến họ"},{"en":"delivers the content","vi":"truyền đạt nội dung"},{"en":"there's no substitute for","vi":"không gì có thể thay thế được"},{"en":"with the guidance of a teacher","vi":"với sự hướng dẫn của giáo viên"},{"en":"guiding and evaluating learning","vi":"hướng dẫn và đánh giá quá trình học tập"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Education","id":"speaking-part-3-035","_displayNo":"#035","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Education","prompt":"Do you think too many subjects are taught at school?\nHave there been any major changes in the education system in your country?\nShould everyone be entitled to go to university?","answer":"Q: Do you think too many subjects are taught at school?\nA: In some systems, yes. Breadth is useful, but overcrowded curricula encourage superficial memorisation. Schools should protect core subjects while allowing enough time for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">deep understanding</strong> and practical application.\n\nQ: Have there been any major changes in the education system in your country?\nA: Education has become more digital, assessment-driven and internationally connected. Students have greater access to information, but teachers now have to help them evaluate sources and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">use technology critically</strong>.\n\nQ: Should everyone be entitled to go to university?\nA: Everyone should have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a fair opportunity</strong>, but university is not the only valuable route. Strong vocational education can offer excellent careers, so policy should create <strong class=\"key-phrase\">multiple respected pathways</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Education","phrases":[{"en":"deep understanding","vi":"sự hiểu biết sâu sắc"},{"en":"use technology critically","vi":"sử dụng công nghệ một cách có tư duy phản biện"},{"en":"a fair opportunity","vi":"một cơ hội công bằng"},{"en":"multiple respected pathways","vi":"nhiều lộ trình được coi trọng"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Education","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-036","_displayNo":"#036","qaBands":["8.5","8.0","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Education","prompt":"How will classrooms change in the future?\nWhat qualities make a good teacher?","answer":"Q: How will classrooms change in the future?\nA: Classrooms will probably combine <strong class=\"key-phrase\">face-to-face</strong> teaching with adaptive digital tools. The technology may personalise practice, but teachers will remain essential for motivation, judgement and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">human interaction</strong>.\n\nQ: What qualities make a good teacher?\nA: A good teacher knows the subject, explains it clearly and notices when students are confused. Just as importantly, they set high expectations while creating a psychologically safe classroom.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Education","phrases":[{"en":"face-to-face","vi":"trực tiếp, mặt đối mặt"},{"en":"human interaction","vi":"sự tương tác giữa con người"}],"source":"Topic reference: IELTS Advantage (2026); questions adapted; answers rewritten and quality-audited by ChatGPT","subtype":"","summary":"Education","id":"speaking-part-3-037","_displayNo":"#037","qaBands":["8.0","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Emotions","prompt":"Do you think it is good to show your emotions when you are angry?\nIn your opinion, do women show their emotions more than men?\nWhy do you think men tend to show their emotions less than women?","answer":"Q: Do you think it is good to show your emotions when you are angry?\nA: It is healthy to express anger clearly, but not to release it without control. Telling someone what caused the problem can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">prevent resentment</strong>, whereas shouting or insulting them usually makes the conflict worse. The goal should be honest communication rather than emotional aggression.\n\nQ: In your opinion, do women show their emotions more than men?\nA: The stereotype is that women express emotion more openly than men, and social expectations may create some difference. However, individual personality, family culture and circumstances matter more than gender, so <strong class=\"key-phrase\">broad generalisations</strong> are unreliable.\n\nQ: Why do you think men tend to show their emotions less than women?\nA: Maybe it's because of the way we are brought up. I think that boys are often taught from an early age not to cry. Also, boys are aware that their friends might see it as <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sign of weakness</strong> if they show their feelings. Perhaps girls are brought up to be more sensitive to their friends' feelings.","author":"Simon","topic":"Emotions","phrases":[{"en":"prevent resentment","vi":"ngăn sự oán giận tích tụ"},{"en":"broad generalisations","vi":"những khái quát hóa quá rộng"},{"en":"a sign of weakness","vi":"một dấu hiệu của sự yếu đuối"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Emotions","id":"speaking-part-3-038","_displayNo":"#038","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Emotions","prompt":"What generally makes people in your country excited?\nAre people in your country generally calm, or do they get excited easily?\nHow do you think people show their excitement?","answer":"Q: What generally makes people in your country excited?\nA: Sporting victories, family celebrations, career opportunities and public events often create excitement. The common element is usually anticipation combined with <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a strong emotional investment</strong>.\n\nQ: Are people in your country generally calm, or do they get excited easily?\nA: It depends on the setting. People may appear restrained in formal situations but become highly expressive at festivals, sports events or family gatherings. Cultural rules often shape <strong class=\"key-phrase\">where emotion is considered acceptable</strong>.\n\nQ: How do you think people show their excitement?\nA: They speak faster, smile, use more gestures and share the news with others. Online, excitement may appear through messages and posts, but <strong class=\"key-phrase\">face-to-face</strong> reactions still reveal it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more spontaneously</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Emotions","phrases":[{"en":"a strong emotional investment","vi":"sự đầu tư cảm xúc mạnh mẽ"},{"en":"where emotion is considered acceptable","vi":"nơi cảm xúc được coi là phù hợp"},{"en":"face-to-face","vi":"trực tiếp, mặt đối mặt"},{"en":"more spontaneously","vi":"một cách tự nhiên hơn"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Emotions","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-039","_displayNo":"#039","qaBands":["8.0","8.0","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Environment & Nature","prompt":"What effects do you think humans have on wild animals?\nWhat measures could we take to protect wildlife?\nIs it the responsibility of schools to teach children about protecting wildlife?","answer":"Q: What effects do you think humans have on wild animals?\nA: Humans affect wild animals by <strong class=\"key-phrase\">destroying habitats</strong>, polluting water and land, overfishing and contributing to climate change. Roads and cities also divide ecosystems into smaller areas, making it harder for species to feed, migrate and reproduce.\n\nQ: What measures could we take to protect wildlife?\nA: Governments should protect habitats, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">enforce anti-poaching laws</strong> and reduce pollution. National parks are useful when they are properly funded and local communities receive economic benefits, because conservation is stronger when residents have a reason to support it.\n\nQ: Is it the responsibility of schools to teach children about protecting wildlife?\nA: Yes, schools can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">play a big part in</strong> educating children about this issue. Children should learn how to look after the natural environment. I think schools already teach children about <strong class=\"key-phrase\">endangered species</strong> and the destruction of rain forests, so hopefully future generations will do a better job of protecting wildlife.","author":"Simon","topic":"Environment & Nature","phrases":[{"en":"destroying habitats","vi":"phá hủy môi trường sống"},{"en":"enforce anti-poaching laws","vi":"thực thi luật chống săn trộm"},{"en":"play a big part in","vi":"đóng vai trò lớn trong"},{"en":"endangered species","vi":"loài có nguy cơ tuyệt chủng"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Environment & Nature","id":"speaking-part-3-040","_displayNo":"#040","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Environment & Nature","prompt":"How does water transport compare with other forms of transport?\nWhat are the advantages and disadvantages of water transport?\nHow important is it for a town or city to be located near a river or the sea?","answer":"Q: How does water transport compare with other forms of transport?\nA: Water transport is slower than air travel but highly efficient for heavy goods. It is less flexible than road transport because routes depend on ports and waterways, yet it can move enormous volumes with <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a lower cost per tonne</strong>.\n\nQ: What are the advantages and disadvantages of water transport?\nA: Its advantages are capacity, fuel efficiency and relatively low cost. The disadvantages are slow speed, limited routes and environmental risks from spills or port development, so it works best as part of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an integrated transport system</strong>.\n\nQ: How important is it for a town or city to be located near a river or the sea?\nA: Historically it was crucial for trade, food and water supply. It remains valuable today for tourism and transport, although cities must manage flooding and avoid <strong class=\"key-phrase\">polluting the resource they depend on</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Environment & Nature","phrases":[{"en":"a lower cost per tonne","vi":"chi phí thấp hơn trên mỗi tấn hàng"},{"en":"an integrated transport system","vi":"một hệ thống giao thông tích hợp"},{"en":"polluting the resource they depend on","vi":"làm ô nhiễm nguồn tài nguyên mà họ phụ thuộc"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Environment & Nature","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-041","_displayNo":"#041","qaBands":["8.5","8.0","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Environment & Nature","prompt":"How aware do you think people are nowadays about environmental issues?","answer":"Q: How aware do you think people are nowadays about environmental issues?\nA: Awareness is much higher than before because climate change and pollution receive constant coverage. However, awareness does not always lead to action when sustainable choices are expensive or <strong class=\"key-phrase\">inconvenient in daily life</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Environment & Nature","phrases":[{"en":"inconvenient in daily life","vi":"bất tiện trong cuộc sống hằng ngày"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Environment & Nature","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-042","_displayNo":"#042","qaBands":["8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Environment & Nature","prompt":"What are the effects of human activities on the environment?\nWhat can be done to protect the environment?\nWhat would be the impact of global warming on the environment?","answer":"Q: What are the effects of human activities on the environment?\nA: Deforestation, fossil-fuel use, intensive farming and waste alter habitats and the climate. The effects include biodiversity loss, poorer air and water quality, and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">greater exposure to extreme weather</strong>.\n\nQ: What can be done to protect the environment?\nA: Governments need enforceable standards, cleaner infrastructure and incentives for low-carbon technology. Individuals also matter, but systemic change is essential because consumers cannot solve pollution when cleaner options are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">unavailable or unaffordable</strong>.\n\nQ: What would be the impact of global warming on the environment?\nA: It will intensify heatwaves, sea-level rise, drought and ecosystem disruption. The greatest burden may fall on poorer communities that contributed least to the problem and have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the fewest resources to adapt</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Environment & Nature","phrases":[{"en":"greater exposure to extreme weather","vi":"mức độ phơi nhiễm lớn hơn trước thời tiết cực đoan"},{"en":"unavailable or unaffordable","vi":"không có sẵn hoặc không đủ khả năng chi trả"},{"en":"the fewest resources to adapt","vi":"ít nguồn lực thích ứng nhất"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Environment & Nature","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-043","_displayNo":"#043","qaBands":["8.0","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Experiences","prompt":"In what ways is life becoming safer, and in what ways is it becoming more dangerous?\nShould people always avoid dangers, or is it a good idea to take a risk?\nWhat risk should people try to avoid?","answer":"Q: In what ways is life becoming safer, and in what ways is it becoming more dangerous?\nA: Life is safer because of medicine, building standards and better emergency services. At the same time, cybercrime, environmental instability and highly connected systems create new risks that can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">spread across borders quickly</strong>.\n\nQ: Should people always avoid dangers, or is it a good idea to take a risk?\nA: No. Reasonable risk is necessary for learning, enterprise and personal growth. The distinction is between informed risk, where consequences are understood, and reckless behaviour that offers little benefit in return for <strong class=\"key-phrase\">serious avoidable harm</strong>.\n\nQ: What risk should people try to avoid?\nA: People should avoid risks that can cause irreversible harm but offer little meaningful benefit, such as dangerous driving, unsecured debt or ignoring serious health symptoms. A useful test is whether the possible reward justifies <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the worst realistic consequence</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Experiences","phrases":[{"en":"spread across borders quickly","vi":"lan rộng qua biên giới rất nhanh"},{"en":"serious avoidable harm","vi":"tác hại nghiêm trọng có thể tránh được"},{"en":"the worst realistic consequence","vi":"hậu quả thực tế tồi tệ nhất"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Experiences","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-044","_displayNo":"#044","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Family","prompt":"In what ways can a family be similar to each other?\nIn terms of personality, are people more influenced by their family or by their friends?\nDo you think daughters are always more similar to their mothers than to male relatives?","answer":"Q: In what ways can a family be similar to each other?\nA: Family members may share physical traits, habits, humour and ways of communicating. Similarity comes from both genetics and a shared environment, but individual experiences still produce <strong class=\"key-phrase\">distinct personalities</strong>.\n\nQ: In terms of personality, are people more influenced by their family or by their friends?\nA: Family usually shapes early values and habits, while friends become more influential during adolescence and adulthood. The balance changes over time, and strong personalities often emerge from <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the interaction of both influences</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think daughters are always more similar to their mothers than to male relatives?\nA: No. Gender does not determine which relative someone resembles. A daughter may share a father’s temperament or a grandparent’s interests, so resemblance is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">individual rather than predictable</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Family","phrases":[{"en":"distinct personalities","vi":"những tính cách khác biệt"},{"en":"the interaction of both influences","vi":"sự tương tác của cả hai nguồn ảnh hưởng"},{"en":"individual rather than predictable","vi":"mang tính cá nhân chứ không thể dự đoán"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Family","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-045","_displayNo":"#045","qaBands":["8.0","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Famous People","prompt":"Are there any differences between the types of people who were seen as celebrities in the past and those who are celebrities nowadays?","answer":"Q: Are there any differences between the types of people who were seen as celebrities in the past and those who are celebrities nowadays?\nA: Yes. In the past, national celebrities were usually political leaders, royalty, military figures or exceptional performers. Mass media then made actors and musicians <strong class=\"key-phrase\">internationally famous</strong>, while social media now <strong class=\"key-phrase\">allows ordinary people to become well known</strong> through personality, visibility or controversy <strong class=\"key-phrase\">rather than a recognised craft</strong>.","author":"Simon","topic":"Famous People","phrases":[{"en":"internationally famous","vi":"nổi tiếng trên phạm vi quốc tế"},{"en":"allows ordinary people to become well known","vi":"cho phép người bình thường trở nên nổi tiếng"},{"en":"rather than a recognised craft","vi":"thay vì nhờ một tài năng chuyên môn được công nhận"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Famous People","id":"speaking-part-3-046","_displayNo":"#046","qaBands":["9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Famous People","prompt":"Is it important for young children to have a role model?\nWhat are the advantages and disadvantages of being a child?\nHow do you imagine traditional relationships changing in the future?","answer":"Q: Is it important for young children to have a role model?\nA: Yes, because role models make values and achievements concrete. Children should have several role models rather than idealising one celebrity, since every public figure has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">limitations and contradictions</strong>.\n\nQ: What are the advantages and disadvantages of being a child?\nA: Children have fewer financial responsibilities and more time to learn, but they also have limited control over their lives. Their well-being depends heavily on adults, which makes a stable home and school environment <strong class=\"key-phrase\">especially important</strong>.\n\nQ: How do you imagine traditional relationships changing in the future?\nA: Relationships will probably become more equal and less defined by fixed gender or age roles. Technology will help people stay connected across distance, but families may need to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">protect time for direct interaction</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Famous People","phrases":[{"en":"limitations and contradictions","vi":"những hạn chế và mâu thuẫn"},{"en":"especially important","vi":"đặc biệt quan trọng"},{"en":"protect time for direct interaction","vi":"bảo vệ thời gian cho sự tương tác trực tiếp"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Famous People","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-047","_displayNo":"#047","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Film & Television","prompt":"Do you think films have changed since you were a child?\nAs the technology for home viewing improves, do you think people will stop going to the cinema in future?","answer":"Q: Do you think films have changed since you were a child?\nA: No, I don't think films have changed much since I was a child. When I was younger I enjoyed watching action films, and the Hollywood formula for this type of film seems to be the same today. For example, I liked the original ’Superman' films, and superheroes are still <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a popular subject</strong> for film- makers.\n\nQ: As the technology for home viewing improves, do you think people will stop going to the cinema in future?\nA: No, I don't think that people will stop going to the cinema. People can already buy fantastic home viewing equipment, but it still feels more special to share the experience of watching a new film with a theatre full of people. I don't think that technology will be able to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">replicate that cinema atmosphere</strong>.","author":"Simon","topic":"Film & Television","phrases":[{"en":"a popular subject","vi":"một chủ đề phổ biến"},{"en":"replicate that cinema atmosphere","vi":"tái tạo bầu không khí đặc trưng của rạp chiếu phim"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Film & Television","id":"speaking-part-3-048","_displayNo":"#048","qaBands":["9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Film & Television","prompt":"Do you think most people watch TV for education or for entertainment?\nShould TV play a role in educating children; how?\nHow do you think TV viewing habits change as people get older?","answer":"Q: Do you think most people watch TV for education or for entertainment?\nA: I think people watch TV primarily for entertainment. There are far more entertainment programmes than educational ones, and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">in my experience</strong> most people treat television as a form of relaxation in the evening. If I think about the most popular TV programmes in the UK, such as talent shows like 'X Factor' or soap operas like 'Eastenders', the focus is definitely on entertainment rather than education.\n\nQ: Should TV play a role in educating children; how?\nA: Yes, it definitely should <strong class=\"key-phrase\">play a role in</strong> my opinion. Good children's TV programmes should tell stories that contain some kind of lesson about how to behave or what is morally right and wrong. Many of the traditional fairy tales, such as 'Cinderella', have been made into TV programmes, and there is always a positive message in those stories.\n\nQ: How do you think TV viewing habits change as people get older?\nA: TV viewing habits obviously change a lot as we get older. While toddlers might watch programmes about talking animals, teenagers prefer action and adventure or sports, and as adults we start taking an interest in news and politics. My own preferences, for example, have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">changed over the years</strong> - I would never have watched news programmes when I was younger. I think it would be very strange if our viewing habits didn't mature!","author":"Simon","topic":"Film & Television","phrases":[{"en":"in my experience","vi":"theo kinh nghiệm của tôi"},{"en":"play a role in","vi":"đóng vai trò trong"},{"en":"changed over the years","vi":"đã thay đổi qua nhiều năm"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Film & Television","id":"speaking-part-3-049","_displayNo":"#049","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Film & Television","prompt":"Do you think the cinema has increased or decreased in popularity in recent years?\nIn your opinion, will this trend continue into the future?\nWhat are the advantages and disadvantages of making films of real-life events?","answer":"Q: Do you think the cinema has increased or decreased in popularity in recent years?\nA: Cinema attendance faces pressure from streaming, but major films and premium venues still attract audiences. The cinema is becoming more of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an occasional social experience</strong> than the default way to watch films.\n\nQ: In your opinion, will this trend continue into the future?\nA: Yes, streaming will remain dominant for everyday viewing. Cinemas will survive by offering better sound, large-scale spectacle and events that people cannot easily <strong class=\"key-phrase\">recreate at home</strong>.\n\nQ: What are the advantages and disadvantages of making films of real-life events?\nA: Such films can make history accessible and emotionally engaging, but they may simplify facts or exploit real suffering. Filmmakers should distinguish clearly between documented evidence and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">dramatic reconstruction</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Film & Television","phrases":[{"en":"an occasional social experience","vi":"một trải nghiệm xã hội thỉnh thoảng"},{"en":"recreate at home","vi":"tái tạo tại nhà"},{"en":"dramatic reconstruction","vi":"sự tái dựng kịch tính"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Film & Television","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-050","_displayNo":"#050","qaBands":["8.0","8.0","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Food","prompt":"If you invite a friend, what meal are you likely to offer them?\nWhat kinds of food are popular in your country?\nWhat are people’s eating habits like in your country?","answer":"Q: If you invite a friend, what meal are you likely to offer them?\nA: I would serve a simple Vietnamese meal with grilled meat or tofu, rice, vegetables and soup. It is easy to share, can suit different tastes and allows the host to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">spend time with the guest</strong> instead of staying in the kitchen.\n\nQ: What kinds of food are popular in your country?\nA: Rice and noodle dishes, street food and regional specialities are extremely popular. Convenience food is growing, but traditional dishes remain important because they combine affordability with <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a strong cultural identity</strong>.\n\nQ: What are people’s eating habits like in your country?\nA: People eat more processed food and order delivery more often than before, especially in cities. At the same time, health-conscious consumers are paying more attention to ingredients, creating <strong class=\"key-phrase\">two opposing trends</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Food","phrases":[{"en":"spend time with the guest","vi":"dành thời gian với khách"},{"en":"a strong cultural identity","vi":"bản sắc văn hóa mạnh mẽ"},{"en":"two opposing trends","vi":"hai xu hướng đối lập"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Food","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-051","_displayNo":"#051","qaBands":["8.0","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Friendship","prompt":"What do you think are the most important qualities for friends to have?\nHow important do you think it is for a person to spend some time alone?","answer":"Q: What do you think are the most important qualities for friends to have?\nA: The most important qualities are honesty, reliability and mutual respect. Shared interests make a friendship enjoyable, but trust is what makes it durable. A close friend should be able to listen, tell the truth tactfully and remain dependable when circumstances become difficult.\n\nQ: How important do you think it is for a person to spend some time alone?\nA: Spending some time alone is essential because it allows people to process experiences and recover from <strong class=\"key-phrase\">constant social demands</strong>. Even a short walk or quiet coffee can create space for reflection. Solitude becomes unhealthy only when it turns into <strong class=\"key-phrase\">persistent isolation</strong>.","author":"Simon","topic":"Friendship","phrases":[{"en":"constant social demands","vi":"những đòi hỏi xã hội liên tục"},{"en":"persistent isolation","vi":"tình trạng cô lập kéo dài"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Friendship","id":"speaking-part-3-052","_displayNo":"#052","qaBands":["9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Friendship","prompt":"How do people usually meet new friends where you live?\nIs it easier for adults or children to make new friends and why?\nHow are friendships different from relationships at work or college?","answer":"Q: How do people usually meet new friends where you live?\nA: People meet through school, work, hobbies, mutual friends and online communities. Shared activity is particularly effective because it gives strangers something natural to discuss and helps them build rapport.\n\nQ: Is it easier for adults or children to make new friends and why?\nA: Children usually find it easier because they spend repeated, unstructured time together and are less cautious. Adults have busier schedules and established social circles, so friendship often requires <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more deliberate effort</strong>.\n\nQ: How are friendships different from relationships at work or college?\nA: Friendships are voluntary and usually more personal, while workplace relationships include roles, evaluation and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">professional boundaries</strong>. Colleagues can become close friends, but trust develops differently when there is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a formal power structure</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Friendship","phrases":[{"en":"more deliberate effort","vi":"nhiều nỗ lực có chủ đích hơn"},{"en":"professional boundaries","vi":"ranh giới nghề nghiệp"},{"en":"a formal power structure","vi":"một cấu trúc quyền lực chính thức"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Friendship","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-053","_displayNo":"#053","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Gifts","prompt":"What kinds of presents do children ask for today?\nWhat effect has advertising had on children's preferences?\nIs there a case for banning advertising directed at children?","answer":"Q: What kinds of presents do children ask for today?\nA: Many ask for electronic devices, branded toys, games and fashionable items they see online. Requests are increasingly shaped by influencers and peer comparison rather than only by <strong class=\"key-phrase\">direct personal interest</strong>.\n\nQ: What effect has advertising had on children's preferences?\nA: Advertising has made children more aware of brands and product launches. Because younger children do not fully understand persuasive intent, repeated exposure can turn a temporary desire into <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a perceived necessity</strong>.\n\nQ: Is there a case for banning advertising directed at children?\nA: There is a strong case for restricting it, especially for unhealthy food, gambling-like games and products that exploit insecurity. A complete ban may be difficult, but regulation should <strong class=\"key-phrase\">protect vulnerable audiences</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Gifts","phrases":[{"en":"direct personal interest","vi":"sở thích cá nhân trực tiếp"},{"en":"a perceived necessity","vi":"một nhu cầu được cảm nhận như thiết yếu"},{"en":"protect vulnerable audiences","vi":"bảo vệ nhóm khán giả dễ bị tổn thương"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Gifts","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-054","_displayNo":"#054","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"History","prompt":"What do you think we can learn by studying events of the past?\nWhat important events do you think might take place in the future?","answer":"Q: What do you think we can learn by studying events of the past?\nA: I think we can learn a lot by studying history. Just as individual people learn from their mistakes, societies can learn from the mistakes made by previous governments or leaders. For example, from what I've read in the newspapers, many economists are looking back to the time of the Great Depression, around 80 years ago, in order to understand the financial crisis that is currently affecting many countries around the world. Even if we don't always learn from mistakes, I think it's fascinating to study history because it gives us an insight into who we are and where we come from.\n\nQ: What important events do you think might take place in the future?\nA: It's really difficult to predict what will happen in the future; most of the big, historic events of the past would have been <strong class=\"key-phrase\">impossible to foresee</strong>. For example, I don't think that anyone living 100 years ago could have imagined that people would one day walk on the moon! If I had to guess what might happen in the future, I'd like to think that scientists will <strong class=\"key-phrase\">invent cures for diseases</strong> like cancer, and we'll all live longer.","author":"Simon","topic":"History","phrases":[{"en":"impossible to foresee","vi":"không thể dự liệu trước"},{"en":"invent cures for diseases","vi":"phát minh phương pháp chữa bệnh"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"History","id":"speaking-part-3-055","_displayNo":"#055","qaBands":["9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"History","prompt":"Studying history can help countries to avoid repeating past mistakes. Do you agree or not?\nHow can studying your own country's history help you understand present-day situations?\nHow important do you consider it to study the history of other countries?","answer":"Q: Studying history can help countries to avoid repeating past mistakes. Do you agree or not?\nA: I agree, although knowledge alone is not enough. History reveals patterns in conflict, economic crises and public policy, but leaders must recognise relevant similarities and have the willingness to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">act on the evidence</strong>.\n\nQ: How can studying your own country's history help you understand present-day situations?\nA: It helps explain institutions, regional differences and current debates that otherwise seem arbitrary. However, national history should be taught critically, including uncomfortable episodes, rather than as <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a simple patriotic story</strong>.\n\nQ: How important do you consider it to study the history of other countries?\nA: It is very important because no country developed in isolation. Studying other societies reduces stereotypes and shows how trade, migration and conflict created <strong class=\"key-phrase\">interdependent histories</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"History","phrases":[{"en":"act on the evidence","vi":"hành động dựa trên bằng chứng"},{"en":"a simple patriotic story","vi":"một câu chuyện yêu nước đơn giản hóa"},{"en":"interdependent histories","vi":"những lịch sử phụ thuộc lẫn nhau"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"History","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-056","_displayNo":"#056","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Housing & Architecture","prompt":"How do you think the design of homes will change in the future?","answer":"Q: How do you think the design of homes will change in the future?\nA: The outside of homes may remain fairly traditional, but interiors will become more efficient and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">technology-rich</strong>. Better insulation, renewable energy, flexible rooms and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">automated systems</strong> are likely to become common. The most useful changes will reduce energy use and adapt homes to ageing populations.","author":"Simon","topic":"Housing & Architecture","phrases":[{"en":"technology-rich","vi":"được tích hợp nhiều công nghệ"},{"en":"automated systems","vi":"các hệ thống tự động hóa"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Housing & Architecture","id":"speaking-part-3-057","_displayNo":"#057","qaBands":["9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Housing & Architecture","prompt":"Do you think it is better to rent or to buy a place to live in?\nDo you agree that there is a right age for young adults to stop living with their parents?","answer":"Q: Do you think it is better to rent or to buy a place to live in?\nA: I think it's better to buy your own home if you can afford to do that. Buying your own home is a better investment <strong class=\"key-phrase\">in the long term</strong>, because you can sell the home and perhaps even <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make a profit on</strong> it. The alternative is to pay rent to a landlord who can ask you to leave at any moment.\n\nQ: Do you agree that there is a right age for young adults to stop living with their parents?\nA: There is no universal age at which young adults should leave home. Financial independence, housing costs, education and family culture all matter. The important point is that adults gradually <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take responsibility for</strong> money and daily decisions, whether they live alone at eighteen or remain with their parents longer.","author":"Simon","topic":"Housing & Architecture","phrases":[{"en":"in the long term","vi":"về lâu dài"},{"en":"make a profit on","vi":"kiếm lợi nhuận từ"},{"en":"take responsibility for","vi":"chịu trách nhiệm về"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Housing & Architecture","id":"speaking-part-3-058","_displayNo":"#058","qaBands":["9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Housing & Architecture","prompt":"How do people in your country feel about protecting historic buildings?\nDo you think an area can benefit from having an interesting historic place locally, and in what way?\nWhat do you think will happen to historic places or buildings in the future?","answer":"Q: How do people in your country feel about protecting historic buildings?\nA: Many people support protection in principle, although they may object when restoration costs public money or limits development. Support is stronger when old buildings remain useful and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">part of everyday life</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think an area can benefit from having an interesting historic place locally, and in what way?\nA: Yes. A historic site can attract visitors, support local businesses and give residents a stronger identity. The benefit is greatest when tourism revenue contributes to maintenance and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the surrounding community</strong>.\n\nQ: What do you think will happen to historic places or buildings in the future?\nA: Important sites will probably receive better protection, while less famous buildings remain vulnerable to redevelopment. Digital documentation will improve, but a virtual record cannot fully replace <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the physical experience of place</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Housing & Architecture","phrases":[{"en":"part of everyday life","vi":"một phần của đời sống hằng ngày"},{"en":"the surrounding community","vi":"cộng đồng xung quanh"},{"en":"the physical experience of place","vi":"trải nghiệm thực tế về không gian"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Housing & Architecture","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-059","_displayNo":"#059","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Leisure & Holidays","prompt":"Do you think that it is important for people to go on holiday?\nWhy do you think some people prefer not to go abroad on holiday?","answer":"Q: Do you think that it is important for people to go on holiday?\nA: Yes, I think we all need to go on holiday at least once or twice a year. It isn't healthy to work all year round without some time off to relax; we all need to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take a break</strong> and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">recharge our batteries</strong> from time to time. Last summer, for example, I went on holiday to France for a couple of weeks, and it was great to leave all of my usual responsibilities behind me. I came home feeling really refreshed and reinvigorated.\n\nQ: Why do you think some people prefer not to go abroad on holiday?\nA: I suppose there are different reasons why some people choose not to go abroad on holidays. Firstly, it's usually more expensive to travel abroad than it is to stay at home. A second reason could be that some people find it stressful to spend time in a foreign country where they don't speak the language, or where they feel that they can't easily <strong class=\"key-phrase\">integrate with the locals</strong>. Finally, many people just love where they live, and don't feel the need to travel abroad.","author":"Simon","topic":"Leisure & Holidays","phrases":[{"en":"take a break","vi":"nghỉ ngơi"},{"en":"recharge our batteries","vi":"nghỉ ngơi và nạp lại năng lượng"},{"en":"integrate with the locals","vi":"hòa nhập với người dân địa phương"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Leisure & Holidays","id":"speaking-part-3-060","_displayNo":"#060","qaBands":["9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Leisure & Holidays","prompt":"What is the relationship between leisure and the economy?\nHow does the economy benefit from people’s leisure activities?\nDo men and women enjoy the same type of leisure activities?","answer":"Q: What is the relationship between leisure and the economy?\nA: Well, people spend a lot of money on all sorts of leisure activities nowadays, so I think leisure is a very important part of the economy of most countries. Leisure could be anything that people do in their free time, such as eating out, going to the cinema, watching a football match, or staying in a hotel. Millions of people are employed in these areas.\n\nQ: How does the economy benefit from people’s leisure activities?\nA: The leisure industry makes a huge contribution to the economy. As I said before, it keeps millions of people in employment, and all of these employees pay their taxes and have money to spend on other goods and services. At the same time, most people spend some of their earnings on leisure activities, and this money therefore goes back into the economy.\n\nQ: Do men and women enjoy the same type of leisure activities?\nA: Yes and no. I think both men and women enjoy things like eating in restaurants or going to the cinema, but I'm sure there are other activities that are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more popular with one gender</strong>. For example, I think more men than women go to football matches.","author":"Simon","topic":"Leisure & Holidays","phrases":[{"en":"more popular with one gender","vi":"phổ biến hơn ở một giới"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Leisure & Holidays","id":"speaking-part-3-061","_displayNo":"#061","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Leisure & Holidays","prompt":"Did people have more or less leisure time in the past?\nDo you think hobbies will change much in the future?","answer":"Q: Did people have more or less leisure time in the past?\nA: When my grandparents were young, I think they had <strong class=\"key-phrase\">less leisure time</strong>. They didn't have the gadgets we use nowadays, so they probably spent more time doing simple things. For example, nowadays we can cook meals in a microwave in less than 5 minutes, whereas in the past people had to cook everything themselves.\n\nQ: Do you think hobbies will change much in the future?\nA: No, I don't think hobbies will change much in the future. I'm sure people will still play games and sports. On the other hand, maybe the Internet is changing the way we spend our free time. In the future, more and more people might have online hobbies.","author":"Simon","topic":"Leisure & Holidays","phrases":[{"en":"less leisure time","vi":"ít thời gian giải trí hơn"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Leisure & Holidays","id":"speaking-part-3-062","_displayNo":"#062","qaBands":["9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Leisure & Holidays","prompt":"Are you a morning or evening type of person?\nWhat activities do people often do in the evening in your country?\nIs evening a good time for doing exercises?","answer":"Q: Are you a morning or evening type of person?\nA: I am a morning person because my concentration is sharper before the day becomes busy. I use evenings for lighter tasks and relaxation, which helps me maintain <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sustainable rhythm</strong>.\n\nQ: What activities do people often do in the evening in your country?\nA: People have dinner with family, exercise, watch entertainment, shop or meet friends. In large cities, evening is often the only time when working adults can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">recover some personal time</strong>.\n\nQ: Is evening a good time for doing exercises?\nA: Yes, if the exercise is not so intense that it disrupts sleep. Evening training can relieve stress, but people should finish early enough to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">wind down properly</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Leisure & Holidays","phrases":[{"en":"a sustainable rhythm","vi":"một nhịp sinh hoạt bền vững"},{"en":"recover some personal time","vi":"lấy lại một phần thời gian cá nhân"},{"en":"wind down properly","vi":"thư giãn đúng cách"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Leisure & Holidays","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-063","_displayNo":"#063","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Leisure & Holidays","prompt":"Is watching television a good way of relaxing?\nWhat leisure activities would you recommend as a way of combating stress?\nDo young people get enough physical exercise these days?","answer":"Q: Is watching television a good way of relaxing?\nA: It can be, especially after a demanding day, but passive viewing does not always restore energy. A short programme may help, whereas hours of automatic viewing can leave people <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more tired than refreshed</strong>.\n\nQ: What leisure activities would you recommend as a way of combating stress?\nA: Walking, exercise, gardening, music and social activities are effective because they shift attention and regulate the body’s stress response. The best choice is one that a person can practise <strong class=\"key-phrase\">on a regular basis</strong>.\n\nQ: Do young people get enough physical exercise these days?\nA: Many do not, because study, screens and urban transport reduce daily movement. Schools and cities should make exercise convenient and social rather than presenting it only as <strong class=\"key-phrase\">competitive sport</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Leisure & Holidays","phrases":[{"en":"more tired than refreshed","vi":"mệt hơn là được hồi phục"},{"en":"on a regular basis","vi":"một cách đều đặn"},{"en":"competitive sport","vi":"thể thao mang tính cạnh tranh"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Leisure & Holidays","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-064","_displayNo":"#064","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Luck & Superstition","prompt":"Do you think people in your country are superstitious?\nCan you describe a superstition that they believe in?\nDo you think people are less superstitious than they used to be?","answer":"Q: Do you think people in your country are superstitious?\nA: Some are, particularly around important events, dates and traditional beliefs. Many people treat these customs lightly, but uncertainty can make superstition more influential when decisions feel <strong class=\"key-phrase\">outside personal control</strong>.\n\nQ: Can you describe a superstition that they believe in?\nA: One common belief is that certain numbers or dates bring good or bad luck. People may choose a wedding date or phone number accordingly, even when they know the belief has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">no scientific basis</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think people are less superstitious than they used to be?\nA: Probably, because education and scientific explanations are more accessible. However, superstition has not disappeared; it often survives as cultural habit or emotional comfort rather than literal belief.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Luck & Superstition","phrases":[{"en":"outside personal control","vi":"nằm ngoài sự kiểm soát cá nhân"},{"en":"no scientific basis","vi":"không có cơ sở khoa học"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Luck & Superstition","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-065","_displayNo":"#065","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Money","prompt":"Why is it important for people to save some of their money?\nIn your view, should children be taught how to manage money?\nDo you think that girls are better at saving money than boys?","answer":"Q: Why is it important for people to save some of their money?\nA: In the long term I think it's important to save for retirement, but it's also a good idea to have a certain amount of money saved so that you can deal with unexpected problems in the less distant future. For example, I've learned to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">put some money aside</strong> for car repairs, and this came in useful recently when I needed to have my car's brake pads changed. If I hadn't had savings, the cost of getting my car repaired could have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">sent me into the red</strong>.\n\nQ: In your view, should children be taught how to manage money?\nA: Not at school, no. I believe it's the job of parents to gradually teach children that kind of thing, or perhaps there's no need for anyone to teach children about money because they learn about it naturally as they grow up. For example, I remember being given money to buy sweets or an ice cream when I was a child, and I soon learned <strong class=\"key-phrase\">what I could afford</strong> and what I couldn't.\n\nQ: Do you think that girls are better at saving money than boys?\nA: I've never thought about that before. I don't see any reason why girls would be better savers than boys or vice versa. I suppose it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">depends more on</strong> the personality of each individual and what their interests are. For example, a child who likes cheap toys might not think about saving, whereas a child who wants to buy something expensive, like a bike or a games console, might <strong class=\"key-phrase\">summon the willpower</strong> to save up!","author":"Simon","topic":"Money","phrases":[{"en":"put some money aside","vi":"để dành một khoản tiền"},{"en":"sent me into the red","vi":"khiến tôi rơi vào tình trạng âm tiền"},{"en":"what I could afford","vi":"những gì tôi có khả năng chi trả"},{"en":"depends more on","vi":"phụ thuộc nhiều hơn vào"},{"en":"summon the willpower","vi":"tập trung đủ ý chí"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Money","id":"speaking-part-3-066","_displayNo":"#066","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Money","prompt":"Do you think other people would feel the same in that situation?\nHave you had a similar experience since then?\nHow would you account for the popularity of credit cards?","answer":"Q: Do you think other people would feel the same in that situation?\nA: Many would feel embarrassed or frustrated, especially if the problem happened publicly. The reaction depends on whether it was a minor mistake or evidence of a more serious financial problem, so context can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">change the emotional impact</strong>.\n\nQ: Have you had a similar experience since then?\nA: I have had minor payment problems, such as a card being declined because of a technical issue. Since then, I keep a backup method because it <strong class=\"key-phrase\">gives me peace of mind</strong>.\n\nQ: How would you account for the popularity of credit cards?\nA: They are convenient, widely accepted and offer short-term flexibility, rewards and consumer protection. The danger is that delayed payment can make spending feel less real and encourage people to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">live beyond their means</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Money","phrases":[{"en":"change the emotional impact","vi":"thay đổi tác động cảm xúc"},{"en":"gives me peace of mind","vi":"giúp tôi cảm thấy yên tâm"},{"en":"live beyond their means","vi":"chi tiêu vượt khả năng"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Money","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-067","_displayNo":"#067","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Museums","prompt":"Do you like museums/ art galleries?\nWould you recommend this museum to other people?","answer":"Q: Do you like museums/ art galleries?\nA: Yes, especially museums that explain context rather than merely displaying objects. A well-designed exhibition can turn an abstract historical period into <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a tangible human story</strong>.\n\nQ: Would you recommend this museum to other people?\nA: I would, because the collection is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">well organised</strong> and accessible to non-specialists. It offers enough detail for serious visitors without making the experience <strong class=\"key-phrase\">overwhelming or confusing</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Museums","phrases":[{"en":"a tangible human story","vi":"một câu chuyện con người cụ thể"},{"en":"well organised","vi":"được tổ chức tốt"},{"en":"overwhelming or confusing","vi":"quá tải hoặc khó hiểu"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Museums","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-068","_displayNo":"#068","qaBands":["8.0","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Music","prompt":"What kinds of music are popular with young people in your country?\nHow has technology affected the music that is popular with young people?\nWhat do you think influences a young person's taste in music?","answer":"Q: What kinds of music are popular with young people in your country?\nA: Pop, hip-hop, electronic music and Korean popular music are widely listened to. Online platforms expose young people to global trends, so taste is now <strong class=\"key-phrase\">far less geographically limited</strong>.\n\nQ: How has technology affected the music that is popular with young people?\nA: Streaming and social media have transformed both discovery and production. Independent artists can reach listeners without a major label, although recommendation algorithms may repeatedly promote similar tracks and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">narrow what people encounter</strong>.\n\nQ: What do you think influences a young person's taste in music?\nA: Friends, family, online platforms, films and personal identity all matter. Music is social, so people often use it to signal belonging while also developing <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a private emotional connection</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Music","phrases":[{"en":"far less geographically limited","vi":"ít bị giới hạn bởi địa lý hơn nhiều"},{"en":"narrow what people encounter","vi":"thu hẹp những gì người nghe tiếp cận"},{"en":"a private emotional connection","vi":"một sự kết nối cảm xúc riêng tư"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Music","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-069","_displayNo":"#069","qaBands":["8.0","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"News & Media","prompt":"In your opinion, are newspapers important?","answer":"Q: In your opinion, are newspapers important?\nA: Yes. Professional newspapers fund reporters, editors and investigations that individual social-media users rarely have the time or resources to produce. Their importance is not the paper format itself, but the disciplined process of verifying information, correcting mistakes and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">holding institutions accountable</strong>.","author":"Simon","topic":"News & Media","phrases":[{"en":"holding institutions accountable","vi":"buộc các tổ chức phải chịu trách nhiệm giải trình"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"News & Media","id":"speaking-part-3-070","_displayNo":"#070","qaBands":["9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"News & Media","prompt":"In what ways are newspapers better for learning about the news than radio or television?\nDo you think newspapers should be completely free to say whatever they want?\nWhat do people enjoy reading in your country?","answer":"Q: In what ways are newspapers better for learning about the news than radio or television?\nA: Newspapers allow readers to control the pace, compare details and return to a passage. Broadcast media can be more immediate, but written reporting often provides <strong class=\"key-phrase\">greater analytical depth</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think newspapers should be completely free to say whatever they want?\nA: No. A free press is essential, but it should still be subject to laws on defamation, privacy and direct harm. Freedom is strongest when it is paired with <strong class=\"key-phrase\">professional accountability</strong>.\n\nQ: What do people enjoy reading in your country?\nA: People read news, entertainment, sport, business, lifestyle content and practical information. Online habits are fragmented, so many readers now follow individual topics rather than <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a complete publication</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"News & Media","phrases":[{"en":"greater analytical depth","vi":"chiều sâu phân tích lớn hơn"},{"en":"professional accountability","vi":"trách nhiệm nghề nghiệp"},{"en":"a complete publication","vi":"một ấn phẩm hoàn chỉnh"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"News & Media","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-071","_displayNo":"#071","qaBands":["8.0","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"News & Media","prompt":"Which do you prefer for news: newspapers, television or radio? Why?\nWhat will happen to newspapers as the internet becomes more dominant?","answer":"Q: Which do you prefer for news: newspapers, television or radio? Why?\nA: I prefer reading because I can slow down, check sources and separate reporting from commentary. Television is useful for live events, while radio works well in the background, but written news gives me <strong class=\"key-phrase\">the most control</strong>.\n\nQ: What will happen to newspapers as the internet becomes more dominant?\nA: Printed circulation will probably continue to decline, but journalism will not disappear. Strong organisations will shift to digital subscriptions, newsletters and multimedia while preserving <strong class=\"key-phrase\">editorial standards</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"News & Media","phrases":[{"en":"the most control","vi":"mức độ chủ động cao nhất"},{"en":"editorial standards","vi":"các tiêu chuẩn biên tập"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"News & Media","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-072","_displayNo":"#072","qaBands":["8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Photography","prompt":"Are you a keen photographer?\nDo you like looking at other people's photographs?\nDo you prefer to take a photo or film and why?","answer":"Q: Are you a keen photographer?\nA: I take photographs regularly, mainly to record travel and family moments. I try to be selective because a smaller set of thoughtful images usually carries <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more lasting value</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you like looking at other people's photographs?\nA: Yes, when the photographs reveal a story or a different period of life. Endless unedited albums can be tiring, but a carefully chosen image can create <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a sense of nostalgia</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you prefer to take a photo or film and why?\nA: I prefer photographs because they are quick to revisit and leave room for interpretation. Video is better for movement and sound, but it often requires more time and storage than the moment deserves.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Photography","phrases":[{"en":"more lasting value","vi":"giá trị lâu dài hơn"},{"en":"a sense of nostalgia","vi":"cảm giác hoài niệm"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Photography","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-073","_displayNo":"#073","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Politeness","prompt":"In your country’s culture, how do you show that you are being polite?\nAre we less polite with members of our families than with people we do not know?","answer":"Q: In your country’s culture, how do you show that you are being polite?\nA: Politeness in the UK is often shown through indirect language, personal space and frequent use of ’please’, ’thank you’ and ’sorry’. For example, people normally say, ’Could we have the bill, please?’ rather than giving a direct command. The wording <strong class=\"key-phrase\">softens the request</strong> and signals respect.\n\nQ: Are we less polite with members of our families than with people we do not know?\nA: I suppose it's normal to be a bit <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more relaxed about politeness</strong> with family members. Most people tend to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">speak in a more informal way</strong> at home; in the UK, we still say \"please\" and \"thanks\", but it's fine to use colloquial language and things like nicknames that you would never use with someone you didn't know.","author":"Simon","topic":"Politeness","phrases":[{"en":"softens the request","vi":"làm cho lời đề nghị trở nên nhẹ nhàng hơn"},{"en":"more relaxed about politeness","vi":"thoải mái hơn về phép lịch sự"},{"en":"speak in a more informal way","vi":"nói chuyện theo cách thân mật hơn"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Politeness","id":"speaking-part-3-074","_displayNo":"#074","qaBands":["9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Risk & Safety","prompt":"How important is risk management?\nWhat can be done to prevent natural disasters?\nWhat are the impacts of natural hazards on the surrounding areas?","answer":"Q: How important is risk management?\nA: It is essential wherever failure could harm people, money or the environment. Good risk management identifies hazards early, ranks them by likelihood and severity, and prepares <strong class=\"key-phrase\">proportionate safeguards</strong>.\n\nQ: What can be done to prevent natural disasters?\nA: Natural events cannot be prevented, but disasters can be reduced through land-use planning, early-warning systems, building standards and public education. The goal is to reduce exposure and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">increase community resilience</strong>.\n\nQ: What are the impacts of natural hazards on the surrounding areas?\nA: They can destroy homes, infrastructure and livelihoods, disrupt schooling and healthcare, and force migration. Environmental damage may last for years, so recovery requires more than simply <strong class=\"key-phrase\">rebuilding physical structures</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Risk & Safety","phrases":[{"en":"proportionate safeguards","vi":"các biện pháp bảo vệ tương xứng"},{"en":"increase community resilience","vi":"tăng khả năng chống chịu của cộng đồng"},{"en":"rebuilding physical structures","vi":"xây dựng lại cơ sở vật chất"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Risk & Safety","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-075","_displayNo":"#075","qaBands":["8.0","8.0","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Seasons","prompt":"Do you think the seasons still influence people's behaviour?","answer":"Q: Do you think the seasons still influence people's behaviour?\nA: Yes, the seasons still influence behaviour. People change their clothing, routines and leisure activities <strong class=\"key-phrase\">according to daylight and temperature</strong>. In summer they may eat outdoors and travel more, whereas winter encourages indoor activities. Global food supply has <strong class=\"key-phrase\">weakened some seasonal habits</strong>, but <strong class=\"key-phrase\">weather still shapes daily life</strong>.","author":"Simon","topic":"Seasons","phrases":[{"en":"according to daylight and temperature","vi":"theo lượng ánh sáng ban ngày và nhiệt độ"},{"en":"weakened some seasonal habits","vi":"làm giảm một số thói quen theo mùa"},{"en":"weather still shapes daily life","vi":"thời tiết vẫn định hình đời sống hằng ngày"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Seasons","id":"speaking-part-3-076","_displayNo":"#076","qaBands":["9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Shopping","prompt":"Do you enjoy shopping for clothes?\nWhat kind of clothes do you feel least comfortable in?\nHow much do you judge a person by their appearance?","answer":"Q: Do you enjoy shopping for clothes?\nA: Only when I know what I need. I enjoy finding a well-made item, but browsing without a purpose can be tiring and encourages <strong class=\"key-phrase\">impulse purchases</strong>.\n\nQ: What kind of clothes do you feel least comfortable in?\nA: I feel least comfortable in clothing that is overly tight, heavy or unsuitable for the weather. Appearance matters less to me than being able to move naturally and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">feel at ease</strong>.\n\nQ: How much do you judge a person by their appearance?\nA: Appearance creates a first impression, but I try not to treat it as evidence of character. Clothing can reflect work, culture or circumstance, so judging too quickly can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">reinforce unfair stereotypes</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Shopping","phrases":[{"en":"impulse purchases","vi":"việc mua sắm bốc đồng"},{"en":"feel at ease","vi":"cảm thấy thoải mái"},{"en":"reinforce unfair stereotypes","vi":"củng cố những định kiến bất công"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Shopping","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-077","_displayNo":"#077","qaBands":["8.0","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Skills","prompt":"Could you comment on the idea that children shouldn't waste their time trying to develop a skill if they lack natural ability?\nIs it important to learn a skill?\nWhat do you think are the most important skills for children to learn in the modern world?","answer":"Q: Could you comment on the idea that children shouldn't waste their time trying to develop a skill if they lack natural ability?\nA: I disagree. Natural ability can affect speed, but most useful skills improve through instruction and practice. Children should stop only when the activity causes persistent distress or prevents them from pursuing <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more meaningful interests</strong>.\n\nQ: Is it important to learn a skill?\nA: Yes, because skill learning develops patience, confidence and the ability to respond to feedback. The specific skill may change, but the habit of <strong class=\"key-phrase\">deliberate practice</strong> remains valuable.\n\nQ: What do you think are the most important skills for children to learn in the modern world?\nA: Children need literacy, numeracy, communication, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">digital literacy</strong> and basic self-management. They also need to collaborate and evaluate information, because future work will reward people who can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">learn continuously</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Skills","phrases":[{"en":"more meaningful interests","vi":"những sở thích có ý nghĩa hơn"},{"en":"deliberate practice","vi":"luyện tập có chủ đích"},{"en":"digital literacy","vi":"năng lực số"},{"en":"learn continuously","vi":"học tập liên tục"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Skills","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-078","_displayNo":"#078","qaBands":["8.5","8.0","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Sports & Exercise","prompt":"Why do you think sport is important?\nDo you think famous sportspeople are good role models for children?\nDo you agree that sports stars earn too much money?","answer":"Q: Why do you think sport is important?\nA: I think sport is important for different reasons. For me, doing a sport is about having fun. When I play football, for example, I forget about everything else and just enjoy myself. Also, doing a sport helps you to keep fit and healthy, and it's a good way to socialise and make friends.\n\nQ: Do you think famous sportspeople are good role models for children?\nA: I think that sportspeople should be good role models. Children <strong class=\"key-phrase\">look up to</strong> their favourite football players, like David Beckham for example, so I think that these people have <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an enormous responsibility</strong>. They should try to be a good influence, and behave in the right way.\n\nQ: Do you agree that sports stars earn too much money?\nA: In my opinion, it's fair that the best sportspeople earn a lot of money. Being a top sportsperson <strong class=\"key-phrase\">requires hours of practice</strong>, and there are millions of sports fans who are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">willing to pay</strong> to see them play. If we don't want sportspeople to earn so much money, we shouldn't go to watch them.","author":"Simon","topic":"Sports & Exercise","phrases":[{"en":"look up to","vi":"ngưỡng mộ và xem là hình mẫu"},{"en":"an enormous responsibility","vi":"một trách nhiệm rất lớn"},{"en":"requires hours of practice","vi":"đòi hỏi nhiều giờ luyện tập"},{"en":"willing to pay","vi":"sẵn sàng trả tiền"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Sports & Exercise","id":"speaking-part-3-079","_displayNo":"#079","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Sports & Exercise","prompt":"Do you often go to sporting events?\nAre you very competitive?\nDo you agree or disagree that governments should spend large sums on major sporting events?","answer":"Q: Do you often go to sporting events?\nA: Not often, but I enjoy major events when the atmosphere adds something television cannot reproduce. A live crowd creates <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a strong sense of community</strong>, although tickets and travel can be expensive.\n\nQ: Are you very competitive?\nA: I am competitive with my own previous performance rather than with everyone around me. That approach keeps me motivated without turning every activity into <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a contest for status</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you agree or disagree that governments should spend large sums on major sporting events?\nA: I partly agree. Major events can improve infrastructure and national visibility, but they are difficult to justify when basic services are underfunded. Spending should be transparent and leave <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a useful public legacy</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Sports & Exercise","phrases":[{"en":"a strong sense of community","vi":"ý thức cộng đồng mạnh mẽ"},{"en":"a contest for status","vi":"một cuộc cạnh tranh địa vị"},{"en":"a useful public legacy","vi":"một di sản công cộng hữu ích"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Sports & Exercise","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-080","_displayNo":"#080","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Sports & Exercise","prompt":"How can regular exercise improve your health?\nWhat are the benefits of exercise?\nHow have the types of exercise people do changed in recent years?","answer":"Q: How can regular exercise improve your health?\nA: It strengthens the cardiovascular system, preserves muscle and bone, improves sleep and reduces stress. The greatest benefit comes from consistency rather than extreme intensity, so routines should be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">realistic enough to maintain</strong>.\n\nQ: What are the benefits of exercise?\nA: Exercise improves health, mood, concentration and confidence. Group activities can also reduce isolation, while individual exercise gives people time to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">clear their head</strong>.\n\nQ: How have the types of exercise people do changed in recent years?\nA: There is more gym training, running, yoga and app-guided exercise than before. People have greater choice, but many jobs are also more sedentary, so planned exercise has replaced some of the movement that once occurred <strong class=\"key-phrase\">naturally during the day</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Sports & Exercise","phrases":[{"en":"realistic enough to maintain","vi":"đủ thực tế để duy trì"},{"en":"clear their head","vi":"làm đầu óc thư thái"},{"en":"naturally during the day","vi":"một cách tự nhiên trong ngày"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Sports & Exercise","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-081","_displayNo":"#081","qaBands":["8.5","8.0","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Sports & Exercise","prompt":"How have games changed since you were a child?\nDo you think this has been a positive change and why?\nWhy do you think children like playing games?","answer":"Q: How have games changed since you were a child?\nA: Children play more digital and highly structured games, while spontaneous outdoor play has declined in many places. Games are more visually sophisticated, but they often involve less movement and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">less face-to-face negotiation</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you think this has been a positive change and why?\nA: It is mixed. Digital games can develop strategy and connect friends, but excessive screen time can displace sleep and physical activity. The key is balance and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">age-appropriate limits</strong>.\n\nQ: Why do you think children like playing games?\nA: Games provide challenge, immediate feedback, imagination and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">social interaction</strong>. They also give children a safe space to test rules and experience winning or losing without <strong class=\"key-phrase\">serious real-world consequences</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Sports & Exercise","phrases":[{"en":"less face-to-face negotiation","vi":"ít sự thương lượng trực tiếp hơn"},{"en":"age-appropriate limits","vi":"giới hạn phù hợp với độ tuổi"},{"en":"social interaction","vi":"sự tương tác xã hội"},{"en":"serious real-world consequences","vi":"hệ quả nghiêm trọng ngoài đời thực"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Sports & Exercise","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-082","_displayNo":"#082","qaBands":["8.5","8.0","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Sports & Exercise","prompt":"What do most people in your country do to keep fit?\nHow important is it for people to do some regular physical exercise?\nWhy do you think that modern lifestyles are not healthy?","answer":"Q: What do most people in your country do to keep fit?\nA: People walk, run, use gyms, play badminton or football, and increasingly follow online workouts. The most sustainable activities are affordable and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">easy to fit into daily life</strong>.\n\nQ: How important is it for people to do some regular physical exercise?\nA: It is extremely important because modern life removes much of the movement humans once did automatically. Regular activity protects long-term health and helps people maintain <strong class=\"key-phrase\">functional independence</strong>.\n\nQ: Why do you think that modern lifestyles are not healthy?\nA: Many people sit for long hours, sleep irregularly, rely on processed food and experience constant digital stimulation. Each factor may seem minor, but together they create <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a cumulative health burden</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Sports & Exercise","phrases":[{"en":"easy to fit into daily life","vi":"dễ sắp xếp vào cuộc sống hằng ngày"},{"en":"functional independence","vi":"khả năng tự lập về thể chất"},{"en":"a cumulative health burden","vi":"gánh nặng sức khỏe tích lũy"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Sports & Exercise","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-083","_displayNo":"#083","qaBands":["8.0","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Sports & Exercise","prompt":"What forms of exercise are popular among young people?\nHave people's attitudes towards exercise changed in your country in recent years?","answer":"Q: What forms of exercise are popular among young people?\nA: Gym training, running, football, badminton and yoga are popular among young people. Social media has also increased interest in programmes that produce visible results and are <strong class=\"key-phrase\">easy to track</strong>.\n\nQ: Have people's attitudes towards exercise changed in your country in recent years?\nA: Yes. Exercise is now more closely linked to mental health, appearance and lifestyle, not only competitive sport. The positive change is greater awareness, although unrealistic online images can create <strong class=\"key-phrase\">unnecessary pressure</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Sports & Exercise","phrases":[{"en":"easy to track","vi":"dễ theo dõi"},{"en":"unnecessary pressure","vi":"áp lực không cần thiết"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Sports & Exercise","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-084","_displayNo":"#084","qaBands":["8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Technology","prompt":"What is the most important invention of the last century?\nCan technology make life harder?","answer":"Q: What is the most important invention of the last century?\nA: The internet is arguably the most important because it transformed communication, commerce, education and access to information. Its influence is so broad that it has become <strong class=\"key-phrase\">basic social infrastructure</strong>.\n\nQ: Can technology make life harder?\nA: Yes. Technology can create distraction, surveillance, dependency and a constant expectation of availability. A tool designed to save time can end up consuming attention unless people set <strong class=\"key-phrase\">clear boundaries</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Technology","phrases":[{"en":"basic social infrastructure","vi":"cơ sở hạ tầng xã hội cơ bản"},{"en":"clear boundaries","vi":"ranh giới rõ ràng"}],"source":"Topic reference: IELTS Advantage (2026); questions adapted; answers rewritten and quality-audited by ChatGPT","subtype":"","summary":"Technology","id":"speaking-part-3-085","_displayNo":"#085","qaBands":["8.5","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Technology","prompt":"What are the main differences between life in the past and life today?\nWhat are the impacts of electrical equipment on our life?\nHow will technology change our life in future?","answer":"Q: What are the main differences between life in the past and life today?\nA: Life today is faster, more connected and less physically demanding because information, transport and household technology save time. The past often involved stronger local routines, but people had fewer choices and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more labour-intensive daily tasks</strong>.\n\nQ: What are the impacts of electrical equipment on our life?\nA: Household equipment has reduced physical labour and improved comfort, hygiene and food storage. The trade-off is greater energy use and dependence on devices that are often <strong class=\"key-phrase\">difficult to repair</strong>.\n\nQ: How will technology change our life in future?\nA: Automation and artificial intelligence will handle more routine decisions and personalise services. The challenge will be preserving privacy, employment opportunities and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">meaningful human control</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Technology","phrases":[{"en":"more labour-intensive daily tasks","vi":"nhiều công việc hằng ngày tốn sức hơn"},{"en":"difficult to repair","vi":"khó sửa chữa"},{"en":"meaningful human control","vi":"quyền kiểm soát có ý nghĩa của con người"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Technology","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-086","_displayNo":"#086","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Technology","prompt":"What do you think are the most important inventions of the last 50 years?\nHow have mobile phones made communications easier?\nWhich household appliances do you think people need most?","answer":"Q: What do you think are the most important inventions of the last 50 years?\nA: Several inventions have been transformative, but the smartphone stands out because it combines communication, navigation, photography, banking and access to information in one portable device. Its impact is extraordinary, although overdependence has created new social problems.\n\nQ: How have mobile phones made communications easier?\nA: They allow instant voice, text, video and location sharing from almost anywhere. This is invaluable in emergencies and daily coordination, although constant contact can create <strong class=\"key-phrase\">an expectation of immediate response</strong>.\n\nQ: Which household appliances do you think people need most?\nA: Refrigerators, washing machines and cooking appliances are probably the most essential. They protect food, save time and reduce repetitive labour, making them <strong class=\"key-phrase\">far more than luxury items</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Technology","phrases":[{"en":"an expectation of immediate response","vi":"kỳ vọng phải phản hồi ngay lập tức"},{"en":"far more than luxury items","vi":"vượt xa phạm vi của những món đồ xa xỉ"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Technology","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-087","_displayNo":"#087","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Technology & Internet","prompt":"How do you think the internet will affect our lives in the future?","answer":"Q: How do you think the internet will affect our lives in the future?\nA: The internet will become even more <strong class=\"key-phrase\">deeply integrated into</strong> communication, shopping, education and entertainment. More services will move online, and personalised systems will anticipate what users need. The benefits will be substantial, but societies will also have to protect privacy, digital access and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">independent judgement</strong>.","author":"Simon","topic":"Technology & Internet","phrases":[{"en":"deeply integrated into","vi":"được tích hợp sâu vào"},{"en":"independent judgement","vi":"khả năng phán đoán độc lập"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Technology & Internet","id":"speaking-part-3-088","_displayNo":"#088","qaBands":["9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Technology & Internet","prompt":"What role does advertising play on the internet?\nHow do you think the internet will affect buying patterns in the future?\nWhat effect has the internet had on the way people generally communicate with each other?","answer":"Q: What role does advertising play on the internet?\nA: It finances many free services and allows firms to reach precise audiences. However, data-driven targeting can blur the line between relevance and surveillance, so users need <strong class=\"key-phrase\">meaningful control over their data</strong>.\n\nQ: How do you think the internet will affect buying patterns in the future?\nA: Online comparison, reviews and personalised recommendations will make purchasing faster and more data-driven. Physical shops will remain important for experience and trust, but routine buying will become <strong class=\"key-phrase\">increasingly automated</strong>.\n\nQ: What effect has the internet had on the way people generally communicate with each other?\nA: The internet has made communication immediate, cheap and global. It has also encouraged shorter messages and public performance, so people may communicate more often while understanding one another <strong class=\"key-phrase\">less deeply</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Technology & Internet","phrases":[{"en":"meaningful control over their data","vi":"quyền kiểm soát có ý nghĩa đối với dữ liệu của mình"},{"en":"increasingly automated","vi":"ngày càng tự động hóa"},{"en":"less deeply","vi":"kém sâu sắc hơn"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Technology & Internet","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-089","_displayNo":"#089","qaBands":["8.0","8.0","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Transport","prompt":"Do you prefer traveling by public transport or by car?\nWhat are the benefits of traveling by public transport?\nIn your opinion, in what ways can governments encourage people to use public transport?","answer":"Q: Do you prefer traveling by public transport or by car?\nA: I prefer public transport when it is reliable because I can read or work instead of concentrating on traffic. I choose a car only when the route is poorly served or I need <strong class=\"key-phrase\">greater flexibility</strong>.\n\nQ: What are the benefits of traveling by public transport?\nA: Public transport reduces the number of vehicles needed to move large populations, which can lower congestion, pollution and household travel costs. It also gives people who cannot drive <strong class=\"key-phrase\">independent access to work and services</strong>.\n\nQ: In your opinion, in what ways can governments encourage people to use public transport?\nA: Governments need frequent services, integrated fares, safe stations and restrictions on excessive car use. Persuasion alone will not work unless public transport is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a genuinely competitive alternative</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Transport","phrases":[{"en":"greater flexibility","vi":"sự linh hoạt cao hơn"},{"en":"independent access to work and services","vi":"khả năng tự tiếp cận công việc và dịch vụ"},{"en":"a genuinely competitive alternative","vi":"một phương án thay thế thực sự có sức cạnh tranh"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Transport","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-090","_displayNo":"#090","qaBands":["8.5","8.5","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Transport","prompt":"Do you think getting to work is easier or more difficult than it used to be?\nHow have methods of transport improved?\nAre there any problems that have been created by new transport systems?","answer":"Q: Do you think getting to work is easier or more difficult than it used to be?\nA: In some ways it is easier because navigation, ride-hailing and new transit lines offer more options. However, growing congestion and longer urban distances can cancel out those gains, so the experience is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">highly location-dependent</strong>.\n\nQ: How have methods of transport improved?\nA: Vehicles are safer, cleaner and easier to coordinate through digital systems. Improvements in ticketing and real-time information have also made journeys <strong class=\"key-phrase\">more predictable</strong>.\n\nQ: Are there any problems that have been created by new transport systems?\nA: Yes. New roads can encourage more driving, divide neighbourhoods and create noise, while ride-hailing can add vehicles to already congested streets. A transport project should therefore be judged by its wider effects, not only by <strong class=\"key-phrase\">shorter journey times</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Transport","phrases":[{"en":"highly location-dependent","vi":"phụ thuộc rất nhiều vào địa điểm"},{"en":"more predictable","vi":"dễ dự đoán hơn"},{"en":"shorter journey times","vi":"thời gian di chuyển ngắn hơn"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Transport","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-091","_displayNo":"#091","qaBands":["8.5","8.0","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Transport","prompt":"How has transport changed in recent decades?\nWill public transport become more popular?","answer":"Q: How has transport changed in recent decades?\nA: Transport has become faster, more connected and more digitally managed. People can compare routes and book instantly, but rising private-vehicle ownership has also intensified <strong class=\"key-phrase\">urban congestion</strong>.\n\nQ: Will public transport become more popular?\nA: It will where it is clean, frequent and cheaper than driving. Environmental concern helps, but most people change behaviour only when the service also offers <strong class=\"key-phrase\">clear everyday convenience</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Transport","phrases":[{"en":"urban congestion","vi":"tình trạng ùn tắc đô thị"},{"en":"clear everyday convenience","vi":"sự thuận tiện rõ ràng trong đời sống hằng ngày"}],"source":"Topic reference: IELTS Advantage (2026); questions adapted; answers rewritten and quality-audited by ChatGPT","subtype":"","summary":"Transport","id":"speaking-part-3-092","_displayNo":"#092","qaBands":["8.0","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Travel & Tourism","prompt":"Would you recommend the place you described to other people?\nDo you enjoy sightseeing in general?\nHave you visited a similar place before?","answer":"Q: Would you recommend the place you described to other people?\nA: Yes, especially to people who enjoy culture and natural scenery. I would advise them to avoid peak periods and respect local rules so that their visit does not <strong class=\"key-phrase\">add unnecessary pressure</strong>.\n\nQ: Do you enjoy sightseeing in general?\nA: Yes, but I prefer a few meaningful places to a rushed checklist. I enjoy learning the background and walking around slowly enough to <strong class=\"key-phrase\">take in the atmosphere</strong>.\n\nQ: Have you visited a similar place before?\nA: I have visited places with similar scenery, but each one had a different scale and local culture. Comparing them helped me appreciate the features that made this destination <strong class=\"key-phrase\">genuinely distinctive</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Travel & Tourism","phrases":[{"en":"add unnecessary pressure","vi":"gây thêm áp lực không cần thiết"},{"en":"take in the atmosphere","vi":"cảm nhận bầu không khí"},{"en":"genuinely distinctive","vi":"thực sự khác biệt"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Travel & Tourism","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-093","_displayNo":"#093","qaBands":["8.5","8.0","8.5"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Work","prompt":"Which technologies are commonly used in workplaces?\nDoes technology make work easier?\nDoes technology cause people to lose their jobs?","answer":"Q: Which technologies are commonly used in workplaces?\nA: In most workplaces people use equipment such as computers, phones, printers, fax machines and photocopiers. I think the computer is probably the most <strong class=\"key-phrase\">essential piece of equipment</strong> because we <strong class=\"key-phrase\">rely on it for almost everything</strong>: communicating by email, writing reports, organising data, and finding information on the Internet.\n\nQ: Does technology make work easier?\nA: Technology definitely helps workers because it makes many tasks so much easier. For example, email is such a useful tool for communication between employees in different offices, or even in different countries. On the other hand, technology can <strong class=\"key-phrase\">make life more difficult</strong>, especially when it goes wrong. It causes a lot of stress when the Internet is down or a computer crashes.\n\nQ: Does technology cause people to lose their jobs?\nA: I think technology is often responsible for people losing their jobs. <strong class=\"key-phrase\">Machines have replaced people</strong> in areas like manufacturing and agriculture, and whenever a new technology is introduced, there are redundancies. At the same time, <strong class=\"key-phrase\">jobs might be created</strong> thanks to a new technology; there would be no computer programmers if the computer hadn't been invented.","author":"Simon","topic":"Work","phrases":[{"en":"essential piece of equipment","vi":"thiết bị thiết yếu"},{"en":"rely on it for almost everything","vi":"phụ thuộc vào nó trong hầu hết mọi việc"},{"en":"make life more difficult","vi":"làm cuộc sống khó khăn hơn"},{"en":"Machines have replaced people","vi":"máy móc đã thay thế con người"},{"en":"jobs might be created","vi":"việc làm mới có thể được tạo ra"}],"source":"IELTS Simon Speaking Part 3","subtype":"","summary":"Work","id":"speaking-part-3-094","_displayNo":"#094","qaBands":["9.0","9.0","9.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Work","prompt":"What is the best way to prepare for a job interview?\nWhich jobs do you think are the most dangerous?\nHow can employers keep their staff happy?","answer":"Q: What is the best way to prepare for a job interview?\nA: Candidates should research the organisation, understand the role and prepare concise examples of their skills. Rehearsal is useful, but answers should remain flexible enough to sound <strong class=\"key-phrase\">natural rather than memorised</strong>.\n\nQ: Which jobs do you think are the most dangerous?\nA: Mining, construction, fishing, firefighting and some forms of transport are particularly dangerous. Risk comes from heavy machinery, unstable environments and fatigue, so strong safety systems must be <strong class=\"key-phrase\">built into the job</strong>.\n\nQ: How can employers keep their staff happy?\nA: Employers need fair pay, manageable workloads, respect, development opportunities and some control over how work is done. Superficial perks cannot <strong class=\"key-phrase\">compensate for</strong> poor management or <strong class=\"key-phrase\">chronic overwork</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Work","phrases":[{"en":"natural rather than memorised","vi":"tự nhiên chứ không phải học thuộc"},{"en":"built into the job","vi":"được tích hợp vào công việc"},{"en":"compensate for","vi":"bù đắp cho"},{"en":"chronic overwork","vi":"tình trạng làm việc quá sức kéo dài"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Work","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-095","_displayNo":"#095","qaBands":["8.5","8.0","8.0"]},{"section":"speaking-part-3","title":"Writing","prompt":"What effect have computers had on the way we write?\nWhat are the advantages and disadvantages of email?\nWill writing remain an important skill in the future?","answer":"Q: What effect have computers had on the way we write?\nA: Computers have made writing faster to edit, share and search, and they allow collaboration across distance. The downside is that constant correction tools may weaken attention to spelling and <strong class=\"key-phrase\">careful revision</strong>.\n\nQ: What are the advantages and disadvantages of email?\nA: Email is fast, inexpensive and creates a searchable record. However, tone is easy to misread, inboxes become overloaded and sensitive issues are often handled poorly without <strong class=\"key-phrase\">real-time clarification</strong>.\n\nQ: Will writing remain an important skill in the future?\nA: Yes. Even if artificial intelligence produces drafts, people will still need to judge accuracy, structure arguments and communicate responsibility. Writing is not only transcription; it is <strong class=\"key-phrase\">a tool for precise thinking</strong>.","author":"ChatGPT","topic":"Writing","phrases":[{"en":"careful revision","vi":"việc chỉnh sửa cẩn thận"},{"en":"real-time clarification","vi":"sự làm rõ theo thời gian thực"},{"en":"a tool for precise thinking","vi":"một công cụ để tư duy chính xác"}],"source":"220 IELTS Speaking Topics — Taraneh Sadeghian & Mahdieh Azaminejad","subtype":"Part 3","summary":"Writing","visual":null,"id":"speaking-part-3-096","_displayNo":"#096","qaBands":["8.5","8.0","8.5"]}],"counts":{"writing-general":29,"writing-academic":69,"writing-task-2":194,"speaking-part-1":90,"speaking-part-2":204,"speaking-part-3":96},"sections":["writing-general","writing-academic","writing-task-2","speaking-part-1","speaking-part-2","speaking-part-3"],"sourceNote":"All entries were rechecked for spelling and OCR artefacts. Highlighted expressions were reduced to context-appropriate collocations, functional language and precise topic vocabulary; ordinary connectors and low-value words were removed. Vietnamese meanings were normalised. Writing scores were estimated against Task Achievement/Response, Coherence and Cohesion, Lexical Resource, and Grammatical Range and Accuracy. Speaking scores assume fluent delivery and accurate pronunciation and assess the written response for lexical resource, grammar and coherence."};
